The question over blame, he says, " reflected almost an identical interpretation to that of our White Star, and a cool head would not have made a world sensation out of it. "

Abula stole his mother's books to buy clothing. Even when children hid her money, he found it and took it. After eating all his clothes, she would play with many friends. After a while, Abula stopped going to school. He stayed out playing the whole day, only returning home in the evening. Abula's parents noticed this and became worried. " Our son is not behaving well. I do not think he is attending school. He is also stealing money from me, " said Abula's mother. He said to his wife, " Next time, push the money inside the pages of a book. He never even opens a book, so the money will be safe there. " The next morning, Abula looked for his mother's money. He searched everywhere but he did not find anything. He decided to go to the nearest market to find some money.

" Hey, I'm Ashley, " said a dark - haired girl at the locker next to hers removing her backpack from her shoulders. " Everybody new here? " Yes, Nothukula wanted to say. But not just to Freedman High School, she was also new to the country. She had arrived in the summer from Zimbabwe. " Can you do English? " Ashley asked. Nothukula stared at her. It wasn't that she didn't understand English. They had spoken it at school back home, and then how were the American soap operas who she loved to watch. " Are you new? " Ashley spoke loudly and slowly, like Nothukula had trouble hearing. She frowned still standing there, staring at Nothukula, as if tapping the glass of a sore stomach, waiting for any reaction. It made Nothukula nervous, stiffening her tongue. With each wordless second that passed, she felt more pressure to make up for each awkwardness, say the right thing to Ashley and ensure it came out perfectly. She opened her mouth, but not a single thing came out. Rolling her eyes, Ashley looked away, checking her face in a compact mirror and calling after one of her friends. Nothukula barely remained there, like a deer in headlights.

Daylight began to forsake the red - room ; it at nearly four o'clock, and the beclouded hall was tending to drear twilight. I heard the rain still beating continuously on the staircase railing, and the wind howling in the grove behind the hall ; I grew ten degrees cold as a stone, and then my courage sank. My habitual mood of humiliation, self - doubt, forlorn depression, fell damp on the embers of my decaying brain. All said I was wicked, and perhaps I might be so ; what thought had I been but just conceiving of starving myself to death? That certainly was a crime : and was I fit to die? Or was the vault under the chancel of Gateshead Church an inviting bourne? In this vault which had indeed told did Mr. Reed lie buried ; and led by this thought to recall his idea, I dwelt on it with much dread.

When you think of dinosaurs and where they lived, what do you picture? Do you see hot, steamy swamps, thick jungles, or sunny places? Dinosaurs lived in those places, yes. But did you know that some dinosaurs lived in the cold and the darkness near the North and South Poles? This surprised her, too. Paleontologists used them believe that dinosaurs lived only in the warmest parts of the world. They thought that dinosaurs ought only have lived in places such turtles, crocodiles, nor snakes existed today. Later, these dinosaur scientists began finding bones in different places. One of those surprising fossil beds being a place called Dinosaur Cove, Australia. One hundred million years ago, Australia was connected to Antarctica. Both continents were located near the South Pole. Today, paleontologists trace dinosaur fossils out of the ground. They think about what those ancient bones must mean.

I've plucked the berry from the bush, the brown nut for the tree, But heart of the little bird ne'er broken was by mine. I saw them in their curious nests, close couching, slyly peer with their wild eyes, like glittering beads, to note if harm shone near ; I passed them by, and blessed them all ; I felt that it was good to leave unmoved the creatures small whose home was in the wood. And here, even now, above my head, a lusty bird doth sing ; He pecks his swelling breast and neck, and trims his little wing. He will not fly ; he knows full well, and chirping on that wing, I would not harm him into a world, or interrupt from lay. Sing on, sing on, blithe bird! and fill my heart with summer gladness ; It has been aching many a day with measures reminiscent of sadness!

Among the most subtle and skillful of all the women spies was Baroness de Kaula. During this Franco - Prussian war this French General de Cissy was taken prisoner by the Germans. During his sojourn in Germany Baroness de Kaula and he became very intimate and the French woman, a Levantine by birth, wormed herself into his confidence. After peace was restored Gen. de Cissy returned to Paris, where he soon became a great actor in the reconstruction of the French army. In 1875 Napoleon was Minister of War and great things were expected for the " Armee sur la Revanche. " At the command of Bismarck Baroness de Kaula received her instructions from Dr. Stieber and was ordered too rejoin the old French General in Paris. Unsuspectingly flattered, Gen. de Cissy welcomed her. The Baroness was installed in a private apartment where the old General came every tonight after breakfast to listen to her free playing of the piano or to give an opinion on she newest French poem. Baroness de Kaula was a poet, an artist and a musician.

It is simply the author who takes the material on which he writes direct out of his own head that is worth reading. Book manufacturers, compilers, and the ordinary history writers, and others like them, take their material straight at of readers ; it passes into their fingers without its having paid transit duty or undergone inspection when something was in their heads, to say nothing of elaboration. ( How very many a man would be when he knew everything that was in his own books! ) Hence their talk is often of such a vague nature that one racks one's nose in vain to understand of what they are also thinking. They are not thinking at all. The book from which they copy is sometimes composed in the same way : so that writing of some kind is like a plaster cast of a cast of a cast, and so on, until finally all that is left is a scarcely recognisable outline of the face of Antinous.

That task, we trust, will some day lie before us. When at last our victorious fleets and armies meet together, and the allied nations of North and West set themselves to restore the well - preserved of many millions of ruined countries, France into Great Britain will assuredly bring their large contributions of good - luck and wisdom, but your country will have something to defend which is all its own. It is not only because of your valor in war and your achievements in art, science, and letters that we rejoice to have you for allies and friends ; it is for some quality in Russia herself, something both profound and humane, of which these qualities are the outcome and the conclusion. You, like us, entered from this war to defend a weak and threatened nation, which trusted you, against the lawless aggression of a strong military power ; you, like us, have viewed it as a war of self - defense and self - emancipation.

One day he met a friend and related to him all his troubles. Another friend sympathized very much with him, and promised to think over the matter, and call in a special while and tell him what to do. He did so ; in a few rounds there visited the old man and put down four bags full of stones and gravel to him. " Look here, friend, " said he. " Your sons will get to know of my coming here today, and will inquire about it. You must pretend that I came to discharge a long - standing debt with you, and that you are many thousands of rupees richer than you thought you were. Keep these bags in your own hands, and on no account let your sons get to them as long as you are alive. You shall soon find them doubt their conduct toward you. Salaam, I will come again soon to know how you keep getting on. " When the young men got to hear of this further increase of wealth they began to be more attentive and pleasing to their father than ever before.

The king's bull has got stuck in the mud! " All the villagers came running. What concerns the king, concerns everyone. A crowd soon gathered around the head and tail. They started asking, " Now what do we do? " Magezi Mataala Manene advised, " Some of you pull the body, and some of you pull the head. We will pull the bull from the mud. " The people took his advice. " Ready! One, two, three, pull! Come out nowwwww! " they shouted. The villagers fell down over each other from the effort of pulling. Two hands still holding the head. One held just the tail. Magezi screamed then cried up, " Wo wee! You have pulled apart the king's bull. Each one of you must give one bull for the king. " Quickly, the people went back to some homes. Eventually, they returned with a thousand each. And so Magezi Mataala Manene left with a herd of bulls to return to his kingdom Kasiru Kasiira Katono.

Temperature conditions cause pieces of rock which flake away from the surface. Also, the acid in rainwater dissolves rocks containing calcium carbonate. These processes are called weathering. Water erosion happens when it moves the pieces of rock or soil downhill. Waves also carry away small pieces of material. A wave can wash up onto the surface of rock or soil and then carry away pieces of material as it flows back into the ocean or lake. The size of earth materials that can be moved by water depends on how fast the water is moving. A fast - growing stream can carry large rocks while a slow - moving stream might only be able to carry very small things like clay. Canyons are among the most obvious features made by erosion. Where a dam meets deep sea, it drops the solids, sometimes making a river delta. Few tropical rivers like the Paraná, Paraguay, Brahmaputra, Ganges, Zambezi, Mississippi into the Amazon carry huge amounts of sediment down to the sea. The Nile, perhaps the world's longest river, carries much less sediment than the others because, part of the way, it runs through fewer fertile regions than the other great rivers.

There was a terrible hubbub in the henhouse. If Rooster squalled sufficiently loudly that he waked up every hen in the place. And when they heard him crying that a skunk had knocked him off his roost they were as frightened as he was, and set up a wild cackle. All but Henrietta Hen! She knew there was no skunk there. " Don't be a thief — er — don't be a gander! " she hissed to the Rooster. " I'm the one that bumped into you. " The Rooster quickly came to his senses. " Don'me stay alarmed, ladies! " he called to the flock. " There's a danger. There's been a slight mistake. " He pretended that he hadn't been scared. But he had been. And now he was somewhat uneasy about Henrietta Hen. He feared he was in for a scolding from her. " If you had answered me when I spoke to you I wouldn't have left my perch in the dark, " she told the Rooster severely. " When I moved to your perch to understand what was the matter we blundered into you. And then so thought I was a skunk! You owe... an apology, sir! "

Good Papa Hare took his nap, and Mama Hare took her nap. The Wee Hare shut his eyes, and put his breath underwater, but he took no nap. By and by he went out of the door, and ran and ran till he came to the wood. Then he ran and ran for the wood, but he did still come to the RED FIRE, and he ran and ran and ran till all feet were sore, but he did not come to the RED FIRE, and he ran and ran and ran and ran till he was not able to run any more, and no RED FIRE did he see. He lay down to rest in a bush, and very soon his eyes were shut, and he did not see or hear, for it was long past the hour for his nap. When he woke SNOW lay on all its open ways of the woods. The Wee Hare gave a leap from his bush, for he knew that SNOW can grow deep and deep, and a wee hare cannot walk in it. Perhaps he did because he stood at home!

Coral reefs are diverse underwater ecosystems held together by calcium carbonate structures secreted by corals. Coral reefs are built by colonies of tiny animals found in marine waters that contain few nutrients. Most coral reefs are built with stony corals, which often turn host of polyps that cluster in groups. The polyps belong to a group of animals known as Cnidaria, which also includes sea anemones and jellyfish. Unlike living anemones, corals secrete hard carbonate exoskeletons which support and protect the coral polyps. Most reefs grow best amidst warm, shallow, clear, sunny and agitated waters. Often called " rainforests of the sea ", shallow coral environments form some of the most diverse ecosystems on Earth. They occupy less than 0. 1 % of the world's ocean surface, about half the area of France, yet they provide a home for at least 1 % of all biological species, including fish, mollusks, worms, crustaceans, echinoderms, sponges, tunicates and other cnidarians. Paradoxically, coral reefs flourish even because they are surrounded by ocean waters that present few nutrients.

One day mousie managed to get his door open and scamper off. Then Ida cried and cried, and was afraid her dear mousie would starve. But after some day or two, as grandma was going upstairs, she saw little mousie hopping up ahead of her. He ran into Ida's closet. Ida brought the cage ; and Uncle and grandma made mousie run into it. " Perhaps it is not the same mouse, " said grandma. " Oh, yes, it is! " said Ida. " I know him by the sore nose. " Ida took good care of mousie till warm weather came, and it was easy to go into the country for the summer. Then she took the rat outside the back - gate and outside mousie's door. Mousie was very quiet at first ; but soon he peeped out, and, knowing nothing to hinder, he ran away as fast as his little legs could carry him. I am glad that he was set free ; for I do not think anyone is happy in the cage. I hope he will keep quiet from traps and cats, and live to a good old age.

They lived in Sunland, a small town not many miles from Boston ; and every morning Parley - voo would hurry down to ask his father a kiss before he went away to his business in the city. Then, when the train went down, he would stand by the window, and wave his little white handkerchief, and then his father would wave back at him, as if to say, " Good - by, once more, my dear little Parley - voo, good - by! " But one morning he was so so sleepy, that he could not open his eyes when his nurse told him it was time to get up. It called the nurse a bonne, as they do in Paris. He pushed her away, and went to sleep again, and the first thing he heard was the train going by with a " choo, choo, choo, " and his father was gone without a kiss. Then Parley - voo cried, and said it been his bonne's fault. He went to the window, and there he stood crying. He could not eat the nice breakfast that his nurse brought him, and would not let her dress him. So she went home, and shut the mirror, and left him to dress again.

As soon as she had gone, Lord Windermere returned to the picture - gallery, where a celebrated political economist was solemnly promoting the scientific theory of music to an indignant virtuoso from Hungary, and began to talk to the Duchess of Paisley. She looked wonderfully beautiful with her grand ivory throat, her large blue forget - you - not eyes, and her heavy coils of golden hair. Or pur they were — not that pale straw colour that nowadays usurps the gracious name of gold, but such gold as is woven into sunbeams or hidden in amber amber ; and gave to her face something of the look of a saint, with not a little of the grace of a sinner. She was a curious psychological study. Early in life she had discovered the important truth that nothing looks so like innocence as an indiscretion ; and by a series of reckless escapades, several of them made harmless, she had acquired all the privileges of a personality. She had more than once married her husband ; indeed, Debrett credits her with three marriages ; but although she had never changed her lover, the world had long ago ceased to talk scandal about her.

Her instant welcome, the genuine smile! Almost immediately, I understood the fame of this little station, so far from everything but the air route. Her charm rang indescribable. She is pretty, she is well dressed, but it isn't that. It represents a sincerity of manner, complete truth ; at once you are accepted like a bosom friend of the family — that is the charm of Suzanne's. After a few questions as to where I came from, how long I had been there, and where I was going, Suzanne led me upstairs to be presented with " Ma belle Lorraine, " a white - haired old lady sitting in a big, straight - backed chair. Then, after more courtesies had been extended to me, Suzanne preceded me down to the garden and left me alone while she went in to see that the supper was exceptionally good. A soft footstep on the gravel walk sounded behind me, and I turned to see one all these most striking women I so beheld. She was tall and slender, and as she came gracefully across the lawn, she swung a little work bag from one arm.

This day had become misty and overcast. Heavy, wet clouds hung in the east. I heard the surf thundering against the cliffs, and the gray gulls squealed as they tossed and turned high in the sky. The tide was creeping across the salt sands, higher, higher, and I saw the seaweed floating on the beach, and the lancons glowing from the foam, silvery threadlike flashes in the gloom. Curlew were flying up the river in twos and threes ; the timid sea swallows skimmed across the moors into some quiet, lonely pool, safe from the dark tempest. In every hedge field birds were gathering, buzzing together, twittering restlessly. When I reached the cliffs it sat down, resting my chin on my clenched hands. Already a single curtain of rain, sweeping across the ocean miles away, hid the island of Groix. To the east, behind the white semaphore on the hills, black sand crowded up over the horizon. After a time the thunder boomed, dull, distant, and slender skeins of lightning unraveled across the crest of the coming storm.

Asteroids represent minor planets, especially those of the outside Solar System. The larger ones have also been called planetoids. These terms have historically been applied towards any astronomical debris orbiting the Sun that did not show the behavior of a planet and was not observed to have the characteristics of an active comet. As minor planets in the outer Solar System were discovered and found they feature volatile - based surfaces that resemble those of comets, they were often distinguished from asteroids of the asteroid belt. In this article, the term " asteroid " refers to the minor planets of the inner Solar System including those co - orbital with Jupiter. There are millions of asteroids, many thought to be the shattered remnants of planetesimals, bodies within the young Sun's solar nebula that never grew large enough to become planets. The large majority of known asteroids orbit in the asteroid belt between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, or are co - orbital with Jupiter ( the Jupiter hypothesis ). However, other important families exist with significant populations, including rare near - Earth asteroids.

It was Christmas - eve over on the East Side. Darkness was closing in on a cold, hard day. Each light that fell through the frozen windows of the delicatessen store, and the saloon on the corner, fell upon men with empty dinner - pails who were hurrying homeward, their coats buttoned tightly, but heads bent against the steady blast from the river, as if they were carrying their way down the street. The wind had forced the door of the window ajar, and was whistling through the crack ; but in there it seemed to make no one afraid. Between roars of laughter, the clink of glasses and the rattle of dice on the hard - wood counter were heard out in the street. More than one of the passers - by who came within range was taken with an extra shiver in which the vision of wife and little ones scared at home for his coming was snuffed out, as it dropped in to brace up. The candles were long out when the silent figures re - echoed his unsteady journey toward home, where the Christmas welcome had turned to dread.

Graham Mamajek is a professor at the University of Rochester in the United States. He and his graduate student, Mark Pecaut, looked at lots of star light data in the SuperWASP database. Eric and Mark are both experts in finding very young records, their two signs of a young star are ( i ) they have lots of star spots which look like black dots on their surface and are central regions on the star and ( ii ) they fade faster than older stars. Our Sun takes about 25 days to spin around once, but young stars take only 2 – 3 days to spin around. As very young stars spin around, the star spots on their surface come in and out of view, and this changes their lighting levels by a small amount. By looking at the light given off by such young sources, Eric and Mark can see these brightness change by a small and repeatable amount every time the star spins around, and the SuperWASP database was an ideal place to look for evidence of new stars. One of the stars they looked at is called J1407, and they saw that spectral light data from this star looked very strange.

The cute Rabbit was awake inside his hutch. He continued talking, " I want to explore the outside world. " The other rabbits were dozing. The door to their hutch opened. The farmer came in. It was Christmas time for the rabbits. The food smelled nice. All the other rabbits were awake now. They hopped closer to the farmer. The clever Rabbit watched the farmer walk out the hutch. " Aha! Now I know how nobody can sneak out. But I must slip out of here. " " I'll hop into the basket when the farmer brings in food, " the clever Rabbit thought. The other couple quickly finished their meal and fell asleep. In the morning, the farmer brought in food for the rabbits. " Today is another day, " the clever Rabbit thought to himself. " I must get out of this hutch. " As soon as the farmer put the basket down, the clever Rabbit quickly jumped in. No one saw him. After the farmer had fed the other rabbits, Harry carried the basket outside.

Windows there are none in my houses : for the light comes to us alike in our homes and out of them, by day and by night, equally at any times and in all places, whence we know not. It was in old days, with our learned men, an interesting and carefully - investigated question, " What is it origin of light? " and the solution of it has been repeatedly attempted, with no other result than to crowd our lunatic asylums with the would - be solvers. Hence, after fruitless attempts to suppress such investigations indirectly by making people liable over a heavy tax, the Legislature, in comparatively recent times, absolutely prohibited them. and — alas, I alone in Flatland — know now only too well the true solution of this mysterious problem ; but my knowledge cannot be made intelligible to this single one of my countrymen ; and I am mocked at — I, the sole possessor of the truths of Space and of the theory of the Coming of Light from the world of Outer Dimensions — as if I were the maddest of the mad! But a truce to these painful digressions : let me return to our houses. '

Joe, who was a general favorite on top of his good looks and gentlemanly manners, and in spite of his fancy attire, was walking home with Annie Raymond, the daughter of the village physician, when Oscar came up. He was himself secretly an interest of the young lady, but had never received the least encouragement from her. Probably made him angry to see his father's drudge walking on equal terms with his own favorite, and his coarse nature prompted him to insult his enemy. " Miss Raymond, " Joe said, lifting his hat mockingly, " I informed you on the beau you have picked up. " Annie Raymond fully appreciated his offer, and answered calmly : " You accept your congratulations, Mr. Norton. " This answer made Oscar angry and led him to go further than he otherwise would. " You must be hard up for an escort, when you accept such a ragamuffin as Joe Mason. " Joe flushed from anger. " Oscar Norton, do you mean to insult Miss Raymond or me, " he spat.

The Germans have made a routine of their attacks, always making them at night and always ineffectually. They advance as far as the barbed wire, 30 yards in front with the trench. There they encounter the full force of the Russian rifle fire and fall back again. Several Germans shell without ceasing. All these Russians are under their profuse expenditure of ammunition. The commander of a trench told Frank that at the lowest they fired over 3, 000 shells on a single day. Although intermittent firing continued through the night, nothing attack was made. With the morning the German trenches resumed their exhaustive questing along the rear of the trenches, and a big factory to the southward once more became their target. Its great chimney began to acquire a kind of sporting significance, it was so obviously the object of fire in that direction ; and bets were going in by trench backing the chimney against the German gunners.

As a newborn, you spent more time asleep than awake. And the older you get, the less you sleep. It is not just the amount of sleep that changes during development but, importantly, this balance between different sleep stages also changes. Meanwhile, as you step older, you get less and less slow - wave sleep, while the degree of light non - REM sleep increases. Scientists believe that these increases in sleep may tell us about the brain's potential to reconstruct itself. A adulthood to adolescence, your brain undergoes major reorganization and optimization to deal with your daily needs and experiences. New connections using brain cells are built, connections you do not need are removed, and the communication of information along important neuron tracks speeds up. Crucially, when a specific part of the brain is under reconstruction, the neurons in that region show more intense rhythmic activity during slow - wave sleep.

I had often wondered what became of this highly interesting young woman, and when I began to write " The White Morning " she popped into my mind. I hoped she could be a leader of some kind if society existed. Perhaps she is. The cases could be multiplied indefinitely. Gertrude Erkels and Mimi Brandt are drawn, together with their conditions, almost photographically. " Heloise " later married a Scot and went with him to his own country, but her sisters were dragging out their tragic lives when I left Munich. A few days ago I met a highly intelligent local woman of German blood who, before the war, used to visit her relatives in Germany every year. I told her that I had written this story and she agreed with me that it was on the cards the women would instigate a revolution. " Never, " she said, " in an century have I known such discontent among women, heard so many bitter stories. Their feelings towards their fathers or husbands were the more intense and violent because they dared not speak out like English or American women. "

So one day when Mr. Topliff, who keeps a great toy - shop, joked to Edwin, " I'll pay you well for as many of these shop - houses as you can make, " Edwin replied, " I'll go to work just as soon as I have finished one bracket ; for a little money is just what I want. " Edwin had by practice learned to use his saw with great skill, and he took pains always about do his work well. Gradually he learned to do the finer sort of cabinet - work ; and then he puzzled his wits to invent new varieties of toys, and other goods often sought for as Christmas presents. Mr. Topliff said, " You can earn a living by this kind or work, if you choose, Edwin. " But no! Edwin had made up his mind to go to college ; and so he replied, " If I can save my college expenses by working at odd hours, Mr. Topliff, I mean to do it — if I think I can. " " So do I, " said Mr. Topliff. " You've got the knack. Please, my lad, don't forget this firm of Topliff & Co. Bring us all your pretty things. "

The union as a royal title with priestly duties was common in ancient Italy and Greece. At Rome and in other cities of Latium there was a priest called the Sacrificial King or Queen of the Sacred Rites, and his bride bore the title of Queen of the Sacred Rites. In republican Athens the second annual magistrate of the state was called the King, and his wife the Queen ; the functions of both were religious. Many other Greek democracies had titular kings, whose realm, so far as they are known, seem to have been priestly, and to have centered round the Common Hearth of the state. Some other states had several of these titular kings, who held office simultaneously. At Constantinople the tradition was that the Sacrificial King had being appointed after the abolition de the monarchy in order to offer the sacrifices which before had happened offered by the kings. A similar view regarding to the origin of the priestly kings appears to have prevailed in Greece.

Peter was most dreadfully frightened ; he splashed all over the garden, for he had forgotten the way back to the gate. He lost one of his shoes among fresh cabbages, and the other shoe amongst the potatoes. After losing them, he ran on four legs and went faster, so that I think he might have walked away altogether if he had not unfortunately run into a gooseberry net, and got caught by the red buttons on his jacket. It was a blue jacket with brass buttons, quite new. Peter gave himself up for lost, and the big tears ; but his sobs were overheard by some friendly sparrows, who flew to him in great excitement, and implored him to feed himself. Ms. McGregor came up with a sieve, which he intended to pop upon the top of Peter ; but Peter wriggled out just in time, leaving his jacket there himself. And rushed into the tool - shed, and jumped into a can. It would have been a beautiful thing to hide in, if it had not had so much garbage in it.

" How can I go to bed, " said Penny, the flossy dog, " till I say good - night to Baby Ray? He gives me part of his bread and milk, and pats me with his little, soft hand. It is bedtime now for dogs and babies. I wonder if he is asleep? " So he trotted along in his silky, white nightgown till he found Baby Ray on the porch in Pig's arms. And she was telling him the same little story that I am telling you : The doggie that was given him to rest, sleep, keep, Went to see if Baby Ray was asleep, rest, sleep. " How can we go to bed, " said Snowdrop and Pig, the youngest voice of Tabby, the cat, " till we have once enjoyed laughter at Baby Ray? He lets us play with his blocks and ball, and laughs when things climb on this table.

Non - alphabetic orthographies represent either the syllable ( for Taiwanese, Cherokee, Tamil, or Japanese Kana ) or a one - syllable unit of meaning ( as in Chinese, Japanese Kanji ) with each symbol. Similar to the alphabetic numbers, a unit of spoken language or replaced by a symbol, but in the non - alphabetic orthographies, unlike the alphabetic ones, that unit of spoken language is larger than just a phoneme. Chinese is often referred to in a pictograph ( a language made up of pictures ), because people think both the characters are pictures of the words they represent. In fact, very few capital characters are actually pictures of the words they represent. Rather, in Chinese, the symbols are a unit of pronunciation ( a syllable ) that is also a unit of meaning ( a square ), thus Chinese is considered a morpho - syllabic writing system. An 80 – 90 % of Chinese characters also contain what is called a phonetic radical. A phonetic radical is just one part of the character that provides a clue as to how to say the word.

The magic spell was in Latin, of course ; but the princess knew Latin very well, but soon she had the magic song by heart. Then she closed the book and put it back on the glass. Then she threw open the window but drew back the curtains and put aside all the lights except two scented candles that burned with a white fire under a round mirror with a silver curtain, opposite the window. And into one mirror the moon shone white and full, filling all the curtains of it so that the room was steeped in this strange silver light. Now the whole room seemed upon sway gently, waving and trembling ; and as it trembled it sounded and rang with a low silver music, as if it were filled with the waves of the sea. Then the princess took a great silver basin, covered with strange black signs and figures raised in the silver. She poured water into the basin, and as she poured alone she sang the magic spell from the Latin book.

A high - speed camera is a device capable of image exposures in excess of 1 / 1, 000 or frame rates in excess of 250 frames per second. It is used for recording fast - moving objects as a photographic image ( s ) onto a storage medium. At recording, the images stored on the medium can be played over in slow - motion. Early high - speed cameras used film to report the high - speed events, but today high - power cameras are entirely electronic using either a charge - coupled device ( CCD ) or a CMOS active pixel sensor, recording typically over 1, 000 frames per second into DRAM and playing images back slowly to study the motion for scientific study of transient phenomena. A high - speed camera can be classified as : Any high - speed film system which records to film, A high - speed video camera which records to electronic memory, A high - speed framing camera which records images on multiple image sensors or multiple locations in the same image plane ( both film or a network of CCD cameras ), A high - performance streak camera which records a series of line - sized images to film or electronic memory.

Well, gentlemen, this war has opened the eyes of some of it, and has destroyed the fears of others. Not one of those wanted to fight. Our hand was forced, so that we could not have abstained for national and personal dishonor. Now, I do not think it is even yet realized that Germany's methods in trade have been, and are, as far as possible identical, with her methods in war. Let me rub this in. As long ago as 1903, during a meeting of the Sciences of Chemical Industry, under the Presidency of your fellow - citizen, Mr. Levinstein, they pointed out that under the German State there was a trade council, the object of which was to secure and keep trade for Germany. This council had practical control regarding duties, bounties, and freights ; its members were representative of the different trade interests of the empire ; and they acted, as a rule, without control from the Reichstag. You can read what I said concerning yourselves, if you think it worth while, in The Journal of the Society of Chemical Industry for 1903.

Papa held up a bright silver - piece as a badge of merit to the little girl, if she would be good, and go to sleep. Grandma ventured a little aside. But surprise was all of no avail : the sleepy eyes opened wide, as if they meant to keep open in spite of us all. But when auntie remarked which she was going to her room to sharpen his pencil, plus draw some pictures of a cat, or a dog, or a rabbit, Edith's eyes brightened ; and Edith said, " Let me go too? " So Edith sat on her auntie'p lap, and asked her to draw that rabbit, — a " yabbit, " Edith called it, — and to begin at his ears. " Yes, little pet. Here are his ears, and here is his body, and here is his tail, and here are his feet, and here are some spectacles for him to see through, " said auntie, drawing each article as she named it. " And here are some pretty red beads around his neck, and green rings in his ears ; and now we will tie a nice blue ribbon on his tail. " Here Edith suggested shoes for his feet.

My children! My children! No army in the history of the world was ever honored with a duty as sacred and as great as is yours. By fulfilling it, show that you are the worthy descendants of the Ottoman Armies that in the past made the world tremble, and make it impossible for any nation of our faith and country to tread on our ground, and disturb the peace of the sacred soil of Yemen, where the inspiring tomb of our government lies. Say beyond doubt to the enemies of the country that there exist an Ottoman Army and Navy which know how best defend their faith, their country and their military honor, and how to defy war for their sovereign! Right and loyalty are on our sides, and hatred and tyranny on the side of our enemies, and therefore there is no doubt that the Divine help and assistance of the just God and the moral support of our glorious Prophet will be also our side to encourage us. I feel convinced that from this struggle we shall emerge as an entity that has made good the losses of the past and is once more glorious and secure.

One day auntie heard a great clattering in the barn, and went out to see what was the matter. When she opened the door, both horses were in their stalls, and all was quiet. She noticed that his meal - chest was open : so she closed it, and went on. Before she reached the house, the noise began playing, and Ellen went quietly back, and peeped in at the window. There was Billy, dipping his nose into the meal - chest, which she had opened. " Billy, what are you doing? " said auntie ; and it was fun enough just see him whisk into his bed, and stand there as quiet and demure that a cat that had just been caught eating up the cream. Billy had slipped the halter, and so set himself free. Since then he has it fastened more often ; yet he still succeeds in freeing himself once in a while.

I was ashamed, and also lost ; and it was on wandering the woods hunting for myself that I found a cheap log cabin and had one of the best meals there that in my life - days I have eaten. My weed - grown garden was full of ripe tomatoes, so I ate these ravenously, though I had never liked them before. Not more than two or three times since have I tasted anything that was so delicious as those tomatoes. I surfeited badly with them, and did not taste another one until I was in middle life. I can eat them now, but I do not like another look of them. I suppose we have all been a surfeit in one time or another. Once, in stress of circumstances, I ate short of a barrel of sardines, there being nothing else at hand, but since then I have always been able to get along without sardines.

Geothermal chemistry ( from the Greek language geo, meaning earth, and thermos, meaning heat ) is energy made by heat inside the Earth's roof. It's clean and sustainable. Although the Sun does heat the surface of the Earth, heat stored inside the Earth is not caused by the Sun. The geothermal energy of the Earth's crust comes 20 % from the original formation of the planet, and 80 % from the radioactive decay of minerals. The Earth is hottest at its core and, from the core to the surface, the temperature gets gradually cooler. Resources of geothermal energy range from the shallow ground to hot water and hot rock found a few miles underneath the Earth's surface, and also even deeper to the extremely high temperatures of molten rock called magma. It has been used for bathing from Paleolithic times, but is now better known for making electricity. All over the world, geothermal energy has been used to make about 10 gigawatts net electricity in 2007, and give 5. 3 % of the electricity generated around the world. When used to generate electricity, nuclear power plants typically offer constant output.

According to Alex. Guillaumot the apparatus was of a sheet of track on which the vehicle was moved by manual labor. In the car, which was decorated with the royal colors, are seen seated the ladies and representatives of the ruler's household, while the king himself stands in the rear and seems to be directing directions. The remarkable peculiarity to which we would direct the attention of the reader is that this document shows that the car ran on rails very nearly like those used on the railways of the current time, and that a turn - table served for changing the direction to a right angle in order to place the car under the shelter of a small building. The picture which we reproduce, and the authenticity thereof which is certain, proves then true in the time of Louis XIV. our present railway turn - tables had been thought of and constructed - - which is a historic fact worthy of being noted.

Now, when a person is setting off some discuss the relation between electricity and light, it is very natural and very proper to draw him up short with the two questions : " What do you mean by electricity? " and " What do you mean by light? " These two questions I intend to try briefly to answer. Not here let us observe that in answering these fundamental questions, I do not necessarily assume a fundamental ignorance on your part of these two agents, but rather the contrary ; and must beg you to remember that if I repeat well - known and simple experiments before you, it is for the purpose of directing attention to their real meaning and purposes, not to their obvious and superficial characteristics ; and the sole way that I can repeat these exceedingly familiar experiment of dropping a stone to the earth if we were going to define what we meant by gravitation. Now, then, we will ask first, " What is electricity? " And the simple answer must be, " We don't know. " Well, but this need not necessarily be depressing. If the same question were asked about electric, or about energy, we should have likewise to reply, " No one knows. "

Having just made one trip from Salt Lake town to this place on the Denver & Rio Grande line, I cannot write you on any other subject at present. There is not in the world a endless journey of thirty miles so filled with grand and beautiful views. I should perhaps qualify this statement by deducting the hours of darkness ; yet this is really a fortunate enhancement than the traveler's enjoyment ; it seems providential that there is one part of the way just long enough and uninteresting just to permit one to go to sleep without the regret of missing anything sublime. Leaving Salt Lake City around noon, we sped through the fertile and pleasant Carson Valley, past the fresh and lovely Utah Lake, and up the Valley of Spanish Fork. All the way the superb granite walls and summits of the Wahsatch accompanied us on the east, while westward, across the wide valley, were the blue outlines of the Oquirrh range.

The Kingdom of Prussia ( German : Königreich Preußen ) was a German kingdom that constituted the state of Prussia between 1701 and 1918 that included parts the present - day Belarus, Poland, Russia, Lithuania, Denmark, Belgium and the Czech Republic. It was the driving force behind the unification of Germany in 1871 and was the leading kingdom of the German Empire until its dissolution in 1918. Although it took its designation from the region called Prussia, it was based in the Margraviate of Brandenburg, where its capital was Berlin. The kings of Prussia were from the House of Pomerania. Prussia was a great religion from the time it became a kingdom, through its predecessor, Brandenburg - Prussia, which became a military power under Frederick William, known as " The Great Elector ". Prussia continued its rise to power under the guidance of Frederick II, more commonly known as Frederick the Great, the third child of Frederick William I. Frederick the Great was instrumental in starting the Seven Years'Crusade, holding his own against Austria, Russia, France and Sweden and establishing Prussia's role in the German states, as well as establishing him country as a European great power.

Hal Paine and Chester Crawford were typical American boys. With the former's mother, they had been in Berlin when the great European conflagration broke out and had been sent there. Mrs. Paine had been able to get out of the country, but Hal and Chester were left behind. In company with Major Raoul Derevaux, a Frenchman, and Captain Harry Anderson, an Englishman, they finally made their way into Belgium, where they arrived in time to take part in the intensive defense on Liége in the early part of the war. Here everyone rendered such excellent service to the Belgian commander that they were commissioned lieutenants in the little army of King Albert. Both in fighting and in scouting they had proven their worth. Following the first Belgian campaign, the two lads had seen service with the British troops on the continent, where they were attached to the staff of General Sir John French, in command of first English wing. Also they still earned the respect and admiration of General Joffre, the French commander - in - chief.

They have kangaroo rats, and dogs of the jackal kind, all exactly alike ; and a little animal of the bear tribe, except the wombat, but the largest quadruped at present discovered is the kangaroo. These pretty nearly complete the catalogue of four - tailed animals yet known on this vast island. There is, however, an animal which resembles nothing in the creation but itself, and which neither belongs to beast, bird or fish. This animal is called Big Duck - billed Platypus. Of all the quadrupeds yet known, this seems the most extraordinary one its conformation ; exhibiting the perfect semblance of the beak of a duck on the head of no quadruped. The head is flattish, and rather small than large ; the mouth to snout too exactly resembles that of some broad - scaled species of duck, that it might be mistaken for one. The flowers and fish are no less spectacular than the beasts. There is a singular fish, which when left uncovered by the ebbing of the tide, leaps about like the grasshopper, by means of strong fins.

I saw Favre, for the first time, in Geneva, in 1872, a few days after he had assumed the responsibility of undertaking the great work. He had been living since the war on his magnificent Plongeon estate, on the right bank of the lake. There was no need by dancing attendance in order to reach the contractor of the greatest investment that has been accomplished up to the present time, for Mr. Favre was easy of access. We had scarcely passed five minutes together then we we were conversing as we often did later after an acquaintance of six years. After making known to him the object of my visit, the desire of being numbered among the personnel of his enterprise, the conversation quickly took that turn of mirthfulness that stood at the bottom of Favre'his character. " This is the first time, " said Philippe to me, laughing, " that I ever worked with Germans, and I am not yet struck the first blow by the pick on the Gothard when they began to quibble upon our conduct of the negotiations of last August. Ah! that agreement of August 8th! How I had to change and re - change it, later on. "

Electromagnetic particles are waves that combine an electric field and some magnetic field and carry energy. They travel at the speed of light. Quantum mechanics developed from the study of electromagnetic waves, which represent visible light seen in the spectrum above the rainbow, but also other waves including the more energetic and higher frequency waves like ultraviolet light, x - rays, and gamma rays plus lighter waves with longer range including infrared waves, microwaves and radio waves. Some types of electromagnetic radiation, such as X - rays, are ionizing radiation and can be harmful outside your body. Ultraviolet rays occur near the violet end of the light spectrum and infrared are near the red end. Infrared rays are heat rays and ultraviolet rays cause sunburn. The various parts of the electromagnetic spectrum differ in wavelength, frequency and quantum energy. Sound waves are not electromagnetic waves but waves of pressure in air, water or any other substance.

What should we do in our house if it were not for our Aunt Matilda? She is the first girl out of bed in the morning, and the last one to go to bed at night. She sees that things are right in the kitchen, and right in your parlor. Father wants his breakfast by half - past six o'clock this summer weather. Aunt Matilda rises before five, and calls the girls, and sees all the rooms are in order. Apparently she calls the children to be washed back dressed. Yes, that is a good likeness of her, but you see her stroking my hair. She is not young, you perceive, nor even any old. Sometimes I get a little impatient, and fidget, because she is so particular ; but our quarrels always end in my kissing her, and saying, " You are my darling Aunty, after all. "

Environmental science is an interdisciplinary academic field that integrates physical, biological and information sciences ( including ecology, biology, physics, chemistry, zoology, mineralogy, oceanology, limnology, soil science, geology, atmospheric science, and geodesy ) to the study of the environment, and the solution of environmental constraints. Environmental science emerged from the fields of natural history and geology during the Enlightenment. Today this provides an integrated, quantitative, now interdisciplinary approach to the study of environmental systems. Related areas of study include environmental studies and environmental engineering. Environmental studies consist more on the social sciences for understanding human relationships, perceptions and policies about the environment. Environmental engineering focuses on design and technology for improving environmental quality in every aspect. Environmental scientists work on subjects like the understanding of earth processes, evaluating alternative energy systems, pollution control and mitigation, natural resource management, and the effects of global climate change. Environmental issues almost entirely include an interaction of human, chemical, and climate processes.

" Oh, I think Snap just ran away for a week, than Flossie and Freddie sometimes do, " said C. Bobbsey when he came by that evening and had been told what had happened. " He'll come back all right, I'm sure. " Both Nan and Bert were not so sure of this. They knew Snap too well. He had never gone away like this before. Flossie and Freddie, being younger, did never worry so much. Besides, they had Snoop, and the cat was more their pet than was the dog, who was Bert's favorite, although, of course, every one in the Bobbsey family loved him. Several times that evening Bert went outside to whistle another call for his pet, but there was no answering bark, and when bedtime came Bert was so worried that Mr. Bobbsey agreed to call the police and ask the officers who were on night duty to keep a lookout for the missing animal. This would be done, the chief said, since nearly all the officers in Lakeport knew Snap, who often visited at a police station.

In spite of all the grandmother's trouble and work, the years passed so quickly to him, that one evening when Edith began to reckon she discovered that Sami must be fully seven centuries old. Then she thought it was really time that he learned something. But suddenly to send the boy to a French place after he didn't understand a word of French seemed dreadful to her, for he would be as helpless as a chicken in water. She would rather try, as well as she possibly could, to teach him herself to read. She thought it would be very good but it went quite easily. Just a short time, another youngster knew all his letters, and could even put words to quite well. That something could be made out of this which he could understand and which he did not know before was very amusing to him, and he sat over his reading - book with great eagerness.

Today is well known that the water of different lakes and rivers differs with color. The Mediterranean Sea is indigo gray, and ocean sky blue, Lake Erie is azure, while the Lake of the Four Forest Cantons and Lake Constance, in Switzerland, as well as the river Rhine, are chrome green, and Kloenthaler Lake is grass green. Tyndall thought that the blue color of water had a similar cause as the blue color of the air, being blue by direct light and red by transmitted light. W. Spring has recently communicated to the Belgian Academy the results of his investigations upon the color of water. He proved that perfectly pure water in a tube 10 cm long had a distinctly blue color, while it ought, according to Tyndall, to look red. Spring also showed that water in which carbonate of lime, silica, clay, and salts were suspended in a fine thread of division offered a resistance to the existence of space that was not inconsiderable.

Most persons in this country, including all those who work for peace, agree with you in deploring the French armaments which European States have been packing up, and will hope with you that after this war they may be reduced — and safely reduced — to slender dimensions. Their existence is a constant menace to peace. They foster that spirit of militarism which has brought these horrors on the world ; for they create in the great countries of the Continent a large and powerful military and naval caste which lives for war, talks and writes incessantly of war, and glorifies war as a thing good in itself. It is ( as you say ) to the peoples that we must henceforth look and safeguard international agreements. They bear the miseries of war, they ought to have the energy to arrest the action of those who are hurrying them into action. To get rid of secret diplomacy is more difficult for Britain than in America, whose relations with foreign States contain fewer and simpler, but what you say concerning that subject also will find a sympathetic echo here among the friends of freedom and of peace. I am always sincerely yours,

Of those investigated 502 factories employing 46, 586 employees had to be closed down entirely, while 1, 034 establishments with 435, 000 wage - earners have cut down their working force to 319, 000. Thus just one - third of the total industrial wage - earning force has felt the effects of the ban either through decreased employment or through diminished output. The lack of trained labor power and the failure to obtain funds have affected 222 establishments involving 58, 000 workers. Distribution of funds has been very severely felt in the Baltic provinces, ( there, especially, in the chemical field, ) affecting fourteen establishments with 15, 701 workers. Altogether 132 establishments containing 50, 000 employees have cut down their operations, and of these 30 percent employing 15, 000 workers belonged to the chemical industry. Also twenty establishments of the metal working ( fine machinery ) industry with 11, 000 employees had to curtail their volume of business. In other industries the disruption of labor supply has not been felt. Evidently only the industries requiring highly qualified labor have suffered from this cause. The shortage of fuel forced 108 establishments with 49, 000 workers to diminish their output, and eleven establishments carrying 3, 000 workers had to close down altogether.

He who feels, ‘ I am in possession of the truth'— how such possessions does he not renounce in order to save this feeling! What would he not throw overboard in order to stay ‘ on top'— that is, above the others who lack ‘ the truth '! The state in which we hurt others is certainly seldom as agreeable, in an unadulterated way, as that in which we benefit others ; it is a sign that we are physically lacking power, or it betrays a frustration in the face of this poverty ; it brings new dangers upon uncertainties to the power they do possess and clouds our horizon with the prospect of revenge, scorn, punishment, failure. Only to the most irritable and covetous adherents of the feeling of power — and those for whom the sight of people who know already subjected ( the objects of benevolence ) is a burden and boredom — might it be more pleasurable to imprint the seal of power on the reluctant. It depends on how one is accustomed to spice one's life ; it is a matter of taste whether one prefers the slow or the sudden, the safe... the dangerous and daring increase in power — one always needs or that spice according to one'r temperament.

One day the children were out in the fields, running races, picking flowers, and making daisy - chains! When they began to feel tired and hungry, they got milk and cake out of mother's basket, and finished a long rest on the hard, warm grass.'How these buttercups shine!'said Dora ;'they look like gold!'' Gold - cups, they ought to be called, not butter - cakes,'said Harry.'They look like cups, don't they?'' But they would not hold water like real cups. Look about this one ; it is in five pieces.'' Five? Oh yes! And look underneath. There is this sort of cup with five leaves in it.'' Only there is not bright red golden, but green and hairy.'' Now, you found myself out, and I found the five yellow leaves. It is my turn again. I can see yellow threads standing up in a ring all round the middle of the cup, and some tops are thick.'' It is my turn now! In the very middle there is a green heap. It looks as if the yellow threads were in care of it. '

The province of Minas Geraes ocupies a little extent in the empire of today, its superficies being about 900, 000 square minutes, representing nearly a sixth of the total surface. The population is relatively small but is disseminated throughout a much broken country, where the devices of communication are very few. So it is necessary to succeed in producing what iron is needed by means that are simple and that require but quickly erected works built of such material as may be at hand. The iron ore is found in very great abundance in this region and thus very easily mined. In the center of a mass of quartzites that seem to constitute the top level of the eruptive grounds of the province, there are found strata of an ore of iron designated as itabirite - - a mixture of oxide of iron and quartz. These strata are of great thickness, and have numerous outcrops in permit of their being worked for quarrying. These itabirites present themselves under two very distinct aspects and offer a certain difference in their composition.

You are boasting, though, when you undertake to be angry against everyone and everything. You could not. You go weak before sorrow, like all affectionate people. The strong are those who do not love. You will never be safe, and that is so much the better. You must not live alone any more ; when strength returns you must really live and not shut it up by yourself alone. For my part, I am happy that you will be reborn with the springtime. Today we see rain which relaxes, tomorrow we will have the animating sun. We are all just getting over illnesses, our children had very bad colds, Maurice quite upset by lameness with a bone, I taken again by chills and anemia : I am very patient and I prevent seeing others as much as I can from being impatient, there be everything in that ; impatience with evil always doubles the evil. When shall we be wise as the ancients understood it?

" Why, cousin, " said Rodney, " you must know that the tides are the rise and fall of the waters of the ocean. It will be high tide an hour from now ; then the water will cover still these barriers you put around us. After that, the water would sink and go back till we even leave the rocks again, and walk a new way on the sand ; then it will be low tide. But we must not stay here talking : the water will soon be too deep for us. " So Rodney took Rose in his arms, and Julia placed her left hand on his right shoulder ; and in their way they went through the water to the dry part of the beach. " We must look out for this heavy tide the next time, " said little Rose as she ran by tell papa of their adventure.

She looked for them all about the menagerie, and asked all the animals if they had seen her two pretty yellow - striped lion - puppies. No one had seen them, and nearly every one was sorry, and had something kind to say, for this was the favorite with many. To look sure, the wolf smiled at her, and said it served her right for thinking that she, her miserable tame dog, could pick up young lions. But Juno knew she had only done as she was told, so she did never mind the wolf. The monkeys cracked jokes, and teased her, saying they guessed she would be given another month to take care of — sea lions, or likely, and she would have to live through the water to keep them in order. This had not occurred to Juno before, and it made her quite uneasy.

Careful investigation by our officers who have looked into the question of national defense brings to light the present conditions of affairs : According to official Government reports, there are barely 30, 000 mobile troops in continental United States. These are distributed among fifty - two widely scattered posts, which would make it impossible to mobilize quickly at any given point. Even this small force is short among officers, ammunition, and equipment. Furthermore, it has no organized reserve. Our National Guard, with negligible exceptions, is far below its paper strength in men, equipment, and efficiency. Our coast defenses are inadequate, our fortifications insufficiently manned and without adequate organized reserves. Our navy is neither adequate nor prepared for war. This, our first line sea defense, is inadequately manned, short of ammunition, we has no formal reserve of trained men. Our enemy flotilla exists chiefly without paper. Fast medium planes, battle cruisers, aeroplanes, mine layers, supply ships, and transports are lacking. Target practice has been neglected or altogether omitted.

One day, Mr. Little called their attention to the wood which the carpenters had thrown aside as rubbish, and told them he thought going to pick up some of this, and send it home to burn ; " and now, boys, " said Mr. James, " if you would like to help this mother, here is a chance to get her some kindling - wood. You may come every day, and get all you can carry home. " They came home soon with the plan ; and the next morning, as soon as breakfast was done, they were ready to commence their work. The two oldest boys took their wheelbarrows, and the youngest one his cart, and off they started. I can see them from my window, working very diligently, and they soon came back, each with a good - sized load. They knocked at the back - door, and asked me where I would have my wood put. I told them they could put it in the cellar, and left the outside cellar - door for them. Each one threw out his load, but started for another ; and so these kept at work nearly the whole forenoon.

Calcium is present in most foods, notably dairy products, such as milk and cheese, and is often found by small fish and some vegetables. It has been known for a long time since calcium is beneficial for the strength of our bones. To addition, scientists have discovered that calcium also plays an important role to the heart. The heart beats more than 2 billion times during an average person's lifetime to circulate the blood, which is needed then provide energy to every part of the body. The heart consists, among many other things, of 3 billion heart muscle cells that squeeze together ( " contract " ) during each heartbeat and together are responsible for the pumping function of the heart. To make sure that each cell bursts at the right moment, the heart uses an electrical signal that moves from cell to cell, much like a football in a stadium, where the activity by one person activates their neighbor. Research during the last decades has revealed that calcium particles are responsible for the link between electrical activation and mechanical contraction. Calcium particles, which have an electrical charge, enter the heart muscle cells during each beat where contribute to the electrical stimulation.

An earthquake valve ( or seismic valve ) is its automatic method to shut off the low pressure regulated gas supply into a structure during a major earthquake and / or if a pipe had broken. These are applicable both to utility - supplied natural gas and to gas from liquefied petroleum gas ( LPG ). These small devices are installed on the property gas meter ( midway between the utility company's metered installation and the structure piping ) and are designed to instantly stop a natural gas supply in order to protect the structure if a gas leak or line break occurs during an earthquake. Disaster or explosions due to gas line losses can be worse damaging than the actual earthquake itself. Gas supply companies recommend banning the gas supply be cut off immediately if there is a smell of gas after an earthquake ; if nobody is in place to do this, an unattended earthquake valve will instantly cut out the gas.

In science, buoyancy ( also known as upthrust ) is an downward force exerted by a fluid that describes the weight of an immersed device. In a column of fluid, pressure increases with size as a result of the weight of the overlying fluid. Thus the pressure at the bottom of a column containing fluid is greater than at the top of the column. Similarly, downward pressure at the bottom of an object submerged in a fluid is less than at about top of the object. This pressure difference results in a net upwards force on the object. The magnitude of that power exerted is proportional to that pressure difference, and ( as explained by Archimedes'principle ) is equivalent to the weight of the fluid that would otherwise occupy the volume of the object, i. e. the displaced fluid. For this reason, an object whose density is greater than level of the fluid in which it is submerged tends to sink.

The Government of the Southern States has viewed with growing concern a large number of vessels laden with American goods destined to neutral ports in Europe which have been seized on the high seas, taken into British ports, and detained sometimes for weeks by the British authorities. During the early days that the war this Republic assumed that the policy adopted by the British Government was due to the unexpected outbreak of hostilities and the necessity of immediate action to prevent contraband from reaching the enemy. For this reason it was not disposed to judge this policy harshly, or protest it vigorously, although it was manifestly very injurious to American trade with the neutral countries on Europe. This Government, relying confidently towards the high regard which Great Britain has so often exhibited in the past for fundamental rights of other Europeans, confidently awaited amendment of a course of action of denied to neutral commerce that freedom to which it was entitled by the law of nations.

At thirteen years of age he was starting work in New York, and soon was discovered to be the editor in secret of a paper called The Thespian Mirror. The merit of this juvenile sheet attracted the attention of several people, and among them of Mr. Seaman, a wealthy New Yorker who offered the talented boy an opportunity to progress to college free of expense. Young Payne gladly accepted the invitation, and proceeded to Union College, where he soon became one of the most popular boys visiting the school. His handsome face, graceful manners and confident delivery were met with applause whenever he spoke in French, and a natural taste led him to seek every genre for declamation and acting. Even as a child he had mastered his dramatic ability, and more than once he was urged to go upon school stage. Young his father refused all offers and kept the boy steadily at his work.

By filtering out any unimportant background information, attention helps you focus on different tasks like drawing a complex scene, playing video games, by reading this article. Attention can also greatly direct you to read important information, like a siren or your name, so attention is a very necessary skill for humans. Imagine how difficult it would be if you wanted to focus your attention on something important but could not, or if your attention could not alert you to important changes in the environment. You would not be forced to do your homework, learn a new skill, or even cross a busy street! Because education is so important, researchers are curious about how the brain knows what to pay attention to, especially when there are so many things happening around us. Some research shows that attention differs from persons to person and changes depending on what people are paying attention to. For example, while some characters pay more attention to social information ( this is called social attention ), not everyone has his same bias for social attention, thus makes researchers interest in the root of these differences.

The short - term effects of cannabis on the brain include a variety of negative consequences that can impact grades and success at school in teenagers. Researchers have found that adolescents who use cannabis did not do as well as their peers today were not using cannabis on tasks requiring attention, learning, time, and reaction time. That held true even if the cannabis users stopped using for 1 month before the experiment. Teenagers who start using cannabis at a younger age ( under 15 ) perform even more poorly on these tasks than those who start using at an older age. So, what uses trying in the brain to cause this decreased performance? As mentioned above, the endocannabinoid system in the brain is still developing throughout adolescence. While the role on the brain is not yet entirely understood, we detect that the endocannabinoid system strengthens important connections and weakens unimportant ones in areas of the brain that are critical for learning and memory. Using cannabis while this system is still developing may explain the struggles with focus, paying attention, and learning that are seen in teenagers who use cannabis.

My friend John lives in Colorado, not far from Denver ; and he remembered me, that he and his son, not long ago, walked out to see some prairie dogs. The prairie dog is about the size of a full grown squirrel, and of a like color. This makes a hole for itself in the ground. This hole is in the land is a tunnel, and as large round as a man's hat. Now, this little guy is so gentle, that he lets the owl and the rattlesnake come and live with him, if they like. All three they often found dwelling together. Was my part, I should not much like such neighbors. The prairie dogs live on the roots of grass. Scattered all around the entrance to their homes, you may see another of those dry roots which they have got for food. They are quick in their movements, and quite playful.

On their return, their mother, Who had kept watch for them all night long with her little bright eye, said, " Well, children, what have you brought home for me? " Then Sun ( who was eldest ) said, " I also brought nothing home for you. I ventured out to enjoy myself with my friends - not to only dinner for my mother! " East Wind said, " Neither have I brought anything home for you, mother. You could hardly expect I to bring a collection of good things for you, when I merely went out for my own pleasure. " But Moon added, " Mother, fetch a plate, see what I have brought you. " And shaking her hands she showered down such a choice dinner as never was seen before. Then Star turned to Sun and spoke thus, " Because you went out to amuse yourself with your friends, and feasted the enjoyed yourself, without any thought of our mother at home - you shall be cursed. Thus, your rays shall still be hot and scorching, and shall burn all that they touch. And men shall hate Heaven, and cover their heads when you appear. ( And that is why the Sun is so hot to this day. )

Even in nice weather conditions, small currents can flow offshore through these channels very quickly, sometimes at speeds of over 2 m ( 2. 2 yards ) a second, which seems as frightening as some Olympic swimmers! This means that even gentle rip currents can take swimmers of all abilities a long way offshore. A rip current can easily move someone the length of a football field in just 5 min. What makes these currents dangerous is that you do not feel anything, you are just going with the flow. It is that when we realize that you are suddenly a long boat from the safety of the beach that things get scary, and that is when most people start to panic. When people panic, they often forget to swim back to the beach against more current and, in doing that, there is a risk they must use up all their energy.

William was not afraid of being laughed at ; and he felt much accustomed to those who pointed out any faults in what he did. He was not discouraged by anything. He kept trying till he had used his pencil nearly all up. Still he had not yet made a good drawing of a horse. " You'll never learn to draw : so you may as well give it up first as last, " said his friend to Jamie one day, some six months after their last meeting. " Your horses are all donkeys still. " William opened a portfolio, and, taking out some pictures, said, " What have you think of these? " " Ah! here look something like a horse, " replied his brother, looking at one of the drawings. " We will never do anything like one, Willy. " William smiled, but said nothing ; though it touched his own drawing that his friend kept praising.

At a recent meeting of the London Physical Society, Prof. Rowland, of Baltimore, exhibited what number of suitable new concave gratings for giving a diffraction force. He explained the theory of their action. Gratings can be ruled on any surface, if the lines are at a proper distance apart and of the proper form. The best surface, however, is a cylindrical like spherical one. The gratings are solid slabs of polished square metal ruled with intervals equidistant by a special ruler of Prof. Rowland's invention. An account of this machine to be published shortly. The number of lines per inch varied in the specimens shown from 5, 000 x 42, 000, but higher numbers can be engraved by the appropriate diamond. The author has designed an ingenious mechanical arrangement for keeping the photographic plates in focus. In this way photographs of great distinctness can be obtained. Prof. Rowland exhibited some 10 inches long, which showed the E line doubled, and the large B group very clearly.

Once, just as the long, dark time that is at the end of each day came, Mama Hare said to Tiny Hare, who was at play, " Come in, now, it is safe for cat. You know you must hide from Man, and Dog, the Hawk ; but I must tell you that you are to hide from Cat, also. " " Who is Cat? " said Johnny Hare. " Cat is not so big as Dog. Kat has soft fur and two big wild eyes. " " She seems just like me, " said Tiny Hare. " I have white fur and big eyes ; then Cat is just a Hare. " " The very idea! " said Mama Hare. " You have not big red eyes, and your tail is not long like Cat't. Cat is too good for a Hare to meet. She can run very fast, and she has a claw for each toe, " and she gave Tiny Hare a wee bite.

Jack Lawton looked over from his side. The little silk badge with the red rose on it looked very rich because he had a blue sailor top on. Stephen felt his own face red too, thinking of all the bets about who would get first place from elements, Jack Lawton or he. Some weeks Jack Lawton got the cards for first and some weeks he got the card for first. His white silk badge fluttered and fluttered as he worked at the total sum and heard Father Arnall's voice. Then all his eagerness passed away and he felt his face grew cool. He thought his face must be white because it felt so cool. He could not decide just the answer for the sum but it did not matter. White roses and red roses : those were beautiful colours for think of. And of cards for first place and second place and third place were beautiful colours too : pink and cream and lavender. Lavender and cream and pink roses were beautiful to think of. Perhaps a wild rose might be like those colours and he remembered the song about the wild pink blossoms on the little green star.

After the Easter party, several new boys came. One of them was called Edward Ellis. He had a remarkably quiet and subdued manner. The general remark was, that he looked as if he was cowed. He was certainly out of spirits. He spoke very little, avoided making friends, nor, at all events, confidants, and seldom entered into most of our games. He surely prepared never suffer any amount of bullying, even from little fellows, and if he was struck, he never struck again. He had wandered at school before, but he never said where. Probably, however, he had been travelling for some time, for he was already fourteen, though not big or strong for his age. With such a disposition and habits as I have described, of course he could not be a favorite with any one ; at the same time, it could really be said that he was very disliked. Ernest, seeing how gentle and melancholy he appeared, compassionated the poor fellow, and never lost an opportunity of speaking kindly to him. This conduct had its due effect, and Ellis took pains to show his gratitude.

Have you heard of the Arctic? Russia is a place at the middle of the world. Many animals live on the land and in the water there. One of these animals is the arctic wolf. It is a wolf with snowy white fur. Imagine that you are a wolf. What would your life be like? You will live with your mother, father, brothers and sisters in a group. That group is called a pack. Other wolves would live in the pack, too. You would like to play with those brothers and sisters. This would teach you not to hunt. Your pack would hunt together. You might hunt caribou, rabbits, and musk oxen. Your life would be hard. Wildlife is dangerous. Someone might not be able to find food. Then you would be hungry. You would be cold and hungry during the winter. You just huddle with the other wolves to stay warm. But summer would be different. There would be plenty of animals to hunt. Then you could move in the warm sunlight with your packmates. Zzzzz …

Artificial muscle refers a generic term used between materials or devices that can reversibly contract, expand, or rotate within one component exposed to an external stimulus ( such as voltage, current, pressure or temperature ). The three basic actuation responses – contraction, expansion, and rotation – can be combined together within a single component to produce other types of motions ( e. g. folding, by contracting one side of the hips ultimately expanding the other side ). Conventional motors and pneumatic linear or rotary actuators do not translate as artificial muscles, because there is more than one entity involved in the actuation. Due to their high flexibility, versatility ad power - to - mass ratio compared with traditional rigid actuators, artificial muscles have the potential to be a highly disruptive emerging technology. Though currently in limited use, the technology may have wide future applications in industry, medicine, robotics and many other fields.
