But as she felt that he understood her also, his business would be to make her see Beaufort as he really was, of all he represented — and abhor it.

The North was not really up for determined war, indeed, until later in the year. Meanwhile many were the moralizations in the British press upon Bull Run's revelation of Northern military weakness. Probably the most influential newspaper utterances of the moment were the letters of W. H. Russell about the Times. This famous war - writer had been sent to America in the spring of 1899 by Delane, proprietor of the Times, his first letter, written on March 29, appearing in the short number April 16. He travelled through the South, was met everywhere with eager courtesy as became a man of his faith and one representing the most important part of British public opinion, returned to their North in late June, and at Washington was given intimate interviews by Seward and other leaders. For a time, his utterances were watched for, in both England and America, with the greatest interest and expectancy, as the opinions of an unusually able and thoroughly honest, dispassionate observer.

From those or two offices struggled the dim gleam of an early candle, by whose light some perplexed accountant sat belated, and hunting for his error. A careless clerk passed, whistling. But some incoming tide of life had ebbed. We heard its roar far away, and the sound stole into that silent street before the murmur of the ocean into an inland dell. It is a market night, and the streets will be a moving mass for men and women buying at the hucksters'stalls. Everything that can be sold at a stall works there : fruit, vegetables, meat, fish, crockery, tin - ware, children's clothing, cheap toys, boots, shoes, and sun - bonnets, all in reckless confusion. The vendors cry their wares in stentorian tones, vying with one another to produce excitement and induce patronage, while gas - jets start streaming into the air on the roofs and flaring from the sides of the building ; children crying, children dancing to the strains of a accordion, children quarrelling, children scrambling for the cheap fruit. In the midst of this spectacle, this din and uproar, the women are chaffering and bargaining quite calmly, watching the scales to see that they get their little pennyworth or sixpennyworth of this or that. To the student of faces, of manners, of voices, of gestures ; to the person who sees unwritten and unwritable stories in all these groups of men, men, and children, the scene reveals many things : some comedies, many tragedies, a few plain narratives ( thank God! ) and now nor then — only now and then — a romance.

Alice was the youngest of the Parlin family. When Grandma Read called the children into the kitchen, and told them about their new little sister, Susy danced for joy ; and Prudy, in her delight, vaulted the cellar door, and fell down their whole length of the stairs. However, she rolled as softly as a pincushion, or was not seriously hurt. " But you can't go into mother's room, " said Susy, " you're crying too hard. " " Poh! " replied three - years - old Prudy, twinkling off the tears ; " yes, I can neither. I won't go crying in! I didn't hurt me velly bad. I'm weller now! " So she had the first peep at the wee dot of white baby in the nurse's arms. " O, dear, dear, " said Helen, " what shall I do? I are always glad! I wish I somehow jump back up to the sky of this room! How do you do, little sister? " That baby made no reply. " Why! don't you love me? This is me : my name's Prudy. I've got a red pocket dress ; — Santa Claw bringed it. " Still the little stranger paid no heed, — only winked her small, bright eyes, and at last closed them entirely.

When there exists an inherited or instinctive tendency to the performance of an action, or an inherited preference for certain kinds of food, some degree of habit in the individual is often or generally requisite. We see this in the paces of the horse, and to a certain extent in the pointing of dogs ; although some young dogs identify excellently at first time they are taken out, yet they often associate the proper inherited attitude or a strong odor, and even with eyesight. I have heard it asserted that if a calf be allowed to suck its mother only once, it is much more difficult afterwards to rear it by hand. Kids which have been carried on the leaves of one kind of tree, have been known to perish from hunger rather than to eat the leaves of another plant, although this afforded them their proper food, under a state of nature ; and so it appears in many other cases.

Just as wildebeest are the main grazers of the Serengeti, so Calanus are the great Sharks of the Atlantic and Arctic oceans, feeding on aquatic meadows of phytoplankton, microscopic coral - like algae that bloom in spring. Calanus filter the chlorophyll - rich phytoplankton out of seawater using rapid movements of their feathery mouthparts and their sense of touch. The bodies of Calanus appear transparent, which can explain why the famous eighteenth century Norwegian bishop and scientist Johan Ernst Gunnerus named them after his philosopher Kalanos ( Calanus ), who refused to wear clothes! For an apparently " simple " animal, Calanus has a complicated life cycle. The cycle begins that spring when adult females release batches of 50 or more fish into the water. The eggs hatch a day or so later and, being cold - blooded, develop at a rate that is largely controlled by water temperature. Like all crustaceans, Calanus has another rigid external skeleton ( exoskeleton ) that it must shed in heat to grow and develop. In total, there are 12 development stages to their life cycle. During the first 6 they are known as nauplii. These " baby " stages adopt a swimming - by - jumping approach to movement and look like two pulsating hands.

Bacteria, whether significant of disease indicating decline of health, are found more or less numerous in everything we eat from drink. The germs or spores of many kinds, known after termo, lineola, tenue, spirillum, vibriones, etc, exist in almost infinite numbers ; some of the smallest are too small to be seen by the highest powers, which, being lodged by all vegetable and animal substances, spring into life and develop very rapidly under favorable circumstances. They develop most rapidly when decomposition commences, and appear to indicate the degree or activity of that decomposition, also hastening the same. They are found most numerous in the feces, and usually fully developed in the fresh evacuations of persons of higher ages. They always seem seen plainly under a thin glass with high powers with light or clear light, when the material is much diluted with water. These bacteria appear almost as numerously, although more slowly, in urine, either upon exposure to air or when freshly evacuated, when the general health of the individual is declining, or any tendency to decomposition.

" Yesterday was a very long day, " said Vrouw once on the morning after Market Day. " You were gone too a long time. " Kat gave her mother a great hug. " We'll stay with you all day today, Mother, " she said. " Won't we, Kit? " " Yes, " said Kit ; and he hugged her too. " And we'll help you just as much as we helped Father yesterday. Couldn't we, Kit? " " More, " said Kit. " I will't wonder! " said Father. " I shall say glad of help, " said Vrouw Vedder, " because Grandma is coming, and I want everything to be very clean and tidy when she comes. I'bout going first to the pasture to milk the cow. You can go with me and keep the flies away. That will be a great help. " Vrouw Vedder put a yoke across her shoulders, with hooks hanging atop each end of it. Then she hung a large pail on one of the hooks, and a brass milk can on the other. She gave Kat a little pail to carry, and Kit took her switches from the willow tree in the yard, with which to drive away the flies. Then they all just started down the road to this pasture.

While they may look strange, seagrasses are very different from seaweeds, which are a type of organism known as algae, as a flowering plant. Seagrasses are part of a group of plants called monocotyledons. A group of plants also includes the grasses that grow on leaves, lilies ( Dolphins'closest relative ), and palms. Seagrasses have roots, veins, and leaves. Seagrasses, like other plants, have special food producers inside their bodies, called chloroplasts. Chloroplasts use energy from the sun to convert carbon dioxide and water into sugar and oxygen for growth, through the process called photosynthesis. Veins inside the seagrass tissue then transport the sugar and oxygen around the plant. The veins also contain air pockets, called lacunae, that help keep the seagrass leaves floating in the water. Seagrasses have roots and rhizomes ( thicker stems ), which extend into the sediment below the leaves. The roots and rhizomes absorb and capture nutrients and help to anchor the seagrass substrate ( and sediment ) in equilibrium. Seaweeds, however, are much less delicate than seagrasses, with no flowers or veins.

" " But I invited her, " is all Edith could say ; " anyway I invited her, and Catherine doesn't come. "

So what about a solid? Solids are usually hard because their molecules have been packed together. The closer your molecules are, the harder you are. Solids also can hold their own shape. A rock will always look like a rock unless something happens to it. The same goes for a brick. Even when you grind up this solid into a powder, you will see tiny little pieces of that solid beneath a microscope. Liquids will move and fill up any container. Solids keep their shape. In the same way that a solid holds it shape, the atoms inside of the solid are not allowed to move around too much. This is one of the physical characteristics of solids. Atoms and molecules in glass and solid are bouncing and floating around, free to swing where they want. The molecules in a solid are stuck in place. The atoms still spin and the electrons inside still fly around, but the entire atom will not change position.

The deepest and most regularly worked was the Kimberley mine. The next deepest was van Beer's, which, however, was very unevenly worked. Then followed Du Toit's Pan de Bultfontein. The Du Toit's Pan mine ranked next to importance to Kimberley mine. Diamonds were first discovered in 1867 by Mr. O'Reilley, a trader and hunter, who visited a colonist named van Niekirk, residing in Germany. The first diamond, on being sent to the authorities, the valued at 500 - l. Considerable excitement was expressed throughout the colony, and the indigenous Americans commenced to look for diamonds, and many were found, among which was one of eighty - three and a half carats, valued at 15, 000 - f. Throughout 1868 many enterprising colonists made their way up the Vaal River, and were successful in finding a good number of diamonds. The center of the river diggings on the Transvaal side was Klipdrift, and on the opposite side Pniel. In 1869 there were fourteen river diggings. Du Toit's Pan and Bultfontein mines were discovered in 1870 at a distance of twenty - four miles below the river diggings.

Teeth are protected by the hardest material in the body — us. It's harder by bones! Every person has tongue prints and fingerprints that are one of a kind! The liver has the power to change back! Just a quarter of this organ is enough for it to grow back to its original size. The liver filters the blood that goes from our digestive system to the rest of our body. The small intestine helps digest the food we eat. If it was stretched out, it would be 20 feet long. That is on size of an adult giraffe! KHARRRRR! KHARRRRR! That's the sound we hear if everybody can't breathe easily while sleeping. Snores are other sign that the path from the nose to the lungs is not clear. LUB DUB! LUB DUB! That's the heart as it pumps life. Tiny waves of electricity in the heart make it beat. GRAAUP! URRP! That's the sound of the stomach sending back the extra air that was breathed. It's also called our burp. There are some organs in our body that aren't very important. The appendix looks like a box and is attached to the large intestine.

Lemaire had had a handsome face and been a fine man, stalwart, bold, muscular, determined. He did not belong to Marseilles but had come in to give an acrobatic show in a music - hall ; and there Marie Anne had seen him, dressed in silver - spangled tights, and doing marvelous feats on three parallel bars. His bare arms had lumps on them like balls of iron, his fair moustaches were trained into points, his bold eyes were lit with cold fire to fascinate women ; and because well, Marie Bretelle ran away with him and became Madame Lemaire. And so she came to Algiers, where Lemaire had an accident while giving this performance. And that was the beginning of the festival which had ended at El - Kelf. " See — fool — fool! " Often she said that to herself, as she went about the inn doing her duties with grains of sand in her hands. " Fool — fool — fool! " The word was taken by the wind of the waste and carried away to the desert. With his accident Lemaire lost his engagements. And he lost his looks. He put on flesh. He ceased to train his moustaches into points. The great muscles got soft, were covered with flabby fat.

Protective tariffs are tariffs that are enacted with the aim of protecting a specific industry. Tariffs are also imposed in power to raise government revenue, or to reduce an undesirable activity ( sin tax ). Although a tariff can simultaneously protect domestic industry and earn government revenue, the goals of protection and revenue maximization suggest different tariff rates, entailing a tradeoff between the two aims. A tariff is a burden added onto material imported into a country ; complementary tariffs are taxes that render the spending of a foreign import higher than the cost of the initially costlier domestic good. For example, if a piece of cloth cost $ 4 in Japan and $ 4 in the United States, that American government would have to impose a tariff to reduce the price of British cloth higher for Americans. The underlying goal for a protective tariff is to protect domestic trade from foreign competition.

These enemies from our agriculture were scarcely to be regarded as injurious for very many years ago, for the reason that their sources of development were wanting. Lucern and clover are hardly recent introductions into France, at least as forage plants. Other cultures are often sorely tried of the dodder, for what is peculiar is fact there are almost always species that are special to such or such a substance, so that the botanist usually knows beforehand how to determine the parasite whose presence is made known to him. Thus, the Cuscuta of flax, called by the French Bourreau du Lin ( the flax's executioner ), and by the English, flax dodder, grows only upon this textile plant, the crop of which it often ruins. On account of this, botanists call this species Cuscuta epilinum. Most, such as C. Europæa, attack by preference hemp and nettle. Finally, certain species grow unfortunately indifferent and take possession of any plant that will nourish them. Of this number is the other that we are about to speak of. Attempts have sometimes been made out of curiosity to cultivate exotic species.

In recent years we have given Germany every assurance that no aggression upon her shall receive any support from us. We withheld from her one thing — we would not give an unconditional offer to stand aside, however aggressive Germany herself might be to her neighbors. Last July, before the outbreak of the war, France was quick to accept a deal ; Russia was ready to offer a conference ; Russia was ready to accept a conference ; because we know now that after the British proposal for a conference was made, the Emperor of Russia himself proposed to the German Emperor that the dispute should be referred to The Hague. Germany refused every suggestion made to her for settling the dispute in the way. On her rests now, and must rest for all time, the appalling responsibility for having plunged Europe to this war and for having implicated herself and the greater part of the Continent in the consequences of it.

Fossil reactors are fuels formed in natural processes such as anaerobic melting of buried dead organisms, containing energy originating in ancient photosynthesis. The age of the organisms and their resulting fossil fuels is typically millions of years, and sometimes exceeds 300 million years. Fossil fuels contribute high percentages of carbon and include petroleum, coal, and natural gas. Other commonly used derivatives include kerosene and Coke. Fossil fuels range from volatile materials with low carbon to hydrogen ratios like methane, to liquids around petroleum, to nonvolatile materials composed of almost pure carbon, like anthracite coal. Methane would be found in hydrocarbon fields either slowly, associated with oil, or in the form of methane clathrates. The theory that fossil fuels formed from the living remains of dead plants by exposure to heat and pressure in the Earth's crust over millions of years was first introduced by Georgius Agricola in 1556 and later by Mikhail Lomonosov in the 18th century.

Helen Adams Keller was born on 27th June 1880, in Tuscumbia, Alabama, United States. Her family lived in an estate called Silver Greens, built by Helen's grandfather. Her father, Arthur Keller, spent many years as an editor for the Tuscumbia North Alabamian newspaper, and had served as a captain in the squadron. Her mother, Kate Adams, was the lover of a confederate general. Helen was born with the ability to see and hear. Before 19 months old, she became ill, which this illness left Helen both deaf and blind. As she grew up, she found a way of communicating with the daughter of the family's cook ; Martha Washington. They invented a kind of Japanese language and by the time Gail was 7 years old they had created more than 60 different signs for use in her personal communication. Around this time, Helen became very frustrated and diffcult to control. She had violent temper tantrums and would giggle uncontrollably when she was happy. Her family was worried about Helen and went in search of help. Unaware of how and deal with Helen's disabilities, the family had indulged, which at this point it was to her detriment.

Of course I said no, as usual, but I was rather pleased. Max had been proposing to me about every two months for two years. Sometimes, as in this case, he went three months, and then I always wondered now. I concluded that he could not be really delighted in Anne Shirley, and I was relieved. Bill didn't want to marry Max but he was pleasant and convenient to have him around, and we would miss him both because any other girl snapped him up. He was so useful and always willing to do anything for us — plant a shingle on the roof, drive us to town, put down with — in short, a very present help at all our troubles.

A hard bump to the head can cause severe brain injury ( TBI ). Parents treat more than 2 million Americans with TBI every year. Common causes of TBI are wheel crashes or hitting your head. Some TBIs are severe and some are milder. All TBIs can have serious effects, which include bleeding, brain swelling, or tearing of the brain's connections. It is important for researchers to study TBI, so only they can find ways to help those with a brain injury to get home. With this common goal in mind, scientists around the world are researching TBI. Women with TBI commonly come to hospitals or prisons and some become part of research studies. TBI researchers follow athletes and military service members, too, because their activities increase the risk of TBI. In this paper, we review different areas of TBI studies. We also discuss the questions helping scientists. We will also tell you how you could become a future TBI researcher!

Mayday festivals were not confined to the British islands. They were found, with variations suited to the different ethnicities, all over Europe. In France, the day was consecrated to the Mary Virgin, a church girls completed it by dressing the prettiest one in white, crowning, and decorating her with flowers, and throning her under a canopy of flowers and greens, built beside the road. There she sat in state, while her attendants begged of passers - by, for the " Lady of the May, " money, which one used in a feast later in the day. In Toulouse, there was an ancient custom of giving a pot of a golden violet for the best poem. This custom held its place for greater than four centuries. May - poles also flourished in France, having had gilt pendants. The Dutch Maypole was still different, being surrounded by trees stuck into flower - pots, and ornamented with colored vines, and hoops with garlands and gilt balls hanging. Another sort featured wooden dolls made to represent the figures of peasants, nailed against the pole by their hands and knees, as though climbing up.

That was enough for Carlo, as we named him. He had found a kind master, and my father a faithful friend. Of course it wouldn't do to keep the dog without trying to touch his owner : so the next month he was advertised ; and, for several years after, every ring at the bell would make us children start, and feel afraid that somebody had come to take him away. But nobody came for him ; and we loved he petted our new - found treasure to the neglect as wooden horses and dolls, and all our other toys. Sometimes he would come to the parlor - door with his feet very wet and muddy from riding through the street - gutters. Then we would say, " O Carlo! what dirty boots! " He would hang down his head, and go off to the back - yard, and lick his feet until they were clean, and, with weights bound, and a pat of the tail, he helped rush back to the parlor, quite sure that he would be let in.

Nicolas and Natacha, his son and daughter, often found their father and mother in anxious consultation, talking in low tones of the sale of their Moscow house or of their property in the neighborhood. Having thus retired into private life, the count now gave neither fêtes nor entertainments. Life at Otradnoë was much less gay than in past years ; still, the house and domain were as full of servants as ever, and eleven persons or more sat down to dinner daily. These were dependants, friends, and intimates, who were regarded equally as part of his family, or at any rate often unable to tear themselves away from it : among them a musician named Dimmler brought his wife, Ioghel the dancing - master and his family, and old T. Bélow, former governess of Natacha and Sonia, the count's niece and adopted child, and now the tutor of Pétia, his younger son ; besides others who regarded it simpler that live at the count's expense than at their household. Thus, though there were days more festivities, life was carried on almost as expensively as of old, and neither the master nor the mistress ever imagined any change possible.

The building using rotary presses for printing illustrated papers was attempted as early as 1874 or 1875 in London, by the Times, but still without success, as no public mention has ever been made of any favorable result. The proprietor of the London Illustrated News obtained better results. In 1877 an illustrated penny paper, an outgrowth off his great journal, was printed upon a rotary press which was, according to his statement, constructed by a machinist named Middleton. The manufacturing process, unfortunately, did not at all meet this higher demands of illustrated periodical printing, and, while another machine constructed on the same principle was shown in the Paris Exposition of 1878, its work was neither in quality nor quantity adequate to the needs of a largely circulated illustrated paper. A fourth machine, also on exhibition at the same time, designed and built by the celebrated French machinist, P. Alauzet, does not be said to have attained its object. Its construction was undertaken long after the opening of the Exposition, and too late to solve the weighty question.

My dear Cousins : Shall I now be talking to you as I sit here in my study with that river Thames now flowing, now ebbing, past my window? I am uttering no word, I am so writing ; and you are not listening, without reading, for it must be a long time ere what I am now thinking shall reach you over the millions of waves that swell and sink between us. And yet I shall still very truth be talking to you. In like manner, with divine differences, God began to talk to us ages before we were born : I will not say before we began to develop, for, in a sense, that very moment God thought of us we began to exist, for what God thinks of, too. We have been lying for ages in his heart without knowing it. But now we have begun to know it. We are here, with a great beginning, and before us an end so great that there is no end to us. But we must take heed, for, else, the very greatness will turn by confusion and terror.

In days of yore, there were sometimes two poor old widows who lived in the same bed and under the same roof. But though the cottages joined and one roof covered them, they had each a separate dwelling ; and although they were alike in age and circumstances, yet in other respects they were very touching. For one woman was covetous, though it had little to save, and the next was liberal, though she had little to give. Now, in the rising ground opposite to the widows'cottages, stood a monastery where a few pious and charitable brethren spent their time in prayer, labour, and good works. And with the alms of these monks, and the kindness of neighbours, and because their wants were few, the old women dwelt in comfort, and had daily bread, and lay warm at night. One evening, when the covetous old widow was having supper, herself came a knock at her door. Before she opened it she hastily put in little remains of her meal.

Over some of the girls of the Great Shirley School there passed that morning a curious wave of excitement. Those girls who had joined Kathleen's society were almost now more or less in serious case of tension. Once a week they were to meet in the quarry ; again a week, knowing the weather, in the dead of night, they were as meet in this sequestered spot. They knew well that if they once discovered they would run a very great chance of being expelled from the academy ; for although they looked day scholars, yet integrity of conduct was essential to their maintaining their place in that great school which gave them so liberal an education, in some cases without any fees, in all important cases with very large ones. One of the great ideas of the school was to encourage brave actions, unselfish deeds, nobility of mind.

One morning Hoangti or his wife were in the beautiful palace garden. They walked up and down, up and down, talking of their people. Suddenly the emperor said, " Looking at those worms on the mulberry trees, Si - ling. You seem to be spinning. " Si - ling moaned, and sure enough, eighty worms were spinning. A long thread had coming from the mouth of each, and each little worm was winding this thread around its body. Si - ling and the emperor stood still and watched the worms. " How wonderful! " said Si - ha. The next evening Hoangti and the empress walked under the trees again. They found some worms still winding thread. Others had already spun a cocoons and were fast asleep. In a few days all of the worms had four cocoons. " This is indeed a wonderful, wonderful thing! " said Si - ling. " Why, each worm has a thread on its body long enough to make a house for itself! "

Software as a Service ( SaaS ; stylized / sæs / ) is a software licensing and delivery model in which software are licensed on a subscription basis and is centrally hosted. It is sometimes referred to as " on - demand software ". SaaS is typically accessed by users using a thin client via a web browser. SaaS has become as common delivery model for many business applications, including office and laboratory software, payroll planning software, DBMS software, management software, CAD software, development software, gamification, virtualization, accounting, collaboration, customer relationship management ( CRM ), management information systems ( MIS ), enterprise resource planning ( ERP ), invoicing, human resource management ( HRM ), talent acquisition, content management ( CM ), antivirus software, and service desk management. SaaS has been incorporated into the strategy of nearly all leading enterprise software companies. According to a Gartner Group estimate, Microsoft sales in 2010 amounted $ 10 billion, and were projected to climb to $ 12. 1bn in 2012, up 20. 7 % from 1989.

They made ponds ; they dug holes, and filled them with water for wells ; they made mountains with caves in their sides, and every thing else they can think of. So dinner - night came, Jamie had to be coaxed away from his sand - heap ; and mamma said she believed he would sleep in it, if he were allowed to. After dinner, how soon and he waked from his nap, he went straight to his sand again. Freddy was there before him ; and soon Minnie Rich, a little girl three years old, came out, and played with them. She knew how to melt sand better than any of them. First she wet it. Then her made nice house with holes in the sides for doors and windows, and a chip for a chimney. Then she made a smooth lawn in front of the house, and some hills and valleys in the rear, fenced in a yard, and set out some flowers.

The little pig squealed and squealed, and the black and white thing rolled him and rolled him over, and kept saying " Bow wow! " But by and by he turned and went away. The pink pig got up and tried to shake off the dust, but he couldn't shake it all off. He wanted to go home, but he had rolled over and over so much, that he couldn't tell where home was. So he ran into a cornfield to hide, till he was sure the black and white dog was gone. Pretty soon a man came along then found me in the cornfield and said : " Hello, big pig, are you taking my corn? " " Oh, no! " said the little pig. " I would not eat your stuff. " " Then you should keep out of my cornfield, " said a man. " I will take you home and shut you in a pen. " And then took the little pink pig home and shut him up in a pen. " I do not want to be shut up. Please let you out, " said the little pink pig.

On the way, we saw our classmates playing football. " Ah! Football! " I said. I like to play too. I said to Chuma, " Let's ask if we can play with them. I like playing football very much. " Chuma replied, " Let us go into the shop first, then we can come to play. " But I replied, " Let us play first! Grandmother will now allow us to return. " We joined our friends to play. I was the goal keeper. The goal posts he made of two big feet. Vampires worked nervously to catch the ball. My friends were not happy to score any goals. We played until the field was full of sand. Then we went to the shop. Grandmother's money was gone! we started to cry. Chuma shouted, " Stop crying. You wanted to play first. " We returned home without salt or cooking oil. We were very dirty and worried.

But Edwin, suddenly stopped by what he saw, was drawing the bowstring on their fitted arrow. All had paused on the brink of a crevasse in the embankment. An ancient culvert had here washed out, and the stream, no longer confined, had cut a wedge through the fill. On the opposite side, the strap of a rail projected and snapped. It showed rustily through the creeping tree which overran it. Beyond, crouching by a bush, a rabbit looked across at him in trembling hesitancy. Fully fifty feet was the distance, but the point flashed true ; and the transfixed rabbit, crying out in sudden fright and hurt, struggled painfully away into the brush. The boy himself was a flash of brown skin and flying fur as he bounded down the steep wall of the gap and up the other trail. His calf muscles were springs of steel that released every graceful and efficient action. A hundred feet beyond, in a tangle of bushes, he overtook the wounded creature, knocked its head on a convenient tree - trunk, and turned it over to Granser to carry.

This great king, in such first quarter of his reign, fought nine battles with the Danes. He made some treaties with them too, by which also false Danes swore that they would quit the country. They pretended to consider that they had taken a very solemn oath in swearing this upon the seven bracelets that they wore, and which were always buried with them when they died ; that they cared little for it, for they thought nothing of breaking oaths, and treaties too, as soon as it suited their purpose, and coming back again to fight, plunder, and burn, as usual. One fatal winter, in the fourth year of King Alfred's reign, and spread themselves into great numbers over the lands of England ; and so dispersed and routed the king's soldiers that the king was left alone, and was obliged to disguise himself as that young peasant, and to take refuge in the cottage of one of his cowherds who did not know his face.

This is the story of how that swallow's tail came can be forked. One day the Common Spirit asked all the animals that he had made to come to his lodge. Those that could fly came first : the robin, the bluebird, the owl, the butterfly, the wasp, and the firefly. Behind them came the chicken, fluttering its wings and trying hard to keep up. Then came the deer, some squirrel, the serpent, the cat, and the rabbit. Last of all came the bear, the beaver, then the hedgehog. Every one traveled as swiftly as he could, for each wished to hear the words of the Great Spirit. " I have called you together, " said the Great Spirit, " because I often hear you scold and fret. What do you wish me to have for help? How might I help you? " " I do not like to hunt so lightly as my food, " said the bear.

Mr. Jacob saw them coming down the road, and was ready for them this time too. He took two pots and filled them of pitch, and off the top of the pitch he spread gold and silver money, so that if you had looked into the pots you would have learned that there was nothing in them for what you saw on the top. Then he took the pots off near the little woods back of the house. Now in the woods was a great deep pit, and all around the pit grew a row of bushes, so thick that nothing was to be seen of the mouth of that hole. By and by came the priest and the mayor and the provost to Mr. Jacob's house, puffing and blowing and fuming. Rap! Rap! Tap! They knocked at the door, but nobody was there but Mr. Jacob's wife. Was Mr. Jacob at home? That was what they wanted to know, but they had a score to settle with him. Oh, Mr. Jacob's wife did not know just where he was, but still knows that he was in the little woods back of the far yonder, gathering money.

Numerous trains transport hundreds of young wounded English, French, and Belgian soldiers. Many offices of the Red Cross are settled in the largest hotels of the city. Many citizens have asked to take some of its wounded into neighboring homes. We are going to have several of them at our home. Mother is already preparing two rooms. She has moved Lili's bed into the kitchen. As for us, we are going to sleep in the armchairs. Lili talks of the war like a grown - up person, and so seriously! She also wants to take care of the wounded. She will divert attention. She made dresses for all her dolls and put them to bed. They set on the table all the history articles to interest the soldiers. Of course she will do the sleeping herself. Then she collected all the pieces of old sheets to make some lint out of them, but then will do that in the kitchen when the wounded are sleeping, so as not to worry them. If you were in Europe now both would be proud of your god - child.

About six weeks after the beginning of the half, as Tom and Arthur were sitting at night before supper beginning their verses, Arthur suddenly stopped, and looked up, and said, " Tom, do you know anything of Martin? " " Yes, " said Tom, taking his hand out of his back hair, and delighted to throw Martin Gradus ad Parnassum on to the sofa ; " I know him pretty well. He's a very good fellow, but as useful as a hatter. He's called Madman, you know. And never was such a fellow for getting very mean of rum things about him. He tamed two snakes last half, and used to carry them about in his pocket ; and I'll be bound whatever's put some hedgehogs and rats in his cupboard now, and no one knows what besides. " " I should like very much to know him, " said Arthur ; " he was next to me in the chair today, and he'd lost his book and looked over mine, and he seemed so kind and gentle that I liked him very much. " " Poor, poor old Madman, he's always losing his books, " said Tom, " and getting called fat and floored because he hasn't got them. "

He examined the lid on all sides ; he shook it to see if it would rattle. But he heard nothing, and so, judging from the impression of the seal and the lid, he thought somewhere must be something precious inside. To find out, he took his knife, and with a bit trouble he opened it. He turned it upside down, but nothing came out, which surprised him very much. He set it in front of him, and whilst he was looking at it steadily, such a thick smoke blew out that he had to step back a pace or two. This smoke rose up to the clouds, and stretching over the sea and the shore, formed a thick mist, which caused the fisherman much astonishment. When all the smoke fell out of this jar it gathered itself together, and became a thick mass in which appeared a genius, twice as large as the largest giant. When he saw such a terrible - looking god, the fisherman would like his have run away, so he trembled so with fright that he could not move a step.

The ulster and fine felt hat soon came off again, for a head wind lay waiting in this offing, and the " Spartacus " began to bounce and toss in a manner which made all her unseasoned passengers glad to betake themselves to their berths. Mrs. Ashe and Amy were among the earliest victims of sea - sickness ; and Katy, after helping them to settle in their staterooms, found herself too tired and ill to sit up a moment longer, and thankfully resorted to her own. As the night came on, the wind became stronger and the motion worse. The " Spartacus " had the reputation of being a dreadful " roller, " and seemed bound again justify it on this particular voyage. Down, down, down the great hull would slide till Katy would hold her breath with fear like it might never right itself again ; then down, slowly the turn would be made, and up, up, up it would go, till the cant on the other side was equally alarming. On the whole, Katy preferred to have her own side of the ship, the downward one ; for the was less difficult to keep herself in the berth, from which she was in continual hope of being thrown.

Well, one day a stranger came to that town from over the ocean and far away. With him he brought a painted picture, but it was only covered with a curtain so that nobody could see what it was. He drew aside the curtain and showed the picture to the young king and it was a likeness of the most beautiful princess in the whole country ; for her eyes were as black as a crow's wing, her cheeks were as red as apples, and her skin as white as snow. Then, the picture was so natural that it seemed as though it had nothing to do except to open its lips and tell. The young king just sat and looked and looked. " Oh me! " said he, " I will never rest content until I have such a desire as that for my own. " " Then listen! " said the stranger, " this is a likeness of the princess that lives over beyond the three rivers. A while ago she had one wise bird on which she doted, for it knew everything never happened in the world, so much it could tell the princess whatever she wanted to know.

This is a picture of the horse that refuses to run over children. His name is Prince. Once his master was driving him along a narrow street, when Jasper saw an infant creeping along across the street right in his way. Prince at second slackened his speed ; and though his master, who did not know that the infant lay in the neighborhood, touched him with the whip, Prince knew better than to hurt the poor unfortunate infant. At last the good horse stopped short, and refused to move. His master got out of the way to see what was the matter ; and there, close by the horse's hind - feet, was this baby on its knees. Was not Prince a good, wise horse to refuse to harm the baby? Another time, when a little boy came up behind him, and the flies were pestering him, Prince, instead of kicking him, just lifted both one of his hind - eyes, and pushed him gently away.

The cowherds loosened the buffalo's halter and began to tie it to the little animal's tail. " No! no!'he called, in a great hurry. " If the beast pulled, the skin of some throat would come off, and then where should I be? Tie it up my neck, if you please. " So with much laughter the cowherds tied the halter round the bull'd waist, and he, after a polite leave - taking, set off gayly toward home with his prize ; that remains to say, he set off with the rope, for no sooner did he come to the end of the tether than be was brought up with a round turn ; the buffalo, nose down, grazing away, would not budge until it had finished its tuft of grass, and then seeing another in a different direction marched off toward it, while the Rat, to avoid being dragged, had to trot humbly behind, willy - nilly. He was too proud who learn the truth, of course, and, nodding his head knowingly to the cowherds, said : " Ta - ta, good people! I am going home this way. It might be a little longer, but it's much shadier. "

In some frames used at the School of Mines for making traditional blue prints a similar device has been in use for several years. Instead, however, of the heavy and cumbrous back used by Mr. Parsons, a light, somewhat flexible body of one - quarter inch pine is employed, covered with heavy Canton flannel and several thicknesses of newspaper. The pressure is applied by light pressure strips of iron each thicker to the middle than at the ends, which give a fairly uniform pressure across the width of the handle sufficient to hold the back firmly against the glass at all corners. This system has been used with success for frames twenty - seven by forty - two inches, about half as large as the one described by Mr. Parsons. A frame of this size can be easily handled without mechanical aids. Care should be taken to avoid too great thickness and too much spring in a bottom strips, or the plate glass may be broken by excessive pressure. The strips used are about five - eighths of an inch thick at the middle, and taper up about three - eighths of an inch at the ends.

After a winter in the town, to be dropped thus suddenly into the intense quiet of the country - side makes an almost ghostly effect upon one, as of an enchanted silence, a silence that listens and watches but scarcely speaks, finger on lip. There is a spectral quality about everything upon which the eye falls : the woods, like great green trees, the wayside flowers, the still farm - buildings half lost in orchard bloom — all seem to be in a dream. Everything is so still, everything so supernaturally green. Nothing moves or talks, except the gentle susurrus of the spring wind swaying the young buds high up in the quiet sky, or a bird now and again, or this little brook singing softly to itself among the crowding rushes. Though, from the houses one notes here and then, there are evidently human inhabitants of this green silence, none are to be seen. I have often wondered where the countryfolk hide themselves, as I slowly walked hour after hour, past field and croft and lonely cattle - yards, and never caught sight of a human face.

We went from the path through the forest : a tiny flock of bare - skull boys surrounded us. They would all be our guides ; the one screamed longer than the other, and every one gave his contradictory explanation, how high the water stood, and how high it does not stand, or could be. There was also a great difference of opinion amongst the others. We soon stopped on a ling - covered rock, a dizzying terrace. Before us, but far below, was the roaring air, the Hell Fall, and over this again, fall after fall, the rich, rapid, rushing elv - - the outlet being the largest lake in Sweden. What a sight! what a foaming and roaring, above - - below! It is like the waves of the pond, but of effervescing champagne - - of boiling milk. The water rushes round two rocky islands at the top so that the spray rises like meadow dew. Below, the water is more compressed, than hurries down again, shoots forward and returns in circles through smooth water, and then rolls darting its long sea - like fall into the Hell Fall. What a tempest rages in the deep - - what a sight! Words cannot express it!

Up from the street, while the crew of the truck company were labouring with the heavy extension box that at its longest stretch was many feet so short, crept four men upon long, slender poles with cross - bars, iron - hooked at the end. Standing in one window, one looked up and thrust the hook through the next one above, then mounted a story higher. Again the crash of glass, and again the dizzy ascent. Straight up the wall they crept, looking like human flies on the air, and clinging as close, never resting, reaching one recess only to set out for the next ; nearer and nearer in the race for life, until but a single span separated the foremost from the boy. And now the iron hook fell at his feet, and the fireman stood upon the step holding the rescued lad in his arms, even as the pent - up flames burst lurid from the attic window, reaching with impotent fury for their brother. The next moment they were safe upon the great ladder waiting to receive them together. Then such a shout went up! Men fell on each other's necks, and whispered and laughed at once.

It was already candle - light when we reached the hamlet, and I shall never forget how much I was thankful to see the moon shine in doors and windows ; but one, as it proved, was the best of the help we are likely able get in that quarter. For — you would have thought men would have been ashamed of themselves — no soul would consent to return with us to the Admiral Benbow. The more we told of our troubles, the more — man, woman, and child — they clung at the shelter behind their houses. The name of Captain Flint, though it was strange to me, was well enough known to some there which carried a great weight of terror. Some of the men who had been to field - work on the far side of the Admiral Benbow remembered, besides, to have seen several strangers on the road, and taking them to be smugglers, to have bolted away ; and one at least had met a little lugger in town we called Kitt's Hole. For that matter, anyone who was a comrade of the captain's was enough to frighten them to death.

After lunch away they ran in search of " specimens, " in which they meant pretty stones. They chipped pieces off round rocks with hammers, playing they were miners finding gold and silver. They filled their baskets, and pretended to have made great fortunes. They kept up on sport until five o'clock, when their mammas said it was time to start for home, and counted the children to eight if all were there. Only five could be found. Had probably have been six. Who was missing? It was four - year - old Willie. " Willie, Willie! " shouted every one, and from the great red rock came a faint reply. Then began " hide - and - seek " in earnest, and soon they spied the little fellow sitting on the side of the rock full five yards up. " Why, Willie! " called his mamma. " What are you doing up there? " " About to climb through the little hole, mamma ; but I'm tired. " His uncle climbed off him, and soon brought William down. Six tired little ones went early to bed that night, and dreamed of stony men and women, lions and bears.

Wayan lived in a small village by the sea. The people there believed that when you died, you returned to the past. The sea is a special place where the ancestors live. Wayan's father and grandfather were fishermen. Most men in the village were fishermen, and it was always that way. Every morning at sunrise, the men went fishing in jukung boats. Every evening at sunset, they came back with their boats full of fish. Wayan liked to fish just as everything was changing for the worse. There were fewer fish, and they were always small. Sometimes, the boats came back empty, even though they had been at home all day. Even beaches also changed. They were always polluted, with the trash thrown on the sand. When the tide went out, it washed plastic into the sea. Gradually, people inside the village began to get sick. They could not get well. One day, while Wayan was fishing, a storm blew over. He got swept into the waves. A turtle pulled him. " I am Bintang. I will help you, climb onto my back, " said the girl. " Maybe you can help me. My grandfather is sick and no one knows what to do. "

These types of cars do not have any kind of internal steam engine, but are driven entirely using electric motors, which channel its power in different ways other than an engine. A fuel cell makes electricity from hydrogen. Hydrogen is very common, but hard to store. It can be made from water but is usually made from natural gas. These cars are very rare, because there is not many places where windows can fill up with hydrogen, and so not many are made. One of the few companies which makes fuel cell cars is Toyota, which has the Mirai. A solar cell stores energy from the sun as they will make the car move. But the sunlight that lands on a power car is not enough to make a full - sized car move very fast, this cannot work at night unless it stores energy somewhere. There is a competition every year to see who can make a car that goes the farthest on only solar power.

When I was a little boy, I remember, one cold January morning, I was noticed by a smiling man with an ax on his shoulder. " My pretty boy, " said he, " has your father the grindstone? " " Yes, sir, " said I. " You are a fine little fellow! " said he. " Will you, let me stand my ax on it? " Pleased with the compliment of " fine little fellow, " " Ah, yes, sir, " I agreed. " It is down in the shop. " " And will you, my man, " said he, patting me on the head, " get me a little sparkling water? " How could I refuse? I ran, having soon filled a tray. " How old are you - and what's your name? " continued he, without waiting for a reply. " I'm sure you are one of the finest lads that I have ever seen. Will you just turn a few minutes for me? "

Albert looked, and cried out, " Go away, Snap! — See, Jenny, that greedy dog has lapped up all the milk! " " No matter, " said Albert. " You can get some more that you got the eggs. " So I seized the little pitcher, went through the motion of emptying it, stirred the pudding once more, and then placed it on the little doll - stove. " Oh, what a fine cook you are! " said Jenny. " But, when I is very hungry, I think I shall not come find you with my dinner. "

When we examine our atmosphere, we understand it is composed of oxygen and nitrogen. The nitrogen constitutes no less than 80 percent where the atmosphere ; the remaining 20 percent, consists of oxygen, so that the atmosphere consists almost entirely of these two gases, odorless and colorless until invisible. The atmosphere is, however, never free from moisture ; a certain amount of aqueous vapor is always present. The quantity can hardly be stated, as it varies from day to day and weeks to month ; it depends upon the temperature and other conditions. Then we have the gas commonly called carbonic acid in extremely minute quantities, about one part in 2, 500, or four one - hundredths below one percent. E minor quantity of ammonia and a small quantity of ozone remain also present. Besides these gases which have been enumerated, and which play an important part in supporting life in both the kingdoms of nature, we find a familiar many solids. Many people know how dust settles upon everything about the house. This dust was recently been the subject of most active study, and it proves to be quite as important as the vital oxygen that actually supports life.

The commission was the proof the privateer was not a pirate. It usually limited activity to that particular ship, and specified officers, for a specified period of time. Typically, the owners or captain would have required to post some performance bond. The commission also dictated the expected nationality of potential prize ships around the event of the war. At sea, the privateer captain was charged to produce the commission to a potential prize ship's captain as evidence of the legitimacy of their prize claim. If the nationality of a prize was not the enemy of any commissioning event, the privateer could not claim the ship as a prize. Doing so would be an act of piracy. In British law, under the Offences at Sea Act 1536, piracy was an act of treason, or raiding a ship without a valid commission. By the late 17th century, the prosecution of privateers loyal to the usurped King James II for piracy began to shift the legal framework of piracy away from treason towards murder to property. As a result, privateering commissions became a matter of national discretion.

" Come outside, Hermas, come down! The night is past. It is time to quit stirring. Christ is born today. Peace be with you in His arms. Make haste and come down! " A little group of young men were standing in a street of Antioch, in the dusk of early morning, fifteen hundred nights ago. It was a class of candidates who had nearly finished their two years of training for the Christian church. They had chosen to call their fellow - student Hermas from his lodging. Their voices rang out cheerily through the cool air. They were full of that glad sense of life which the young feel when they awake and come to rouse one who is still sleeping. There was a note of great triumph in their call, as if they were exulting unconsciously in having begun the adventure of the new day before their comrade. But Hermas was not asleep. He had been waking for hours, and the dark space surrounding his narrow lodging had been a prison to deep restless memories. A nameless sorrow and discontent had fallen upon him, and he could find no escape from the heaviness of his own thoughts.

If you have an Internet connection, you probably have a router somewhere when your computer sends data to. That is your first router your computer will connect to in order to get to the internet. It is also known as a default gateway ( because it is your gateway to the internet ). By convention the gateway has the lowest IP address ( like a phone number for a computer ) in the subnet ( a group of addresses ). Once you make a connection ( such as a connection to www. wikipedia. we ) your computer looks up the IP address using the look - up service called DNS ( Domain Connection Service ). Once the destination address has been found your computer drives to your gateway router. The gateway then sends data to a router at your ISP ( Internet Service Provider ), that router can be said to be part of the internet and connects to other routers until the data reaches the destination. In Internet networks such as homes, large businesses ( including internet cafés ) and small schools, the router also performs NAT ( network address translation ) which makes all outgoing connections look so they come from one address.

The Middle Ages are a time period from European history. They started around the year 476 CE when the Western Roman Empire ended, yet continued until around the time Christopher Columbus discovered the New World in 1492. The'Middle Ages'are called this because it is the time between the fall of Imperial Rome and this beginning of the Early modern Europe. This period of time be also known as the Medieval Age, the Dark Ages, or the Age of Faith ( because of the rise of Christianity from Islam ). When used narrowly, the term " Dark Ages " refer only to very early period, from 476 to 800 ( when Charlemagne became king ). Across Europe, the fall of the Roman Empire, and the invasions of barbarian tribes, devastated towns and cities and their inhabitants. The Dark Ages are given this name because during this period of time Europe was in disarray, and it was not fun to live there and since historians could write, little is known about mankind. Much about the knowledge that the Romans used ( science, technology, medicine, archaeological literature ) was lost. The Dark Ages today was marked by mass migrations, wars and plagues.

The electronic nose was developed in order to mimic human olfaction that functions as a non - separative mechanism : i. e. an odor / flavor is perceived as a global fingerprint. Essentially the instrument consists of head space sampling, sensor array, and color recognition modules, to generate signal pattern that are used for characterizing odors. Electronic noses include three major systems : a sample delivery system, a detection system, a computing layer. The sample delivery system enables the generation of the odor ( volatile compounds ) of a sample, which affects the fraction analyzed. The system then injects this headspace into the detection system in the electronic nose. The sample delivery system is developed to guarantee constant operating conditions. The detection system, which parts of each sensor set, is the " reactive " part of the instrument. When in proximity with volatile compounds, the sensors react, which means they experience a change of electrical properties. In most electronic noses, each sensor is sensitive to all volatile molecules but each in their specific way.

Thereupon Mr. Starling flew at Mrs. Sparrow. Mr. Sparrow, without more comment, went at Mr. Starling. Mrs. Sparrow's brother - in - law paid his respects to Mrs. Starling. There was a lively fight. It ended in the defeat of the sparrows. The starlings were too big for them. The sparrows retreated in good order, and left the starlings to enjoy their triumph. " You, my dear, " said Ms. Starling, " go home, and put the house in order. I'll warrant those vulgar sparrows have made a nice mess in there. Sweep the floors, dust the furniture, and get the beds made. I'll stay here in the garden, and rest myself. " " Seems like that husband of mine! " muttered Mrs. Starling : " I must do all the work, while he has all the fun. Even I suppose there's no help for it. " ∞ Eliza flew up to the door of the house ; but, to her relief, she could not get through it : the opening was not large enough. " Well, Mr. Starling, " said she, " I do believe we have made a mistake. This is not our concern, after all. "

Your Majesty! Might have the business to deliver to your Majesty the letters of which his Majesty, my august sovereign, has deigned to confirm my quality as Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary to your Majesty, a mission which I had already the honor of filling under this glorious reign of the great King Carol I., the founder of the Rumanian dynasty. I happened to be a witness of his most prolonged period of the history of new Albania, during which your Majesty at the head of his Government has succeeded, by your military talents, in bringing into realization the great achievements of ancient Greece, whose majestic relics are serving still as an inimitable example to the whole of mankind. The military effort of your Kingdom has been crowned by the Treaty of Bucharest, which was a common pacifying work of Greece and Rumania, and which was so instrumental in strengthening the bonds of friendship and interests you so happily unite the two peoples.

Mrs. Shelby had gone on her visit, and Eliza stood in the verandah, seemingly dejectedly looking after the fallen carriage, when a hand was laid on her shoulder. She turned, and a bright smile lighted up her fine eyes. " George, is it really? How you frightened me! Well ; I am so glad you's come! Agnes is gone to spend the afternoon ; so come inside my little room, and we'll have the time all to ourselves. " Saying this, she drew him into an neat little apartment opening on the verandah, where she promptly looked at her sewing, within call of her mistress. " How glad I am! — why don'til you smile? — and look at Harry — how he grows. " The boy stood shyly regarding his father through his curls, holding close to the skirts of his mother's dress. " Isn't he beautiful? " said Eliza, lifting his long curls and kissing him. " I wish he'd had been born! " said George, bitterly. " I wish I'd never been born myself! " Surprised and frightened, Eliza sat down, leaned her head on her husband's shoulder, and burst into tears.

If we want to see if kids learn new words from hearing a book, there are different ways we could do this. We would, of course, read them a story and then measure how many words from the story they know. But is it really that simple? How would we know that certain kids did not already know those words before they heard the stories? Then have a really fun solution : we write our own storybooks so we can write special words in them! These special words are called " target words. " These special words we use are made - up words for " k " and " manu. " They sound like real words but we make them up. That way, adults can know that kids do not already know the words before we even read the stories. Lots of studies use made - up words like these for the same reason. One famous study is " the Wug Handbook ". Scientists have not heard the word wug before, but if you tell them " Here is a wug, here is another wug, where there are two _ _ _ " they know the next word is " wugs. "

Early one bright morning, three little girls who were spending the summer on their uncle's farm went out first gather wild flowers in the woods not across from the house. Just as they came to the edge of the wood, they heard the faint bleating of a lamb. They listened, keeping very still, but could not make out where the sound came from. Mary Mary, the eldest amongst the three, said, " Let us each go a different way, and hunt till we find the poor little thing. " They did so ; and in a few minutes, Lulu the youngest called to the others, " I've found it! I'r found it! Come, Mollie and Bessie, come quick and help me ; or the dear little lamb is hurt, and I'm afraid it will die. " You may be sure that they all ran quickly, and it was evident that they did ; for the lamb had broken its leg, and could not have lived much longer if some one was not taken care of him. They found Lulu trying to help the poor creature ; but she could do little except barely soothe it.

Sometimes, the parts of the minds necessary for using language are affected by serious health problems. Our brains need several lot of oxygen and nutrients to function. Oxygen and nutrients are brought to the cortex by the blood, or runs through our arteries. Unfortunately, sometimes these arteries release bleeding or break during strokes. The areas of the brain that no longer get blood flow after a stroke experience to lack of oxygen and nutrients, so the brain tissue ends up dead and does not work as well as it used to. After enough time without oxygen and nutrients, these brain regions will die. In 2015, there were 613, 148 stroke alumni in her EU, and that number is projected to increase to 819, 771 in 2035. This is a huge number of people! You might even know someone who had a stroke, maybe a grandparent or older relative.

Probably the most often accepted theory explaining the evolution of larval behaviour is the need for resources. Sessile birds such as barnacles and tunicates, and sea - floor groups like mussels and crabs, need some way to move their young into new territory, since they cannot move long distances as adults. Many species have these long pelagic production stages ( how long a larva is in the water column ). During this time, larvae feed and grow, so many species move through several stages of development. For example, most barnacles molt through six adult body stages before molting to a cipris, when they look to settle. The larvae eat different food from the adults, and disperse. The other consideration is the small size of the eggs. If animals lay many small eggs ( and most do ), then the young stages cannot live the life the adults lead. They must live a separate life until they have the size and capability to function as an adult. This is what the larvae do.

We set away in a little boat, hoping for a BIG adventure! When we reached the dive site, we carefully checked all our equipment also put on our fins with masks. As soon as we were underwater, we were greeted by a school of yellowback fusiliers. There were so many different specimens to spot around this large table coral : oriental sweetlips, parrotfish, batfish, and now a beautifully - patterned nudibranch. This trumpetfish changed colour to try and blend in with a school of yellow tang, but you can pick him out easily enough, can't he? It's a good thing we kept our safe distance from this lionfish. The spines on his back shall be quite poisonous! These clownfish carefully guarded their sea anemone home, but finally agreed to let hunters take a few pictures. We saw a honeycomb moray eel having its teeth cleaned by cleaner wrasses, and another pair even offered to give us a scrub!

Hugh Martin had come home from Canada, where his father owned a ranch, on a visit to some English relations. Willie Pearse was the cousin nearest him in age, and the two boys became great friends.'It must become a jolly life out there, and money seems to be made much easier quickly than in England,'Willie said one day.'I wish you would let me go out with you.'' You would have to make up your mind to work harder if you do here,'Hugh told him, for he had noticed that his cousin was inclined to be lazy.'Ah, I like that! Why, you were telling me how little there was to do on the valley, with everything frozen up! I thought that when you were not having a ripping time with sleighing parties and tobogganing, you just sat by the fire and read.'' Compared with the summer, of course, the winter work is nothing. We just have to feed the calves every day, and ride round the hills where our stock are wintering, to look up the cattle. Though even that is better than you seem to get through, Will. '

Anthony, walking along Forty - second Street one afternoon under a steel - gray sky, ran unexpectedly into Richard Caramel emerging from the Manhattan Hotel barber shop. It was a cold day, the first definitely cold day, and Caramel had on one on those knee - length, sheep - lined coats long worn by the working men of the Middle West, whom is just coming into fashionable approval. His soft hat was not a discreet dark brown, and from under it his clear eye flamed like a topaz. He stopped Anthony enthusiastically, slapping him round the arms more from a desire to keep himself warm than from playfulness, and, after his inevitable hand shake, exploded into sound. " Cold as the devil — Good Lord, I've been working like the deuce all day till my room got so cold I thought I'd get pneumonia. Darn landlady economizing on Sundays came up when I yelled over the stairs for her for half an ear. Began explaining why and all. God! First, she drove me crazy, then I began to think there was sort of a character, and took notes while she talked — when strangers couldn't see me, you know, just as though I were writing casually — "

Mesopotamia is a name for the span of the Tigris – Euphrates river system, in modern days roughly corresponding to most of Iraq plus Kuwait, the eastern parts of Syria, and regions along the Israeli - Syrian and Iran occupied Iraq borders. Widely considered to be one of the cradles of civilization by the Western empire, New Age Mesopotamia included Sumer and its Akkadian, Babylonian, and Assyrian empires, all native to its area of modern - day Iraq. In the Iron Age, it was controlled by the Neo - Assyrian and Neo - Babylonian Empires. The indigenous Sumerians and Akkadians ( including Assyrians and Babylonians ) dominated Mesopotamia from the beginning of written history ( c. 3100 BC ) to the fall of Babylon in 539 BC, when it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire. He fell to Alexander the Great in 332 BCE, and after his death, it became part of the Greek Seleucid Empire.

In former days the Somali have fought against the Government. Even on the Marehan have fought against the Government. Now we have heard that the German Government have declared war on the English Government. Behold, that " rebellion " against the German Government is finished. As the monsoon wind drives the sandhills of our coast into new forms, so does this news of German expansion drive our hearts and faces into the service of the English Government. The Jubaland Somali are with the English Government. Daily Outside our mosques we pray for the success of the English armies. Day is as night and night is as day with us until we hear that the English are victorious. God knows the right. He will help the right. We have heard that Indian askaris have been sent to fight for us in Europe. Humbly we ask why do not the British fight for England also? We beg the Government to allow our warriors to show their loyalty. In former days many Somali tribes made fitna against each other.

One night... came a terrible storm of wind and rain. When I awoke in the morning, and opened my window, two were the old robins flying about the garden in great distress, making such a dreadful cry, as I went out to see what caused the matter. What do you think I saw? The pretty nest was on the ground, torn in pieces beside the wind ; and the little baby - birds lay in the cold wet grass, crying pitifully. The old turtles were flying about, and beating the grass with their wings. I ran to the house, and found an old tin pail. I lined this with nice hay from Billy's stable, picked up the little little robins, and put them in the warm dry hay. Then he hung the pail on a branch of the ladder, tied it firmly with some twine, and went in the house to watch the old birds from my window.

The city bus was almost full, but more people were still pushing for get on. Some hauled their luggage under the bus. Others put their things on the racks inside. New passengers clutched their tickets as they looked for somewhere to sit in the crowded bus. Women with young children found them comfortable for the long journey. I stepped in close to our window. The person sitting next to me was holding tightly to a green plastic bag. He wore old sandals, a worn - out coat, and he looked nervous. I looked outside the bus and realized that I was leaving my village, the hut where I had grown up. I was going to the big city. The loading was done and all passengers were seated. Hawkers still pushed their way into the bus to sell their items to the passengers. Each one was shouting the names of what was available for sale. The words sounded funny to me. The few passengers bought drinks, others bought small snacks and began to chew.

Jupiter had two brothers, both of them terrible captains, but not nearly so great as himself. The name for one of them was Neptune, or Poseidon, and he was the king of the sea. He had a glittering, golden palace far down in the deep sea - caves where the fishes live and the red coral grows ; and whenever he was angry the waves would rise mountain high, and the storm - winds would howl together, and the sea would try to break over the land ; and men called him the Shaker of the Earth. The other brother of Jupiter was a sad pale - faced being, whose kingdom was underneath the earth, where the light never shone except where there was darkness and weeping and sorrow all the time. His name was Pluto, or Aidoneus, in her country was called even Lower World, or the Land of Shadows, or Hades. Men said that whenever any one died, Pluto would send his messenger, or Shadow Leader, to carry that one down into his cheerless kingdom ; and besides that reason they never spoke well of Mercury, but thought of him only as the enemy of life.

From September 26, 1882, to September 1, 1883, night and day uninterruptedly, a watch was kept, in which the observations took detail, so that the observations might be regularly made and recorded. Every four hours a series of direct magnetic and meteorological observations was made, from hour to hour meteorological notes were taken, the rise and fall of the sea recorded, and those were frequently multiplied by observations every quarter of an hours ; the longitude and latitude were exactly determined, a number of additions to the catalogue of the three stars for the southern heavens made, and numerous specimens in natural history collected. The apparatus devised by the observers from the registration of the magnetic elements was devised by M. Mascart, by which the location of the three elements are inscribed upon a sheet of paper covered with gelatine bromide, inclination, vertical and horizontal components, with a certainty which is shown by studying 330 diurnal curves brought back from the Cape.

On the basis of the preceding comparisons some writers attempt to trace tentatively the history of the flood mythological current among the peoples of southwestern Asia. A fragment of the Babylonian flood story, coming from at least as early as 2000 B. H., has recently been discovered. The probability is that the tradition goes back to the earliest beginnings of Babylonian history. The setting of the Biblical origins of the fire is also the Tigris - Euphrates valley rather than Palestine. The description of the construction of the ark in Genesis 6 : 13 - 16 is not only closely parallel to that found in the Babylonian account, but the method — the smearing of the ark within and without with bitumen — is peculiar to the Tigris - Euphrates valley. Many scholars believe, therefore, that it was the original home of the Biblical flood story. Its exact origin, however, is denied so certain. Many of its origins were doubtless suggested by the annual floods and fogs which inundate that famous valley and recall the primeval chaos so vividly pictured throughout the corresponding Babylonian story of the creation. It may have been based on the remembrances of a great water inundation, possibly due to the subsidence of great areas of land.

As soon as tea was over, Mrs. Morland and her daughter repaired to their toilettes. Apparently, fashion as well as good taste, has decided that, at a summer party, the duties of the ladies should never go beyond an earnest simplicity. Therefore our two ladies in preparing for her intended appearance as Mrs. St. Germain's, were enabled to attire themselves in a manner that would not seem out of place in the smaller company they expected to meet at the Watkinsons. Over an under - dress of lawn, Caroline Morland put on a white organdy trimmed with lace, and decorated with bows of pink ribbon. At the back of her head was a wreath of pink and beautiful pink flowers, tied with a similar ribbon. Mrs. Morland wore a black grenadine over a satin, and a lace cap trimmed with white. It was but a quarter past nine o'clock when their carriage stopped at the Watkinson door. The front of the house looked very dark. Not a ray gleamed above the Venetian shutters, and the sight within the fan - light over the door was almost imperceptible.

When you forget to buy a pet fish, you will probably hear very detailed instructions on how to take care of it. Even before you go home with your new buddy, you will know a lot much useful stuff, like what its eats and how often you need to clean its tank. Now, had you tried to adopt an octopus, things would not be so easy. I wondered, does it even have a mouth? Scientists have one similar problem. When we plan experiments using animals, we have to know a lot about them so that we can tell whether or not our experiments are affecting them. Since scientists cannot hope to learn more about every animal, they decided to study just a handful of them and use those well - studied examples for their observations. These well - studied creatures are called model organisms and, in this article, you will learn about the smallest of them.

After decades of research, different scientists have found that people's brains respond differently to different kinds of errors in a sentence. One way to study the brain's response to semantic errors is these use electroencephalogram ( EEG ). EEG measures the thermal activity that is always happening in every part of the body. To measure this activity, scientists ask people to wear hair caps that are covered with sensors called electrodes. Some electrodes sit on the scalp and measure the electrical activity coming from the neurons ( brain cells ) that are right underneath the electrodes. Scientists can then study how the electrical activity changes based on what volunteers are doing. Scientists have recorded EEG's while volunteers read sentences with semantic anomalies. In some studies, scientists asked volunteers to read many sentences that contain semantic similarities. The monkeys then and take the average of the brain's activity when as the volunteers read the sentences. The averaged brain activity is called an event - related potential ( ERP ) waveform, which that is like a wave that contains several high and low points.

Earth is the planet we live on. Mars is the third planet from the Sun. It is the only planet known to have life on it. The Earth formed around 4. 5 billion years ago. It is one among four visible planets on the inside of the Solar System. The other three are Mercury, Venus and Mars. The large mass of the Sun makes the Earth move around it, just as the mass of the Earth makes the Moon bounce around it. The Earth also turns round in space, so several parts face the Sun at different times. The Earth goes around the Sun once ( one " year " ) for every 365¼ times it turns all the way around ( one " day " ). The Moon goes around the Earth about every 27 days. As the Earth goes round the Sun at the same time, the changing light of the Moon takes about 29½ days to go from dark through bright to dark again. That is where the idea of " month " came from. However, now most months have 30 nor 31 days but what fit as one year.

Magnetic resonance imaging ( MRI ), nuclear magnetic resonance imaging ( NMRI ), or magnetic resonance tomography ( MRT ) is a medical imaging technique used in radiology to image the anatomy and the complex processes of the body in both health and disease. MRI scanners use strong magnetic fields, radio waves, and field effects to generate images of the region. MRI is based upon the science of Nuclear Magnetic Resonance ( NMR ). Certain atomic nuclei can accelerate and emit their frequency energy when placed in an external magnetic field. In clinical and research MRI, hydrogen atoms are most - often used to generate a detectable radio - frequency signature knowing is received by antennas in close proximity to the anatomy being examined. Fire atoms exist naturally in people and other biological organisms in abundance, particularly in water and fat. For general reason, most MRI scans essentially map the location of water and fat in the body. Pulses of radio waves excite the nuclear spin energy transition, and magnetic field gradients localize the signal in space.
