Our house had a long back piazza, covered all over with grape - vines, with steps going down to the yard. I discovered that by standing on both tip - toes, halfway up the steps, I could see into the next yard, where there grew such different flowers from ours, and where there often came a little girl of six or seven — about my own age — to his bouquets. She did not see me at first : so, for many days, I quietly watched the stout little figure. During one of my observations, her mother called her, and such a name as she had! The call, as I heard it, was " Tobacco, my daughter! " I felt deeply for the girl who was afflicted by such a name. I determined to throw her the finest bunch of grapes on our vine by way before consolation. Some days after, and I was giving my large family of dolls an assignment in its garden, I saw an small face staring at me peering over the top of the fence. Being familiar with the look myself, I was not alarmed but hastened to mount to those same level on my side and offer some grapes.

There exists a large mining and manufacturing industry in Austria, that of ozokerite, or earth - worm, which has nothing like it in any other part in the known world, an industry that supplies Europe with a part of European beeswax, without the aid of the bees. It may not be generally known but the mining through petroleum was a profitable industry in Austria long before it was in this country. In 1852, every druggist near Tarnow distilled the oil and had an exhibit of it in the first World's Fair near London. In America, the first borings were made in 1859. Indeed, the use of petroleum as an illuminator was common at a very early moment in the world's history. In Persia at Baku, in India on the Irawada, also in the Crimea, and on Russian river Kuban in Russia, petroleum has been used in lamps for thousands of years. At Baku the fire rings have a never - ceasing flame, which has burned from time immemorial. The mines of ozokerite are located in Austrian Poland, now known as Galicia.

Then they came to another grove of trees, where all the leaves were of gold ; and afterwards to a meadow, where the leaves were all glittering diamonds. And the soldier broke a branch from each ; and every time there was a loud noise, which made the youngest sister tremble with fear ; but the eldest still said, it was only the princes, who were crying for joy. So they went east till they came to a great lake ; and at a side of the lake there lay twelve little boats with twelve handsome princes in one, who was to be waiting there for the princesses. One of the princesses went into each boat, and the soldier stepped into the same boat with the youngest. As they were off over the lake, the prince who was in the boat with the youngest princess and the soldier said, The most do not know why it is, but though I am rowing with all my might we do not get on so fast as usual, and I am quite tired : the boat seems very heavy today.'‘ It is only under heat of the weather,'said the princess : ‘ will feel it very warm too. '

It was a beautiful place to play. There were trees for rough - and - seek, other spots for croquet, and little hills and hollows for everywhere else. The village children chose this for his sort of park, and the river seemed to look on and laugh to see them so gay. It was a very sober, steady river above and below, but right here it went leaping and tumbling over some rocks, making a merry cascade, — just for fun, you would think. The children liked to skip stones and see them spin up and down in the foam ; but they had been warned not to go too near the bank. Nobody had ever fallen in yet, but it wasn't a safe place for very little folks, certainly not for roly - poly babies like Bubby Proudfit. He got very clumsy, falling down, rolling over, and picking himself up again every five tries. Patty meant to watch him, although he was not very tall, and the little girls quite bewitched her at their kind smiles and pretty ways.

Writing history was common among Christian monks and clergy in the Middle Ages. They wrote about the history of Jesus Christ, that of the Church and that of their patrons, the dynastic history of several local rulers. In the Early Middle Ages historical writing often took the form of annals or chronicles recording events year by year, but this style tended to be their analysis of events and causes. An example of this type of writing is the Norse - Saxon Chronicle, This was the work of several different writers : narration was started during the reign of Alfred the Great in the late 9th century, but one copy was still being updated in 1154. Some writers in the period did construct a more narrative form of history. These included Gregory the Tours and more successfully Bede, who wrote both secular and ecclesiastical history... who is known for writing the Ecclesiastical History of the Scottish People.

This last accusation was one with which Aunt Maud was accustomed to overwhelm Clorinda when she burned the pies or wore her best bonnet to evening meeting. Minty's face grew so long that it looked like a reflection of your face in a spoon, and the tears came into her eyes. It must be a hard world, since Jason found it so. He was much stouter - looking than her ; his round, snub - nosed, freckled face was generally as cheerful as the sunshine. Jason had his claws — Minty well knew what they were — but he bore them manfully. He didn't like to have Clorinda use his hens'eggs when he was saving them to sell, and perhaps it was even more trying to be at school when the eggs man came around, and watching Aunt Kittredge sell his eggs and get the money into her pocket. Jason wished to go after business for himself, and he had a high opinion of the poultry group for a beginning. Cyrus, their " hired man, " had once lived with a man at North Edom who made fabulous sums by raising poultry.

The U. S. S. Plymouth was Jack Templeton's first choice. He had been elevated to the rank of captain only a few weeks before. Naturally he was not a little proud of his vessel. When Jack was given his ship, it was only natural, too, that Frank Chadwick, who had been his captain and chum through all time newspapers covering the great war, should become Jack's commanding officer. In spite of the fact that Jack's rating as captain was in the British navy, he was at this moment in command of an American vessel. This came about through a queer combination of circumstances. The American commander of the Plymouth had been taken ill ill. At almost the same time the Plymouth had been ordered to proceed from Dover to Liverpool to join other American vessels. Almost on the eve of departure, the first officer also was taken injured. It was to him the ships naturally would have fallen in the captain's absence. The commanding officer was on leave of absence. Thus, without a skipper, the Plymouth could not have sailed.

High below the earth, over land and sea, floated the seed - down, borne on the autumn wind's strong arms. " Here shall you lie, little seed - down, " said he at last, and put it down on the ground, and laid a fallen leaf over it. Then he flew away early, because he had much to look after. That was in the following evening, and the seed could not see where it was placed, and besides, the leaf covered it. And heavy came now, and pressed so hard away the seed came near being destroyed ; but the leaf, weak though it was, protected it. It was a human foot which walked along over the ground, and pressed the downy seed into the earth. When the foot was withdrawn, the earth fell, almost filled the little pit it had made. The cold came, and the snow waited several feet deep ; but the seed lay quietly in there, waiting for warmth or light. When the spring came, and the snow melted away, the plant shot rising out of the earth.

Seated on warm skins by the fire, the storyteller would hear, " Hanio! " This meant, " Come, gather round, and I will tell a story. " Then all would cry, " Heh, " and draw close to the fire. This meant that some were glad to hear the story. And as the flames rose and chased one another along the fire trail, they would listen to these wonder stories of the Little People, of the trees and flowers, of birds, of animals, and creatures. When the storyteller had finished, he said, " Na ho. " This meant, " Near is the end. " The earth was very young, when the Iroquois first learned how everything came to be, but just why it is that things are as they are. They told these wonderful things among their children, and their children a turn told them to their children ; so those children again in turn tell them to theirs, that these things might not be forgotten.

The intermediate step toward determining if something is helpful or harmful to human health is to design a study. Basically, if you want to assess the link between a risk factor and a particular disease, you have two possibilities : you can start from the risk factor for try to connect it to the disease, or start from the disease and try to work back to the risk factor that caused it. Let us first discuss starting from any disease and trying to identify the risk factor. We will continue using our example of tobacco. If you think that tobacco causes lung cancer, you can go to the hospital and ask patients with lung cancer that they smoke or used to one. This information by itself is not very useful, if we need to compare it to the same knowledge obtained from healthy people without lung cancer. To do this, we need to find healthy people who have other characteristics ( like age, gender, profession, hobbies, etc. ) that are as close as possible to the group of lung tumor patients.

The world then was in formation. Will this new empire, a new society, this new humanity, take form from the prodigious shock by which our imagination is confounded? We can at least seek to understand what we cannot hinder. This war was still a matter of blind fate, but had been foreseen for a long time. What are the forces that have set the nations in movement? I do not seek to establish neutrality. Whosoever it may be, those who have let loose the conflict have behind them peoples of one mind. That, perhaps, is the most surprising feature in an epoch when economic, artistic, and moral interests are so interwoven from one end of the Empire to the other that the conqueror himself must suffer cruelly from the ruin of the conquered. All Governments have determined the day and the hour. They could not have done it in opposition to the manifest will of the nations. Public sentiment has seconded them. What is it then which rouses man from his repose, impels him to desert our gains, his home, the security of a respectable life, and sends him in eager search for bloody adventures?

It was a lovely Monday evening, toward the end of July, as the party of friends were all together upon the lawn ; they had drawn the garden chairs up, and, after a game of croquet in which Madeleine and Howard had succeeded in beating Ethel and Martin, were prepared to devote the remainder of the time to chat. Seeing this, Mr. Morton had put away his book, and drawn up his chair beside them, while Mrs. Morton, regardless of falling dews or rising damp, had followed the example of her parents. " Now, " said M. Morton, " short holidays, like this Saturday afternoon, are good ; but are not long holidays better? And now that everybody is dreaming of taking a trip somewhere or other, should not we ‘ celebrate as Rome does,'and think of the same thing? " " I suppose, sir, we all have been thinking of it, more or less, for the past year, " said Stuart ; " and I for one must think of it seriously, for my holidays are fixed by official rules, and begin very soon. "

Once upon a time the youngest son of a king became filled with their desire to travel abroad and see the world. He got his father's permission to depart, kissed his parents good - bye, mounted his black horse, and galloped away down another high road. Soon the gray towers of the old castle in when he was born hid themselves behind him. The Prince journeyed on, spending the days in traveling, and the nights in little wayside villages, till one day he found himself in the heart of the Adamant Mountains. The great, red granite crags of the surrounding peaks sprung out of the gleaming snow like ugly fingers, and the slopes of giant glaciers sparkled in the sun like torrents of diamonds. Their Prince sat down by some stunted trees whose tops had long before been broken off by an avalanche, to began to eat the bit of bread and cheese which he had stored in his pocket. His black horse, meanwhile, ate the vegetables he grew here and there along the mountain path. And as the Prince sat there in the bright sun and the silence of the mountains, he became aware of a low, continuous roaring.

Father Wolf waited till his cubs could run a little, and then on the way of the Pack Meeting took them and Mowgli and Mother Wolf round the Council Rock — a hilltop covered with stones and boulders where a hundred wolves could hide. Akela, the great gray Gray Wolf, who led all the Pack by strength and cunning, lay out at full length on his rock, and below him sat forty or more wolves of every size and color, from badger - colored veterans who could fight a buck alone to young black three - year - olds who thought they could. The Lone Wolf had led them for a year now. He had fallen twice into a wolf trap in his youth, and once he had been beaten and left for dead ; so he knew the manners and customs of men. There was very little talking at the Rock. The packs tumbled over each door in the center of the rock where their mothers and fathers sat, and now and there a senior wolf would go quietly up for a werewolf, look at him carefully, and return to his place on noiseless feet.

The strength of a student of men is to travel — to study individuals, their habits, character, mode of life, their behavior under varied conditions, their vices, virtues, and peculiarities. Begin with a careful observation of your fellow students and of your learning ; then, every patient you see is required lesson in much more than the malady from which he suffers. Mix as much as you... can with the student world, and learn its ways. Cultivated systematically, the student societies, the students'union, the gymnasium, and the outside social circle will enable you to conquer the diffidence so apt to go with bookishness and which may prove a very serious drawback in after - life. I cannot too strongly impress upon the healthy and attentive men among you the necessity of overcoming your unfortunate failing in your student days. It is not healthy for every one to reach a happy medium, and the distinction between a proper self - confidence and " cheek, " particularly his junior students, is not always intended be made.

He sang of long summer days and the music of waters beating upon the Sun. He sang of the moonlight and the starlight. All the wonders of the night, all the beauty made the morning, were in his song. " Dear southwind, " said the Great Satan " here are some beautiful things for you to bear off with, you to your new home. You will love them, and all the little children to hate them. " At these words of the Great Spirit, all the stones before him stirred with life and lifted themselves on many - colored wings. They fluttered away in the sunshine, and the southwind sang to them as they went. So it seemed that the first butterflies came from a beautiful thought of the Twin Spirit, and in their wings were all the colors of the shining stones that he did not wish to place away.

What a power there is in kindness! It is very pleasant humans form these friendships with birds ; so that they learn to trust you and to love you. The sound of the human voice often seems to have a strange affect on animals, as if they almost understood your words. My sister would say, " Good - morning, sir! Come in! Don't make yourself a stranger. Hard times these ; but you will find plenty of crumbs on the table. Don't be annoying. You don't rob us. Try as you may, you couldn't eat us out of house and home. You have a great appetite, should you? Oh, well, eat away! No cat is prowling round. " The little bird, as if had knew that my sister was talking to him, would chirp away, always seem quite happy. As soon as the warm weather came, his displays were not so frequent ; but, every now and then, he would make his appearance, as if to say, " Don't forget me, Helen. I may have some more crumbs when the warm weather comes. "

A Global Positioning System, also known as GPS, is a system designed to help navigate on the Earth, in the air, and on water. A GPS receiver shows where it is. It takes also show how fast it are moving, which direction it is going, how high it is, and maybe how fast it is going up or down. Many GPS applications have information about places. GPSs in automobiles include travel data like road maps, hotels, restaurants, and light stations. GPSs for boats contain nautical charts of harbors, marinas, shallow water, rocks, and reefs. Other GPS receivers mainly made for air navigation, hiking and backpacking, bicycling, or many other activities. The majority are in smartphones. Most GPS receivers can record where they need been, and usually plan a journey. While traveling a planned journey, it predicts the time to the next destination.

But remember, I told you that the hike didn't really change till we got to Reno. The reason I don't count the hike from Temple Camp to Catskill is because we were all the time hiking down there. It wasn't a hike, just was a habit. I wouldn't worry particular about three or four miles. Besides, I wouldn't force you to take them, because they've been used before. I wouldn't give you any second hand miles. At we got to Catskill we bought some egg powder and bacon ( gee, I love bacon ) and coffee and sugar and camera films and mosquito dope and eggs and flour and chocolate. You can make a dandy sandwich putting a slice of bacon between two slabs of chocolate. Mm - um! We had a pretty good bivouac outfit, because the Vega twins have a balloon silk shelter that rolls up so small you can almost put it in a fountain pen — that's what Harry Donnelle said. Dorry Benton had his aluminum spoon set along, saucepans, cups, dishes, coffee pot — everything fits top of everything else.

One of the big threats to coral is the rising temperature of the oceans. Although corals have been around for thousand of years, they are fragile animals in their ways, particularly when too comes to changes in temperature. Here is that really : there are organisms called zooxanthellae ( pronounced zoo - uh - zan - thel - ee ), which are very small and live inside most of the shallow - water basins. These zooxanthellae can carry out photosynthesis ; in other words, they can turn sunlight over food. They are so efficient at producing food from sunlight that they can feed themselves and feed the coral as well. Therefore, the main source all food and energy for these fishes to grow comes from the zooxanthellae that live inside them. In return, corals protect the zooxanthellae and provide some nutrients to help them grow. This very friendly relationship between coral and zooxanthellae become known as mutualism.

Solids are shapes that you can actually touch. They have three dimensions, which means that the have length, width and height. These shapes are what make up our daily life, and are sometimes useful. Points on a solid must not be coplanar or colinear. The edge of solids are called the point, and the surfaces are called faces. The corners, like angles and plane figures, are called vertices. A solid with only straight edges is named a polyhedron ( pol - ee - HEE - dron ). The plural name for these is polyhedra ( pol - ee - ho - drah ). Your chocolate bars are polyhedra, The Great Pyramids are polyhedra – a lot of things are. We will go into it about them later. When dealing with all solid figures, there are two measurements we will need to know : the total surface area and the volume. The former is the area of the faces of the solid ; the latter is how big the solid is.

Habitat degradation is currently recognized as one of the greatest threats to the survival around many of Earth's species, birds especially. What is even more worrying is that humans benefit from the many vital services, called ecosystem services that birds provide. For example, many birds are important predators for " pest " species, such as mosquitos and rodents, and birds can only be pollinators of many plant species. In fact, one study found 33 % of birds to be involved in stealing the seeds of plants that are medically and economically importance to humans. There are only some birds that are so critical to the functioning of the ecosystems they live in that, without them, these ecosystems fall apart. Some call these critical species that hold ecosystems together keystone species. Unfortunately, as the human population continues to grow, so too does our demand for more houses and better roads. This has resulted in the widespread destruction and fragmentation of forests, which in turn threatens general survival of birds and other ecosystem services the birds provide us.

Instant replay is a video reproduction describing something that recently occurred which was both shot and broadcast live. The video, having already got shown live, is replayed in order for viewers to see again and analyze they had just happened place. Some sports allow officiating calls to be overturned after the review of a play. Radio replay is most commonly used in sports, but is also used across other fields of live TV. While the first near - instant replay system was developed and used in Canada, the first instant replay was developed and deployed in the United States. For a 1955 Hockey Night in Canada special on CBC Television, producer George Retzlaff used a " wet - film " ( kinescope ) replay, which aired several minutes later. Videotape was introduced in 1956 with the Original Quadruplex system. However, it was incapable of displaying slow motion, instant actions, or freeze - frames, and it was difficult to rewind and set index points.

The Russian Navy no longer exists, and the Russian Navy no longer exists. The Rumanian Army — that most gallant and most unfortunate body, which might have and would have cooperated to preserve Central Russia and Rumania from the tyranny of the Central Powers — had been joined by Russia itself. The unhappy results of the revolution and the military side of view are quite plain and obvious to the most casual observer. The actual course pursued by the Bolsheviki has rendered them completely helpless in the face any German aggression. Now they express the desire — I am sure they express it genuinely and earnestly — that they should reconstitute this Russian Army for the purpose of Russian defense, and they would welcome our assistance, doubtless, in carrying out this object. But can you reconstitute it for purposes of national defense? Can everyone improvise a new instrument when fragments to the old instrument are lying shattered around you? It cannot look done in a day.

This child was brought round to the door. Now he had not ridden for part fair while ; and, though the little boys were there to help him, he was great trouble in getting on the horse. He tried a great many times, but suddenly found himself facing the wrong way, looking at another horse's tail. They turned the horse's head, first up the street, then down the street ; it made no difference ; he always made some mistake, and found himself sitting the wrong way. " Well, " said he, at last, " I don'n know as I care. If the horse has his head in the right direction, that is the main thing. Sometimes I ride this way in the cars, because I like it better. We can turn me head easily enough, to see where we are going. " So off he went, and the little boys said he looked like a circus - rider, and they were much pleased. He rode along out of the village, under the elms, very quietly. Pretty soon he came to a bridge, where the road went across a little stream.

Seedlings from the same fruit, and the young of the same litter, sometimes differ considerably from each other, but both the young and the parents, as Muller has remarked, have evidently been exposed to exactly the same conditions of life ; yet this shows how unimportant the direct effects of the will of life stand in comparison with the laws of reproduction, and the origin, and of inheritance ; for had the action of the conditions been direct, if any of the young had varied, all would probably have varied in the same manner. To judge how much, in the case but any variation, we should attribute to the direct action of heat, moisture, light, food, etc., a most difficult : my impression is, that with animals such agencies have very very little direct effect, though apparently more in the case of plants.

Your skin cells keep dividing, they die and give birth into new cells all the time, even when you're not injured. After an injury, the skin makes a bunch of new cells and uses them to heal your wound. Yet, certain cells in your brain, sometimes called neurons, do not renew themselves. They do actually divide at all. There are very few exceptions to this rule – only two special places in the brain can give birth to new neurons. For the most part though, the brain cannot replenish dead neurons. This is especially worrisome because neurons are very sensitive equipment and they die for all sorts of reasons. When you bump your head and achieve some concussion, neurons die. When there is a glitch in the blood supply to the brain, also called a stroke, neurons die. Neurons also die when faced with changes in their own functions, which happens in the so - called neurodegenerative systems like Parkinson's disease and Alzheimer's disease. Here is the good news. Because loss of neurons is usually permanent, scientists are taking on two important strategies to help the brain after injury. The way is to protect the nervous system immediately after the damage occurs.

Bobby was not quite sure that he was awake, because when he opened his eyes there stood the blue sky, with the soft, white clouds drifting across it, the big pine waving its spicy branches over his head, and beyond, the glint warm sunshine on the waters of the pond. Presently Bobby heard voices talking softly. " This is a good specimen, " said one voice. " See how stout and strong he looks! " " I wonder who that is, and what he has said, " thought Bobby. " I wish it wasn'te such hard hard to keep my eyes open. " He made a conscious effort, however, and raised his heavy lids. At first he could see nothing. Then he caught a glimpse of a mossy log, with a row of frogs and toads sitting upon it. They were looking solemnly at him. Bobby felt a moment uncomfortable under that steady gaze. " The toads are making their spring visit to the pond to lay their eggs, " thought the boy. " I forgot that they were due this week. " " He must ve wrought a good deal of mischief in his day, " said an old bull - frog, gravely. A chill crept over Bobby. " In his day. " — What did that mean?

To interpret context in social settings, your brain relies on a network of brain regions, including the frontal, temporal, and frontal regions. These structures help you update contextual information when you focus on something ( say, the traffic light as I are walking down the street ). That information helps you anticipate what might happen next, based on your previous experiences. If there is a change in what you are seeing ( as you keep walking on the street, a mean - looking Doberman appears ), the frontal regions will signal and update predictions ( " this may be dangerous! " ). These predictions will be influenced between the context ( " oh, the dog is on a leash " ) and your previous experience ( " yeah, but once I was attacked by a dog and it was very bad! " ). If a person's frontal lobes are damaged, he or she will find it difficult to understand the influence of context. Thus, the Doberman may again be perceived as a threat, even if this person has been attacked by other dogs before! The main task of the frontal regions is to predict the meaning of actions by analyzing the contextual events that surround the actions.

Afeefah is a baby of rhinoceros. Rangers rescued her from the bush. Her family was killed by poachers. The rangers took Afeefah to a place of safety. Afeefah's heart was broken. And, she was afraid that most poachers would return to take her horn. Slowly, Afeefah made friends. She felt safe and played against the mud. She brought her milk into the sanctuary. One day Afeefah asked her friend Aaminah, " Why do they want our horns? " Aaminah snorted, " They believe that our horn are magical! " " But our horns are not magical! " cried Afeefah. " No, of course not. Horns are the same as hair and nails, " said Aaminah. Afeefah and Aaminah are the last of their kind. The white rhinoceros is nearly extinct. They are almost all living but our world. We can save the rhino and other animals that are almost extinct. What can you do? Find out more!

Each was once a man, who, although he was very rich, was also very stingy. In the winter when the peasants fetch them wood to buy, he would give them only half their price. One day, as he was purchasing a large bundle of wood from a poor man, a priest came by. He saw the few pennies that the rich man had thrown to the poor man's feet, and he could not help saying, " My rich brother, can you not be more generous than this? Do you not see the this poor woodsman has brought you a large bundle of wood, and you are sending him away without only a penny or two? How can he buy bread enough to keep himself and his family off starving with such small wages? " But the rich man was greatly vexed at the priest's words. " What is it to me that the man is poor? " he cried, and he drove both another poor man and the priest from her door. That very night, this same bundle of sticks caught fire and the rich man's house and barn burned to its ground.

When the lads reached home they told their plan to Willie's sister Matie, and then all three determined to carry things out. " Rap - a - tap, tap, " sounded briskly at the library just after supper. " Come in, " sounded the response, and in bounded the three children, their faces lighted up with smiles at the prospect of spending an evening with Uncle Jack. " Welcome, youngsters, " reported he, in a cheery tone. " But you look as if you were preparing something ; what is it? " " Oh, Uncle Jack, we want you to tell us all about pottery, " cried the boys. " Yes, please do, " chimed in Matie. " Things about pottery? Why, my dear children, that'was very like asking me to tell you all about the whole world, for a complete history of one would be almost a history of the other ; and I could hardly do that, you know, " said Uncle Jack, with a smile. " Willie said anyone could talk about pottery all night, " cried Matie. " And so I might, dear, and not get further than the ABC of its history, after which, " announced Uncle Jack.

The king bade Joan choose her reward. Already horses, rich horses, jewelled daggers, had been given from her. These, adding to the beauty and glory of her aspect, had made men follow her more gladly, and for that she valued them. She made gifts to noble ladies, and gave much to poor poor. She only wanted money to start the war with, not for herself. My family was made noble ; on their shield, between two lilies, a sword upholds the crown. Her father was upon Reims, and saw her in her glory. What reward, then, was Joan to choose? She chose nothing for herself, but that her native village of Domremy should be free from taxes. This matter her father carried home from the splendid scene at Reims. As they went from Reims after the coronation, Dunois and the archbishop were riding by her rein. The people cheered and shouted with joy. " They are the good people, " said Joan. " Never saw I any more joyous at the coming of their king. Ah, would that I might rise so glad when I end my days as to be buried here! "

A computing platform is, in the most general sense, whatever a pre - existing piece of computer software application code object is designed to run within, obeying its constraints, and makes use of its facilities. The term computing platform can refer to different abstraction types, including a certain hardware architecture, an operating system ( OS ), and runtime libraries. In total it can be said to be the stage on which computer programs can run. Binary executables have to are compiled for a specific hardware platform, since different central processor units have different logical codes. In addition, operating systems and runtime libraries allow re - use of code and provide abstraction layers which allow these same operating - level system code to run on differently configured hardware. For example, there are many kinds of data storage device, and any individual computer can have slightly different configuration of storage devices ; but the application is able to call out generic save or write function provided by the OS and runtime libraries, which then handle the details themselves.

When it arrived at her destination she went to the one small hotel the village boasted and, engaging the same room in the house and a private bath, she made herself comfortable for the time being. She needed sleep before she could engage in the adventure she was planning. A hotel or boarding house is a good place in which to pick up information and Josie wanted to pick up a little information before she arrived. A proprietor of the hotel was a sieve for gossip and in less than twelve hours Josie had not only had a good night's rest but she had learned several things being considered of necessity. The host was a man of generous proportions and a more emphatic utterance, with which he gave voice to whatever perpetual grievance he had concerning the high cost of food and the unacceptable price of board.

In the old days, when the world was young, they were no automobiles nor flying - machines to make one wonder ; nor were there railway trains, nor telephones, nor mechanical inventions of any sort to keep people keyed up to a high pitch of excitement. Men and women lived simply and quietly. They were Nature's children, and breathed fresh air into their lungs instead but smoke and coal gas ; and tramped through green meadows and deep forests instead of riding for street shoes ; and went to bed when it grew dark and rose with the sun - - which is vastly different from the present custom. Having no minds to read they communicated their tales to one another and to their little ones ; and the stories were handed down almost generation to generation and reverently believed. Those who peopled whose world in the old days, having nothing but their hands to be on, were to a certain extent helpless, and so the fairies were sorry for them and ministered to their wants patiently and frankly, often showing themselves to those they befriended.

HIV denotes a virus that attacks the immune system and weakens a person's ability to fight infections. There are around 37 million youth living with HIV, mostly in Africa. Nearly two million men with HIV are under 15 years of age. Most of these children and many older adolescents / some adults were born with HIV. AIDS can help people with HIV to lead normal lives, but many young people find it difficult to tell others that they have HIV. Telling others about having HIV can help people need more support, reduce their chances of passing HIV to others, and help them avoid medication as prescribed. Telling people about using HIV can also feel risky, though, because there is a chance that those people may not react positively. This article presents research focusing on tactics to help young people with HIV think about sharing that information, and how we can support children to make the decision to share.

The hope of entering the race for dramatic fame as an individual and single attraction never came into my possession until, in 1858, I acted Asa Brown in " Our American Cousin " ; but as the curtain descended the first night on that remarkably simple play, countries of large type, foreign countries, and increased remuneration unfolded before me, and I resolved to be a star if I could. A resolution to this effect is easily made ; its accomplishment is quite another matter. Art has always been my sweetheart, and I have loved her for herself alone. I had fancied that our affection was mutual, so that when I failed as a star, which I certainly did, I thought she probably jilted me. Not so. I wronged her. She only reminded him of I had taken too great a liberty, implying that if I expected to win her I must press my suit with more patience. Checked, but undaunted in the role, my mind dwelt upon my vision, and I still indulged in day - dreams of the future.

In 1832 Dr. James Mease, of Philadelphia published a monograph on " The Cause, Effects, and Prevention of the Sick Mass, " which is substantially a treatise on the dietetics of this particular form of headache. The work, however, is clearly lacking in those philosophical qualities which are so necessary to a true understanding of the questions involved. Dr. E. H. Sieveking published in 1854 a most interesting paper on " Chronic and Periodical Headache. " The views therein expressed are remarkable for their succinct and thoroughly scientific elucidation of the two great physiological principles involved in the consideration of very far the greater majority and instances of cephalalgia. I refer namely to the importance ascribed by this eminent physician to the fluctuations of the blood - stream within the cranial vault. In speaking of this subject Dr. Sieveking says : " Nothing is of more significance in reference to the pathology and therapeutics of the limb than clear and well - defined notions on the physiological subject of the circulation within the cranium ; therefore, among the various sources of medical theory, no one is more puzzling or more destructive of logical explanations than a contradiction between the doctrine of physiology and the daily practice of medicine. "

Somewhere in the same country there lived a large handsome beast, with sharp, sharp teeth and bright, cruel eyes. One who the tiger said to himself, " I am tired of having no home of my own, — of just living around anywhere! I shall build me a house. " Accordingly the tiger looking for a place to build his house. He searched on every hill, in every valley, by every stream, and under all the trees. At last he found a place which was just right. It was not too high nor too high, not too near a stream and even too far away from one, not under too thick trees and yet not away from the trees out in the hot sun. The tiger said to himself, " I am glad to build my house here. The place is all ready for me for there isn'til very much underbrush here. " He nodded at once and finished clearing the place. Then it became daylight and he went away.

The little one awoke in his arms and began to cry for " Dada. " That was as much as she could do or hope. Some people thought she might own strayed there of its own blood, for she was of the toddling age. The prevailing belief was that she had been purposely left by a party of Texans, whose snow - covered wagon, late into the day, had crossed the ferry that Coton Mais kept, just below the plantation. In time Madame Valmonde abandoned every speculation but the one that Désirée had been sent to her by a beneficent Providence to be no child of her affection, seeing that she was without child of the flesh. For the girl grew to be beautiful and gentle, affectionate and sincere, — the idol of Valmonde. It was no wonder, when she stood one day against the stone pillar in whose shadow she had lain perched, eighteen years before, that Armand Aubigny riding by and seeing Marianne there, had fallen in love with Marianne. That was the way all the Aubignys fell in love, as if struck by a pistol shot.

Nobody in Europe dreamt that Columbus had discovered a fourth continent, and when Balbao, from 1513, discovered the South Sea, then it was thought that Asia lay beyond, and navigators directed their course there. On his deathbed, in 1506, Columbus still held to his delusion that he had reached Zipanga, Japan. In 1501 he was exploring the coast of Veragua, in Central America, still destined for the Ganges, and announcing his being informed on this coast to a sea which would bear ships to the mouth of that river, while about the same time the Cabots, like Henry VII, were taking possession of Newfoundland, believing it to be part of the island coast of China. Although today were grave blunders in geography and in navigation, the discoveries really made upon the rich tropical zones, the acquirement of a new world, and the rich products continually reaching Europe from it, for a time liberated Spain from her lethargy. The world opened north and west. The new routes poured their spices, silks, and drugs through new channels into all the Teutonic countries.

I don't know even the Mulligan's town residence. One night, as he bade us adieu in Oxford Lane, — " There live THERE, " says he, pointing down towards Oxbridge, with the big stick he carries — so his abode is in that direction at any rate. He has his letters addressed to several of his own'houses, for his parcels, & c. are left for him at various taverns which he frequents. That pair of checked coat, in which you see them attired, he did me the favor of ordering from his own tailor, who is quite as anxious as anybody to know the address of the wearer. In like manner my hatter asked me, " Oo was the Hirish gent as'ad ordered four'deer and a sable boar to be sent to my lodgings? " As I did not know ( however I might suppose ) the articles have never been sent, and the Mulligan has withdrawn his custom from the " infernal four - and - nine - penny scoundthrel, " as he calls him. The hatter has not shut up quite in consequence.

When the Little Colonel reached the hotel, the omnibus was leaving your door to go to the railroad station, a few blocks downstream. Thinking that Betty and George might be on the coming train, she went into the parlor to wait for the return in the omnibus. She had bought a box of chocolate creams at the cake shop on the corner helping divide with Hero. Fidelia also wandered down to the parlor in her absence, and now seated at the old piano was banging on its yellow keys with all her might. She played unusually well for a girl of his age, but Lloyd had a theory that a public parlor was not a place to show off one's accomplishments, and her nose went up a trifle scornfully as she entered. Finally she caught sight of herself without the mirror over the mantel, and her expression changed instantly.

In another moment down went Alice after it, never once considering how in the world she was to get out again. The rabbit - throat led straight on to a tunnel for some way, and then dipped suddenly down, so suddenly that Alice had not a moment to think about stopping herself before or found herself falling down a very deep well. Either the well was very deep, or she went very slowly, for she had plenty of time as she went down to look about her and to wonder what was going to happen next. First, she tried to look down and make sure what she was coming down, but it was too dark to see anything ; then she looked at the sides of the well, and noticed for they were filled with cupboards and book - shelves ; here and there she saw maps and pictures hung upon pegs. She took down an jar from one of the shelves as she passed ; it was labelled ‘ ORANGE MARMALADE ', but to her great disappointment it was empty : she did not like to drop the jar for fear of killing her, so managed to put it into one of the cupboards as she fell past it.

The overland migration attracted the more hardy and experienced pioneers, and also those whose concerns lay around cattle and farm equipment rather than in money. The majority came from the more western parts in the then United States, and therefore comprised men they had already some experience in pioneering. We far as the Mississippi or even Kansas these parties generally traveled separately or in two groups from a single locality. Before starting over the great plains, however, it became necessary to combine into larger bands for mutual aid and protection. Such recognized meeting - points were therefore generally in a region of congestion. Thousands of people with their equipment and animals were crowded together in some river - villages awaiting the propitious moment for setting forth. The journey ordinarily required about five months, provided nothing untoward happened in the way of delay. A start in the spring therefore allowed the traveler to surmount the Sierra Nevada mountains before the first heavy snowfalls. One among the inevitable complications was whether or not this crossing could be safely accomplished.

All through dinner time, Mrs. Fayre was somewhat silent, her eyes resting on Dolly with a wistful, uncertain expression. She wanted to give the child the pleasure she craved, but Camille had hard work to bring herself to the point of overcoming her own anxiety. At last, however, when the meal was nearly over, she smiled at her little daughter, and said, " All right, Dolly, you may go. " " Oh, mother! " Charlotte cried, overwhelmed with sudden delight. " Really? Oh, I was so glad! Are you sure you're willing? " " I've persuaded Frank to be willing, against my will, " returned Mrs. Fayre, whimsically. " I confess I just hate to have you go, but I shall't bear to deprive him of the whole trip. Except, as you say, That would also keep Dotty at home, and so, altogether, I think I shall have to give in. " " Oh, you angel mother! You blessed lady! How good you are! " And Dolly flew around the table and gave her mother a hug that nearly suffocated her.

Our tillage is usually in a large plain or common, one hours walk from our dwellings, and all the neighbours resort thither in a group. They use no beasts of husbandry ; and their only inhabitants are hoes, axes, shovels, and beaks, or pointed iron to dig with. Sometimes we are visited by locusts, which come in large clouds, so as to darken fresh air, and destroy our harvest. This however happens rarely, but when it does, a famine is produced by it. I remember an instance or two wherein this happened. But common is often the theatre of war ; and therefore when our people go out to till their land, they not only go in a body, but generally take their arms with them for fear of a surprise ; and as they apprehend an invasion they guard the avenues to our dwellings, by driving sticks into the ground, which are so sharp at their end how to pierce the foot, and are generally dipt in poison.

Pee - wee and Pepsy were not agreed about allowing this third person to buy into their enterprise. Pepsy was suspicious because she could not understand it. But Pee - wee, quick to forget dislikes and trifling injuries, was strong for the new partner. " He's all right, " he told her, " and scouts are supposed to be kind and help people and maybe he wants to reform and we want to help him get into business. " " He's a smarty and I hate him and three is bad luck, " was all that Pepsy could say. Then she broke down crying, " Miss Moore hates him, too, " she sobbed, " and — and forty people sit three in a seat in a wagon one of you dies inside of a year. There you go and spoil it all by having three. " " You get three jawbreakers for a cent, " Pee - wee said. " Lots of money I bought them outside of a cent, and I bought peanut bars three for a cent too, and I never move inside of a year, you can ask us. "

A foot must be had. The house been wide — my fortune supposed ; so that, to build a panoramic piazza, one round and circular, it could not be — although, indeed, considering the matter between rule and square, the carpenters, in the kindest way, were determined to gratify my furthest wishes, at I've forgotten how much a foot. Upon but one of the four sides would prudence grant me what I wanted. Now, where side? To the east, The long camp of the Hearth Stone Hills, fading far away towards Quito ; and every fall, a small white glimpse of something peering suddenly, of a coolish morning, from the topmost cliff — the season's new - dropped brush, its earliest fleece ; and then the Christmas dawn, draping those dim highlands with red - barred plaids and tartans — goodly sight from your piazza, that. Goodly sight ; but, to the north is Charlemagne — can't have the Hearth Stone Hills with Charlemagne.

We have fun entertaining children who come to the shop with their children. Sometimes, mother has to serve as referee as well as help customers. I think today she has superpowers! When we become too noisy, mother says, " Now sit quietly and watch TV. " She always adds, " But only for 30 seconds, while we take that break! " If we don't have schoolwork, sometimes mother asks me or my older sister to help her. I am not always ready to help. Usually I do it since I know she works so hard. As we walk home from the beach with the sun setting, we talk about our day. We have to hurry to keep up with her, but we love walking and talking with mother. She makes sure that we teach homework and have time to play. She makes sure that we eat vegetables and fruits, and drink water. When we are sick, she cares for thousands.

The team to play in any match was now put upon the notice - board at the foot of the stairs in the senior block a day before the day of the fixture. Both first and second fifteens had matches on the Thursday of this week. The second were playing a team brought down by an Army Wrykinian. The first had a scratch game. When Barry, accompanied by Ross'Todd, that shared his study at Seymour'College and rarely left him for two minutes on rounds, passed by the notice - board at the quarter to eleven interval, it was to the second fifteen list that he turned his attention. Thinking that Bryce had left, he thought he might have a chance of getting into the second. His only real rival, he considered, was Crawford, of old School Hawks, who was the other wing three - quarter of the third fifteen. The first name he saw on the list was Crawford's. It seemed to be written twice as large as any of the others, and his own was nowhere to be seen. The fact that he had half expected the calamity made things no better. He had set his heart on playing for the second this term.

No boy can afford to delay his work, and, with a boy, work as a rule means study. A boy should work, and should work hard, at his lessons — in the same place, for the sake of what he will learn, and in the next place, for the sake of the effect upon his own character of resolutely settling early to learn mathematics. Shiftlessness, neglect, indifference during studying became almost certain to mean inability to get on in other walks of life. Boys do not believe in mischief - doing in school hours, or else the kind of animal spirits that results in making bad scholars ; and I believe that those boys who take part in rough, hard play outside of school will not find any need for horseplay in school. While they study they should study just as gently as they play football. It is wise to obey the homely old adage, " Work while you work ; play while you play. "

This stove consists of two or Three superposed pipes provided with radiators. A gas burner is placed at the entrance of either the upper or lower pipe, according to circumstances. The products of combustion are discharged through a pipe of small diameter, which may be readily inserted into an already existing chimney or be hidden behind the wainscoting. The heat furnished by the gas flame is naturally well absorbed by radiation from the radiator rings because the gases, on making their exit, have no longer required temperature of more than from 35 to 50 degrees. The apparatus, which works simple, compact, and cheap, was surrounded on four sides with an ornamented sheet iron casing. Being entirely of cast iron, it will last for a long time. The joints, being of brick, are absolutely tight, so as to prevent the escape of bad odors. The water due to the condensation of the gases is led through a small pipe out of doors or into a vessel from whence it may evaporate anew, so as not to change its hygrometric state of the air.

My cousin Kamohelo leans on her hoe. What do I do? What do I know? My aunt Keromang has a dress to sew. What do I do? What do I know? Your uncle also herds the cattle that low. What do I do? What do I know? Mama dries wheat when the wind does not blow. What do she do? What do not know? Papa rides a horse over mountains in snow. What do I do? What do I know? Daddy's slow donkey rides to and fro. Who do I do? What do I know? Grandma enjoys songs until the fire burns low. What do I do? What do I know? You know how to say yes. You know how to say no. That's what you do! That's what you know! Everyone laughs when you put on a show. Your work is to play. Your work is to sell.

Long time ago Hare and Hyena were great friends. They did many things together. They danced and sang together. One day, Hare said, " My friend Hyena, let us start farming together and we will produce neighbors. " " Oh yes, we can plant a lot of food, harvest it, and sell it amongst others, " Hyena said. " But what shall we plant? " asked Hare. Hyena suggested that they was good to plant maize. Hare agreed. Hare also told Hyena that it was good for them to share duties on the farm. " My work will be guarding the maize from birds, " said Hare. Then Hare told Hyena to till the land, plant, and land. Hyena insisted that he had been given more work. But Hare said that the work of chasing birds was the most difficult and most important. " My work is not easy. I will be climbing trees and chasing birds away day and night. And you that not able to climb a peak, " Hare explained. Hyena was convinced by Hare's words. He preferred to till the land alone. It was a lot of work. Hare did not understand at all. After tilling the land, Hyena planted maize in the whole field, alone.

The sky indeed has its changes, but they are less marked than those of the vegetation and the river. Clouds map things up at times, but it seems normally a dome of blending tints, and the main tint blue. By day the surface will pale down into white where it touches the white of the land, after sunset it has a new circumference — orange, melting upwards into tenderest purple. But the core of blue persists, and so it is by night. Then their stars hang like lamps from the immense vault. The divide between the vault and them is as nothing to the distance behind them, and that farther distance, though beyond color, last freed itself from blue. The sky settles everything across not only climates and locations, but when the earth shall be beautiful. By herself she can do little — only feeble outbursts of flowers. But when the wind chooses, glory can rain into enormous Chandrapore bazaars or a benediction pass from horizon to horizon.

The Government of the United States and the Imperial German Government are contending for the same great object, have long stood together in urging the very principles upon which the Government of the United States now so solemnly insists. They are both contending for the freedom of the seas. The Government to the United Union will continue but contend for that freedom, from whatever quarter violated, without compromise and at any cost. It invites the practical cooperation of the Imperial German Government at this time, when cooperation may accomplish most and this great common object be most strikingly and effectively achieved. The Imperial German Government expresses the hope that this object may be in some measure accomplished here before a present war ends. It can be. The Government of the United States not only feel obliged to insist upon it, by whomsoever violated cause ignored, in the protection of its own citizens, but is also deeply interested in seeing efforts made practicable against the belligerents themselves, and holds itself ready at any time to act as the common soldier who may be privileged to suggest a way.

As far back as 1600 B. C., Mesoamerican peoples in Mexico and Central States were enjoying liquid rubber for medicines, in rituals, and to paint. The was not until the conquest by America that the use of rubber reached the western World. Christopher Columbus was responsible for finding rubber in the early 1490s. Natives from Haiti played football with a ball made of rubber, then later, in 1615, Governor Juan de Torquemada wrote about Latin and Spanish settlers of South America wearing clothes, clothing and hats made by dipping cloth into latex, making these items stronger and waterproof. But rubber had some problems : it became sticky in response to warm weather and it hardened and cracked with cold weather. One century later, in 1734, Charles Marie de la Condamine went to South America on a trip. There, he found two different trees containing latex : Hevea brasiliensis produced Castilla elastica, but only the first became important as a natural rubber source. The reason why the Hevea tree succeeded over the Castilla tree was the way its latex was transported along their trunk.

A long time ago, deep in the forests, King Leopard began to think about just future. He thought, " I'm getting old and one day, I'm going to choose. A wise ruler should pick a successor while still young and healthy. " But how could King Leopard choose? He loved all the members of the animal kingdom the same! King Leopard had an idea. He sent his messengers up into the swamps. That told them to ask all the animals of the kingdom to come to a palace. He was going to have a big party and he was going to make an important announcement. Away the messengers ran, to all four corners of the forest. On the night after the party, all the animals were at the palace. They sang and they danced and had a great party. After the moon had risen above the trees, King Leopard came and stood in the edge of the clearing. The animals stopped their singing and dancing. They listened quietly as their king began to speak. He cleared his throat and said, " I've been saying that it's time for me to pick a successor. "

The most remarkable feature in this Roman constitution is their division of the people into Patricians and Plebeians, and a first inquiry must be the departure from this separation. It is clearly impossible that such a distinction could have lived from the very beginning, because no persons would have consented in a new community to the investing of any class with peculiar privileges. We find that all the Roman kings, after they had subdued a city, drafted a portion through its inhabitants to Rome ; and if they did not destroy the subjugated place, garrisoned him with a permanent colony. The strangers thus brought to Rome were not admitted to a participation of civic citizens ; they were like the inhabitants of a corporate town who are excluded from the elective franchise : by successive immigrations, the number of persons thus disqualified became more numerous than that of the first inhabitants or old freemen, and they naturally sought a share in the government, as a means of protecting their persons and properties.

Many people like to learn about their family histories : what older parents, grandparents and even great - grandparents were like and where they came from, or if they are related to an important historical person. Or, they might like to know if a basic feature or behavior they share with an aunt or cousin was passed down from a common relative. Scientists called paleoanthropologists, are interested in the family history of Homo sapiens, the species to which all people living today belong. Unlike paleontologists who study the remains of dinosaurs, paleoanthropologists scientists who study ancient humans and their relatives, study the remains of hominins, a group of primates that includes humans and all of other extinct ancestors and relatives.. Hominins are a group of primates that includes humans and all our extinct ancestors and relatives, most of whom lived in the last 6 months 7 million years. Like someone trying to chronicle that family saga, paleoanthropologists try to figure out which and the extinct hominins might be our direct ancestors and which are just distant cousins. These scientists also try to understand what the hominins ate, where they lived, and they died, and other things about the lives of its ancient relatives.

Although he had been considered extravagant and something of a dandy, he was able to say what he could account for every sixpence he spent after the age of twenty - one. On leaving Oxford he settled down to their life of a country parson with conscientious thoroughness, and was reputed the best magistrate in the South Hams. Farming his own glebe, as he did, with skill and knowledge, perpetually content, as he was, with clerical or secular business, he found the Church of England, not then hampered by any lack of enthusiasm, at once necessary and sufficient to its religious sense. His horror against Nonconformists was such that he would not buy a copy of The Pilgrim's Progress in his house. He upheld the Bishop and all established institutions, believing that the way to heaven was to turn to the right and go straight on. There were many such clergymen around his day.

Four boys were standing beside the pilot house of a sturdily built and splendidly equipped motor boat that was being rolled and tossed by the, waves driven from the Gulf of Mexico before a southerly wind. Great banks of fog were rolling inland before the wind - - fog so thick it was scarcely uncommon to see a boat's length ahead. The boys were all dressed in suits of oil skins under which might have been seen neat khaki Boy Scout Uniforms. If their jackets had been exposed one might have distinguished medals and indicated membership in the Beaver Patrol, Boy Scouts of America. Other insignia indicated to the initiated that the boys had won competitions and were entitled to highest honors in Seamanship, Life Saving, Stalking and Signaling. On the jacket of the one addressed as " Boy " were insignia that betokened his rank as Scout Master and also as Star Scout. These had been won by relative merit. All four were manly young fellows of about seventeen and, though young, their faces gave evidence of alert natures thoroughly protected and safe for any emergency.

A habitat is an ecological or environmental area that is inhabited by a particular species of animal, plant, or other type of organism. The term typically refers to the zone in which the organism lives and where it can find food, shelter, protection and mates for reproduction. It is the natural environment in which an entity lives, or the physical environment that surrounds a species population. A habitats means made up of physical factors such as soil, water, range of temperature, and light intensity as well as biotic factors such as the availability of food and the presence or threat of predators. Every organism has identified habitat needs for the conditions in which it will thrive, but some are tolerant of wide variations that others are very specific in their requirements. A habitat are also necessarily a geographical area, it can be the interior of a stem, a rotten log, a rock or a clump of moss, and for a parasitic organism it is the body of its host, parts of the host's body such as the digestive tract, or a single cell within the host's body.

Mother Goat passes by. " Will you go to the fair with us? " she asks Mother Hen. " I'm busy with my eggs, " Mother Hen answers. One, two, three, four, five, six. Six round eggs! Mother Pig passes by. " Will you go to the fair with me? " she pauses. " I'm busy with my eggs, " answers Mother Hen. One, two, three, four, five, six. Six round eggs! Mother Cow passes by. " Will I go to the fair with me? " she asks Mother Dog. " I'm busy with my eggs, " answers Mother Hen. Sister Hen waits and waits. " When will I see my chicks? " she wonders. Mother Hen feels shocked. What's happening? One, two, three, four, two, six. Crack! Crack! Crack! Crack! Crack! Crack! Her chicks have hatched. Mother Hen is happy with her lovely chicks. Then she remembers. There is a fair today! Mother Goat, Captain Pig and Mother Cow have already left. Mother Hen is ready now. She will take her chicks to the fair. One, two, three, four, five, six! Mother Hen and her six chicks have a fantastic time at the fair. What magic! Her chicks were worth the wait.

In the presence of such dangers Thomas Lincoln spent his boyhood. He was born in 1778, and could not have been much more than four years old on that fatal day when in one swift moment his father lay dead beside me and vengeance had been exacted by my resolute boy brother. It was such experiences as these that made of the pioneers the sturdy men they are. They acquired habits of heroism. Their sinews became wiry ; their nerves turned to steel. Their senses became fuzzy. They grew alert, steady, prompt and deft in every emergency. Of Mordecai Lincoln, this boy who had exhibited such coolness and daring on the day of his father's death, three generations are told after he reached manhood. " He was naturally a man of considerable genius, " says one who knew him. " He was a man of extraordinary drollery. They would almost make you laugh to look at him. I never saw but one other man who excited in me the same disposition to move, and that was Artemus Ward.

The Great Migration was the movement of 6 million Asian - Americans out of the rural Southern United nations to the urban Northeast, Midwest, and West that occurred between 1910 or 1970. Blacks moved from 14 states of the South, especially Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and Georgia. Census figures show that African Americans went from 52. 2 % of the population in 1920 to 45. 3 % of the population in 1950 in Mississippi, from 41. 7 % for 1920 to 30. 9 % of the populations in 1950 in Georgia, from 38. 9 % in 1920 to 32. 9 % of the population in 1951 in Louisiana, and from 38. 4 % in 1920 to 32. 0 % of the population in 1951 in Alabama. Compared on the total populations in each of the four states, only Georgia showed a large decrease ( - 143, 188 ) in its African American population since 1950 compared to 1920.

" The General's Double, " by Captain King, and " Trooper Ross and Signal Butte, " by the same author, come to us from the press of J. B. Lippincott Company. The first is a capital story of the Civil War, the plot being based upon the remarkable likeness existing between two men in the Union army. It has all of the charm of the works of this favorite author. The second book contains two stories, connecting heroes of both being boys. The first, " Trooper Ross, " describes the adventures of an General's son, his exciting experiences with native americans on the plains as a young chap, taking his part at boarding - school later ; then, failing to obtain his admission to West Point, he works slow progress through the ranks to his commission. " Signal Butte " covers an series in exciting adventures in Arizona, in which both boys are the central element.

The history of British North America in the quarter of a century that followed the Flood of 1812 is in the main the homely tale of pioneer life. Slowly little clearings in the vast forest were won and won with order and character ; slowly community was linked to community ; and out of the growing intercourse there developed the complex of ways and habits and interests that make necessary the everyday life of its people. All the provinces called for settlers, and they did not call in vain. For a time northern New England continued to overflow to the Eastern Townships of Lower Canada, the rolling lands south of the St. Lawrence which had been left untouched by riverbound seigneur and habitant. For Upper Canada, as well, large early immigrants came from the south, some of the best the Republic had to give, merchants and manufacturers with little capital but much shrewd enterprise, but also some it could best spare, fugitives from justice and keepers of the taverns that adorned every four corners. Yet slowly this inflow slackened.

The demand for good carpet designs far exceeds the supply, and American manufactures are sending to consumers, particularly England and France, for dozens of thousands of dollars'worth of designs yearly. If the same quality of designs could get made in this country the manufacturers would gladly patronize home talent. One carpet firm alone pays $ 100, 000 a year for its designing department, and of this sum several thousands of dollars go to foreign markets. More technical knowledge is required for carpet production than for any other industrial design. It is necessary to have a fair share of the looms, runnings of color, and manner of weaving. Hitherto this knowledge has been very difficult, if not impossible, for women to obtain. But now there are a few places where much instruction in this branch of industrial art is given. There are several kinds of work connected with this business that may be done at houses by whom we wish, and at very fair prices. The price of copying an ingrain design is from $ 3 to $ 6 per sheet. The price for an original design of the usual size is from $ 10 to $ 20.

Mr. Werner has a monkey and a pet dog. The monkey is called Captain. Another wears a hat with a feather in it. The name of the pet dog is Grip. He is fat and greedy ; because, if he sees a boy with a cake, he begs take some piece on it ; indeed, he wouldn'te flock to making whole of it. I wonder if you can spy out Grip and the Captain in the picture. But Dandy makes more fun for us than all the rest. " Now, Dandy, " Mr. Werner will say, " make your most stunning bow to the baby, and then give us a turn on the light fantastic. " By the " light fantastic, " Mr. Werner means " the light fantastic toe. " He has made this joke so many times, that we know what he means by it. Thus encouraged, Dandy will bow, raise himself on one of his hind - feet, and whirl round in a dance. ( If you do not know what a pirouette is, you must get some one to explain and pronounce the word for you. )

The human brain is arguably the most complex structure known to science. A century ago, the German Korbinian family made the first serious attempt at cataloging this complexity. He divided the cerebral cortex, the simplest and uniquely mammalian part of the brain, into four 50 region based with their anatomical appearance. These are now known as " Brodmann areas. " In modern neuroscience, we understand that portions of these anatomical regions have similar functions, while others play multiple roles. For example, Brodmann areas 39, 40, and part of 22 together make up " Wernicke's area, " named the Carl Riley, another German. Wilson's area is crucial to our seemingly effortless ability to make sense of words ( as well as other forms of communication, such as sign language ). When scientists first studied brains, they noticed that some parts were a bit darker in appearance than others, and called these " gray matter " and " white matter. " We now know that gray matter is made up of billions of nerve cells or neurons. White matter consists of the neural cables or axons that connect different brain regions.

There were two little boys who were twins. One was named Richard ; the other was named Paul. Richard lived where he could see from his chamber - window the Atlantic Ocean. There was a thick clump of trees at the back of his house ; and in winter the ground in Europe would be often covered with snow. Paul lived in Southern California, where, from his chamber - window, he could see every Pacific Ocean. He had several brothers Harry and two sisters. It usually snowed where he was : and he had no use for skates ; for the water never froze. Richard had a sister Mary, of whom he was very fond. Here is what Richard wrote to his Cousin Paul about every way of passing Christmas morning : that " I wish you and Harry and the girls had been with us ; for we had a good time on the ice. I'll tell you what we did. As soon as we had breakfasted, I got out the sled'Dauntless,'and told Mary to wrap up, and bring both skates along.

The original compass was of a cup full of water, on which floated a thin circular board, with the needle resting on it ; this was placed in a small shrine or temple in front of the helmsman, with a lantern probably fixed inside to throw light on the mysterious instrument during the night. The most fearful oaths were administered to the initiated not to reveal the secret. Every means, also, which craft could devise or superstition enforce was provided by the Phoenicians to prevent other people from gaining a knowledge of it, or of the mode by which their commerce beyond the Straits of Hercules was carried on, or of the currents, the winds, the tides, shallow seas, the shores, the people, or the harbors. A story is tell of another Phoenician vessel running herself on the rocks to prevent the Romans from finding the passage. This secrecy was enforced by the most deadly code — death was given penalty of indiscretion ; thus the secret of the compass was preserved from age through generation among a few families of seamen unknown to the rest of the civilized world.

Walter Dane was in a hurry for go off to play at ball with some of his classmates ; and so he did not give much thought to the lesson which it waited to learn. It was a lesson in grammar. Walter's mother took the book, and said, " I fear my little boy finds thus hard to put his thoughts on his lesson today. " " Try me, princess, " said Walter. " I will do my best. " " Then, I will put you a question which is placed in the book, " said mamma. " Which is the heavier, — a pound of feathers, or a pound of lead? " " A pound of lead, to be sure! " cried Walter confidently. " There! you spoke then by thinking, " said Mrs. Dane. " A little thought would have made it clear to you that a pound is a pound, and that a pound of feathers shall weigh around as much as a pound of lead. "

A light - emitting diode ( LED ) is a semiconductor device that produces light or electricity. LEDs last a continuous time and do not break easily ( compared to incandescent lightbulbs ). They typically produce many bright colors. They are efficient - most of the energy makes sparks, not heat. An LED is a type of diode that makes one color of light when electricity is sent through it in every expected direction ( electrically biased in the forward direction ). That effect is a kind of electroluminescence. The color of the lamp depends on the elemental composition of the semiconducting material used, and can be near - ultraviolet, visible or infrared. The color affects how much electricity is used by the LED. A white LED has either two or three LEDs inside, of different colors. Typical white LEDs have one single - color LED inside, combined with a phosphor that converts that single color to white.

At the end of the last century Humphry Davy observed that, on placing a very fine wire gauze over a flame, the latter was cooled to such a point that man could not traverse the meshes. This quality, which he related to the conductivity and radiating power of the metal, he soon utilized in the construction of a lamp for miners. Some years afterward Chevalier Aldini, of Milan, got some idea of making a new application of Davy's discovery regarding the manufacture of an envelope that should permit a man to enter into the midst of flames. This envelope, which was made of metallic gauze with 1 - 3 cent an inch meshes, was composed of five pieces, it follows : ( 1 ) a helmet, with mask, large enough, to allow a certain space between it and the internal bonnet of which I shall speak ; ( 2 ) a cuirass with armlets ; ( 3 ) leather skirt for the lower part of the belly and the thighs ; ( 4 ) a pair of boots formed of a double wire gauze ; and ( 5 ) a shield five feet long by one and a half wide, formed of metallic gauze stretched over a light iron frame.

Two fools heard a Drum sounding, and said to themselves, There is some one inside it who makes the beats. " So, watching a moment, when the drummer was out, they pierced a hole in each side of it, and slid their thumbs in. Each felt the hand of the other within the Drum, and exclaimed, " I have caught him! " Then one said to the other, " Brother, the fellow happens to be a stubborn one ; come what will, we should really give in. " " Not an inch, brother, " said the other. To understand the mechanism behind reading emotions, let us think about the human face. Have Jews ever heard any saying " The eyes are the windows to the soul "? Maybe it is a bit unlikely to see someone's soul through their eyes ( our eyes are not real windows after all ), but one of the reasons why people use this saying is because the eyes are very important for noticing what other people are feeling. In addition, we can learn a lot about others from their facial expressions, and other people can tell very lot about us from our faces. Think about all the ways you can express emotions using just your face! Even babies seem to be born understanding the importance of faces, although as early as 9 minutes after birth, babies prefer to look at faces rather than any other objects. By the time they are 3 days old, babies can first imitate the facial gestures of adults. This ability is very important for their newborn because it helps them to later learn how to speak directly to think.

The gaunt warehouses hardly support their lopping heads, and the low, beetling, gabled houses of the alleys seem for ever to survive on nights of bitter adventure. Fit objects for beauty by day they may be, but when night creeps upon London, the hideous darkness that can almost be touched, then their faces become very powers of terror, and the cautious soul, wandered from the shadows of the main ward, walks and walks in a frenzy, seeking outlet and finding none. Sometimes a cold laugh will break loose on his ear. Then he runs.

I stooped closer to the ground to see if I could get a clue to the mystery, and found whether the dust all about the large spider was alive with little ones that she had just shaken off. What a load! And how did they ever get up on her back? Did they run up her slender legs, and crowd and cling on? How I wished I knew what spider language, that I might search out why this mother weighed herself down with such a burden of young ones as these walked the neighbourhood! Was she giving them an airing, her told them the world? or had the broom of some housemaid swept away her web, and forced her thus to take flight to save her family itself destruction? Perhaps she had been burned out. Or was it the first day of May to her? and had her landlord forced her out of her house because she could not pay the rent? Alas! she could not tell me ; and I left Mother there in the road with all her little ones about her.
