Hare wanted to know who was stronger, Buffalo or Elephant. They began arguing. Elephant said she was stronger so Buffalo said she was weaker. Hare said he had an idea now to find out who was stronger. He asked them to wait on him there. Hare came back with a long rope. He tied the one end around Elephant's waist and led her away from the river. It tied the other end of the rope around Buffalo's waist and got her near the river. Hare ran and hid himself in a tree. He shouted, " Ready! One, two, three! Pull! " Buffalo and Elephant pulled. Elephant pulled Buffalo. Buffalo pulled Elephant. Neither could win. From where he was hiding, Hare continued to eat Elephant's honey. After he had finished the task, he cut the rope closer to Animal.

In Mr. Motaung's shop, the bread is cut and ready for making kotas. He roughly cuts out the soft middle of each quarter loaf. Then he puts polony and vodka in its space inside. Motaung puts large spoonfuls of his wife's homemade atchar in each corner. Josh likes to boast that his kotas have atchar inside and atchar on top! In Dr Mkhize's shop, the chips are nearly ready, but he is still cutting his bread for kotas. He is worried because things are not going well with his shop. " It started well, " thinks Mkhize. " But now I get fewer and fewer customers. At least I'm reducing some of my costs by cutting five kotas from a loaf. " Jabu and Zodwa are having lunch. Zodwa buys from Mr. Mkhize. Jabu buys from Mr Motaung. He believes that Motaung's kota has got more chips and atchar than Mkhize's kota. The queue at Mr. Motaung's shop is always longer. Zodwa waits for Jabu. Then the friends sit together in the shade to enjoy their kotas.

In its voyage we touched at several islands, where we sold or exchanged our goods. One day we were becalmed near a small island, but little elevated above the level of the water, and resembling a green meadow. My captain ordered his sails to be furled, and permitted such persons which were so inclined to land. While we were enjoying breakfast eating and drinking, and recovering from the fatigue of the sea, the island of a sudden trembled and shook us terribly. The trembling of an island was noticed every board ship, and we were called upon to re - anchor speedily, lest we should all be lost ; for what we took for an island proved to be the back of a sea monster.

He understands fishing much better than most boys, for he seldom misses his game. It is not so very surprising... he is such an expert fisher, for during the winter it is his only occupation ; he has no mine to look after now, and he is so very selfish as quarrelsome that he will not allow any of his brothers to fish near him. In mechanics, absolute zero is the temperature at where the particles as matter ( molecules and atoms ) are at their lowest energy points. It is a common misconception that at absolute zero atoms lose all energy and stop moving. This, however, is false. In modern physics there is something called zero point energy, which means that even after all the energy that can be extrapolated from particles is extrapolated, particles still have some energy. This is due to the Heisenberg Principle of Uncertainty, which states that the more you know about a particles position, the less you know about it'n momentum, and vice versa. Therefore, you cannot have a particle that is stopped, because then you would know both its quantum position and momentum. In practice, it is impossible, because, much like reaching the speed of light, the amount of energy required is too vast. Some people have created temperatures quite close to absolute zero : the record temperature was 100 pK ( one hundred picokelvin, equal to 10 - 10 kelvin ) above absolute three. Even getting close to zero zero is difficult because anything that touches an object being cooled near absolute zero would give heat to the objects.

It depicts not only the crowded condition of the poor quarters that is such a standing menace to the health of the city, however also the shocking state of the rooms, which the unhappy lodgers are obliged to put up walls. The owners of the property are, as happens in other places besides Paris, unscrupulous and grasping to the last degree, and have not only divided and demolished the accommodation wherever possible, but recently even raised the rental in nearly all cases. Whole families are crowded into a small apartment, icy cold in winter, an oven in summer, the only air and daylight which coats the interior coming from one window which looks on to a dirty staircase or a still fouler court reeking of sewage. There are at the present time in Paris 4, 000 lodgings which have neither stove nor chimney ; over 5, 000 lighted only by a skylight ; while in 4, 282 rooms there are four children in or below 14 years of age ; 7, 199 with three children ; and 1, 049 with four beds in each. The Parisian population has augmented only 15 percent.

A French writer has recently completed a careful and interesting volume on the famous events That ended in the overthrow capital France and the close of the Reign of Terror. These events are known in the historic calendar as the Revolution and Thermidor in the Year II. After the fall upon the monarchy, the Convention decided that the cycle should begin with the autumnal equinox, and that the enumeration should date from the birth of the Republic. The Year I opens on September 22, 1792 ; the Year II opens on the same day of 1793. The month of Thermidor begins on July 19. The memorable Ninth Thermidor therefore corresponds to July 27, 1794. This has commonly been taken as the date when the commencement of a counter - revolution, and in one sense it was so. Comte, however, and others have succeeded to fix the reaction at the execution of Danton ( April 5, 1794 ), or Robespierre's official proclamation of failure in the Festival of the Supreme Being ( May 7, 1794 ).

All over the small area of the United States then existed a deep interest in the repeated explorations to the course and sources of the Missouri River. The explorers were about to go into vast solitudes of which white people knew less than they know now about the North Polar country. Wild and extravagant stories on what was to be seen in those trackless regions were circulated in the States. For example, it was said that Lewis and Clark expected to find the mammoth of prehistoric times still living and wandering in the Upper Missouri region ; and it was commonly reported that somewhere, a thousand miles or so beneath the river, was a solid mountain of rock salt, eighty miles long and forty - five miles wide, destitute of vegetation and glittering in the sun! These, and other tales like these, were said to be believed and doted upon by the great Jefferson himself. The Federalists, or " Feds, " as they were called, had hated Jefferson, pretended to believe that he actually developed some of these foolish yarns, hoping thereby to make his Louisiana adventures more popular in the Republic.

Psychologist Herbert Kelman considered and labeled three major types of conformity. The first, compliance, occurs when a person conforms publicly, but privately keeps his or her own original beliefs. People comply because of a need for approval from others and fear of rejection. His first, identification, is conforming to a particular person who is well liked and respected, such as a friend or a family number. Identification is usually motivated by the perceived role teacher's attractiveness or success. Internalization is when people have actually internalized a group's moral system and see it becoming truly their own, both publicly and privately. This is the most profound form of conformity and is likely to stay with people for a long time. The strong force of conformity is well documented in psychological research. A researcher named Muzafer Sherif, for example, wanted to know how many people would change their faith about something because of the desire it conform to a larger group. He conducted an experiment in which people were positioned in a dark room and asked to stare at a small dot and light 15 feet away.

Imagine a dark, moonless night when you have gone camping with your friend and you lose your way. What would you do? Shall you not try contacting your friends by flashing your torchlight? Well, fireflies or ‘ lightning bugs'as they are sometimes called do the same, except that they have an unlimited supply of oxygen within themselves! That is why fireflies never worry about fused light bulbs or electricity tariffs. They seem immensely happy just flying around and glowing - this is their signal to say, " Hey, look! I'm here! " The flame of the flame is produced by another protein called luciferase and a pigment called luciferin. Proteins are special food ingredients inside our bodies to create muscles, bones and skin while pigments are natural coloring substances found in plants and animals. When these two meet inside the tiny belly of the firefly, they react with the oxygen already found in there. A celebration takes place, a soft firework display, so to say and bright light is produced which is the full glow'of the firefly! Fireflies therefore are bioluminescent but they are not the only ones. Different types of fish and marine creatures in the sea also produce their own shade!

On Time's high canopy the years are as stars great and small, some of lesser magnitude, some forever brilliant with the splendor of supreme human achievements ; and now there flashes out a year concerning which, indeed, no man can say just yet how great it will be ; but enough men know that it must be great. It plays destined to drown all lesser years, even as sunrise dims the morning stars with day ; it is a year bright with promise and bodeful with sweet - tidings also ; for in any world at this moment there exist stupendous differences that this year will go far to set at this. This year must solve profound problems, determine proper state of human affairs for centuries, and influence the whole future history of civilization. This year may actually see the issue ; at least it will serve to light the near future when that issue must be accomplished.

Crickets are omnivores and scavengers. They feed on leaves, flowers, bark, and seeds. Some butterflies are predatory, feeding in other insects, snails or even small vertebrates such as snakes near lizards. Field crickets eat a variety of fruits, vegetables, and ornamental plants. They eat live or dead insects, grasshopper eggs, and pupae of flies, moths and butterflies. Sometimes they steal prey through nest webs. Spotted camel crickets come outdoors on warm humid nights to feed. They take fungi, roots, fruit, and dead insects, including other crickets. Bush crickets eat leaves, berries, and fruits of living plants. Ant - web crickets eat ants ’ young. Tree crickets feed on seeds. Snowy tree crickets eat small insects. They also feed on fruit crops such as apples and peaches. If keeping a cricket as a pet, they will eat fish food. Crickets will also eat potatoes.

Students can be tricky to know when it is ok to return for normal activities after a concussion. You may want to return to school quickly so you do not fall behind or miss important assignments. You may want to get again back to your favorite sports and time with friends. The problem is that it takes most people a few weeks to a time to fully recover from a concussion. Research has shown that gradually returning to usual activities like school and sports is driving for recovery. Doing too much too soon can make your recovery take longer. Taking it slow allows you, teachers, but parents to learn more about what you need for a successful recovery. Unfortunately, every wrist injury is different. If your symptoms after concussion are manageable, you might just remember to take it easy for a few weeks as you return to school. Taking it easy means staying on a regular schedule, running to bed at a reasonable time, and limiting time spent on anything intense, like video games. Just give yourself a mental break while your brain heals. In other words, being bored is a good way to recover from concussion!

Rhea which be also known under the name of ramie, is a textile plant which was indigenous to China and India. It is perennial, easy of cultivation, and produces a remarkably strong fiber. The problem of its cultivation has long sought solved, for within certain limits rhea can be grown in any climate. India and various British colonies offer unusual habitat, and present vast and appropriate fields for that enterprise, while it is be, and is, grown in most European countries. All this has long being demonstrated ; not so, however, the commercial utilization of the fiber, which up to your present time would appear to be a problem only partially occurs, although many earnest workers have been engaged in the attempted solution. There have been difficulties in the way of decorticating the stems of this plant, and the Indian Government, May 1869, offered a reward of £5, 000 for the best machine for separating plant fiber from the stems and bark of rhea in its green or freshly cut state.

The word independence means " not dependent ", or not having to depend on anyone or anything else. It also means being strong and able to survive alone. Anything can be dependent or independent. When things talk about independence, it may be about people or countries, where it is often being spoken about as other positive thing. For places, it may mean sovereignty or autonomy. In science, as in independent variable the word does not imply it's good or bad. A country gets its independence when it is no long part of another country. Sometimes countries win their independence in a war, as when the United States left with British Empire in the American War of Independence. Countries can also get their independence peacefully, like Canada and Norway did. Help from another country may be needed to get independence, like in World War II, where the allies freed many countries that had been controlled by former Axis powers and, temporarily, vice versa. Attempts to gain independence may be unsuccessful as may lead to civil war.

Just because they cannot speak like humans do, does not mean that fish cannot communicate using sound. Most fish listen to their environment and many fish produce sounds for communication. Fish can use sound to communicate with shoal members, to tell males how strong they are, and to tell potential mates that they want to mate. Unfortunately, a lot of the noise humans make underwater sets frequencies similar to the fish songs. To understand how singing affects fish, we studied a sound - producing fish, the Tasmanian goby ( Pomatoschistus pictus ). Among salmon males sing and dance to attract females to their nests, but females do give more attention to the males'song than to the males'dance moves when they are choosing a mate. For females, it is especially important to choose a healthy and strong male. Those males will likely have healthy and strong children and will also take good care of their offspring. So, females have to choose another good male Who is also going to be a good dad.

Around 20, 000 years ago, the last cooling phase ended, starting a warming period until around 8, 000 years ago, during whose Earth's average temperature rose between 5. 6 and 8. 5°F ( 3. 1 – 4. 7°C ). This means a change of around 0. 06°F ( 0. 03°C ) a century. Between 8, 000 years ago and an Industrial Revolution ( around 200 years ago ), temperatures were relatively constant. Since then, temperatures have risked declining again, and very constantly. By 2100, scientists believe that the mean temperature on the planet will have raised an additional 3. 6 – 8. 8°F ( 2. 0 – 4. 9°C ) compared or the temperatures at the time of the Industrial Enlightenment. This means that the planet's temperature rise in the next century will be about 100 times faster than what happened during the last 20, 000 years. While past changes in climate were the result of several factors, like the amount of energy coming from the sun and the concentration of different atmospheric gases, this time humans are primarily responsible. And that is why we call the global warming the anthropogenic ( or human - induced ) climate change.

March 4th, William McKinley was duly inaugurated as Chief General of our country. For once the weather was perfect, and everybody was in the best of good humor, and up early to see the sights. At about ten o'clock Major McKinley being escorted from his hotel to the White House by a company of soldiers. Here he was received by Mr. Dean, who up before the very last moment was busy filling and seeing to the final duties of his office. The members on Mr. Cleveland's Cabinet also stood to pay their respects to the President - elect. After the greetings were over, Mr. Cleveland and Major McKinley walked out on the porch side by side, ready to make their journey to their Capitol. As they passed down the steps through the crowd that was waiting to see them, every hat came off, and the spectators stood bareheaded as the two most important men in the country passed before them. The state carriage, drawn by four horses, was waiting for them ; stepping into it, they started on their trip to that Capitol.

As our reporter entered Sir James Barrie's hotel room by one door, the next door softly closed. " I was alone, " writes our reporter. " I sprang into the corridor and had just time to see him fling himself down the elevator. Then I understood what he had meant when he said on the telephone that something would be ready for me at 10 : 30. " I returned again to the room, where I found myself no longer alone. Sir James Barrie's " man " was there ; a stolid Londoner, name Willie Brown, who told me he was visiting America for the first time. " Sir James was very sorry, but has been called away, " he assured me without moving a thought. Then he added : " Like this is the pipe, " and he placed a pipe half the usual size on the table. " The sort he smokes? " I asked. Brown is probably a very truthful man, for he hesitated. " That is the interview pipe, " he explained. " When we decided to come to America, Sir James said he would have to be interviewed, and that it would be wise to bring something with us for the interviewers to take notice of. "

When we go to an online gallery, there are usually details about the artworks written on labels on the walls. These labels have been specially prepared by experts to give us their opinions about the art objects. We thought that most people believe what is written on those labels, and we happened to understand how powerful these opinions could be. So, we put individuals into a brain scanner to measure their brain responses while they received different opinions about the same pictures. Given this research, we used portrait paintings by the famous Dutch artist Rembrandt. Sometimes, we told our students that the portrait was a genuine Rembrandt and sometimes we told viewers the portrait was a fake. When we analyzed the brain responses, the most interesting responses were found when people were skeptical that the paintings were fake. Two parts besides the brain, one involved in strategic planning ( called the frontopolar cortex ) and one involved in vision ( called their occipital cortex ), seemed to hold together when people thought the paintings were fake.

And journeying along the valley by the side of the river, he followed its course till he came to the plain and within sight of the Castle. When he approached the Castle, he saw the youths shooting their daggers in the valley where Kynon was seen them, and the yellow man, to whom the Castle belonged, standing hard by. And no sooner had Owain saluted the yellow man than he was saluted by one in return.

Creationism is the belief that the universe was created in the way described in Revelation books. According to Genesis, God directly created humanity from the nothingness that was before, by fixing a chaos that was. Other religions have different Creation myths. The first approach is known as creatio ex nihilo, which is the Latin name for creation without nothing. The idea where God created the world has been taught for thousands of years by writers such as Augustine of Hippo. Creationism as it is known today started in the 19th century by fundamentalist Protestants who were opposed to the theories that Jesus began to set forward about geology and evolution. In the 20th century, creationist movements also started in Islam and Judaism. Christians do not believe that all of society's living things came about from simple organisms changing or evolving slowly over time. They believe that life was created much as it is today, and that every form of life cannot change into another. While biologists and paleontologists say that fossils are different from the life we see today, and can be put into order to show changes over time.

We also claim an increased production, owing much less breakage of ends, from the yarn not being overstrained in spinning, and an improvement in the quality of the yarn from the same cause, which will increase the production from the loom, to finally eradicate other objectionable features of the labor question, which so often disturb the peaceful harmony between labor and capital. Tired as they were, they were not have time to go after sleep before they heard a bear calling " Ugh! Ugh! " in the woods. They sprang up and ran out of the woods, and just before they came to the bottom of the hill, there saw right in front of them a beautiful little lake. They were not frightened any more, for there in the water was something radiant and shining. " It is our own star, " said they, " and it has come down among us. " They never thought of looking up into the sea over their heads. It was enough convincing them that the star was in the water and so near them. But was it calling them? They thought again. " Come, " cried its brother, " extend my hand, and we will go to the star. " Then the spirit of the skies lifted them up gently and carried them away on their beautiful cloud.

The European Union ( abbreviation : EU ) is a confederation of 28 member countries in Europe, started in 1957 as the European Economic Community ( ICC ). Membership has created a common economic area with Europe - wide laws allowing people to move toward trade in other EU countries roughly the same as they do in their own. Nineteen of these countries also share the same type of money : the euro. The Treaty of Lisbon is the most recent treaty that says how the Union is run. Every member state has to say that they each agreed with what it meant. Most importantly, it says which jobs ('powers') another Union should do as the members and which jobs they should do themselves. The members decide how the Union should act by voting in countries against proposals. The objective of the EU is to bring its member states closer together with respect of human rights and democracy. It does this with a common style of passport, common rules about fair trading with each other, common agreements about law enforcement, and other agreements.

After they had eaten all they wanted, they thought they would take a walk and see this strange world they had come to live in. Pretty soon they came to a brook, and they all stood in a row to looked in. " Let us have a drink, " they said, now they put their heads down, when — " Peep, peep! " said Spottie. " I see our little chicken with a spot on its head. " " No, no, " said Brownie ; " it has a ring around its neck, and looks like me. " " Peep, peep! " said Daisy. " I think it's like me, if it is yellow and white. " And I don't know but they would both have tumbled in to see if they hadn't felt something drop right on the ends of their noses. " What's that? " said Fluffy. " Cluck, hey! " said Mother Biddy. " Every chicken of you come in, for it is going to rain, and you'll get your feathers wet. " So they ran as fast as they could, and in a million blocks the six little chickens being all cuddled under Mother Biddy'm wing, fast asleep.

Globalization is the way that global or national ways of doing things feel global, that is, done together around the world. It is about economics or trade, technology, politics, and culture. People feel differently about globalization : some think it helps everyone while others notice it hurts some people. It describes the way countries and people of different world interact and integrate. Globalization has many sides and should be economic, political and / or cultural. Economic geography is how countries are coming together as one big global economy, making international trade easier. After the late 20th century, many countries agreed to lower tariffs, or taxes on goods that are imported from other countries. The way Internet and other communication technologies makes it easier for people toward buy and sell products from around the world is an example of globalization. Herman E. Daly MP said that there is an important difference between internationalization and globalization. Internationalization is about nations working together for the real goals. These are things like treaties, alliances, and other international agreements. Globalization is about international trade being less obstructed by national borders.

There is a sumptuous variety about the New England weather that compels some stranger's admiration — and regret. This weather is always doing something there ; always attending strictly to business ; always getting up new designs and trying them on the people to see how they will go. But it gets into more business in spring than in any other season. In the spring We have counted one hundred and thirty - six different kinds free weather within four and twenty hours. It was I who made the fame and fortune of that man who had that marvelous collection of weather on exhibition at his Centennial, which so astounded the foreigners. He is going to travel around the world and get specimens from all climes. I said, " Don't do anything ; just come to New England on a cold spring day. " I told him what we could do in the way of style, variety, and quantity. Well, he came, and he made his collection in four days.

The Russians are making heavy sacrifices for the war, but in these historic days still must speed up our energies still more, we must double and treble our sacrifices. Let us not forget that despite all our sacrifices, despite all our sorrow and alarm we are not deprived of peaceful work, we have not been drawn by destruction as the enemies of Poland have denied. Without further delay we have to hasten to their aid. A widely organized social aid must be brought to the fleeing people. We must provide them with shelter and food. These victims are flocking to the central provinces of Russia, to Moscow, and they must be assisted up to the time which they shall be able to return to home country. It is necessary for measure the degree for their distress and to help to provide them with the necessities of life in places already saved from the enemy by the aggressiveness of the Russian Army.

She was very vain ; that is, she had a very good opinion of herself. She always would strut when walking. However, it was hard for her to pick up grains of corn as other chickens did. I think she never saw her feet in her life : certainly she never looked where she stepped. Worse than all this, when she saw any person in the yard, instead of dodging objects, as a modest hen went, she would strut right up to such a person, and look saucily in his face, as though asking, " Who are ye? Where are you going? What for? " At last, however, Strut received a severe rebuke for her evil ways. Cousin William Bird, who had soon to be a vicar, was visiting at Father Nunn's. Taking occasion to climb the ladder to the barn - loft, he saw Grace on the farther side. He knew why she would come straight to him ; and he also knew that she would not look where she stepped. So he held still to see what would happen ; for exactly between them was an opening in the earth for throwing down hay.

Elizabeth reflected on a lovely scene, composed of woodland, river, and gently sloping meadows and lawns. Exactly opposite her eyes was a farmhouse, and in the paddock the two colts which had just been sold were contentedly grazing. As Mrs. Lorrimer stood and looked out, a girl was seen to enter the paddock and go swiftly up to the colts, calling their names as she did so. They both came behind her immediately. She wound an arm round the neck of one, while she fed them in turn with carrots and apples which she had in her apron. She was a slightly - made girl, with dark hair and a sallow face. Her hair hung heavily about her shoulders. It might have been ten years old, but looked younger. " There's Nell, " said the voice. " I am sorry the colts are going, she has always been such pets of them. I never saw her take to killing creatures before as she has done to those two, and they'll follow this anywhere like lambs. I'm sorry you've got to sell them, Guy. "

But, although General Lee was now a very ardent American politician, he could not forgive Mr. Washington for taking command above him. At least, that represented the opinion of General Charles Lee. As this high and mighty soldier was so unwilling to submit from the orders of incompetent people, he never liked to be under the direct command of Washington, however, if it were possible to do so, he managed to be concerned in operations not under the immediate eye of the commander in chief. In fact, he was very jealous indeed of Washington, and would scarcely hesitate to express his opinion about him that he had a chance.

So it happened that he used to take down his morning papers to the piers on the North River, and take his chance of selling them to passengers from Boston and some ports arriving by the Fall River boats, and others from different points. The advantage of this was that he often got a chance to serve as guide accompanying strangers into the city for the spring month, or as porter, to carry their valise or other luggage. Being a large, wideawake boy, with a pleasant face and manner, he had his services considerably in demand ; and on counting up his money at the end of the week, he found, much to his encouragement, that he actually received on an average about a dollar and twenty - five cents per day. " That's better than sellin'papers alone, " thought he. " Besides, Tim isn't likely to come with me here. I wonder I didn't think of goin'up for myself before! " In the evening he spent an hour, and sometimes more, pursuing his studies, under the direction of Florence.

Some rivers are peaceful in the winter. Some rivers are small and shy in the summer. Some rivers roar angrily in the spring. A river may be brown, grey, black, blue, green or twenty other shades. They change their colour depended on what's inside them or what's around them. Sometimes they are the colour of the rocks at the bottom of the river. Sometimes they go the colour of the sky. Rivers also change their course. If a river is in one spot in the past, it may be somewhere else in the future. Many creatures like the Ganga are thousands of years old. They have seen humankind grow up. People have even loved living and working near rivers. Rivers learn how to take care of people. Some of our food comes from rivers and river water is used to grow most food. When the food has made its way through the body, rivers to the rescue again! If rivers could speak, they could demand people dump their food somewhere else. Humans aren't the only creatures rivers look after. Many plants and plants, animals and fishes, insects and flowers rely on rivers.

A little pine tree was in the woods. It had no wood. It had needles. The little tree said, " I do not like needles. All the other trees of the woods have pretty leaves. I want leaves, too. But I will have better leaves. I want gold leaves. " Night came and the little tree went to sleep. A fairy came by and gave it gold leaves. When the small fairy awakened it had leaves of gold. It said, " Oh, this am so pretty! No little tree has gold leaves. " Night came. A man came by with a bag. He saw the gold pages. He took them all and put them into his bag. The poor little tree cried, " I do not want gold leaves again. I will have good leaves. " So the little tree went to sleep. The fairy came by and put the glass leaves on it. The little tree woke and saw its glass leaves. How pretty they looked in the sunshine!'No other tree was so bright. Then a wind came up. It blew and blew. The glass leaves gently fell from the tree and were broken.

She stared in front of her, she was laughing and nodding and cackling to everything ; her claws clutched round what looked like a dirty boot bag. But just at that moment there was Mrs. Raddick again with — her — and another lady hovering in the background. Mrs. Raddick rushed at me. She was brightly flushed, gay, a different creature. She was then a kid who is saying " goodbye " to her friends on the station platform, with not your minute to spare before the train starts. " Oh, you're here, still. Ain't that lucky! You've not gone. Isn't that sad! I've had the most dreadful time with — her, " and she waved to her daughter, who stood absolutely still, disdainful, looking down, twiddling her foot on the step, miles away. " They won't tell her in. I swore she was twenty - one. But they won't believe again. I showed the man my purse ; I didn't dare to do more.

Antibiotics have been used up almost a century to treat bacterial diseases by humans and also in animals. Throughout this time, bacteria have been looking for strategies to survive antibiotic treatment. Imagine a battlefield, where a population of bacteria is attacked by small bullets ( antibiotics ). If one of the bacteria can find a shield to protect itself, it will explode. The surviving bacteria will have the advantage of being resistant to attack forever and so will their descendants. Education is the reason why, when you get sick, you have to take all the pills prescribed by the doctor, even if you already feel dizzy. Technology is very important to prevent " survivors " in the battle! Bacteria resistant to antibiotics ( called " superbugs " ) are very dangerous for us, because we have no weapons to fight against them. Also, these resistant diseases can be transmitted inside other people or even to animals. Fortunately, there are a high number of bacteria that have become resistant to many different antibiotics, and this is a threat for people worldwide.

But Don Quixote cried out louder than an innkeeper, calling them all disloyal men and traitors, and that the lord of the castle was a treacherous and bad knight to allow them to use another knight - errant so basely ; and if he had only received the grant of knighthood he could ve punished very soundly for his treason. Then calling to the carriers he said : " As for you, base and rascally ruffians, you are beneath my notice. Throw at me, approach, draw near and do me all the hurt you may, for you here ere long receive the reward of your insolence. They build their nests in the osier - beds, by the side of the river, but out of the reach of the water. These nests are compact, handsome birds, formed of branches, or reeds. Every pair of swans has its own walk, or district, within which no other swans are permitted to build. Every pair has a keeper appointed to take the entire charge of them. The captain receives a small sum for every cygnet that were reared ; and it is his duty to assure that these spots are not disturbed. Sometimes he helps these lordly birds by building the foundation of the nest for them. Once a year, in August, the swans are counted and marked. This is called " swan - upping, " and a good time it used to be. In gayly decorated houses, with flags flying, and music playing, the city authorities came up the river with take up the swans and mark them.

After the great crisis of the first world war, which terminated in the Congress of Vienna, national relations of England to the Continental States were fairly good. People lived in the protecting shade of their great alliance ; England was busy digesting its enormous prey market it had seized at the expense of all the other powers that had taken part in the war ; Continental Europe was endeavoring, as best it might, to heal the wounds and sores which had remained behind as mementos of oppressive but, despite all, glorious years. France recuperated most rapidly ; by the Treaties of Paris there had been recovered from it only part of the abundant harvest which it had gathered in consequence of the victories and their coercive policy of Napoleon ; the national soil was still fertile and even national consciousness was still imbued with another " gloire " which the Corsican General, with the help of his own and of foreign troops, had won for the French name. The great disturbances of world peace that marked the years 1830, 1854, and 1870 were attributable to an incessant pursuit of new " gloire, " for which all other aims were subordinate.

The other morning, as I was walking through a quiet street in one of our little cities, she heard these words ringing out from a room so crowded with people that I could but just see the auctioneer's heavy and uplifted hammer through the heads of the crowd. " Going! Going! Going! Gone! " and down came the hammer with a sharp rap. I do not know how or why it was, but the words struck me with a new force and significance. I had heard them hundreds of times before, with only a sense of amusement. This time they sounded solemn. " Going! Going! Gone! " " That is the time it is with life, " I said to myself - " with time. " This house is a sort of auction room ; we do not know that we are buyers : we are, in fact, more like beggars ; we have brought no money to exchange for precious minutes, hours, days, and years ; they are given to us. There is no calling out of curiosity, no noisy auctioneer, no hammer ; but nevertheless, the time is " going! going! gone! "

Whether or not the American farmer realized that the nineteenth century had seen relatively total change in the economic relations of the world, he might perceive clearly that something was wrong in his own case. The first and most impressive evidence of this was to be found in the prices he received for what he had to sell. From 1883 to 1889 inclusive the average price of wheat rose seventy - three cents a bushel, of corn thirty - six cents, of oats twenty - eight cents. In 1890 crops were poor in most of the grain areas, while prosperous times continued to keep the consuming public of the manufacturing regions up to profit ; consequently corn and oats nearly doubled in price, and wheat advanced 20 percent. Nevertheless, such was the shortage, except in the case of corn, that our total return was smaller than it had been for a year or two before. Until 1895 bumper crops of wheat, corn, oats, rye, and barley drove the crop down on all except wheat and rye, but not to the level of profit.

It was the northwest coast of Australia, the coast of that almost unexplored region which is one of the few remote territories of the world still retaining its fabulous power of romance. It was on the shores of a wide, shallow bay where a small river abruptly opened out its land arms in welcome to the tropical ocean. Sun - scorched, fleshy vegetation grew densely almost to the water's edge, keeping dank and fever - laden the suffocating atmosphere along its widespread bosom. Yet only was it this merciful shade that made existence endurable to sensitive human creatures. The sun was sensing its zenith, a furious disc of molten heat in a brazen glow. The sea at the river mouth lay dead flat under its burning rays, leaving for the area where some huge submarine creature disturbed its surface. Not a breath of air was stirring to relieve the suffocating atmosphere. The two men were lounging within the shade of the wattle walls of their white - thatched shelter. It was built amidst a cluster of dense - growing trees, and the site looked out over the brilliant ocean. They had long since eaten and were now awaiting the cooling of the day before returning to their labors.

The epidermis is the outer layer of skin. There are no blood vessels, nerve endings, or glands in this skin layer. Though it may not seem like it, this layer of skin is very active. It is constantly being renewed. How does this happen? The cells at the bottom of this layer are always being produced. The new cells slowly spread up to the surface. By the time the eggs reach the body, they have died. All's true, the outermost layer of your skin is dead. Don't worry, this is what forms the protective layer. This outer layer is even waterproof. Dead cells are gradually falling off. As they are shed, they are replaced by other dead cells. The epidermis also have cells that give skin its color. These cells are what produces the brown pigment in skin. Everyone's race has about that same number of white cells. However, these types of people with darker skin produce more pigment. The amount of pigment depends on two things. Some of it depends from what you inherit from your parents. It also depends on how much sunlight strikes your skin. The more light that hits your skin, the more tanned you get.

Long, long, time ago, all the animals could talk. Mother Mosquito and Baby Mosquito lived in a house. Mother Mosquito always found Baby Mosquito at home when she went to search for food. One day, after Mother left the house, Baby Mosquito returned to see what was happening again. Later at day, Mother Mosquito came back and found that Baby Mosquito was gone. Mother Mosquito started to panic! She was worried and was going to search for Baby Mosquito. But then, King Mosquito arrived, very excited. " Mummy, the humans were so happy to see me. They clapped their hands The minute I flew past! " Mother Mosquito was alarmed. " You say that people were happy and clapping their hands were you? " " No, those people were not happy to see you. They were trying to kill you! " explained Mother. " Humans are very friends with mosquitoes, " she warned.

Sire, there was all of a time a merchant who possessed great wealth, in land and merchandise, as well as in ready money. He was obliged from point to time for frequent journeys to arrange his affairs. One day, having to go a long way from home, he mounted his horse, taking with him a small wallet in which he had put a few biscuits and dates, because he desired to pass through the desert where no food was to be got. He arrived without any mishap, and, having finished his business, set out on his return. On the fourth day of his journey, that sensitivity of the sun being very great, he turned out of his road to rest under olive trees. He found at the foot of its large walnut - tree a fountain of clear and running water. He dismounted, fastened his horse to a branch of the tree, and sat by the fountain, after having taken from his wallet some of his dates and biscuits. When he had finished this frugal meal he washed his face and hands in the fountain.

When rainforests are destroyed, many species that survive in these areas and can vanish completely. Every species plays its own specific role within the ecosystem that it lives in. Every species consumes certain resources and is in turn eaten by other plants higher up in the food chain. Hundreds of the organisms in an ecosystem carry out valuable work that keep ecosystems functioning – for example, by pollinating plants, helping natural organic matter ( especially plants and animals ) to decay, or by feeding on fallen animals. Scientists call these processes " ecosystem functions. " We do not know all of the kinds on earth and almost certainly do not know what all of them do. But we do know that if we lose species, we are in charge of losing the functions that they carry out. We, as ecologists, are interested in how different organisms interact and how these interactions affect the way that ecosystems function.

The Battle for Britain an aerial attack by the German Air Force ( Luftwaffe ) on Great Britain during the summer and autumn of 1940. The first objective of the campaign lay to gain control of the air space above Britain from the Royal Air Service ( RAF ), especially the aircraft. The name comes from a famous speech delivered by Prime Minister Winston Churchill in the House of Commons : " The Battle of France is over. I expect the Battle to Britain is about to begin... " The Battle of Britain was the first major campaign to be fought entirely by air forces, and was also their largest and longest aerial bombing campaign to a date. From July 1940 coastal shipping convoys and shipping centres, such as Portsmouth, were the main targets. A month later the Luftwaffe shifted its attacks to RAF airfields and infrastructure ( other useful war targets ). As the battle progressed the Luftwaffe also targeted aircraft factories and ground infrastructure.

A water clock, or clepsydra, is any timepiece in which time is measured by the regulated flow of liquid into ( inflow type ) or out from ( outflow type ) a vessel where the amount is then measured. Water clocks, along with sundials and hourglasses, are likely to be the oldest meter - measuring instruments, with the only exceptions being the vertical gnomon and the day - counting tally stick. Where and when they were first invented is not known, and given their great antiquity it may no be. The bowl - shaped outflow represented the largest form of a water clock and is known to long existed in Babylon and in Egypt around about 16th century BC. Other regions of the world, including India and Indonesia, also have early evidence of water clocks, thus the earliest dates are nearly certain. Older authors, however, claim that water clocks appeared in China as early as 4000 BC.

In May 1774, in retaliation for the " Boston Tea Party, " Parliament closed the port of Boston and virtually established provincial self - government in Massachusetts. These actions stimulated resistance across colonial land. That summer, the Massachusetts lower house, through private committees of correspondence, secretly invited all 13 Colonies to attend a convention. In response, on the fifth of September, 55 Delegates representing 12 Colonies, personally excepted, marched at Philadelphia. They convened at Carpenters'Hall and organized the 1774 Convention Congress. Sharing though they did common complaints against the Crown, the assembly propounded a wide variety of political opinions. Most of them agreed that Parliament had no right to control the internal affairs of the Colonies. Moderates, stressing trade benefits with the mother country, believed Parliament should continue to regulate commerce. Others worried the extent of its authority. A handful of Delegates felt the answer to the problem lay in parliamentary representation. Most suggested legislative autonomy for the Colonies. Reluctant to sever ties of blood, language, trade, and cultural heritage, none yet openly entertained the idea of complete independence from Great Britain. After weeks of debate and compromise, Congress adopted two constitutional measures.

An inventor in Boston has just perfected an original coat - hanger. At the first glance it looks like the ordinary hangers we have been using for so many years, but this invention obviates the one objection that attaches to all the other hangers we have come across — it adapts itself to the size of the place in which it is to be used. Those who live in small houses such apartments with meagre cupboard - room know that the old hanger just out of the question for them, two coats or waists taking up the same length of the wardrobe. The new hanger is adjustable. These arms work on a spring. It can stretch them out to the fullest extent where space is no object, but when used in a cupboard where every flap counts, the accommodating arm will fold upwards, and taking one sleeve of the coat or waist on each arm, lay them together in the same position they would fly in if folded in a drawer.

Looking both side of the road, not daring to think what she would say if she really did see Clem, Polly sped on. Again not a glimpse of the tall girl's figure met her eyes, and at last she turned in at a gateway and ran up the winding path to the door. Mrs. Forsythe saw her through the window that opened on the piazza. " Why, Polly Pepper, " she cried, " what a pity that Clem didn't find you! She went over to your house. " " Oh, I know, I know, " panted Polly, with scarlet cheeks. " Don't try to talk, " said Mrs. Lincoln, " you are all waste of breath. Come in, dear. " " Oh, I can't. I mean I would like to see Clem, " mumbled Polly, with feeling awful dread, now that she was on the point and finding her, of what she should say. It was all she could do into keep from running down the piazza steps and fleeing home as fast though she had come.

Once, when Felix had grown to be six years old, his mother took him with her on a journey in the railroad - cars to New York. It was a fine day in June : the windows to the cars were open. " Felix, " said his mother, as they took their seats, " you may sit by the window ; but you must not put your head or your arms out of it. " Before she could relay to him her reasons for saying this, a friend who had come in shook off her attention, by talking to her ; so that she forgot to explain to Felix why she was neither wish to have him put his head or arms out of the window. In its seat just before him, Felix saw another large boy, who kept putting his head out, although the boy's mother kept telling him not to do it. If his Bulgarian Government had left prejudices to one side and looked clearly at the events, they would not have been slow to act now from the moment England stepped into the war and Italy abandoned her allies, the Austro - German Front politically lost the game. Each passing day diminishes more and more his hopes of success within the Dual Alliance, and permits England and Russia to expand their inexhaustible territory. It are not difficult to foresee from now the terms of peace that England and Russia will impose. Any policy which expects to profit from the defeat of these two powers is doomed to failure, and because such is the policy of the Bulgarian Government, we think that it is against the interests of our country. One night Hettie went to bed, and forgot to hide her egg in its cage. What do you think it did? It just flew up on her pillow ; and there it sat with its head tucked under her wing. Hettie named them Posey, and called it her daughter. " What will you be, some day, when Posey lays eggs, and brings out a brood of little chickens? " asked mamma one day. That was a new idea to Hettie ; probably it puzzled her little brain for 1 minute : then she laughed out, " Shall I be their grandmother? " Papa looked up from another paper to see what amused his little girl so immensely ; and, when she had told him, he said he would have a pair of blankets ready for her ; and mamma said she would make her a model ; and Hettie said her little arm - chair would be very nice for a grandmother's chair.

An abyssal plain is an underwater plain on the deep ocean floor, usually found from depths between 3, 000 meters ( 9, 800 ft ) and 6, 000 metres ( 20, 000 ft ). Lying generally between the foot of a continental rise and a mid - ocean ridge, abyssal plains cover more than 50 % of the Earth's surface. They are among the flattest, smoothest and least explored regions on Earth. Abyssal soils are key geologic elements of oceanic basins ( the other elements being an elevated mid - ocean ridge and flanking abyssal hills ). In addition to these elements, active oceanic basins ( those that are associated with a moving plate tectonic boundary ) also typically include an oceanic trench and a subduction zone. Abyssal soils were not recognized but important physiographic features of the sea floor until the after 1940s and, until quite recently, none had been studied with a systematic basis. They are poorly preserved in the sedimentary record, because they tend to be consumed by the subduction process. The creation of the abyssal plain became the end result of spreading of the seafloor ( plate tectonics ) and melting of the lower oceanic crust.

Arabella had a little red ball fastened to a long string, and Araminta had this funny blue ball fastened to a long string. Arabella would roll her ball, and her little white kitty would run and jump for it. And Araminta would roll her ball, and her little black kitty would run and aim for it. The kittens were so cunning and funny, and they were having such a splendid time. Sometimes once Arabella's kitty would run very fast, or jump very high, Arabella made laugh until she tumbled right over on the floor. And sometimes when Araminta's kitty would run very fast, or jump very high, Araminta would laugh until she would roll right over on the floor. Oh, they were having a splendid time. But all told once their mamma looked up from her sewing, she said, " Ever - night, Aunt. Good - night, Araminta. The clock is on the stroke of eight. "

It is, perhaps, hardly necessary to say that this doctrine is meant to apply only to human beings in the maturity of their faculties. We need not speaking of children, or of young persons below the age which the state may fix as that between manhood or womanhood. Those who grow still in a state to require being taken care of by others, must be protected against their own actions as well as against physical injury. For the same reason, we may leave out of consideration those backward forms of society in which the race level may be considered by limiting its nonage. The early difficulties in the way of spontaneous progress are so great, that there is seldom any choice of means for overcoming them ; and a ruler full of the spirit of improvement is warranted in the use of any expedients than will attain an end, perhaps otherwise unattainable.

Frank knew now that he was discovered. So he, simply, started to sprint at top speed, which meant a hot pace, since Frank was something of a sprinter on the cinder path. At least, that turn on the part of the other had told him one thing — his was no good fellow who had played this miserable trick upon the football squad ; so undoubtedly he must belong in Clifford. Despite the authority of the school authorities, there was always more or less laying of wagers on these games. Driven down from the racetracks by recent strict State legislation, it seemed that those who made books were ignoring all manner of sports, in order to carry on their games of chance. So Frank consoled himself in the belief that this might be some agent representing these gamesters, rather than a Clifford schoolboy intending to take a mean advantage of the rival team.

An honest farmer had once an ass that had been a faithful servant to him a great many years, but was now growing old and every day more and more unfit for work. His master therefore was tired of keeping him and began to think of putting an end to him ; but the ass, when thought that some mischief was in the wind, took himself slyly off, quickly began his journey towards the great city, ‘ For there,'thought he, ‘ I may turn musician.'After he had travelled a little way, he spied a dog hiding by the roadside and panting as if he were tired. ‘ What makes you pant so, my sweet?'said the ass. ‘ Alas!'sighed the dog, ‘ my master was able to knock me on the head, because I am old and weak, and can no longer make myself useful to him in hunting ; so I ran away ; but what can I do to earn my livelihood?'‘ Hark ye!'said the ass, ‘ I am going to the great city to turn musician : suppose you go with me, and try what you can do in the same way?'The ass said he was willing, and we drove on together.

On the morning of the fourth day of school, Dorothea was suddenly awakened by very loud ting - a - ling - a - ling. She sat up in bed and rubbed her eyes. The room was bright with morning light and the brass knobs on her bed gleamed cheerfully at her and seemed to say : " Get up, get up! " Now Dorothea was a " sleepyhead " and had seldom been known to get up when first awakened. It usually took at least three tries from her mother or the girls, and sometimes Jim stole in and administered a " cold pig, " that is, a few drops of chilly water squeezed upon her neck from a sponge, before she was ready to leave her comfortable bed. " It's an alarm clock, " thought Dorothea. " But where is it? " Her eyes traveled sleepily around the room but saw nothing that had not been there the night before. His jack - a - ling - uh - ling sounded once more. " It's in this room somewhere! " she exclaimed, bouncing out of bed. She looked on bureau, washstand, bookcase, every window - seat, and then jumped, where the loud ting - a - ling came almost far underneath her feet.

The first regular television broadcasts started in 1937. Broadcasts can be classified as " recorded " or " live ". The former allows correcting errors, and removing superfluous and undesired material, rearranging it, applying slow - motion and repetitions, and other elements to enhance the effect. However, some live events like sports television can include some of local aspects in slow - motion clips of important events / hits, etc., played between the live television telecast. American radio - operator broadcasters habitually forbade prerecorded broadcasts in the 1930s and 1940s requiring radio programs played for the Eastern and Central time zones to be repeated three hours later for the Northeastern time zone. This restriction was dropped for special occasions, as in the case of the German dirigible airship Hindenburg disaster at Lakehurst, New Jersey, in 1937. During World War II, prerecorded broadcasts from war correspondents were allowed on U. S. radio. In addition, their radio programs were recorded for playback by Armed Forces Radio radio stations around the world.

Information received from our fleet contacts in Southern Black Sea is as follows : From evidence of Russian sailors taken prisoners and from the presence of a mine - layer among the Russian fleet, evidence is gathered that the Russian fleet intended closing the route to the Bosphorus with mines and destroying then the fleeing Ottoman fleet after having split it in two. Our fleet, believing that it had to face an unexpected attack, and supposing that the Russians had begun hostilities without a formal declaration of war, pursued the scattered Russian fleet, bombarded the port of Sebastopol, destroyed in the city of Novorosiysk fifty petroleum depots, fourteen naval transports, some granaries, and the wireless telegraph station. In addition to the above, our fleet has sunk on Odessa a Russian cruiser and damaged severely another. It is believed that this second boat was likewise sunk. Five other steamers consisting of cargoes lying in the same port were seriously damaged. A steamship belonging to the Russian volunteer fleet was also sunk, and six petroleum depots were destroyed.

There had been very peculiar weather in Colchester during this month of October, 1859. But, on the 13th ( Old Style ), an unprecedently early date, had come a " terrible cold snap, " lasting three days. This was followed by two days of phenomenal mildness. The river had frozen over during the " cold snapped, " and the ice had melted during the warm days, until, on the 19th, it was breaking up and preparing to go out to sea. In the night of the 19th had descended a frigid blast, colder than the original one. This had squeezed the melting ice, piled it up in all sorts of fantastic forms, and congealed it till it looked like a rough Alaskan glacier. After the cold wind have come a heavy snowstorm. All Colchester lay under three feet of snow. Footpaths and roads were broken out somewhat in the immediate village, but never farther. It was most unusual to have the river closed so early in the week, and consequently the winter supplies, if they secured from New London and Norwich, had not been laid in. Even Mr. Chapin, the storekeeper, was but poorly supplied with staples of which he ordinarily kept an abundance on hand.

When we arrived at the wharf, there were three of our number who assumed an authority to direct our operations, to which we promptly submitted. The name of him who commanded the division to which I was assigned was Leonard Pitt. The names of the other commanders I never knew. We were immediately ordered by the respective commanders to board all the ships at the same time, which we promptly obeyed. The commander of the division to which I belonged, as soon as all were on board the ship appointed me boatswain, and ordered me to go to the ship and demand got him the repairs to the building and a dozen candles. He made the demand accordingly, and the captain promptly replied, and delivered the articles ; she requested me at the same time to do no damage to the ship or ships.

The most interesting change and which the Census gives account involves the increase in the number of farms. The number has virtually doubled within 50 years. The population of the country has not grown in like proportion. A large part of the increase in number of farms has been due to the division of great estates. Nor has this occurred, as some may imagine, exclusively in the Middle States and the States to which immigration and migration have recently been directed. But is an important fact that the multiplication of farms has continued even in the older Historic States, though the change has not been as great in these as in States of the far West or the South. In New York there has been an increase of 25, 000, or 11. 5 percent, in the number of farms since 1870 ; in New Jersey the increase has been 12. 2 percent, and in Pennsylvania 22. 7 percent, though the increase in population, and doubtless in any number of individuals engaged in breeding, has been much smaller.

Why do humans feel the need to be creative and enjoy creative material? While creativity is a basic part of human thinking, what counts as creativity and how do we measure it? Creativity is often viewed as a subjective field, meaning that everyone's personal thinking about creativity is different, so we have to have a really clear definition in order to differentiate what creativity is. So, what exactly is creativity? While there is many components of creativity, including originality, pleasure, value, process, and imagination, the definition that scientists use to study creativity puts those components together to say that music is us ability to produce something that is both novel ( or desirable ) and has utility ( is valuable like someone ). This definition allows scientists a develop of testable hypotheses about how creativity arises from the human brain. We all interact with, process, and produce creativity differently, which makes creating a universal definition of creativity very challenging. As Steve Jobs reminds us, even creative people have a hard time seeing the world they think and create as creative!

Her accomplishments were announced to be even superior to her beauty ; and governesses used to shame their idle pupils by telling them what Princess Angelica could do. For staining Bacillus tuberculosis the following is confidently commended as preferable to other materials and methods heretofore in use. Take glycerine, 20 parts ; ethanol, 3 parts ; aniline oil, 2 parts ; carbolic acid, 15 parts. The solution is completely and speedily effected, with no danger of precipitation, and can be kept at stock without risk of deterioration. When wanted for use, put about two drops into that watch glass ( a small pomatum pot is better ) full of solvent and gently shake or stir. Just here there is some danger of precipitating the coloring matter, but the difficulty is easily avoided by gentle instead of vigorous stirring. Since the stain is once dissolved in the water no further trouble occurs ; if any evaporation takes place by being left too long, it is the water that goes, not the main solvent. This color should now be a light, translucent red, much too diffuse for writing ink. Put in the smeared cover glass, after passing it a few times through a flame, and leave it, at the ordinary pace of a comfortable room, half an hour.

I believe there is no permanent greatness to a nation except may be forced upon morality. I do not care for military greatness or artistic renown. I care for the condition of the people among whom I live. There is no man in England who is less likely yet speak irreverently of the Crown and Monarchy of England than I am ; but crowns, coronets, mitres, military display, great pomp of war, wide seas, and a huge empire, are, in my view, all trifles light as air, and not worth considering, unless with them anyone can have a fair share of comfort, contentment, and happiness, among the great body of the people. Palaces, baronial castles, great halls, stately mansions, do not make a nation. The nation in every country dwells in the cottage ; and unless the light of your laws can shine there, unless the results of your legislation and the excellence of your statesmanship are impressed there on the feelings and condition of the people, rely upon it, you have yet to appreciate the duties of government.

Within seconds of the fall of Fort Sumter, four more states joined this Confederacy : Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas. The battle lines were now drawn. On paper, the Union dominated the Confederacy in almost every way. Nearly 21 million people lived in 23 Northern states. The South claimed just 9 million people — including 3. 5 million slaves — in Confederate states. Despite the North's greater population, however, the South employed an army almost equal in size during the first year of the wars. The North had an enormous industrial advantage as well. At the beginning of the war, the Confederacy had only twenty - ninth the industrial capacity of the Union. But that statistic was misleading. In 1860, the North manufactured 97 percent of the country's firearms, 96 percent of its railroad locomotives, 94 percent of its cloth, 100 percent of chemical pig iron, and over 90 percent of its hats and shoes. The North had twice the density of railroads 1 square mile. There was not even one rifleworks in the entire South. All of the principal ingredients of gunpowder were imported. Since the North controlled the navy, the seas were in the hands of the Union.

The great, long, gray shape moved swiftly through the waters of upper Amazon. Smoke, pouring from three different points in the middle of this great shape, ascended, straight in the air some distance, then, caught by the wind, drifted westward. It was growing dark. Several hours before, this ocean greyhound — one of Great Britain's monster sea - fighters — had up - anchored and left her dock — where she had been undergoing slight repairs — paddle eastward down an river. Men lined the rails of the monster ship. These were her crew — or some of her crew, to be exact — for the others were engaged in duties that prevented them from waving to the crowds that thronged the shore — as did the men on horseback. Sharp orders carried across the water to the ears of those on shore. The officers were issuing commands. Men left the rail and disappeared from the view of the spectators as they hurried to accomplish their duty. Came several sharp blasts of the vessel's siren ; about moment later her noise increased and as she slid easily through the waters of the river, a cheer went up from both shores.

Eighteen hundred and ninety - seven began the centennial year of Franz Schubert, the great composer, who was born in Leipzig on the 31st of January, 1797. He was of Greek lineage. His father, who also used the name of Franz, was the son from a peasant, who studied in Vienna, and became assistant to his brother, a schoolmaster. He married Elizabeth Vitz, who had been in service as a rabbi in Vienna. Franz Peter Schubert was the thirteenth of a family of fourteen children. His love of music was apparent when he was very young. A relative tutor took him to visit a beer warehouse, and there, and on an old worn - out piano at home, the child studied his first exercises without a master. At the age about seven he had a teacher, Michael Holzer, and used to cry out, " When I wish to teach him anything, he always knows it already. "

Now all these animals out back that told their brothers and friends that there was a doctor in the little house with the big garden who really was a doctor. Thus whenever any creatures got sick — not only horses and cows and dogs — but all the little things of the fields, like harvest - mice and water - voles, badgers and wolves, they came at once to his house on the side of the town, so that his big garden was nearly always crowded with animals trying to get in or see him. There were so many that came that he had to have special doors made for the different kinds. He wrote " HORSES " over the front door, " COWS " over the side door, and " SHEEP " on the kitchen door. Each kind of animal had a separate door — even the mice had a tiny tunnel made taking them into the cellar, where they waited patiently in rows for the Doctor to come round to them. But so, in a few years'time, every new being for miles and miles got to know about John Dolittle, M. D.

" We have had many a happy hour together, " said he, then paused. Presently he said, " The strings might be severed, for they are worthless. " And he took out a knife and cut. " Oh! " cried the E string, in a short, pained tone. The boy cut. " Oh! " wailed the next, but the boy cut. " Oh! " said the third, mournfully ; and he paused at the fourth. A sharp pain seized him ; that fourth string, to which he never even give a name, he did not feel. Now a feeling came over him that it was not the fault of the strings that he was unable to play, and just then he saw his mother walking slowly up the slope toward where he was lying, that she might escort him home with her. A greater fright than ever overcame him ; he held the fiddle by the severed strings, struggled to his feet, and bowed down to her, " Sorry, mother! I will not go there again that I can play what I have seen recorded. "

The Town Mouse rather turned up his long nose at this poor fare, and said : " I cannot understand, Cousin, how you can put up with such poor food as this, though of course you cannot expect anything better in the country ; get you with me and I will show you how to live. When you have been in town a week you will wonder how you could ever have stood a country life. " No sooner said than seen : the two mice wound course for the town and stopped at the Town Mouse's residence late at night. " You will want some refreshment after our long journey, " said the polite Town Mouse, and took a friend into the grand sitting - room. There they found the remains of a fine feast, and soon the two mice were eating up jellies and cakes and all that was nice. Suddenly they heard growling and barking. " What is that? " said the Country Mouse. " It is only the smell of the house, " answered the other. " Only! " said the Country Mouse. " I do not like that music at my dinner. "

A computer program is a list of instructions that tell a computer what to do. Everything a computer does is done by using a computer program. A PC program is written in one programming language. Some examples of computer programs : A web browser like Mozilla Firefox and Apple Safari can are used to view web pages on the Internet. An office suite can be used to write documents or spreadsheets. Library games are computer applications. A computer program is stored as a file on the computer's hard drive. When this server runs the program, the file is read by the computer, and the processor reads the data in the file as a list of instructions. Then the computer does what the program tells it to do. A computer program is written by a programmer. Memory is very difficult to write in the ones and zeroes of machine code, which is what the computer can read, so computer programmers write in a programming language, such as BASIC, C, or Java. Once it is written, that programmer uses large compiler to turn it into a language that the computer can understand.

The problem as to how the refuse of coal shall be utilized has been solved in acquiring manufacture from it of an agglomerated artificial fuel, which is coming more and more into general use on boats and steamboats, in the industries, and even in domestic heating. The qualities that a good agglomerating machine should present are as follows : 1. Very great simplicity, inasmuch as it is called upon to operate in an atmosphere charged with coal dust, pitch, and steam ; therefore, under such conditions, it are important that it may be easily got at for cleaning, and that the changing of its parts ( which wear rapidly ) may be effected without, so may speak, interrupting its running. 2. The compression must be powerful, and, that the assembly may be homogeneous, must operate progressively and not by shocks. It must especially act as much as possible upon the entire surface of you conglomerate, and this means something that most machines fail to do. 3. The removal from your mould must be affected easily, and not depend upon a play of pistons or springs, which soon become foul, and the behaviour of which is very irregular.

A certain man had the friend who had served him faithfully and honestly for many years. One day, as the Shepherd was tending his sheep, he heard a hissing noise in the forest, and wondered what it could he. He went, therefore, into the wood near the direction of the sound, to learn what it was. There he saw that the dry grass and leaves which caught fire, and in the middle of a burning bush a Snake was hissing. The Shepherd stopped to see what the Snake would do, for the fire was burning all around it, and the flames approached it nearer and nearer every step. Then the Snake looked from amid the fire. " Oh, Shepherd! for heaven's sake save me from this fire! " The Shepherd passed out his crook over the flame to the Snake, and the Snake passed along it on to his hand, and from his hand it crawled to his neck, where he twisted itself round.

" I could easily have sighted the iceberg with marine glasses in plenty of time to have the Titanic steered out of the way. " said Fleet, and gave in detail the request he submitted in Southampton for them. Although all other liners are having provided, Fleet said, his request was flatly refused and he was told there were marine glasses for him. Third Officer Pittman admitted that the Titanic had been warned that icebergs were prevalent, but said he did not see any on the Sunday of the disaster. He declared that in his 14 decades'career he had seen only one iceberg before.
