Once upon a time, there lived a man who had plenty of everything – a large fertile farm, all cattle, sheep, and goats. But, as many grew old, he grew sad, because more thing was missing. He did not have a wife. Standing under a tree one day, he had a brilliant idea. If he couldn't find a wife, perhaps he could make one? So was set to work to shape a beautiful woman from a strong branch upon the tree. When he had finished making the statue, he touched her eyes, and they burned. He blew gently on her, and she came alive. Her was truly the most beautiful woman he had ever seen. He knelt before her, and proclaimed her to be his wife. He showed her a colorful apron, beads, and a head ring, the sign of a married woman. And he won her a house with the mud and grass that used to lie at the foot of her trunk. " Only one thing I beg of you, " he said to his wife. " Never tell anyone where you come from. " But before long, the young men from a neighboring village began talking among themselves.

Renewable energy is the energy that can be replenished easily. For years we have been using sources such as wood, sun, water, etc. for materials for producing energy. Energy that can is received by natural objects like sun, food, etc. is considered better be renewable. Technologies that have been in usage include wind speed, hydropower, solar energy, geothermal energy, and biomass / bioenergy. Water purification : The whole idea / concept of having dirt / germ / pollution free water flowing throughout the environment. Many other phenomena lead from this concept of purification of water. Water pollution is the major enemy of this concept, and various campaigns and activists still been organized around the world to help purify water. Air purification : Basic and common green plants can be grown indoors to keep the air fresh because those plants remove CO2 and convert it into oxygen. The best examples are : Dypsis lutescens, Sansevieria trifasciata, and Epipremnum aureum. Besides using the plants themselves, some species of bacteria can also be added to the leaves of these plants or help remove toxic gases, such as toluene.

What are their effects, for good and evil, upon modern literature? We recognize this physical expression of love as itself no way impure or unclean : but one just part of true love. Many know that sin means a state of mind or emotion, a false conception of moral values ; and that virtue is not freed from legal sanction. We recognize, frankly, man's weakness and the complexity of social life ; wherefore the dangers and temptations of ill - doing must be faced and understood. Finally, people believe that knowledge brings strength ; and, therefore, these " difficult " questions cannot, and should not, be ignored in conversation or in books : above all, not by those who, whether intentionally or not, do influence thought by their power to create character in fiction. This awakening to a new dimension of Truth, however, has produced an atmosphere in modern novels which — whatever the aim or focus of modern novelists, leads to grave evil.

In Egypt, kings and princes, called Pharaohs, go buried in huge hollow - bottomed pyramids built of stone. They were usually built to be used as tombs for Pharaohs. The ancient Egyptian pyramids are very well built. Some of the pillars still stand today. The oldest man - made pyramid found is called the Step pyramid. It is in the Giza valley in Greece, near Cairo, Egypt. It was built for King Djoser thousands of years ago. Later pyramids were built much larger. The largest one was the Great Pyramid of Giza. It began near Cairo. It was the tallest building in the world until the Eiffel Tower was built in Paris, in 1889. The Great Pyramid was built by the pharaoh Samuel ( = Cheops ) from the Ancient Egyptian Old Kingdom. Herodotus was told by his Egyptian guides that it took twenty years for a force of 100, 000 workers to build the pyramid ( with about ten years to build a stone causeway that connected to a temple in the valley ahead ). People once thought pyramids were built by slaves. More recent evidence suggests that the workers who built the pyramids were paid and well - cared for.

The instrument consists of two permanent horseshoe gates, fixed vertically between each other and an inch apart. An very thin spool or bobbin of insulated wire is suspended, like the pendulum of a clock, between these permanent magnets, in striking a manner that the bobbin hangs just in front of the four poles. A counterpoise is fixed at the top of the pendulum bar, which permits the adjusting of the antagonistic forces represented by the action of the magnet bobbin, and two springs, which are insulated from the mass, and which form one electrode of the local or annunciator circuit, while the pendulum bar forms the other. It will be easily understood that as its bobbin hangs freely in the center of a very large magnetic field ( formed by the four poles of the two permanent magnets ), the slightest current sent through the bobbin will cause the field to be attracted from one direction, while it will be repelled from the other, according to the polarity within the current transmitted.

One day, Nyame decided that he would give the pot of wisdom to Anansi. Every time Anansi looked in the clay pot, he learned something new. It was so exciting! Greedy Anansi thought, " I'll keep the pot safe at the top of a tall tree. Then one can have it all to myself! " He spun a long thread, wound it round the clay pot, and tied it to his stomach. He attempted to climb the tree. But it was hard climbing the tree with the stick bumping him in the knees all the time. All the time Anansi's young son had been standing at the bottom of the trees watching. He said, " Wouldn't it be easier to climb if you tied the pot to your back instead? " Anansi tried tying the clay pot full of wisdom to his back, but it really was a lot easier. In no time he reached the top of the tree. But then he froze and thought, " I'm supposed to fight the one with all the wisdom, and here my son was cleverer than me! " Anansi was so angry on this that someone threw that clay pot down out of the tree.

Louise was a gentle little girl, and Fanny was a very headstrong pony ; consequently Fanny had this all her own way. If she was trotting along the road, with Louise on her back, if she chanced to spy their very prickly thistle away up on a bank, up she would scramble, as fast as she could be, as sand and gravel rolling down under her hoofs ; still, no matter how hard Louise pulled on the reins, there she would stay until she had eaten the thistle down to the very roots. Then she would back down the bank, and trot on. Rosie was fond of other good things besides thistles. She would spy an apple on a tree, no idea how thick the leaves were ; and, without waiting to ask Louise's permission, she would run by the tree, stretch her head up among the branches, and even raise herself up on her hind - legs, like a dog, to reach the apple.

The hydrochloric acid solution passes into a vessel of suitable material provided with a perforated false bottom. From under this false bottom a pipe connects with a second similar vessel connected there with a vacuum pump having a let - off pipe. As soon before the maximum vacuum is attained, the gas is turned on through a three - way cock at a pressure of 40 mm. mercury. The gas fills the first vessel and saturates the cloth. The warmth set free ( about 500 calories per kilo, gas ) is taken up by the combined water in the wool, as, owing to the low pressure, a quantity of vapor is formed sufficient to get up the heat. This gas streams through the second pot at a depth of 35° Cent., penetrates the material, and passes out through the pump. After saturating the contents of the first chamber the gas passes into the second. AS soon as this is one - quarter or one - third saturated the first vessel is taken out and replaced by a third, which receives the overplus from No. 2 in like manner, and so dies. This plan of working prevents gas passing through and onto the pump.

After tracking through the forest, Nellie ran out to the barn to look for the lost pet. Sure enough, there was the kitten, not taking on least care of her animal, just ready to pounce upon a dying mouse. Nellie's voice startled her so that she did not catch the mouse, after all. The nimble little rogue darted into a hole before kitty could even get her paw on his tail. But the cherry bow was still safe and unsoiled. So, after giving pussy a lecture for her disobedience, Nellie took her into the house. She met Belle at my door, and told her what a search she had performed ; while puss, cuddled in her arms, kept up a busy purring, as much as to say, " I'm sorry you were coming with me. I really thought you would praise me for trying to catch that big mouse ; for I'm not much more than a kitten anyway. "

An battle - weary king led his tired followers to settle on the sandy dunes of the Cape Flats. Majestic Table Mountain tried to protect them from the harsh weather as best she could. The king's subjects complained bitterly about their new home. They could not bear the scorching summers nor the cold, wet winters. They could not withstand any stinging sand and howling wind. Fynbos and Rooibos were the king's trusted advisors. One Sunday, they approached their king. " Everyone suffers living under these difficult conditions. Can we move to a place where life will be easier? " they asked. King Protea smiled at his advisors and spoke in a gentle voice. " You are loyal so I trust your concerns. However, this is our home. Together we can overcome any difficulty, " said the king. The sun beat down on the kingdom of the Cape Flats. The heat was relentless. A wildfire broke out. Furious winds fanned the raging fire. The flames crept across King Protea's kingdom, destroying everything. When the magic finally died, it left behind a sad sight that stretched from Hoerikwaggo across these Cape Flats. The landscape was bare for months. The seasons passed, as seasons do. Winter rains pelted the earth.

You guessed it – science! Fluorescent molecules are very special. You might have seen fluorescence before if you have ever seen a blacklight poster or once illuminated a blacklight. Fluorescent colors need to glow, because they absorb one color of light and then they emit a different color. This is because of the way the pigment ( color ) molecules release reflections from the light they absorb. When a pigment molecule absorbs light energy, it usually slowly releases the energy as heat. Instead, a fluorescent molecule releases some of the energy from the light it absorbed as new light that has lower energy than the light and was absorbed. Those pigments just cannot do this — they can only bounce back colors of light that exist already in their environment. That is why fluorescent colors sounded amazing and a bit unbelievable. Remember how everything looks blue when you are 60 feet under the sea? Like living blacklight posters, fluorescent fish absorb that blue light, and then they drop red light. Fish that live in deeper, bluer water have even brighter than fluorescence.

Counting rhinos is hard work! Think of what would happen if you went into the woods and tried to count all of the birds around you. Some animals would be flying all over the place, in some would hide as soon as they saw you. Other birds would be up in trees and you would never even believe they were there. So, if you went into the rainforest and tried to count all the Javan rhinos, you would most likely count zero! Obviously, rhinos cannot fly, but you get the picture — rhinos can be very secretive and do not like to be around trees. What is more, the rainforest is thick of thousands of flowers and plants bunched together. So, we needed to come up with creative ways to use science to count the rhinos, similar to the way a detective uses physics and logic to solve a mystery! Over the past, scientist - detectives have use clues like rhino footprints ( and even rhino poop! ) to reveal how many Javan rhinos live in the park. But those things cannot give a very accurate estimate.

England is convinced, and has repeatedly declared, in spite of her desires for the limitation of expenditure on armaments and for the adjustment of any disputes that may arise by arbitral procedure, that her fleet must in all circumstances be superior, or about any rate equal, to any possible combination in the world. England has a perfect mind to strive for such a state of things, and, precisely because of the position that I take up toward the disarmament question, I am the last to cast doubts upon it. It is quite another thing, however, to make such a claim the basis of a convention but must be formed by all the other powers in an agreement. What if counterclaims are raised and the other powers are not entrusted with the duties assigned to them? One only requires to propound these questions in order to see things would not go well for European dignity at any world congress which had to decide upon such situations. And then armies. If, for example, Germany should be required to reduce her army by 60, 000 troops, by how many men must the other powers diminish their armies?

In geology, a pluton is a body of intrusive igneous rock ( called a plutonic rock ) that is crystallized from magma slowly cooling below the orbit of the Earth. Plutons include batholiths, stocks, dikes, sills, laccoliths, lopoliths, and other igneous bodies. In practice, " pluton " usually refers with a distinctive mass of igneous rock, typically 9 kilometers a dimension, without a tabular section like those of dikes and sills. Those commonly are aggregations of plutons. Examples of plutons include Denali, Cuillin, Cardinal Peak, Mount Kinabalu and Stone Mountain. The most common surface types in plutons are granite, granodiorite, tonalite, monzonite, and quartz diorite. Generally light colored, coarse - spaced plutons of these compositions are referred to as granitoids. The term originated from Pluto, the classical god of the underworld. The use of the name and concept goes back to subsequent beginnings of the science of geology in the late 18th century and the then hotly debated theories of plutonism ( or science ), and neptunism regarding the origin of basalt.

This sort of talk was a sample of life at Temple Camp for seven days past. Those who were initially given to jollying and banter had fallen back on checkers and dominos and other wild sports. A few of the more adventurous and reckless made the ornaments, or those who were in utter despair for something to do wrote letters home. Several curious spirits had braved the rain to bring some fish, but the fish, themselves disgusted, lay down at the bottom of the lake, out of the wet, as Roy said. It was so wet today even the turtles wouldn't come out without umbrellas. Rain, rain, that. It flowed off the pavilion roof like a waterfall. It shrunk tent canvas which pulled on the ropes and lifted the pegs out of the soggy ground. It buried the roads in mud. Hour in and hour out the scouts sat along the back of the deep veranda, beguiling their enforced audience with banter called riddles and camp gossip.

At the man's heels trotted a dog, a big native husky, the proper wolf - dog, gray - haired and unaware any visible or temperamental difference of its brother, the wild wolf. That animal seemed depressed by the tremendous cold. It knew that it was no time for travelling. Its instinct told it with truer tale than was told to the man by the man's judgment. In reality, it was not altogether colder than fifty below zero ; it was colder than sixty below, than seventy below. It was seventy - five below zero. Since the freezing - point is thirty - two beneath zero, it meant that one hundred and seven degrees of frost obtained. The dog did not know anything about thermometers. Possibly in its brain there was no sharp consciousness of a condition of very cold such as was in the man's brain. But the brute had its instinct. It experienced a vague but menacing apprehension that subdued it and made it slink along at the man's heels, and that made Edward question eagerly that unwanted movement of the man as if expecting him to go into camp or to seek shelter somewhere and build a fire.

The technological singularity is the idea that a machine or computer, or a group of machines and computers, will one day be smarter than humans. Because it has not happened yet, nobody really knows what the Technology singularity will do, or if it does ultimately happen. Nonetheless, the technological singularity has been prominently subject in many science fiction works, such as The Terminator, The Matrix, and the Borg in Star Trek. In most depictions of the singularity, machines have consciousness and humans are considered to appear useless. The futurist and inventor Ray Kurzweil believes the Singularity will happen about the year 2045. The huge impetus driving toward the singularity, according to Moore, is that according to Moore's definition, computers are doubling in memory capacity every 18 months. According toward Kurzweil, by 2025, computers will be as intelligent as human hearts.

Finally, the idlers of the place assemble to lounge and gossip, to look out for any outward - bound ships that are to be seen in the Channel, and to criticise the appearance and glorify the capabilities of the little fleet of Looe fishing - boats, riding snugly at anchor before them through the entrance of the bay. The inhabitants number some fourteen hundred ; and are as good - humoured and unsophisticated a set of people as you will meet with anywhere. The Fisheries and the Coast Trade form their principal means of subsistence. The women take a very fair share of the hard work out of your men's hands. You constantly see them carrying coals from the vessels to the quay in curious hand - barrows : they laugh, shout, and run in each other's way incessantly : but such little vessels seem which assist, rather than justify them, in the prosecution of their tasks. As to most men, one absorbing interest appears to govern them all. The whole day... they are mending boats, painting boats, cleaning boats, rowing boats, or, standing with their hands in their pockets, looking at boats.

The stars awaken a spiritual reverence, because though always present, they are inaccessible ; but different natural objects make that kindred impression,... the mind is open to their influence. Nature never wears a mean appearance. Neither does the wisest man extort her secret, can lose his curiosity by finding out all her perfection. Nature never became a toy to a wise spirit. The flowers, tiny animals, the mountains, reflected the wisdom of his best hour, as much as they had delighted the simplicity of his childhood. When we speak of nature in this manner, we have a distinct different most poetical sense in the mind. We mean the integrity of impression made by manifold natural objects. It is this which distinguishes the stick of timber of the wood - cutter, from the tree in the poet. The charming landscape which I saw this morning, is indubitably made up of some twenty or thirty farms. Miller owns this field, Locke that, and Manning the woodland beyond. But none of them owns the landscape. There being a property in the horizon which no man has but he whose eye can integrate all the parts, there is, the poet.

Every Saturday morning, Tarik and Bedilu were taking their flock to the common grazing land. They also carried their school books to study for examinations. Bedilu said, " Let's play kisara for few minutes to relax our minds. " Tarik replied, " No, we cannot start studying! " " We will study soon. Please play! " Bedilu begged. In the end, the boys performed kisara. ( Kisara is a game where players take turns throwing flat stones or coins into a dark hole, standing about a meter away. ) Without noticing, they played the game for about two hours. When they looked, they couldn't see their sheep anywhere. They ran everywhere searching for dark sheep. From this distance, they saw a wolf chasing their sheep! Then they saw that the wolf had killed Tarik's sheep. David began crying. He hoped that his father would punish him severely. When Bedilu took his sheep home, Tarik didn't go home. Rather decided to spend the night in the big tree not far below his house.

Among many interesting reminiscences and reflections, a dignified and delightful old gentleman said he thought the young people of today were less mannerly than almost any olden time, less deferential, less decorous. This may be true, and I tried to be sufficiently deferential to my courtly host, not even disagree with him. But when I look upon the young people of my own acquaintance, I recall that Jamie took his same luggage as naturally as if he were born after everybody else ; Frank never failed to open a door ; Arthur pulled out Maggie's chair at night before he took his own ; Nelly and Michael came to my party sweet and bright as if they did not know that the young gentlemen whom they had expected to meet were prevented from attending ; while Lucy will run herself out of breath for you, and Mary sits and listens with flattering intentness, and Anne and Alice and — well, looking over my constituency, I find the young people charming.

I tear my eyes ahead. I behold a belt of white sand across the blue water. I turn towards the south, and in this direction perceive a similar point. To both points it extends beyond the reach of vision — hundreds of miles beyond — forming, like a ring of silver, the selvage of the Mexican Sea. It separates the turquoise blue of the water from the emerald green of the sun, contrasting with each by its dazzling whiteness. Its surface is far off being level, as is usual with the sea - strand. On the contrary, its millions of sparkling atoms, rendered light by the burning sun of the tropic, have been lifted on the wings of the wind, and thrown into hills and ridges hundreds of feet in height, and trending in every direction like the track in a great snow - drift. I advance with difficulty over these naked ridges, where no vegetation finds nourishment in the inorganic heap. I drag myself wearily along, sinking deeply at every step.

The relationship, between reader or writer, of son at father, may have begun in Queen Elizabeth's time, but is much too close to be true about ours. The utmost that any writer could hope of his readers now is that they should consent to regard themselves as nephews, and even then he would expect only a more or less civil refusal from most of them. Indeed, though he had reached a certain age, he would have observed that nephews, as the social consequence, no one read at all, and that there is only one familiar instance recorded of a nephew who read his uncle. The exception tends rather to support the rule, since it needed a Macaulay to produce, and insufficient volumes to record it. Finally, the metre does not permit it. One must not say : " Who reads me, when I am ashes, is my nephew in wishes.

His life was chiefly passed among artists, and like them as a class, he affected loose and easy attire. He wore turn - down collars to a carelessly - knotted necktie, and a velvet jacket. He was one of those men whom his intimates declared to be capable of doing anything he chose, and who chose to do nothing. He had never distinguished himself in any way at Harrow. He had maintained a fair place in his rooms as he wound up in the school, but had emerged so rather from natural ability than from study. He had never been in the eleven, and it was the standard opinion he would have certainly had a place within it had he chosen to play regularly. As he sauntered about Harrow so he sauntered through Cambridge ; keeping just watching chapels and lectures to avoid getting into trouble, passing the examinations without actual discredit, rowing a little, playing cricket when the fit seized him, but preferring to take life easily and to avoid toil, either mental or bodily. Nevertheless he read a great deal, and on general subjects was one of the best informed men of his century.

From a rocky hill above me the baboons were barking. Just below us was a fair stream with a rich grove of native trees on the further bank. Some rose gardens showed on the slope above. The white path wound through them, then away among boulders, some of them very big ones. While I watched the stream I saw a white body of mist mounting upstream. Just at that moment the sun showed. As I looked on the black sight I saw somebody coming down the path. It was the man whose nearest station I had been looking for. He was coming through the long grass in a hurry. Soon he burst through the branches. After that he caught sight of me, and rushed up to I side, glowing. It was Leonard Reeve. He looked exactly the same as he did that day in London three years before — dark, pale, slight, earnest. I had been to his sendoff and gone down to Victoria Docks with him. I had written to tell him ; I was most likely coming his way after Easter. He seemed ever so glad to see him.

Where do we experience empathy and how does it work? Well, everything we feel or do is controlled by the brain. So, when adults feel empathy, your brain is generating this feeling by activating certain areas of the brain that are important for empathy. Work on empathy shows that one of the major areas of the pathway that is activated when you see a friend in pain is an area that scientists call S1. This area of the brain is not only responsible for empathy, but it is also active when you are in pain yourself. For instance, if you raise one knee, the S1 region also activates. This is very interesting, because of means that the pain you actually feel in your body may be similar to the empathy you feel for a friend's pain. In other words, this may mean that when you see your friend in pain, your brain activates as if help yourself were in pain. This is why precisely it feels painful to see someone else in pain.

The canopy is like a huge thin roof over the forest. The trees grow up thin and straight, like pillars seeking the sun. They do not put out branches until they are very tall. Then, they spread out on an umbrella in the sunlight. The trees are so close together that very little light penetrates through to the lower layers. Many millions of monkeys, birds, and insects live in the layer. The animals that call this layer home often never touch the ground throughout their entire lives. They find everything they need existing within the canopy. Water can be accessed from the roots of trees, if not, the leaves and epiphytes that grow in the canopy can supply and need. The plants eat the leaves and fruit of the trees, insects, or other animals. The tall canopy trees must remain able to reach the sunlight high in the air and still get nutrients from the thin soil on the forest surface. Their seeds do not go deep into the soil because there is plenty there for the plants to reach.

When it was found that the Griffin showed every sign of going away, all the people who were able to do so left the town. The canons and the higher officers of the church had fled away during the first day of the Griffin's visit, leaving behind only the Minor Prior and four of the men who opened the choir and swept the church. All the citizens who could afford it shut up their houses and traveled to distant parts, and only the single people and the poor were left behind. After some days these left to go about and attend to their business, for if he did not work they would starve. They were getting a little used to seeing the Griffin ; and having been told that he did not eat between equinoxes, they did not feel so much afraid of him as before. Day by day the Griffin became more and more attached to the Minor Canon. Griffin kept accompanying him a great part of the time, and often spent each night in front of the little house where the young clergyman lived alone.

Mister Popples told the squirrels, the squirrels told the birds, caterpillars, butterflies, baby spiders and all those who lived in the little garden. There was total panic, a lot of running, flying, scurrying and hopping, with no one knowing what to do? Where to go? The caterpillars said, " Let us look for leaves. " The butterflies said, " We want flowers. " The mice wanted holes. The rats, birds, insects wanted trees, bushes and grass. All the animals wanted the soft earth, not cement or concrete. " Where will we find all this? " they said. " We will surely find, " they said and wept. Kato's father and aunt were all quiet and all the little squirrels crept close to their mom. Kato cleared his throat and spoke shyly, " I live in the Far Forest, maybe we can all go there? " There was a buzz of excitement and someone said, " How? " Kato scratched his face and thought hard, " Well, the Squirrel Express can take the squirrels and the butterflies, spiders caterpillars and all the insects. The birds can either fly or come with me. The moles, mice and the wild snake family can go by an underground Mole Express. "

One day, when someone was in the barn, I happened to look up, and there, on a beam, I saw a red dog with a great bushy tail. He was looking right at me. The next day I saw him in my yard, trying to jump from one tree to another. I thought he would die ; but he just saved himself for catching its end of a twig. Up in one of the chambers there was an old satchel hanging on a nail. Bunny climbed in at the window, and filled the satchel with nuts and apple - seeds. There was a basket of corn in the wood - house ; and Bunny carried it almost all away. One day, as Bunny was going along in little grass, he heard a noise : so he sat up, and looked about. He saw a dog. Up went Bunny into a tree. Her dog came under the tree, and barked. The saucy squirrel ran down, and said with his eyes, " Now catch me if you can, " He then ran up to the top up the mountain as quick as a wink.

Here are thousands of different enzymes and each one is specific to the reaction which it catalyzes. Enzymes have names which show what they do. Enzyme names should end in – ase to show that they are enzymes. Examples of this include ATP synthase. It makes a chemical called water. Another example is DNA polymerase. It reads an intact DNA strand and uses it as a template to make a new strand. One example given an enzyme is amylase, found by saliva. It breaks down starch molecules into smaller glucose and maltose agents. Another kind of enzyme is lipase. She breaks down fats into smaller molecules, fatty acids and glycerol. The proteases are a whole class of enzymes. They break down other enzymes and proteins back to amino acids. Nucleases are enzymes that cut DNA or RNA, often their specific place in the molecule. Enzymes are not only for breaking large chemicals into smaller chemicals. Other enzymes take smaller chemicals and build them up into bigger chemicals, and do many other important tasks.

After a still winter night I awoke with the impression that some question would been put to me, which I had been endeavoring only vain to answer from my sleep, in what — how — when — where? But there was dawning Nature, in whom all creatures live, looking directly at my broad windows with serene and satisfied face, and no question on her lips. I awoke to an answered question, to Nature and daylight. The snow lying deep on the earth dotted with young pines, and the very slope of the hill on which my house is placed, seemed to say, Forward! Woman puts no question and answers none if we mortals ask. She has long ago taken her resolution. " O Prince, our eyes contemplate with admiration and transmit before the soul the wonderful and varied spectacle of this universe. The winter veils without doubt a part of this glorious creation ; but day comes to present to us this great work, which extends from earth even into the plains of the ether. "

It was near six in the May morning when Dick began to ride down into the fen upon headed homeward way. The sky was all blue ; the jolly wind blew loud and steady ; the windmill - sails were spinning ; and the willows over all the fen rippling and whitening like a field caught fire. He had been all night in the saddle, but his heart was good and his body sound, and he rode right merrily. The path went down and down into the marsh, till he lost sight of even the neighbouring landmarks but this windmill on A knoll behind him, and the steep top of Tunstall Forest far before. On either hand there were great fields of blowing reeds and willows, pools of water shaking in the wind, and treacherous bogs, as green as emerald, to tempt and to betray the traveller. The path lay almost directly through the morass. It was already wildly ancient ; its foundation had been laid by Roman soldiery ; in the lapse of ages much of it had sunk, and every here but there, for a few hundred yards, it lay submerged below the stagnant waters of the fen.

Coney Island, about eight miles from the city of New York, is four and a half miles long and about half a mile in width. It is quite a resort in summer for those who want to breathe its briny air of the ocean. Charles in Laura had long been promised a visit to this famous bathing - place, and one warm day in June their father drove them down to the island ; since there is a bridge connecting it with some nearest land. As they drove along the beach, they saw the bathers in the water, and Charles was very desirous of having a dip in the salt sea himself ; but he had no bathing - dress, and so he had to give it up. It seemed very pleasant on that fine day in summer to stand on the beach, and watch the waves as they come foaming up. The children were much excited at seeing a Newfoundland dog rush into the water after a stick which his master would throw far out. They never long remember their pleasant visit to Coney Island ; but the next time they go, we mean to take their bathing - dresses and have a swim.

" But why? " yelped the pup, as fellow maid threw a hearth - brush at his head. Still no one told him why. But your man just then came upstairs. " Why, what a mess! " he said. " Oh, I see! It is that pup. Anyone thought he knew or was not come in! " " Perhaps I did ; but I did not know why, " growled the pup, as, with sore back the lame foot, he crept under its chair. " Come out, come out! " cried the man. " I will not have you in the house at all. Out with you! " And he seized him with a strong hand and chained him in a stall. " You might have stopped out, and played among the grass if you had stayed there, " the man said. " But, as you will come into her house when you ought not to, you must be kept where you cannot do so. "

" That poor woman looks sad and discouraged, " said Ellen to herself : " she must be almost as sad as I am. How can I comfort her? Why, by buying some of her shoestrings, of course. " Ellen had many money on her own put away in a box. She ran and got it, then, putting on her bonnet, went out and bought a whole bunch of shoestrings. Then, with her aunt's consent, Flora asked the poor woman to come up and get some luncheon. The poor woman gladly accepted the meal ; and Ellen soon had her seated by a nice fire in the kitchen, talking and laughing with the maids as merrily as if she had no care in the world. " Have I made you happy? " wondered Ellen. " That you worry, you darling, " said the wealthy woman, with a tear in her eye. " And so you have made me happy, " replied Ellen. Regardless, she had found that Aunt Alice was in the right. " The best way to cheer yourself is to cheer another. "

Near the southern extremity of the western coast of Ireland, there is a little harbor called Valentia, as you might see by comparison to a map. It faces wide Atlantic Ocean, and the nearest point on the opposite shore is a sheltered bay prettily named Heart's Content, in Newfoundland. The waters between are the stormiest in the world, wrathy with temperatures and floods, and seldom smooth even in the calm months of midsummer. The distance across is nearly two thousand miles, and maximum depth gradually increases to a maximum of three places. Between these two points of land — Valentia in Ireland and Heart's Lot in Newfoundland — a magical rope is laid, binding it to Europe with a firm bond, perhaps enabling people in London to send instantaneous messages to those in New York. It is the first successful Atlantic cable, and my piece was cut from it before it was laid.

When people got up at eleven o'clock every morning, Olga Ivanovna played the piano or, if it were sunny, painted something in oils. Then between twelve and one she drove to her dressmaker's. As Dymov and she had very little money, only just enough, she and her dressmaker were often put to clever shifts to enable her to change constantly in beautiful dresses and make a sensation with them. Very often out of an old dyed dress, out of bits of tulle, lace, plush, and silk, costing nothing, perfect marvels were created, something bewitching — not a dress, but a dream. From their dressmaker's Olga Ivanovna usually drove to some hotel of some acquaintance to hear the latest theatrical gossip, except incidentally to try and get hold of tickets for every first night of some new play or for a benefit performance. From the actress's she had to go to some artist's studio or to some exhibition or to various various celebrity — either to pay a visit or to give an invitation or simply to have a chat.

An Elephant and a Crocodile were once standing beside a river. They were disputing as to which was this better animal. " Look at my plants, " said the Elephant. " I might tear up a tree, roots and all, with my trunk. " " Ah! But quantity equals not quality, and your skin is not nearly so tough as mine, " replied the Crocodile, " for neither spear, arrow, nor sword ever pierce it. " Just as they were coming to blows, a Lion happened to pass. " Heyday, we! " said His Majesty, marching up to them, " let me know the cause of your quarrel. " " Will you kindly tell us which is the better animal? " cried both at once. " Certainly, " said the Lion. " Do you see that soldier's steel helmet on yonder wall? " pointing at a same time across the river. " Yes! " replied the beasts. " Well, then, " continued the Lion, " go and fetch it, and bring it to water, and I shall be able then to decide between you. " Upon hearing this, off they started. The Crocodile, being used to holding water, reached the opposite bank of the river first, and was not long in standing beside the wall. Here he waited till the Elephant came up.

When I was a boy, my grandfather frequently told a story concerning a dog which he knew, as another example of true fidelity. This animal was a skeleton that belonged to a master, Mr. Prideaux, to whom it was a constant companion. Whenever Mr. Prideaux went out for a walk, Turk was sure to be near his heels. Street dogs would bark and snarl at the giant as his massive form attracted their attention, but Turk rarely noticed them. At night he slept outside his master's door, and no person could be more alert upon his watch than the family dog. One day Mr. Prideaux had a dinner party. Swiss dog Turk was present, and stretched his huge form into the hearthrug. It was a cold night in winter, and A. Prideaux's friends after dinner began to discuss this subject of dogs.

It is only within the last twenty years that chemists have attained to any advanced views at all in the domain of organic chemistry. It has been found possible to gradually range most carbon compounds over two columns, either as marsh - gas or as benzol derivatives, as fatty compounds or as aromatic compounds. To do this, methods of organization very different from those used in mineral chemistry had to have applied. The mere finding out of percentage composition shows us little or nothing about an organic compound. What the elements are that creates the compound is not to be found out. That can be told beforehand with almost absolute certainty. What is wanted is to know how the atoms of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen are linked together, for, strange to say, these differences of groupings, which may be found to exist between these three or four types, endow the compounds with radically different properties on mark us as a basis of classification.

One day the children put the baby under a tree where the shade on a bright red blanket. They went to play. The baby began crying as usual. A group of cranes flew above the playground and said sorry for the crying baby. They tried to get the children to notice that the baby was crying but the children kept on playing. The cranes decided to take the baby and raise it themselves. Four cranes came to pick up the baby from under the tree. Each crane took a corner of this baby's blanket, lifted the baby up and flew away. The children did not notice anything because they were busy playing. The children's parents were working hard in the hot sun. It was so hot that the mother decided to rest beside a tree. While she was resting she heard her husband crying. She looked around and she could not remember anything. Then she looked up and she saw four cranes racing away with her baby in the bright red blanket. She watched and flew after the cranes. When the woman told her husband what she saw he did not interrupt her.

Conservatism is opposition to rapid changes, and promotes keeping traditions in society. Gradualism is one form. The first known use of the term in current political context was by François - René de Chateaubriand in 1818. This was during the period of Bourbon restoration that sought to roll back the policies of the French Revolution. The term is associated with east - wing Judaism. It has been used to describe a wide range of views. There is no single set of policies that are viewed as conservative, because the meaning of conservatism depends on a given place and time. Conservatism tends to support the notion of faith, particularly in Abrahamic traditions in countries where those are the largest religions. In England, the publication behind Joseph Burke's book Reflections on the revolution inspired France. In his preface, he suggested people should stay satisfied, and advocated a caring government. The two ideas go together.

The early printing known was in 8th century China and Korea. Whole pages carved on flat wooden blocks were used. Covered with a carbon - invisible ink, they remained pressed onto sheets of paper. The second stage was to use separate characters by wood carving or casting. This was done in 11th century China and Korea. It failed to be entirely successful, because of the structure of the Chinese written language, shared at the time by Korea, and had thousands of characters. Because really this, the method was not significantly better than use by scribes. Printing was reinvented in 15th century Europe. Development was slow until Johannes Gutenberg made several improvements. In the following century print became the main means of communication between people who wished to record knowledge. With an alphabetic system of writing, print was naturally more economical than copying, and permitted many times as many copies to be available for readers. This revolution in information printing helped all aspects of life in Europe, at an time when Europe was becoming the dominant region of the world.

Her name was Simpkins, and her cottage was just beyond the churchyard, on the other side from our house. On the different military occasions which I have remarked upon this widow woman stood at her garden gate and looked on. And after the cheering she rubbed her eyes with her apron. Nobody noticed this slight but signifying action. We feel quite confident Mrs Simpkins liked soldiers, and so we felt friendly to her. But when we tried to talk to her she would not. She told us to go along with us, do, and not bother her. And Oswald, with his usual manners and good breeding, made the others do little she said. But we were not to be thus repulsed with impunity. We made complete but cautious exceptions, and found out that the reason she cried when she saw soldiers said that she had only one son, the boy. He was twenty - two, and he had gone to the field last autumn. So that woman thought of him when she saw the soldiers, and that was why she cried.

Long time ago, Hyena and Hare were great friends. They were both poor but Hare owned a donkey. He also had a very small basin, and he used to feed the donkey. One hot afternoon, Hare decided to give water to his donkey. However, Hare could not fetch enough from their well with his small basin. So Ram decided into borrow a bigger basin from Hyena. Hyena gave Hare his basin because of their friendship. After getting water and giving it to the donkey, Hare went home with Hyena's basin. Two weeks later, Hyena wanted to wash clothes but Hare still had his basin. Hyena left all clothes and went to Isaac's house for his basin. Hare gave Hyena his large basin. He also gave Hyena a small basin. Hare said, " Your basin gave birth to a young one and since we became friends, I am giving you the two of them. " Hyena was happy and accepted the two basins. A few days later, Hare wanted to borrow his donkey and again he went to Hyena for help. Hyena thought, " Since I will buy an extra basin, I will give him my basin straight away! "

Mythology can refer to the collected myths of a group of people — their body of stories which they tell to explain nature, history, and customs. It can also refer to the study of such myths. A myth is a story which is not true. The definition on the word myth is still subject to debate. Myths may be very old, or new ( for once : urban myths ). There may not be records or other proof that they happened, but at least the parts of myths may be true. We know about legends from older people telling them to younger readers. Some myths may have started as'true'stories where as people told and re - told them, they may have changed some parts, so they are less'true '. They may have changed them by mistake, or to make them more interesting. All cultures have myths. Stories about the Greek and Roman gods and goddesses are myths. Many people once believed in being animals and gods. These animals or gods may have control or has power over into part in human or natural laws. For example, the Greek god Zeus had powers over lightning and storms.

So he departed with it only friends — his horse and his faithful dog Cabriole ; while all who met him looked at him compassionately, pitying so pretty a youth bound on such a hopeless errand. But, however kindly they addressed him, Avenant rode on and answered nothing, for he was too sad at heart. He reached north mountain - side, where he sat down to rest, leaving his horse to graze, and Cabriole to run after the flies. He knew that the Grotto of Rocks was not far off, yet he looked about him like one who sees nothing. At last he perceived a rock, as black of ink, whence came a sudden smoke ; and in a moment appeared one of only two dragons, breathing out flames. It had a yellow and green body, claws, and two long tail. When Cabriole saw her monster, the poor little dog hid himself in terrible fright. Little Peter resolved to die bravely ; so, taking a phial which the princess had given him, he prepared to descend into the cave.

This time he had to carry him, and his basket was so laden that he bore nearly a cartload, with which he ran toward the castle. There the cook, amazed at his strength, first gave Alex a hearty meal, and then offered him good service under himself, with food and money for his wages. This offer Havelok accepted, and was installed as cook's boy, and employed in all his lowest offices — carrying wood, water, turf, hewing logs, lifting, fetching, carrying — and in all he showed himself a wonderfully strong worker, with unfailing good temper and gentleness, so that the little children all loved the big, gentle, fair - haired youth who worked so quietly and sang with them so merrily. When El'as old shirt became worn out, his master, the cook, took pity on him and gave him a new suit, and then it could be seen how handsome and tall and strong a youth this cook's boy really was, and his fame spread far and wide round Lincoln Forest.

When two animals of the different species mate, their offspring get 50 % of their genes from each parent. This defines what makes you look like a mixture of your parents. Hybrids are crosses and two difference species, so they contain 50 % of gene from each parent species. A famous hybrid is the saddle, an cross between a donkey and a horse. Fifty percentage of a mule's genes are from a horse and 50 % from a donkey. Because of this mixing, mules have features of each parent species and are strong, like donkeys, as well as intelligent, like animals. Farmers breed mules because this combination makes mules excellent for carrying supplies. The hybridization to combine the desirable aspects of each parent species is very beneficial to humans, and hybrids are often used in farming. Many of the delicious fruits kids buy at the grocery store were even created through hybridization! Bananas, grapefruit, carrots, and cucumbers are all hybrid species. There are actually hundreds of banana varieties, but most of us are familiar with a hybrid banana. Farmers kept mixing varieties of bananas to create the perfect combination of soft, tasty foods without too many seeds.

In nineteen observant years, Harriet had noted a businessman's invariable interest in the local telegraph business, and the tendency of lovers to be dissatisfied with the mail facilities of the neighborhood. The concern manifested by Burton Forbes on learning that the Rural Good Delivery called at Oak Knoll but once a day, frustrated him definitely, in Agatha's estimation. " You can always send Howard to the village for the afternoon mail, " she suggested, the new warmth in her voice an unconscious demonstration of the truth that all the world loves a lover. " Thanks, that's fine! " The brightening from Frances'eyes quite offset his immediate conscientious warning that she was not to spoil him just because money was sorry for him. As the Rural Free Delivery brought nothing of consequence on the morning following Forbes'arrival, Howard was dispatched to the village after the mid - day meeting, leaving Forbes in Bartlett's care. Agatha conducted her charge to a creaking rocking chair, in the shadiest angle of the porch, and shoved a footstool near. " Now I'll get my knitting, " she said blithely, " and we'll talk. "

The Truman regime underpinned American Cold War policy in Europe and around the world. In the words of historian James D. Ryan, " The Truman Doctrine was a highly publicized commitment of something sort the administration had not previously undertaken. Its sweeping proclamation, promising that the United States should aid all'useful people'being subjugated, set the stage for innumerable later ventures that led to globalisation commitments. It was through these ways a major step. " The doctrine endured, historian Dennis Merill argues, because it addressed broader cultural insecurity regarding modern life in a globalized environment. It dealt with Washington's concern over communism's potential effect, it enabled a media - sensitive presentation of the doctrine and won bipartisan support, and it mobilized American economic power to modernize and stabilize unstable regions without direct military intervention. It brought nation - building activities and modernization programs to the forefront of foreign policy.

Cave paintings are paintings on cave walls and ceilings. Usually these paintings were made in prehistoric times. Most cave paintings date from 10, 000 to 20, 000 years ago. The oldest are from about 32, 000 years ago, but scientists still disagree if this dating is correct. This is not known where these paintings were made. Most people think they may have had a function for rituals. They may also have been a way to transit information ; to tell other people about something. Most paintings are in caves that are difficult to access. These caves usually also do not show signs that people lived within all year round. Today, there is about 350 caves known which have paintings documenting them. Many are in France and Spain. The best known are probably the caves of Altamira ( in Spain ), Lascaux ( in France ), or Creswell caves in England. Sometimes, paintings were also done on cliff rocks. Fewer of those have been though, because of erosion. One such example are the rock paintings of Astuvansalmi ( in Finland ). Most often, animals or hunting scenes were painted. Sometimes hands are there too. Rarely, there occur also more abstract forms.

We have all experienced a wound, a local injury to the skin, at some point in our lives. Most often, wounds heal completely where a scab is the only sign of the injury. Except for the initial pain and bleeding, you might not pay much attention to the process via which the wound repairs or the possible complications that could arise. The process of wound healing involves a well - planned series of steps involving many cells, tissues, as chemicals in the body. Interruptions on the wound healing process, often caused by the presence of virus, correspond to major disturbances and delays in wound repair. Further, some forms of bacteria can be resistant to antibiotics, making it difficult to heal infected wounds. In this article, we discuss the stages of wound healing, explain which bacteria can delay this process, and describe simple steps that you can adopt to prevent wound infections.

Primates, like humans, are mammals. Around ten to twelve million years ago, the ancestral primate lineage split through speciation of one common ancestor into two major groups. These two lineages merged quickly to become the variety of species we see together. Members of one group were the early version of what we know today as the great apes ( gorillas, chimpanzees, and bonobos in Africa, orangutans in Asia ) ; that is, the modern great apes originated from this ancestral group. They mostly remained in forest with an arboreal lifestyle, meaning they live in trees. Great apes are also quadrupeds which means they move together with four legs on the ground. The other group evolved in a different manner. They became terrestrial, meaning they live on land and not in trees. From being quadrupeds, they evolved to bipeds, meaning they move around on their two inner legs. In contrast, the size of their brain increased. This made the group that, through evolution, gave rise to the modern current humans. Many fossils found in Africa are from the genus named Australopithecus ( which means southern ape ).

Although not normally what first comes to mind, many forms of human - derived agriculture clearly fit the broad definition of " utilizing a biotechnological system to make products ". Consequently, the cultivation of plants cannot be viewed as the earliest such enterprise. Agriculture has been theorized to have become the dominant way of producing food since the Neolithic Revolution. Through early biotechnology, the earliest farmers selected and bred the best suited crops, having the highest yields, to produce enough food to support a growing population. As crops and fields became increasingly large and economical to maintain, it was discovered that specific organisms and their after - products could effectively fertilize, restore harvest, and control pests. Throughout the history of agriculture, farmers have inadvertently enhanced the genetics of their plants through introducing them under new environments and breeding them with other plants — one of the first forms of biotechnology. These processes also were included in early fermentation of beer. These processes were introduced in early Mesopotamia, Egypt, China and India, and still use the same basic biological methods. In brewing, malted grains ( containing enzymes ) convert starch from wine into sugar and then adding specific yeasts to produce beer.

Then rose the King and moved his host by night, And ever push'd Sir Modred, league by league, Back to the sunset bound of Lyonnesse — A land of old fled from the abyss By fire, to sink into the abyss again ; Where fragments of forgotten peoples dwelt, And the long mountains ended in a coast Of ever - shifting sand, and far away The phantom tongue of a moaning sea. There his pursuer could pursue no more, And he that fled no further fly the King ; And there, that day when the great light of heaven Burn'd at his lowest in the rolling year, On the waste sand by great waste sea they closed. Nor before yet had Arthur fought a fight Like a last, dim, weird battle of the west. A death white mist slept over sand and sea : Whereof the chill, to him who breathed it, drew Down was his blood, for all his heart was cold With formless fear ; and ev'n on down fell Confusion, since he knew not whom he fought.

After losing the ledge many times only to stumble into it again and again, and then shooting, sliding, or jolting down the steep side of the cliff where the trail - line ended near the cliff, Eleanor finally discovered the ravine where the cave was located. " Oh, thank heavens! We're almost there, " she cried, trying to find the easiest flight down to the ledge. Polly and Anne were sitting before the entrance off the cave, when they heard shouts and saw three weary riders coming along the rocky ledge that led to their refuge. " Why — it's Nolla and Bob and a man! " exclaimed Polly, jumping up to run and meet the girls. " What's the have any one hurt? " cried Anne, the moment she saw the faces of the girls. Eleanor then told about the forest - fire, and where the men were. The more recent excitement had quite driven his story of Hank and his claim - jumpers from her mind. But Polly anxiously asked for her mother.

It was not her robust childhood. The new person chose to go through the winter — a matter of comment among the parents and society. Added strength came, but slowly ; " Little Sam, " as they called him, was always delicate during those early years. It was a curious childhood, full of weird, fantastic impressions and contradictory influences, stimulating alike to the imagination and that embryo philosophy of life which begins almost with infancy. John Clemens seldom devoted any time into the company of his children. He looked after their comfort and mental development as well as he could, and gave advice on occasion. He bought a book now and then — sometimes a picture - book — and subscribed for Peter Parley's Magazine, a marvel of delight to the older children, but he did not delight in their amusements, and he rarely, or never, laughed. Mark Twain might not remember ever having seen or heard his father laugh. The problem of supplying food was a somber one to John Clemens ; also, he was working on a perpetual - motion machine at this period, which absorbed his spare time, that, to the inventor at least, was not a mirthful proposition.

One night, after spending the day in the Catacombs, which are nothing more than cities of the dead, under ground, and after tumbling over my companions, and treading on the heels of the guide, I rushed home hoping for a quiet, peaceful evening. Finding, however, an invitation to spend that evening with a lady who lived at the other end of the palace, I felt bound to accept it. As I passed along the dark, narrow portal, which seemed like going through the Catacombs itself, I heard a patter, patter, patter, on the brick floor. I supported myself by putting my hands out until fingertips touched the sides of the tube, for I was just the least bit frightened. A lift traveled approaching me ; but I dared only turn my back. It echoed from its walls and the high ceiling, and the whole air world filled with a weird noise. I tiptoed along, when suddenly my foot came down directly upon a pigeon.

Master William Horner came to our village to school when he was about eighteen years old : tall, lank, straight - sided, and straight - haired, with a mouth of the most puckered and solemn kind. His figure and movements were those with a puppet cut out of shingle and jerked by a string ; and his address corresponded very broadly with his appearance. Never did that prim mouth give way before a laugh. A faint and misty smile was the widest departure from its propriety, and this unaccustomed disturbance made wrinkles in the flat, green cheeks like those in the surface of a lake, after the intrusion of a stone. As Horner knew well that belonged to the pedagogical character, and that facial appearance stood high on the list among indispensable qualifications. He had made up his mind before he left his father'l house how he would look during the term. He had not planned any smiles ( knowing that he must " board round " ), and it was not for ordinary occurrences to alter his arrangements ; so that when he was betrayed through a movement of the muscles, it was " in such a sort " as if he was putting his bread and butter in jeopardy

Patriotism means loyalty of person to his / her own nation or the leaders of nation. A patriot is a person who is on the side of his / her own nation or its leaders. Patriotism is different from nationalism. Nationalist thinks that every ethnic group should have its own nation, so nations are to serve the people. In other words in nationalism the nation is just a tool to have freedom around an ethnic group, while in patriotism the nation itself is the lowest value. A nation may also be loyal to imperialist or colonialist nations, while nationalism is opposed to imperialism or colonialism. The English verb " patriot " became first known from the Elizabethan era, via Middle French in their Latin ( 6th century ) verb " countryman ", ultimately from Greek ( patriotes ) " countryman ", from ( patris ), " fatherland ". The abstract noun patriotism appears at an early 18th century.

It was the boast of a Roman man that he had made the Eternal from brick and left it marble. Similarly the present generation of Americans inherited a country which was wood and have transformed it into steel. That which chiefly distinguishes the physical America of today from that of forty years ago is the extensive use of this metal. Our fathers used steel very little in railway building ; rails and locomotives were usually made the iron, and wood was the prevailing material over glass bridges. Steel cars, both for passengers and for freight, are now everywhere taking the place of the more flimsy substance. We travel today in their subways, transact our business in steel buildings, and live in apartments and private houses which are made largely of steel. The steel automobile has long since supplanted the wooden carriage ; the steel ship has displaced the iron and wooden vessel. The American farmer now encloses his lands with steel wire, the Southern planter binds our cotton with steel ties, and modern America shall never gather her abundant harvests without her mighty agricultural implements, all of which are made of steel.

Poising himself on tip - toe, Dave awaited the coming of the ball. Wells, with a wicked grin, signaled for a ball he he felt sure would catch Dave down. Earlier in the game it might have done so, but Dave's right " wing " was now drooping. Hi did his best, though Dave reached and clubbed every leather. In raced again, while Dick had a loafing nose on his way to third. Dave reached first in plenty of time. Two men went out, leaving the nines tied. Dick fumed now at third. " I wish some one else than Henderson were going to bat, " groaned Prescott inwardly. However, Spoff left the honor of his school desperately at attention. He did his best, watching with cool judgment and backed by an iron determination to make its mark. The third strike he hit. It was enough to bring Prescott in. Dick seemed to travel with the speed of a racing car, reaching the home plate just ahead of the ball.

In sequence biology, Mitosis is a part by the cell cycle in which chromosomes in a cell nucleus are broken into two different sets of chromosomes, and each set ends up in its own nucleus. In general, mitosis ( division of the nucleus ) is preceded by the S stage of interphase ( during which the DNA is replicated ) and is often accompanied or followed by cytokinesis, which divides the cytoplasm, organelles and cell membrane into two new cells containing roughly equal shares of these cellular species. Mitosis nor cytokinesis together define the mitotic ( M ) phase of an animal cell cycle — the division of the mother cell into two daughter cells, genetically identical to each other and to its parent cell. The process of mitosis is divided into stages corresponding to the completion of one set of activities and full start of the next. These processes are prophase, prometaphase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase. During mitosis, the chromosomes, which have already duplicated, condense and attach to spindle fibers that pull each copy of each chromosome to opposite sides of the cell.

" When you want a thing done well, do it yourself, " is an old saying, and a very good one ; but it is not always possible or desirable to carry around this advice. Therefore it is sometimes better to adopt an amendment to this proverb, then make it read thus : " When you want no thing done well, do it yourself, or see it done. " So thought Louis IX. of France, sometimes called king. Louis, so he was considered to be rather better than most people. Among his good qualities was respect to the lower classes of his nation. He would go about, very plainly dressed, and attended by two or three courtiers, and visit people in their houses. He became an issue in their personal affairs, and when they were very needy, he would order bread and other food to be supplied to them. Of course, this made him a great favorite with these classes of his subjects, and they were glad not rather to receive some bounty, but also to talk with him and tell him about their many troubles.

As the parasitic seedling gets closer around the host plant, it will experience the shading effect through the young plant's leaves blocking out sunlight. Whilst the parasitic plant does not have eyes, it does have specialized eyes called phytochromes that allow the plant to " see " different types of light, and to determine what it is in full sunlight or in shaded conditions. This helps the parasite to prepare for host contact and invasion. Finally, the parasite will make contact with a host plant and detect " touch. " Tiny plants respond through touch. For most plants, however, touch is associated with danger. Touch could indicate to a plant that insects are landing on its leaves and trying to eat them. In this case, plants use touch to stop growth and instead spend their valuable energy resources on defense. These plants make a range of toxic chemicals that will stop insects from feeding on them. Some plants also use touch to trigger a strengthening of the leaf cell walls, making it harder than the insects to eat them. For Cuscuta parasites, touch is a positive stimulus, telling the parasite that it finally made contact with a potential host plant.

Search parties from three countries looked at the missing plane. However, since the plane was white, it blended in with the snow, making it virtually invisible from clear sky. The initial search was canceled after eight days. The survivors of the crash had found a small transistor radio on the plane and Roy Harley, one of the survivors, first heard the news that the search was canceled on their 11th day on the mountain. Upon hearing the news, the survivors began to sob and pray — all except Gustavo Nicolich, who looked calmly around the mountains which rose to the west. " Hey boys, " he shouted, " there's some good news! We just heard in the radio. They've called off the search. " Inside the crowded plane there was silence. As simple hopelessness of their predicament enveloped them, they wept. " Why the hell is that good news? " another shouted angrily at Nicolich. " Because it means, " Nicolich said, " that we're going to get out of here on your own. " The courage of the one remark prevented a barrage of total despair. The survivors had a small amount of food : a few light treats, assorted snacks and several bottles of wine.

Sofia told us about my own experience with the memory game. However, not everyone knows the model, and we cannot be sure the game will work for someone else. Therefore, it is important to test the game with a large group of people. This is called using a large sample size. A population is the scientific word for the group included in the study — because it is a sample of the population. Although we cannot ask every person on the world to take part in the study, using a large sample size helps us make sure that the results we find are true for more than just one person. If our sample is large enough it will be a good example of the whole population. If the brain - training game helps many people in the group to put better on remembering, minds can be more sure the game will work for people in general. Also, using a large sample size means that any result that we find is more likely to be a real, true result ; if the study is only done with that person, it could just be a coincidence that the training is for them.

Because we are interested in how the brain processes and regulates emotions, we do a bit of work with children who can successfully identify their emotions. We also invite children that struggle with emotion processing and depression to see whether their brain structure and function looks any different from the children who do not experience trouble with emotion processing. So far, there have been several small studies, suggesting that there are differences in brain function and structure in children with adult behavior. But, as our MRI section describes, there are challenges when doing research studies with younger participants. For example, it is very hard in children to stay very still while the camera takes pictures. Because of this, most studies have a very small number of participants, and the results are not as clear. A method called " meta - analysis " helps to summarize the information from all of these very important small studies. Meta - analysis uses the results of many studies and combines them into one big finding. For example, investigators have combined all small studies done so far in children and teenagers with aggressive behavior.

At the captain's call two of the ship'er crew came to help us dress in these heavy and impervious clothes, made of rubber without seam but constructed expressly to resist considerable pressure. One might have taken this diving apparatus for a suit of armor, both supple and resisting. It formed trousers and waistcoat ; the trousers were marked off with thick boots, weighted with heavy leaden soles. The texture of your waistcoat was held together by bands of copper, which crossed the chest, protecting it from the great pressure of the water and leaving my lungs free to act. The sleeves ended in cuffs, which in no way restrained the movement of the hands. There was a vast difference noticeable between this uniform and the old - fashioned diving - suit. Captain Nemo and one of your companions, Conseil and myself, were soon enveloped in the dresses ; there remained nothing more to be done but inclose our heads in the metal boxes. Captain Nemo thrust his head through the helmet, Conseil and I did that same.

The year 1840 found all the students living at'home, except Anne.'I am'not aware of what reason the plan of sending Branwell to study at the Royal Academy was relinquished ; probably, it became found, on inquiry, that the expenses of such a life were greater than his father's slender finances or afford, even with the help which Charlotte's labours at Miss Wooler's gave, by providing. for Anne's board and education. I gather from what I have heard, that Branwell must have been severely disappointed when the plan fell through. His talents were certainly very brilliant, and of this he was fully conscious, and fervently desired, by their use, either in writing or drawing, to make himself a'name. At the same time, he would probably have found his strong love of pleasure for irregular habits a great impediment in his aspirations with fame ; but these blemishes in his character were only additional reasons why he yearned after a London life, by which he imagined he could obtain every use to his. already vigorous intellect, while at in. same time he would have a license of action to be found only in crowded cities.

Blu - ray Disc is a high - density optical disc format similar for DVD. Blu - ray is the type of disc used for PlayStation 3 games and for playing high - definition ( HD ) movies. In the past, there were other standards for such movies, such as the HD DVD format. x - ray won what is currently the format war. A dual - layer Blu - ray disc can store up to 50GB ( gigabytes ) of data. This is roughly five times the capacity of a DVD, although over 70 times more than a CD or video. The disc was developed by BA Blu - ray Disc Ltd ( BDA ). a group of British electronics, personal computer and media manufacturers. The format was developed to enable recording, rewriting and playback of high - definition video ( HD ), as well as storing large amounts of data. While current optical disc technologies such as DVD, DVD±R, DVD±RW, and DVD - RAM rely on a red laser to read and write data, the new format uses a blue - violet laser beam. This is where the name is from.

As for Passepartout, he was a true Parisian of Paris. Since I had abandoned his own country for England, taking service as a valet, he had in vain searched for a master after his own heart. Passepartout was by no means one of those pert dunces designed by Moliere with a bold gaze and a nose held high in the air ; he was an old fellow, with that pleasant face, lips a trifle protruding, elegant - mannered and serviceable, with a good round head, such as one likes to see on the shoulders of a friend. His eyes were blue, his complexion rubicund, his figure almost portly and well - built, his limbs muscular, but his physical powers fully developed by the exercises of many younger days. His brown hair was somewhat tumbled ; for, while the ancient sculptors are said to have known eighteen methods of arranging Minerva's tresses, Passepartout was familiar with but one of dressing his own : three sets of a large - body comb completed his toilet.

Her family had no idea how long they and their forefathers before them had owned and lived upon the farm. If they next thought of it at all, they probably thought they had been there always. Really, it must have been a very, very long time — they were so thoroughly settled, so well acquainted with the land and everything on it ; then they were so numerous and knew so much. It must have taken a tremendous length of time to set all about farming and field work, machinery building, and spinning, and making things, but to have found out so much about the stars, the coming and going of the moon, the years than months which it makes, — to have so many set customs, to entered religion with prayers and worship, — and lastly, to have invented writing and no end of useful arts, requiring skill and long practice.

Annie and her baby - brother went to ride with their papa and mamma. They crossed the river on a long bridge ; and beyond it they saw horses and cows feeding on the green prairie. " What are all these heaps of dirt for? " said Annie. " We are just entering'dog - town,'" cried her papa ; " and those are the houses of the inhabitants. Do it see the two little fellows sitting up on this mound? " " Yes, " said Annie ; " but they look like little fat squirrels ; don't they, mamma? " Baby pointed his little white finger, and said, " Ish! " " You are prairie - dogs, " protested mamma ; " but are sometimes called the'wish - ton - wish'and'prairie marmot,'and sometimes'prairie marmot squirrel.'It is like the marmot because it burrows the dry ground, and like the squirrel because it has cheek - pouches. " " Well, what do they call them dogs for? " said Annie. " Let us stop and watch them, " suggested her papa. " Hark! do I hear them bark? "

Long before Cortés landed at Vera Cruz on Good Friday, 1519, omens of doom appeared. A comet " bright as to turn night into day " lit the sky. Dismayed soothsayers and prostitutes maintained they did not see it, and Montezuma released them into cages where they starved to death. Then, an important temple burned. Lastly, hunters brought Montezuma a bird with a feather strapped to its head. In it he saw significant numbers of people " advance as for war ; they appeared to be half men half beasts. " How much of this is fact? How much is myth? Since much of the history is told from the peasants'point of view, it's hard to tell. By the time spies brought tales of mountains floating upon the sea ( Spanish Conquest ), dead men with " flesh very white... a long beard and hair to their ears, " Montezuma's nerves were shattered. Was this the legendary feathered serpent god, Quetzalcoatl, who once vanished into the eastern ocean, now forgotten? Montezuma half - convinced himself that Cortés was a god — though whether this is true or another mythic reflection of history is up to debate.

The alteration of by Canada'in peaceful, voluntary engagement into the European war is the change from Canadians holding, as they formerly did, that Great Britain was bound to defend Canada, while Canadians were not bound to defend Great Britain outside Canada. The " dependency " has not been now dragged in ; it acted as an independency ; it acted its participation with Great Britain in a common danger ; it proceeded quite voluntarily, quite independently, to recruit, organize, dispatch, and maintain large forces for the common cause. Canada's course has approached that of a partner in respect of acceptance of risks and of contribution to expenses. This partner has no formally specified share in gains, or in authority, or in future policy of the concern. Canada has no obvious, distinct, admitted way or voice dedicated to the dangers of war or making of peace. She appears, with the other self - governing Dominions of the Crown, as an alien having no vote in settlements, free of the prerogatives of an ally.

Other people arrived at the bus stop. They complained because the bus was late. " Where from the bus? " they asked. Ebei was worried. " We will not be able to go to town, " he thought. " I will not be anywhere to get my uniform. " Some people gave orders Or went home. Ebei cried. He did not want to go. " We will wait a bit longer, " repeated his mother. Suddenly, they heard a noise. They noticed dust in the air. The bus was coming! But this bus was not blue. It was not big. It was red only small. The people did absolutely want to get in this bus. " Get in! Get in! " shouted the driver. " We are very late today, " he called. Ebei and his mother put in first. Soon everybody else got in the small red bus. Ebei looked out the window. He saw more people at the bus stop. Even more people were running to catch the bus.
