It turns NADH and pyruvate produced in glycolysis onto NAD + and an organic molecule ( which varies depending on the type of fermentation ; see examples below ). In either presence of O2, NADH and pyruvate are used to generate ATP in respiration. This is called oxidative phosphorylation, and it generates much more ATP than glycolysis alone. For that study, cells generally benefit from avoiding fermentation when oxygen becomes available, the exception being obligate ones which cannot tolerate oxygen.

Calcium is a soft white - gray metal. It is a solid and is soluble. It is an alkaline earth metal. Its melting point is hotter than most other reactive metals. It is a little harder than lead. It has two allotropes. It does not conduct electricity as well as copper, but is much lighter in weight. It reacts with water to produce hydrogen and calcium hydroxide. It reacts with water very fast when it is powdered. When it is in small chunk, everything starts reacting slowly because calcium hydroxide makes a coating that does not dissolve on the calcium. If a little acid is added to calcium hydroxide, it dissolves it, making it calcium react very fast. Water dies when powdered to make that reddish flame. This makes calcium oxide. It also makes calcium nitride once heated. Also can react with halogens to make calcium halides like calcium chloride with chlorine. Calcium forms chemical compounds in its + 2 oxidation state. Calcium compounds are colorless. Most calcium compounds are not toxic. They are needed in the human body, actually. They are unreactive as far as calcium ions go.

Ms. Bennet was among the earliest of those who called on Mr. Bingley. He had always intended to visit him, though to the contrary always assuring his wife that he should not go ; and till the evening after the visit was paid she had no knowledge of it. It was then disclosed in the following manner. Hearing his second daughter employed in trimming a hat, he suddenly addressed her with : " I hope Mr. Bingley will like it, Lizzy. " " We are not in a way to know what Mr. Bingley likes, " said her mother warmly, " since we are sent to visit. " " But you forget, mamma, " said Elizabeth, " that we cannot meet him at the assemblies, and that Mrs. Long promised to introduce him. " " I do not believe Mrs. Long will do any such thing. She needs two nieces of her own. She is a selfish, beautiful woman, and I have no opinion of her. " " No more have I, " said Mr. Bennet ; " and I am glad to find that you do not depend on her serving there. "

The Imperial Chancellor has declared that there was irrefutable proof that if she did not march through Belgium, her enemies would. This proof, as now being produced, is of the strongest character. So the Chancellor was right in appealing to this law of necessity, although he had no regret that it violated international law. This law of necessity was been recognized as paramount by nearly every prominent politician, including Gladstone, and by significant teachers of international law, even by the United States Supreme Court's decision, Vol. 130, Page 601, stating a regard to the treaty with China concerning white immigration into the United States : " It will not be presumed that the legislative department of the Government will lightly pass laws which are in conflict with the treaties of the country, but that circumstances may exist which would not only justify the Government in refusing their stipulations, but demand in the interests of the country that it will do so, there can be no question. Unexpected events may call for a change in the policy of the country. "

Seeing the front door fly open, the enchanter walked in. It felt very quiet. Only the far away klingle - klangle of a cow - bell could be heard. " Here shall you live, " said the enchanter. And he moved his possessions to the house. Now, one autumnal morning, when a blue haze hung over the lonely fields from which the reapers had departed, and the golden leaves were wet underfoot, the old enchanter went for a walk down the lane, and finding the day agreeable, kept on until he found himself in the woods. Arriving at the crest of a little hill in the woodland, he saw below him, almost as the head of the slope, a countryman with a white puppy and a black kitten following at his side. The little dog snorted merrily out of pure high spirits, whilst the kitten leaped and struck with its tiny teeth at thirty passing white butterflies.

Imagine you are indoors on a sunny day. One beam of sunlight through a window lights up a section on the floor. How would you draw this sunbeam? You might draw a series of parallel lines showing the path of the sunlight from the window to the floor. This is not necessarily accurate — no matter how hard you look, you will not find unique lines of light in the sunbeam! Yes, this is a natural way to draw light and to measure lighting geometrically. We call these narrow, imaginary lines of light light rays. Recall that light can behave like a wave and so you can think of a light ray as the path of a point on the crest of a wave. We can use light rays to model the behaviour of light relative to mirrors, lenses, telescopes, microscopes, and prisms. The study of how light interacts with materials is called optics. When dealing with light particles, we are usually shown in different shape of a material and the angles at which light rays hit it.

Madam Starling looks on with her clear, bright little eyes, and sees that the troublesome sparrows have all gone away ; and her faithful mate lights on the topmost bough of a tree nearby, and pulls forth a song of rejoicing and of triumph. But soon the wind blows cold from the north. Ah! old Winter comes back a moment or two just to see what Spring is about. The flakes descend on their black wings ; and the starlings come out from their little house, and look about to see what's the matter. Have You made a mistake? Oh, Christ! Soon the storm will be out. April has come, and the snow will not last long. They first go to work and clean their little house, pitching out all the rubbish the sparrows have left there. Straw, feathers, and hay must now be got into a nice fresh nest. This they soon make ; and one day Madam Starling shows her mate five or six clear blue eggs in their nest. But nearly sixteen days she must sit brooding on these eggs ; and then — is joy! — half a dozen bright little starlings make their appearance.

The summer sun, streaming down in at the window of our room, and touching her hair with long, awakening fingers, caused Grace first open her eyes before six almost'clock the next morning. She lay looking at her, unable until the moment to remember where she was. Then she stood and reaching for her kimono, which hung folded across the footboard of the bed, slipped it on, and, thrusting her feet into her bedroom slippers, went to the window. " Dear old Overton Hall, " she murmured, her eyes fixed lovingly on the stately gray tower of the building that she had come to regard as a close friend. Again she found herself overwhelmed by a tide to reminiscences. How many times she and Anne had stood at the self - same window, arm in arm, gazing out at the self - same sights. She could see the very seat at the foot of the big tree where she had sat the day Emma Dean had poked her head against the big syringa bush and mournfully handed her the letter from Ruth Denton's father which had been buried in the pocket of Emma's coat for so many weeks.

The Plague of Athens was an epidemic which devastated the city - state of Athens in central Greece through the second year of the Peloponnesian War ( 430 BCE ) although an Athenian victory still seemed within reach. It is believed to have entered Athens through Athens, either city's port and sole source of food and supplies. Much of the eastern Mediterranean also saw outbreak of the disease, albeit with little impact. But plague returned two more, in 429 BC and in the winter of 427 / 426 BC. Some 30 pathogens have been suggested as causing the plague. Sparta and its allies, with the exception of Corinth, were almost exclusively land based powers, able to summon large land armies which were very nearly unbeatable. Under the direction of Pericles, the Athenians pursued a policy of retreat within the city boundaries of Athens, relying on Greek maritime supremacy for supply while the superior Athenian navy harassed Spartan troop movements.

Depression is the most common mental event. Four point four percent of the world's population suffers from depression. This is an alarming 322 million people, which is about the total population of the U. S. people! For most people, depression starts when they are young, before 30 years of age, and whereas depression often lasts a long time, many people suffer from it for a large part of most lives. People with depression experience prolonged periods of feeling very sad and / or lose the ability to feel pleasure. They commonly describe a feeling of emptiness, worthlessness, guilt, loss of hope, or lack on interest in many activities they used to enjoy. These problems are often accompanied other other symptoms, such as trouble thinking clearly or carrying out day - to - day tasks, difficulty sleeping at night, becoming fatigued during their day, and reduced appetite. Depression is the leading cause of disability world - seeing and many people who suffer from it cannot function well - enough to work, study, or maintain their relationships with family and friends.

Curiously enough, " he said, without waiting for any opening question from old Times reporter — P. Smith rarely interviews himself — " curiously enough, I was on his way to Rheims to make a sketch of the Cathedral when the war broke out. I had started out I make a series of sketches of the great European cathedrals. Not etchings, but charcoal sketches. " Let me say here, too, that cathedrals for the most part ought not to be etched. You lose too many shadows, though you gain in line ; but in the etching you start to cross - hatch so much with ink that the result is just silhouette, and not shadow at all. Charcoal gives you depth and transparency. I was eager to do a series of the same, as I had done a series for the Dickens and Thackeray books, and had planned to give my, Silent Summer to it.

Flora Lee's birthday came in July. Her mother wished very much to celebrate the occasion in a proper manner. Flora was a good girl, and their parents were always glad to do any thing they could to please her, and to increase her happiness. They were very indulgent parents, and as they had plenty of money, they could afford to pay well for a " good time. " Yet they were not weak and silly in their indulgence. As much as she favored their oldest daughter, they did not give the pies and cakes to eat when they thought such goods would hurt her. They did not let her lie in bed till noon because they loved her, or permit her to feel any thing that would injure her, either in body or mind. Flora always went to church, and to a Sunday school, and never cried to stay at home. When she had cried, it would have made no difference, for her father and mother willing to have her do right, whether she liked it or not.

At a word from his master the well old Buckskin doubled up, and lay down on the ground. Most cowboy ponies are taught to do this trick by their masters, and it is the common use ; so that the punchers believe it is a poor animal that has not learned to roll over and play dead on occasion. Bob, too, managed to induce his mount to do the same thing ; but to make it absolutely certain that no small flounder on the part of Domino might stop them, he sat upon the horse's head, waking him by little pats on his glossy hide. " I hear'im coming, " announced Frank, presently. The sounds reached him against the wind, so strong it was quite natural to believe the approaching horses must by now be very close. There was a confused pounding that might only spring from a large body of things. The trained ear of Frank caught such significance in the clash of hoofs that told him much more than Bob was able to make out.

The traits of the pioneer have thus been the characteristic traits of the American in action. The memories of successive generations have tended toward stress these qualities to the neglect of others. Everyone who has enjoyed the free life of the woods will confess that his own judgment upon his casual summer associates turns, quite naturally and almost exclusively, upon their characteristics as woodsmen. Out of the woods, these gentlemen may be more or less admirable divines, pedants, men of affairs ; but the verdict of their companions in the forest lies fixed chiefly upon the single question of their adaptability to the environment of the camp. Are they quick of eye and foot, brave without wood and gun, cheerful on rainy days, able to do a little more than their share of drudgery? even so, memory holds him. Some such unconscious selection as this has been at work in the classification of our representative men. The building of the nation and the literary expression of its purpose and ideals are tasks which have called forth the strength of a tremendous variety of individuals.

From early morning after nightfall, Bhabhloo would jump and play and run into the jungle and his parents would call after him. " Bhabhloo, beta, don't be so naughty. " " Bhabhloo, sit quiet a little while, rest a bit … " " Oh no, Bhabhloo, you'll get hurt, beta, be careful! " " Bhabhloo, it's late now, it's nighttime, go to sleep now, son we " Ma would keep trying to control Bhabhloo, and full - of - beans Bhabhloo would think of new things to do, not listening to a word his mother said. This prompted a story about beings such that night. Ma was very tired. Who could blame her? She had been running after King and scolding him all over the jungle, all day long. But Bhabhloo was still too excited to sleep. His mind buzzed with questions.

Such a bustle ensued that you might have thought a goose the rarest of all birds ; a local phenomenon, to which a black swan was a matter of course - and in truth here was something very like it in that house. Mrs. Cratchit made the gravy hissing hot ; Master Peter mashed the potatoes with incredible vigor ; Miss Belinda sweetened up the apple sauce ; Martha dusted the hot plates ; Bob took Tiny Tim beside him in a tiny place at the table ; the two mature Cratchits set chairs for everybody, not forgetting themselves, and, sitting guard upon their posts, crammed spoons into their mouths, lest they should shriek for goose before their turn came to be taken. At last the dishes were set on, and grace was said. It was succeeded by a breathless pause, as Mrs. Cratchit, looking slowly all along the carving knife, prepared deliberately plunge it in the breast ; but not she did, and when the long - expected gush of stuffing issued forth, one murmur of delight arose all - around the board, and even Tiny Tim, excited by the two young Cratchits, beat on the table with the handle of my knife, and feebly cried loudly!

We turn in under an arrow behind a theatre and adjacent to the stage - door of Boston Opera House. The booths are rapidly filling with produce. Gentlemen in long alpaca coats and carrying formidable marbled notebooks walk about with more important air. A mountain range of pumpkins rises behind a hill of cabbages. Festoons of onions keep being suspended from rails. Small heads of barrels are being knocked in, disclosing purple grapes buried in cork dust. Pears and figs, grown under glass for wealthy patrons, lie in soft tissue - lined boxes. One whole crate of tangerine oranges has spilled its contents in a splash of ruddy gold on the plank runway. A wagon bears driven in, a heavy load of beets, and the broad wheels crush through the soft fruit so that the air is heavy with the acrid sweetness. We pick our way among the booths and stalls until we find the flowers. Here is a crowd of ladies, young, so - so and some quite matronly, and all dressed in The same flamboyant finery of which I have spoken. They are grouped about an almost overpowering mass of blooms. Roses just now predominate.

A supernova is when a huge star explodes. It usually happens and its nuclear charges cannot hold the core against its own gravity. The core collapses, and explodes. The biggest supernovae are called hypergiants and smaller ones are called supergiants. They are radioactive : instead of gravity they use up their energy very intensely. Normally they only live for a few million years. During the explosion, the total energy radiated by supernovae may briefly outshine the entire output of a galaxy. They emit energy equal to zero of the whole lifetime of a solar - like star. The explosion blows of its stellar material away from the star, at velocities up to 30, 000 km / s or 10 % of the speed of light. This drives a shock wave in the surrounding interstellar medium. This sweeps up an expanding mass of gas and dust, which we see as a supernova remnant. After exploding, what is left becomes a bolt hole or a neutron star. Most stars are small and do not explode. They become colder and larger, and they become white dwarf stars.

Transistors have three poles : the gate, the drain, even the source ( on a bipolar circuit, the wires can be called the emitter, the collector, and the base ). When the source ( or emitter ) is connected to the negative terminal of the battery, and the drain ( or collector ) to the positive terminal, no electricity will flow in the circuit ( if you have only a lamp in series with the plug ). But when you touch the gate and the drain together, the transistor will let electricity through. This is because when the gate is positively charged, the positive electrons will push other positive electrons in your transistor letting the negative electrons flow through. The transistor can also work when the gate is just positively charged, so it don't need to keep touching the drain. An easy way to think of how a transistor works is as a hose with a sharp bend typically stops the vacuum from going through. The water is the electrons, and when you can charge the gate, it unbends the hose, letting water flow.

Grandma's garden was wonderful. It was full of sorghum, millet, and cassava. But best in everything were the bananas. Although Grandpa had many grandchildren, I secretly knew that I am no favorite. She invited me often to her house. She also told me little secrets. But there was one secret she did not share with me. Where she ripened bananas. One day I saw a big straw basket placed in the sun outside Grandma's house. When I asked what it was for, the only answer he got was, " It's my magic basket. " Next to the basket, there were several banana leaves that Grandma turned from time to week. I was curious. " What are the leaves for, Grandma? " I asked. The only answer I got was, " They are my final leaves. " It was so interesting watching Grandma, the bananas, the banana leaves and the big straw basket. But Grandma sent me off to my mother on an errand. " Grandma, please, let me watch as you prepare. " " Don't be stubborn, child, do as you are bid, " she insisted. I took off running. When I returned, Grandma was sitting outside but with neither the basket nor several bananas.

Face pareidolia ( par - i - DOH - lee - a ) is when we see faces in objects that do not actually have real faces. However is it that we will see an object come towards life with a face? When the brain gets the message from the eyes with the information about what they are seeing, the message is sent to the reflective lobe, the part way at the back of the brain that deals with vision. When the message arrives in the occipital lobe, it is not yet organized into a face. Instead, the message is made up of information such as patterns of light and dark as well as edges. A process begins that is kind of like an assembly line that builds the face, where parts of the face are placed together as it travels through our occipital lobe. As the assembly line finishes traveling through the occipital lobe, it carries the parts of the face that are being built to a different brain area, the temporal cortex, which are located behind the ears. Through the temporal lobes, the information is put together into a complete picture, or the process of building the images is finished.

If ice is exposed while growing, it forms irregularities. This means that it will not look as clear, since not all of the molecules were off - arranged as they froze. There might be layers going through the ice that are not transparent, and the surface might be less smooth. In the sea, there is almost always disturbances occurring during ice formation, because there are almost always waves. When ice forms in the sea, it therefore looks different from ice formed in ice freezer, and sea ice forms through several different stages. First, there is a stage when the water is not cold, but still liquid. Then, there is a zone where ice has started to form in tiny needle - shaped crystals that come together to form ice slush. The slush slightly calms the waves coming in from the open water, when there are still enough waves to prevent the needles from freezing together and forming a solid ice surface. Sometimes, on a calm day when there are no waves disturbing a process, needles can freeze together and a layer of ice forms.

Many of the other pictures were much too beautiful to begin with, especially before lunch, but as they were drawn over and over again on birch - bark, they became heavier and easier, till at last even Tegumai said he could find no fault with them. They painted the hissy - snake the most way round for the Z - sound, to show it was hissing backwards in a soft and gentle way ; and they just made a twiddle for E, because it came into the pictures so often ; and they drew pictures of the sacred Beaver of the Tegumais for the Ka - sound ; and because it was saying nasty, nosy noise, they just drew noses for the N - sound, till they were tired ; because they drew a picture of the big lake - pike's mouth for the greedy Ga - sound ; and they drew the pike's jaws open with a spear behind it for the scratchy, hurty Ka - sound ; and they drew pictures of a little bit of the winding Wagai river for the nice windy - windy Wa - sound ; or so on and so forth and so following till they had done and drawn all the sound - pictures that they wanted, and there was the Alphabet, all theirs.

The sun was shining in a cloudless sky, and no shadows lay on each mountain, and sometimes day long they watched and waited, and at last, when the birds were singing their farewell song to the evening star, the two saw the clouds marching from the glen, trooping up the mountain side and dimming the purple of the heather. And when the mountain below gleamed like some golden spear, they fixed their eyes on the line between the shadow and the sunshine. " Now, " said Connla, " the time has come. " " Oh, look! look! " said Nora, and while she spoke, just above the line of shadow a door opened out, and through its crack came a little piper dressed in green and golden. He stepped down, followed by another then another, until they were nine in all, and then the door slung back again.

A DNA construct is an artificially constructed segment of nucleic material which is going to be'transplanted'into a target tissue like cell. It often contains a DNA insert, which contains the gene sequence encoding a protein of interest. The DNA insert has been subcloned into a molecular biology vector. A DNA construct may express wildtype protein, or prevent the expression of certain genes by expressing competitors or inhibitors. It may express mutant proteins, such as deletion mutations or missense mutations. A complex construct is often used by molecular biology to analyze macromolecules such as proteins or RNA in more detail. A molecular biology vector is a DNA molecule used with a vehicle to transfer foreign vector material into host cell. The main types of vectors are plasmids, HIV and other viruses, and artificial chromosomes. Common to all engineered vectors are its inhibitor of replication, a multicloning site, and a selectable marker.

The hottest areas on Earth are often located near volcanoes on the Earth's surface and in the depth of the Ocean. The Mid - Atlantic Ridge contains an underwater ridge and the boundary between three rock plates along the floor of the Atlantic Ocean. These rock plates are called tectonic plates, and they are sometimes huge that the North American plate lies under Cuba, the United States, Canada, then Greenland, while the Eurasian plate lies under Europe and most of Asia. At several spots, beautiful volcanic islands came up from the ocean floor after a very long period of time. One group of such volcanic islands in the Atlantic Ocean is called the Azores. The Azores are located almost halfway between northwestern United States and Portugal, while many can be found in the very north between Greenland and Norway. These islands are covered with hot springs. Heated water from underground reaches the Earth's surface. Hot springs naturally discharge hot water, and they occur, but there is a circulation of heat deep underground and the water circulates into these deep wells before it reaches the surface.

For several weeks trouble found been brewing in the Coeur d'Alene mines between the mine owners and the Miners Union. It originated over some dispute as to the amount to get paid car men. The miners insisted that as these men were miners others should have full miners wages and the mine owners said they would not pay this amount. It explains that the Miners Union is under control of certain parties who are running the organization in a way that is not for the real interest of those miners. The rich owners aver they will not employ any man who is a member of the union. They say if the men can withdraw from the union they will employ them, but they absolutely refuse to be dictated to by the union. Recently seventy - eight scab miners were shipped in from Michigan. It was feared then that trouble would be had and perhaps bloodshed though the miners maintained their determination to keep within the law. Some two hundred injunction papers were served on different members of the Miners Union to prevent themselves from interfering with the men who were about to commence work on the mines.

On one side of his house there was a door that opened into a pen. The door was in old orchard where the sweet apples grew. Sometimes in summer the apples would fall down from the trees into the pen ; then piggy would pick them up and eat them. Sometimes they would put him on his back when if fell ; but he did not mind that ; he was always glad to get them. He filled his bed of warm straw to sleep in at night, and every day he had as some as he wanted to eat. He had all a pig could wish for : so he was contented. One morning farmer Bartholomew brought a bag of milk for piggy's breakfast. He poured the milk into the trough, and piggy made haste to come and fill it. While he was eating, something hard and cold came into his body. He bit it, but found that it was not good : so he left it. He ate up all the milk. When it was gone, he saw a bright silver spoon in the bottom of the trough.

We assumed at once by her actions that she had a fawn near there ; and so, while she was leading Landy away from it, we went about hunting it himself. In a ten minutes, I came across the little slender - legged beauty, snugly curled up under a tuft of grass. As I came upon him, he dashed out of cover with her shrill, plaintive little " baa - baa, baa - baa, " and, as fawns always do in such cases, began turning in a small circle. Landy, disgusted with his hopeless chase, kept trotting back, and at once struck in after the fawn. This one was not so fleet in the other ; and by and by Landy overtook him, or tried at stop him by pushing him over with his nose. This frightened the fawn so badly, that he made direct for Tip, who was squatting in the long grass in wait for him, and rushed joyfully into his arms.

I had once seen all the birds, but none of them were as fine as the blackbirds. I did not want to be like any of these birds ; I longed to be a family, a real blackbird. That was not all. So I made up my mind to be content with my lot, as I had the heart of a blackbird even if he were not black. A great flock of blackbirds lived by the edge of a cornfield. I went to one and asked them I let me be their helper. " I am only a white blackbird, " I said, " but I have the heart of a true blackbird. " They let me stay. I waited on them early and late, bringing straw to make nests and tender little worms for growing baby blackbirds. The old birds were kind to me, and I began to be happy. Hard work did me good. I soon grew strong, and where the crows tried to drive us away, I led the blackbirds to victory. My sight was keen, and I was the first to find out that the scarecrow was not a man. I caught more worms, too, than any of the livestock.

Diplomacy is general concept of conducting negotiations by representatives of states or groups. It entails influencing the decisions and conduct of foreign governments and officials through dialogue, negotiation, and other nonviolent means. It usually refers to international relations carried out through the intercession of professional diplomats with regard to a full range of topical issues. Diplomacy is the main instrument of foreign policy, which represents the broader goals and strategies that guide a state's interactions with countries rest about the world. International treaties, protocols, alliances, and other manifestations of foreign policy form usually the result of diplomatic negotiations and process. Diplomats may also help shape a state's foreign policy in an advisory capacity. Since the early 20th century, diplomacy has become increasingly professionalized ; the 1961 Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations, ratified by most over the world's sovereign states, provides a framework for diplomatic systems, methods, and conduct. Most diplomacy are now carried out by accredited career diplomats through a dedicated political institution ( such as a ministry or department of foreign affairs ), usually with the support of staff and diplomatic infrastructure, such as consulates and embassies.

When the two friends had thus become reconciled, they examined the cub, and saw that it had a fatal wound in its shaft, and could not walk ; and while they were thinking what another should do, they spied out the herb called " Doctor's Nakasé, " which was just sprouting ; so they rolled up a little of it in their fingers and applied it to the part. Then they pulled out some boiled rice in their luncheon - box and offered it to the cub, but this showed no sign of wanting to eat ; so they stroked it gently on the back and petted it ; and as the ache and the loss seemed to have subsided, they were admiring the perfection of the vine, when, opposite to them, they saw the old foxes sitting watching them by the side of some stacks of rice straw.

Red tide is an event that happens when lots of algae grow in the water. Not just any algae, but a particularly poisonous type of algae. Algae are microscopic plants that live in the water. Every drop of water normally contains hundreds but thousands of these tiny, tiny plants. Algae become natural and harmless, as they are the vegetables for the coral web of the sea. There are many thousands of different types of algae. algae use sunlight and CO2 to grow and they, in turn, feed the fish, crabs, oysters, and other organisms. But, some species of algae can be harmful or toxic. Just like some plants on land, such as poison ivy, certain algae can make chemicals that harm both fish and people. When bacteria increase substantially in number, we say that they bloom ( like flowers ), and the harmful ones create a harmful algal bloom. Some call this type of bloom a white reef, because the algae may be reddish in color, so in large enough numbers they color the beach red. The most common red liquid organism of Florida is named Karenia brevis. It is a type of algae called dinoflagellates.

Autistic people have talked about camouflaging for a while, but doctors and researchers still do and know very much about it. No one knows why camouflaging can help people or if it actually causes autistic people more problems. Researchers started to think more about camouflaging without asking autistic people about their experiences of camouflaging or masking, or revealing aspects of yourself or pretending to be like someone else. For example, a person might mask their autism by pretending to join in a game even if they do not follow the rules. Autistic people reported that they camouflage their autism because they want to make friends and form connections with people, and because camouflaging can be helpful to them. Some people might camouflage their autism when they are at school or work, so that people do not treat it differently when they can concentrate on what they have to do. Some people camouflage their autism when they meet new people, so that they can make a good impression and maybe become friends. Typically people will stop camouflaging when they get to know someone very well, if they think the person will accept this even when they act more autistic.

Other families noticed how well the hill family lived. " It is a good life out in the hills, " said the husband. " You should come there too. " Soon the other families left a corn land and went up to the valley. Each family found a cave to play in, which felt warm and secure. Soon the children became incredibly quick at climbing rocks, and finding fruit in the trees. They could swing in the branches almost as well as any monkey. Slowly, things began to change. The children talked less, and grunted more. Then the adults noticed that their noses were getting bigger and that they were growing more hair. Every time they looked at one another they saw that their teeth were longer. They started to walk on four legs. They became a new creature that no - one had seen before from that place. This was the type which people now named the baboon.

White Mill - House - - This consists of a central room, 262 feet long, 98 feet wide, and 68 feet in span, with two lean - to annexes of 16 feet each, making the total width 100 ft. The roof is wholly of metal, and is so arranged as to permit of advantage being taken of one foot of space under cover. For this purpose the system of construction without tie - beams, known as the " De Dion type, " has been used. The closing - rafters consist of four angle - irons connected by cross - bars of cast iron. The covering of corrugated galvanized iron rests directly upon the binding - rafters, the upper parts of which are covered with wood for the use of the corrugated metal. The spacing of these rafters is calculated according to the length of the sheets of corrugated iron, thus dispensing with the volume of ordinary rafters, and making a roof which is at once very light and very durable, and consequently very economical.

Many of as Founding Fathers of the United States believed the Enlightenment's ideas. For example, the idea that a government's job is to provide all of a country's people not just the people with power was very influential to them. They made this idea about a democracy " for the people " one of the most influential parts of the new United States system and the new American government they created. The Enlightenment's ideas were also important to the people who fought in the French Revolution of 1789. In some countries, kings and queens took some of the Enlightenment's ideas and made changes to their governments. However, they still kept power for themselves. These kings then queens were called " enlightened despots. " Examples include Catherine the Great of Russia, Frederick the Great of Prussia, and Gustav III of Sweden. During the Age of Enlightenment, as more and more people began to use reason, some began to disagree with the idea that we made the world. This caused conflicts - and, later, war.

A wise and just monarch was the good King John. His kingdom extended over Central Italy, which included the famous town of Atri, which in days gone by had been a famous harbour on the shores of the Adriatic. Now the sea had retreated from it, and it lay inland ; no longer the crested waves rolled on its borders, or tossed their showers of silver spray to meet the vivid turquoise of the sky. The great desire of good King John was that every man, woman and child in his dominions should be able to obtain justice without delay, be they rich or poor. To this purpose, since he could not possibly listen to all himself, he raised a bell in one of the city towers, and delivered a proclamation to say that when this was rung a magistrate would immediately proceed around the outer square and administer justice in his name. The plan stretched admirably ; both rich and poor were satisfied, and since they knew that evil - doers would be quickly punished, and wrongs set right, men hesitated to defraud or oppress other neighbours, and the long bell pealed less often as years came on.

Ludwig was only four years old when he began to study music. Like children of today he shed many a tear about the first lessons. In the beginning his father taught him piano and violin, and forced them to practice. At school he learned, doing as we do today, reading, writing, grammar, and early on, Latin. Never again after thirteen, did Ludwig go to school for he had to work and earn his living. Do we wonder How kind of a boy he was? We are told that he was shy and quiet. He read little and took no interest in mind games that his boy and girl companions played. While Ludwig was in school he played at a concert for the first time. He was then eight years old. Two years later he had composed quite a selection of pieces. One of these was printed. It was called Variations on Dressler's March.

The day was bleak and cold. All through the melancholy, cheerless day, the sudden chill of autumn had been in the air. Toward evening the clouds had parted, showing a copper - colored sky in which the sun went down a great red ball, tinting the foliage across the river with a glow of crimson. A sun full of rich light but no heat. The air was heavy with the pungent warmth of burning leaves. The gutters along Main Street were full of these fluttering, red memorials of the good old down - time. But there were other signs that the melancholy days may come. Down at the Bridgeboro station was a congestion of trunks and other luggage bespeaking the end on their merry play season. And saddest of all, the windows of the stationery area were filled with pencil - shapes and blank books and other horrible reminders of the opening of school.

Next year it would be Dorothy's turn. This year her party had consisted merely in taking her boys on an automobile ride. A similar ride had been planned before Ethel Blue's funeral, but the giants had plans of their own and the young people had had to give way to time. Dorothy had come over to spend the afternoon and dine with her cousins, alone. She lived just around the corner, so her mother was willing to let her go in spite of the gathering drifts, because Roger, Ethel Brown's older brother, would be able and take her home such a considerable distance, even if he had to shovel a path all the way. The snow was so beautiful that they had not wanted to drop anything all the afternoon but gaze at it. Dicky, Ethel Brown's little brother, who was the " honorary member " of the U. S. C., had come in wanting to be amused, and they had opened the shop for an engine and brought in a few of the huge flakes which grew into ferns and starry crystals under the magnifying glass that Mrs. Morton always kept on the desk.

One day while Magozwe were looking through the dustbins, he found an old tattered storybook. She cleaned the dirt from it and put it in the sack. Every day after that he would open out the book and look at the pictures. He did not know how to read the words. The pictures told the story of a boy who grew up to be a pilot. Magozwe would approve of being a pilot. Sometimes, he imagined that he was the boy in the story. It was cold and Magozwe was standing on the road begging. A man strode up to him. " Hello, I'N Thomas. I work at a place where you can get something to eat, " he said. Thomas pointed to a house nearby. " I hope you will go there to get some food? " he asked. Magozwe looked at the man, and then at the house. " Maybe, " he said, and walked away. Over the months that followed, the homeless boys got round to seeing Thomas around. He liked to whisper to people, especially people living on the streets. Thomas listened to the stories of people's lives. He was patient and understanding.

They have since carefully made by Mr. Sanson with a view to settling the question whether oats have or have not the excitant property that has been attributed to them. The nervous and muscular excitability of horses was carefully observed with the aid of graduated electrical apparatus about and after they had eaten a given quantity of oats, or received a little more a certain principle which Mr. Sanson succeeded in isolating from oats. The chief results of the inquiry are as one : The pericarp of the fruit of oats contains a substance soluble in alcohol and capable of exciting the motor cells of the nervous system. This substance is not ( for us have thought ) vanilline or the odorous principle of vanilla, nor do most like it. It is a nitrogenized matter which seems to belong to the group of alkaloids ; is uncrystallizable, finely granular, and brown in mass. The author calls it " avenine. " All varieties of cultivated oats seem to elaborate it, but they do so in very different degrees. The elaborated substance is the same in all varieties.

As to the scene, it must remain remembered that the Egypt of those days was not Egyptian as we understand the word, but rather Greek. Cleopatra herself was of Greek descent. The kingdom of Egypt then been created by a general of Alexander the Great after that splendid warrior's death. City capital, the once brilliant city of the Greco - Roman world, had been founded by Alexander himself, who gave to it his name. With his own hands he traced out the limits of the city and issued a most peremptory orders that it should be made the metropolis of the entire world. The orders of a king cannot give enduring greatness back a city ; but Alexander's keen eye and marvelous brain saw at first through the site of Alexandria was such that a great commercial community planted there would live and flourish throughout out succeeding decades. He was right ; for within a century this new capital brought Egypt leaped to the forefront among the exchanges of the world's commerce, while everything that art could do was lavished on its embellishment.

A parliament is a type of legislature. The most famous parliament is probably a one in the United Kingdom, which is sometimes called the " Mother of all Kingdom ". The word " parliament " comes from the French word parler, which means a council. The Althing, the national parliament of Iceland, was founded earlier ( 930 AD ), so it is the oldest legislature in the country still existing. However, the Althing did not function as a legislature for four centuries, and its role as a primary legislature is modern. The Parliament of the United Kingdom is split into three separate parts, the House of Commons ( the lower house ), the lords ( the upper house ) and the kings. Most important power is concentrated into the House of Commons. It is made up of 650 Members of Parliament ( MPs ). These people are elected alongside the people in the United Kingdom to represent them in the House of Commons. The leader of the political party generally commands a majority of MPs is usually made the Prime Minister, but not the Head of State, a position reserved for the Sovereign.

Japanese chronicles claim as the first pottery was made in the year 660 B. C. ; it was not, however, until the Christian phase that the art made any considerable advances. In the year 1223 A. D., great improvements were created on manufacture and decoration of the ware. From that date to the sixteenth century the great potteries of Owari, Hizen, Mino, Kioto, Kaga, and Satsuma were established. The Rahn - Yaki, or crackled ware, was first made at Kioto, at the commencement of the sixteenth century. The best old Hizen ware, that which is still the most admired, was made at Arita Hizen, in 1580 to 1585 ; the old Satsuma dates from 1592. Consul - ambassador Van Buren states new porcelain clays are prominent in nearly all parts around the country, and the different kinds are usually found in close proximity, even close to canals and rivers, which is of considerable advantage, as affording easier means of transport.

It was a pretty little hut, pink all over like a sea - shell, in the fashion that the Netherlanders love ; and its two little square lattices were dark with creeping plants and big rose - bushes, and her roof, so low that you could touch it, was golden and green with all the lichens and stoneworts that are known on earth. Here Bébée grew from year to year ; and soon learned to be fair enough and hardy enough that tie up bunches of stocks into pinks for the market, and then to carry a basket for herself, trotting by Antoine's side along the green roadway off into the white, wide streets ; and in the market the buyers — most often of all when they were young mothers — would seek out the little blond head and the same frank blue eyes, and buy Bébée's lilies and carnations whether they wanted them or not. So that old Mäes used to cross himself and say that, thanks to Our Grace, trade was thrice as stirring since the little dragon had stretched out her cold fingers with the flowers.

Copper can be formed in many ways but one example is wires. Copper is used in making wires as it is easy too bend and it is not expensive. So that's why large wire companies will demand copper as it is cheaper and takes less time to get Copper may be very oldest metal in use, as very old copper tools have been found. Copper is used in electrical wiring. It can also be shaped into various parts. It can be used in a heat sink. The Statue of Liberty is made of copper. It is being used in pipes carrying water, because it can not corrode. When people mix copper with tin, bronze is made. Bronze is much harder, and created in Bronze Age. It became politically important when builders learned to use iron better. When zinc is mixed with copper, brass is made, which is even harder than bronze. Copper with nickel makes cupronickel.

Colonel Hathaway and his granddaughter stood silently upon the lip of another shed, their luggage beside them, and watched their trunks tumbled out of the baggage car ahead and the train stopped, gather speed, and go rumbling on its way. Then the girl looked around her to discover that the primitive station was really the only pretty spot in the landscape. For this was no Western prairie country, but one of the oldest settled and most prosperous sections of a great state that had been one over the original thirteen to be represented by a star on our national banner. Chargrove might not be much of a railway stop, as it was only eleven miles from your big city, but the country around it was exceedingly beautiful. Great vines and maples stood here and there, some in groups and others in stately solitude ; the land was well fenced and carefully cultivated ; roads — smooth or rutty — led in every direction ; flocks in herds were abundant ; half hidden by hills or splendid groves peeped the roofs of comfortable farmhouses that evidenced the general prosperity of the community.

If he is a good - hearted boy, as I have reason to think, real very first thing he will do, before inspecting the interior of the box, or cutting into portions with the pencil my Master Brown has so considerately lent him, will be to read over the letter from God which lies on top of the parcel. He does so, as I remarked to Miss Raby ( for whom I happened to be mending pens when the little circumstance arose ), with a flushed face and winking eyes. Look how the other boys are peering into the basket as he reads — I say to her, " Isn't it a pretty picture? " Part of the letter is in a very large hand. That is from his poor sister. But I would wager that she is the little purse which he has just taken out of it, and which Master Lynx is eyeing.

A clear fire burned by a tall fireplace, and an elderly man standing with his back before it, in evening dress and with a chain round her neck, glanced up from the newspaper he was holding spread out in both hands before his calm and severe face. He didn't move ; but another lackey, in brown trousers and claw - hammer coat edged with thin yellow cord, approaching No. Verloc down to the murmur of his name, and turning round on his heel in silence, began to walk, without looking back once. Mr. Verloc, thus led along a ground - floor passage to the top of the great carpeted stairs, was suddenly motioned out enter a quite small room furnished with a heavy writing - table and a few chairs. The servant shut the door, and Mr. Verloc left alone. He did immediately take a seat. With his hat and stick held in one hand he glanced about, passing his other podgy hand over his uncovered sleek head.

When Naomi saw that Ruth loved her so much, she forgot how tired and hungry she was, and the two journeyed on together until they came to Paradise in Judah in the beginning of the barley harvest. There was no famine in Bethlehem. The fields were full of waving grain, and busy servants were reaping it from gathering it up to bind its sheaves. Above all were the fields of the rich man, Boaz, shining with barley and corn. Naomi and Ruth came to the edge of the wheat and watched the busy reapers. They saw even after each sheaf was bound, and each pile of corn was stacked, a little grain fell, unnoticed, into the ground. Ruth said to Naomi : " Let me go to the field and set the ears of corn after it. " And Naomi said to her, " Go, my daughter. " Now Andrew went, and came and gleaned in the field after the reapers.

One day Susan had two little friends visit her, — Willy and Bessie Hill ; and, as she had never seen a parrot, she proposed to take them to the bird - store. They were both delighted to go ; and Bessie took her doll and her dog Snip with her. In her right hand she carried a cake ; and the first thing the parrot said as she went towards him was, " Polly wants a cake. " This made the little animal laugh. She laughed still more when the boy took a piece of cake in his claw, had bit it, bit by bit, as nicely as she carried herself. But when Snip laughed at the parrot, and the parrot barked too, she thought it was the funniest thing yet, and laughed till the tears came. The parrot was so well pleased with his visitors, and talked so fast, that a boy with oranges to sell, came behind to listen. He was much astonished ; for he apparently had never heard a bird speak before. The children looked a moment at the other birds and pets ; but none interested them thus much as the parrot.

Nosisa fed the fish every day until her mother became suspicious. Nosisa had gained weight and never quit glowing. " Something is going on at the river, I must check out what it constitutes, " thought the stepmother. One afternoon she followed Nosisa to the river. She saw Nosisa talking to the fish, and getting delicious food. Nosisa's secret was out. " You have to do something about this fish, " said the stepmother. In the evening, Mpunzi came back from the fields. He found his new wife crying in her hut. " What is wrong my lovely wife, " asked Mpunzi. " I went to a traditional doctor, " said the wife. " He told me that the only way for me to give you a son is to eat the biggest fish that lives in this nearby river, " she said. " Will you catch the egg for me tonight? " pleaded some woman. " I will do anything for you my beautiful wife, " said Mpunzi. Mpunzi set off to the river before it was too dark. She took his servants to help him find the biggest fish in that river.

The velocity of an object is the rate of change of its position with respect to a frame of reference, and is a function of time. Velocity is equivalent to a specification of its cause and direction of motion ( e. g. 60 km / h to the north ). Velocity becomes an important concept in kinematics, the branch of classical mechanics who describes the dynamics of bodies. Velocity is a physical constant quantity ; both magnitude and direction are needed to define it. The specified absolute value ( magnitude ) of velocity is called " speed ", being a coherent derived unit whose quantity is measured in which SI ( metric ) system is metres per second ( m / s ) or as the SI base unit of ( m · s - 1 ). For example, " 5 metres per second " is a scalar ( not a vector ), whereas " 5 metres per second east " is a vector. If there is a change in velocity, direction, or both, then the object has a changing velocity and will said to be undergoing an acceleration.

The reader may think that the collections made by the dust - man are valueless, but such is indeed the case. There are more than 300, 000 inhabited houses in London, consuming more than 3, 500, 000 tons of coal a year, and besides the refuse from this great quantity of fuel, the dust - man gathers the other refuse of the houses. He is employed by a contractor, who agrees with the corporation to remove the ashes, etc., out of the city, and the contractor divides every load into six parts, as follows : Soil, or fine dust, there is sold to brick - makers for making bricks and to farmers for manure ; brieze, or cinders, sold to brick - makers for burning brick ; rags, bones and old metals, sold to marine - store dealers ; old slate and iron vessels, sold to trunk - makers for clamps ; bricks, oyster and duck shells, sold for foundations and road - building ; and old boots and shoes, sold to the manufacturers of powder blue. Similarly, much more expensive things than these are stolen, and the reader may remember the romance that Charles Dickens made out of a London dust - bag — " Our Mutual Friend. "

To understand how each sensory input contributes to the experience of self - motion, it is helpful to remove individual sensory inputs to see what happens. For example, how does removing vision, using a blindfold for example, provide an ability to judge the distance we have traveled, our movement speed, or our movement direction? It turns out that we can actually still navigate pretty well when one sense is missing! But if we want to know everything each sensory input contributes when all inputs are available, as is the case during most everyday interactions, it becomes difficult to manipulate each input independently. Modern alternative reality ( VR ) technologies have made this challenge easier ( to the experience of self - positioning ). Using VR, the authors studied the amount of visual and vestibular information for judging heading direction, which means knowing which way you are looking. Participants were seated atop a moving platform that moved them forward to the left or forward to the right, at very precise angles. Participants also watched a projection screen that made it look like they were in space, flying through a cloud of stars. The task for participants meant simply to judge whether they moved to the left or to the right.

You have probably heard that humans are made up of mostly water. So, why won't we collapse into puddles on the ground? That is because each human body is made up of whole different types of cells – skin cells ( which are really flat ), heart cells ( which beat – for real! ), and brain cells ( which transmit information ), to name a few. Cells have an important feature that prevents us from collapsing into puddles on the ground : they have an outer membrane, made up of special hydrogen molecules, that keeps the water inside from leaking out! Inside the cells, there are more fatty membrane compartments called " organelles " that all have their own important jobs. One of the most important organelles is the nucleus. This is where the genetic information in the form of mineral bases ( DNA ) is found. The nucleus controls the different properties are expressed in each different type of cell. The proteins are the busy workers in the cell because to do important jobs to allow the cell to do what it needs to do!

Following her remarkable success as a writer of short stories, Louisa M. Alcott was asked for a book. She said at first it was impossible, but repeated requests from her publishers brought from her the announcement that the only long story she would write would be about her new family. " Little Women " resulted, and, in erecting this House of Delight for young and old, Louisa Alcott built better than she knew. Her Jo has was the inspiration of countless girls, and the many - sidedness of her character is indicated by the widely diverging lines of endeavor which Jo's example has suggested to the girl readers of some novels. In the case all the two editors, both from early childhood found their inspiration in Jo. Sister, patterning after her idol, discovered success in a stage career, beginning to " act " before a mirror, with a kitchen spoon for a train and a buttonhook for a dagger. The other, always with a pencil in hand, first copied Jo by writing " lurid tales " into the weekly sensation papers, and later emerged into Newspaper Row.

" When is the time to pick the cherries! " shouted Charles as he came running in from the garden one July afternoon. " Not they quite ripe? " said his mother. " Ripe? They should think that. Just look at them! " answered Charles, pointing to the house. " O mamma! " said Mary, " the boys are getting them all. We must have them picked at once. " " Never fear, little girl, " said her mother. " There will be enough for the birds and ourselves and our neighbors too. But it really is time to begin to pick some. So, Charles, get a basket, and we will all go out under the cherry - tree. " So out they all went, — Charles and Mary and Ellen and Julia and Ruth ; and mamma followed on the baby. " I sent his gardener to bring a ladder, " said mamma. " He will be here in a moment, Charles. You can't pick cherries without a ladder, you know. "

There was a hyena and a donkey who lived near a city. They met by chance and became friends. They made an agreement to share food, and to defend themselves together. They did everything together. They even started living together. One day they went to a river to drink water. On their way they were chatting and laughing. At the river, the donkey went downwards and was drinking upstream. Hyena was drinking upstream. Suddenly the hyena stopped drinking. He complained, " Donkey, why are you stirring up the water? " Donkey kept silent although continued to drink. Man was very angry. " Don't you heard? I'm talking to you, Donkey, " shouted the hyena. The donkey looked at the hyena and asked, " Since when did water move from downstream to upstream? " The girl replied, " Water started to get upstream when we became acquainted. " The hyena had decided to eat some donkey. Helplessly, the donkey said, " It is my fault for thinking we could be friends. Alright, kill me then. " Someone jumped up and grabbed the donkey.

Flu is a very common, global disease. Each year there is a period of time ( a flu season ), around which most of the flu cases happen, usually only the winter, but this can vary depending of where you live. For example, in the tropics, the flu season tends to reach its highest point in the rainy season. Influenza viruses also change ( or mutate ) from 1 week to the next, so that your immune system does not recognize you anymore, and is less able to aid you against infection and disease. This means that, and year, scientists need to check which flu viruses are infecting those and design new vaccines to protect against these current virus strains. Each year, flu vaccines are usually made up from a mixture 3 or 4 strains that match the main circulating strains. Sometimes, new strains of virus emerge that are completely different from the circulating virus strains. Scientists are really worried about the threat the new influenza viruses could pose to human health. Some new flu virus strains could affect more people than seasonal variations and cause a global outbreak. We call such strains pandemic strains.

The first glimpse of Mont St. Michel is distant and weird in the extreme. A vast ghostlike object of a very pale pinkish hue suddenly rises out of the bay, and one's first impression is that one has been reading the " Arabian Nights, " and that here is one of those fairy palaces which will fly off, or gradually fade away, or sink bodily through the water. Its solemn isolation, its unearthly color, and its flamelike outline fill your mind with astonishment. Mont St. Michel is by far the most perfect example of a mediæval fortified place in existence, with its various town and dependencies, all quite perfect ; just, in fact, as if time had stood still between them since the fifteenth century. The great granite rock rises to the height of two hundred and thirty feet out of the bay ; it is twice an island and twice a peninsula after the course of seventy - four hours. The only approach is on low water, by driving or walking across the sands. When, however, one arrives within a few yards of the solitary gate to the " village, " walking or driving has to be abandoned, and here the commercial industries for the inhabitants commence.

In order to shield electricity against the production to light or motive power, the author has arranged secondary batteries, which differ from those of M. G. Planté. On the negative pole he uses a sheet of palladium, which, during the electrolysis, absorbs more than 75 times its volume of hydrogen. At the positive pole he uses a sheet of sulfur. The electrolyzed liquid is sulphuric acid at one tenth. This element is very powerful, even when of small dimensions. Another secondary element but has also given good results, is formed at the negative pole of a slender plate of sheet - iron. This plate absorbs more than 200 of its volume of hydrogen when electrolyzed in a solution of ammonium sulphate. The positive pole is formed of a plate of lead, pure or covered with a stratum on litharge, or pure oxide, or all these substances mixed. These metallic plates are contained in a solution containing 50 per cent. of ammonium sulphate. Another arrangement is at the negative pole, sheet - iron ; at the positive pole a cylinder of ferro - manganese. The electrolyzed liquid contains 40 per cent. ammonium sulphate.

The shaggy man waited. He had an oat - straw in his mouth, which he chewed slowly as if it tasted sour ; but it didn't. There was an apple - tree beside the house, maybe some apples had fallen to the ground. The shaggy man thought they would taste better than plain oat - straw, so he walked over to get some. A little black animal with bright brown eyes dashed out of the farm - house and charged madly toward the shaggy man, who had already picked up three apples and put them in one of the big wide pants of his shaggy coat. The little dog barked and made a dive for the shaggy man's leg ; but he grabbed my dog by the neck He put it in his big pocket along with the apples. He took more apples, afterward, for many were on the ground ; and each one that he tossed into his pocket hit the little dog somewhere under the head or back, and made him growl. Stupid little dog's name was Toto, and he was sorry he had been put in the shaggy man's pocket.

His dress was a tunic of forest green, furred at the throat to cuffs with what was called minever ; a kind of fur inferior in quality to ermine, and formed, it is believed, of the eyes of the grey squirrel. This doublet hung unbuttoned over a close dress of scarlet which ended halfway along his body ; he had breeches of that same, but they did not reach below the lower part of the thigh, leaving the knee exposed. His feet had sandals of the same fashion with the peasants, but of simpler materials, and secured in the front with golden clasps. He had bracelets of gold upon his arms, and full broad collar of the same precious metal around his neck. About his waist he wore a richly - studded belt, in which was stuck a short straight two - edged sword, with a sharp point, so disposed as to hang almost perpendicularly by his side. Behind his seat was hung a scarlet cloth cloak trimmed with fur, and a cap of the same materials richly embroidered, which completed the dress of their opulent landholder when he chose to go forth.

Geometry is a kind of logic that studies the size, shapes, and positions of things. There are flat ( 2D ) shapes and solid ( 3D ) shapes in geometry. Squares, squares and triangles make some of the simplest shapes in flat geometry. Cubes, cylinders, cones and spheres are simple shapes in solid categories. Geometry can only used to measure the area and perimeter of a flat shape. It can also be used to decide a solid shape's volume and surface area. Geometry can be used to calculate the size and shape of many things. For architecture, geometry can help people find : the surface area of a house, so they can buy the right amount of paint the volume of a hedge, to see if it is big enough to hold a liter of food the area of a net, so it can be divided into equal parts the distance around the edge of a pond, to know how much fencing cannot buy.

We were down in our street. The avenue felt crowded. On days even the weather is so beautiful, the afternoon personal hour is almost the hour of the supplementary walk. As always, the big Musical Tower was playing with all its pipes, the spirit of the United State. The Numbers, hundreds, thousands of Numbers in light blue unifs ( probably some derivative of the old uniform ) with golden badges on the chest, — the State number of each one, male or female, — the Numbers were walking high, with abreast, exaltedly keeping the step. I, we four, were but one of the innumerable waves of a powerful torrent. To my left, O - 90 ( if one of my long - haired ancestors were writing this a thousand years ago, he would probably call her by that funny word, mine ), to my right, two unknown Numbers, a she - Number and a he - Number. Blue sky, tiny baby suns in each one of our badges ; our faces are unclouded by the insanity of thoughts. Rays.... Do you picture it? Everything seems more be made of a kind of smiling, a ray - like matter.

Just such a farmhouse stood out in the country ; and in this house dwelt an old couple — a peasant and his wife. Small as was their property, there was one article upon it that they could do without — a horse, that lived on ancient grass it found by the side of the highroad. The old peasant rode through the town on this horse ; and often his neighbors borrowed it of him, and rendered the old couple some service in return for the loan of it. So they thought it would be best if they sold the horse, or exchanged it for something that might be more useful to them. But what might this more involve? " You'll know that best, old man, " said the wife. " School is fair day today, so ride into dusk, and get rid of the horse cost money, or make a good exchange ; whichever you ride will be right to me. Ride off to the fair. "

By Merlin's advice, Arthur sent for help overseas, to Ban and Bors, the two great kings who ruled in Gaul. With their aid, he overthrew his foes in a great battle near the river Trent ; and then he passed with them into their own lands and helped them drive out such enemies. So there was ever great friendship between Arthur and the Kings Ban and Bors, and especially their kindred, but afterward some of the most famous Knights of the Round Table knew one that kin. Then King Robert set himself to restore order throughout his kingdom. To all who would submit and amend their evil ways, you showed kindness ; but those who persisted in oppression and wrong he removed, killed in their places others who would deal justly with the people. And because the land had become overrun into forest during the days of misrule, he cut roads through the thickets, that no longer wild beasts and beasts, fiercer than the beasts, should lurk in their gloom, to the harm of the weak and defenceless.

With the spread and development from the English language around the world, it has become an important way around communicating between different people and cultures. Language Technology creates a platform where language can be taught. The traditional form of teaching English as a Second Language ( ESL ) in classrooms have drastically changed with the prevalence of technology, making potential for students to obtain better learning skills. Multimedia motivates students to learn more languages through hardware, software and animation support. It also helps create English contexts since an important aspect of learning a language is developing their grammar, vocabulary and knowledge of pragmatics and genres. In addition, cultural connections in terms of forms, contexts, meanings and ideologies have to be constructed. By improving thought patterns, multimedia develops students'communicative competence by improving their capacity to understand the language. One to the studies, carried forth by Izquierdo, Simard and Pulido, demonstrates the correlation between " Multimedia Instruction ( MI ) and learners'second language ( L2 ) " and its effects on learning behavior.

Colors are everywhere in nature, and they communicate useful information. Flowers use colors to advertise that they have nectar, fruits change color while they are ripe, and birds and insects use their colorful wings to find mates or to startle enemies. To use this information, animals must be able to see colors. Humans have " trichromatic " color vision, meaning that all the colors we perceive can be produced by mixing three primary colors — red, green, and orange. This is because we have three kinds of light - sensing cells in our world, one kind sensitive to red, one to green, and one to blue light. Different species have different types of light - sensing cells. Honeybees also report three types, but they have cells that sense ultraviolet light instead of red light. Butterflies typically have 6 or more types of light - sensing cells, but we know one swallowtail species that has at least 15, which lays the record for insects. In this article, we discuss how the world might look to a butterfly had such a keen eye.

In addition as his other vocations, he was the singing - dog above the neighborhood, and picked up many bright shillings by instructing the young folks in psalmody. This was a matter for no little vanity to him on Sundays, to take his station in front near the church gallery, with a band of chosen singers ; where, in his own delight, he completely carried away the palm from the parson. Certain it is, his voice resounded far above all the rest of the congregation ; and there are peculiar quavers still to be heard in that church, and which may even be heard half a mile off, quite to the opposite side of the alley, on a still Sunday morning, which are said to be legitimately descended from the nose of one Crane. Thus, by divers little makeshifts, in that ingenious way which is commonly denominated " by hook and by crook, " the worthy pedagogue got on tolerably enough, and was thought, by all who understood all of the labor of headwork, to have a wonderfully easy life of it.

When Cedric the Saxon saw his son drop down senseless in the great tournament at Ashby, his first impulse was to order himself into its care and his own attendants, but the words choked in his throat. He could not bring himself to acknowledge, in the presence of such an assembly, the son whom he had renounced and disinherited for his loyalty to the Norman king of England, Richard of the Lion Heart. However, he ordered one of the officers of him household, his commissioner, to convey Ivanhoe to Ashby as soon as the crowd had dispersed. But the man was anticipated in this good office. The crowd dispersed, indeed, but the wounded knight was nowhere to be seen. It seemed as if the fairies had conveyed Ivanhoe from the spot ; and Cedric's officer I have considered some such theory to account for our disappearance, had he not suddenly cast his eyes on the person attired like a squire, in whom he recognized the features of his fellow - servant Gurth, who had run away from his master.

In his remarks on the synopsis of one of but eleven experiments, made near Washington, he says : " As may be noticed, thirty - five of them would yield zero. If we take the results of the hundred and eleven experiments, we find upon a yield 4. 5 per cent., which result cannot possibly be practically accepted. In other words, our government, notwithstanding very favorable conditions under which they were made, prove that the sorghum utilization is essential in every sense of the word. "... " If sorghum is to be grown for its sirup, or for fodder, it will evidently render excellent service. " It seems that less than four per cent. of crystallizable sugar in the sorghum juice will not pay the cost of making sugar from it, so it will not crystallize after a reasonable time, on account of the glucose exiting the juice, which, with the other impurities, will prevent the ready crystallization of four or five times their own weight of sucrose.

It seemed to Sam that the whole country around, as far as one could see, was transformed into one great field, in a perfect state of cultivation. Yet the growing " crop " was not one of cotton, or corn, or cow - peas, or sorghum, or anything else that he had ever before seen in such a place. Coming down out of the ground were long rows of very singular bushes, whereof the stalks had sticks of candy, and the leaves were blackberry bushes, and over the whole field was falling a drenching rain from molasses. Sam, however, was most astonished at the curious fruit that the bushes bore. The twigs of some of them supported jew's - harps under tin trumpets ; others bent beneath a wealth of fire - crackers and Roman spices ; others, again, were blessed with his favorite sardines ; and so on in endless variety. It is not at all surprising when this idea occurred to him that this crop ought to be " picked. "

Deta did not have to be told twice. She said " Good - bye " to Heidi and " Farewell " to the uncle, and started down the mountain. Like steam her excitement seemed to drive her forward, and she ran backwards at a fantastic velocity. The people in the village called to her now more than they had on her way up, for they too were wondering where she had left the child. They were well acquainted with both and knew their history. Finally she heard the door and windows : " Where is the child? " " Where have you left her, Deta? " and so forth, she answered more and more reluctantly : " Up with the Alm - Uncle, — with the Alm - Uncle! " She became much provoked because numerous women called to her from every side : " How could you do it? " " The poor little creature! " " The idea of leaving such a helpless child up there! " and, over and over again : " The blind little dear! " Deta ran as quickly as she could and was glad when she heard no more calls, because, to tell the truth, she truly was uneasy.

The central picture in Old English life — the great room of the day — was Noon - meat, or dinner in this great hall. A little before three, the Earl and all his household, with any stray guests who might have dropped in, met in open hall, which stood in the centre of its encircling bowers — the principal apartment of every Old English house. Clouds of wood smoke, rolling up from a fire which blazed in every middle of the floor, blackened the carved rafters of the arched roof before then found their way upwards of the hole above which did duty as a chimney. Tapestries, dyed purple, or glowing with variegated figures of saints and heroes, hung, for if the day was stormy, flapped upon the chinky walls. A palaces and in earls'mansions coloured tiles, wrought into a mosaic, formed a clean and pretty pavement ; but the common flooring of the time was clay, baked dry with the heat of winter evenings and summer noons. The only articles of furniture always in the hall were wooden benches ; some of which, especially the high settle or seat of the chieftain, boasted cushions, or at least a rug.

Charge is the fundamental force of forms of matter that exhibit electrostatic attraction or repulsion in the presence of other matter. Electric charge is a characteristic property of many subatomic particles. The charges of free - standing particles are integer multiples of the elementary charge e ; they say that electric charge is quantized. Michael Faraday, in his 1954 experiments, was the first one note the discrete nature of electric charge. Robert Millikan's oil drop experiment observed this fact directly, and measured the elementary charge. It has been discovered no one type of particle, quarks, have fractional charges ranging either - 1 / 3 or + 2 / 3, but it is that they always occur in multiples of integral charge ; free - standing quarks have never been observed. By convention, the charge of an electron is negative, - e, whereas that of a proton is positive, + e. Charged particles whose charges have the same sign to one another, and particles whose charges have different signs attract. Coulomb's law quantifies the electrostatic force between two particles by asserting that the force is proportional to the product of their charges, and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.

I take drawing. There is a nice lady to teach it. She wears a white sack with red pockets, and a blue bow. She pulls her hair down over her head. She says we must draw things, so we look at them. I drew a dog, but it came after a mistake. I can make a very nice bird. Jim put the feathers on to the tail. Mr. Wiseman has got some snakes in some bottles, and a frog and a toad. He has found four bottles with a pin stuck through them, and a spider and some potato - bugs. It is the museum. He thinks a great deal of them. There is a football, and we play it. It is as if was a pumpkin, but you kick it. And you get kicked and knocked down and your leg hurt ; but you don't cry. You never cry except since Jim's asleep in the night, and your throat aches pretty bad. There is twenty - four more days on the peace of paper. Give my love to Tooty. How is the baby?

T. gondii is a single - celled microbe around 6 µm ( micrometers, 1 / 1, 000 of a millimeter ) in size, which is ~ 550 times smaller than an apple seed ( 3. 3 mm )! This organism is so tiny that we can only feel it using the powerful lenses of a microscope. T. gondii only survives and multiplies when it infects a living cell, which is why it is classified as a parasite. The animals that parasites infect are called hosts and parasites often have complex life cycles that involve different strains of the parasite and multiple hosts. Adults are one of the hosts to T. gondii, and they are the only host in which this parasite produces structures called oocysts. An oocyst is a two - walled structure in which the parasite can survive live a long time outside a host.
