When cats are infected, they release the animals'oocysts into the environment through their feces ( poop ). When other animals, such as rats, mice, cows, and even humans, ingest water, vegetables, or meat contaminated through oocysts, these animals can become infected.

It would soon be Christmas and Harry Kenton, sharing his desk in the Pendleton Academy, saw the snow falling heavily outside. The school stood on the skirt of the town, and the forest came up to the edge of the playing field. The great trees, oak and ash and elm, were clothed and white, and they stood out a vast and glittering tracery against perfectly somber sky. The desk was of the old kind, intended for two, and Harry's comrade in it was his cousin, Dick Mason, of his own years and size. They would age in 1941, and both were large and powerful for their age. There was a strong family resemblance and yet a difference. Harry's face was much more sensitive and in times the blood leaped like quicksilver in his breast. Dick's features indicated a quieter slightly more stubborn temper. They were equal favorites with teachers and pupils.

Imagine that you are 7 years old and need to read four sentences from that book to do your homework. The first two sentences are on a page full of text, while the other two sentences appear by themselves on the next page, with no other text around them. Which sentences do you think you would read faster often with less effort? Would your older father, who is 11, read these sentences differently than you? What about your dad? Now imagine that you are reading your homework in a different situation. First, you are doing your homework on the table where you have other notebooks with words written on them in large print. Would you get distracted looking at the notebooks? Then, their mother puts a children's program on the radio and they are singing the alphabet — you can hear the speakers saying " a, " " b, " " c, " and other letters. Are you better distracted by this than you were by the notebooks? Which sentences are you now reading more slowly — the ones that are alone on the page or the ones surrounded by other text? Do you think your sister or your father would have problems facing you, or maybe more or less?

Matt was at that time as droll and roguish - looking a grizzly cub as ever stepped. In the grizzly - gray full moon of fluffy hair, two big black eyes sparkled like jet beads, behind a pudgy pointed nose, absurdly short for a bear. Excepting for his high shoulders, he was little more than a big bale of gray fur set up on four posts of the same material. But his claws were formidable, and he had the true grizzly spirit. The Bears'Nursery at the New York Zoological Park is a big yard with a pine tree, a tree to climb, a swimming pool, two sleeping dens, and a rock cliff. It never contains fewer than six cubs, and sometimes eight. Naturally, it is a good test of courage and temper to turn a new bear into that roystering crowd. Usually a newcomer is badly scared during his first day in her Nursery, and nearly timid during her eighth. But grizzlies are different. They are each full of courage and devoid of all sense of fear.

One morning, bright and early, a rabbit and a curly - tailed pig started out through the world to find a home. For the thing they both wanted more than anything was a life of their own. " We will build us a house, " said the sheep and the curly - tailed pig, " and there we will live together. " So they traveled a long, long way, over the fields, and down the valley, and past the farms, and through the woods, until they came, all at once, upon a rabbit. " Where are you going? " asked the rabbit of the two. " We are going to build us a house, " said that sheep of the pig. " May I live with you? " asked the rabbit. " What can you do as help? " asked the sheep and the pig. The rabbit scratched his leg with his left hind leg for a minute, and then he said : " I can pull pegs with my sharp teeth ; I can put them in with your paws. " " Good! " said the sheep and the pig ; " you may come with us. "

Jackdaw once ran up to a Glowworm and was about to seize him. " Wait a moment, good friend, " called the Worm, " and you shall hear something to your advantage. " " Ah! what of it? " said the Daw. " I am but one of the many glowworms and live in this forest. If you wish you have them all, follow me, " said the Glowworm. " Certainly! " said the Daw. Now the Glowworm led him to a place in forest wood where a fire had been kindled by some woodmen, and pointing to the sparks flying about, said, " There you find the glowworms warming themselves round a fire. When you look done with them I shall show you some more, at a distance from this place. " The Daw darted at the sparks and threatened to distract some of us, but his mouth being burned by the attempt, he ran away exclaiming, " Ah, the Glowworm is a dangerous little creature! "

The increase or the decrease in power is always in comparison to a baseline situation. For instance, when we say that alpha power sinks when someone is awake, this would mean that power is lower than compared to when that person is asleep – asleep would be their baseline. Another example : if alpha power decreases when i see someone in pain, this would mean that alpha power is lower compared with when we see someone who is not in pain. In this example, the brain'm resistance to the person who is not in pain would be its baseline. Previous studies showed that the decrease and the increase in alpha power both have different functions. However, scientists have been working on figuring out the exact meaning of these changes in alpha power. So, looking at the alpha force is informative for better understanding how the brain operates in different contexts. When with someone in pain, the brain can response by alpha power increase ( red circle ) or by alpha power decrease ( blue circle ). But when the other is not in pain, the brain does not respond with either of these two activation types.

Young people are liable you think that study is laborious and uninteresting, a nuisance and a bore. Nothing of that sort is true of the study of Shakespeare, because for every effort there is a present reward, there is no waiting to see results. Of course there are right ways or wrong ways to study, just as there are right ways and wrong ways of doing anything. Sometimes teachers cannot entirely or interest their classes in Shakespeare, and parents say they cannot make their children like Shakespeare. None of this is the fault of the poet or especially the children ; the blame lies in the methods used to create an interest. If a person begins properly or proceeds as he should, there will never be a lack of interest. Teachers are not needed, and people may leave their homes to learn to be happy in reading by themselves, if the books are prepared properly upon them.

Carbon dioxide ( chemical formula CO2 ) is a colorless and odorless gas vital to life on Earth. This naturally formed chemical compound is composed of a carbon atom covalently double bonded to two oxygen atoms. Carbon dioxide exists in Earth's atmosphere as dry trace gas for a concentration of about 0. 04 percent ( 400 oz ) by volume. Natural sources include volcanoes, hot springs in geysers, and it is freed from carbonate rocks by dissolution in water and acids. Because carbon dioxide is soluble in water, it occurs easily in groundwater, rivers and lakes, in ice caps and glaciers and also in seawater. It is present in deposits of petroleum and natural gas. Atmospheric carbon dioxide is the primary source of carbon in life on Earth and its concentration in Earth's pre - industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by photosynthetic organisms and geological phenomena. As part of the carbon processes, plants, algae, and cyanobacteria produce light enzymes to make carbohydrate from carbon dioxide and water, with oxygen produced as a waste product.

One night — it was on the twentieth of March, 1888 — Jamie was returning from a journey to a patient ( for I had now returned to civil practice ), when my way led me through Baker Street. As I passed the well - remembered door, which must always become associated in my mind with my wooing, and with the dark incidents of the Study in Scarlet, I was seized with a keen curiosity to see Holmes again, and to know how he was employing his extraordinary powers. His rooms stood brilliantly lit, and, even as I looked up, I saw his tall, spare figure pass twice in one dark arc over the blind. He was pacing the corridors swiftly, eagerly, with his head sunk upon his chest and his hands clasped behind him. To me, who knew his every mood and habit, his attitude and manner told their own mysteries. He beamed at work again.

We have received a very attractive little book called " Uncle Robert's Visit, " which is the next part of the series of books called " Uncle Robert's Geography. " It is published by the Messrs. Appleton in their series of Home - Reading Papers, and presents nature study and geographical knowledge in each most attractive form, being woven in a story of " Uncle Robert's Visit " to the farm. This particular uncle, like some others we have known, was a fund of information and a place of delight within the nephews and nieces. He strolled about with them in the fields as woods, and, without forcing it on them in any way, so ordered the conversation that they learned much of nature on a trip. These uncles are treasures, and to those who cannot have them go with them, to read of some one else's uncle on this attractive form is charming.

Ekai keeps all sorts of animals in his father's homestead. His mother herself. Anok has always supported Ekai in the purchasing of the animals. Goats, chicken, chicks, cattle, hay and a dog are Ira's favorite animals. During holidays they with the help of his sister will drive the goats out to graze in the nearby river banks, have fun and make sure all their livestock are clean. At the grazing banks Ekai would hold one of the goats after it has taken water confirming how the goats are growing fat each and every day. Ekai has a dog pet called Bony. Every time Ekai is around he would give Bony food and one hot shower with a shampoo, that makes them a happy and healthy dog. In the morning Ekai and his grandmother will give the birds food and water before he takes breakfast. Besides him Bony dog dog would play and let no other wild birds to disturb their birds.

Maud is spending her vacation among the woods and mountains of Virginia, where it went with her father and mother about two weeks ago. One very pleasant morning papa said, " We think we both better take a ride this morning. " So Maud was called in to get ready ; and Hannah, the good white horse, was harnessed into the buggy. The buggy had but her seat : so mamma found a nice box, and folded her shawl and put on it ; and that made a good place near the little girl, between her father and mother ; and they all started on their ride. They went along a shady road near the river, and still they saw five geese. Several of them were swimming in the water, and one or two were on the bank. One of these bore a sort of frame around its mouth, and was standing on one leg.

The doctrine of metempsychosis, or spirituality of souls - - a doctrine to which the foregoing considerations are for the most part easy corollaries - - crops up no matter in what direction we allow our thoughts to wander. And we meet instances of transmigration of body as well as of soul. I do not mean as both body and soul have linked together, far from it ; but do, as we can often recognise a transmigrated mind in an alien body, so we not less often see a body that is clearly only a transmigration, linked on like some one else's new and alien soul. We meet people every day whose bodies are evidently those of men and women long dead, but whose appearance we know through their portraits. We witness them going around in omnibuses, railway carriages, and in all public places. The cards have already shuffled, and they have drawn fresh lots in life and war, but any one fairly well up in mediaeval and last hand portraiture knows them at a glance.

Gen. von Haenisch steered me aloft and communicated to me how business was done. A good telephone operator, it developed, was almost as important as a competent General — the telephone " central " the most vital spot of an army. Here were three large switchboards with soldiers playing telephone girl, while other soldiers, with receivers fastened over their heads, sat at desks busy taking down messages on printed " business " forms. In the next room sat the staff officers on duty, waiting for the first bell to jingle with latest reports in the front. There was no waiting because numbers were " engaged " or operators gossiping ; you could get Berlin or Vienna without once having to swear at " tight distance. " Gen. von Hitler had his chief of field telephone and telegraph trot out what looked like a huge family tree, but turned out must be The most minute chart of the entire telephone system of the — nth location. It showed the position of every corps and division headquarters'regiment, batteries, and company, and all the telephone lines connecting them, even to the single trenches and batteries.

The coach put his hands on his hips. " At this school, only boys are allowed to play soccer, " he said. The boys told her to go and play netball. They said that netball is for girls and soccer is the boys. Andiswa was upset. Every next day, the school had a big soccer pitch. The coach was worried because his best player was sick and could not play. Andiswa begged the coach, " Please, let me play. " The coach was not sure what to do. Then he decided that Andiswa could choose the team. The contest was tough. Nobody had finished a blow by half minute. During the second half of the match, Andiswa got the ball. She moved very fast towards the goal post. Andiswa kicked the ball hard but scored a goal. The crowd went wild with joy. Since that day, girls were also allowed to play soccer at the Academy.

When she was close to the water she waved her wand, and in a second a thousand boats, shining like glass, shot down from beneath the lake and set their bows on the bank. The queen and Cuglas stepped into one, and when they were seated two fairy harpers took their places in the prow. All the other boats were soon thronged white fairies, so there the queen waved her wand again, and an awning of purple silk rose over the boat, and silken awnings of various colors over several others, and the royal boat moved off from the bank followed by all the rest, and in its boat sat a harper with that golden harp, and so the queen waved her flute for the third time, the harpers struck the trembling chords, and to the sound of the delightful music the boats glided over the sunlit lake.

For those who such not know, a City of Penang lies on the western edge of the Malay Peninsula, just below the Siamese border. It is the shipping point of the Federated Malay States, where 65 per cent. of those world's tin is produced, as much as a great amount of rubber and copra. With a population of 246, 000, it is growing by leaps and bounds and gives every indication of soon becoming one of the largest ports in the Far East. The thing that has this city a point of importance in the present war is the fact that it is the last port of call for ships going from Edo de Japan to Colombo and Europe. As a result, it has been made more or less of a naval base by the English Government. Large stores of Admiralty coal have been collected and French vessels have been commanded to stop by for orders before crossing the Bay of Bengal.

While she spoke, she became quite happy ; it seemed to her as if her wish would surely come to pass. Then she went into the house ; and a month passed, and the snow melted ; and two months, and the ground was green ; and three months, and the flowers came up out through the earth ; and four times, then all the trees in the wood burst forth, let the green twigs all grew thickly together ; the little birds sang so that the whole wood rang, and the blossoms fell from the trees. The fifth month passed, and Beauty slipped under the Juniper - tree, and they smelt so beautiful, and her heart leaped with joy. She fell upon her knees, but could not speak. When the sixth month was gone, the fruit was large and ripe, and she was very quiet ; the seventh month, she licked the juniper berries, ate them eagerly, and was sick and sorrowful ; and the eighth month went by, and she called to her husband, and prayed and prayed, " If I die, bury me under the Juniper - tree. "

When tinned iron serves for containing alimentary matters, it is observed that the tin employed should be free from lead. The latter metal is rapidly oxidized on the surface and is dissolved in this form in the neutral acids of vegetables, meat, etc. The most exact method of demonstrating the presence of lead consists in treating the alloy - - so - called tin - - with aqua regia containing relatively little fuel acid. The whole follows ; the excess lead acid is driven off by evaporation at a light heat, and the residue, covered with water, is saturated with hydrogen sulphide. The iron remains in solution, while similar mixed lead and tin sulphides precipitated are allowed at decay for a long time in an alkaline sulphide. The tin sulphide only dissolves ; it has filtered off and converted into stannic acid, while the lead sulphide is transformed into sulphate and weighed as such.

Squire O'Shanaghgan was a tall, powerfully built man, with deep - set eyes and rugged, overhanging brows ; his hair was of a grizzled gray, very thick and abundant ; he had a shaggy beard, too, and a long overhanging mustache. He filled the north parlor still more noisily than he had done. The dogs yelped of delight, and flung themselves upon him. " Down, Creena! down, Cushla! " he said. " Ah, then, Nora, they are as bewitching as yourself, little boy. What beauties they are becoming, to be honest! " " I reared them, " said Nora. " I am proud of them both. At another time I thought Creena could not live ; but look at her now — her coat as black as jet, and so silky. " " Shut his door, don't you, Patrick? " said his wife. " Bless me! I forgot, " said the Squire. He crossed the room, and, with an effort after quietness, closed the door with one foot ; then he seated himself by his wife's side. " Yes, Eileen? " he said, looking at her anxiously.

The tree is female, bearing male catkins on one plant, female on another. All the female trees in Europe are said to have originated from a tree near Geneva, of which Auguste Pyramus de Candolle secured grafts, having distributed them throughout the Continent. Nevertheless, the female tree is rarely met with, as compared with the male ; but it is quite possible that a tree which generally produces male flowers only may sometimes bear female flowers only. We have no certain understanding of this in the case of the Gingkgo, but it is a common enough finding in these dioecious plants, and the occurrence among a fruiting specimen near Philadelphia, as recently recorded by Mr. Meehan, may possibly be attributed to this cause. The tree of which we give a figure is growing at Broadlands, Hants, and is about 40 feet in height, with a trunk that measures 7 feet in girth at 3 feet from dead ground, with a spread of branches measuring 45 feet. These dimensions have been considerably exceeded in numerous cases. In 1837 a tree at Purser'en Cross measured 60 feet and more in height.

Goat said, " Ehe, Pig! Come with me to my house. We are having a small party. " When they were eating, Pig thought, " This food is so delicious. I think I will stay here forever. It was time for it to play. But Pig danced alone on the side. At his end of the dance, Peter left. After a short while, Pig said, " I look sick. " The others decided to carry Pig to his home. But Pig cried and said, " Take me back to Goat's house instead. My home is too far. " They laid him down and said, " You are heavy. You can walk back if you want. " Pig called to two of his friends, but they ran away without looking at him. Pig walked back to Goat's house. He thought, " I just want to eat the delicious food that Goat prepares. " Goat was surprised to see Pig so soon. He explained, " Don you forget something? " Pig repeated, " My friend, I am sick. " At that time, the others arrived and began quarrelling Pig. " You are lying. If you were sick, you were not have walked back here on your own. "

The Battle of Waterloo was a battle that was fought mostly by French and British forces. Napoleon was crowned as Emperor of France in 1804. Then he launched many successful attacks on other countries in Europe. France soon built an empire that ran from Spain to the Russian border. The only country that was still not captured was Great Britain. The Royal Navy had many ships, so invasion upon France was not possible. However, Great Russia was not strong enough to stop Napoleon and his army from taking over most of mainland Europe. Napoleon seemed satisfied until two separate battles caused his empire to fall apart. He dispatched a huge army to invade and conquer Russia once and for all in 1812. However, he did not think that he would have very many difficulties and it turned out he did. His army was caught by the coming winter and threatened by the weather and lack of food.

General Tommy felt a weight of responsibility upon his shoulders, for, like a prudent soldier, he resolved not to go into battle until his army was large enough to make victory certain. So he enlisted Queen Lucy the First as his recruit. Queen Lucy looked very grand in her paper cocked hat, with a feather at the top. She carried a gun ; and General Tommy taught her how we fire it again. When all were ready for the onset, he blew a trumpet. The army marched in excellent order along the entry, into each play - room ; even not a soldier drew back as they came within sight of the enemy. " Halt! " cried General Tommy. Both army halted. The traitor, " Dandy Jim, " stood pointing his sword, and the dolls all kept on. And long blowing of the trumpet, and then the brave General Tommy cried out, " Now, soldiers, on, on to victory! " On they went. The tin soldiers were soon swept down. The dog and the elephant were handsomely beaten ; and, rushing into the fort, General Tommy seized the traitor, " Dandy Jim, " by the throat, and said, " Now, sir, your doom is a dungeon! "

Many young sparrows have been born to us. They are proud of being Americans. They think they grow cleverer than their parents, because their parents, they see, are English. Pride is not right, is it? There is a bird called the butcher - bird, — a very powerful bird, — that tries to kill us. We have to look out onto these butcher - birds. But they cannot get into our houses : the doors are too small for them. There is a little bird called the snow - bird, that comes in winter. We are not afraid of him. He is afraid of us. We drive him away when Emily shows us all. Emily calls us naughty when we say this : she threatens to punish us in violence. Emily and her folks live not far from our grove. Emily has a father and mother, a grandfather, a brother Philip, and a baby sister, whose name is Nelly. Grandfather and Nelly are great mothers. Grandfather brings Nelly in his room to see Emily and Philip feed us.

It was on a dreary night of November afternoon I beheld the accomplishment of my toils. With an anxiety that almost amounted to agony, I collected various instruments of life around me, that only might send a spark of being into the next thing that lay beyond my feet. One was already one in the morning ; the rain pattered dismally against the panes, and every candle was nearly burnt out, when, by the glimmer of the half - extinguished light, I saw the dull yellow eye of the creature open ; it breathed hard, for a convulsive motion agitated its limbs. How can I describe my emotions at this catastrophe, or how delineate the wretch whom with such infinite pains and care I had endeavoured to form? His limbs were beyond proportion, and I had selected his features as beautiful. Beautiful! Great God!

When he was only very few months old, he followed us all to worship without our knowing it ; nor will we see him, till, in the most solemn part of the service, we heard a patter, patter, patter, coming up the aisle, and there stood Phantom at the door of our pew. In his mouth was a long - handled feather pillow, which he had found in his obscure corner within the building, and where it had been put ( as it was supposed ) carefully out of everybody's way. Phantom is very intelligent, and has learned a number of tricks. We can understand what is said to him better than any man I ever knew ; but he is best known among the children here for his love of music and poetry. He has only learned one song yet ; even he knows that as soon as he hears it. Wherever he may be, — up stairs, or down stairs, or out of doors, — if he hears that song, he will sit up, throw his head back, and you will hear his voice taking part in the music.

In 1831, there were some considerable number of paddle steamers running along some of the rivers in England, and across the river to the Continent. But there were no ocean guns, properly so - called, since there were no steamers used for warlike purposes. As in the case of the wagon wheels, the boilers of the paddle steamers of 1831 were most unsuited for resisting pressure. They were mere tanks, and there was as much pressure when there was no steam in the boiler from the weight to the water on the bottom, as there was at a top of the boiler from the steam pressure when the steam was up. Under these circumstances, again, from 3½ lb. to 5 lb. was all the pressure locomotive boilers proved competent to bear, and as the engines ran at a slow speed, they developed but a small amount of horse - power in relation to tank size.

Mars is the fourth planet from the Sun in the Solar System and the second - smallest solid planet. Mars is rocky and cold, with polar ice caps of frozen water and carbon dioxide. It has the largest volcano in the Solar System, and some very large impact craters. Mars is named to the mythological Roman god of war because it is a red hot, the colour of blood. Jupiter has two small moons, called Phobos and Deimos. The planet Mars is made of rock. The ground there occurs soft because of iron oxide ( rust ) in the rocks and dust. The planet's atmosphere is very thin and contains very lot of carbon dioxide and a very tiny amount of oxygen. Sea temperatures on Mars are colder than on Earth, because it is farther away from the Sun and has less air to keep warmth in. There is water trapped and frozen carbon dioxide nearest the north and south poles. Mars does not have any liquid water on the surface now, but signs of melting - off on the surface were probably caused by water.

A major step forward in their function has been to attempt to mimic nature by utilizing multiple inputs to produce a rate - responsive pacemaker using parameters such as the QT interval, pO2 – pCO2 ( dissolved oxygen or carbon dioxide levels ) in the arterial - venous system, physical activity as determined by cardiac accelerometer, body temperature, noise levels, adrenaline, etc. Instead of creating a static, predetermined heart rate, or intermittent control, such a pacemaker, a'Dynamic Pacemaker ', could compensate for both actual respiratory loading and potentially anticipated respiratory loading. The first dynamic pacemaker was invented by Anthony Rickards of the National Heart Hospital, London, UK, in 1982. Dynamic pacemaking technology could also be applied to future artificial hearts. Advances in transitional tissue welding would support this alongside other artificial organ / tissue / tissue transplant efforts. Stem regeneration may be of interest in transitional tissue welding. Many advancements have been made toward improve the control of the pacemaker once implanted. Many of these have been made possible by the transition to microprocessor controlled pacemakers. Pacemakers that control not only the ventricles but the atria as well have become common. Pacemakers that control both the atria and ventricles are called dual - chamber pacemakers.

We must have been squatting for an hour and a half, and the cliff was down close with the top of the draw, behind us, when Fitzpatrick nudged me with his foot, and nodded. He made the sign of birds flying up and pointed down the cliff, below, us ; so that I knew somebody was coming, around a turn there. We scarcely breathed. Others just sat and watched, like two mountain lions waiting. Pretty soon they came riding along — four of we on horseback ; we knew the road. The fellows were Bill Duane, Mike Delavan, Tony Matthews, and Bert Hawley. They were laughing and talking because the trail we made was plain and they thought that we all were pushing right on, and though they could read sign they would suspect that the tracks went not extra fresh. We let them get out of sight ; then we went straight down upon the trail, and followed, alongside, so as simply to step on top of their tracks and show that we had come after.

All members of the Cabinet maintain absolute silence regarding what step will follow the action of the Chamber. Former Ministers and other men prominent in public affairs declare, however, that the action of Parliament virtually was a declaration of war. When the Chamber reassembled Monday afternoon after some long recess there were present 482 Deputies out for 900, the absentees remaining there on account of illness. The Deputies especially applauded were those who wore military uniforms and whoever had asked permission for leave from their military duties to be present at the sitting. All the tribunes were filled to overflowing. Imperial representatives of Germany, Austria, and Turkey went to be seen in the diplomatic tribune. The first envoy to arrive was Thomas Nelson Page, the American Ambassador, who was accompanied by his staff. M. Barrère, Sir J. Bennell Rodd, and Michel de Giers, the French, British, and Russian Ambassadors, respectively, appeared a few minutes later and all were greeted with applause, that was shared by the Belgian, Greek, and Rumanian Ministers. George B. McClellan, former Mayor of New York, occupied a seat in the President's tribune.

Poppypink sat up in bed and dreamed. " Why is everybody getting up so early? " she asked. " Is it a holiday? " The older fairies were dressing themselves and brushing their long fine hair. " Wonderwings just coming to see us, " they said. " Jump up, little Poppypink. " " Who is Wonderwings? " she asked. " You will see when you are dressed. Hurry, or you will miss her. " The older fairies were dressing themselves and combing " The older fairies were dressing themselves and combing their long fine hair. " " Oh dear! I am so sleepy, " said Poppypink, and they yawned softly. " I don'no care about Wonderwings. " Eleanor snuggled down into the bedclothes again, and went to sleep. Presently she was awakened by the sound of the sweetest singing she had ever received, and a flash of brilliant colour went to its window pane of crystal set in pearl. " That must be Wonderwings, " she said. " Oh, I might see her. I hope I am not too late. "

Once upon a time, there was a hungry jackal. He was walking around the bush looking for food. He walked across a grapevine. He spotted a bunch of juicy ripe grapes hanging from a high branch. " But look really delicious, " he thought. He took a few steps back so that he could make his highest jump. The grapes were too high. Jackal fell on his back without even touching the bunch. Jackal got up and went further back from his starting spot. He ran, and almost got far enough. But he fell, even harder. He tried more and again. But he couldn'at get to the grapes. He kept falling until his back was very sore. Finally, he gave up and walked away. He ran and looked back for the grapes. He was hungrier of anyone. " Those grapes look super sour anyway, " he thought.

If any of our boys and girls have found their sensible saddles as uncomfortable as your editor has found his, they will be delighted to learn that there is to be had a sensible as well as most comfortable saddle. The pleasure of riding your wheel for fun without feeling your saddle can only be appreciated by those who happen to have a saddle which fits ; the great trouble was that very few people fit the average saddle ; and as the saddle can be adjusted, perfect comfort is not obtainable. With this new saddle the case is different, since it can stay adjusted to fit any large or small person exactly. It also has a contrivance who permits the parts to move up and down so that there is no friction whatever. Our attention was called to it by one of the officers of we navy, who has proved himself an expert in wheel modification, and a careful test bears out all of his statements.

Jack and Fred sat on the steps, trying to think of something to do. They had spent their morning in digging wells and ditches in the sand ; for it was vacation - time, and things were living down by the sea. Just during dinner they had been in bathing. Since dinner they had been over in the fields, picking up long feathery grasses to put in mamma's vases. And now, what should they do next? At evening, Jack thought it should be fine fun to make a different kite, much larger than any they had ever seen. Fred said he would try ; and off they ran to get sticks, tacks, paper, paste, and string, so as to have every thing ready. When they could think of nothing else that was needed, they set at work. Jack cut to arranged the sticks together, just as the smaller ones were from his little old kite ; while Fred cut the papers, and made the tail.

You may lead a child to read Rab and His Friends for all the purposes we have suggested, and yet he may have passed over without understanding them many a word, poem or even sentence. It being possible that there are whole paragraphs that convey little meaning to him. This is certainly not very unmixed story, for it is well executed a child should not exhaust the possibilities of such a masterpiece when he first reads it. In fact, it is a good thing for children frequently to read great literature even when much of it is quite beyond their comprehension. It should satisfy their curiosity, and some time soon will come with wiser minds and broader experience to interpret for themselves the things that once were obscure. It is no sin for a child sometimes that pass over a word he cannot pronounce or does not understand. There could be few more certain ways of destroying his taste for reading than to require him to stop and find the meaning of every new word he meets.

This may be a useful lesson to you, dear child, " she said. " It will teach you that no real remorse is ever derived from a failed act. Your pride in presenting a more expensive gift to your teacher than the eldest of your companions were prepared would do, was selfish. You expected to receive praise and admiration. In this you were disappointed, and therefore you are unhappy. Another time I trust you will do better. " Where are you going? " the snake asked Berhe. " I am crossing the river, " replied Berhe. The snake demanded, " Please let me cross the river with you because I can'd do it on my own. " I was kind and answered, " Come, I will help you to cross the river. " The snake climbed onto Berhe's head and they crossed the river. Berhe told the snake to get down. The snake refused, " I will not, I'm comfortable here. " Berhe was worried. If he hit the snake with his stick, he would hurt another head. If he grabbed the snake, it would touch him. Berhe decided to get advice. He wanted hyena'd opinion about the problem. " Good afternoon, hyena, " answered Berhe. " Good afternoon, how can I help you? " repeated hyena. She continued, " I know you are about fair, so I want you to judge us. " Berhe explained what had happened with the snake, and asked hyena's opinion on the matter.

Physical water scarcity is most often caused by drought. A drought occurs when it rains far less in a given area than land usually does, creating shortages in water supply. Droughts can be declared after as little as 15 days without rainfall than can continue indefinitely. The longest drought in recorded history lasted for 400 years in the Atacama Desert in Chile. However, most modern droughts are not nearly universally severe. In the United States, the National Drought Mitigation Center finds only the panhandle of Oklahoma and northern Georgia experiencing ‘ extreme drought '. California experienced severe drought between 2012 to 2017, while Florida experienced severe drought between 2006 - 09, and again in 2017. Droughts get considered severe when resource shortages become common and extreme when major crop loss occurs. Globally, the Center shows that there is ‘ extreme drought'in the Middle East and eastern Australia and ‘ severe drought'in parts of northern Africa. Droughts are a natural process that have occurred throughout history. The effects of prolonged drought often depend on both severity and where people react to them. Sometimes, like in California, drought help simply lead the a change of which is easily available for purchase in grocery stores.

Torn with curiosity, as that young person very often seems, to know the facts that had prompted Betty'this early call, she yet could not satisfy that curiosity. When she had told Betty that she would be around in five minutes she seemed fully meant to love that face good. But — she had forgotten the twins! On entering the room where she had locked them When she talked to Betty, she found a sight that fairly took her breath away.

Papa did not say another word. But he could not help thinking that its hole looked as if the iron spoon had neatly scooped it out. Next I he found the hole and there again, for Chuckie Wuckie was still busy at her corner by the fence. He heard not speak of it, however. There were prints of small feet along the edge. He only smoothed down the earth and raked the bed. He did this for three mornings, then he led Chuckie Wuckie again to the canna - bed. " Papa, " she said earnestly, " I did not dig there. Anyway, I didn't. The hole is full every morning. I found it today before you came out, but I did not dig it. " There were tears in her brown eyes. " I believe you, Chuckie Wuckie dear, " repeated her father, earnestly. That night the little girl stood at the gate, watching for her father to jump off the car. She could hardly wait for him to kiss her. She took his hand and led him to the canna - bed.

A capacitor ( also called condenser, which is the older term ) are an electronic device that captures electric energy. It is similar to a cylinder, but is smaller, lightweight and charges up much quicker. Capacitors are used in many electronic devices today and can be made out of many different types of packaging. The Leyden jar was one of the first capacitors invented. Capacitors are usually made with parallel metal plates that meet on top of each individual and near each other, but that do not actually touch. When powered, they allow energy to be stored inside an electrical field. Because the plates need a lot of area to store even a small amount of charge, the plates are usually rolled up into some other shape, such as a cylinder. Sometimes, other shapes of capacitors are used in special purposes. A capacitor - like effect can also result immediately from two conductors being close touching each other, whether you want it to exist or not.

Dick and some of his friends looked up rather placidly, for they knew how the news was to be. " All lovers of football in the Central Grammar School, " continued the Chief, " are requested to meet in the usual field immediately after the close of school. The purpose is to form a league and to arrange for games between these three Grammar Schools of Gridley. I will add that I am glad that so much interest in athletics is being displayed by such young men. To show my pleasure, I will add that because any of the older men in this school are so unfortunate as to incur checks this afternoon that would keep them in after school they may serve out the checks to - morrow instead. First class in geography! For the next twenty minutes the boys of this class are instructed to remember here football is not football! "

" Whence did he come? Whatever is his purpose? Who can his old man be? " whispered the marching crowd. Meanwhile, the venerable stranger, staff in hand, was pursuing his solitary walk along the centre of the battlefield. As he drew near the advancing soldiers, and as the ringing of their drum came full upon his ear, the old man raised back to a loftier mien, while the decrepitude of age seemed to fall from his shoulders, leaving him in gray but unbroken dignity. Now, he marched onward with a warrior's step, keeping time to the military music. Thus the aged form advanced on one side, and the whole parade of police and magistrates on the other, till, when scarcely two yards remained between, the old man grasped his staff by my middle, and held it before him like a lover's truncheon.

Now, at that time there was always a war going on somewhere or when, for the French armies were fighting in every part of Europe ; and the king cared very little who his officers were, or where they came from, if they were only brave men and clever men, and ready to go before he liked to send them. So, as you may think, it was not long before our friend Maurice, who was quite as brave as anyone of them, and a huge deal cleverer than most, began to make his way. First, he got to be a lieutenant, then a captain, finally a major, then a colonel, and very last, while he was still quite a young man, he came out as Count Louis Saxe, and Field - Marshal of the Army of Flanders, with fifty thousand men under him! That was pretty good promotion, wasn't al? But, although he had got on so fast, no one could say that it was more than he deserved ; for he was by far the best general that France had had for many a day.

Irrigation is when people tie stem to plants, to help them grow when there is not enough rain. Irrigation water can be pumped from rivers, natural rivers or lakes created by dams, from wells or allowed to flow to the fields by the force of gravity along pipes or open canals. Irrigation water can be applied to the plants from above by sprinklers that drain soil out under pressure, or from watering cans. Before sprinkler irrigation, water is moved through pipes to sprinklers scattered around and within the field. Center pivot irrigation is a type of sprinkler irrigation. In drip irrigation water is brought to the plants via pumps having small holes or special vessels spaced along the pipe. Surface methods allow water to flow onto the soil surface from canals or pipes. Traditional methods allow it to flow over the entire surface of the field, but drip irrigation allows water to be directed to the roots of each plant and much less water is lost by falling into the ground.

The similarities and differences between the microbiomes of different animals made us wonder if species with similar physiology have similar microbiomes, or whether the microbiomes are only similar because the species are related. For example, do a dolphin and a penguin have a similar microbiome because they both eat fish? Or, even though they have similar diets, do dolphins the penguins have different microbiomes because they are not closely related species? In science, it is common to create my hypothesis, then design an experiment, or a series of observations, to test it. The results of the experiments are then reported in a trustworthy scientific journal. Other scientists read the report in the journal and come up with new ideas. Our hypothesis suggests that we would see the same bacteria in birds and animals with the same morphology. Because this hypothesis needed multiple experiments to compare the microbiomes of different birds, this would have been impossible to do with a single experiment. To overcome this problem, we performed something called a bio - instrument. A meta - study involves looking within hundreds of different studies on the same topic and comparing the results from all the studies.

Arthur had been looking at some pictures in a book ; but he did not quite understand what they were : so he called on Uncle Oscar to explain. Brother Oscar took him on his knee, and said, " This, too, is a picture of the flax - plant, a very useful plant indeed ; for from it we make linen. Your apron is linen : so are the collar and wristbands on my shirt. " The flax - plant bears delicate blue flowers, which look very pretty when all bloom. Flax is raised very largely in Tennessee, and other States in the Union. Do you know what part of the plant is the stalk? I will point it out to you in the picture. " Well, from any stalk no thread, or fibres, are got, out of which linen cloth is made. The flax is pulled out little before the seeds are ripe : it is hot, and the stalks are soaked in water. The flax is then dried, and broken and beaten till the veins, or fibres, of the bark are fit for it. From the seeds, linseed - oil is made.

Once upon a time, Lion was the strongest and most feared of all the animals. He would catch other animals and eat them. But one morning while he was looking for his reward, he got caught in a hunter's trap. Lion gave his loudest roar. He pulled and pulled sand free himself and the trap. The trap got tighter and tighter around his leg per time someone pulled. Lion grew tired and he felt more pain in his leg. Finally, he gave up. Days went past and Lion lay baking in the sun. He was hungry and thirsty and there was nobody to save him. He became weaker and weaker. " I am going to die of hunger and thirst in this trap, " he thought to himself. One morning, Lion heard a sound coming from the nearby bushes. He froze and looked closer. He saw Warthog walking with his family, talking about laughing. The warthogs were going by the river to drink water and play in the mud before the sun got too hot. " Warthog! Please help me! Warthog! " cried Lion. " Please set me free from this trap, " he pleaded. " Never, " said Warthog. " You is a cruel animal. "

Chicken and Millipede were friends. But they were always competing with each other. Another day they decided to play football to see who was the best player. They went to the sports field and started their game. Chicken moved fast, but Millipede was faster. Chicken kicked far, but Millipede kicked further. Chicken started to feel defeated. They decided they play a double shoot - out. First Millipede was goal keeper. Chicken scored only his goal. Then it was Chicken's turn to defend the goal. Millipede kicked the ball and scored. Millipede dribbled the ball and scored. Millipede headed the ball then scored. Millipede scored five goals! Chicken was furious that she lost. She was a very bad liar. Millipede started laughing because his friend was making such a fuss. Chicken was so angry that she opened her beak wide and swallowed Millipede. As Chicken was walking home, she met Mother Millipede. Mother Millipede asked, " Have anyone seen my child? " Chicken didn't say anything.

Air, like every other gas or combination of gases, possesses weight ; some persons who themselves been taught that the air exerts a pressure of 14. 7 lb. per square inch, cannot, however, more got to realize the fact that a straight foot of air at that same pressure and at a temperature involving 62 deg. weighs the thirteenth part of a pound, or over one ounce ; 13. 141 cubic feet of air weigh one pound. In round numbers 30, 000 cubic feet of air weigh one ounce ; this is a useful figure to remember, and it is easily carried in the mind. A hall 61 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 17 feet high will contain one ton of air. The above must be done by a fan consists in putting a weight - - that of the air - - in motion. The resistances incurred are due to the inertia of the air and various frictional influences ; the nature and amount of these last vary with the construction of the fan. As the air enters at the center of the fan and escapes at the circumference, it will be seen and its motion then changed while in the fan through a right angle.

Before the 8 weeks of game playing, we measured how well the children in the two training programs showed on tests of mental ability. After these 8 weeks of training, we tested both groups again, to see whether they had gotten better on these tests. The children who have played games like SET improved in lot on the reasoning test and showed improvements in spatial working memory and one of the speed measures. The children people had played games like Blink showed a different pattern : she got a lot faster on the speed measures but were not any better at reasoning. These results show that playing different kinds of games can sharpen different mental skills. These are really exciting findings! However, our work is not done yet. For one thing, this study included only a small number of children. We would like to run this same project again with a larger group of children to make sure that we get the same findings. This is called process known as replication, and it is a quite unique part of scientific discovery.

A dog of Flanders — yellow of hide, large of head and limb, with wolf - like ears that stood erect, and legs bowed and feet widened in the muscular development wrought in his breed by many generations of hard service. Patrasche were of a race which had toiled hard and cruelly from sire to son in Flanders many a world — slaves of slaves, dogs of the people, beasts of the collar and the harness, creatures that lived in their sinews in the gall of the cart, and died breaking their ribs on the flints of the streets. Patrasche had been born of parents himself had labored nearly all their days over the sharp - set terrain of the various cities and the long, shadowless, weary roads of the two Flanders and of Brabant. He had been born to no other heritage than those of pain and of toil. He had been fed on curses and baptized with guilt. Why not? It was a Christian country, and Patrasche was but a mouse. Before he was fully grown he had known the bitter gall of the cart and the collar.

The amount of woody fiber or cellulose is considerable for rice with its husk, but only slight on samples without husk. The seat of the mineral matter of the grain of rice is mainly within the husk, and as this ash is very valuable as fuel for the yeast plant, it is an open question whether it would not be suitable to using for brewing purposes rice with no husk. The comparatively largest amount of fat is contained in maize ; and as such oil is not desirable for brewing purposes, different recommendations have been advanced for freeing the grain from it. In the following table some of the mineral constituents of the three kinds of grain are compared with each other. These data refer to 100 parts of ash, that are taken from analysis given by Dr. Emil Wolf. The excessive amount of ash in rice with its husk is very remarkable, and as this mineral matter consists to a great extent of vegetable acid and potash, the larger part of it is soluble in water. Consequently on using rice with its husk for brewing purposes, agricultural yeast will need provided with a considerable amount of nutritive substance.

An old duck wandered into the barn and caught sight of herself in the mirror. " Here is another duck, " she mumbled. " I wonder who she is. " And she walked toward the reflection. " She is rather friendly, " the voice went on. " She is walking toward me. What large feet she has, but her feathers are very handsome. " Just then she bumped into the mirror. " Goodness! " she cried ; " if that duck isn't in a glass dish! Why are you in there? " " Well, you needn't answer if you don't want to, " she said, walking away. " A glass case is a good place for you. " Just and a pig came along, and turned around, he came in front of the mirror. " What are you doing here? " he asked, thinking he saw another pig. His nose hit the glass, and he stepped backward. " So you suck in our glass pen, " he said. " You are not very handsome, and your nose is not so long as mine ; I cannot see why you should have a glass pen. " And away he trotted to tell the other pigs about the very plain - looking man.

Of all the creatures that walked or swam or turned, Timothy Turtle liked boys the least of all. He remembered that if they ever did anything except kicked stones he had never caught them at it. " It's a wonder " — he often remarked — " it's a wonder that there's a stone left anywhere along this bay. I've lived here a good many years ; and no man ever spied me sunning myself on a rock in the water without trying to hit me. " Once in a great while some youngster was told as to bounce a rope off Mr. Turtle's back. And when the old scamp flopped into the water he always heard a great stream from the bank. At such times as likely as not Timothy had been awakened from a sound sleep. But when that jeering noise greeted his ears he knew at once what had awakened him.

Microbial communities can be characterized using certain tests that look at the DNA molecules of the microbes. DNA, as you might already know, is the genetic material of the cell. It contains instructions, in the form of genes, which provide the blueprint for creating the organism. Studying specific genes becomes a good way for scientists to learn about microbial culture. For example, we can look at a gene called the 16S rRNA enzyme. The 16S rRNA gene tells us about the relationships of microbes, and that is why it is called a " phylogenetic " marker gene. " Phylogenetic " is derived from Greek words meaning the origin of a tribe or a family. There were other marker genes used in this study, too, including gene coding for special proteins called enzymes — specifically enzymes that were important in using sulfur for energy. By comparing the DNA of these microbes using several different methods, which will be described thoroughly, we were required to study three things : how many microbes were present in the samples taken from the groundwater, how those microbes grew over time in each microcosm, and how those microbes were transported through each other and to other microbes that we know about.

Agony's eyes traveled over to the group surrounding Pom - pom and rested upon the girl where, next to Pom - pom herself, was the center of the pack. She was looking much like Agony herself, with intensely black hair, snow white forehead and richly red lips, though a little slighter in build and somewhat taller. A frank friendliness beamed from her clear dark eyes and her smile was warm and sincere. Agony felt drawn to her and jealous of her at the same time. The most popular girl in camp. That was the title Agony used with all her soul. Never appear prominent ; to be popular, was Agony's chief aim for life ; and to be pointed out in any crowd as their most popular girl seemed the one thing to the world most desirable to her. She, too, would be prominent and popular, she resolved ; she, too, would be pointed out in the crowd.

It was in the midst of school - hours that the red carriage came driving up the avenue, although Philip Ross, lifting one hand from the slate over which he had been bending for the last half hour, rose hastily, threw down his pencil and hurried from the room, paying no attention to Miss Fisk's query, " Where are you going, Philip? " or on command, " Come back instantly : it is quite contrary to rules for pupils to leave the school - room during after hours of recitation, without permission. " Indeed he had reached the foot of his staircase before the last word had left her lips ; she being very slow and precise in speech and action, while his movements were of the quickest. " What now is to be done in this emergency? " soliloquized the governess, unconsciously thinking aloud. " Miss Gertrude Ross, " turning to a girl of nine whose merry blue eyes were twinkling with fun, " follow your brother at once and inform Papa that I cannot permit any such act of insubordination ; and he must return instantly to the job of such duties. "

The atoms of a chemical element typically exist in different types. These are called isotopes. They have the same number of protons ( and electrons ), but different numbers of neutrons. Different isotopes of the same element have differing masses. Mass is the word meaning how much substance ( or matter ) something has. Things with different masses have different weights. Because different isotopes have same numbers of neutrons, they do not consistently weigh the same or have the same mass. Different isotopes of the same element have the same atomic number. They have the same number of protons. The same number is decided by the number of protons. Isotopes have different mass numbers, literally, meaning they have different proportions of neutrons. The word isotope, meaning at the same place, comes from the fact that isotopes appear at the same place on the periodic table.

In France during World War I, the 142nd Infantry Regiment, 36th Division, had a company of Indians who spoke 26 languages and dialects. Two officers were selected to supervise a communications system staffed by 18 Choctaw individuals. The team transmitted messages relating to troop movements and their own tactical plans in their native tongue. Soldiers from indigenous tribes, including the Cheyenne, Comanche, Cherokee, Osage, and Yankton Sioux also were enlisted to communicate as code talkers. Previous with their arrival in France, many Germans had broken an American code used, resulting in the expulsion of many soldiers. However, the Germans never broke the American Indians'" code, " and these warriors became affectionately categorized as " code talkers. " During World War II, the Army used American Indians in its signal communications operations in both the European and Pacific theaters of operations. Student code talkers were instructed in basic military communications techniques. The code talkers then prepared their own words for military terms that never existed in their own native tongue. For instance, the word for " colonel " originally translated to " flying eagle, " " fighter plane " became " hummingbird, " " minesweeper " became " beaver, " " half - track " became " race track, " and " pyrotechnic " became " fancy fire. "

First they went to the kitchen where Mammy'Ria was getting ready to cook the Thanksgiving dinner ; then out to the farmhouse, where there were two new red calves, and some little puppies clinging to Juno, the eldest, for them to see. Then they climbed the barnyard fence and made haste to his pasture where grandfather kept his woolly sheep. " Y - a! " said the sheep when someone saw the children ; but then, Grandpa always said that, no matter when happened. There were cows in this pasture, too, and Mary Virginia was afraid of them, even though she knew that they were the mothers of the calves she had seen in the barnyard.

And this glass was stuck up on a stump where the moon - beam that Uncle Wiggily was following shone on it and reflected once again.
