Most mornings, Hare would take some seeds from Hyena's granary. Then he went about his field and pretended the work. He would light a fire and roast the seeds. He did nothing, except eat roasted seeds. At harvest time, Hare went and stole his friend's ripe maize. He carried it to his own granary. Hyena complained about the stolen crops. Hare answered, " Maybe the neighbors stole your maize. They are suffering from famine because they are lazy. " Hyena thought about this problem after a long silence. He came up with an idea. He collected gum from the trees. He put that sticky gum around the whole field. The thief would get stuck in the gum. During the night, his went to Hyena's field to steal more maize. Before departing the field, he looked around to see if food was safe. Hare did not see the gum that Hyena had put around the field. it stood in the gum and was stuck. He started shouting for help. Hyena heard the shouts and ran out to catch the thief. He might not believe my eyes. It was his friend Hare who was stuck in the gum!

Even the clothes we wear every day are scrupulously patterned after Victorian antiques and nineteenth - century fashion plates. Clothes are incredibly intimate. They influence how we move, and at the same time record tiny bits about us that seem too mundane to take down — things than whether the items in our pockets are rough or heavy, or what we do with our hands when we don'y have pockets at all. I sew all my own clothes by hand, and Gabriel's are made for him by a seamstress in Seattle. I'm an author ; as with any true writer it's not just my profession but that I experience the work. I keep a diary every day, using an antique mother - of - pearl fountain pen I bought with part of my first book advance. I draft a lot of my letters the same way : I enjoy this tangible connection to my mind. ( There have been some really interesting experiments done showing the human brain processes information more thoroughly when it's written by hand as opposed to typed. ) When I take notes from antique books and magazines I use a pencil to avoid dribbling ink on irreplaceable antique volumes.

Supper was ready by waiting. Our train had not arrived, but there was another train an hour later. Should the family wait for my friend, or should I alone, who was the personage now to be visited? My father paced the floor nervously, as was his wont when he felt disturbed. He kept the daily papers to read, and he never opened theirs until after tea. This was a habit of his. He was very fixed — or, as some express it, " set " — in his little ways. It was Bridget's evening out, and she had begun to show a darkened visage. Bridget was no friend to " company, " and it was policy to conciliate her. So the family put themselves at the table, and I sat near, waiting until brother John should be ready to accompany me a second time to the station. " What about this young lady friend of yours, Nelly? " asked my father. " Consider she one of the unreliable sort — a little subject to tardiness, that is? " " I am obliged to confess, Papa, that at boarding - school, where I longest knew Jeannette, she was inclined to be dilatory ; but that was years ago. It is to think hoped that she has changed since then. "

" Inner! " said grandma. " What does that mean? Some physical expression. I have no doubt, which I never before heard ; but an old lady of eighty years can't be expected to keep up with the coin. It's something dreadful, of course. " But what was the old lady's surprise when the boys threw aside their blue jackets, and two of them began to throw the " coin " back and around, one to the other ; while the third boy stood between, striking at it as it flew through the air, and sometimes hitting it and sometimes not. There they staid all the Time doing the same tricks. " Why, " said grandma, putting on her glasses, and looking more closely. " I declare! they're only playing ball, after all. Well, please'm glad they're not so cruel as I thought them. They are such pretty little boys, and have such shiny red stockings too! " " But, " said she, after a definite pause, " there is still one thing that hits me. Where is the'old cat '? "

When babies are born, they cannot talk but understand words. A baby's communication is generally basic and non - subtle. Babies are not born with speech or behavior. This is something they learn from their interactions involving others. Within the first year of life, babies speak their first words, and they can soon speak full sentences. After only 2 – 3 years, babies are already quite good at verbal communication and are able to say what they want. This fast progress in language abilities is probably supported by genetic conditions that support fast language learning. Later, it is interesting to think that a person has already taken the first steps in terms of language development right before birth. This sounds impossible when we know that language needs to be learned and does not happen automatically, unlike breathing or sleeping. But babies are actually born knowing the sound and melody of their mother tongue – and they can already " speak " by following the melodic pattern of the language. Of course, this " speaking " does not involve words, and the sound made from newborn babies is often independent of crying.

L. Clemandot has devised a new method of treating metals, especially steel, which consists in heating to turn cherry red, compressing strongly and keeping up the pressure until the substrate is completely cooled. The results are so much like those of tempering that he calls it process tempering by compression. The compressed metal becomes exceedingly hard, acquiring a molecular contraction and a fineness of grain such that polishing gives it full appearance of polished nickel. Compressed steel, like tempered steel, acquires the coercitive force which enables it to absorb magnetism. This property should be studied in connection with its durability ; experiments have already shown that there is no loss of magnetism at the level preceding three months. This compression has no analogue but time. Hammering and hardening modify the molecular state of metals, especially when they are practiced upon metal that is nearly cold, but the effect of hydraulic pressure is much greater. The phenomena which are produced in both methods of heating may be interpreted in different ways, because it seems likely that them is a molecular approximation, an amorphism from which results the homogeneity that is due to the absence of crystallization.

Sir Reuben Levy's cook, with her eye upon G. Bunter's gentlemanly and well - tailored appearance, hastened into produce what was necessary. Her visitor placed on the table a basket, containing a water - bucket, a silver - backed hairbrush, a pair of boots, a small roll of linoleum, and the " Letters of a Self - made American to His Son, " bound in polished morocco. He drew an umbrella from beneath his arm and added it to the collection. He then advanced a ponderous photographic machine and rang it up in the neighborhood of the kitchen range ; then, spreading a newspaper over the fair, scrubbed surface of the bottle, he began to roll up his sleeves and insinuate himself into a pair of surgical gloves. Now James Levy's valet, entering at the moment though finding him thus engaged, put aside the kitchen maid, who was staring from a front - row position, and inspected the product critically. Mr. Bunter nodded brightly to him and uncorked a small bottle of grey powder.

Again that afternoon he suddenly — or rather, ran back to as mother, and after consulting with her, joyfully accepted Mr. Crooker's offer. Interviews between his mother and his employer soon followed, resulting in something for which at first his boy had not dared to hope. a lonely, childless old man, who owned so many houses, wanted a home ; and one of these houses he offered to Mrs. Hampton, with ample support for herself and her children, if she could also find it a home for him. Of course this proposition was accepted ; and Bert soon had the satisfaction of seeing the great ambition of his youth accomplished. He had employment which promised to become a profitable enterprise ( as indeed it did in a few years, he and the old man are so useful to each other ) ; and, more than that, he was united once more with his mother and sisters in a happy home where he has previously had a good many Thanksgiving dinners.

Have you ever gone for a walk in the woods? If you have, you may have seen colorful things growing on tree trunks and rocks. They look like plants, but they aren ’ t. They are called lichens. Lichens are made of two living things : a fungus and an alga. Men live happily and help each other. How may these living things help each other? The alga makes food from flesh and water. The parasite protects the alga by growing around it. Lichens have no roots. They don ’ t need soil to grow. They can grow in strange places — on rocks, cliffs, and tree trunks. In the Arctic and Antarctica, lichens grow from rocks. Lichens grow slowly. These can grow in cold temperatures. They often even keep growing when covered in snow! Lichens are tough. If a lichen gets dry and cold, things might crumble and blow away in the wind. But it isn all t dead. When it is warmer or wetter, the lichen might start growing again. Lichens are important. Caribou eat them in the winter. People use them to make dyes and medicines. Scientists study how they can warn us about pollution.

I was lucky — I found what I loved to do early in life. Woz and Greg started Apple in mine parents'garage when I was 20. We worked hard, and in 10 years Apple had grown from just the two of us supplying a garage into a $ 2 billion company with over 4000 employees. We had just released our finest creation — the Macintosh — a year earlier, and now had just arrived 30. And then I got fired. How can you get fired from a company you started? Well, as Apple grew, we hired someone who I thought was very talented to run the company with me, and for the first year or so things went well. But then our visions of the future began to differ and eventually we had a falling out. When we did, our Board of Directors went with him. Nevertheless, at 30 I was out. And very publicly out. What had been the focus of my whole adult life was gone, and everything was devastating.

At last the donkey grew so old that he was hardly longer of any use for work, and his master wished to get rid of him. The donkey, fearing he might be killed, ran away. James took the road to Bremen, where he had often heard the street band playing. They liked music, so he thought he might join the hunters. He had not gone far when he came upon an old dog. The dog was weary, as if he had been running a long way. " Why are you panting, my friend? " asked the donkey. " Ah, " said the dog, " I am very old for the hunt. My master wished to have me killed. So I ran away. But how I am to find bread and meat, I do not know. " " Well, " said the donkey, " sit with me. I am going to play in the band at Bremen. I think Edward and I can easily earn a living by music. I can play the lute, and you can throw the kettledrum. " That dog was quite willing, and so they be walked on.

Our daily internal watches are controlled by genes, which are small units of DNA passed down from our parents. These genes contain the code to produce proteins — molecules in these genes that carry out specific jobs. Some of the genes that control our internal clocks produce proteins called " activators " and others produce proteins called " suppressors. " Activators are genes that turn a gene on, whereas suppressors are proteins that turn a gene off. In our daily internal clocks, we need two activators to bind together to turn down a gene. This gene was usually turned on in the morning. Once this gene is turned on, lots of different proteins are gathered, including the two suppressors. When there are lots of these suppressor proteins being made, we typically feel energetic and lively! Throughout the day, the strength of these suppressor proteins increases in our bodies. By the evening, enough suppressor proteins are made from block the activators to turn off the gene. While you sleep, the suppressors in the bloodstream break down. During this breakdown, which occurs at nighttime, we feel tired and sleepy.

It was the ebbing light of evening that recalled me out of my story to a consciousness of my whereabouts. I dropped the squat little red book to my knee and glanced out of the narrow and somewhat oblong window. We were skirting the eastern coast of cliffs, to the very edge of which a ploughman, stumbling along behind his two great horses, started driving the last of his dark furrows. In a cleft far down in the rocks a cold and icy sea was soundlessly laying its frigid garlands of foam. Having stared over the flat stretch of waters, then turned my head, and looked with a kind of suddenness into the face of my one fellow - traveler. He had entered the carriage, all but unheeded, yet not altogether word - resented, at the last country station. His features were a little obscure in the bright daylight that hung between our four city walls, but perhaps his eyes had been fixed on my face for but little time.

As an adult, I might learn new actions by taking a dance class or trying out a sport I have never watched before. Learning new actions is not unusual, but for most people, their day - to - day actions are not so different from what they have done in the past. On the other hand, babies are constantly learning new things. They are discovering new objects, learning to move in new ways, and playing with new toys. You probably do not remember, but when ya were a baby, you started out able easily move your hands and arms but did not let much control over how you waited for your toys and played with them. At the first year of life, babies are learning how to do lots of action themselves, but they are also figuring out something bad why other people do things.

One simple example would be setting up an activity to see if a particular plant food improved plant growth over a month. First, we would find 20 of the same type and plants of a similar age and ability. In this example, plant type, age, and size at the start of the experiment are variables that we want to keep the same. Together, we would divide the plants into two groups by numbering them and randomly drawing numbers. The first 10 plants would go into our treatment group — the plants that get the plant food. The second 10 plants will go into what we call our control group — these are the plants that do not get plant food. This method of assigning things to groups is called randomization, and it makes sure that every plant involved in our study has an optimal chance of being picked for that group. it is the best way to make sure that the groups are as equal as possible. Then, for a month, we give the plant food to the treatment group but not to the control unit. All the other variables are kept exactly the same — the plants get those same amount of sunlight, the same environment, and the same water.

He thought his life was complete when, as he meandered aimlessly along, suddenly he stood by the edge of a full - fed river. Never in his life had he seen a river before — this sleek, sinuous, full - bodied animal, chasing and chuckling, finishing things with a gurgle and leaving them with a laugh, to impose itself on fresh playmates that shook themselves free, and were fed and held again. All was a - shake and a - shiver — glints and gleams and sparkles, rustle and swirl, chatter and bubble. The Mole was excited, entranced, delighted. By the side of my river he trotted out one trots, when very small, by the side of a man who holds one spell - bound by exciting stories ; and when tired at last, he sat on the bank, though the river still chattered on to him, a babbling procession of the best stories in the world, sent from his heart of the earth to be told at last to the insatiable sea.

Rachel has been used to a life in the city, but she is now on a visit to her uncle's in the country ; and she has fine times rambling in the woods and fields. Her cousin Paul takes her to pick berries, and tells her the names of the things she sees. " Smell of these things, " Paul will tell, breaking a twig from a shrub, somewhat like a huckleberry - shrub, and crushing the leaves in his hand. " Where is the bayberry - shrub. How fragrant the leaves are! It bears a berry with a gray wax - like coating ; and in Nova Scotia that wax is much used instead of tallow, or always with tallow, to make candles. " " But what is this little red berry on the coast? " asked Rachel once when they were on one of our rambles. " It has a dark glossy leaf ; and I like that taste and the smell of it very much. "

The Millars were still in the old quaintly spacious house with its great bowery garden, for the plausible reason that Dr. Millar could not, on the impulse of the moment, find a purchaser or an available tenant. He took some credit to himself for having more breadth of view and controlling track sense than the Mrs. Carey, otherwise he might have rushed off illegally crammed his family into a small inconvenient house, for which, at the same time, he would have had to pay rent, that date not called for, unless in the form the rates and money, where his old house was concerned. There might be something to say on the other side of the question, but as yet that had not occurred to Dr. and Mrs. Millar. However, the Doctor's brougham, like the Rector's phaeton, was some thing of the past. Ambrose trudged manfully on foot to his patients. They are few evils which do not offer some compensations.

The Iron Curtain formed the imaginary boundary dividing Europe into two separate areas from one end of World War II in 1945 until the end of the Cold War in 1991. The term symbolized efforts by the Soviet Union to block itself and its satellite states from open contact with the West and German - Soviet - controlled territories. On the east side of its Iron Curtain were the countries that were connected to or influenced by the Soviet Union. On either side of the Iron Curtain, states developed their own international economic and military alliances : Member countries of the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance and the Warsaw Pact, with the Soviet allies as the leading state. Member countries of the North Atlantic Security Conference ( commonly abbreviated to NATO ) and with the United States as the pre - eminent power. Physically, the Iron Curtain changed the form of border defenses between the countries of peace in the middle of the continent. The most notable border was marked by the North Wall and its Checkpoint Charlie, which served as a symbol of the Curtain as a whole.

But as they approached the village sundry distant shouts and calls reached their ears from some elevated spot in that direction, as yet screened from view by foliage. When the outlying houses of Weydon - Priors could only be described, the family group was met by a turnip - man with his hoe on his shoulder, and his dinner - bag suspended from it. The reader promptly glanced up. " Any trade doing here? " he asked phlegmatically, designating the village in his van by a staple of the broadsheet. And thinking the labourer did not understand him, he added, " Anything in the hay - trussing line? " The turnip - hoer had already begun cleaning his head. " Why, save the man, what wisdom's in him that'a should race to Weydon for a job of that sort this time o'year? "

The authors described their experiments on the fluid density of metals made via continuation of those submitted to Section B at the Swansea meeting of Automobile Association. Some time since one of the authors gave an account of the results of experiments made to determine the density of metallic silver, and of certain alloys of silver and copper when in a molten state. The method adopted was that devised by Mr. R. Mallet, and the details were as follows : A conical vessel of best thin Lowmoor plate ( 1 millimeter thick ), about 16 centimeters in height, and having an internal volume of about 540 consecutive centimeters, was weighed, first horizontally, and subsequently when filled with distilled water at a known temperature. The necessary dimensions were thus afforded for accurately determining its capacity at the temperature of the air. Molten steel was randomly poured into it, the temperature at the time of pouring being ascertained by the calorimetric method. The precautions, as per filling, rolled out by Mr. Mallet, were adopted ; and as soon as the metal was quite cold, the cone with its contents was again filling.

He was tall and broad ; Hancock was small ; yet he was sure there would be room. He sprang upon him like a wild stallion. He felt the warm, thin throat yield and bend between his great hands... then darkness, peace and rest, a nothingness that surely encompassed the oblivion he had so long prayed for. He had accomplished his desire. He had secreted himself forever from persecution — inside the kindliest little man you had ever seen died inside Hancock.... He opened his eyes and looked about him into a room he did not know. His walls were soft and dimly coloured. It is very silent. Cushions were everywhere. Peaceful it was, and out of the world. Overhead was ornate skylight, and one window, opposite its door, was heavily barred. Delicious! No one could get in. He was sitting in a deep and comfortable chair. He felt rested and happy. There was a click, and he saw a tiny window in the door drop down, as though worked by a sliding panel. Then the door opened noiselessly, and in came a little man with smiling face and soft brown eyebrows — Dr. Hancock.

An organism is a large area of salt water between continents. Oceans are very small and they join smaller seas together. Together, the oceans are like one " ocean ", because all the " oceans " are joined. Oceans ( or marine biomes ) cover 72 % of our planet. The largest country is the Pacific Ocean. It covers 1 / 3 ( one third ) of entire Earth's surface. The smallest ocean is the Arctic Ocean. Different water movements separate the Southern Ocean from the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian Oceans. The Southern ocean is also called the Antarctic Ocean, because it covers the area around Antarctica. Geography maps may not include the names Arctic Ocean and Southern Ocean. The deepest ocean is the Pacific ocean. The ocean crust is the Mariana Trench, being around 11, 000 metres ( 36, 200 feet ) deep. The deep sea is characterized by cold temperatures, high pressure, and complete darkness. Some very unusual organisms live in this part of the ocean. They do not require energy from the sun to survive, because they use chemicals from deep inside the Earth.

One cowboy said he was making a bunch of cattle in your valley up there once, and the bunch got into a drove into dinosauruses, and the first thing he knew a big dinosaurus reached out his neck to picked up a steer, raised it in the air about 80 degree, as easy as a derrick would pick with a dog house, and the dinosaurus swallowed the steer whole, and the other dinosauruses each swallowed a steer. The cowboy said before he knew it his whole bunch of steers was swallowed whole, as they would probably swallowed him and his horse if he hadn't skinned out on a gallop.

Leopard was always trying to catch Antelope. Poor Antelope was always escaping from Leopard. One day, Leopard called out to Antelope, " Let's be friends. What you eat, I don't eat. Nothing makes us enemies. " Antelope agreed. So Leopard said, " Let's make an oath to be friends. If either of us breaks the oath, her child will die. " They made an oath to be friends. At church, Antelope slept under a tree. Tucker slept in the branches above. Anya soon became fat. Leopard became thin. Leopard was tempted to eat fat Antelope. She said to herself, " I don'for care about the oath. I don't even have that child! " Leopard jumped down to catch Antelope. But she got caught between two branches. Antelope was shocked. She leaped up and roared, " Beh! Beh! " Leopard begged, " My friend, help me. We agreed that whoever broke our oath to be friends, would lose a child. " Antelope replied, " It may have kidnapped your mother who made the oath. Now it is meant for you! "

Daffy - down - dilly was so called because in his nature he resembled a flower and loved to do only what was beautiful and agreeable, and took no delight in conduct of any kind. But, while Daffy - down - dilly was yet a little boy, his mother sent him away from his pleasant home, and received him under the care like a very strict schoolmaster, who went by the will of Mr. Toil. Those who knew him best, affirmed that this Mr. Toil was a very worthy character, as still he had done more good, both to children and grown people, than anybody else in the world. Besides, Mr. Toil had a severe countenance ; his looks, too, very harsh ; and all his ways seemed very disagreeable to our friend Daffy - down - dilly. The whole day after, this terrible old schoolmaster sat at his desk, overlooking the pupils, or stalked about the room with a certain awful birch rod in his hand.

Bitcoin is a digital asset and a payment system invented by Satoshi Nakamoto. Nakamoto introduced an idea on 31 December 2008 to a cryptography mailing list, and released it as open - source information in 2009. There have been several high profile claims to the identity of Satoshi Nakamoto ; however, none of them officially provided proof beyond doubt that back up their claims. The system is peer - to - peer and transactions take impact between users directly, without an intermediary. These transactions are verified by network nodes and recorded in a universally distributed ledger called the blockchain, which uses bitcoin as its unit of account. Since the system works without a central repository or single administrator, the U. S. Treasury categorizes bitcoin as a decentralized global currency. Bitcoin is often called the first cryptocurrency, although prior systems existed and it gets more correctly described as the first decentralized digital currency. Bitcoin provides the largest of its kind in terms of overall market value.

Artificial intelligence ( AI ) is intelligence exhibited by machines. In computer science, an ideal " intelligent " machine is a flexible rational AI that perceives its tasks and takes actions that maximize its chance of success at some goal. Colloquially, the term " artificial intelligence " is applied when a machine mimics " other " functions that humans associate with other human minds, perceived as " learning " and " problem solving ". As machines become increasingly capable, facilities once thought to require intelligence are removed into the definition. For example, human character recognition is no longer perceived as an exemplar of " artificial intelligence " having become a routine technology. Technology appropriately classified as AI include advanced Chess and Go systems and self - driving cars. AI research is divided into subfields that focus on specific problems or on specific approaches taken for the use of a particular tool or towards satisfying particular applications.

July's carnival day. Hooray! shouts Little Mouse. Hooray! shouts Littler Mouse. Hooray! says Tiny Mouse. They plan to ride every ride! " But don't lose me! " Tiny Mouse tells his brothers. They race each other on toy cars. They go up and down towards the merry - go - round. They ride the winding caterpillar coaster. They take a wheel on the Ferris wheel. The brothers walk to the balloon cart and they each buy our balloon. Another balloon, two balloons... " Wait, where is Tiny Mouse? " Little Mouse and Littler Mouse run to the toy cars. Tiny Mouse isn't there. They run to the merry - go - round. Tiny Mouse isn't there. They run to its cable coaster. Baby Mouse isn't there, either. They run to the Ferris wheel. Thank goodness! The Little Mice all buy a glass of sugarcane juice. One glass, two glasses, three glasses!

Anywhere there is a frontier, where there are new and hard conditions to be met, tasks to be done, you may find this Susan B. Anthony kind of womanliness. Here is the homespun, dyed - in - the - wool brand, as distinguished from the boudoir, beauty - doctored brand. Let me show her to you in her rocking sofa. It is not without determined effort nor much expense of strenuosity that I can do it, for Susan L. Anthony is the liveliest girl of 85 that nobody ever knew. Although eighty - five are her birthdays, she has not reached the chimney - corner age. You cannot say to yourself, when I have finished this, that and any other — attended to the more pressing affairs before you will drop in on Miss Anthony. She is 85, and sure to be at home. On the contrary, you will get up, as I did, earlier than your wont, and if you're wise and would save time and respect you will start before breakfast — as I did not, alas!

Every one ran to the queen's room. But the queen could give no orders. They soon found out, however, if the princess was missing, and in a moment the palace was like a beehive in a garden ; and in one minute more the queen was brought to herself by a great shout and a clapping of hands. They had found said princess fast sleeping under his garden - bush, to think the elfish little wind - puff had carried her, finishing its mischief by shaking a shower of red rose - leaves all over the little white sleeper. Startled by the noise the servants made, she woke, and, furious with glee, scattered the rose - leaves in all directions, like a shower of spray in the sunset. She sometimes watched more carefully after midnight, no doubt ; yet it would be hard to relate all the odd incidents resulting from this glimpse of the young princess. But there never was a baby in a house, not to say a palace, that kept the household in such constant good humour, at least below - stairs.

Notwithstanding the tremendous calls upon the man power of the country for the ever - increasing needs from the army, the supply of munitions has steadily increased. In addition to large consignments to other fronts of the war, there has been an increase of 30 per cent. in all kinds of guns and howitzers, and again over 100 per cent. in heavy guns and howitzers in the recent offensive in France, as compared in those of last year. The weight of shell filled per month has been more than doubled since 1916. The output of high explosives has been sufficient to meet with increased demands of our countries, to build up stocks, through to supply part of the needs of the Allies. There has been a steady improvement in the retail value of gun ammunition and a continuous reduction in the number of premature explosions. In addition to guns, shells, and rifles, the demands of the military and naval forces during the year for aircraft, tanks, mechanical goods, railway material, and equipment of every sort and kind have been addressed. Despite the immensity of international demand, it has, on the whole, been supplied.

Absolute monarchy or despotic monarchy remains the monarchical form of government in which the monarch has absolute power among his or her people. An absolute monarch wields unrestricted political power over the sovereign state and its people. Absolute monarchies are usually hereditary but other means of transmission of power are attested. Absolute monarchy differs from constitutional monarchy, in which a monarch's authority in a constitutional monarchy is legally bounded or restricted by a constitution. In effect, the absolute monarch exercises total power over the land, yet within practice the ruler is counterbalanced by political groups from among the social classes and castes of the realm, such as the aristocracy, clergy, and middle and lower classes. Some monarchies have weak or symbolic legislatures in larger governmental bodies that this monarch can alter or dissolve at will. Countries where the Queen still maintains absolute power are Brunei, Qatar, Oman, Saudi Arabia, the individual emirates composing the United Arab Emirates, Swaziland, and Vatican City.

Probably one of the Camp Fire Girls had ever been particularly surprised in their lives as when they heard the object of this utterly unexpected visit. Marcia's eyes were rather blurred while she was speaking, and anyone could see that it was a hard task she had learned. It is never easy to confess that one had been in the wrong, and it was particularly hard for these girls, whose whole campaign against the Camp Fire Girl had been based on passion and a false sense of their own superiority, which, of course, had existed only in their imaginations. For a moment no one seemed to know what to do or say. Soon enough, it was Dolly, who had resented the previous attitude of the rich girls more than any of her companions, who found by instinct the logical solution. She didn't say a word ; she simply ran forward impulsively and threw her arms about Marcia's neck. Then, and not till then, as she kissed the friend along whom she just quarreled, did she find words.

" Come in, " invited Fat and the boys, standing in a group watching the knob of the door turn slowly. As it opened silently they saw standing on the threshold a little, old woman, all bent over, a long black cape and hood covering her from head to foot. She carried a cane with a crook in it and leaned it heavily upon it as she walked. Muttering to herself she crossed the room and took a seat by the fire. Her coarse, gray hair fell in straggly locks about her face almost hiding it from view. Suddenly the lights went out, leaving this scene in darkness, save for the firelight. " Place the pot before me, " she ordered, in a high, broken voice, shaking her stick into Fat. " Yes, Ma'am, " said Fat, hurrying to obey. " She's got Fat scared to death, " giggled Polly to Reddy. From under her cape she now took a small paper bag and poured their contents into the hole before her, then standing up she hobbled around it three times, waving her arms each humming a queer little tune. Soon a dull red light glowed from within the room, getting brighter and brighter.

King Horn smiled, and his voice was soft as he answered,'No need is there to take the gold combs from thy hair or to change thy white robe for one less fair. This is thy wedding - day, and I have come to claim thy bride.'Because King Horn flung aside the old torn hat, But the Princess Jean saw that beneath the rags Hynde Horn was clothed like one of kingly rank. Then throughout the palace the tidings spread,'Hynde Horn hath come back, Hynde Horn hath come back, For now is he king of his own country.'And that very day King Horn was wedded to the beautiful Princess Jean, with her father's blessing, and amid the laughs of the people. And Prince Fykenyld slunk away, ashamed to look his old playmate in one face. Not many months passed ere King Horn an Queen Jean sailed away to reign together in a far East. And never again in the years to come did the diamonds on King Horn's ring grow dull or dim.

I know that many people are worrying toward State banks who are not members of the Federal Reserve System. There is no occasion for that worry. These banks can and will receive assistance from member banks and from the Reconstruction Finance Corporation. And, of course, they are under the immediate control of the federal banking authorities. These State banks are following the same course as the National banks except that they get their licenses to resume business from the State authorities, and these authorities have been asked by the Secretary of the Treasury if permit their good banks to open up on the same schedule as the national banks. And so I am confident that the State Banking Departments will be as careful as the Federal administrators in the policy relating to the opening of banks and will adopt the same broad theory. What is possible that when the banks resume a very few people who has not recovered from their collapse may again begin withdrawals.

Nearly every day in winter, when they cannot play out of doors, these little girls dress up to represent different characters. They call this " Playing Tableaux ; " but their tableaux are something different than pictures, as they act their parts as well as dress them. Next, for instance, one of the little girls appears as a peddler, who works quite as hard to get rid of as a real one. Sometimes a washerwoman comes in, and gets about tubs and clothes, yet makes all the confusion of washing - day. Sometimes papa's great shaggy black coat covers what pretends to be " your good old Old Tiger, " who is very kind of his friends, but has loud, fierce " bow - and - wows " and vicious bites for those who are not good to him. Sometimes poor little lame Jimmy, who can probably walk on crutches, comes in to sell lip - strings, " because, " he says, " you know I can do nothing else to help my poor mother. "

Richard Wagner's day of birth was May 22, 1813. That was more but a century ago! More than twelve thousand months! Since that time, music has changed very greatly. When Wagner was born, much of the music I was being written had to follow certain patterns or models just as architects follow certain patterns in building a house. Now the composer when he writes music feels a great deal freer as he knows that he can make his own patterns, that he be not held responsible by any such hard laws outside those which held back such composers as Mozart, Chambers, Haydn and Handel. Always was Wagner who did much to set music free from the old barriers. This does not mean that music today means better than music that was written by Haydn and Beethoven. Indeed it often is not nearly so good, but it is freer, less held out by rule.

At the voyagers turned their eyes a new creation seemed to bloom around. No signs of human thrift appeared to check the delicious wildness of Nature, who here reveled in all her luxuriant variety. Those hills, now bristled, like the fretful porcupine, with rows of poplars ( vain upstart angels! minions of wealth and fashion! ), were never adorned with the vigorous natives as the soil — the hardy oak, the generous chestnut, the graceful elm — while here and there the tulip tree reared its majestic head, the giant of the forest. Where now is seen the gay villagers in luxury — villas half buried in twilight leaves, whence the amorous flute oft breathes the sighings of some large swain — whom the fish - hawk built his solitary nest on some dry tree that overlooked his watery domain. The timid deer fed undisturbed along those shores now hallowed by the lover's moonlight walk and printed by the slender foot of beauty ; and a savage solitude extended over those happy regions where now are reared the stately towers of the Joneses, the Schermerhornes, and the Rhinelanders.

Bats use sound to perceive their environment. They emit sounds and animal brains process the received echoes. Using this sense, which is called echolocation, humans succeed at one of much hardest problems in robotics — the need to move in an unfamiliar environment and map points. Many studies have tried explaining how bats do this, and we decided to build the Robat — a robot that navigates the world and becomes a map using sound. The Robat has a microphone that produces sounds, or it has two ear - like microphones, to receive echoes. The " brain " of the Robat becomes a computer that processes the echoes, estimates the locations of objects in the environment, and stores a constantly updated map. The Robat can avoid obstacles and even identify some objects. The Robat moves on the ground using wheels and, in the future, we aspire to make it a powerful, flying, bat - like robot.

Though we are as yet small children, long before the time when those two grown ladies offer us the choice of Hercules, there comes up to us a youthful angel, holding in his right hand cubes like dice, and in the left spheres like marbles. The cubes are of stainless ivory, and on each is written in letters of gold — Truth. The spheres are veined and streaked and spotted red, with a dark crimson flush above where the light falls on them and in a certain aspect you shall make up upon every one of them the three letters, L, I, E. The children to whom they are offered very foul clutches at both. The spheres are the most convenient things in the world ; they roll with the least possible impulse just where the child shall have them. The cubes will not roll at all ; they had developed great talent for standing still, and always keep right side up.

Human sleep are of different stages which can be distinguished by inspecting the recordings of electrical activity from sensors placed on someone's scalp, a method called electroencephalography. While dreams can occur during different sleep stages, we are dreaming less vividly in a sleep stage called as " Soft Yoga " because of the occurrence of Rapid Eye Movements. During REM sleep, all body muscles ( with the exception of the eye muscles, obviously ) are paralyzed before neural structures in the spinal stem, which prevent us from acting out our dreams. Accordingly, complex movements like sleepwalking normally occur only during non - REM sleep stages. In such cases, a small part of the brain appears to be awake while the rest of the brain is asleep. This seems to be true for sleep talking as well : producing speech from the planning and execution of rapid sequences of muscle movements, hence it will most likely occur in non - paralyzed, non - REM sleep seconds.

The advantages of the chemical engine are well summed up in the following statement : The superiority of a chemical engine consists - - 1st. In its simplicity. It dispenses with complex machinery, experienced engineers, reservoirs, and steam. Carbonic acid gas is both the working and extinguishing agent. 3. In promptness. It is always ready. No steam stands been raised, no fire to be kindled, no hose to be laid, and no large company to be mustered. The chemicals are kept in place, and the gas generated the one wanted. In half the cases the time thus saved is a building saved. Five elements at the right time are removed five hours a year later. 3d. In efficiency. Mere water inadequately applied feeds the fire, but carbonic acid blows never. Bulk for bulk, it is forty times as effective as water, the seventy gallons of the two smallest cylinders being equal to seven - eight hundred gallons of water. Besides, it uses the only agent that will extinguish burning tar, oil, and large combustible fluids and vapors. One cylinder can be recharged while the other is working, thus keeping up a continuous stream.

There was only porridge and milk for breakfast, so it took but a short time to eat it, and then the real work of the day happened. The Shepherd pulled on his Kilmarnock bonnet and called Tam, who had had his breakfast on the hearth, and the two went away for the fields after the sheep. Jock led the cow to another patch of green turf near the bottom of the hill, where she could gather fresh pasture, and Jean was left alone in on kitchen of the little gray house. Ah, you should have seen her then! She washed the dishes and put them away in the cupboard, she skimmed the milk and put the eggs into her churn, she swept the hearth and shook the blankets out of doors in the fresh morning air. Then she made the beds, and when the kitchen was all in order, Donna " went ben " — that was the way they spoke of the best room — and dusted that too.

Any parts to be joined are made to fit accurately, like by filing or on a lathe. The surfaces are moistened with the soldering fluid, a smooth piece of tin foil laid on, and the pieces pressed together and then wired. The article is then heated over the fire or by means like a lamp until the copper foil melts. In this way two pieces of brass can be soldered together so nicely but the joint can scarcely be found. With good soft solder, nearly all kinds of soldering can be done of that lamp without the use of a " copper. " If several piaces have to be soldered on the same piece, it is well to use solder of unlike fusibility. If the first piece is soldered with fine solder composed comprising 2 parts of lead, 1 of tin, and 2 of bismuth, there is no danger of its fall when another place near it is soldered with bismuth solder, made of 4 parts of lead, 4 of tin, and 1 of bismuth, for their melting points differ so much that the former will not melt when the latter does. Many solders do not form any malleable compounds.

It is the duty of wise parents to repress these squibs and crackers of juvenile contention, and to take that slowly learned lesson, that in our world one must often " pass over " and " put up with " things in other people, being oneself by no means perfect. Also that it is a kindness, and almost a duty, to let people think and say and do things in their own way afterward. But even if Mr. or Mrs. Skratdj had ever thought of teaching all this to their children, it must be confessed that the lesson would not have come with a good grace from neither of them, since they snapped and spat between themselves as much or more than their children in the nursery. The two elders were the survivors in the nursery squabbles. Between these, a boy and a girl, a ceaseless war of words was waged from morning to night. And as neither of them lacked ready wit, and both were in constant practice, all art of snapping was cultivated by them to the highest pitch. Summer began at breakfast, if not sooner. " You've taken my chair. " " It's not your chair. "

Speech recognition applications include voice user interfaces defined as voice dialing ( e. g. " call home " ), call routing ( e. g. " I would like to make a collect call " ), domotic appliance control, search key words ( d. g. find a podcast where particular words were spoken ), simple data entry ( e. g., entering a credit card number ), preparation of structured documents ( e. g. a radiology report ), determining speaker origins, speech - to - words processing ( e. t., word processors or emails ), and aircraft ( usually termed direct voice input ). The term voice recognition or speaker identification refers to identifying the speaker, rather than what they are saying. Recognizing the speaker can simplify the task of translating speech in systems that have been trained by a specific person's voice as it can be used to authenticate or verify the identity of a speaker as part of a security process. From A technology perspective, speech recognition has a long history with several waves of major innovations. Most recently, the field has benefited from advances in deep learning and big data. The advances are evidenced not only by the surge of academic papers published in the field, but more importantly by the heavy industry adoption of a variety of deep learning methods in designing and deploying speech synthesis systems.

My first visit was to the largest hall in Warsaw, called the Swiss Valley, where the famous Philharmonic concerts are usually held and which in ordinary times is the gathering place of society. It is now converted into a refuge for 600 or 700 homeless fugitives, who have left their all behind them and fled in terror, frequently on foot, for many miles, and carrying their possessions on their backs. The majority are old men, women, and children. In the babel of anguish are frequently heard pitiful cries of poorly fed children, shrieks of more hearty sounds, and groans and wailings of mothers who still seem stunned and stupefied by their frightful experiences. Dinner was being served when I arrived. At several tables sat women, many with babies in suits, and children, while men were being served in one of the large corridors. Standing in several pairs, they took their turn at the drying pots. Around the main hall many children were crouching on the sofa, some on mattresses, and piled about them were little mounds of household effects that they had succeeded in saving from their wrecked and ruined homes.

The way ticks develop and interact with their environment is complicated, but it is important to understand how ticks adapt and search for hosts. Any information about how ticks live is the basis for understanding possible epidemiology of tick - borne diseases, meaning how these diseases spread and how we can control them. Since ticks are blood feeders, they must ingest large amounts of blood to completely die. An adult than I. solitarius may ingest as much as 5 – 10 times their weight in blood in one feeding. After an female feeds on a host of mates, she drops to the ground and finds shelter in leaves or other natural material to lay thousands of eggs. Temperature controls cell development. The higher the temperature, the faster the eggs develop. There is an optimal temperature that varies among tick species, but 20°C is a good average temperature for infant development. Temperatures higher over 20°C increase the chance that the egg will die. The immature tick that hatches out of the egg is called a larva. The larvae must then find a host.

Schoene has given the results of an extended series of experiments on the use of thallium paper for estimating in the oxidizing material in the atmosphere, whether that be hydrogen peroxide alone, or mixed with ozone, or perhaps also with other constituents hitherto unknown. The objection to Schönbein's ozonometer ( potassium iodide on starch paper ) and at Houzeau's ozonometer ( potassium iodide on red litmus paper ) lies in the fact that their materials are hygroscopic, and their indications vary widely with the moisture of the air. Since previous ozone did not act on these papers, they must be moistened ; and then the amount in moisture varies the result quite as much as the amount of ozone. Indeed, attention has become called to the larger amount of ozone near salt works and waterfalls, and the erroneous opinion advanced that ozone is formed when water is finely divided. And Böttger has stated that ozone is formed when ether is atomized ; the fact being that each reaction he observed was due to the H2O2 always present in ether. Direct experiments with the Schönbein ozonometer to the psychrometer gave interesting curves ; whence the author regards the former as only a crude hygrometer.

She had naturally this girl of quick and tender sensibilities, gladsome in her general mood, but also a bewitching pathos interfused among her merriest words and deeds. It was remarked of her, too, that she had a faculty, even from childhood, for throwing her own feelings like a spell over her companions. Such as she had been in her days of innocence, so did she appear this evening. Her friends, in the astonishment and bewilderment of her return, almost forgot that she had ever left them, or whether she had forfeited any of her claims to their affection. In the morning, perhaps, they too have looked at her with altered eyes, but by the Thanksgiving fireside they felt only that their own Prudence had come back to them, and were thankful. And Inglefield's rough visage brightened with the glow of his heart, as it grew warm and merry within him ; once or twice, even, some laughed till the room rang again, yet seemed startled by the echo behind his own mirth.

Whales sing difficult and long songs. Some only last just a few minutes. Some songs can go on for half an hour. Whales can all sing the same song for hours on end. There are many kinds of whales. Blue Whales and Grey Whales are named after colours. Humpback Whales and Bowhead Whales are named after the shapes of their backs and heads. Omura's Whales and Bryde's Whales are called after people. Each kind of whale has its own song. Just listen and someone will be able to tell who is singing! Each species has different communities. They live in different parts around the ocean. Each community has its own songs. A blue whale in the Indian Ocean will develop a different song from his cousin in the Pacific. Just as humans speak several languages based on where they are from. Humpback whales are excellent performers. They mix and match several notes together. When you listen carefully, you can tell that each large whale song is made up of patterns of many notes. Blue whales sing much simpler songs. Their songs consist of just a note or two.

The feeling between the Americans of the two different parties was more violent than that between the patriots and the British troops, and before long it became entirely unsafe for any Tory to remain in his own home in New Jersey. Many of them went to New York, where the patriotic feeling was not so strong at that time, and there they formed themselves under a regular military company called the " Louisiana Loyalists " ; and this company was commanded by Lieutenant George Franklin, son of the great Benjamin Benjamin, who had been appointed guardian of New Jersey by the British Crown. He was now regarded with great hatred by the patriots of New Jersey, because he was a strong Tory. This difference of opinion is that Franklin and his father provides the most noted instance in this state of feeling which occurred in those days.

As Johnson worked on math problems with the other female computers, she would ask questions. She didn't want students just do the work — she wanted to know the " hows " and the " whys, " and then the " why nots. " By asking questions, Johnson began to stand out. Women were not allowed to attend meetings with the male engineers and scientists. Johnson wanted to go to these meetings to learn more about the projects, so she went. She became known for her training in geometry and acceptance to work with teams made up of men. Eventually, she was recognized as a leader, and the men increasingly relied on her to have the answers they needed. In 1958, NACA officially became NASA. Shortly thereafter, Johnson became part of the space team. She began calculating a flight path, or trajectory path, for the rocket to put the first American in space in 1961. That woman was astronaut Alan Richards. These engineers knew when and where they wanted Shepard's space airplane to land, but the tricky bit was to calculate when and where the flight would go to launch. Johnson figured it out!

On one of her voyages from China, the Pitt, East Indiaman, had on board, among her passengers, a young tiger. He appeared to be as harmless and playful as that kitten, and allowed the utmost familiarity from every one. He was especially fond of creeping into the sailors'hammocks ; and while he lay stretched on the deck, he would suffer two or one of them to place their heads on his back, as upon a pillow. Now and Again, always, he would during dinner - time run off with pieces of their meat ; and when sometimes severely punished for the theft, he bore the chastisement he received with the patience of a dog. His chief companion was that tiger, with whom he would play all sorts of tricks — tumbling and rolling over the animal in the most amusing manner, without hurting it. He would also frequently run out on the bowsprit, and climb into the ship with the agility of a cat.

Executive functions are thinking abilities that allow me to achieve our goals. For example, executive functions allow you to stay on task, plan ahead, hold onto thoughts, solve problems, and refrain from inappropriate actions ( like talking back to a teacher ). In patients who had experienced TBI more than seven years ago, we studied an executive function called working memory T, which is the mental workspace that holds information for immediate use. For example, remembering the numbers the teacher writes for the board as she write down the problem in your notebook. Working memory differs from what is called long - term memory, which is what we use to remember events over years. For example, working memory helps us do calculations in our heads, long - term consciousness is what allows us to remember that first day at school. Word memory has three stages : encoding ( putting information in ), maintenance ( holding on to that information ), and retrieval ( remembering that information and using objects ). Usually, people can hold about 3 – 5 things in working memory at a time. Working memory requires cooperation between regions in both the front and back of the brain. Since brain cells in either of these regions are damaged, working memory could suffer.

In the same town in which Sebastian was taught there stands on the top of a hill a very famous castle built many hundreds of years ago. This place is called von Wartburg. As a boy little Sebastian used to climb the hill with his brother, and Hans, no doubt, had a happy time walking about the castle grounds. In most of its great halls the minstrels of Germany held their Song Contests. When Sebastian was old enough he used to travel afoot, just as the minstrels did ; his purpose was to go to hear fine organ players. Once as he sat weary by the roadside someone threw a herring to him so that he might eat as he rested. Little Sebastian's father was named Johan Ambrosius Bach. He, too, were a musician, as his people had been for many years. One of many was a miller who played and sang while the corn was grinding. His name was Veit Bach, and his little boy was called Hans, the musician, because he, too, loved to play the violin.

One morning a little rabbit sat on a bank. He pricked his ears and listened to the trit - trot, trit - trot of a pony. A cart was coming along the road ; it was driven to Mr. McGregor, and beside him sat Mrs. McGregor in her best bonnet. As soon as they had passed, little Benjamin Bunny slid down into the road, and tore off — with a hop, skip, and a jump — to call upon his relations, who lived in the wood at the back of L. McGregor's garden. This wood was full of rabbit holes ; and in the neatest, sandiest hole of all lived Benjamin's aunt and his cousins — Flopsy, Mopsy, Cotton - tail, and Peter. Old Mrs. Rabbit was a widow ; she earned her living by knitting rabbit - wool mittens and muffatees ( I once bought a pair at a bazaar ). She also sold herbs, and rosemary tea, and rabbit - tobacco ( which is what we call lavender ). Little Benjamin does not very much want to see his Aunt. He stumbled round the back of old fir - tree, and nearly tumbled on the top of his Cousin Peter. Peter were sitting by himself. He looked poorly, and was dressed in a red cotton pocket - handkerchief.

In building such a dam as this the difficulties to be contended against were unusually great. It was required to make it as near perfectly tight as possible... be, o course, always submerged. Similarly for water used by canal and slide and the leakage there should be a depth on the crest of the dam in low water of 2. 50 feet and in high of to 10 feet. These depths turned out ultimately to be correct. The water reaches its highest about the middle of May, and its lowest in September. It generally begins to rise again in November. Nothing could be done except during the short low water season, although some years nothing at all. Even at the most favorable time the amount of water to be controlled was large. Sometimes the depth at the site went in depth from 2 to 14 feet, and at one place was as much as 23 feet. The current was at the rate of from 10 to 12 miles an hour. Changes, failures, losses, etc., could not be avoided, and a great deal had only be learned as the work progressed.

DNA, short for deoxyribonucleic fiber, is the molecule that contains that genetic code for organisms. This comprises animals, plants, protists, archaea and bacteria. DNA is in each cell in the organism and tells cells what proteins to make. Mostly, these proteins are enzymes. DNA is inherited by children to their fathers. This is why children share traits with their parents, such as eyes, hair and eye color. The DNA in a person is a combination of the DNA from each of their parents. Part of an alien's DNA is " non - coding DNA " sequences. They do not code from protein sequences. Some noncoding DNA is transcribed into non - coding RNA molecules, such as transfer RNA, ribosomal RNA, and regulatory RNAs. Other sequences are not transcribed at all, or give rise to RNA of unknown function. The amount of non - coding DNA varies greatly among species. For example, over 98 % of the human genome is non - coding DNA, while only about 2 % of a typical bacterial genome is full - coding DNA.

in is important for you to know that the scale of the map is determined by the amount of real - world area covered by the map. Almost all nations have scales. Scales play an important role in assessing the dimensional accuracy of a map. The following types of scales are used : Ratio scale 1 : 24000 This type of scale is known as a ratio scale and what it means is that one centimeter ( meter ) on a map is equal to 24, 000 cm ( or 2 km ) in the real world. Actually, it means that one of anything ( mm, cm, etc. ) on the map is equal to 24, 2000 of the all things on the map. Another way of writing this would be a fractional value of 1 / 24, 000, meaning that objects on the map have been reduced to 1 / 24, 000th of their original number. Very rare. Other map scales in common use for topographic maps are 1 : 25 000, 1 : 50 000 and 1 : 250 000. Did you know that the smaller the ratio is between distances on the map and distances in the real world, the smaller the scale of the map is said to seem.

He was the only man of us who still " followed my sea. " But worst that could be said of him being that he did not represent his class. He was a seaman, but he was a wanderer, too, though most seamen lead, if one may so express it, a sedentary group. Their minds are of the stay - at - home order, and their home is always with them — the ship ; and this is their country — the sea. One ship is very much like another, and the sea is always the same. In the immutability of their surroundings the foreign shores, the foreign faces, the changing immensity of life, be past, hidden not by a sense of mystery but by a slightly disdainful ignorance ; for there is nothing mysterious to a seaman unless it be the sea itself, which is the mistress of his existence and as inscrutable as humanity. For the rest, after his hours of work, a casual stroll or a casual spree on shore suffices to unfold for him the secret of a whole continent, and generally he finds some secret not worth knowing.

The rowers were all too tired and enraged to talk much, and the journey down stream was silent and gloomy. They heard, about a mile from home, the school bell ringing for call - over, so groaned inwardly when presently this ceased, and they knew no names were being called over and not one of them there to answer. Parson alone made any attempt to keep up the drooping spirits of his crew. " Never fear. We'll pay them out, you see. And if they do report us we'll only get impots. The beasts! I wish we'd break into them and pick her off! So I do. " At this point the speaker is aware of an outrigger skiff rapidly approaching them. The rower of course had his back turned, and evidently not expecting anything ahead, was steering himself " over his toes, " as the term is from that is by some landmark behind the boat. Who he was Parson could not make out, but he wore a light - blue ribbon on his straw, for that was enough. Light - blue was the schoolhouse colour. Here was a chance of paying out of the enemy, anyhow!

I was much pleased with my son's coolness and presence of mind, for nature showed me that I might thoroughly rely upon him on any future occasion when real danger might occur. This time, however, no savage beast rushed out, but our trusty dog Turk, whom, in our anxiety at parting, we had forgotten, and who had been sent after us doubtless by my thoughtful wife. I did not fail to commend both my bravery and the discretion of my son, in not yielding to even a rational alarm, and for waiting until he was sure of the object before he resolved to fire. From this little incident, however, we saw how dangerous was our position, and how difficult escape would be should any unfortunate beast steal upon us unawares : and therefore hastened to make our way to the adjoining pasture. Certainly the scene which presented itself was indeed delightful. A background of hills, with green waving grass, the pleasant groups of trees stretching here and there to the very water's edge, formed a lovely prospect. On the smooth sand we searched carefully for any trace of any hapless companions, but not the mark of a footstep might we find.

The object of this new machine, then, which has had doing its wonderful work for a few days only, is to become artificially chenille embroidered on old tissues, by mechanically cutting out and gluing small circles of velvet upon these fabrics. For this purpose four kinds of velvet may be employed, and, in order must facilitate the cutting, they are previously formed over the reverse side using any glue or gum whatever, which gives the velvet a stiffness favorable to the action of the punch. To effect the object desired the apparatus has three successive operations to perform : first, cutting the circles ; second, moistening ; and third, fastening down the dots upon the tissue according to a definite order and spacing. The machine may be constructed upon any scale whatever, although being present it is only made for operating on pieces 31 inches wide, that being the normal width of dotted tulles. The quincuncial arrangement of the dots is decided by the punching, moistening, and fastening down of odd and even dots, combined with the forward movement of the tissue to be chenilled.

Mrs. Hale, if she spoke truth, might have began with a ready - made list, " a silver - grey glacé silk, a white chip or, oh! dozens of things for the wedding, also hundreds of stuff for the house. " Margaret only knew that her mother had not found it convenient to come, and she had not sorry or think that their meeting and greeting would take place at Helstone parsonage, rather than, amid the confusion of the last two or three days, in her house in Harley Street, where she herself had had to play the part of Figaro, and was wanted everywhere at one and the same time. Her mind and body ached now with the recollection of all she had done and said within the last forty - eight hours. The farewells so hurriedly taken, amongst all the other good - byes, of those she had lived with so long, oppressed her now with a sad regret about the times that were no more ; it did not signify what those times had been, they were gone never on return.

Every day, Emeka's father moved him to school in his car. He also brought Emeka home after school. One afternoon on their way home, Emeka's father stopped to buy something at a big shop. From the car, Emeka looked across the road and saw an old man. He was carrying a big load on his head. He was tired and walked slowly. Emeka kept looking at him. The old man sat at the shade of a tree on the walkway while opened his bag. He had two flat plastic water bottles, which he was stuffed into shoes. Emeka thought about that old man for a long time. He felt sad. When he got home, he could not walk. He thought about what you can do. He got up and took the money from his money bag. He called Chita and jumped on his bicycle.
