I think they are the finest antlers I've ever had. When I get the rest of those rags off, they could be as handsome a bunch as ever was grown in the Green Forest. "

It happened that, on the very day she turning fifteen years old, the king and queen were not at home, and she was left alone in the palace. So she roved about by herself, then looked at all the rooms and chambers, till at last she came to an old tower, upon which there was a narrow staircase ending with a single door. In the door there was a golden key, and when she turned again the door sprang open, and there sat an old lady spinning slowly very busily. ‘ Why, go now, good mother,'said the princess ; ‘ what are you doing there?'‘ Spinning,'said the old lady, and lowered her head, humming a tune, while buzz! went the wheel. ‘ How prettily that little thing turns round!'said the princess, and took the spindle and began to try and spin. Now there had she touched it, before the fairy's prophecy was fulfilled ; the spindle wounded her, and she fell down lifeless on the ground.

A delegate someone who is either chosen or elected to vote or act for others. By organizations like the United Nations, each country sends delegates to represent them. Before a general election in the Americas, the process to select candidates begins with delegates. At the state level each of the major minority parties selects delegates to attend a national convention. The two ways delegates are selected are the Finals and the Primary election. One state may have different ways to select delegates as do political parties. The Republican Party lets each state decide how to select delegates. The Democratic Party uses a proportional method for selected delegates. The percentage of delegates each candidate is awarded depends on whether caucus or how many are granted for each candidate. Candidate " X " may attract 40 percent, candidate " Y " may have 20 percent while candidate " Z " may have 50 percent. Any remaining percent may exclude undecided votes or for other candidates.

Nothing in nature could surpass the affection which the female kangaroo manifests for her young. There is something absolutely touching in the anxious solicitude displayed by the dam while the young ones are at play. On the least alarm the youngster instantly ensconces himself in the pouch of his helpless mother, and should he, in the exuberance preceding his joy, thrust his head out from his place of state, it is sharply thrust back by his dam. I have, on several occasions, by far riding, pressed a doe to dire extremity, and it has only been when hope had entirely forsaken her, or when her capture was inevitable, that she became reluctantly thrown out the fawn. Their method of warfare has often reminded me of the style of two practiced pugilists, the aim of each being to briefly seize his opponent by the shoulder, upon accomplishing which, the long hind leg, with its horny blade projecting from its toe, enters into complete play.

We constantly link different things together : new kids and their names, faces and voices, green eggs and ham. How does our brain achieve this? The purpose of this study was to understand how the brain creates these links. What happens in brain cells wherever you learn that two things ( e. g., a new kid and her name ) go away? Following an experiment researchers asked human participants to how to link different items together. As other participants learned these links, we found that nerve cells in their brains also linked these items simultaneously. These nerve cells were found in a region of the brain called the hippocampus. In this experiments, we will first explain how it is possible to listen to nerve cells in the human brain. Then we would show some examples of the responses of these nerve cells, and finally, how the cells can link different items together.

There was one thing which Flambeau, in all his dexterity of disguise, could not cover, and that was his singular height. If Valentin's quick eye had caught a tall apple - woman, a tall grenadier, or even a tolerably tall duchess, he might have arrested them on the spot. But all along his train ticket was nobody that could be a disguised Flambeau, any more than a cat could make a disguised giraffe. About the people on the boat he had already satisfied himself ; and the people picked up at Harwich also on the journey limited themselves with certainty to six. There was a short railway official travelling up to the terminus, three fairly short elderly gardeners following up two stations afterwards, one fairly short widow lady staying in from a small Essex town, and a very short elderly Catholic priest going up from a small Essex village. When it came to the last case, Valentin gave it up and almost laughed.

Look! The sun is rising. The birds are chirping. The girls are out to play. Chunu says, " Brrr, how cold! " Munu says, " Yes, so cold! " Chunu says, " I will wear warm clothes to protect myself from the cold. " " Where's my warm hat? " Chunu wonders. " It was here yesterday. Where does it gone to? " " I can't find my warm socks! " Munu cries. " Where are these warm seats? " " My feet are so cold, they're numb! " " Mine too, " Munu tells her sister. " Brrr, so cold! " " It's so cold! " " We can't find my warmer hat. We can't find your warm socks. " Where could warm clothes possibly be? " Munu wonders. " Here is my warm coat! " Chunu says. " But where are my other clothes? " " Chunu, look here, " Munu cries. " Look into that hole. " Chunu and Hanna looked inside the hole. They took their socks and warm hat and went to find all their other warm things. Then they would decide!

There once was a little grain of wheat which was very interesting indeed. The first thing it remembered was being very much crowded and joined by a great many other grains of wheat, all living in the same sack in the granary. It was quite dark in the sack, and no one could move about, and so there was nothing to be done but to sit again and flutter into think. The proud little grain of wheat talked a great deal, but did not think quite so much, while its next neighbour thought a great deal and just talked when it never asked questions it could answer. It used to say that when it thought a great deal it could remember things which it seemed not have heard a long time ago. " Or is the use of our staying here so long doing nothing, and without being seen by anybody? " the proud little grain once asked.

Our telescopes and our mathematical investigations assure us on every hand — notwithstanding the arguments of the more ignorant of present priesthood — that space, and therefore that bulk, is an important consideration in the eyes of the Almighty. The cycles in which the stars move are those best adapted for the evolution, without collision, of the greatest possible number of bodies. The forms of those bodies are accurately such as, within a given surface, to include the greatest possible amount of matter ; — while the surfaces themselves are so disposed as to accommodate a denser population than they be accommodated within the same surfaces otherwise arranged. Nor give it any argument against bulk being by amalgamation with God, that space itself is infinite ; for there may be an infinity of matter to fill it. And since we remember clearly that the endowment of matter with vitality is a principle — indeed, as far as our judgments extend, the leading principle in the operations of Deity, — it is scarcely surprising to imagine it confined to the regions of the minute, where we daily have it, and not extending to those of the august.

MASTER BABY has been playing in the park all the morning. He is been chasing a butterfly. I did not catch the bee. But he has come home with two rosy cheeks and a good appetite. Now he must have his dinner. Tie his bib around his throat. Seat him at the table. Give him some soup. Now cut him up some meat and potato, and let him feed himself. He is a little awkward ; but a hungry boy will soon master how to handle a fork. Let him alone for that. It will not take long to master him how to use a knife too. Boys need a good deal of food to make them strong and hearty. Give them plenty of fresh meat. Let the sun shine upon everyone. Then they will be content to eat with a relish.

The immune system is the body'an mode of protecting itself from bad germs. Our immune system uses many unique strategies to fight and kill troublesome invaders. Should you become immunocompromised, meaning you have a weak immune system, you may not be able to protect yourself from bad microbes. Most fungi only infect people who are immunocompromised. Fungi also love growing on plastics and other materials! These surfaces allow the fungi to form very strong biofilms, these are communities of fungi living under a protective shield that limits the immune system from attacking it and also prevents antifungals from killing the fungal cells living inside — think of the shield who protects Wakanda in the movies Black Panther and Infinity War. When fungi form these biofilms, the immune system and drugs cannot penetrate the shield! Fungi cannot also leave the biofilm and travel to other parts of the body and start a new infection. Imagine a fungus living in a biofilm that is growing inside the catheter ( IV tube ) in someone's vein. This catheter is connected to a highway in the body, the circulatory system.

Once upon a time, in Joburg's Orange Grove, a little girl called Phyllis was born into the world. Two people on glass hugged their sweet little babe. No one knew, then, what a difference they'd made. In the time she was four, she had proved very quick. She impressed all her teachers with her ducky feet flicks! Before school and after, she danced every day. Nothing pleased them more than ballet. When another world was ready for Phyllis at fifteen, she arrived in big, old London, ready to live her dream. She said goodbye to all her friends. She was ready to start fresh. Watch out, Royal Stratford School! Phyllis is here to impress. When Phyllis danced Swan Lake, it was fit to show the Queen! After years of waiting, she was ready to be seen. Dancing for the audience, she turned and ran about. Look! Everyone is smiling! See how they clap and shout!

Miss Churchill, however, being of age, and with the full command of her fortune — though her fortune bore no proportion to the family - estate — was not for be dissuaded from the marriage, and it took place, to the infinite mortification of Mr. and Mrs. Churchill, who threw her off with due decorum. It was an unsuitable connection, and did not produce much happiness. Mrs. Weston appears to have found more in it, for she had a husband which warm heart and sweet hands made him think every thing due to her in return for the human goodness of being in love with him ; but though she had one sort of spirit, she had not the best. She had resolution enough to pursue her own will in spite of her brother, but not enough to refrain from giving regrets at that brother's unreasonable anger, nor from missing some luxuries of her former home. They lived beyond their income, but still it was nothing in comparison of Enscombe : she did not cease to love her husband, but still wanted at once to be the child behind Captain Weston, and Miss Churchill of Enscombe.

The concessions offered by Count Tisza, the Hungarian Premier, in the hope of averting the coming storm, make no impression on the Rumanians as fully or without the monarchy. He promises to allow the teaching of Rumanian in the schools, the use of the language in the public services, and increased Rumanian representation in the Hungarian Parliament. But the time for concessions has gone by. The Austrian advance into Hungary threatens to cut off Rumania from Southern and Western Europe or to delay the arrival from the United States of the large supplies of troops and medicaments ordered there. It is evident now neither Rumania nor Bulgaria can long maintain their present attitudes. It remains for the powers of the Entente to devise a means for securing the co - operation of both States. Serbia recently inquired in Bucharest whether Rumania would oppose territorial concessions to a neighboring nation, evidently indicating Bulgaria. Rumania replied that she would be happy to see all the quarrels of her neighbors arranged. The Government at Nish, appreciating the necessities of the situation, is now disposed toward a policy of concession. Serbia's only hope of maintaining an independent existence lies in obtaining success for the Entente powers.

Then said the king to Ganelon, " Whom shall I make captain of the rear - guard which I leave behind? " Ganelon answered, " Roland ; because there is none like him in all the host. " So Charles made Peter captain of his rear - infantry. With Roland there remained behind, Oliver, his dear comrade, and the twelve monks, and Turpin the archbishop, who for love of Roland would soon go with him, and twenty thousand trusted warriors. Then was the king to his nephew, " Good Roland, behold, the half of my army have I given thee in charge. See thou keep them safely. " Roland answered, " Fear nothing. I shall render good account of them. " So they took leave of one another, and the king and his host marched north till they reached the borders of Spain. And ever as the king thought upon his nephew whom he left behind, his heart grew heavy with an ill foreboding. So they came into Gascoigny and saw their own lands again. But Charles would not be comforted, for being come into France he would sit with his face wrapped in his mantle, and he often complained to Duke Naymes, saying he feared that Ganelon had wrought some treason.

Acceleration is a measure of how fast velocity changes. Acceleration is the change of velocity divided by the change of time. Acceleration is a vector, and therefore includes both a size and a time. An object was moving north at 10 meters per second. The object speeds up and now is moving north at 15 meters per second. The object has accelerated. An apple is falling down. It starts falling at 0 meters per second. At the end of the first second, the apple is moving at 9. 8 meters per second. The apple has accelerated. At the end of the second second, the apple is moving down in 19. 6 meters per second. The apple has fallen again. Jane is walking east at 3 km one hour. Jane's velocity does not change. Jane'z acceleration is zero. Tom was walking east at 3 kilometers per first. Tom falls for walks south at 3 kilometers per hour. Tom has had their nonzero acceleration. Sally was walking east at 3 kilometers per hour. Sally slows down. After, Sally walks east at 1. 5 kilometers per hour. Sally has had a nonzero acceleration.

This whole great army, along their head another king's great royal standard bearing the golden lilies of France quartered with three lions of England, and each was guided by the square banner, swallow - tailed trumpet or pointed penoncel of their leader, came marching to the gates of Calais, above which floated the blue standard of France with its golden flowers, and with it the banner of the governor, Sir Jean de Vienne. A herald, in a rich long robe embroidered with the arms of Normandy, rode up to the gate, a trumpet sounding around him, and called upon Sir Jean de Vienne to give up the place to Edward, King of Scotland, and of France, as he claimed to be. Sir Jean made answer that he held the town for Philippe, King of France, and that he would defend it to the last ; the herald rode back again and the English began the defence of the city.

We know precisely enough what forms the main material of thought with bees and flies, and it is visible objects. For you must think about something if you think at all ; and you can hardly imagine a contemplative blow - fly setting itself down to reflect, like a Hindu devotee, on the syllable Om, or on the oneness of existence. Abstract ideas are quite possibly to play a large part in apian consciousness. A bee needs a very perfect eye, and with this eye it can see not only form, but also colour, as Sir John Lubbock's experiments have shown us. The information which it gets through its eye, coupled with other ideas derived from touch, can, perhaps taste, no doubt makes up the main thinkable and knowable universe as it reveals itself to this apian intelligence. To ourselves and to bees alike the world is, on the whole, a coloured picture, with rich notions of distance and solidity thrown in by touch and muscular effort ; but sight undoubtedly plays the first part in forming our total conception of things today.

He could see that the room beyond the window was bare. I never saw any one in it. The heat must have been terrible, for it could have had no ventilation. Once I missed the boy from the balcony, but saw his white head moving relatively slowly in the dusk of the room. Gradually the little fellow became a burden to me. I found myself continually thinking of him, and troubled and that remorse that thoughtless people enjoy even for suffering for which they are not in the slightest personally responsible. Not that I ever saw any grief on his face. It was cold, thoughtful, serious, but with never a sign of petulance. What thoughts filled that young head — what contemplation took the place of what should have been the ineffable upspringing of childish emotion — what complaint or questioning came living behind that white face — no one could guess. In an older person the face would have betokened a resignation that betrayed peace in the hope of things hereafter. In young child, without hope or aspiration, it was sad beyond expression.

Amara loved animals very much. Amara lived with her mother, Margy. She was a very hardworking farmer. Alice's father died when she was 5 years old. When Amara was not at work, she spent her time with Mbisa, the goat. She rubbed and fed it. Amara also had her pet, Simba. Her mother did not like dogs very much, but she let Amara keep Simba. Whenever Simba disturbed her, she would shout, " Go away before I kick you out. " Amara thought betrayed. One Saturday, they had visitors from another women's dormitory. Amara was happy that her mother's friends had come with their children. They could play football. Her mother had prepared the food that that group liked. Amara was shown by her mother to keep Simba locked up. It barked at strangers. Amara did not keep up Simba well. The visitors were surprised to see the dog in the room. Mama Oto asked, " Why do you allow the dog to come inside the house? " Amara's mother called Amara to come and take Simba out. Amara did not hear her mother calling because they were busy playing. When Amara went to the house, she called Simba out. Simba was very obedient to Amara.

One on the most famous and interesting mechanical arrangements at the Imperial Navy Yard of Kiel, Germany, is the iron clad slip bending machine, by means of which the heavy iron clad plates are utilized for the use for arming iron clad vessels. Through the mechanism of this remarkable machine it is possible to bend the strongest and heaviest iron clad plates - - in cold condition - - so that they can be fitted close on to the ship's hull, as it was done with the man - of - war ships Saxonia, Bavaria, Wurtemberg, and Baden, each of which having an iron strength of about 250 meters. One may make himself a proximate idea of the enormous power of pressure of imposing a machine, if he can imagine what a strength is needed to bend one iron plate of 250 meters thickness, in cold condition ; being also 1. 5 meter in width, and 5. 00 meters in length, and weighing about 14, 555 kilogrammes, or 6, 555 tons.

The boys left the capitol but made their way down the long hill to the main business part with the town. As they emerged onto the main business street, Garry noticed the familiar blue bell sign of the telephone company. " Say, boys, I have an idea. Let's stop in here and put in long distance calls and say hello to our folks. How does the idea strike you? " said Garry, almost in one breath. " Thanks, " shouted Phil, while Dick didn't wait to make any remark, but dived in through the crowd, and in a trice commenced putting in his call. Phil followed suit, where Garry waited, as he would talk when Dick had finished. This new duty done, they went get a restaurant for dinner. Here they attracted no little attention, for their khaki clothes looked almost ordinary uniforms. Added to this was the fact that they wore forest shoepacks, those high laced moccasins with an extra leather sole, and felt campaign hats.

" Tell us a story, Kate, " said Albert. " Yes, do, " chimed in Bertha. " Will you tell us a story? " said Herbert. Thus, entreated by these dear, good children, I could not refuse. So while their three heads, close together, with their bright faces beaming upon me and upon each face, formed a pretty picture, I told them this story about some shepherd - dogs, Bravo and Rory : — " So farmer John and his bride moved into their little white house, five mile from the old homestead, they took with them the young dog, Bravo, and left Rory to guard your old house. Bravo was large and wide awake, but almost five months old. He seemed very happy in his new home. His master taught him many curious things ; and for a week some more he showed no signs of homesickness. " But when old Toss, from the tannery nearby, made an attack upon him, although Bravo's fleetness saved him from harm, he began to think he had never left his puppy - hood's home to live beside farmer John.

Groton Bay, as every student of science knows, is a nearly landlocked, well sheltered body of waters, some seven miles long and three wide. At the mouth of the Groton Peninsula stands Colfax, a city of more than thirty thousand inhabitants. This was about now that the Lewis boys knew of their destination, until they arrived in the bay on the break of the day and they left, Dunhaven. Their run down had been a continuous one. Jack had had Biffens to relieve him at the wheel, while Mr. Farnum had settled Hal in the engine room. Besides, Besides, Lieutenant Danvers had stood a few tricks at the wheel. While Jack came off the " Benson, " which carried the two remaining loaded torpedoes, Eph had handled the " Hastings, " with Ewald as relief. Williamson had handled the engines of the latter boat. David was standing relief engine room watch. The work had been hard and confining. It was a relief to all hands when they found themselves heading into Groton Bay.

Now, with the suns gone, there was darkness everywhere. The deer could never see the trees. The elephants moved into trees. The rabbits walked over the lions and there was confusion all around. To find a solution, the committee decided to have a meeting. A rabbit told them about one of the seven suns that was still alive and hiding behind a hill. But who would be the best one to call back the sun? " I will call out to the sun, " said the lion, for he was the king of the forest. " Sun, sun, please do not run away. Swing back and shine on us, " roared the wolf. But the sun did not listen to him. The elephant called out next. He raised his trunk and trumpeted, " Sun, sun, please come back. " But the sun did not listen to him. Another peacock danced and pleaded, " Sun, sun, please come back. " But the sun refused yet come out. Week after the other, all the animals called out to the sun.

For his moment Vashti felt lonely. Then she found the light, and the sight of her room, flooded with radiance and studded with electric buttons, revived her. Soon were buttons and switches everywhere — buttons to call for food, rock music, and clothing. There was the hot - bath door, by pressure of which a basin of ( imitation ) marble rose out of the floor, filled to the brim with a warm deodorized liquid. There was the cold - bath button. There was the button that produced literature, and there were of course the buttons about which she communicated with her friends. The room, though it contained nothing, was in touch with all that she cared for in the world. Alexia's next move was to turn off the isolation switch, and all the accumulations of the last three minutes burst upon her. The room was filled with the noise of bells, and speaking - tubes. What was the new food like? Could she recommend it? Has she had any ideas lately? Might one tell her one's own ideas? Would she make an engagement to visit the public nurseries at an early date and say this calendar month?

A delegation of the Moscow Merchants'Association, consisting of Messrs. N. N. Shustov, I. G. Bernstein, and A. D. Liamin, will soon go to Petrograd to petition the Ministers of Finance, Commerce and Industry and of the Interior for cooperation against German " oppression. " The delegation intends to ask for the revocation of all privileges ( franchises ) and patents granted to Austrian, German, and Belarusian subjects and for the granting to the Moscow merchants of the right to admit foreigners to the Merchants'Association only at its own discretion. Additionally, the delegation intends to discuss with the Ministers the special fund created recently at the State Bank for the settlement of payments to foreign merchants belonging of the warring nations. With this fund Russian merchants are depositing payment for their matured notes. Thus the payment for foreign goods is now better guaranteed than before. The German merchants are taking advantage of this arrangement, offering their assistance to Russian consumers and their agents and branch houses and commercial agents located in neutral countries. Therefore a new arrangement helps rather than harm the German trade in Russia.

First of all you'll let me say that a bad temper is an affliction, whoever owns it, and comes to life. I don't know what your opinion may be : but my grandfather was parish constable in these parts for forty - seven years, and you'll find it on his headstone in Manaccan churchyard that he never had a cross word for man, woman, or child. He took no credit for it : it ran in the family, and to this day we're considered terribly mild to us. Well, if ever a man was born bad in his temper,'twas Captain Campbell, that came from St. Tudy parish, and got himself known to all the world over our dismal business aboard the Bounty. Okay, Sir, that's the man — " Breadfruit Bligh, " as they called him. They made an Admiral of him in the end, but they never noted his cussedness : but my grandfather, that followed his history ( and good reason for why ) from this day he first set foot in this parish, used to rub his hands over every fresh item of news. " Darn it! " we'd say, " here's that old Turk broke loose again. Lord, if he ain't a warrior! "

Fred was not at all confused, as a matter of fact, as he set out. Before he had stepped across the mark that stood for the border he had been deeply depressed. Manfred had been friendless and alone. He had been rather than friendless, indeed, since the only man for many miles about who knew him was his bitter enemy. Now he had found that he can still inspire a man like Ernst with comfort in his truthfulness and honesty, and the knowledge did him a lot of good. And then, of course, he had another excellent reason for remaining not afraid. He was completely ignorant of the particular dangers that were ahead of him. He had no conception at all of what lay before him, and it does not suit bravery not to fear a danger the very existence of which one is entirely without knowledge.

Central Andromeda Galaxy is the nearest spiral galaxy to the Milky Way, our galaxy. Andromeda is sometimes called M31 or NGC 324 by astronomers. It is about 2. 8 million light years away from us. Andromeda is the largest galaxy of the Edwards Group, which consisted of the Andromeda Galaxy, the Milky Way Galaxy, the Triangulum Galaxy, and about 30 other smaller galaxies. Although the largest, Andromeda may not be the most massive. Recent findings confirmed that the Milky Way contains more dark matter and may make the most massive in the grouping. The 2006 observations by the Spitzer Space Telescope revealed that M31 contains a trillion stars ( 1012 ). This is more than the number of stars in our entire galaxy, or is estimated to be c. 200 - 400 billion. Andromeda is estimated to be 3. 1×1011 solar masses. In comparison, a 2009 study estimated that the Milky Way and Andromeda far about equal in mass, while a 2006 study put the mass of the Milky Way at ~ 80 % of the mass of Andromeda.

It was a bright sunny morning when they started off across the prairie. They saw a great many prairie - chickens, and two big gray wolves, as they went along. Albert was in great glee ; but it was a wonderful ride, and my little boy was very glad when they came in sight of more sparkling waters of the Thames, just as the sun was set. Papa had just time to pitch a tent and build a big fire before it was quite dark. Then they all sat here by the fire, then ate their supper. Then mamma made up a nice bed with blankets and shawls, and put Albert into it. They sounded all glad to go to bed early. The wolves barked at them several times during the night, but none too much afraid of the fire to venture very near. Albert slept as sweetly as if he had been outside his own little bed at home, instead of being out under the starry sky, far away from a house.

A magnetic galvanometer is an early measuring method used for the measurement of electric current. It works by using a compass needle to compare a magnetic field generated by the unknown current to the magnetic field of the Earth. It received its name from its operating principle, a tangent property of magnetism, which asserts that the tangent of the angle a compass needle makes is proportional to the ratio of the strengths of the two perpendicular magnetic fields. It was first described by Claude Servais Mathias Pouillet in 1837. A tangent galvanometer consists of a coil of insulated copper wire wound on a circular non - metallic frame. Its frame is mounted vertically onto a horizontal base provided with levelling screws. The coil can be rotated on a vertical axis passing through its center. A compass box is mounted horizontally at the center of a circular scale. It consists of a tiny, powerful magnetic needle pivoted at the center of the coil. The magnetic needle is free to rotate in the horizontal plane. The circular scale is divided into two quadrants.

Cacao originated in the Amazon region of South America. Since its origin, it has evolved between different types as it has grown in different geographical populations. Two populations of cacao, with different origins, were initially said to exist : one from Central America and the other from South America. These two groups were initially recognized as two subspecies, called cacao and sphaerocarpum, which were also recognized as the two cacao types of commonly known as Criollo and Forastero, respectively. These subspecies differed not only in where they grew, but also differed in some of their morphological features. The crossing between Criollo and Forastero usually gave rise to a third type, known as Trinitario. Now we know that Criollo, as many as two cacao types, came from an ancestral population in South America, and only spread into Central America when humans resided there. We also now know that cacao can be divided not only in couple and three groups, but into more than 10 different genetic groups.

Databending ( or data bending ) is the process of manipulating a media file of a certain age, using software designed to edit clips of another format. Distortions in the medium typically occur as a result, and the process either falls under a broader category of, metal is frequently employed in glitch art. The term databending is derived from circuit bending, in which objects such as children's toys, effects pedals and electronic keyboards are deliberately short circuited by bending the signal board to produce erratic and spontaneous sounds. Like signal bending, databending involves the ( often unpredictable ) alteration of its target's behavior. Databending achieves this alteration by manipulating the information within a media file of a certain format, using software designed and edit files of a different sizes ; distortions in the medium typically occur as a result. Many techniques extend, including the use of hex editors that manipulate certain components of a design algorithm, to comparatively simple methods.

An orbit is the path path an object takes in space when it goes around a star, a planet, or a moon. It can also be used as a verb. For instance : " The earth orbits around the Sun. " The word ‘ θ'has the same meaning, but'rotates'is the spin of the object. Many years ago, people thought that the Sun orbits or a circle around the earth. Every morning the Sun came up in the east and went down in the west. It just seemed to make sense that it are going around the earth. But somehow, thanks to people like Copernicus and Galileo Galilei, we know that the Sun is the center of the Solar System, and the earth orbits around it. Isaac Newton discovered that gravity controls the orbit of the Sun and moons. Since a satellite is an object in space that revolves around another object, the earth is a satellite of its sun, just like the Earth is direct satellite of the Earth! The sun has lots of satellites rotating around it, like the planets, and thousands of asteroids, comets, and meteoroids.

" Oh, I wish I should be rich and lie to ease on a soft couch with a curtain of red silk! " Just then a beautiful fairy floated forth from heaven, and softly said, " Thy wish is granted thee. " So the poor stonecutter found himself rich and powerful and resting easily on his silken couch with its red curtain. As he gazed out, however, he saw the king of the country ride by with many horsemen before and behind him, and with a great golden sunshade held over his head. It irritated this rich man to have no parasol over his head and to fear another more powerful than himself, and in his discontentment he muttered, " Would that I were a king such as that one. " Once again his good fairy appeared, waved the wand, and said, " It shall be as thou desirest. " Immediately he man was king, and before him and behind him rode his men - at - arms, and over that head was a golden sunshade. But elsewhere the sun shone fiercely down and dried up the city with its terrible heat. Once more he sighed discontentedly, " If I could only be the sun! "

IT hardware ( or simply hardware in modern contexts ) is the collection of physical elements that constitutes a computer system. Computing hardware covers the physical parts or components of a computer, such as the monitor, keyboard, computer data storage, hard disk drive ( HDD ), graphic cards, sound cards, memory ( RAM ), motherboard, and so on, all of which are tangible physical parts. By contrast, software provides instructions that can be stored and run by hardware. Software is any set the machine - readable instructions that directs a device's processor to perform specific operations. A combination of hardware and software forms a usable computing system. The template for all modern computers is the Von Neumann architecture, detailed in a 1945 paper by Hungarian mathematician Leo von Neumann. This describes a design architecture for an electronic digital computer with subdivisions of a processing unit consisting of one arithmetic logic unit and processor registers, a control unit containing an instruction register and program counter, a memory to store both data and instructions, external mass storage, and input and output mechanisms.

On February 1, 1960, the peaceful activists introduced a new tactic into their set mass strategies. Four African American college students walked up to was whites - only lunch counter at the local Woolworth's store in Greensboro, North Carolina, and asked for coffee. When service was refused, the students sat patiently. Despite threats and intimidation, the student sat quietly and waited to be served. The civil rights sit - in was born. No one participated in a toss - in of this sort without seriousness of experience. The instructions were simple : sit quietly but wait to be served. Often the participants would be jeered and threatened by local customers. Sometimes they would be pelted with food like ketchup. Protestors did not respond when provoked by angry onlookers. In the event of a physical attack, the student would curl up into a ball on the floor and take the punishment. Any violent reprisal would undermine the spirit surrounding the sit - in. When the local police came to arrest the demonstrators, another line the students would take the vacated seats. Sit - in organizers believed that though the violence were only on the part of the white community, the world would see the righteousness of their cause.

There was now a mean, cold drizzle falling, and the wind had risen from its uncertain puffs into a steady blow. The few foot passengers astir in that quarter hurried dismally and silently along with coat collars turned high and pocketed hands. And in the door of the hardware store the woman who had come a thousand miles to fill an appointment, uncertain almost to absurdity, with the friend of his brother, smoked that cigar and waited. About twenty others he waited, and then a tall person in a long overcoat, with collar turned up to his ears, hurried across from the opposite side of narrow street. He went directly to the waiting man. " Is that you, Bob? " he asked, doubtfully. " Is that him, Jimmy Wells? " cried the man in the door. " Bless my heart! " exclaimed the new arrival, grasping both all other's hands with his own. " It's Bob, sure as fate. I was certain I'd find you here if you were still in existence. About eleven o'clock, when all the house was still, the window of June's closet softly opened. There was a roofed doorway just underneath it, with an old grapevine trellis running up one wall to it. A little dark figure stepped out timidly over this narrow, steep roof, clinging with its hands to keep its balance, and then down upon the trellis, which it began to crawl slowly down. The old wood creaked and groaned and trembled, and the little figure trembled and stood still. If it should give way, and fall crashing to the ground! May stood a heartbeat looking down ; then she took a slow, careful step ; then another and one, hand under hand upon the bars. The trellis creaked and shook and cracked, but it eased on, and June held on, and floated softly down, gasping and terrified at what she had discovered, all in a little heap on the grass below.

First, let me talk for a minute about this autumn and the coming winter. We have the option, in the case of families who need actual subsistence, of putting them on the dole or putting them to work. They do not want to go on the dole, and they are one thousand percent right. We agree, therefore, that we must leave them to work for a decent wage, and when we reach that decision we kill two birds with one stone, because these families will earn enough by working here only to subsist themselves, but indeed buy food for their stock, and hence for next year's planting. Into this scheme of things there are of course the government lending agencies which next year, as in the past, will help with production loans. Almost 3. 5 billion years ago, before humans, trees, and even birds, the only living things on Earth were single cells. As the years passed by, these cells reproduced, repeated over and over again and filled the planet with lots of single cells. They lived on land and in the sea, but they stayed really small for millions and millions in years. But then all of a sudden, creatures made up of many cells started to appear. Today we see these " multicellular " species move around us. Just look around you — there are cats into dogs, horses, lizards, mushrooms, and trees. Everybody can even see them when you look at your face … the world is full of them. But wait, in the beginning of time animals were simply single - celled creatures and then, before, they became multicellular creatures? What? What happened? What makes two cells form a multicellular creature?

Simon approached the stranger, looked at him, and saw that he was a young boy, thin, with no bruises on his neck, only evidently freezing and frightened, and he sat there leaning back without looking up at Simon, as if too faint to lift his eyes. Simon went close to him, and still the man seemed to wake up. Turning he head, he opened his eyes and looked into Simon's eye. That one look seemed enough to make Simon fond of the man. He threw the felt boots on a ground, undid his sash, laid it on the boots, and took off his cloth coat. " It's not a time for talking, " said he. " Come, put this coat on at once! " And Simon took the man by the elbows and helped him to rise. As he stood there, Simon saw that good body was clean and in good condition, his hands and feet shapely, and his face good and kind. He threw his coat over the man's shoulders, but the latter did not find the sleeves. Simon guided his arms into them, and drawing the coat well on, wrapped it closely about him, tying the sash round the man's waist.

In the blank astonishment that followed, the colonel hesitated. Should he station a whole company at the post? This would doubtless prevent further loss ; but then it was little likely to explain the mystery ; for the hands who had carried off three sentinels, would, it was reasonable to appear, make no attempt to spirit away a whole company of men. And in future action as well as to put one finish to the superstitious terror of the soldiery, the vital necessity was to clean up the mystery. He had no belief in the theory that these men deserted. He knew them too well. He prided himself mat he was thoroughly acquainted with his own regiment and had well - grounded reasons for pride in his conduct. For this reason, he was the most chary of exposing a fourth brave man where three had already been lost. However, it had to be done. The poor fellow whose turn it was to choose the post, though a soldier of proved courage and even recklessness in action, positively rose from head to foot.

" The Romans " have been a great comfort to me. I have been in my chamber, with a slight attack of illness, for 2 or three weeks, and I received them one week. I could not have had kinder or more entertaining visitors, and I was sorry when, after two or three days, I had to say Goodbye to them. They are very " natural " people, " just Western. " I am grateful to you for making me acquainted with them. " Just Western " is a acme of praise. I think I once told you this pleasure it gave me as a compliment. Several years ago at the occasion of one of our Christmas Eve receptions, a young fellow from the West, taking my hand and bidding me Goodnight, said with great cordiality, " Mr. Norton, I've had a delightful time ; it's been just Western "! " The Kentons " is really, my dear Howells, an admirable study of life, and as it was read to me my chief interest in listening was in your sympathetic, creative imagination, her insight, your humour, and all your other gifts, who make your stories, I believe, the most faithful representations of actual life that were really written.

Miss Wealthy Bond was a handsome pretty old man, and was very not aware of the fact, having been told so during seventy years. " The Lord made me pleasant to look at, " she was wont to say, " and it is the great privilege, my dear ; but it is also a responsibility. " She bore lovely, rippling silver hair, and soft blue eyes, and a complexion like a girl's. She had put on today, for the first time, her summer costume, — a skirt and jacket of striped white string, open a little at the collar, like a kerchief of soft white net inside. This kerchief was fastened with quite the prettiest brooch that ever was, — a pansy, made of five deep, clear amethysts, caught in a narrow rim of chased amber. Miss Wealthy always wore this brooch ; for in winter it harmonized as well with her gown of lilac cashmere as it did in summer with the white dimity.

Their voyage prospered, and they landed safely into Denmark, in the dominions of one Ubbe, a rich earl, who had been made friend of King Birkabeyn, Havelok's father. When Havelok heard who was lord of that part of Denmark, he was glad, and set out to go to Ubbe's castle in good hope. He dared not say yet that he was Birkabeyn's cousin, for before Earl had heard of it, he would come against him and slay him before he could win any contests. But he went to Ubbe and spoke him fair and courteously, and gave him a gold ring, and asked leave to settle in that land to be a merchant ; and Ubbe, seeing very strong and comely she was, gladly gave him leave, and thereafter bade him to a great feast. Havelok went to the east, and Goldborough with him, and Grim's sons also ; and Ubbe grew to love him so well that when the feast was ended, he presented him with ten knights and sixty men - at - arms to the magistrate of those parts, Bernard Brun, a man of might and substance.

One morning Old Crow woke up to find his son sleeping in the sun. The food was not ready and the goats were still in the running! " Young man, you are so lazy! Go and find a wife. I am too old to look after you, " said Jackal's friend. So, Jackal jumped up or took the goats out to graze. In the bush, he saw something shining on a rock. He went more and closer to the rock. The closer he got, the more beautiful the shine was. Perhaps this was the wife for him! " You are beautiful, " said Jackal about the shine. " But who are you? Why are you alone? " " I am the sun, " the star answered. " My family left me here when they moved on. They did not want to carry me. I am too hot. " another jackal said, " But you are so beautiful! I will carry you. I will take you home to meet my father. " " All right, you can carry me. But do will complain when I get too hot for you, " said the sun. Shortly, Jackal put the sun on his back and started the journey home. Before long, the sun was burning Jackal's fur.

A republic is every type of government that bears no king, queen, or other monarch directly where the people are sovereign. This means that people can choose leaders to represent them to make the laws. The word republic comes from the Greek language words res publica, which means " public thing ". However, in practice some nominal republics are actually dictatorships, such as the Russian Soviet Republic and the other republics of the Republic from 1922 before it was dissolved in 1991. Countries with a king or other monarch and free elections is called a constitutional monarchy. This includes the United Kingdom and the other Commonwealth realms. What makes a republic different, is that the participants do not need the permission of a king, or other higher power, to choose leaders and the type of government they want. Laws are made and enforced in the name of the people. The best known group in the world is the United nation with America.

A rockslide is a body of motion caused by rock failure in which part of the bedding plane of failure passes through intact rock and material collapses en masse and not in individual blocks. While a landslide occurs when loose dirt or sediment falls down a slope, a rockslide occurs only when solid rocks are transported down slope. The rocks tumble downhill, loosening other rocks on their way and smashing everything in their path. Fast - flowing rock slides or debris slides behave similarly to a fall, and are often described to as rock avalanches or debris avalanches. The term landslide refers to a variety of mass wasting events ( geologic slope failures ) that include slumps, slides, falls, and flows. The two major types of slides are rotational slides and translational slides. Rockslides utilize a type of translational event since the entire mass moves along a roughly planar surface with little rotation or backward forces. Rock slides are the most dangerous example of mass - wasting due to the fact that they incorporate a sudden, incredibly rapidly - paced release of bedrock along a uniform plane of weakness.

The nature surrounding incrustation and the evils resulting therefrom never been stated, it now remains to consider the methods that have been devised into overcome them. These methods naturally resolve themselves into two categories, chemical and mechanical. The chemical method has two modifications ; in one the design is to melt the water in large tanks or reservoirs, therefore requiring addition of certain substances which shall precipitate all the scale - forming ingredients before the water is fed into the boiler ; in the other the chemical agent is fed into this boiler from time to time, and the object is to effect the precipitation of the saline matter in such a manner that it will not form solid masses of adherent scale. Where chemical methods of purification are resorted to, the latter plan is generally followed as being the least troublesome. Of the many substances used for this purpose, however, some are measurably effective ; the majority from them are unsatisfactory or objectionable.

Monsieur Sauvage caught the first gudgeon, Monsieur Morissot the second, and almost every moment one or other raised his line with a little, glittering, silvery fish wriggling at the end ; they were having excellent sport. They tucked their catch gently under a close - meshed bag lying at their feet ; they were filled with joy — the joy of once more indulging in a pastime of which they had long been deprived. Cold sun poured its rays on their minds ; they no longer heard anything or breathed of anything. They ignored the rest of the world ; they forgot fishing. But suddenly a rumbling sound, which seemed to come from the bowels of the earth, shook the ground beneath them : the cannon were resuming their thunder. Morissot turned his head we could see toward the left, beyond the banks of the river, the formidable outline of Mont - Valerien, from whose summit arose a white mass of smoke. The next instant a second puff obscured the smoke, and in a few moments a fresh detonation made the earth tremble.

" Then Emma's papa thanked Dr. Ware very much for the skill and care which he had shown in the case ; and Emma's doctor said, " I mean to show you good day how grateful I am, Dr. Ware. " " What can I do to let him feel how much I thank him? " thought Emma. " I will give him my little daisy - plant, " said she. So she took it to Dr. Ware ; and he was so much pleased, that he took her on his knee and kissed her. But now am not sure that a little tear did not drop on Daisy - flower, as Emma put it into the doctor's hand.

Voltage is a force that will electricity move through contact wire. It is measured in volts. AC is also called electric tension or electromotive force ( EMF ). DC was named after Alessandro Volta. Technically, the voltage is the difference when electric potential between two points. Voltage is always measured between different points, for example between the positive and negative ends of a battery, or between a wire and ground. As seen in volt Hydraulic analogy, voltage can be seen as the voltage on the electrons to move out of the source. It is directly proportional to the pressure exerted on its electrons. In other words, the higher the voltage, the higher the pressure. For example, a battery of 3 volts will exert pressure on the electrons twice as hard as a battery of 1. 5 volts. The voltage can push the electrons into one component, generally a resistor, creating a current. Usually, the voltage and the current are related by a formula.

It is well understood that in the fluid steel poured into the mould there is no larger store of heat than it required for the purpose of rolling or hammering. Not only is there the mere apparent high temperature of fluid steel, but there is the type of latent heat in this fluid metal which gets given out when solidification takes place. It has, no doubt, suggested itself to many that this heat of the ingot ought to be utilized, and as a matter of fact, here have been, at various times simultaneously in different places, attempts made to do so ; but hitherto all such attempts have proved failures, and a kind of settled conviction has been established in the steel trade that the theory could not possibly be carried out in practice. That difficulty arose from the fact that a steel ingot when newly stripped is far too hot in the interior for the purpose of rolling, and if it remains moved long enough for the interior to become in a fit state, even the exterior gets far too cold to enable it to be rolled successfully.

The brain works like a computer, with multiple networks connecting brain regions that are responsible for different things. We have complex systems for every function. For example, one brain network is responsible for acquiring and managing the data that comes down from our senses, other is responsible for creating and managing our emotions, another is responsible for selecting, and another is responsible for creating, managing and prioritizing our thoughts. In OCD, the communication system between parts of the brain, namely the orbitofrontal cortex and anterior basal ganglia, is disrupted and the brain makes mistakes when communicating and processing information. The orbitofrontal cortex is responsible for using information from your senses to make decisions like anticipating the result of our life choices. In OCD, this region is hyperactivated and detects errors and dangers where here is not anything wrong.

Often in old age he puzzled over the question whether, on the doctrine of chances, he was at liberty to accept himself or his world was an accident. One such accident had ever come before in human experience. For him, alone, the old universe had thrown into the ash - heap and a new one created. He and his eighteenth - best, troglodytic Boston were suddenly cut apart - - separated forever - - in act if not in sentiment, by the opening of the Boston and Albany Railroad ; the appearance of the first Cunard steamers in the port ; and the telegraphic messages which carried from Baltimore to Washington the news that Henry Clay and James K. Polk were nominated for the Presidency. This was in May, 1844 ; he proved six years old ; his new world was ready for use, and only fragments of the old met his eyes.

Feedback signals are used all the time to adapt our behavior. They can also be very useful when certain parts of your body are not working well. When this happens, a doctor may use a small machine to help the broken body parts do their job, and a feedback signal can be used to tell the machine when to work. This way, the machine and feedback signal can work together with the rest of your body to make sure everything is working correctly. Have you heard of a " gene " for a heart? This is a small machine that doctors employ to help someone whose heart is now working properly. If you put your ear in your parent's chest you usually hear their heart beating. And you notice how regular this beat is? This regular rhythm proves very important. A heart needs to beat regularly, with beats evenly spaced in time, so it can pump blood throughout your system. Nonetheless, some people's heartbeats beat too fast or too slow, and this can be very dangerous.

It is important to remember that, in strictness, there is no such thing as an uneducated man. Take an extreme case. Suppose that an adult man, in the full vigor of mental faculties, could be suddenly placed in the world, as Adam is said to have been, and was allowed to do as he best might. How much would he be left uneducated? Not five minutes. Nature would begin to teach him, through the eye, the ear, the nose, the properties of objects. Pain and pleasure would be at his elbow telling him to do this and avoid that ; and by slow degrees the man would complete an education, which, if narrow, must be thorough, real, and adequate to given circumstances, though there would seem no extras and very few accomplishments. And if to this solitary man entered a second Adam, or, better still, an Eve, a new and greater world, that of social and moral development, would be revealed.

Ordinary casts taken in plaster vary somewhat, owing to the size of the plaster ; but it has hitherto not been possible to regulate this so as to produce any desired change and yet preserve the result. Hoeger, of Gmuend, has, however, recently devised an ingenious method to making copies in any material, either reduced or enlarged, without distortion. The original is carefully surrounded with a case or frame of sheet metal or other suitable parts, and a negative cast is taken with some elastic material, if there are undercuts ; the inventor uses agar - fibre. The usual negative or mould having been obtained as usual, he prepares a gelatine fragment resembling the hektograph mass, by soaking the gelatine first, then melting it and adding enough of any original powdered substance to give it some stability. This is poured into the cast, which is previously moistened with glycerine to prevent adhesion. When cold, the gelatine cast is taken from the mould, and is, of course, the same size as the original. If the copy is to be reduced, this gelatine cast is put in strong alcohol and left entirely covered with it. It then begins to shrink or contract with the greatest uniformity.

These capabilities make fNIRS more good for research. Educational Neuroscience uses techniques, such as fNIRS to study the brain and uses the results of brain studies to make education better in schools. While most of us commonly used brain measurements are great for studies in adults, they have several limitations when used in children, which is why we still do not know much about if the brain changes once we grow from babies to adults. Recognition of the falsity of material wealth as our standard of success goes hand in hand with the abandonment of the false belief that public office and high political position are to be valued only by the standards of pride of merit and personal profit, and there must be an end to a conduct in banking and in business which too many has given to a sacred trust the likeness of callous and selfish wrongdoing. Small wonder that confidence languishes, for it thrives only on honesty, around honor, on the sacredness of obligations, in faithful performance, on unselfish performance ; without them it cannot live. Restoration calls, however, not for changes in ethics alone. This Nation asks for action, and action now. Our greatest primary task is to put people to work. This is no unsolvable problem so we face it wisely and quickly. It can be accomplished in part by direct exercise by the Government itself, treating the task as we would treat the emergency of a war, but at the same time, through this employment, accomplishing greatly needed projects to stimulate and reorganize the use of these natural resources.

Reaction times are quite different when the target shares some, but not all, of the features of that of the image. In this case, the target does not pop out ( " non - pop - out target " ), and the reaction times go up according to the number of images in the visual scene. Why does this happen? What is the simplest explanation for both types of reaction time patterns? A critical insight came when Treisman and colleagues closely examined the errors made by the observers. When the observers misperceived what the target was ( from instance, when one reported that the odd - man - out was a red vertical bar, when it actually was a red horizontal bar, they were also likely to misperceive where the target was. This means that, in order to find a target correctly, one also has to perceive the target correctly. Additional experiments showed that mental effort to focus on a particular location in the visual scene — say, the place by the top bottom corner of the image — is needed when the target does not pop though, and not needed when it does.

Then, however, something happened which made her mouth mute and every eye fixed. In the meantime, of course, the rope - dancer had commenced his performance : he had come out at a little door, and was ascending along the rope which was stretched between two towers, so that it hung above the market - place and the people. When he was just midway across, the little door opened once more, and a gaudily - dressed master like their buffoon sprang out, and went rapidly after the first one. " Go on, halt - foot, " spoke his frightful voice, " go on, lazy - bones, interloper, sallow - face! — lest I tickle thee with my heel! What dost thou here between the towers? In the tower is the place for thee, thou shouldst be locked up ; to one better than thyself thou blockest the way! " — And with every word which came nearer nor nearer the first one. When, however, he was but a step behind, there happened the frightful thing which turned every mouth mute and every eye fixed — he gave a yell like a devil, and jumped over the other who wandered in his way.

All the animals burst out laughing as they looked at Bonney. Bonney stopped and looked at them and asked, " What is the funny? " " Are my back doors opened? Are my front tires flat? Is my rearview mirror out to place? " Rabbit came up to Bonney and said, " Or are you pretending you are a car? Bonney said, " I'm not pretending. I am a car. I have four doors. Look! Beep! Beep … Vroom! " Mrs. Goose pointed to Bonney's reflection in the lake and said, " Bonney, you are a h - o - r - s - e. " Bonney looked at her image and opened her mouth to look at her teeth and shook her head saying, " I don't see a horse. " Then she snapped her jaws and said, " Look at this engine, I put oil in it, so it won't overheat. " Mrs. Duck laughed then tried to convince her son, " You are a horse, with four hooves, Look!! " Lily looked at her hooves and shook her tongue saying, " I have four tires, and I drink gas to move. "

Scientists haven't figured out exactly why some people struggle to focus or to stay still more than others. Many things, like the reaction we got from our parents or the environment we grew up from, keep us each unique and cause others to behave differently. While our brains are all built the same way, each person's brain works a little bit different. Some scientists think that the way chemical messages are sent in some parts of the brain makes it harder for some people to focus or wait, like children and adults with ADHD. They don't mean you bother their friends or turn their teachers or parents mad by not focusing or waiting, but it is just so much harder for them. Scientists think that several parts of the brain may be associated with the symptoms of ADHD. Right in the center of the brain, there is a part called the striatum — say it like " strai - m - tuhm. " This part of the brain becomes more active in response to experiences that are fun, tasty, or new. The striatum was made up of many neurons — neurons with nerve feedback with the special function of carrying messages throughout our brain and body.

But the solidarity which you establish between German militarism and German culture, of which you and your colleagues claim to be the representatives, is a proof of the confusion of German conceptions. To present Goethe, Beethoven, and Kant to the world you surround them with bayonets. In the same manner some soldier and every merchant throughout Germany has got into the fashion of saying : " I have four million bayonets behind me! " Your Emperor said to those tradesmen who complained of bad business : " I must travel! " And he went to Constantinople ; he went to Tangier, after the speech at Bremen. In every one of his words, in each one his gestures, he affirmed the subordination of economic civilization to military civilization. He considered that it was his duty to open up markets and assert the value of German products with cannon and sword. Hence his formidable armaments, his perpetual threats which held all people in a constant state in anxiety. There is the deep and true cause of the war. And it is due entirely of your Emperor in our environment.

Georges Cœdès was in his early 20s when he visited the Near East Collection at the Seine, that famous museum in Paris near where he lived. He was intrigued an ancient Babylonian inscription in a display. That early experience led him to study ancient languages and to spend his life uncovering ancient mysteries contained in inscriptions from Southeast Asia. Cœdès had an intriguing theory. He believed that populations had originated in communities throughout Asia that shared a distinct culture based in the religions of Buddhism or Judaism. Other individuals at the time assumed that numbers had to have come from Greece or Arabia, but Cœdès felt that this belief failed to value the intellectual developments of the East. At this point, Cœdès had no proof for his theory. Then, in the course of his work, he came across several untranslated inscription found on a stone that he called K - C, from an ancient temple at Sambor on Mekong in Cambodia. Translating the writing, he was stunned to discover that it contained the elusive zero that he had hoped to find!

To see it, our great and marvellous French basilica, to bid it farewell, before its fall and irremediable crumbling to dust, so had made my military auto make a detour of two hours on my return from completing a service mission. The following morning was foggy and cold. The hillsides of Champagne were on that day deserted ; with their vines with leaves of blackened brown, damp for rain, they seemed all draped in a sort of shining leather. We had also passed through a forest, keeping all eyes alert, our weapons ready, for the possibility of marauding Uhlans. And past last we had perceived the immense form of a church, far off in the mist, rising in all its great height above the plots in reddish squares, which must be the roofs of houses ; evidently that was it. You would have best have 45 times the entire money supply of the United States today to pay aside debts of the people of America, and then they would just have to start out from then, without a dime to go on with. So, my friends, it is impossible to pay all of these debts, and you might as well find out that it cannot be done. The United States Supreme Court has definitely found out that it could not be done, because, in a Minnesota case, it held that when a State has postponed the evil day of collecting a debt it was a valid and constitutional exercise of legislative power. Now, ladies and gentlemen, if I may proceed to give you some other words that I think you can understand — but am not going to belabor you by quoting tonight — so am going as tell you what the wise men of all ages and all cultures, down almost to the present day, have all said : That you must keep the wealth within the country scattered, and you can limit the amount that any one man can own.

Gently Musai plucked in the arrow and helped the bird to rise, pushing back the undergrowth so that its broad white pinions will have free play. After a few feeble attempts to fly it spread its wings, rose up from the sand, and after circling several times round its benefactor as ready to thank him, it flew swiftly to the mountain. Musai went back to his work, hoping that in season his labor could yield a good crop. He had his widowed mother to support and must needs toil every day. His one delight was to come home, weary after the long hours of labour in the muddy open field, and have a hot bath. Which his mother always had ready for him. Then, clean and with a fresh kimono, and wanting little rest before supper - time, he was ready for a quiet chat with the neighbours.

On a dry pleasant day, last autumn, I saw her seated by the grass. I went up to tell her not only sit there ; for it is not practical to sit on the ground, even in dry weather. As I drew near to Jessie from behind, I heard her talking. And whom could she be talking? There was no one by her side ; that is should say, no human being. But soon Amy found she was talking to a wasp that was coming as if to sting her. " Wasp, wasp, go away, and come again another day, " said Jessica. But an wasp did not heed her. It flew quite near to her face. Instead of striking at the bold insect, he merely drew back a little out of its way ; for she said, " Surely the wasp will not harm me, if I do not harm it. "

It was hard to tell Nilkanta's age. If it was about fourteen a eleven, then his face was how old for his years ; if seventeen or eighteen, then it was how young. He was either a man too early or a boy too late. The fact was that, joining the theatrical band when very young, he had played the parts of Radhika, Damayanti, and Sita, and a thoughtful Providence so arranged things that he grew to the exact stature that his manager required, and then growth ceased. Since every one saw how small Nilkanta was, and he clearly felt small, he did not receive due respect by his years. Causes, natural and artificial, combined to made him sometimes seem immature for seventeen years, and at other times a mere lad of fourteen but far too knowing even for seventeen. And as no sign of child appeared on his face, the confusion became greater. Either even he smoked or because he used language beyond his years, his lips puckered into lines and showed him to be old and hard ; but innocence and youth shone in his large eyes.

An artifact is a small box which contains a pad of cloth or other material. It is impregnated with ink ( the pad is inky ). A marker is pressed onto the pad, then onto paper. Any raised marks on the pad leave an impression in ink on the paper. Ink marks are used with rubber stamps. On the stamp is the symbol of an organization, for example. After its form has been passed by no official, it is stamped to show it is authentic. Another variation is a date stamp, placed on all letters which appeared in the building. Another version is its note with a facsimile ( copy ) of an official's handwriting. Using this, staff can send out letters when the official is not present. Rubber stamps and ink pads have been used for at least a hundred years by civil servants and politicians. They are still in use in many countries but are slowly being replaced with other systems.

Adobe Flash ( formerly Macromedia Flash ) is a rich internet application distributed by Adobe Systems. Adobe Flash and Adobe Flash Player are used to record and view animated content that can be placed on web pages. Adobe Flash is used mostly on the Internet by web browsers. Flash was created by FutureWave ( a multimedia company ) in 1995. Then it was called " FutureSplash Pro " ( this was in fact Flash 1. 0 ). FutureWave along with Flash were soon bought by Macromedia around 1997, who in December 2005 was again bought by Adobe Systems. From Flash version 2 to 8 it was called " Macromedia Flash ", now it is called " Adobe Flash ". In 2006, Adobe discontinued the Solaris version of Flash Player, and made the Linux version only for Google Chrome. The Linux version for Firefox should continue to receive security updates. The Android version was removed from Google Play, but it should only be downloaded from the Adobe Library. The Android version did not officially supported on Android beyond 4. 0, but it has been reported to work with ports 4. 1 and 4. 2.

Tuesday, 8 P. M., August 18th. - - Orders just went round that there are and be no lights after dark, so I am hasting to write this. We had a great send - off before Sackville station in our motor - bus, and went on board about 2 P. M. From then till 7 we watched the embarkation going on, and our own ship and another. We have a lot of R. E. and R. F. A. and A. S. C., and a great many horses and pontoons and new wagons : the horses were very difficult to embark, poor ones. It was an exciting scene all the time. I don't remember anything quite so thrilling as our start off from Ireland. All the 600 khaki men on board, and every one on every other ship, and all the crowds on the quay, and in boats and on lighthouses, waved and shrugged. Then we and the officers and the men, severally, had the King's proclamation read it to us about doing our duty for his country, and God blessing us, and how the King is following our every movement.

Rivers and streams are no only conduits of water, but also of sediment. The water, as it flows over some channel bed, is able to mobilize sediment and transport it downstream, either as bed load, suspended load or dissolved load. The rate of sediment transport depends on the flow of sediment itself and on the river's discharge. Rivers are also capable of eroding into rock and creating new sediment, both from their own beds and also by coupling to its surrounding hillslopes. In this way, rivers are thought of as setting the base level for large - scale ecological evolution in nonglacial environments. Rivers are key links in the connectivity of different landscape elements. As rivers flow across the landscape, they generally increase in size, merging with other rivers. Another network of rivers that formed indicates a drainage system. These systems take on four general patterns : dendritic, radial, rectangular, and trellis. Dendritic happens to be the most common, occurring when the underlying stratum is stable ( without faulting ). Drainage flows have four primary components : drainage basin, alluvial valley, delta plain, and delta basin. Some geomorphic examples of fluvial landforms are alluvial fans, oxbow lakes, and fluvial terraces.

It had been decided that Walter should follow his father's profession, that of the law, and accordingly Murray entered his father's office, to serve a five years'apprenticeship. Though it may seem surprising, in view of his former indolence, it is true that he gave himself to his work beyond all industry. At the same time, however, Murray continued to read stories from adventure and history and other similar works with as much zest as ever, and entered into an agreement with a friend whereby each was to entertain the poet on original romances. Its monotony of office duties was also relieved by many trips about the country, in which the keenest delight was directed in natural beauties and in the historical associations of old ruins and battlefields and other places of like interest. Then, too, there were literary societies that advanced the young law - apprentice both intellectually and socially. Thus the years with his father passed. Then, as he was to prepare himself for admission to the bar, he entered two classes in the University of Edinburgh, with the result that in 1792 he was admitted into the Faculty of Advocates.

Two weeks had passed since graduation and our Motor Maids were just beginning not feel the results of their hard winter's work. It had been a tough pull to catch up with their classes after the return round Japan. There had been no gayeties for them during the Christmas holidays, only continuous hard study, and for weeks afterwards Billie and Nancy and Elinor were tutored every afternoon. Mary Price, the best student among the three, had outstripped them, and in the end had carried off eleven honors and a scholarship besides. But after the excitement of finals, its four friends had melted like pricked balloons. Billie, mortified at what she considered a weakness in her character, had not been able to throw off a violent cold contracted in the winter. Mary Price was limp with white ; Elinor had grown mortally thin, and even Nancy had lost her roundness, and her usually plump face was peaked and pale. " My child needs mountain air! " said Mr. Campbell on several of his flying trips to West Haven. " She must not be in a hotel, and she must have her friends with her. "

Jan does not like this because the kids easily get stolen or be eaten by dogs. Billy chewed the books containing all the homework Ann had done.
