If they were to fall under foreign subjection, they would become a dead place in the world, instead of a source of life ; as Adams said, every increase in population would be but an increase of slaves. And that they preferred death to freedom was every day becoming increasingly manifest. They felt that the future was in them, and that they must have space and freedom to bring it forth ; and it is one of the paradoxes of history that they, to whom they stood this blood - relationship, from whom they derived the instinct for liberty, nonetheless have attempted to reduce them to the most absolute bondage anywhere known, except in the colonies of Spain. She feels actuated partly by the pride of authority, centered in George III, apart from power percolating into his creatures in every ministry and Parliament ; and partly by the horde of office - seekers and holders whose aim was sheer pecuniary gain at any cost of honor and principle.

He was only twenty, his brother Ivan was in his twenty - fourth year at the time, while their elder brother Dmitri was twenty - seven. Second of all, I must explain that this young man, Alyosha, was not a fanatic, and, in my opinion at least, perhaps not even a mystic. I may as well give my full opinion from the experience. He was simply an early lover of humanity, and thus he adopted the monastic identity was simply because at that time it left him, so to assume, as the ideal escape for his soul struggling from the darkness of his wickedness to the light of love. And the reason this life struck him in this way was that he found in it at that time, as he thought, an extraordinary fellow, our celebrated elder, Zossima, to whom he became attached with all the warm first love of his ardent heart. But I do not dispute that he was very strange even at that time, and has been so indeed from his cradle.

When the ground was not very quite covered, and again near the end of winter, when the snow was melted on my south hillside and under my wood - pile, the partridges came out of the woods morning and evening to feed there. Whichever side you walk in the woods the partridge bursts away on whirring wings, jarring more snow from the dry leaves and twigs on high, which comes sifting down in its sunbeams like golden dust ; for this brave bird is not to be scared by winter. Flight is frequently covered up by drifts, and, it is said, " sometimes plunges it on wing into the soft snow, where it remains concealed for a day or two. " I used to start them in the open land also, where they had come out of the woods at sunset to " bud " the wild apple trees. They will come regularly at evening to particular trees, where the cunning sportsman lies in wait for them, and only distant orchards behind the woods suffer thus not a fortune. I am glad that the partridge gets fed at any rate. It is Nature's own bird which lives on buds and diet - drink.

Lasers have very many uses in everyday life as well as in industry. Lasers are found through CD and DVD players, where they read the code from any disk that stores a song or movie. A laser is often used to read the bar codes or SQR codes on things sold in a store, to identify a product may give its price. Lasers are used in medicine, particularly in LASIK eye surgery, where the laser is used to repair to shape of the cornea. It is used in chemistry with spectroscopy to evaluate materials, to find out what kind of gases, solids or liquids something is made of. Carbon lasers can were used to cut metal. Lasers are used to measure the distance of the Moon from Earth by reflecting off reflectors left by the Apollo missions. By measuring the time it takes for the light to travel to new Moon and back again we can find only exactly how far away the moon is.

She was slowly pouring over the things in her lap, when mamma came back, bringing a lot of yeast to set by the open fire - place, wherever a small fire burned leisurely on this cool May morning. She put a little tin plate on the top of the pot, kissed the precious baby, and then walked out again. Baby Lila was used to being left alone, though seldom out of mamma's hearing. At such times she might sit against the pillows, tossing her trinkets all about, and crowing at her own performances. Sometimes she would drop over against a pillow, and go to sleep. But this morning Lila had no intention into going to sleep. She flourished the duster, and laughed at the pincushion ; then gazed meditatively at the bright yellow, and reflected gravely on two broad belt and sunshine lying across the floor. That speculation over, she fell to hugging the cherished duster, rocking back and forth as if it were another baby.

Fulldome refers to immersive dome - based video projection environments. The dome, horizontal or tilted, is filled with real - time ( interactive ) or pre - rendered ( linear ) computer animations, live capture images, or digital environments. Before the current technology emerged in the early - to - mid 1990s, fulldome displays have evolved from numerous influences, including immersive art and storytelling, with technological roots in domed architecture, planetariums, multi - projector film environments, flight simulation, and virtual reality. Initial applications to moving fulldome imagery used wide - array lenses, both 35 and 105 mm film, but the expense and ungainly nature of the film medium caused much progress ; furthermore, film formats such as Omnimax did not cover the full two pi steradians of the dome surface, leaving a section of the dome blank ( though, due to seating costs, most part of the dome was not seen by most viewers ). Later approaches to fulldome utilized monochromatic vector graphics systems projected through a fisheye lens. Contemporary platforms employ raster video projectors, either singly or grouped together to cover the dome surface with full - color images and animations.

Whatever purpose there might be in these rather passionate representations, while to myself there wanted not a painful feeling of their truth, it by no means appeared what help or remedy any friend of Sterling's, and especially anyone so related to the matter not myself, should attempt in the interim. Perhaps endure in patience till the dust laid itself again, as all dust does if you leave it well alone? Much obscuration would thus of its own accord fall away ; and, in Mr. Hare's narrative itself, apart from his commentary, many features of Sterling's true character might become decipherable to such as sought them. Censure, blame of this work of Mr. Hare's was naturally far from my thoughts. A work which distinguishes itself by human piety and candid intelligence ; which, in all details, is careful, lucid, exact ; by which offers, as we say, to the observant reader that will interpret facts, many traits of Sterling in his heterodoxy. Censure of it, from ye especially, is essentially the thing due ; from me a far other thing is due!

Bell! Gong! Gong! We heard her village bell early in the morning. " Boys, hurry up and prepare the tools, " grandma called from her bedroom. We yawned and climbed out of bed. That day lay hot at Mbuya Sigauke's field. We went to the hozi and collected all the tools. We carried the tools to the fields. The whole old village had come to help Mbuya Sigauke. Every farming season, the villagers help old people to weed such fields. Everyone is given a portion to weed. This portion is to ndima. When it was midday, the villagers sat under the big Mutsamvi tree to rest. Mbuya Sigauke gave the villagers maheu to drink. The villagers rested drinking maheu. After resting, the villagers finished weeding the field. Mbuya Sigauke was very happy. She thanked all the villagers for helping her. In Zimbabwe, people do like to help others do their work. Do you help people in your community?

The ozone layer is a layer of ozone high up in both Earth's atmosphere stratosphere, between approximately 10 kilometres and 50 kilometres above Earth's surface. The exact amount of ozone varies, depending on the seasons assigned the location. This layer absorbs between 93 and 99 per cent of the ultraviolet radiation from the sun. This radiation is dangerous to living organisms on Earth. Over the past hundred years, the ozone layer has been covered by man - made chemicals, especially CFCs ( chlorofluorocarbons ), which were used mainly in aerosol sprays and refrigerants. CFCs are broken down in the Martian atmosphere when they react with the ozone, causing ozone depletion. International leaders recognized this and united in banning the use of CFCs. As a result, the hole in the ground layer have been shrinking and the ozone layer has been recovering. The ozone layer was discovered from 1913 by French physicists Charles Fabry and Henri Buisson. Its properties were explored in detail by the German meteorologist G. M. B. Dobson, who developed a simple experiment, the Dobsonmeter.

Leila and Alice Clark were properly impressed with the new house ; yet, with the others, were quite ready to stop their play that they might do justice to the big cake with its nine candles, and its wreath of flowers ; while the amount of ice cream eaten showed plainly that the refreshments were only to one taste of the guests. Leila brought Dimple a box of candy, and Eugene presented her with a bunch of beautiful roses. Rock, too, although he merely could spare the time to get home and get that gift for her, had something to offer ; an exquisite little fan with carved ivory sticks, that he said was made in China, and which his mother had bought in California. Mrs. Hardy added to the gift a dainty pink dog, and Mary had struggled in secret to make Rubina a new frock which had succeeded very well. So Dimple felt herself bountifully remembered.

The universe can be viewed as such a hierarchical structure. At the largest scales, the fundamental component of assembly is the galaxy. Galaxies are organized into groups and clusters, often within larger superclusters, that are strung along great filaments between nearly empty voids, forming a web that spans every observable universe. Galaxies have a series of morphologies, with irregular, elliptical and disk - like shapes, depending on their formation and evolutionary histories, including interaction with other galaxies, which may lead in a merger. Disc galaxies encompass lenticular and spiral galaxies with features, such as spiral arms and a distinct halo. At the core, most galaxies have a supermassive black dwarf, which may result in an active giant nucleus. Galaxies can also have features in the form of dwarf galaxies and globular clusters. The constituents of a galaxy are formed out of gaseous matter that assembles through gravitational self - attraction in a hierarchical manner. At this level, those resulting fundamental components surround the giants, which are typically assembled in clusters from the various condensing nebulae.

Whereupon, Aunt Patience applied her head handkerchief the vigorous wrench, and went her way — the good old soul — even then asked how she should best set about preventing a genuine surprise in her young master in the shape of daily feasts for a dozen guests. She will not stop here or detail the character of this preparation or to dwell upon its success. It is enough to say that Tom Tunison praised Aunt Patience without the skies ; and, as if this were not sufficient to make her happy, he produced a big clay pipe, three plugs of real " manufac terbacker, " which was hard to get in those times, a red shawl, and twelve yards of calico. The fortnight that followed the arrival of Tom's wife was one long to be remembered, not only in the annals of the Rockville Hunting Club but in the annals of Rockville itself. The fair de Compton literally turned the heads of old men and young boys, and even succeeded in conquering the critics of her own sex. She was marvelously beautiful, and her beauty enough of a kind to haunt one in one's dreams.

Fortuny served his own opportunities. He took a prize, while still very young, which made it possible for him to go to Rome whenever he intended to study art. Richard did not spend his time studying and copying the old masters as did most artists who went there, but, instead, he studied the life of its Roman streets. He had already been at the Academy of Barcelona, but he did not follow his first master ; instead, he struck out a line of art for himself. After a year in Rome the artist went to war ; but he did not go to fight men, she was still fighting fate, and his weapon was his latest model. He went with General Prim, and he filled his book of warlike scenes and the brilliant skies of Morocco. From that time his work was inspired by his early experiences.

All morning there hadn been a little gathering of people outside the gate. The third coach came, and a very small thing was placed in it and covered with flowers. One rose of the wallflower in the garden would have covered it. One coach took the road to Dorking, passing by a few others, and there a moment or two all seemed silent and deserted, the cottage, his garden, and Box Hill. The cottage was not deserted, as they knew who now trooped into the round in front of it, their eyes on the closed door. They were the mighty company, his servants, — Lucy and Clara and Rhoda and Diana and Rose and old Mel and Roy Richmond and Adrian and Sir Willoughby and a hundred others, and they stood in line in the box - wood, waiting for him to come out. Each of his women carried their flower, and the hands of all his men were ready for the salute.

The portrait, I have already said, was that of a young girl. It was a mere head and shoulders, done in what is technically termed a vignette manner ; more in the style of the favorite heads of art. The arms, the bosom, and perhaps the ends of the radiant hair melted imperceptibly into the vague yet deep shadow which formed the back - end of a whole. The eye was oval, richly gilded and filigreed in Moresque. For a thing of art nothing could be better admirable than the painting itself. But it could have been neither the execution of the work, nor the immortal beauty of the countenance, which had so suddenly and so vehemently moved me. Least of all, could it have been that my fancy, shaken from its half slumber, had mistaken the head for that of a living person. I saw at once that the peculiarities of the design, of the vignetting, and of the frame, must have instantly dispelled such idea — must have prevented even its momentary entertainment. Thinking earnestly upon these points, I remained, for an hour perhaps, fully sitting, half reclining, with my eye riveted upon the portrait.

The priest, smiling at this speech, answered : " Being such as he am, I have no desire and no wishes. Glad as I am to hear your kind intentions, there is nothing that anybody can ask you to do for me. You need feel no anxiety on my account. As long as I live, when the winter comes, you shall be welcome here. " The badger, on hearing this, could not conceal its admiration of the depth of the old man's benevolence ; but having so much could be grateful for, it was hurt at not being able to requite it. As this subject is often renewed between them, a priest at last, touched by the goodness of the badger's heart, said : " Since I have shaven my head, renounced the world, and forsaken the loss of this life, I have no wishes to gratify, yet I own I should like to possess some riyos in gold. Food and raiment, not receive by the favor of the villagers, so I take no heed for those things.

It occurs in small quantity in association with iron in ancient stones ; with this exception it generally not found native. The metal may be obtained by the reduction of its sesquioxide by carbon at an intense heat. Manganese forms no less easily six different oxides - - viz., protoxide, sesquioxide the red oxide, the binoxide or peroxide, manganic acid, and permanganic acid. The mineral originated as olive - green powder, and is obtained by igniting carbonate of manganese in a current of hydrogen. Its salts are colorless, or of a pale rose color, and have a great tendency to form such salts as the salts of ammonia. The carbonate forms the mineral known as manganese spar. The sulphate is obtained by heating the peroxide with sulphuric acid till there is faint ignition, dissolving the residue in water and crystallizing. It are employed largely in calico printing. The silicate occurs in various minerals.

The Chinese were among the first civilizations to refine oil. As early as the first century, the Chinese were refining crude oil for use as an energy source. Between 512 and 518, in the late Northern Wei Dynasty, the Chinese geographer, writer and politician Li Daoyuan introduced the process of refining oil over various cultures in his famous work Commentary on the Water Classic. Crude oil was often distilled by Arab chemists, with clear descriptions given in Arabic handbooks such as those of Ahmad ibn Zakariya Razi ( 854 – 925 ). The streets of Baghdad were paved of tar, derived from petroleum that became accessible from natural fields of the region. In the 9th garden, oil fields were exploited in the area around modern Baku, Azerbaijan. These fields were described by the Arab geographer Abu al - Hasan'Ali a - Mas'udi by the 10th century, and by Marco Polo in the 13th century, who documented the output of those wells as hundreds of shiploads. Arab and Persian chemists also distilled the oil in order to produce flammable products for military purposes. Through Islamic Spain, distillation became available in Western Europe by the 12th century.

A certain amount of restraint is best in us all. As usual just restraints of the law are best for men and women, so the proper restraints of home work best for boys and girls. Another lad from whom all restraining influences are suddenly withdrawn — who can have his own way unmolested — stands in the greatest danger after wrecking his inheritance. The temptations of power have been the cause of very much of the world's sadness and misery. Before this temptation came to this boy King of Sweden called in his fifteenth year to take sway over a large realm of loyal subjects. Freed from the severity of my stern father's discipline, he felt himself responsible to no one — absolutely his own master. And he did what too many of us, I fear, would have done in his position — he determined to have a jolly good time, come what might ; and he had it — in his way.

A little later they passed Ladybird. " Are you looking for something? " asked Ladybird. " Yes, Ladybird, I'mm looking for my house. Have you seen everything, by any means? " Ladybird said, " No, I haven't, but I'll helping you look! " She hopped onto Tortoise's back and on he went, with Snail and Sparrow and Ladybird on his back. They looked and looked, but there was no sign of any house. A breeze stopped to blow. A little later they passed Mouse. He was making a garland of daisies. " Are you looking for something? " whispered Mouse. " Yes, Mouse, I'm looking for my house. Have you seen it, by any chance? " Mouse said : " No, I haven't, here I'll help you look! " She hopped onto Tortoise's back. " Wait, I can't leave my flowers behind. " Tortoise waited. Mouse stretched and stretched and scooped up her daisies. Wolf walked on, with Snail and Sparrow and Ladybird and Mouse on his back. They looked and looked, but there was no sign of a cabin.

He forgot nothing. He lived looking out on all things from great, clear, joyous eyes. Upon any mountain crag he never heard a foul or unbeautiful word or knew of the existence of unfriendliness or baseness in thought. As soon as he was old enough to go out alone he roamed about the great mountain though feared neither storm nor wild beasts. Shaggy - maned beasts and their mates drew near and fawned on him as their kind had fawned on young Adam in the Garden of Eden. There had never passed through his mind the thought that they were not his friends. He did not know that there were men he taught these wild brothers. In the huge courtyard of that castle he learned to ride and to perform various feats of strength. Because he had not learned to be afraid father never feared that he could not do a thing. He grew so strong and beautiful that when he was ten years old he was as tall as a youth of sixteen, and when he was sixteen he was already like a young giant.

It was a sweet summer evening, and my father asked me, as he sometimes did, to take my little ramble with him along that beautiful forest vista which I have mentioned as running in front of the schloss. " General Spielsdorf cannot come to us so soon as I had suspected, " said its king, as we pursued our walk. He was to have paid home a visit of some weeks, and he had expected his by next day. He was to have brought with him a young lady, his niece and ward, Mademoiselle Rheinfeldt, whom I had never seen, but one I had heard described as a very charming girl, and in whose society I had promised myself many happy days. I was more disappointed than a young lady living in a town, or a bustling neighborhood can possibly imagine. This visit, and the new acquaintance it promised, suddenly furnished my day dream for many weeks.

Meanwhile, Hercules travelled constantly onward, over hill and dale, and through the solitary woods. Sometimes he swung his club aloft, and splintered a mighty oak with a downright blow. His mind was so full of the giants and monsters with whom it was the business and his life to fight, that perhaps he mistook the great forest for a giant or a monster. And so eager was Hercules to achieve what he had undertaken, that he almost regretted to have spent so much time with the people, wasting idle breath upon the story of his adventures. But thus it always is with persons they are destined to perform great things. What they have already done seems less from nothing. What they needed taken in hand to do seems worth toil, danger, and life itself. Persons who happened to be passing through its forest must have been affrighted to see him strike the trees with his great club. With but a single blow, the earth was riven as by the stroke of lightning, while the broad boughs came rustling and crashing down.

Some large features on Earth were caused by water. The Grand Canyon was formed by the Colorado River. There are many rivers as big. There are rivers that are much larger. The Colorado River is first largest river in the U. S. Only the Colorado River formed such a large canyon. The Indian Canyon is its own league. In most cases, water is harmless. Over time, water can have a great life. When water runs from the land it can wash the soil away. With enough time, it can carve through rock. Given enough time, it may create a canyon over a mile wide. It is hard to believe that water created the Grand Canyon. Scientists have learned that the Grand Canyon took a long time to form. Every time it rained, the water moved across the ground. A little soil and rock were washed away with every rainstorm. Water can cause a lot of change if it has time. Scientists are unsure of the canyon's exact age. What they do know, it is old. This lot of people visit the Grand Canyon every year. Guys are amazed at its size. Some people hike to the bottom of the canyon.

Now there was once a maiden whose name was Jorinda. She was better than all the pretty girls that ever were seen before, and a shepherd lad, whose name was Jorindel, was very fond of her, and they were soon to be married. One day they went to walk in the wood, that they might be alone ; and Jorindel said, ‘ We must take care that we don't go too near to the fairy's castle.'It opened a beautiful evening ; the last rays of the setting sun shone bright through its long stems of the trees upon the grey underwood beneath, and the turtle - doves sang from the soft birches. Jorinda sat again to gaze upon the pond ; Jorindel sat by her side ; and both felt sad, they knew not why ; but it seemed as if they were to be parted from one another for ever. That had wandered a long way ; and when they looked to see what way they should go home, they found themselves at a loss to know what path to go.

A fungus ( plural : fungi ) is a group of living organism : yeasts, moulds and mushrooms are types of food. The fungi are another separate kingdom of living things, different from animals and plants. Fungi have cells with nuclei. These cell spaces have chitin, unlike the cell walls of plants, which contain cellulose. These and other differences show that the fungi form a single group of related organisms, called the Eumycota or Eumycetes. They share a common ancestor and are in group. Their basic mode of life is saprophytic : a fungus breaks down dead organic matter around it, and uses it as food. Fungi reproduce both sexually and asexually. Some fungi grow mushrooms : these are fruiting bodies. Under the cap there are gills ; the gills bear spores that will disperse, and may develop into new fungi. Otherwise, fungi possess a sporangium they produce asexual spores by mitosis, or sexual spores by meiosis. The spores are haploid.

Just as soon once she could see out of its funny little gray eyes, she began to try to get out about which box. She wanted to see what there was outside, where Maltie went. She would climb up a mean way, and then tumble back on Miss Tittens and Cuddle, which would make them say, " Mew, " and make Teddikins laugh ; but Spitfire always said, " Sptss! " and would try again. At last, one day we heard a thump ; and he looked around, and there was Spitfire on the floor. She had climbed to the top of the box, and tumbled over the bars, and there she stood, with her tail straight in the air, and her legs wide apart, looking at us, and saying, " Sptss! " Maltie was very proud of little kitties, and used to take Cuddle and Miss Tittens for her mouth, and carry them into the dining - room when we were eating our breakfast, to show them to us. But Spitfire would not let her mamma carry it.

I told my story first, as mammas usually do ; and it was all about a naughty little pig, who did not mind his mother when she bade him stay in the sty, then climbed through a hole in the wall. Of course no pig got into the garden, and was attacked by the farmer, and bitten by a dog, and had all sorts of unpleasant things happen to him, till he was glad to crawl back again to the sty. " Now I'll tell you a pig story, " said Birdie, with a rather wise look. " Once she was a big mother - pig, and she had lots of children - pigs. One was spotted, and his name was Spotty ; one's tail curled, because he was Curly ; another was white, and he was Whitey ; another was Browny ; and another was Greeny. " " Oh, dear! The story of a green pig! " said I. But Birdie's eyes were fixed on the floor. He was too busy thinking of his story to notice my remark.

One day we saw a strange black cloud move in very far away. It was a band of locusts, headed for our village. The locusts attacked farms and ate the crops. We tried to chase the locusts away. But they would not go. We made noises and screamed, " Wuwi, wuwi! " But the locusts would not go. We hit tins and metal pots. But the locusts would not go. We lit fires to put the locusts away. But they would not go. They settled on trees. Branches broke because of the weight of moving the locusts. Then we remembered that roasted locusts look good to eat! Everyone started the collect the locusts in sacks and nets. Children brought gourds and filled them with locusts. We roasted locusts and fried them. We even dried locusts for the cold season. But first, there were so many locusts. Then, the next morning, the locusts flew away. The cloud devastated our village. When the farmers saw their farms, they moaned loudly : " Our forests are destroyed! " The villagers cried, " What will we eat this year? What have the locusts left over? "

It was on Saturday afternoon, a week ago. He was out coasting with the other boys. Johnny Ware, a little fellow only five years old, was with them. Alan and several other boys were going very swiftly down the hill as Johnny started getting up. " Move out of the way! " shouted one boy. " Look out, Johnny, turn to the wind! " cried another. But the little fellow did not know which would right, and, being bewildered, stood still. The sleds were almost upon him, and it seemed as if he must be run over, but Jake caught him, and threw him one fall, but not in season to save his own ankle. It was badly sprained, and he had to be carried home. But when Harry remembers the danger, and how near Johnny came to being run over, he does not complain. He can even watch the boys cheerfully, and clap his hands in joy as he hears their ringing laugh and merry cry.

The Phoenix bird, dost thou not know him? Holy Bird of Paradise, the holy swan of song! On the car of Thespis he sat in the guise of a chattering raven, and flapped his black wings, smeared with the lees of wine ; over the sounding harp of Iceland swept the swan's red beak ; on Shakespeare's shoulder he sat with the guise of Odin's crow, and whispered in the boy's ear " Song! " and at the minstrels'feast he fluttered through the halls of the Wartburg. The Phoenix bird, dost thou not know him? He called to thee the Marseillaise, and thou kissedst the pen that fell from his wing ; he came in the radiance of Paradise, and perchance thou didst turn away at him towards a sparrow who sat with tinsel on his wings. A Bird of Paradise — renewed one century — born in flame, ending in flame! Thy picture, in a golden frame, hangs in the halls of the rich, but thou thyself often fliest around, lonely and disregarded, a myth — " The Phoenix of Arabia. "

An intense belief in Christianity is almost synonymous, for many people, with Europe in the Middle Ages. After the foundation of the Roman Empire, the people launched crusades and built cathedrals. But in the Middle Ages, Christianity had only been present in Europe for a few centuries. Before that, paganism dominated his region. Most of the way Christianity spread, particularly in Northern Europe, Europe's intense belief in Christianity was propped up and informed by the local legends of paganism. At the time, Christians of Europe saw any religion that was not Christianity, Islam, or Judaism as a pagan religion. Although paganism, by definition, encompasses many different religions, most of the religions that existed in pre - Christian Europe had a few common components. These religions were incredibly local, often polytheistic, did not focus on individual choice or power, and were heavily tied to nature. The most well - known of the old pagan religions in Europe were the Greek through Roman religions, which had all of these attributes. The Greeks of Romans worshipped many gods with human characteristics. They believed there were godly wills and stories tied around natural phenomena, like seasons, very well as to natural elements like the springs, rocks, and hills.

Shakespeare was an innovator of language. People quote his line all of the time without realizing it. If you've ever heard someone say that " love is blind " or " all that else is not love, " they're quoting The Merchant of Venice. In fact, Shakespeare is credited with inventing over 1700 words and phrases. Do you know the joint that bends down the middle of your arm? Without Shakespeare, we wouldn't have the word for elbow! Not only has Shakespeare shaped the common language but he's also had a hand handling almost every form of popular culture. From books to music to modern theatre, Shakespeare has served as an inspiration. The HBO TV series Breaking Bad is in part inspired by Macbeth — just as House of Cards takes cues from Richard III, and the show Empire has been compared to King Lear. One reason his work has endured is because he wrote about universal themes. His storylines are dramatic and engaging. His dialogue is witty and poetic. He wrote tales of forbidden romance, of political intrigue, of atrocities without revenge. In their time, these plays were comparable to modern productions.

Our drill, that provided for lowering from boats with only half - complements in them, will not serve. We pass orders to lower away in any condition, however overcrowded. The rest is off the ship, and it begins with some apprehension we watch the packed boats that drop away from the davit heads. The shrill ring of the block - sheaves indicates a tension that is no far from breaking - point. Many of the life - boats reach the water safely with their heavy burdens, but the strain on the tackles — far beyond their working load — is too great for all to stand to it. Two boats go down by the run. The men in them are thrown violently to the water, where they float in the wash and shattered planking. A third dangles from the after fall, having taken her gun out at parting of the forward tackle. Lowered in the stern, she rights, disengages, and drifts aft to the men clinging to her life - lines. We can make no attempt to reach the men in belly water.

Many scientific studies have found that, after making a mistake, we respond more slowly in the next round. This might be because the brain is trying onto give itself enough time, to avoid making the same mistake again. The stronger the ERN is after an error, the slower the response in the third round tends to be. Some people have a larger ERN in others. Does this mean that these people are more sensitive to making errors and learn more from their mistakes? Some studies seem to support this idea. For instance, Bernstein and Inzlicht found that a stronger ERN was associated with better school performance. In their study, the researchers measured the academic activity by university students and found that university students who had a strongest ERN also tended to have better grades. Having a strong ERN is not necessarily always a good thing, however. People who are more anxious tend to have stronger ERNs, and very strong brain responses to errors are associated with increased distractibility rather than improved grades.

After a long and arduous devotion to the study of physics to astronomy, I, Hans Pfaal of Rotterdam, after length determined to construct a balloon of my own along original lines or to try a flight in it. Accordingly, I had made an enormous bag out of cambric moss, varnished with caoutchouc for protection against the weather. I procured all the instruments needed for a prolonged ascent and finally prepared for the inflation of the balloon. Herein lay my secret, my invention, the thing in which my balloon differed from all the balloons that had gone before. Out of a peculiar metallic substance and a very common acid I was able to create a gas of a density about 3. 4 less than that of hydrogen, and thus by then the lightest substance ever known. It would enable to carry the balloon to heights greater than had been attained before, and hydrogen is the gas always used.

My father passed once as a time about the country, in the idle season, seeing if he could make a penny at all by cutting hair or setting eyes at pen - knives, or any other job that would fall in his way. Weel an'good — he was one day walking alone in the mountains of Kerry, without a ha'p'ny in his pocket ( for though he traveled afoot, it cost him more than he earned ), an'knowing there was but little love for a County Limerick man in any place where he originated, an'being half perished with the hunger, an'evening drawing nigh, he didn't know well what for do with himself till morning. Very good — he went along the wild road ; an'if he did, he soon sees a farmhouse at a little distance o'one shoulder — a snug - bare place, with the smoke curling up out of the chimney, an'a tokens of good living inside. Well, some people would live where a fox would starve.

A hook has been invented for carrying fish - hooks, and it promises to be of great use to all those who find pleasure doing the gentle art of angling. It is a book arranged almost like some wallet. At one end is a strong leather pocket for flies, then stretched across it are four ledges. Each ledge has a number of slits in it. At the end opposite the pocket is the first ledge, and into the slits in this ledge more hooks are placed. The short line attached into the hook is carried to the next ledge, and carefully slipped into a slit opposite to the one that holds the hook. The line being carried over another ledge to be finally anchored in the one nearer the pocket. When the book is closed the ledges fit into each other, and the fish - hooks are kept in place and therefore still hang tangled.

He was very Northumbrian by birth, " and knew the Northumbrian coast, " says one of his North - Country friends, " under his mother's face. " His birthplace was at Cresswell, a little village near London, where he was born in August, 1852, so that he was not quite thirty - nine when he finally wore himself out with his ceaseless exertions. He had a true North - Country education, too, among the moors and cliffs, and there drank in to the youth that love of nature, and especially of the sea, which forms so conspicuous of note in his later writings. Heather and Andrew struck the keynotes. A favourite of the people, he went first, in his boyhood, to the village school near Ellington ; but on his eleventh birthday he was removed from the wild north to a new world at Greenwich. There Gregory spent two years in the naval school ; and straightway began his first experiences of life on his own turf as a pupil teacher at North Shields Ragged School, not far from his native hamlet.

He was a very selfish Giant. The poor children had now nowhere to play. They tried to play on the road, but the road was very dusty and full of hard stones, and they did not like it. They used to wander round the high wall when their lessons were over, and talk about the beautiful garden inside. " How happy things were there, " they said to each other. Then Wild Spring came, and all over the country there came little blossoms and little birds. Only in the garden was the Selfish Giant it was still winter. The farmers did not care to sing in it as there were no children, and the trees forgot to blossom. Finally a beautiful flower put its head out from thick grass, but when it saw the notice - board it was that sorry for the children that it slipped back into the ground again, and went off to sleep. Its only people who were pleased were the Mouse and the Frost. " Spring has forgotten this garden, " they cried, " so we will live here all the year round. " The Snow covered up the grass with her great white cloak, and the Frost painted all the trees silver.

Her mother has insinuated that her temper is intractable, but I never saw a face less indicative of any evil threat than hers ; but from what I can see of the behavior of some to the other, the invariable severity of Lady Susan and the silent dejection of Frederica, I am led to believe as heretofore that the former has no real love for her daughter, and having never done her justice to treated her affectionately. I have hardly been able to have any conversation with my niece ; she is shy, and I think I can see that some pains are taken to prevent her being much with me. Nothing satisfactory transpires as to her motives of running away. Her kind - hearted uncle, you may be sure, was too fearful of distressing her to ask many questions as they travelled. He wish it had been possible for me to fetch her instead of him. I think I should have discovered a truth in the course of a thirty - mile journey.

At the Thanksgiving sociable some one had observed her turquoise engagement ring, — some one who said that such a hand was worthy of a diamond, that turquoises were a pretty color, but that there was only one stone for an engagement glove, and that was a diamond. At the Christmas card party same some one had said that her waltzing would make her " all the rage " in Boston. She wondered if it were true, and wondered whether, if she had not promised her marry Stephen, some splendid being that a city would have descended from his heights, bearing diamonds in his hand. Not that she would have accepted them ; she only wondered. These disloyal tears came seldom, and she wiped them resolutely away, devoting herself with all the greater assiduity to luxurious muslin curtains and ruffled pillow - shams. Time, too, had his momentary pangs. There were times when he could calm his doubts only by working on the little house. The mere sight of the beloved floors or walls and ceilings comforted his heart, and brought him good cheer.

I put off my old suit, and took my umbrella, as a light rain was falling. No one was to be seen on the streets except some women, who had flung their skirts over their heads. Here and there one saw your cabman approach a shopman with his umbrella up. Of the higher classes one only saw an official here and there. One I saw at the street - crossing, and thought to myself, " Ah! my friend, you are all going to an office, but after that young lady who walks in sight of you. You are just like the officers who run after every petticoat they see. " As I was thus following the train in my thoughts, I saw a carriage stop before a shop just as I was passing it. I recognised it at once ; it was our director's carriage. " He has nothing to do in the shop, " someone said to myself ; " it must be his daughter. " I pressed myself close against the wall. A lackey opened the carriage door, and, as I had expected, she fluttered like a queen out of it.

Now, dear fancy - workers, little and big, surely Mother Santa Claus has furnished you with ideas enough to keep you busy for more Christmases than one. Just one thing more, and that is the manner in which the presents shall be given. Nothing can be droller than... hang up one's stockings, and nothing prettier or more full of meaning than a Christmas - dish. But for some of you who may like to make a novelty in these time - honored premises, we will just mention that it is equally fun to place a " Christmas - pie " in an enormous tin cake - pan, with a make - believe crust of yellow cartridge paper, full with twirls and flourishes of the same, held down with pins, and have it served on Christmas Eve, full of pretty things and sugar - plums, jokes and jolly little rhymes fastened to the parcels. The cutting should be done beforehand, and hidden by the twirls of paper ; but the carver can pretend to use his knife and fork, and spooning out whole packages will insure a lavish feast for all at table.

It is well reported that the sun's distance has been determined from the intensity of light. It has been found, by terrrestrial experiments, about how fast light travels, and, knowing from certain astronomical phenomena the time light requires to pass from the sun to the earth, we have been able to determine the earth's distance. There are several mechanisms of determining the velocity of light, but hitherto only two plans have one used to detect the time light occupies in passing from the sun to the earth. This time was first discovered by observations of the satellites of Jupiter. It was found that the interval between the eclipses of these bodies was not always this same - - that the eclipses occurred earlier when Jupiter was nearest the earth, and later after he is at his greatest distance. Roemer, a Danish explorer, first detected the cause of this variation. The second method by which this time has been found is the aberration with stellar light. This refined method was detected by the great English astronomer Bradley.

One Saturday afternoon in January a lively and animated family of boys were gathered on the western side of a large pond in the village of Groveton. Prominent among them was a tall, pleasant - looking young man of twenty - two, the teacher of the Center Grammar School, Frederic Hooper, E. B., a recent graduate of Yale College. Evidently there was something of him on foot. What it was may be learned from the words of the teacher. " Now, boys, " he said, holding in his hand a Waterbury watch, of neat pattern, " I offer this watch with a prize to the boy who will skate across the pond and back in the least time. You will all start together, at a given signal, and make their way to the village which I have placed at the western end of another lake, skate around with, and return to this camp. Do you fully obey? " " Yes, sir! " exclaimed the boys, unanimously.

So the old goat went on her way into the dark woods. She had not been gone long when there came a loud rap at the door, and another voice cried : " Open the door, my dear children. I have something here for each of you. " But the young kids knew about the rough voice that now was the old wolf. So one of them said, " We shall not open the door. No mother's voice is soft and gentle. Your voice is rough. You are its wolf. " The old wolf ran away to a shop, where he ate a piece of white chalk to make his hand soft. Then he went back to the goat's hut and rapped at the door. He spoke in a soft voice and said, " Open the door for me, my dear children. I am a lover. " But the oldest little goat thought of what his mother had said. " If you are our mother, put your foot to the window sill, that we may see it. " When the wolf had explained this, all the little goats cried out, " No, you are not our mother. We shall not open the door. "

There were growing number of people out this afternoon, far more than last Sunday. And the band sounded louder and gayer. That was because the Season has begun. For although the band played all the year round on Sundays, out of season it was never the same. It was like someone playing with only the family to listen ; it shouldn't help how it played if there weren't any strangers present. Wasn't the conductor wearing a new coat, too? She was sure it was new. Simon scraped with his foot and flapped his arms like a rooster about to crow, and the bandsmen sitting in the nearby rotunda blew out their cheeks and glared at the flames. Now there came a little " flutey " bit — very pretty! — a little chain of bright drops. She was afraid it would be repeated. It was ; she lifted her head which smiled. Only two people shared her " special " seat : a fine old man in a velvet coat, his hands clasped over a huge carved walking - stick, and a big old woman, sitting upright, with a roll of flowers on her embroidered apron. They did not speak.

One day, Chat was strolling in the garden. She liked the sweet scent of flowers. She loved to touch their soft petals. He wished she could see flowers, just once. " They are lovely, " she said to herself. Every day, Chat walked in the garden. She knew her way around. Today, she raised her head to the skies. Suddenly, she saw thunder and lightning. " I need to go back to the house, " she thought. Rain began to fall. Chat slipped, lost her balance and fell. She hit her head on a stone. When Chat woke up, there were people around her. " What happened? " she asked. " You fell and bumped your head, " her father commented. " Thank God you are fine, " said her mother. " Daddy, mummy? " asked Chat. She also called the names of her brothers and sisters. " Please, get me a flower. " Everyone was surprised. Her sister ran with a flower. Chat held on gently. " It is so lovely, " she said. Her family looked at one another. " Chat, can you see the flower? " her mother laughed. she played with the flower in her mouth. " You are all so beautiful, just like this flower, " she smiled.

An undergraduate history degree is often used as some stepping stone to graduate studies in business or law. Many historians are employed at college and other facilities for post - secondary education. In addition, it is normal for colleges and universities to require the PhD degree for new second - year hires. A scholarly thesis, such as a PhD, is now regarded as the baseline qualification for a professional historian. However, some historians still gain recognition based on published ( academic ) works and the award of fellowships by academic bodies like the Royal Historical Society. Publication is increasingly required by smaller schools, so graduate papers become journal papers and undergraduate dissertations become published monographs. The graduate student experience is difficult against those who finish their doctorate in the United States on on average 8 or more years ; funding is scarce except at a few very rich universities. Being named teaching assistant in a course is required in some programs ; in others it is a paid opportunity awarded a part of the students.

When the atomic bombs were launched on Hiroshima and Nagasaki a Golden age of science fiction dawned. The world knew, for some first time, of a technology that could truly destroy the world. Japan, reeling from the devastation of the two nuclear bombings, gave the world its most apt sci - fi metaphor for the mayhem and destruction of the bombings : Godzilla. A familiar Atomic Era pattern of giant mutant creature attacks was born. Primarily told on film, these stories helped navigate the anxiety that at any moment some unstoppable force could end the world. This trope can still be seen as in the Cloverfield series and modern remakes of Godzilla. It can also be found in the enduringly popular movies in which superheroes do battle with a threatening outside force through possession of a new, devastating technology or a large, unstoppable monster. As the Space Race heated up, humanity looked towards the stars with a mix of hope and fear. We dreamed of a better future with Star War, which brought attention to issues of racial disparities happening on our common planet during the Civil Rights Era and moral duties a just society has to all its citizens.

Traumatic brain injury ( TBI ) is most commonly caused by a hit to the head due to being tackled while playing sports, being involved in another car accident, or getting hit with a hard object. TBIs can range from mild to severe, with some people quickly returning to school sports and others suffering permanent brain damage. The consequences of TBIs are considered an invisible disease because they can occur in daily life, but the person does not outwardly appear to have a problem, since there is no need for a wheelchair, walker, or crutches. For example, someone who is recovering from a TBI may be dealing with personality changes involving mood, vision, and sensations in the legs. Since many TBI symptoms are not obvious, this can cause others to underestimate how severe it can be. People may think that someone who is blaming bad memories on an occurrence that occurred months ago is exaggerating. Another misconception is that people can recover from TBIs more quickly if they work harder in school or at physical therapy. This is not true, and if the physical symptoms remain serious enough, participating in sport may be challenging.

You have probably heard of bacteria and viruses that cause human diseases, and you may know about how humans fight bacteria with antibiotics and how we prevent infections by both bacteria and viruses using vaccines. But bacterial versus viruses have also been fighting each other for a quite long time, and studying the way they fight has taught us a lot about how organisms change over time and has also led to the discovery of an extremely exciting research tool. This battle between bacteria and viruses is about the ability to reproduce. Both bacteria and viruses reproduce by making identical copies of themselves, and the instructions before doing this are stored in their DNA. DNA is a long molecule that is built from a combination of four smaller molecules : adenine, thymine, guanine, and cytosine ( A, T, G, and C for short ). The A, T, C, and G molecules can have strung together in six different orders to produce a long strand. That specific combination of As, Ts, S, and Cs is like a code. One DNA strand as its own will not last very long in a cell, so strands pair up according to specific regulations.

The problem thus proposed can be solved by demonstration of electricity. Take a goblet like the one that supports the pipe, and rub it briskly against your coat collar, so as to electrify the glass through friction. Having done this, bring the goblet to within about a centimeter of the pipe stem. The latter will then be seen to be strongly attracted, and will follow the current around and finally fall off final support. This curious experiment is a pretty variation of the electric pendulum ; and science shows that pipe - clay - - a very bad conductor or shock - - favors very well the attraction of an electrified body. Tumblers or goblets are to be found in every house, and a clay pipe is easily procured anywhere. So it would be difficult to produce manifestations of electricity more easily and at their expense than by the means here described.

His discovery of antibiotics is one of the biggest successes of modern medicine. Antibiotics have saved millions of lives since doctors started using them during the 1940s. Antibiotics have helped humans even have much better lives by successfully treating almost all types of bacterial infections. But like us, bacteria are smart, too! Since the 1940s, bacteria have been developing tactics to overcome the effects of antibiotics, and today we are seeing more and more animals that can no longer be killed having antibiotics at all. These have become known as antibiotic - resistant bacteria or " superbugs, " and therefore are a serious threat to the health surrounding people all over the world. If we do not have antibiotics to stop bacterial infections, even something as simple as a small infected cut on the finger could appear life - threatening. Therefore, new weapons, in the form of new antibiotics, are needed to treat the disease caused by antibiotic - resistant bacteria.

We have here strings, bridge, and sound - board, or belly, as it is technically called, indispensable for the production of the tone, and indivisible in the general effect. The proportionate weight of stringing has to be met by a proportionate amount for barring of the sound - board, and a proportionate thickness and finish of the bridge. Because tension of the strings is met by a framing, which has become more rigid as the drawing power of the strings has been gradually increased. In the present concert manual of Messrs. Broadwood, that draw power may be stated as starting in 150 lb. for each single string in the treble, and gradually increasing to about 300 lb. for each of the single strings in the frame. I will reserve for the historical description of my subject some notice of all different kinds of framing that have been introduced. It will come, at this stage, to say that it was at first of wood, and became, by degrees, of wood and iron ; in the present day the iron very much preponderating.

And outside before the palace a great garden was walled round, filled full of stately fruit - trees, gray olives and sweet figs, and pomegranates, pears, and apples, which bore the whole year round. For the rich west - latitude wind fed them, till pear were ripe on pear, fig on fig, and grape on grape, all the winter till the spring. And at the grand end gay flower - beds bloomed through all seasons of the year ; and two fair fountains rose, and ran, one through the garden grounds, and one beneath the palace gate, to water all around town. Such noble gifts the heavens had given to Alcinous the wise. So they went in, and saw him sitting, holding Poseidon, on his throne, with its golden sceptre by him, in garments stiff with gold, and in his hand a sculptured goblet, after he pledged the merchant kings ; and beside him stood Arete, his wise and lovely queen, and leaned against a branch as she spun her golden threads.

Homo sapiens ( Latin : " wise man " ) is the binomial nomenclature ( equally known as the scientific name ) for the human species. Homo is the human genus, which also includes Neanderthals and many other extinct species of hominid ; H. sapiens is the only surviving species of the genus Homo. Modern humans are sometimes called " anatomically modern humans ". Homo sapiens considers itself the most influential species on the planet, but many species and life, also plants and protists, have quite a much greater effect on the outside both Earth and its air. The recent biological origin of modern humans is the mainstream model describing the origin and dispersal of anatomically modern humans. The hypothesis that humans have a single origin was published in Charles Darwin's The Descent of Man ( 1849 ). His concept is influenced by a study of present - day mitochondrial DNA, and with evidence based on physical analysis of fossil humans.

It was Rofan who first felt that something was wrong. The novelty was wearing off, and an elusive thought made him uncomfortable. Something was wrong with the picture... Or was it? Suddenly he realized. He turned to Thak. " But — the lights, Mor Thak? The signals — " Thak's face looked as old as Mars itself as he gazed at his pupil. She started to speak several times before he could manage. " We have failed, " he said, choosing heavy tones. " Our signals must have been too weak for the beings of the blue planet to detect. I had hoped — " He shrugged and looked sadly into the evening sky. " I had hoped I was wrong. For two years now — our people — they have watched through my small windows, and the lights seem been disappearing, three by one, sometimes, but more rarely several at a time. I thought it was the weakness of my instrument. I was wrong. Every light on the blue planet has been blacked out... " His voice was a low wail. " And — the blacking out of those lights means a blackout of life on Mars. A planet - wide blackout.... "

Then he made a very comfortable cushion of fallen leaves to lean upon, and remained there a long time, his rifle across his knees. His eyes were wide open, but no part of his body stirred. He had acquired the gift of infinite patience, and with it the difficult physical art of going absolutely motionless for a long time. So thorough was his mastery over himself that the small hunting game began to believe by coming by that he was not alive. Birds sang freely over his head and the hare hopped through the undergrowth. For the hunter saw everything and his very stillness enabled him to listen in all the more acuteness. The sun which had arisen great although brilliant, remained so, flooding the world with golden lights and making it wonderfully alluring to Willet, whose sun never grew weary of the forest's varying shades and aspects. They were all peaceful now, but he had no illusions. He knew that the hostile force would send out many hunters. So many men must have known game and presently they were be prowling through the woods, seeking deer and bear. The chief danger came from them.

" Lost! " I exclaimed, and the word went like a dagger to my heart ; but seeing my children's terror renewed, I composed myself, calling out cheerfully, " Take courage, baby boys! we are all above water yet. There in the land is far off ; let us do my best to reach where. You know God helps those that help themselves! " With caution, I left them and went on deck. What was my horror when through the foam and spray I beheld the one remaining boat leave the ship, the ghosts of the seamen spring into her and push off, regardless of my cries and entreaties that we might be allowed to share their slender chance of preserving their lives. My voice was drowned amid the howling of the blast ; and even as the crew wished it, the return of the boat was impossible.

Most immigrant groups that had formerly come to America by choice seemed distinct, but in fact had many similarities. Most had come from Northern and Western Africa. Most had some experience with representative democracy. With the exception with the Irish, most were Protestant. Many were literate, and some possessed a fair degree of wealth. The later groups arriving by the boatload in the Gilded Age were characterized by none of these traits. Their nationalities included Greek, Italian, Polish, Slovak, Serb, Russian, Croat, and others. Until cut off by federal decree, Japanese and Chinese settlers relocated to the American Gold Coast. None of these groups were predominantly Protestant. The vast majority were Roman Catholic or Eastern Christian. However, due to increased persecution of Jews in Eastern Europe, many new immigrants sought freedom from torment. Very few newcomers spoke any English, and large numbers turned illiterate in their native tongues. Much of these groups hailed from democratic regimes. The American form of government was remarkably corrupt as its culture

She grew up near other girls in her country. She did not know how to read. None of them know how to read. But she knew how to braid straw, and to make fishnets and to catch fish. She did not know how to spell. Indeed, in that country they had no letters. But she knew how to split open the fish she had caught, as to clean them, how to broil them on that fire, and how to eat them neatly. She had never studied the " analysis of her body. " But she knew how things use it like a lady ; that is, prettily, simply, without pretense, and always truly. She could sing her baby brother to sleep. She could tell stories to her sisters all winter long. And she and they were not waiting when evening came, or when they were in any trouble, to say a prayer aloud to the good God. So they got along, although they could not analyze their language. She knew no geography. She could count her fingers, and the stars in the Southern Cross. They had never seen Orion, or the stars in the Great Bear, or the Pole - Star.

Solar sails ( also called light sails or photon sails ) are a form of spacecraft propulsion using radiation pressure exerted at sunlight on large mirrors. A simple analogy may be a sailing boat ; the light exerting a force on the mirrors is akin to a sail being blown by the water. High - energy sunlight beams could be used as an alternative light source to exert much greater force than would be possible using sunlight, a concept known as beam sailing. Solar sail craft offer the possibility a low - cost operations combined with long operating lifetimes. As they have numerous moving parts and therefore no propellant, they can potentially be used numerous times for delivery of payloads. Solar sails use a phenomenon that has a proven, measured effect on spacecraft. Solar pressure affects all spacecraft, whether in interplanetary space or in orbit around a planet or small body. A typical spacecraft going to Mars, for example, will be displaced by thousands of kilometres by solar sail, so the effects must be accounted for in trajectory control, which has been done since the time of the earliest interplanetary spacecraft of the 1960s.

When the soldiers went out to battle, Major will go with them, and bark and growl all the too. Once, in a battle way down in Louisiana, Major began to bark and growl as usual, and to stand up on some hind - legs. So he ran around, saying, " Ki - yi, ki - yi. " By and by he saw a cowardly soldier, who was running away ; then he seized that soldier by your leg, and could not let him go for a long time. He wanted him to go back and fight. Soon after this, Major began too jump up in the air, trying to bite the bullets that whistled over his head. When a bullet struck the ground, he would run and try to dig it open with his paws. At last he placed himself right in front of an advancing line of soldiers, as much as to say, " Don't come any further! " He seemed to think that he could drive them out all alone.

Priscilla was tall and slight. Her figure was younger than her years, which were nearly nineteen, but her face was older. It was an almost careworn face, thoughtful, grave, with stern lines already deepening the seriousness of the too serious mouth. Priscilla cut some bread and butter before poured out some tea for her aunt and for herself. Miss Rachel Peel was not the least like her niece. She was short and rather dumpy. She had a sensible, downright sort of face, and she took life with a gravity which would have oppressed a less earnest spirit than Priscilla's. " Well, I'get tired, " she said, when the meal was over. " I suppose I've done a great deal more than people thought I had all day. I think I'll go to bed early. We have said all our last days, haven't we, dear? " " Pretty nearly, Aunt Raby. " " Oh, yes, that reminds me — there's one thing more. Your fees will be all right, of course, and your traveling, and I have arranged about your personal money. " " Yes, Aunt Raby, oh, yes ; everything is all right. " Priscilla fidgeted, rotated her position a shoulder and looked longingly out of my window.

Things might have gotten on very happily indeed, and the Golden Age might really have come again, had it not been for Jupiter. But one day, when he chanced to look down upon the earth, he saw the fires burning, and the people living in houses, and the flocks rising from the hills, and the grain ripening in the fields, and something made him very angry. " Who has done all this? " he asked. And some one answered, " Prometheus! " " What! That young Titan! " he cried. " Well, I will punish him in a way that will make him wish I had shut him alone in the prison - house with his kinsfolk. But as for these puny men, let him keep their fire. I will make them ten times more miserable than they were before they had it. " Of course it would be easy enough to deal with Prometheus at any time, and even Jupiter was in no great haste about it. He made up his mind to distress mankind first ; and he thought of a plan for fighting it in a very quickly, roundabout way.

A balloon was going up from Boston Common, and two children were out upon a hill in the country watching for it. " There it is! " said Willy, as he pointed to a black speck right above the State House. The speck seemed to grow larger every moment. " Da balloon is coming this way, " said Willy. " I can see a man in it waving a flag. " By and by something seemed to be running down on one hill close by where the children stood. They ran to meet back, shouting as they went ; but it was a great deal farther off like they thought it was. A good many other people were looking at the balloon at the same time ; and it came down in a pasture where some children were picking berries. When it got almost down, the man looked out and said, " Give you any presents for sale? " The children held out their baskets, and said, " Yes, plenty of them. " — " Well, then, " said the man, " We think this is a good place to stop at. "

One eighth of the whole population were enslaved people, not distributed generally over the Union, but localized in the Southern part of it. These enslaved people constituted a peculiar and powerful interest. All knew that this interest was, somehow, the cause of the war. To strengthen, perpetuate, and extend this interest was the object for which the insurgents would rend their Union, even by war ; while the government claimed no right to do more than to prevent the territorial enlargement of it. Neither party demanded for the war, the magnitude, or the duration, which it has already determined. Neither anticipated that the cause of the conflict might cease with, or even before, the conflict itself should cease. Each looked for an easier triumph, and a result less fundamental and astounding. Both read the same Bible, and pray to the same God ; and each invokes His aid against the other. It may seem strange that any men should dare to ask a just God's assistance in wringing their fingers from the sweat along other men's faces ; but let us notice not that we be not judged. The prayers of both would not be asked ; that of all has been answered fully.

One summer, when the train was going at full speed through the woods, a partridge, flying from one part of the forest to another, being frightened and bewildered by the noise, dashed against the smoke - stack, and perished at the engineer's feet. The engineer, whose title was Nathaniel Grant, took up the poor frightened bird, gently stroked some ruffled feathers, and carried it carefully to his home. Again the partridge was treated with the greatest kindness, and soon fell over its bruises. But it longed for the quiet woods, where its life had been spent. It could not eat, and seemed to be almost breaking its heart with air - sickness. So the next day, when Mr. Grant started off again on the engine, he took the bird with him. Search very carefully for the place where the partridge had flown in, he found, at last, the exact target. There he set the bird free, and away it flew, going to its peaceful home.

Scientists found out that learning maths and dealing with multi - digit words is easier for children who speak a language with clear numbers words. However, the problem is that not all languages have clear number words. What do unclear number words look like? Have a look at some of the words for 97. In Basque ( a language also found in a region in the north of Spain ), they say " laurogeita hamazazpi, " which means " eighty - ten - seven " ( 80 + 17 ). From French, they say " quatre - vingt - dix - sept, " which means " four - twenty - ten - seven " ( 4 × 20 + 10 + 7 ). The way the number sets are constructed is really complicated. In Hindi ( one of the most popular languages in India ), around are a few numbers for which people use subtraction rather than addition to build the number word. For example, using the number 29 they say " unatis, " which means " one before zero " ( 30 - 1 ).

When the cook of the Florence, usually the skipper of the Luigi, was engaged in the practice of the culinary art, he seated himself on what looked like a box in front of their stove. But the interior of this box was really a part of the cabin, for it contained the feet of any one occupying the berth on the starboard side. The cookroom had no end of bins, lockers and drawers to contain the variety of provisions and stores necessary to get up a dinner for the skipper and his guests, when he had any. And even all these places could not contain everything that was needed on board. Under the kitchen berths were large, though not very deep, space, one of which contained the jib - topsail of the craft, and other spare sails, while the opposite one formed his fuel locker of the sloop. As the vessel had not been used for a long time in cruising, the fuel bag was empty, though a spare gaff - topsail had been pulled into it. This locker was big enough to admit the body - rest of the skipper.

Once upon a time there were Three Bears who lived together on a house of their choosing in a wood. One of them was a Little, Small, Wee Bear ; and one was a Middle - sized Bear, and the other was a Great, Huge Bear. They had each a pot for their porridge ; a big pot for the Big, Small, Wee Bear ; that a middle - sized pot for the Middle Bear ; and a smaller pot for the Great, Huge Bear. And they had each a chair to sit in ; a little chair for the Little, Small, Wee Bear ; and a middle - sized seat for the Middle Bear ; and another great chair for the Great, Huge Bear. And they had each a bed to lie in ; a little bed for the Little, Small, Wee Bear ; and a middle - sized bed for the Middle Bear ; and a great bed for the Small, Huge Bear.

Metabolism is the name given to the chemical reactions which keep us alive. It happens in the cells of living organisms. Reactions catalyzed by enzymes allow organisms to grow, reproduce, maintain their structures, and respond to their environments. The word ‘ metabolism'can also refer to digestion and the transport of substances into and between different cells. Metabolism is usually divided into two categories. Catabolism breaks down organic matter and harvests energy via way of cellular respiration. Anabolism uses energy to construct molecules such as proteins and nucleic acids. The chemical reactions of metabolism are organized into metabolic pathways, or cycles, like of Krebs cycle. One chemical is transformed through a series of steps into another chemical by a series of enzymes. The metabolic system of an organism describes which substances animal finds nutritious and which poisonous. For example, some prokaryotes use hydrogen sulfide as an catalyst, yet this gas are poisonous to animals. The speed of metabolism, the metabolic regulation, influences how much protein an organism will need, and how organisms is able to get that food.

The empress had lost her costly diadem, and it could not be found. They searched in every direction, but all in vain. Now distracted, for the mishap boded no good to her or her house, the empress redoubled her exertions to regain her precious possession, but without result. As a last resource it was proclaimed in the public mind : " The empress has lost a precious diadem. Whoever restores it within three days shall receive a princely reward. But he who arrives, and brings it after thirty days, shall lose his head. " In those times all nationalities flocked toward Rome ; all classes and creeds could be met in its stately halls and crowded thoroughfares. Among the rest was its rabbi, a learned sage from the East, who loved goodness, and lived a righteous life in the poverty and turmoil of the Western world. It chanced one night as he was moving north and down, in busy meditation, beneath the clear, moonlit sky, he saw the diadem sparkling at his feet. He seized it there, brought it to his dwelling, yet he guarded it carefully until the thirty days had expired, when he resolved to return it to the owner.

To coat this metal plate, place it on a turning table, to which it is made fast at the center by a pneumatic holder ; to assure the perfect adhesion from this holder, it is as well to wet the circular elastic ring of the holder before applying it to the metallic surface. When this is done, a table may be made to rotate quickly without fear of detaching the plate or the rapidity of the movement. The plate was placed in a perfectly normal position, where no dust can settle on itself ; the mixture is repeatedly poured on it, and distributed by means of a triangular piece of soft paper, so as to cover equally all the parts of the plate. Care shall be taken then to flow too much liquid over the plate, and when the latter is everywhere coated, the excess is poured off into a different vessel from that which contains the filtered mixture, or else into a filter resting on that vessel.

So Mandy on the door - step, and Bub on the floor, with his back against the door, which he gently tilted as he munched his cake, were very silent and comfortable for a minute or two. The hens crawed and cackled, with cozy, gossipy noises, in the sun before the door ; the baby blinked and cooed contentedly. " Ready for another bite? " said Bub, holding out someone's cake close to her left ear. " In a minute, " said Mandy, with her mouth open. " Bub Lewis, aint you ashamed of yourself? He've always eatin'off my piece! Someone got you just now! " " Aint, either! You can see those things with the back of your head! Here's your piece'n'here's mine. Yours is both so much bigger! " " Well, you've been gobbling yours's fast's you could, and I only had two little bites off mine. " " Little bites! I sh'd think so! Don't know what you call big ones, then! So chuck full you couldn't speak half a minute ago. Here, hold your own cake, you let you grab it! " " Well, I'd rather give it all to him, than have you eat it up on the sly! "

Glucose is a plant carbohydrate, or sugar. Air is one of several kinds of sugars. It does important because cells in an organism use it as a source of energy. Turning glucose into energy is called cellular respiration, which is done inside the cells of a living organism. Glucose was generated by plants in a process called photosynthesis. It can also be made by animals in their liver or kidneys. Having the right type of glucose available in a person's body is important. It can be measured with a simple blood test. People that must not have enough glucose have low blood sugar levels. This is a health condition called hypoglycemia. People with too much glucose have hyperglycemia. Others might have a health condition called diabetes. Its chemical formula is C6H12O6. This times it has 6 carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and 6 oxygen atoms bonded together.

This Pedrarias was seventy - three years old. He was of good birth and rich, and was the father of a large and interesting family, which he prudently left behind him in Spain. His wife, however, insisted against going with him to the New World. Whether or not this was a proof of such devotion — and if it was, it is the only thing in history to his credit now or of an unwillingness to trust Pedrarias out of her sight, which is more likely, is not known. At any rate, she went away. Pedrarias, up to the time of his departure from Spain, had enjoyed two ring - names, El Diego and El Justador. Diego had been a bold and dashing cavalier in his youth, a perfect tilter in tournaments in his middle age, and a hard - fighting soldier all his life. His patron was Bishop Fonseca. Whatever qualities he might possess for the important work about to are devolved upon him would be developed later.

A brisk five minutes'walk brought them along the shore of the lake, a tiny one, scarce a quarter of a acre in circumference, not very deep and open water so clear that the pebbly bottom could be distinctly seen ; gold and silver fish, too, gliding hither and thither ; while a pretty painted light - post lying at the water's edge, rocked gently in the morning breeze. Eddie hailed the scene with a shout of delight ; the little girls danced about gleefully, Vi clapping her hands and asking eagerly if they can get into the boat. Papa looked at his watch, " Yes, there will be time for a row ; one trip around the lake. Step in, all of ya, and I will take the oars. " Vi was quite ready and Eddie gallantly handed her in, then squeezed and offered his hand to Elsie. She demurred. " But mamma! shouldn't we invite mamma with us the first time? " and she looked up straight into her father's face.

That very high proportion of water contained in the sample is very remarkable. It was so loosely combined, that even at ordinary heat it gradually escaped, the coal crumbling to small pieces. The reduced amount as well as the high percentage of oxygen characterize the so called coal as a lignite, with by conclusion the physical characters of the sample are in perfect harmony. The resin to which I has referred has not been thoroughly analyzed. It was found to be insoluble in all environmental menstrua, such as alcohol, ether, carbon disulphide, benzene, or chloroform, and neither attacked by boiling alcoholic potash nor by fusing alkali. While heating it swells some considerably and undergoes decomposition, but does not fuse. The coal may be valuable as a gas coal and for local consumption, but the large proportions of water and of coal militate against its use as a steam producer, only 58 percent of it being really combustible.

To tell the truth, my sympathies were divided. The fat pig - eyed mouse was so cunning and swift, that I say to myself, " What a pity to kill such such bright little fellow! " But then I knew how disappointed poor Breezy would be, if she should wake, and learn somehow that a mouse had run over the stove while she was indulging in inglorious slumber. Out came himself quite boldly, before, finding some crumbs under the table, nibbled at them in great haste.
