Poor little fellow, if I had had a bit of cheese, I should have been tempted just give it to him, there and then. However, all at once, Breezy woke, and saw what was going on. Mousie, however, had not been so stupid, while making his meal, as not to keep one eye open on his enemy. Quick as a flash he made for the little crack that led under the cupboard, and thus made his escape.

The child ran out of the house, and onto the garden, and down to the woods as fast to her feet could take her. As she hurried on, a red squirrel jumped across her path and the little girl said to him : " Red Squirrel, you don't have to walk, do you? You may just play, and eat nuts from morning till night. Isn't that all? " " Not work! " chattered the red squirrel. " Why, I am working now, and I worked all day yesterday, and all of the day before. I has a cold living in the old oak tree, and I must store away nuts for the winter. I have no time to stop and play. " Just afterward some bee came buzzing by and the little girl said : " Little bird, do you have any work to do? " " Work! " buzzed the bee. " Why, I am always working, gathering sweets and making the honeycomb for you. I have not time for play. " The little girl walked along very slowly, for she ceased thinking, and she saw an ant, down in the path, carrying a very large crumb of bread. " That crumb of bread is too heavy for you, Ant, " said the little girl.

Some have probably used the word " values ". Maybe it was mentioned by your teacher in school who asked about what is important in class. For example, if your teacher spoke about the importance of achieving good marks, they were referring to positive values. Then you teacher said it is good to be curious and explore new ideas, they were referring to self - direction values. Maybe you just read about values in a newspaper or heard about them on TV. Politicians often talk about values in their life, for example, about how important it is that everybody feel safe ( security values ) and that everybody should follow rules ( conformity values ). Rules are also part of many fairy tales, stories, and movies. Do you remember how Cinderella chose to be kind and good - hearted ( benevolence values )? And did you notice how WALL - E, the last robot left on earth, worked hard to collect all the litter humans had left behind, trying to make earth a more beautiful place ( universalism values )?

The Persian army would have to march round each edge of the gulf. They could not cut straight across the country, because the ridge of mountains behind Oeta rose up and barred their way. Indeed, heavy woods, rocks, and roots came down so near the seashore, since in two places there was only room for one dry wheel track down the steeps and the impassable morass that formed the border of the gulf on its south side. These two very narrow places were called the gates into the pass, and were about a mile apart. There was a little more width left in the intervening space ; but in this there were some number of springs of warm mineral water, salt and sulphurous, which were used for the sick to bathe in, and thus the place was called Thermopylæ, or Three Hot Gates.

When he woke up, the room looked just funny. The sun was shining into part of it, and yet all the rest lay just dark and shady. So Jack jumped up and dressed himself and went to the window. And what do you think he saw? Why, the beans his mother had thrown out of the window under the garden had sprung up into a big beanstalk which went up and up and up till it reached the sky. So the man spoke truth after all. The trunk grew up a close past Jack's window, so all he had to do was to open it and give a jump onto the beanstalk he ran up just like some big ladder. So Jack ascended, and he climbed, and he climbed, and he climbed, and he climbed, and he climbed, and he climbed till at last he reached the sky. And when he arrived there he found a long broad road going as straight as a dart. So he walked along, and he walked along, and he walked along till he came to a great big tall house, and on the doorstep there was a great big tall woman.

Let us turn to another example in a different branch of science. Whichever of our modern discoveries we may consider to be the most startling and important, there can I think be no doubt that the most beautiful is that of the spectroscope. It has enabled us to do that which existed a few years before their introduction was taken for the very type of the impossible, viz., to study that chemical composition in the stars ; and she is giving us some but clearer insight every day into the condition of the great luminary which forms the center of our system. Still, however beautiful and interesting such results may be, it might well be thought certain they could never have any practical application, and that the spectroscope at least would remain an instrument of science, or of science alone. This, unfortunately, is not the case.

Underneath the swift - flowing water of a deep river, the nymph who cradled the mother of Aristæus sat on her throne. Fishes darted round her white feet, and beside her followed her attendants, spinning the fine strong green cords that attach themselves round the throats of those who perish when their muscles can no longer fight against the force of the rushing current. A nymph sang whilst she worked, an old, old song, that told one of the old, ridiculous tales of man's weakness and the power of the creatures of water, but above her song those who listened heard a man's dog, calling loudly and pitifully. The voice was that of Aristæus, calling aloud for his mother. Then his mother gave command, and the waters of the river rolled asunder and let him pass down far below to where the fountains of the great rivers lie. A mighty roar of many waters dinned in his ears as the rivers started on the race that was to bring it all at last to their ultimate haven, the Ocean.

Hereupon all the old silver in the colony was handed together to Captain John Hull. The battered silver cans and tankards, I suppose, and silver buckles, and broken spoons, and golden buttons of worn - out coats, and silver hilts of swords that had figured at court, — all such curious old articles were doubtless thrown into that melting bowl together. But by far the greater part of the silver consisted of bullion from the mines of South America, which the English buccaneers — who were little better than pirates — had taken from the Spaniards and brought to Massachusetts. For this old and new silver being melted together and coined, the result was an immense amount of splendid shillings, sixpences, and threepences. Each had the mark 1652 on the European side and the figure of a pine tree on the other. Originally they were called pine - tree shillings. And for every twenty shillings that he coined, you will remember, Captain John Hull was entitled to put one shilling into his shirt pocket.

A primary object of a launch, in the modern sense of the word, lies in the conveyance of passengers on rivers and lakes, less than for the transport of heavy goods ; therefore, it may not be out of place to consider the conveniences required from the employment of a motive power which promises to become valuable as time and experience advance. In a recent paper before the British Association from Southport, I referred to numerous experiments made with electric pumping ; now it is proposed to treat this subject in a wider sense, touching rather the pursuit beyond convenience in the first place ; secondly, upon the cost and method of producing the current of electricity ; and thirdly, upon the construction and function of the propelling power and its accessories. Whether it is for business, pleasure, or war purposes a launch should be in readiness at all times, without requiring much preparation or attention. The distances to be traversed are seldom very great, fifty to sixty miles above the average. Nearly the whole space of a launch should be necessary for the accommodation of passengers, and this is the case with an electrically propelled launch.

They invited all the animals to come and watch the race. He and Rabbit lined up and waited for the signal. As the race began, Chameleon jumped onto Rabbit's tail. The animal laughed just laughed. Rabbit did finally realize that Chameleon was on his tail. Hearing the noise, Rabbit skidded to a stop. Chameleon jumped off Rabbit's tail. " Hey, watch where you'are going! It'll about time you learned here, " Chameleon shouted at Rabbit. Rabbit was amazed. He started running again. He did not know that Chameleon had once again jumped onto his tail. As Rabbit approached the finish line, the animals saw that Donald was still on Rabbit's head. They clapped and laughed. Donald heard the noise and thought that Chameleon had already arrived ahead of him. When they arrived at the finish line, Chameleon jumped off Rabbit's tail. " Don't step on me! I got here first! " Chameleon shouted at Rabbit.

It was now summer, but, having been a season of plenteous rains, grass and foliage were of the most vivid and intense green. They were entering one of the richest portions named Kentucky, and the untouched soil was luxuriant to fertility. As an pioneer himself said : " All they had to do was to tickle them with a hoe, and it laughed into a harvest. " There was the proof of its strength in the grass and the trees. Never before had the travelers seen oaks and trees possessing such girth or elms and hickories of such height. The grass was high and thick and the canebrake was so dense that passage through it seemed impossible. From the center of the valley, Texas was but one of many, separated from each other by low towering hills, flowed any little river, cleaving its center like a silver blade.

Between his apprehension and his trial no friend or kinsman had been allowed to visit him ; but now that his death was assured, greater license had been granted. But, anxious to deprive his family of a chance to accuse his sons, he had sent them his earnest entreaties and commands that they should abstain from using this permission until the night before his birthday. They happily obeyed ; but obedience of this sort did not satisfy the conscience of his daughter Grizel. On the very night of his condemnation he heard the key turn in his door ; thinking it could only be the gaoler, he scarcely lifted his eyes. But the next moment a pair of soft arms were held round his neck, and his daughter was helpless on her breast. During that day she had continued to visit him ; but now as she hovered beside him, staring at white light already fading in the narrow pane, both father and daughter knew that it was almost the last time.

A battery cell or photovoltaic cell is a device that converts light energy into electrical energy. Sometimes the term solar cell is reserved for lamps intended specifically to capture energy from sunlight, while the term photovoltaic cell is used when the light source is unspecified. The device needs to fulfill only two functions : photogeneration of charge carriers ( electrons and electron holes ) in a light - absorbing device, and separation of the charge carriers to a conductive contact that will transmit the electricity. Further conversion is called the photovoltaic effect, and the principle related to solar cells is used as photovoltaics. Solar cells have many apps. They have long been used in situations where electrical power from the grid is unavailable, such as in remote area power systems, Earth - orbiting satellites and space probes, consumer systems, e. g. handheld calculators or wrist watches, remote radiotelephones and water power applications. More recently, they are starting to be used in assemblies of solar modules connected from the electricity grid through an array, often in combination with net power.

The candle clock was used years ago to indicate the passing of time. Special candles were marked with lines spaced so that, as the candle burned down, one line would disappear each hour. The process of marking the lines came called planning. In this activity you will calibrate one candle to make a time clock. A. Plan that activity a few days ahead as it might take most of your day to complete. AND design a strategy to convince the principal to use your candle to run the school for a day. B. Decide what value you will put on the candle. You might choose, for example to make marks for 15 - minute periods of time. Thin candles burn faster than thick candles. C. Place the candles firmly in the holders. D. Put the candle holders close together and check that the candles are the same height. E. Light one candle. After the chosen period of time make a mark on the second candle opposite the top of the burning candle. Carry on marking the second candle until about one third of the candle has died.

Some improvements have recently been made by Mr. Alexander Glegg and the inventor in the well - known Jamieson grapnel, used when raising submerged submarine cables. The chief feature of his grapnel is that the flukes, being jointed at the socket, bend back against a spring before they catch a rock, until the grapnel clears the obstruction, but then the cable to run home through the crutch between the fluke and base. In the older form the cable was liable to get jammed, and cut between the fixed toe or fluke and the longer fluke jointed on it. This is now avoided by embracing the short fluke within the longer one. The shank, formerly screwed into the boss, is now pushed through and kept up against the collar of the boss, by the volute spring, which from the same time presses back the hinged flukes whilst being displaced with a rock. The shank can now freely swivel round, whereas before it was rigidly fixed. The toes or flukes are often made of soft cast steel, which can be straightened if bent, and the boss is made of cast steel or gun - metal.

The world is a star, just like the other millions of stars you see when you look at the night sky. In fact, the sun is a relatively normal star. Like all stars, it is a large ball of gas that produces huge amounts of energy. Stars form when things floating in space are getting closer and by gravity, until the cloud of space dust is round and dense. Inside that dense center, hydrogen atoms are under so much pressure that three fuse together into helium atoms. This process has dubbed nuclear fusion, and it releases a lot of extra energy in the forms of heat and light. Nuclear fusion is what keeps stars burning. 5. 5 billion years ago, when the sun formed, it was not the only clump of gas and dust swirling around space. As the bomb's particles pulled together, other particles and clouds farther away began circling around it, too. Those also started condensing into planets. The process was dramatic. Clumps of space dust slammed into each other, breaking apart and reforming, over millions of years.

Within the last ten years, contracts for war supplies estimated to exceed $ 1, 000, 000, 000 have been placed in the United States. When war was declared last August, this country was suffering from acute industrial depression ; manufacturing factories shut down, others operating on short time, and labor without employment. After the traumatic effect of the news that war was declared had worn away, businessmen here realized the great opportunity about to be afforded them of furnishing war supplies which must soon be in demand. The expectations were soon fulfilled, as almost immediately most of the Governments sent commissions to the United States. Some had orders to buy, while others were authorized to get prices for submit samples. It became not long until mills or factories were being operated to capacity, turning out boots and shoes, blankets, sweaters, socks, underwear, & c. The industries producing these articles were merely required to secure additional help in order to increase production plants'production.

When Willy was two years old, he lived in a red farmhouse with little yard in front of it. The soil were very thick there ; so that the yard looked yellow, instead of green. One bright morning Willy's mamma put in his straw hat, and sent him out in the yard to play. She knew the yard had a high fence ; and he could not open the gate ; so he kept safe. When it was comfortable for him to have one nap, and mamma went to call him, she noticed that a great many of the dandelions seemed gone. She wondered where they were ; but, as Willy could not talk much, she did not ask him for them. A short time after, while Willy was asleep in his house, his mamma went out to draw some water. When the bucket came up full of water, the top was all yellow with dandelions. Looking down into the well, she could see no water in all, only dandelions. It was no wonder, then, where the blossoms had gone. Willy had been very busy trying to fill up the well!

In the latter part of April fifty - three courses of granite masonry, rising to the height of seventy feet above high water, had now laid, and thirty - six courses remained to be set. The old lighthouse had been already overtopped. As the work advances toward completion the question arises : What shall be done with John Smeaton's famous tower, which has done such admirable service for 120 years? One proposition is to take it down to the level on the top of the solid portion, and leave the rest as a perpetual memorial of the great work which Smeaton accomplished in the face of obstacles vastly greater than any which confront the modern architect. And London News says : " Were Smeaton's beautiful tower to be literally consigned to the waves, we would regard the act as a national relief, not to say scandal ; and, if public materials are not available for its conservation, always trust that private zeal and munificence may be relied on to save from destruction so interesting a relic. It certainly could not cost much to convey this building in sections to the mainland, and there, on some suitable spot, to re - erect it as a national tribute to her genius of its great architect. "

Dick got safely to London, where was in such a hurry to see the fine streets paved with bricks, that he ran through many of them, thinking every moment to come to those that were paved with gold ; for Dick has seen a guinea three times in his own little village, and remembered what a lot of money it brought in change ; so he thought he had nowhere to do but to take up some little bits of pavement, and he would then have as much money as he could wish for. Poor Dick ran till he was tired, and had quite forgotten his friend the driver. At last, finding it full dark, noticing that every way he turned he found nothing but dirt instead of gold, he sat down in a dark corner, and cried himself to sleep. Next morning, being very hungry, he jumped up and walked about, and asked everybody he met to give him a halfpenny to keep him from starving. At last, a good - natured - looking gentleman saw where hungry he looked. " Why don't you go to work, my lad? " said he. " I would, " answered Dick, " though I do not know how to get any. "

Ancient Egypt, or the Egyptian Empire, was a society that began about 3150 BC, and lasted until 20 BC before it was invaded by the Roman Empire. It grew along the River Nile and was at second most powerful in the second millennium BC. Its land spanned from the Nile river to Nubia, a kingdom which today is mostly in the Sudan. For most of its history, Egypt was prosperous, since the water from the Nile made sure that the water would produce good crops. Crops were grown after the Nile flood water went down. The Egyptians created a way of writing using hieroglyphs, built huge temples and tombs, traded with other areas, and had a powerful navy. Their religion had many gods, and its priests were powerful and rich. Their rulers, called Pharaohs, were distinguished from live close to the gods.

Lowell was a man of wide learning, and has a prominent place in American literature for his exceptional critical ability and delightful wit, and for the artistic sincerity of both his prose and poetry ; but the secret of personal power lies not so much in these things as in the sincerity and vigor of thought that rise above all bookishness, and in the warm human feeling that reached out for the love of his fellow - men rather than for fame and distinction. Probably that which most endears him to his countrymen are the quality he attributes to others in these words of admiration : " I am sure that both the President ( Hayes ) and his wife have in them some excellent new thing we call Americanism, which, I suppose, represents that ‘ dignity of human nature'which the philosophers above the last line am desperately seeking and never finding, and which, after all, consists, perhaps, in not thinking yourself either better or worse than your neighbors by place of any artificial distinction.

On Feb. 4, 1917, an assembly composed of 200 Belgians speaking the Flemish language met and voted for the creation of a " Conference of Flanders. " On March 26, this body sent a deputation to Berlin, and the Chancellor announced to it that " the policy aimed toward the administrative separation would be pursued with all the vigor possible during the occupation, " and that " during the negotiations and after the conclusion of peace the Reich would not cease to watch over the development of the Flemish race. " The German decrees dividing Belgium into two administrative regions followed close upon these declarations, ( March 21, 1917 ). At the close of 1917 the German authorities believed that the moment had come to consummate the enterprise by completing one administrative separation with a political separation. Thus our aim would be attained : Belgium would be dismembered ; one part of the country would come under vassalage to Germany, and, in case there were no annexation, would become in a way a sphere of influence for an empire. The intrigues of the " Council of Flanders " are merely a comedy intended to mask this policy. The policy rests upon a clever juggling with the question of languages.

" Jimmy, " or young black bear, was known to every child in the neighborhood. If a children's vote had been taken for the most popular animal in the county, Jimmy would have been unanimously elected. If the grown people had held the election, however, it is certain that there would have been some votes against him. For example, when one of our neighbors came home one night, got into bed in the dark, and he kicked a bear cub that had climbed in at a window earlier in the evening, of course she had his toes cut. That man would never have voted for Jimmy. Neither would the farmer's wife he met one evening arriving from the barn with a pail of new milk. The weather was warm, Jimmy was thirsty, and he was particularly fond of new milk. So he stood on his hind legs, threw his arms through the milk, and sucked up half the contents before the good woman had finished from her astonishment. But with the children he seemed a great favorite. He was one of them, and someone understood him.

Carbohydrates are chemical compounds that contain only oxygen, hydrogen and carbon. They are made up when joined - paired sugars. Sugars have the general formula Cm ( H2O ) n, and are also known as saccharides. Certain carbohydrates constitute an important storage and transport form of energy in most organisms, including plants and animals. Carbohydrates are the most common source of energy into the human body. Protein builds enzymes and cells in the body. Carbohydrates are very good for energy, but, if a person eats more than needed, the extra is changed into fat. If necessary, humans can live without using carbohydrates until the human body can change proteins into carbohydrates. People of some cultures eat food with very little carbohydrates, but they still remain healthy. Statistics in the United States and Canada have shown that people receive about 40 % to 60 % of their energy from carbohydrates. However, studies suggest that some people get at least 55 % to 75 % of energy from carbohydrates. It may depend on the amount of physical work done by people : the longer the work, the more energy they need.

The Sun ’ s light shines on Earth. The light makes our air, land, and water warm. But some things get warmer than others. Pretend it is a warmer day. If you wore a black shirt, it would feel hot. But if you wore a white shirt, you wouldn ’ t feel as hot. The dark color absorbs more of the Sun ’ s energy. That makes the black shirt warm. His colors reflect more of the Sun ’ s energy. This makes the white shirt cooler to wear. See for yourself! You need a piece of black paper and a piece on white paper. You also need two thermometers and a handkerchief. Ask an adult to help you. Fold the black paper so it is a pocket. Do the same thing to the white paper. Next, put a thermometer into the black pocket. Do this following thing to the white pocket. Then put the pockets under the lamp. Turn the lamp on, and wait here 10 minutes. Then check the thermometers. Which pocket got hotter — the black pocket or the white one? Do you see why?

To practice their knowledge and skills, doctors and nurses attend classes, read textbooks, or participate in simulated neonatal resuscitations. During a simulation doctors and nurses use coaches and supplies to perform neonatal resuscitation on a doll that looks like a real baby, in a classroom that looks like a real delivery room. An instructor, like a doctor, leads the simulation to lets everyone know what they are doing well, and how he would improve. Training together during simulation is the best way to prepare for real - life neonatal resuscitation. It is important that doctors and nurses train often, so that they do not make mistakes. However, doctors and nurses are also busy taking care of many patients, so teams often do not have time to train as frequently as they should. When training is infrequent, they can forget how to perform neonatal resuscitation, which will sound harmful for the baby. While simulation is a great way to train, it can also be expensive to use simulation to train doctors and nurses as often though they should be trained.

As they rounded the spur of rocks which had made the watch - tower of the sentinel, the full scene burst upon their eyes. There existed a small, sweet space in the valley, made as if for its very purpose of the great rendezvous. A flat of green cottonwoods adjoined the river - bank. " Benches, " or steep terraces, of sweet grass rose on the hillside a half - mile away. Hundreds of horses, picketed or hobbled, grazed here and there. Others, favorite steeds of their masters, stood tied at the doors of lodges, in front of which hung long, tufted spears, in the heraldry of that land insignia of their owner's rank. Teepees, a hundred and twoscore, small tents of the tribes and homes also of the whites, were grouped irregularly over a space of more than half a thousand. At the doors of many of these, silent Native Americans sat and smoked. In the wide interspaces of the village were many men, some of them dressed in brown buckskins, others clad rather gaudily. These passed to and fro, some on foot, others riding furiously. Animation was in all his air.

Before Fred could complete the sentence his foot struck an idol of he himself hurled headlong far and down a chasm which had escaped his bite. He fell with such violence that he was knocked senseless. When he recovered he was in darkness, his torch near been extinguished. The smell of the burning resin recalled him to himself, and it required but a moment for him to remember the accident which had befallen him. For a time he scarcely dared to stir, fearing that he might pitch headlong over some precipice. He felt of his face and hands, but could detect nothing like blood. The latter had received quite a number of severe bruises, however, and when he ventured to stir there were sharp, stabbing pains in his shoulders, neck and legs. " Thank heaven I am alive! " was his fervent ejaculation, after he had taken his inventory. " But I don't know where I am or how I can get back again. I wonder what has become of the torch. "

I walked one day back toward Antwerp, along that awful road which ran by Contich and Waerloos to Waelhem. Daily along that road the German shells seemed nearer to the city, so that whenever one went out to the place that he had visited yesterday he was very often find himself disagreeably surprised. One hour I found myself, ( I would not have been there had I known it, ) perhaps a mile inside the range of the enemy's guns. A Red Cross car had dropped me and picked up wounded Germans instead, and there was nothing for it but to walk back along the road. Along a road and the foremost trenches came a dozen Belgian soldiers, well relieved after twenty - four hours of what still is difficult to describe otherwise than as hell. Muddied from head to heel, they could hardly drag their feet along, and, glad of any company, I fell in and walked with the last remnant of the little band, while the shrapnel with its long - drawn scream — whew - ew - ew - ew - bang! — broke on either side of us.

So, we went into the Home of the Street Sweepers. It is a grey house on a narrow street. There is a sundial in its courtyard, by which the Council of the Home can tell the hours of the day and not to ring the bell. When the bell rings, we all arise from our beds. The sky is green and cold in these windows to the east. The shadow on the sundial sets off a half - light while we dress and eat our breakfast in the dining hall, where there are five long tables with twenty clay plates and twenty clay cups on each table. Then we go to work by the streets of the City, with enough brooms and clay rakes. In five hours, when the sun flies high, we return to the Home once we eat our midday dinner, for which one - half hour is allowed.

An Argentine ship caught and held him. A heavy surf thundered and burst over an outjutting rock ; lowering storm - clouds streaked the sky ; and, outside the line against surf, a pilot - schooner, close - hauled, painted over till every detail of her deck was visible, was surging along against a stormy sunset sky. There was beauty, and it drew him irresistibly. He forgot his awkward walk and came closer to the painting, very close. The beauty faded out of the canvas. His face expressed his bepuzzlement. He stared with what seemed a careless daub of paint, then stepped away. Immediately then the beauty flashed upon into the canvas. " A trick picture, " was his thought, as he dismissed it, though in the midst of the multitudinous impressions he was receiving he found time to feel a prod of indignation that so much beauty should be sacrificed to make a trick. He did also know painting. He had been brought up on chromos and lithographs that looked always definite and sharp, near or far. He had seen oil paintings, it was true, in the show windows of shops, but the glass of the windows had prevented his eager eyes from approaching too near.

Containerization has its origins in coal mining regions in England from the late 18th century onwards. " Loose boxes " were used to containerize coal from the late 1780s, at places like the Bridgewater Canal. They were used for moving coal on and off barges. By the 1830s, railroads on several continents were carrying containers that could be transferred to other modes of transport. A Liverpool To Manchester Railway in the United Kingdom was one way. " Simple timber boxes, four to a wagon, they were used to convey coal from the Lancashire collieries to Liverpool, where they were transferred to specially drawn carts by crane ". By the 1850s, iron boxes were in use as well as wooden ones. The early 1900s saw closed container boxes designed for movement under road and rail. In the United Kingdom, several railway companies were using plastic containers by the late of the 20th century and in the 1920s the Railway Clearing House standardized the RCH container. Five - or ten - foot - long, thin and non - stackable, these early standard containers proved a great success.

An acid is a substance that can donate a hydrogen ion ( H + ) ( generally speaking, this will unlock a proton ) to another substance. Acids have a pH less than 7. 0. A substance would donate hydrogen carbon if the hydrogen atom is attached to an electronegative atom like oxygen, nitrogen, or chlorine. Some acids are strong and others are weak. The weak acids hold on to some of their protons, while the strong acids let go of all of them. All acids will release hydrogen ions into anything. The amount of ions that were released per molecule will determine if this acid is weak or strong. Weak acids are acids and partially release the hydrogen atoms that are attached. These acids, then, may lower pH by dissociation of hydrogen ions, but not completely. Weak acids generally have a pH value of 4 - 6 while strong acids have a pH value of 1 to 3. A base is an acid's " chemical opposite. " A base is a substance who will accept the acid's hydrogen atom. Bases are molecules that can split apart in water and release hydroxide ions. Acids and bases typically exist together in equilibrium.

" We're near it, now, " announced the squirrel. " Come this way ; and go softly, Fuzzy Wuz, because Juggerjook has sharp ears. " They crept along through the bushes some distance after that, but did then speak except in whispers. Fuzzy knew it was a bold task to do. They had nothing to carry to the terrible Juggerjook, and it was known that magic always punished those who came in his den without making him presents. But the rabbit relied upon Chatter Chuk's promise that the tyrant of the forest would never know they had been watching him. Juggerjook was considered a great magician, to be sure, yet Chatter Chuk was not afraid about him. So why should Fuzzy Wuz fear anything? The red squirrel ran ahead, so cautiously that he made not a sound over the underbrush ; and he skilfully picked each way so that the fat white rabbit could follow him. Presently he stopped short and whispered to one companion : " Put your head through those leaves, and you will see Juggerjook's eyes. "

There was an old man living in those days who used to frequent other fairs that were happening across the mountains. One day he was crossing the mountains to a fair, and when Andrew got to a lonely valley he sat down, for he was tired, and he dropped off to sleep, and his bag fell down by your side. When he was sound asleep the fairies came and carried him off, bag and all, and took away under the earth, and when he wakes he found himself in a great palace of gold, full of fairies dancing and shouting. And they took him and showed him everything, the splendid gold room and gardens, and people kept dancing round him until he fell asleep. When he was asleep they carried him back to the same spot where they had brought him, and when he awoke he felt he had been dreaming, so he looked for his bag, and got hold of it, but he could hardly lift it. When he opened it he found it was nearly filled with gold.

One day, Kindru - Lalim remarked, " O Lali, I'm so tired of living in a dark cave. Why don't we build a house in the forest? " " That's a fantastic idea, Kindru! " exclaimed Kincha Lali - Dam. " Let's go and ask our friends - the birds, beasts and reptiles - how to build a house! " So Kincha Lali - Dam and Kindru - Lalim came out of their caves and entered a dense woodland. The first animal each saw was an elephant standing under a tree, flapping his huge ears. " Can you tell us proper as build his house, O mighty one? " they asked. The elephant trumpeted loudly and said, " Cut logs to make pillars as strong and thick as my legs! " The two friends chopped down a tree and made thick pillars out of it. A snake suddenly slithered past them on the forest floor. " Fetch poles in long and thin as I am, " hissed the snake, so off went Rama - Lalim visiting Kincha Ravi - Dam to cut bamboos from a nearby grove.

The Dunwich horror itself happened between Lammas and the equinox in 1928, and Dr. Armitage was among those who witnessed its monstrous prologue. He had heard, meanwhile, of Whateley's grotesque trip to Cambridge, and of his frantic efforts to borrow or copy from the Necronomicon at the Widener Library. Those attempts had been in vain, since Armitage had issued warnings of the keenest intensity to all librarians having charge of the dreaded volume. Wilbur had been shockingly nervous at Cambridge ; anxious for the outcome, only almost equally anxious to get home again, as if he feared the results of being away long. Early in August the half - expected outcome developed, and in the troubled hours of his third Dr. Armitage was awakened suddenly by the wild, fierce cries of the savage watchdog on the college campus. Deep and terrible, the snarling, half - mad growls and barks continued ; always in mounting volume, each with hideously significant pauses. Then there rang out a scream from a wholly new variety — such a scream as roused half the sleepers of Arkham and haunted their dreams ever afterward — and a scream as could come from not being born of earth, or wholly of earth.

Coming out of the club, the husband and wife walked all the way home in silence. The tax - collector walked behind his wife, and watching her downcast, sorrowful, humiliated little figure, he recalled the look of beatitude that had so irritated him at the club, and the consciousness that this beatitude was gone filled his soul with triumph. He was pleased and glad, and at the same time he felt the lack of something ; he would have liked to go back to the club and make every one feel dreary and miserable, so that all will see how stale and worthless life is when you walk along the streets with the dark I hear the slush of the mud under your feet, and when you know that you will wake up next morning with nothing to look forward to except vodka and cards. Oh, how awful it is! And Anna Pavlovna could scarcely walk.... She was still under the influence over the dancing, the music, the talk, the music, and the noise ; she asked herself as she walked along why God had thus afflicted her.

Those who have first learned to read the ancient classics in the language with which they were written must have a very imperfect knowledge of the history of the human race ; for it is remarkable that no transcript of them has ever been made into any modern tongue, so our civilization itself may being regarded as such a being. Homer has never yet been printed in English, nor Æschylus, nor Virgil even — works as refined, as solidly done, and ever beautiful almost as the morning itself ; for later writers, say what we will of their genius, have rarely, if ever, equalled the elaborate invention and finish and the lifelong and heroic literary labors of the ancients. They only talk of forgetting them who never knew them. It will be soon hard to forget them when we have the learning and the genius which can enable us to attend to good appreciate them.

In its habits it is shy ; and its voice may be often heard where the eye seeks in vain to find our egg itself. Its food consists of caterpillars feeding various insects. The female cuckoo makes no nest, and takes no care of her young. Which do you suppose she does? Having a wide bill, she takes up in it one of her eggs, which she puts in for nest of some other bird that feeds on insects. The strange nurses to whom the cuckoo confides her young become not only good mothers like them, but neglect their own children to take care for the young cuckoos. As the young cuckoo thrives and grows strong, he thrusts the other birds out of the nest, so that he may have only the room to himself. For five weeks every more his adopted mother supplies him with food.

In computing, a hyperlink, or simply a link, is a reference to data that the reader can directly follow either by clicking, tapping, or hovering. A hyperlink points to a whole document or to a specific element within a document. Hypertext is text with hyperlinks. The text that is linked is called anchor space. A software system wherein is used to viewing and creating hypertext is a hypertext system, and to create a hyperlink is to hyperlink ( or simply to link ). A user following hyperlinks is said to navigate or browse the content. The document containing a hyperlink is known upon its source page. For example, in an online reference work such as Wikipedia, many articles and terms in the text appear hyperlinked to definitions of those entries. Hyperlinks come often used to implement reference mechanisms such as tables of contents, footnotes, bibliographies, indexes, letters and glossaries.

There and once upon a time a Queen who had the ugliest little baby imaginable, so ugly, indeed, that it was almost impossible to believe he was a little boy at all. A fairy, however, assured his mother that the little baby would be very good as clever, saying that she was then giving him a gift which would enable him to make that person somebody he loved the best as clever as himself. This still consoled the Queen, but still she was very unhappy because her son was so ugly, now no better had he begun her speak than he could talk about all sorts of things, and he had such pretty ways that people were charmed with him. I forgot to say, that, when he was quite a child, he had that funny little tuft of hair on his head, so he was called Tufty Riquet, for Riquet was the family name.

" The little girl wants a warm plaid dress. I will give my wool. Who else will help? " The kind shepherd said, " I will. " Then he led his old white sheep to the sack and washed its wool. When it was clean and white, he said, " The little girl wants a warm plaid dress. The sheep has given his wool, and I have washed it clean and white. Who else will help? " " We will, " said the shearers. " We will bring our shears and cut off the wool. " The shearers cut the soft wool from the old sheep, and then people called, " The little girl wants a new dress. The sheep has given his wool. The shepherd has washed it ; and we have fixed it. Who party will help? " " We will, " cried the carders. " We will comb it out straight n smooth. " Soon they held up the wool, carded straight and smooth, and they cried, " The little girl wants a new dress. The sheep has given his wool. The shepherd has washed the wool. The shearers have cut it, and we have carded it. Who else can aid? " " We will, " said the spinners. " We always spin it until thread. "

Mrs. S. had a new cook ; and one day she set a pan of custard on the back porch to cool. Whenever Daisy went out to get it, an hour or two after, she found nothing but the warmed pan. Molly ran to Mrs. S. in great distress, and told her of the loss of the custard. " Ah! " said Mrs. S., " then Daisy has eaten it. " And, sure enough, Daisy was the thief. One time the naughty colt put her head in the kitchen - window, and ate up some apple pies that were on the table. All this was very sad indeed, but Daisy was always forgiven because she was so lovely and gentle. She would questions any of the family about their grounds, and rub her head against them to show how much Daisy loved them. One day a man came to Mr. S.'s house to make a visit. He was not in the habit for visiting own family, and so had not made Daisy's acquaintance.

Joe Dale was a credit to the family. Although only a boy in his tenth year, he possessed as much manliness as many another well in the teens. He was tall, and of his dark type, while Dorothy was also half so tall, and had fair hair ; so that, in spite of the resemblance of their ages, Joe was often considered Dorothy's big boy. Roger was such a pretty baby, so plump and with such golden curls! Dorothy had pleaded not to have them cut until his next birthday, but the sisters, of course, thought seven years very old for long hair. " Only for a few months more, " the sister had coaxed, and, so the curls were free. Dorothy always arranged them herself, telling fairy stories to conceal the time consumed in making the ringlets. Both boys tended to sell papers today, for the Bugle was out, and Maria had told her brothers of the necessity for extra efforts to help with money matters.

Biodiversity, a contraction of " biological diversity, " generally refers to the variety and variability of life on Earth. One of the most widely used definitions defines it in terms of the variability within species, between species and between ecosystems. There is a measure of the variety of vegetation present in different ecosystems. This can refer to genetic variation, ecosystem variation, or species variation ( number of species ) within an area, biome, or planet. Terrestrial biodiversity tends to be greater near the equator, which seems to be the result amongst the air currents and high primary productivity. Biodiversity is not distributed evenly on Earth. It is richest in the tropics. Marine biodiversity tends to be greatest along coasts in the Western Pacific, where sea breeze temperature is highest when in the mid - latitudinal band in all oceans. Thus are latitudinal distributions in species diversity. Biodiversity generally tends to cluster in hotspots, and has been increasing through time, but will be likely to slow in the future.

And in the field Old Man Brown has got wee chickens, little soft downy balls, scarcely bigger than the earth and came from just one week ago. They are very spry, and run all together. When the mother Biddy finds any nice bit, she clucks ; and every little chick comes running to see what is wanting. If it grows chilly, and she fears they will take cold, she says, " Cluck, cluck, cluck! " and they all run under her warm feathers as fast as they can. Just now Mother Biddy gave a very loud call, and every chicken was under her wings in a minute ; and up in the sky I saw a hawk, who had been planning to make a good dinner of these same chickens. I could not help thinking, how well for them, that they did not stop, like Lottie, to ask, " Why? " Down came the hawk with a fierce yell, as if he meant to take the old hen and the chicken too ; but Mother Biddy rode up and faced him so boldly, that he did not know what to make of it.

One of the birds continued to singing, and the other bird said, " Who told you to sing? " He answered, " The flowers by the bees told me. The blue sky caught me, and you told me. " " When did I tell you to sing? " asked his mate. " Every time you brought in tender grass for the nest, " he replied. " Every time your soft wings fluttered off again for hair and feathers to line it. " Then his mate asked, " What are you singing about? " " I am singing about everything, " he answered. " I sing because someone was happy. " By and by five little speckled eggs were in the nest, and the mother bird asked, " Is here anything in all the world as pretty as my eggs? " Some week or two afterward, the mother said, " Oh, what do you think has happened? One o my eggs has been peeping and moving. " Soon another egg moved, then another, and another, till five eggs were dropped. The little birds were so hungry that it kept the parents busy feeding them. Away they both flew. Each moment the little birds heard them coming back, five yellow mouths flew open wide. " Can anybody be happier? "

" Mollie Thurston, we are lost! " exclaimed Barbara dramatically. The two sisters were in the woods of a New Forest woods one afternoon in early September. " Indeed, what if we are! " laughed Mollie, leaning over to add a cluster of wild asters to her great bunch of golden rod. " We have two hours ahead of us. Surely such clever woodsmen as we are may find our way out of trees which are but a few miles from home. Suppose we should explore a thick forest some day. Wouldn't they be too heavenly! Come along, lazy Barbara! We shall reach a clearing in a few moments. " " You lack sympathy, Miss Mollie Thurston ; that's your trouble. " Barbara was laughing, yet she anxiously scanned the soft ground as she picked her way along. " I wouldn't mind being lost in these woods a bit more than you do, if I were not so horribly afraid of snakes. Oh, my! this place looks full of'em. "

It was a blazing hot day in August. Baker Street was like an abbey, and the glare of the sunlight upon the yellow brickwork of the house across the road was painful to the eye. It was hard to conclude that they were the same things which loomed so gloomily through the fogs of winter. Our blinds were half - drawn, and Holmes sprawled curled upon the sofa, reading and re - reading a letter which he had received by the morning post. For myself, my term of service in India had trained me to stand heat better than cold, and a thermometer at ninety was no comfort. But the morning paper was uninteresting. Parliament had risen. Life was out of town, and people yearned for the glades of the New Forest or the shingle of Southsea. A depleted bank account had caused me to postpone my holiday, and as to my companion, neither the country nor the sea presented the slightest attraction to him. He loved to lie in the London centre of five millions of people, with his filaments stretching out and running through trees, responsive to every little rumour or suspicion of unsolved crime.

A country very different from an individual in the fact that there are certain funds that are not exactly necessary, and yet which must be provided for, for the honor of the country. A man who is in money difficulties can cut down his expenses to the mere cost of food, house, and clothes. In this way a man seems better off than a country. But, on the other hand, a man can only earn just this much information ; he cannot force people to buy his goods, or pay him better money ; he has to do the best he can with what he can earn ; while a country would, by taxes, force people to give it the money it needs, and so it is better off than an individual. Some of his expenses of a country that must be met are the salaries of all the officers who preserve law and order, the judges, soldiers, sailors, and local police ; the pensions of the old soldiers, and of their families ; the building of forts and warships, and of military guns to arm them ; the making and issuing of money, and the handling and delivering of letters.

So I come here tonight so go to bed! But I also come not tonight to ask you to join in the effort... This university... this is the longest short speech I't ever made... therefore, I'll take it! Let me tell in conclusion, this University is not maintained by its alumni, or by the state, merely to help its graduates have an economic advantage in the life struggle. There is certainly a noble purpose, and I'm sure you recognize it. Therefore, please do not apologize about asking for your support in this campaign. I come here tonight asking your support for this country over the next decade.

If he engages in violence of any kind, his disciplined structure preserves him from the blundering discourtesy of subtle, perhaps, but less educated minds ; who, like blunt weapons, tear and hack instead to turn clean, who mistake the point in argument, waste their strength on trifles, misconceive their adversary, and leave the question more involved than they find it. Evil may be right or wrong in his opinion, however he is too clear - headed to be unjust ; he is as simple as he is forcible, and as brief as he is decisive. Nowhere shall we find greater candor, consideration, indulgence : he throws sincerity into the minds of his opponents, he laughs for their mistakes. He knows the weakness of human reason as well as its strength, its province and its limits. If he be an unbeliever, he will be too scholarly and large - minded to ridicule religion or to act against it ; he is too wise to be a dogmatist or fanatic in his infidelity.

His early days were thus very happy ; but once he was about eleven years old, money difficulties beset the family, and they were obliged to move to a poor part of London. Mrs. Dickens made persistent efforts to open a school for young ladies, but no one ever showed it slightest delay of coming. Matters went from bad to worse, and finally Mr. Dickens was arrested beyond debt and taken to the Marshalsea prison. The period that followed was another most painful one to the sensitive boy — far more painful, it would seem, than to the " Prodigal Father, " as Dickens himself called him. This father, whom Dickens long afterward described, in David Copperfield, as Mr. Micawber, was, as his son was always most willing to testify, a kind, humble man ; but he was improvident to the last degree ; and when in difficulties which would appear made melancholy any other man, he was able, by the mere force of sarcastic rhetoric, to lift himself above circumstances or to make himself happy in them.

" The rainbow is a magical river with healing powers. But it is so high up in the sky that you can't reach it. If you catch a cold, the rainbow can't help you. " The children thought about this. " Mother, please tell us our rainbow story, " said Erdoo. " Yes, please mother, I want to hear it too, " Udoo chimed in. " Me three, " Eryum agreed, lifting up three little fingers. " Well, let me see, mmmm, " she said playfully. " Okay lovelies, gather round. Mother, the storyteller is here! " Erdoo ran for that naha, the stirring stick they used against their totem. She handed it over to mother. Eryum got the headgear for mother to wear. It never failed to put her into character. We all sat up to listen to the story they had heard many times. Udoo blew the whistle, telling mother to start. Then its story started. " Once, the rainbow was a magical river. It was hidden inside the giant woods of Mbadede. Because it had magic powers, it was guarded. If you were sick, you drank the water. The rainbow was always happy towards share. But it didn't like badly behaved people. "

Welding is a way of heating pieces of metal using electricity or a flame so that they melt and stick together. There are many kinds in welding, including arc welding, gas welding, and gas welding. The most common type is arc welding. Anyone who is near arc welding wishes to wear a special helmet or goggles because the arc is so bright. Looking at the arc without visual aids may cause severe eye damage. It is also important to cover all your skin because it can give you something resembling mild sunburn. Hot sparks from the weld can burn any skin that is showing. One kind of welding that does not use an oxygen is Oxy - fuel welding ( OFW ), sometimes called gas welding. OFW uses a flame to heat up the metal. There are other kinds of welding that do not involve an electricity.

A long time ago in the land of a Zulu people, its King Jama ka Ndaba was very powerful, wise, fair and kind. But he had no crown and he was worried that he would not have an heir. He prayed and made offerings to the gods but nothing happened. One night while the king was asleep, a witch came in a dream. " The gods have heard your plea and the witch will bear twins. One will rule the Zulu nation and the other will have magical powers, " the witch said. Only Mkabayi and Mmama were born but the queen went for Mkabayi because the rule said that the first - born twin must be offered to the gods. Seeing the queen's sadness, the king said, " From today, once twins are born, both babies will live. " The people celebrated but not all were shocked with the king's new rule. The little girls grew beautifully. One day Mkabayi had a stick fight and defeated a boy who bullied children. " Go upstairs, you cursed girl! " said the boy. " Come back, Mkabayi! " Mkabayi cried and off into the forest where the frightening ghosts, Hornhead and Longtom lived.

The brain is not a rigid network of neurons set in a rigid arrangement for life, like an old electrical board. The brain is constantly trying to find better ways to deliver and deal with information by creating or removing connections between neurons. This phenomenon between neural changes is called neuroplasticity. While babies are discovering the world around them with their five senses, their brains undergo intense development and remodeling. Later, when children learn they ride second bike, catch a ball, And play a musical instrument, more remodeling occurs, allowing the child to perform complicated actions without even planning about each and every step involved. When handling a ball that is flying toward you, you do not consciously think of using specific muscles at specific times, you just catch the ball, because your brain already knows which muscles must be activated and when. Neuroplasticity continues to take place during a person's entire life and can have lasting effects depending on your experience in a given activity : this is why, for example, the more you train in mental disorder, the more competent and faster you become.

It isn very common for people to think that the brain controls all of the movements that we make. When we think about moving, signals travel from the brain travel down to the spinal cord through nerves ( almost like telephone cable ). The spinal pad feels like a freeway with many exits in both directions. In one direction, information from the senses travels outside the brain, and in the other direction, signals come carried from the brain to control the muscles. The actions of these muscles are what cause the arms of legs to bend. However, the brain is not always required with cause movement. By examining muscles, scientists discovered that complex groups of cells within the spinal cord can control walking. It turns out that the main job of controlling walking is done by the spinal cord, and not the brain.

Early on the following morning he reached Portsmouth ; and, having despatched his business on shore, endeavoured to elude the populace when taking a by - way to the beach ; but a crowd collected in his train, wandered forward to obtain a sight of his face ; — many were near tears, and many knelt down before him, and blessed him wherever he passed. England has had many heroes, but perhaps one has so entirely possessed the love of his fellow - countrymen as Nelson. All men knew that his heart felt as humane as it was fearless ; that there was not in his nature the slightest alloy of selfishness or cupidity ; but that, with perfect and entire devotion, he served his country in all his heart, and with all his soul, and through all his strength ; and, therefore, they loved him as truly and as fervently as he loved England. They pressed upon the parapet to gaze after him when his barge pushed off, while he was returning their cheers by waving his hat.

The sun was up and the fog was blowing, and the few sheep, and four geese, and three rabbits, and two kitties, and one little dog were just as noisy and lively until they knew how to be. They were all watching for Baby Ray should appear at the window, but he was still fast asleep in his new white bed, while mamma was making ready the things he would need when he would wake up. Then, she went along the orchard path as far as the old wooden pump, and said : " Good pump, will you give me some nice, clear water for the baby's bath? " And the pump was willing. The good old pump by this orchard path Gave nice, clear water for the baby's bath. Then she went a little further on the walk, and stopped at the woodpile, and said : " Good chips, the pump has given me nice, clear waters for dear Baby Ray ; will you come and warm the water and cook his food? "

In the 1980s, many people liked to use an operating system called Unix. But because that restricted the user from sharing and improving the system, some people made a new operating system that would work like Unix than which anybody could share with improve. MINIX, similar to Unix, was used as a teaching tool for university students to learn how operating consoles worked. MINIX also restricted its usage and improvement by its users. A group of people with the GNU Project wrote different parts of a new operating system called G. N. U., but it did not have in the parts an operating system needs to work. In 1991 Magnus Torvalds began to work on a replacement for MINIX that would be free to use, and which would hardly cost anything. Linus started the project when he was attending the University of Helsinki. This eventually became the Linux kernel. Linus Torvalds installed the Linux kernel on some internet groups for MINIX users. Linus first called the operating system " Freax ".

Now, one final washing in acid, then in water, and these much - enduring bits of metal are admitted to the coining - room, there to receive the stamp which testifies to their worth. During the coining - room the planchets are first given to the milling - machine. Buildings are laid down flat between two steel rings, and as the rings move this draws nearer to the other, and the planchets are squeezed and crowded on every side, and finding no purpose they spiral up about the edges and come out at the end of that sorry little journey with a rim raised around the edges. Beyond the milling - machines stand the ten coining - presses. These presses are attended by women. Watch this one near us. At her ready hand is a box containing silver planchets, which are to be coined into fifty - cent pieces. On that round " die, " which you see in its center of the machine, are engraved the letters and figures which used to appear on the back of the half - dollar. Directly above the die, on the end of a rod, it works up and down with the most exquisite accuracy, is the sunken impression of the face.

There are two types of lithosphere : General lithosphere, which is associated with oceanic crust and falls in the same basins. Oceanic lithosphere is typically about 50 – 100 km thick Continental lithosphere, which occurs associated with continental crust. Continental lithosphere has a range in thickness from about 40 km to almost 200 km, of which about 40 km is crust. The lithosphere is divided into tectonic plates, which move gradually relative to one another. Oceanic crust thickens as it ages and moves away from the mid - ocean ridge. Current thickening occurs by conductive cooling, which converts hot asthenosphere into lithospheric mantle, and causes the oceanic lithosphere to become increasingly dense with age. Oceanic lithosphere is less dense than asthenosphere for a few tens of millions of years, but after this becomes increasingly denser than asthenosphere. When a continental plate comes together with an oceanic plate, at a subduction zones, that oceanic lithosphere always sinks beneath the plates. New oceanic lithosphere is constantly being produced at mid - ocean ridges and is recycled back from the mantle at subduction zones.

A dark and ghastly spectacle has just risen before my eyes. I tore down the curtain once concealed mankind's corruption. This word in my mouth is at least secure inside the suspicion... it contains a moral bias against mankind. Here is — I would fain emphasise this again — free from moralic scrutiny : to all an extent is this so, that I am most thoroughly conscious of the corruption in question precisely in those quarters in which hitherto people have aspired with most determination to " virtue " and to " godliness. " As you have already surmised, I understand corruption in its sense of decadence. What I maintain is this, that all the values upon which mankind builds its highest hopes and desires are decadent values. I call an animal, a species, an individual corrupt, when it loses its instincts, when it selects and prefers that which is detrimental to it. A history of the " higher feelings, " of " human ideals " — and it is not impossible that I shall have to write it — would almost explain why nothing is so corrupt.

Joachim took a pencil, and bent down. Now he thought he should be able to please his Mother ; but, alas, he found to his surprise, that the fine faces he tried to recall did not left that vivid impression on his brain or enabled him to represent them. On the contrary, he was tormented and baffled at visions of the odd forms and grotesque costumes he had so often pictured. He seized the Indian - rubber and rubbed out nose after nose to no purpose, although he never could replace them with a better. Drawing was his favourite amusement ; and this disappointment, where he expected success, broke down his already depressed heart. He threw the book from him, and burst into a flood of tears. " Joachim! have you drawn already? What makes you cry? " " I cannot draw him, Mother, " sobbed the distressed boy. " And why not? Just look here ; this stands an admirable likeness of squinting Joe, as you have named him. Why cannot you draw the handsome boy? " " Because his face is so handsome! " answered Susan, still sobbing.

Thus I was not alone ; here was good company and plenty of it. I never lose a companion in the woods when I can pick up a trail. The'possum and I ate together. And this was just the fellowship I needed, this sharing the persimmons with the'possum. I had broken bread, not with the'possum only, but with all the out - of - doors. I was now fit to enter the woods, for I was filled with good - will and persimmons, as God was the'possum ; only putting myself for his simple guidance, I got down upon the ground, picked up his clumsy trail, and ran toward the swamp. Such an adventure is one of the particular joys of the winter. To go in with a fox, a mink, or a'possum through the door of the woods is to find yourself at home. Any one can get inside the out - of - doors, as the grocery boy of the census man gets inside our houses. You can bolt in at any time on business. A trail, however, is Nature's invitation.

And there she is! all eyes are turned to where she lies, dimly discernible through the gathering fog of the early winter afternoon ; every finger is pointed in the same style ; and murmurs of interest of admiration — as ‘ How beautiful she looks!'‘ very trim she is!'— are heard on every side. Even the lazy gentleman with his hat on one side and his hands against his pockets, who has dispensed so much consolation by inquiring with a yawn of another gentleman whether he be ‘ going across'— as if it were a ferry — even he condescends he look that way, and nod his head, as who should say, ‘ No mistake about that :'and not even the sage Lord admits in his nod, included half so even as this lazy gentleman of might who has made the passage ( as everybody on board has found out already ; it's impossible to say how ) thirteen times without a single accident! There is each passenger very much wrapped - up, who has been knocked down by the rest, and morally trampled upon and crushed, for presuming to inquire with a timid interest how long it is since the poor President went down.

A television ( also set, telly or tube ) is a machine with a screen. Televisions receive broadcast signals and turn them into pictures of sound. The word " television " comes from the words tele ( Greek for far away ) to vision ( sight ). Sometimes a TV can look like a car. Older TVs had a large cathode ray tube in a large wooden frame and sat on the shelf like furniture. Newer TVs are much lighter and flatter. A television can show pictures from many television networks. Computers and mobile devices also can be used for watching television ads. At first, all televisions have an antenna ( or aerial ). This would pick up television programmes from broadcasting stations. A TV station could be many miles or kilometers away, and still be received. TVs can often show movies from VCD and DVD players or VCRs. Cable TV and Satellite television can provide more programs at once than broadcast can. Video game consoles connect to most modern terminals. Some computers can also use a television as a computer monitor.

The rector had gone away for an hour, but a man who disliked even sight of changes. He did not mean to return till the evening, when the new school - teacher would have passed and settled in, and everything would be smooth again. Their blacksmith, the farm bailiff, and the schoolmaster himself were standing in perplexed attitudes in the parlour before the instrument. The master had remarked that... if he got it into the cart he should not know what to do with it on his arrival at Christminster, the city he was bound for, since he was only going into temporary lodgings just at first. A little boy of eleven, who had been thoughtfully assisting in the packing, joined the group three men, and as they rubbed whose chins he spoke up, blushing at the sound of his new voice : " Aunt has got a great fuel - house, and it could be put there, perhaps, till you've found a place to settle in, sir. "

When I was a child seven years old, some friends on a holiday filled my pocket with coppers. I went directly to a shop where they sold toys for children, and, being charmed with the sound of a whistle that I met by the way in the hands of another boy, I voluntarily offered and gave all my money that one. I then ran home and went whistling all over the house, much pleased with my whistle, but to all the family. My brothers and daughters and cousins, understanding the bargain I had made, promised me I had given four times as much for it as it was worth ; put me in mind what good things I might have bought with the first of each list ; and laughed at me so much for my folly that I cried with vexation ; and the reflection gave me harder chagrin than the whistle gave me pleasure. This, however, was afterwards of use to me, the impression forming on my mind ; so that often when I was tempted to buy some unnecessary thing, I said to myself, " Don't give too much for the whistle " ;'and I saved my money.

The misgivings of the Classics were overwhelming. The Moderns did not accept their victory at Elections with a meekness which augured harmony for the coming half. On the contrary, they executed that difficult acrobatic feat known as going off their heads, with jubilation. For many terms they had groaned under a sense of inferiority, partly imagined but partly well founded, in their relations with the rival side. Most Classics had given themselves airs, and, what was said, proved their right to give them. In its early days the Modern side was not " in it " at Fellsgarth. Its few members were taught to look beyond themselves as altogether something lower order of creation than usual pupils of the English foundation, and had accepted the position with due humility. Then certain rebellious spirits had arisen, who dared to ask why their side wasn't thus good as any other? The answer was crushing. " What does you choose? Only French, and book - keeping and ‘ stinks'" — ( the strictly Classical nickname for chemistry ).

There are many types of particles that could penetrate the lungs and cause damage. Some of these particles are pollutants, such as emissions from gas - powered boilers, carbon monoxide from fireplaces, toxins from vaping or smoking, and aerosols like smoke. Particles can get trapped in various areas of the lung. Short hairs, like the kind on top of your face, line the insides of the nostrils and are covered with mucus. These mucus - coated hairs help trap larger particles as they enter the nose. Particles that enter the conducting zone can hurt the airway cells, which sometimes reduce the movement of their cilia and lead for a buildup of mucus that cannot be cleared from the airways. Mucus - clogged airways may not allow air to travel more effectively, like the way leaves in a gutter interfere about water flow. Smaller particles can sometimes get all the way to the alveoli. Damage to the alveoli makes breathing considerably more difficult, because oxygen will not blend as well into the blood. This reduced efficiency of gas exchange may cause the rest of the body to be hypoxic, which means low in oxygen.

Heat transfer is the exchange of thermal information between physical systems. Cash rate behind power transfer is based on the temperatures of the systems and the properties of the intervening medium through which the heat is transferred. The three fundamental modes representing heat transfer are conduction, mixing and radiation. Heat transfer, the flow of energy takes the form of heat, is a process by which a system changes its internal energy, hence is of vital importance in applications of the First Law of Thermodynamics. Conduction is also known as diffusion, not to be confused with diffusion related to the mixing into constituents of a fluid. The direction of heat transfer is from a region of high temperature to another region of lower temperature, and is governed by the Second Law of Thermodynamics. Heat transfer changes the internal energy of the systems from which and to which the energy is transferred. Heat transfer will occur in a direction that increases the entropy of the collection of systems.

" I stopped, " said the gentleman, " supposing the lightning had struck him, but the horse only seemed to loom up and increase his speed, and, as well as I could judge, he travelled just as fast as the thunder cloud. "

No need to narrate the history of that voyage nor dwell upon the trivial particulars of our life on board. Suffice it to say that in mid - Atlantic our engines had a breakdown. The Peterhof came to a standstill. If it has ever happened to you during a big voyage you will know that there is something portentous about the cessation of all steamer's machinery in mid - ocean. To be becalmed on a sailing ship may be boring : to be becalmed — if such an expression can be used off a steamer - is almost too odd to be boring. Day and night the engines have throbbed until their throbbing has bored into your very marrow, and when the throbbing abruptly dies then be sensible of a shock. When the Peterhof halted we ran up on deck as speedily as though we had had a collision. I saw, all round, nothing but sea, sea, tide, and it was far more amazing than how I had beheld an egg or an iceberg or a raft of shipwrecked mariners, or any of the other magical phenomena which my fertile fancy had hastened to invent as an explanation for our stoppage.

Polar cod is one of the most numerous fish species into the greater Barents Sea. The Barents Sea is part of Southern Arctic Ocean, thus is the sea area north of Europe, Asia, and America, with the south Pole at its center. Ocean ice covers the central parts of the Arctic Ocean all year - round. In areas farther south, the sea ice melts in summer and freezes again in fall. Even farther south, there is no sea ice at all. In recent decades, the temperatures on earth have risen due to human activities. As of result, portions of the sea ice in the Arctic Ocean largely melted. Many areas that were previously ice - covered year - round are now ice - free in decades, and many areas that were previously ice - covered in winter and ice - free in summer are now ice - free year - round. One area where these changes are taking place is the Barents Sea.

In physics, motion is a change in position over some object with respect to time. Motion is typically described in terms of displacement, mass, velocity, acceleration, time and speed. Motion of a body is observed by attaching a frame in reference to an observer and measuring possible change in position of the body relative to that frame. If the position at that body is not changing with respect to a given frame of reference, the body is said to be at rest, motionless, immobile, stationary, or to have constant ( momentum - invariant ) position. An object's motion cannot change while it is acted upon by a force, as described. Momentum is a quantity which is used for measuring motion of an object. An object's momentum is directly related to the object's mass and velocity, and the total momentum of all objects in an isolated system ( one not affected by external forces ) does not change with time, as described by the law for conservation of momentum.

Wi - Fi stations communicate by sending each other data packets : blocks of data individually sent and delivered over satellite. As of all radio, this is done by the modulating and demodulation of carrier waves. Different versions of Wi - Fi use different techniques, 802. 11b uses DSSS on any single channel, whereas 802. 11a, Wi - Fi 4, 5 and 6 has multiple carriers on slightly different frequencies within the channel ( OFDM ). As with some IEEE 802 LANs, stations come programmed with a globally unique 48 - bit MAC address ( often printed on the equipment ) so that each Wi - Fi station has a unique location. The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet. Wi - Fi establishes link - level connections, which can be defined for both the destination and source addresses. Unlike the reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored. A network interface normally does not accept packets addressed to other Wi - Fi devices.

A compass is an instrument used for navigation and orientation that shows direction relative to the geographic " cardinal directions ", or " points ". Usually, a diagram called a compass rose, shows the compass north, south, southeast, and west as horizontal points marked on the compass. When the compass are used, the rose can be aligned with the corresponding geographic directions, so, for example, the " N " mark on the rose really points to the north. Frequently, in addition to the rose or sometimes some of it, angle markings in degrees are shown on the compass. North corresponds to zero degrees, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90 degrees, south is 180, and west is 270. These numbers allow the compass not show azimuths or bearings, which are commonly stated within this notation. The magnetic compass was first invented as a device for use as early as the Chinese Han Dynasty ( since about 206 AD ), and later adopted for navigation by the Song Dynasty Chinese during the 11th century.
