The company pairs off quickly, and the whole room is soon in motion. Apparently nobody knows how the waltz, but that is nothing of any consequence — there is music, and children dance, each as he pleases, just like before they sang. Most of them play the " two - step, " especially the young, with whom it is the fashion. The older people have dances from home, strange and complicated steps which they execute with grave passion. Some do not dance anything at all, but simply hold each other's hands and allow the undisciplined joy of motion to express itself with their feet. Among these are Jokubas Szedvilas and his wife, Barbara, who together keep the delicatessen store, and consume nearly as much as they sell ; they are too big to carry, but they stand in the opening facing the floor, holding each other fast in their arms, kicking slowly from side to side and grinning seraphically, a picture of toothless and perspiring ecstasy.

There stands to reason that were our summers warmer we should be able to grow grapes successfully on open walls ; it is therefore probable that a new grape bag, the bag of M. Pelletier, 20 Rue de la Banque, Paris, intended to serve a double purpose, viz., protecting the fruit and hastening its maturity, may, when it becomes known, be welcomed in this country. It uses of a square of curved glass so fixed to the bag that the sun's rays are concentrated upon the fruit, thereby rendering its ripening more certain in addition to maintaining its quality generally. The glass is affixed to the bag by wire of a light iron wire support. It covers that portion of it next the sun, so that it increases the amount of light and warms the grapes without penetrating them, a result due to the convexity of the glass and the layer of air between it and the bag. B. Pelletier had any idea of rendering these bags thinner by employing plain squares instead of curved ones, but the advantage thus obtained was more than counterbalanced by their comparative inefficacy.

The Earth's warming climate is reducing snow and erosion. The warming in the polar seas causes the sea surface to freeze less in place and glaciers to retreat, generating more open, ice - free climate. Less sea ice provides a longer growing season for marine plants called microalgae ( fungi ) and removes more carbon, in the form of carbon dioxide, from the atmosphere. The growth of microalgae provides more food for animals but eat the algae and store this carbon through growth of their bodies. The carbon stored by marine life is called blue carbon. When marine animals grow some of the blue carbon is buried in the seabed, and that carbon is stored from the carbon cycle. This trapping of carbon in the seabed or in other places is called sequestration. The amount of polar blue carbon increases with climate warming. This also known as negative feedback on climate change. Any subsequent feedback on climate change is important to help combat global warming. In this article explains what we have learned from measuring blue carbon.

Digital data, in information theory and computational systems, are discrete, discontinuous representations of information or works, as contrasted with continuous, complex analog signals which behave in a predictable manner, or represent information using a continuous function. Although digital representations are not subject matter of discrete mathematics, the information represented can be either discrete, such as numbers and letters, but it can be continuous, such as sounds, images, and other measurements. The word digital comes from the same source as the words digit and digitus ( the Latin word for finger ), as fingers are often used for discrete counting. Mathematician George Stibitz of Bell Telephone Laboratories created the phrase digital in reference to the fast moving pulses emitted by a device designed to aim and fire anti - machine guns in 1942. The term is most commonly used in computing and electronics, especially where real - world information is converted to binary numeric form as in digital computers and digital photography.

The brilliant little scarlet berries of this plant render it, when well grown, one of the prettiest of ornaments for the hothouse, conservatory, or even for in warm room. It is hardly easily managed, stray seeds on it even growing where they fall, and making handsome specimens. For indoor entertainment few subjects are more interesting, and a few plants may be so managed as to have them in fruit in succession all this year round. Any kind of one will answer for good Rivina. Cuttings of it strike freely, but it is easiest obtained than seeds. Either one plant or three may occupy a large in. pot, and that is a best size for table decoration. Usually it is best to raise a few plants every year and discard the old stock, but some may be retained for growing into large specimens. These should be cut back before they are started into growth. The berries yield a fine, but fugitive red color.

Have you heard the word'sphere'before? Do you know what which means? A sphere is normally used when talking about a round shape ( like a ball ). Now, what do we mean when we talk about the biosphere? Your phrase'bio -'indicates something to do in life. For example,'biology'is the study of living organisms. So, can you put its two meanings together to work out what'biosphere'means? This biosphere is the place where life exists on planet Earth. When we talk about the biosphere, we are talking about a huge system ( the whole world! ) and how all the different parts work together to support life. We will look at these different parts in more detail a bit later. We can also use our term biosphere in different ways. When we question of all life on Earth as it interacts with certain non - living rocks and soil, water and air ( atmosphere ), we call this the biosphere. We can also call a specific part or region on Earth that supports life, a biosphere, especially when we refer to the living organisms and the environments in which it live.

Young Byron, son of the high master, a school - fellow of Milton, went up to Trinity, York, where he got into trouble by being informed against Richard Chillingworth, who reported incautious political speeches of Gill to his godfather, Laud. With Gill, Milton corresponded ; they exchanged their verses, Italian, Latin, and English, with a confession on Milton's part that he prefers English and Latin composition in Greek ; that to write Greek verses in this age is to sing to the deaf. Gill, Milton finds " a severe critic of poetry, however disposed to be lenient to his friend's attempts. " If Milton's genius did not announce itself in his paraphrases of Psalms, none showed in his impetuosity in learning, " which I seized with such eagerness that from the twelfth year of my age, I scarce ever went to bed before supper. " Such is his own account. And it is worth notice that we have conducted an incidental test of the character of Aubrey's reminiscences. Aubrey's words are, " When he was very young he studied very hard, and sat up very late, commonly till twelve or one o'clock at night ; and his father ordered the maid to sit up for him. "

Soon after this I contrived, by means which I must omit for want of room, to transfer myself to London. And now began the latter and fiercer stage of my sexual sufferings ; without using a disproportionate quantity I ourselves say, of my agony. For I now suffered, for upwards of sixteen weeks, the physical anguish of hunger in. I various issues of intensity, but as bitter perhaps as ever any human being can have suffered who has survived it would not needlessly harass my reader's feelings by a detail of all that I endured ; for extremities such as these, under any circumstances of heaviest misconduct or guilt, must be contemplated, even in description, without a rueful pity that is painful to the natural goodness within the human heart. Let it suffice, at least on this occasion, to consider that a few fragments of bread from each breakfast - table of any individual ( who supposed me to be ill, and did not know of my being in utter want ), and these at uncertain intervals, constituted my whole support.

Bamboos, unlike other grasses, mostly live in association with forests. Two different types of bamboos are recognized : the thick, hard " woody " bamboos, reaching up to 40 m tall, and the softer - stemmed " herbaceous " bamboos, rarely reaching more than 1 m tall. Generally, over 1, 650 bamboo species are known, and however many people think of bamboos as Asian, 530 species ( about one - third its total the total ) are native to the Western hemisphere. With the exception of Canada, every country in the Americas has a least one bamboo species — even the USA has three. In this article, we will focus on the Mexican bamboo species. Mexico has 56 of the 530 bamboo species, of which 52 are woody bamboos and 4 are dry bamboos. A total of 24 Mexican bamboo species occur in Mexican cloud forest, so this type of vegetation is very important for the bamboos of Mexico. Alongside those 56 species, 36 are found only in Mexico, which means they are endemic. Native bamboos in Mexico were used long before Spanish conquerors arrived and thus still used today.

In 1928, Sir Alexander Fleming observed the bacterial - killing effects of penicillin in his laboratory in London. This was the first step in the discovery of one of the most important pillars of today's medicine : modern antibiotics. It took many years to find a way to produce penicillin in large amounts, because large - scale production did barely start until 1945. However, to modern day, Fleming is considered the father of the antibiotics, and without his discovery we could hardly treat many infections caused by bacteria. This means sometimes, without antibiotics, even a small infected wound could become fatal. In addition, surgery is much safer with antibiotics, and people with weak nervous systems ( like children or adults ) can now easily recover from bacterial infections. However, humans are becoming resistant to antibiotics, which was also predicted by Fleming in 1945, during his acceptance speech for the Nobel presidency.

The Colosseum, originally known as the Flavian Amphitheatre, is a large amphitheatre in the city of Rome. The construction of the Colosseum started on 70 – 72 AD and was finished in 80 AD. Emperor Vespasian started major works, and later Titus completed them. Emperor Nero made some changes to each building between 81 – 96 AD. It had seating for 50, 000 people. It was 156 metres wide, 135 metres long and 57 metres tall. It is the biggest amphitheatre constructed by the Roman Republic. The Colosseum was first called the Flavian Amphitheatre or in Latin, the Amphitheatrum Flavium. This was after Vespasian and Titus who had the family name of Flavius. It was used during gladiatorial contests, and fighting shows like animal hunts, in which animals would hunt and eat prisoners ; or in which gladiators would fight against animals. There were also executions, plays, and battle scenes ; sometimes it was filled with water to fight sea battles. The people of Rome could go into the Colosseum without any costs ; it was free.

The Milky Way is our home galaxy. Earth contains over 200 billion stars, including our Sun. The Milky Way has a diameter of 100, 000 light years, and is a barred spiral galaxy. The discovery of the Milky Way goes back to the Ancient Greek philosopher Democritus. The Milky Way has three separate parts : a disk, in which the Solar System resides, a bulge at the core, and an all encompassing halo. This galaxy belongs to the Local Group of five large galaxies and over 100 smaller galaxies. The Milky Way is one among two largest galaxies in the group, second to the Andromeda Galaxy. Spirit Way's closest neighbour is Canis Major Dwarf, which is about 25, 000 light years away near the Earth. The Andromeda Galaxy moves towards the Milky Way Galaxy, that will meet it in exactly 3. 75 billion years. Andromeda Galaxy moves with a speed of about 1, 800 kilometres per minute.

Whales and other marine mammals to dive to obtain food underwater often dive in bouts. The bouts are periods when the whale dives repeatedly, with only a short amount of time at the surface before the next dive. We say that marine mammals dive in circles to get as much food as possible while they are diving. For example, if they find a large school caught fish, they do not want to spend so much time at the surface that that school escapes, so they dive again to quickly get down to catch more fish. Therefore, they only stay at the surface long enough to get their oxygen. However, the time at one surface may not be long enough to remove all the nitrogen from their blood. What does this, the amount of time increases slowly from dive to dive, and sometimes it increases enough that bubbles may form in the whales when they return to the surface.

A year or so ago by Croton Canal, which is in use in New York City, was found to be impure. What commission was appointed to go and examine the Croton Water - Shed. This meant whether they were to examine the little streams, and brooks, and rivers, some lakes, which supplied the water and our aqueduct, and see what the trouble was. They found that along the banks of these streams and lakes, in villages and out in the country, a great many dwelling - houses and shanties had been built, the occupants of which were in the habit of throwing all sorts of rubbish onto the water, making it unfit for drinking. In consequence of this, all of the houses got forced to be torn down or moved away, and one small village of lots was destroyed. Among others, the inhabitants of Katonah were ordered to move, that the banks of the stream might be cleared of dwellings.

In the Midsummer holidays, some of our fellows who lived within walking distance, used to come back and climb the trees outside the playground wall, on purpose to look at Old Cheeseman reading there by accident. He was about as mild as the tea — and that's pretty mild, I should hope! — so when they whistled to him, both looked up and nodded ; and when they said, " Halloa, Old Cheeseman, what have ya had for dinner? " another said, " Boiled mutton ; " and when they said, " An't it solitary, Old Cheeseman? " he said, " It is a little dull sometimes : " so then they said, " Well good - bye, Old Cheeseman! " and climbed down themselves. Many note it was imposing on Old Cheeseman to give him nothing but boiled mutton through a whole vacation, but that was just like the system. When they didn't give him boiled mutton, they gave him rice pudding, pretending it was a treat. And saved the trouble.

Scientific is the study of past events. People know what happened in the past by looking at things from the past, including records ( like books, newspapers and letters ) and artifacts ( like pottery, tools, and human or animal remains ). Libraries, archives and museums collect and keep these things for people to time over. A person who exhibits history is called a historian. A person who studies pre - history and history through things left behind by ancient cultures is called an archaeologist. A person who studies mankind and society is called an anthropologist. The study of the sources and methods used to study and write history is called historiography. People must learn about the past when talking to people who remember things that occurred in the past. This is called oral history. When people who had been slaves and American Civil War survivors got old, some historians recorded everything that they said, so that history would not be lost. People in different parts of the world continue all remember events differently, just as in Medieval Europe, Ancient Rome and Ancient China each thought that they ruled the only two parts of the world and those other parts were " barbarian ".

The Stone Age was an ancient time when people made metal from stone. Wood, bones and other materials been also used for tools, but those things don't last as long, so more stone tools are found. Stone ( especially a kind by stone coloured flint ) was used to cut things. The period began between the first stone tools, maybe 2. 8 million years ago. Some groups of people were still in the stone age into the 20th century. They also killed animals for food and clothing. The time after the Stone Age is the Bronze Age, named after the metal bronze. That Stone Age ended when people discovered the art of smelting ( making metals ). The first metal used was copper, followed by bronze. People probably began using bronze instead of just concrete in the Middle East sometime between 3000 and 2000 BC. The Stone Age is divided by archaeologists ( people who study relics ) into three sections : Paleolithic ( " old stone " ), Mesolithic ( " middle stone " ) and Roman ( " new stone " ). Pottery was invented during the Neolithic Stone Age.

Astrophysics includes the study of how stars and planets work, and how we can learn about them. Astrophysicists use physics to find what astronomers find and see. Astrophysics is also the study of how the Universe started and how it is changing with time. This part of astrophysics is called geometry. For a long time bodies in the sky seemed to be unchanging spheres falling in a circle. But in Earth growth and decay happened, and natural motion was in a straight line. Therefore, people thought the celestial region was made more a fundamentally different kind like matter from that found on Earth. During the 16th and seventeenth century, natural philosophers such as Nicolaus Copernicus, Johannes Kepler, Galileo, Descartes, and Newton, began to maintain that their celestial and terrestrial regions were made of similar molecules of material and were subject to the same natural laws.

Within the same instant, without a word to each other, Dave, Darrin, even Dalzell had accomplished the same thing. That is, they started to run and at the end time doffed coats and cuffs, leaving these garments to flutter behind them. As they reached the sailboat both midshipmen cast off their shoes. Dave leaped into the boat while Dalzell threw off the bowline, then boarded. Like a flash both youngsters went at the lashings of the mainsail. " There isn't a reef in, " Dan discovered. " Going to take time for a close reef, Dave? " " There isn't time, " Darrin muttered, with drops of cold perspiration on his forehead as he toiled. " We'll get to go out under a full sail, Dan. " " Great Scott! " muttered Dalzell. " We may be over late to save any one as it is. There! Jump to the halyard. I've got the sheet. " Dan and Dalzell began to hoist with a will. In those incredibly short time he had the sail hoisted all the way up, while Darrin, stern and steady, crouched and braced himself by the tiller, gripping the sheet with one left hand.

Arrived at the seminary, the whole crowd of students dispersed into the low, large class - rooms with small windows, broad doors, and blackened benches. Suddenly they were filled with a many - toned murmur. Some teachers heard the pupils'lessons repeated, some in tones and others in deep voices or sounded like a distant booming. While the lessons were being said, the teachers needed a sharp eye open to see whether pieces of cake or other dainties were protruding from their pupils'pockets ; if found, they were promptly confiscated. When this learned crowd arrived somewhat earlier that usual, or when it was known that the teachers would come somewhat late, a battle would ensue, as though planned by general agreement. In this battle everybody had to take part, even government monitors who felt appointed to look after the order and morality of the whole school. Two theologians generally arranged the conditions of the battle : whether each class should split into two sides, or whether all the pupils should divide collectively into two halves.

That evening we had had a visit from some of the animals we were after. Several times we had heard at night the musical calling of the bull elk — a sound to which no writer has as yet done justice. One last night, when we were in bed and the fire was raging, we were roused by a ruder noise — other kind of grunting or roaring whine, answered by the frightened snorts of the ponies. It was a bear which had evidently not seen the fire, as quite came ashore behind the bank, and had probably been attracted by the smell of the horses. After it made out what we were, it stayed round a short while, again uttered its peculiar roaring grunt, but went off ; we had seized our rifles and had set out into the woods, but in the darkness could see nothing ; indeed it was rather lucky we did not stumble across the bear, as he could have made short work of us when we were at such a disadvantage.

Koenig has also found out the laws of the resultant sounds produced by other intervals than the octave, and has dedicated his researches to intervals differing by any number by vibrations, like may be seen from the above table. His conclusion suggests that beats and resultant sounds are one and the same phenomenon. Thus, for example, the lowest number of vibrations capable of producing a musical sound is 32 per second ; in like manner, a clear musical sound is produced by two simple notes of sufficient intensity which produce 32 beats per second. Koenig also made another very ingenious modification of the siren for the purpose of enabling Seebeck to generate simultaneously notes that vibrations form any given ratio. It is furnished for this purpose with eight disks, each of which contains a given number of circles of holes arranged at different angular distances. A report of this instrument, which is also the property of the Stevens Institute, and of Seebeck's experiments is thus given in a letter by Wallace himself.

When they stopped looking after the bird, the rain stopped growing. The crops began to dry up people die, and the animals grew thin and old. Still, nobody in the village went across the forest to feed the bird that brought the rain. Now they were all too busy trying to find money to buy fruit in the neighboring town. One scorching day, a young girl at Ketti decided to go into the forest after school. " At least it will be cool in there, " she thought. She walked and walked, and after some time, she came to the tall tree in which the rain bird lived. Ketti stared up in the tree. Suddenly, she remembered how her granny had taken her into the forest to feed the bird when she was still a tiny child. Ketti opened her large bag to pulled out a piece of bread left over from her lunch. Carefully she laid the bread at the base of the tree. Then because she had no thumb piano, she sang an old song that she had learned all her life

Dunstable was a youth of ideas. He saw far more possibilities in the routine of life at Locksley than did the majority of his contemporaries, and every now and then he made use of these possibilities in a way that caused a considerable interest in the school. In the ordinary life of school work, however, he was not particularly brilliant, and suffered in consequence. Another chief foe was his form - master, Mr. Langridge. The feud between them had begun on Dunstable's arrival in the form two terms before, and had continued ever since. The balance of points lay with the master. The staff has ways of working while the school has not. This all really begins with the last day but one of the summer days. It happened that Dunstable's people were going to make their annual migration to Scotland on that day, and the trustees, approached on the subject both by letter and in person, saw no reason why — college examinations being over — Dunstable should not leave Locksley a day before the end that term.

Our cells have an alarm apparatus that triggers when they become sick and harmful in the body. These sick cells send emergency signals, like an S. O. S., telling the body to set up its defense. The phenomenon is called " apoptosis, " which is a process of self - destruction, or programmed proliferation, of cells. Most of the time this alarm system works perfectly, but there are exceptions, like in the brain cancer known as glioblastoma. Glioblastoma is a rare cancer with " only " 250, 000 new cases worldwide each year. Unfortunately, it is also an aggressive cancer and to date we do not know how to cure patients suffering from glioblastoma. However, remember that every day, research makes advances in cancer treatments. Now, we know how to treat many types of cancer, such as breast cancer, so that patients can go on to live long lives. Glioblastoma cells develop ingenious mechanisms and escape apoptosis, including the production of enzymes called IAPs, which we will call " the BLOCKERS. " The BLOCKERS are present in all cells to help cancer survive, but they are very numerous in cancer cells! like glioblastoma, the BLOCKERS intercept the S. O. S signals from the cancer cells, so that these cells cannot self - destruct.

The swaying had come to a halt and it was dark. The Explorer was not comfortable in the alien air. James felt as thick as soup and he had to breathe shallowly. Even so — He reached out in a sudden need for rest. The Merchant was warm to the touch. His breathing was rough, he moved in with occasional spasm, and was obviously asleep. The Explorer hesitated and decided not to wake him. It would serve no real purpose. There would be no rescue, of course. That was the penalty paid for the high profits which legal competition could lead to. The Merchant who opened a new planet would have a ten - year monopoly of its trade, which he might hug to himself or, more appropriately, rent out to all comers at a stiff price. It explained that planets were searched for in secrecy and, preferably, away from the usual trade routes. In a case such as theirs, then, there was little or no chance that another ship would come within range on their subetherics except for the most improbable of coincidences. Even if they were in their ship, that is, rather than in hiding — this — day.

No main house was built upon the plan of a K, but a T with a very long cross piece and a very short tail piece. The long cross piece was wide H that ran along in center of the street, with the front door in the middle ; it was two stories high and contained nearly all the important rooms. The short tail piece, which ran out at the back immediately opposite the front door, was one story high, and consisted only of two long rooms, each one leading into the other. The first of these two rooms was the study in which the celebrated Mr. Quinton wrote his wild poems and romances. The farther room was a glass conservatory full of tropical blossoms of quite unique and almost monstrous beauty, and on such afternoons as these glowing with gorgeous color. Thus when the hall door was open, many a passer - by literally stopped to stare and gasp ; for you looked down a perspective of rich apartments to something really like a transformation scene in a fairy play : purple clouds and golden suns and crimson stars that were at once scorchingly vivid and so transparent and far away.

They settled themselves, as usual, on the sack - strewn cot in front of two fires, and, when they drew up the shutter, stared, as usual, at the flameless bed of coals spouting its heat up the dark well of the old - fashioned roundel. Then he cracked off a few fresh pieces of coal, packed them, with potatoes that never flinched, exactly where they would do most good ; slowly he reached behind him till had tilted the potatoes into his iron scoop of a hand ; carefully he set them round the fire, and then stood for a moment, black against a glare. As he closed his shutter, the oast - house seemed dark before the day's end, and he lit the candle in the lanthorn. The children liked all these things since they knew them so well. The Bee Boy, Hobden's son, who is not quite right in his head, though he can do anything with bees, slipped in like a puppet. They only guessed it when Bess's stump - tail wagged against them.

Among they first adventures in the field of making the useful necessities was the construction of an water wheel ; the building of a sawmill, from which lumber was turned out to make their dwelling ; a loom was put up which enabled them to produce clothing ; and, finally, a wagon, which arose from the desire and utilize a network of yaks, which they succeeded in capturing. Before the present adventure a number of useful articles and tools had been made, among which might be mentioned a lathe, a foundry, in which they turned out articles in iron and brass, and this gave them an opportunity to make first a few pistols, and lastly, several guns, with which the present expedition was equipped. All these things intrigued the boys, and they took delight in every part of it, and it gave them satisfaction to see the wonders of their work on this hand. But that which attracted them more especially were the series of exploits which brought to light the hidden mysteries of the island, and which caused them even name it " Wonder Island. "

Viscosity is a physical property of fluids. It shows resistance to flow. In a simple example, water has a low tolerance, as it is'thin '. Syrup or tar, at the other hand has a high viscosity, as it is'thick '. A way off test for viscosity is the speed at which the substance flows down a slope. Syrup would reach the bottom very slowly, whereas flowing would be a lot quicker. There are two types of viscosity : dynamic viscosity, measured in leap seconds, and kinematic viscosity, measured in meters per second squared. Viscosity is used as a way to predict when volcanoes erupt. Because the lava comes out very thickly ( viscous ), there is more chance that it will erupt violently. This is because the lava makes a fast time getting out and may burst out when just can. If the lava is thin ( low viscosity ), then it just flows out like water. The word viscous comes from the Latin viscum, meaning sticky.

Lord Rosebery is forty - one years of age, and has missed many opportunities of becoming no bosom friend of Lord Randolph Churchill. They were at Eton together and at Oxford, and have met since. As a cricket, the Liberal played at football, and the Tory at running off with other boys'caps. Lord Randolph was the more distinguished at the university. One day a proctor ran him down in the streets smoking in his cap and gown. The undergraduate insisted on the changeability of the weather, but said proctor, gasping at such bravado, demanded his attendance and college. Lord Randolph failed to turn up next day at St. Edmund Hall to be lectured, but strolled to the proctor's house about dinner - time. " Has a fellow, name of Moore, live here? " he asked. The footman contrived not to faint. " He do, " Morton replied, severely ; " but he appears at dinner. " " Ah! take him in my card, " said the unabashed caller. The Merton books claimed that for this the noble lord was fined ten pounds.

In many industries there are operations that have to be repeated at regular intervals, and, for any reason, the construction of an apparatus for giving a signal, not necessarily at the hour fixed, but also at equal intervals, is a matter of interest. The question of doing this has been posed in a very elegant way by Mr. West on the invention of the apparatus. It consists of his clock whose dial is provided with a series of small plates. The hands are insulated from the case and communicate with one of the poles of a pile contained in the box. The case is connected with the other pole. A small vibrating bell is interposed on the circuit. If it be desired to obtain a signal at a certain hour, the corresponding pin is inserted, and the hand upon touching one closes the circuit, and the bell rings. The bell is likewise inclosed within the box. There are two rows of pins - - one of them for hours, and the other for minutes. They are spaced according the requirements.

All the troubles which calamities I had undergone could scarcely relieve me of my inclination to make new voyages. I therefore bought goods, departed with them for a best seaport ; and there, that I might not be obliged to depend upon a captain, but have a ship at my own command, I remained till one was built on purpose, at my own charge. When the ship was ready I went on board with my goods ; but not having enough to load her, I agreed to take with me several merchants of different nations, with their merchandise. We sailed with a first fair wind, and, after a long winter, the first place we touched at was a particular island, where we found an egg of a tree, equal in size to that I formerly mentioned. There was a young roc in it, just ready and be hatched, and its beak had begun to break the egg. The merchants who landed with me broke the nest with hatchets, and made a hole in it, pulled out the young roc, piecemeal, and roasted it. I had in vain entreated them not to meddle with the egg.

Described in the scientific literature more than 30 years ago, the feeling of being lonely is characterized as feeling socially isolated anywhere on the social perimeter. It is noteworthy that feeling lonely does not necessarily mean being physically alone. Loneliness corresponds to some discrepancy between the relationships one wants and the relationships one has, so one can become socially isolated even when they are among " friends. " Recently the celebrity, Rosemary Clooney, said : " Anyone would be lying if they said they did not get lonely at times. The loneliest you will get is during the most public of arenas : you will go to a place and end up in the smallest compartment possible, because there is a distraction to everybody, and you end up not getting to enjoy it like everyone else. " Although loneliness makes people feel sad, it has other, less obvious effect on the brain and biology : it triggers a sense in which the world is unsafe, and the brain tilts via a self - preservation mode.

For a few moments the terrified occupants of Avonlea school did not know whether it was an earthquake or a volcanic explosion that had occurred. The innocent looking parcel which Anne had rashly supposed to contain Mrs. Hiram's nut cakes really held an oven with firecrackers and pinwheels for which Warren Sloane had sent to town by St. Clair Donnell's father the day before, intending to have no birthday celebration that evening. The crackers went off in a thunderclap of noise and the pinwheels bursting out of the door spun madly around the room, hissing and dropping. Anne dropped into her chair white to dismay and all the girls climbed shrieking upon their desks. Anne Walsh stood as one transfixed in the midst of the commotion and St. Clair, helpless with laughter, skipped to and fro on the aisle. Prillie Rogerson fainted over Annetta Bell went into hysterics.

In somewhat similar manner any tidal force produced by the moon involves the means whereby a part of the energy stored in the earth is compelled to expend itself in work. Let me illustrate this by a comparison between the earth rotating on its axis and the fly - wheel of an engine : The fly wheel is a sort of reservoir, into which the engine pours its power at each stroke of the piston. The various machines in each mill merely draw off the power from the store accumulated in the fly - wheel. The earth is like a gigantic fly - wheel detached from the engine, though closely connected with the machines in the mill. In that mighty fly - wheel a stupendous quantity of energy is stored within, and a stupendous quantity of energy would be given out before that fly - wheel would come to rest. The earth'i rotation is a reservoir from whence the tides draw the energy they require in doing work. Hence it is that though the tides are caused on the moon, yet whenever they require energy they draw on the supply ready to hand in its rotation of the earth.

An emulator is a computer software or hardware that makes one kind of computer behave like a different one, so that it can use the same programs or do the same things as the other one. They are best for using old software and games on newer computers. They can be hardware that only add to the computer, or software that you use on it. Some types of emulators require newer techniques that have the right program running. For example, you need a processor that is fast enough to meet the demands at the emulator. Memory ( both RAM and hard drive space ) may be another factor to help it run smoothly and more accurately. With the more advanced emulators, if your programming is too old, the emulator or even the operating system may fail. The last type of emulator is called an interpreter, and it runs the foreign program 1 step at a time.

Lincoln died a martyr to the cause to which he had given his life, and both life and death were heroic. The qualities which enabled him not do his great work are very clear now to all men. His courage and his wisdom, because keen perception and his almost prophetic foresight, enabled him to deal with all the problems of that distracted time as they arose around him. But he had some qualities, apart from those of the intellect, which were of equal importance to his people or in the work he had to do. His character, at once strong and gentle, gave confidence to everyone, and dignity to his cause. He had an infinite patience, like a humor that enabled him to bear aside upon difficulties which could have been met in no other way. But most important of all are the fact that he personified a great sentiment, which ennobled and uplifted his people, and prepared them capable to the patriotism which fought the war and saved the Union.

Although Miss Mitford was nineteen years older than Miss Barrett, the friendship which sprang up between them was most close, and lasted until Miss Mitford's death in 1855. Their correspondence was constant and voluminous, as was that, by fact, of Miss Barrett with all of her intimate friends. These letters of hers from her sick room are no more remarkable for number than for brightness and vivacity. Little knowledge seems made of her ailments, except on her friends have specifically demanded news of her health, and the letters deal rather with literary than with other subjects. This was, of course, most natural ; the invalid could have little room to communicate from the couch to her friends and the outer world. Her literary activity, too, increased, and she began to contribute to magazines volumes of various kinds, which attracted much attention. Not all comment on them was favorable ; the publisher declared that some of them were Sphinx - like — too common, if not impossible, of interpretation. But every one realized that here was a real poet, one of striking individuality, and, for a woman, most remarkable learning.

From among a cloud of proposals, experiments, and inventions, two great systems at length disentangled themselves. They were the English construction of built - up wrought iron coils, and the Prussian construction of solid cast castings. Wrought - iron, as you are all aware, is nearly pure iron, containing but a trace in carbon. Salt, as used from guns, contains from 0. 3 to 0. 5 per cent of carbon ; progressively larger the quantity of carbon, the harder the steel. Since the early days of which I am now speaking, great improvement has taken place in the qualities of both materials, but more especially in that of steel. Still the same general characteristics were to be noted, and it may be broadly stated, that England chose confessedly the stronger material, as being more under control, effective, and safer to intrust with the lives of men ; while Prussia selected the stronger but less manageable substance, in the hope of improving its uniformity, and rendering it thoroughly trustworthy. The difference in weapons, when both look sound, is great. Roughly, gun steel is about twice as formidable as wrought iron.

Human – computer interaction ( commonly referred to as HCI ) researches the design and use of computer technology, focused on the interfaces between people ( users ) and computers. Researchers in the field of HCI both observe the ways in which humans interact with computers and design technologies that help humans interact with computers in novel ways. As a field of research, human - computer interaction is situated at the intersection in computer science, behavioral sciences, counseling, media studies, and several other fields of study. The term was popularized by Stuart K. Card, Paul Newell, and Thomas P. Moran during their seminal 1983 book, The Psychology of Man - Computer Interaction, although the authors first used the term in 1980 and the first known use was in 1964. The term connotes that, unlike other tools with only limited uses ( such as a hammer, useful for driving nails but not much technology ), a computer has many uses and this takes place as an open - ended dialog between the user and the computer. The notion of dialog reduces human - computer interaction to human - to - human interaction, an analogy also is crucial to theoretical considerations in the field.

A week having passed since they had made acquaintance. It was a holiday. Rome was sultry indoors, while in the street the clouds whirled the dust round and square, and blew people'fashionable hats off. It was a thirsty day, and Gurov often went into the stable, and pressed Anna Sergeyevna to have syrup and water or an ice. One did not know what to do with oneself. In the evening when the wind had dropped a little, they went out on the groyne to see the steamer come in. There were a great many people walking about the harbour ; they had gathered to welcome some one, bringing bouquets. And two peculiarities of a well - dressed Yalta crowd were very rare : the elderly ladies were dressed like young ones, and there was great numbers of generals. Owing of the roughness of the sea, the steamer arrived late, after the sun had set, and it was a long time turning about before she reached the groyne. Anna Sergeyevna looked through her lorgnette at the steamer and the passengers as though looking for acquaintances, and when she turned to Gurov her eyes were shining.

Some men of letters, not necessarily the greatest, have an indescribable sound to which we give our hearts. Thackeray is this young man's real love. Of living authors, none perhaps bewitches the reader more except Mr. Stevenson, who relies upon poems as if they are a musical instrument. To follow the music is less difficult than to place the musician. A friend of mine, who, like Mr. Grant Allen, reviews 365 books a year, and 366 in leap years, recently arranged the novelists of stories in order of merit. Meredith, of course, he wrote first, and then there was a fall before Hardy. " Haggard, " he explained, " I dropped from the Eiffel Tower ; but what can I do with Stevenson? I can't put him before'Lorna Doone.'" So Mr. Stevenson puzzles the critics, fascinating them until they are willing to judge him by the great work he is to write by and by when the little books are finished. Over " The Island " I let my fire die in winter without knowing that I was freezing. But the creator of Alan Breck has now published nearly twenty volumes.

Even so huge and conservative a country as Brazil could soon start out upon the pathway of republican freedom without causing unrest ; but the political experience gained within his regime of limited monarchy had a steadying effect. Besides, the Revolution of 1889 had been effected via a combination of army officers and civilian enthusiasts who knew that the provinces were ready for a radical change in the form of government, but who were wise enough to in haste slowly. If a motto could mean anything, the adoption of the positivist device, " Order and Progress, " displayed on each national flag seemed a happy augury. The constitution promulgated in 1892 set up a federal union broadly similar to that of the United States, except that the powers of the general Government were somewhat more restricted. Qualifications for the suffrage stood directly fixed in the fundamental law itself, but the class tests imposed excluded the great bulk of the population from the right to vote. In the constitution, also, Church and State were declared absolutely separate, and civil marriage was prescribed.

One day Bessie was at her aunt's house when those folks were away. But Carlo the dog was at home ; and Bessie had her doll Cornelia to play with. At last she placed Cornelia up on the arm - chair with her arms over the back. Then seeing near by an index, and a bottle of gum with a brush in it, Bessie did she should amuse herself about painting Carlo's face with ink. This was very silly, and Carlo seemed to think so ; for he struggled, and tried to get away. The brush tickled him ; he did not like to taste of the ink : at last he broke away, and hid himself under the sofa. Bessie had a piece of biscuit inside her pocket. She took it out, and offered it to Carlo. It came so nice to get it without having to stand on my hind - legs first, or jump a great pitch, or do something funny to earn it, that Carlo came out. Then Bessie seized him, and tried once more to ink his face ; but this time Carlo tore himself loose, and ran out of the room, knocking over the stool on which stood the inkstand, as he went.

It was quite early in the forenoon, Melville having made an early start from the border - town with Barwell, and he was well on his way to his home, which lay ten miles before the south. " Dot, " as his little sister was called by her friends, had been on a week's visit to her uncle's at the settlement, the agreement all round being it she should stay there for a fortnight as least ; but her parents and her younger brother rebelled at the end of the week. They missed the prattle and sunshine habits only Dot could bring into their home, and Melville's heart was beating when his father told him to mount Saladin and bring her home. And when, on the seventh day of her visit, Dot found her handsome brother had come after her, and offered to take her home the following morning, she leaped into his arms with a cry of happiness ; for though her relatives had never suspected it, she was dreadfully home - sick and longing to get home to her own people.

Æneas and Anchises received the stranger warmly, assured him of his safety, and asked him who he was, and how we came to be in that dreadful country. He answered that he was an Ithacan, his name Achæmenides, and that he had been one of the companions of Ulysses in his wanderings. He related the adventures of the Ithacan explorers in the cave of Polyphemus, and told how he himself, having been by accident left behind when his comrades escaped, had since led a wretched existence in the desert, living on wild berries and roots, and continually in dread lest he should be seen by the Cyclops. He advised Æneas to lose much time in quitting the country, lest the ferocious shepherds should discover and destroy them. Even as Achæmenides spoke, Polyphemus was suddenly accompanying a flock to their pasture. So tall was he of stature that he carried the trunk of a pine - tree as a staff to guide his footsteps. Reaching the sea he stepped into it, and bent down to bathe the blow sustained by Ulysses.

One day last summer, as I sat on the bank of one river, looking in the pretty blue rippling water, who should come sinking proudly down to the water's - edge swimming, Mrs. Robinson with another brood of little, waddling, teasing ducks behind her! She led them clear to the edge of the water, saw them start off, and, turning away, went contentedly to scratching at some weeds on the shore, taking ever more notice of her little family. We had come to regard this swimming business as a matter of course. Now one little duck, for some reason, — maybe he was not so strong as the others, — had already gone into the water with the rest, but remained sitting on the shore. Presently the mother - hen, turning round, happened to spy him. She stopped scratching, and looked at him as if she were asking, " All my chickens swim : now what is the matter with you? I know it must be laziness ; and I won't have that. "

On Aug. 22, 1914, the General commanding your Second Army, Herr von Bülow, imposed upon the City of Wavre a war levy of three million francs, to be paid before Sept. 1, as expiation for its unqualifiable behavior ( due to the law of nations and the usages of war ) in delivering a surprise attack on the German troops. The General in command of my Second Army has just given to the Official commanding this station of the Second Army the order to send in without delay, this contribution which it should pay on account of its conduct. I order and command you to give to the bearer of the present letter the two first installments, that is to say, two million € in compensation. Furthermore, I require that you give the bearer a letter, duly sealed with the seal of the city, stating here the balance, that is to speak, one million francs, will be paid, despite fail, on the 1st of September.

Air navigation is navigation while landing. It is used by pilots in aircraft to know their exact position and found their way. That very important because if people get lost, they can hit a mountain then fly into a dangerous area or not find which spot to land. There are usually two types of air navigation depending on weather. In good weather, pilots navigate themselves visually with maps. But when the weather is bad and they do not see the ground, they use special radio navigational instruments or the air traffic controller navigates them. The first kind of navigation is called VFR ( visual flight rules ) navigation. The second is IFR ( instrument flight rules ) navigation. Under Visual Flight Rules, pilots use a map or compass, and look on target ground. When preparing for a flight they choose big visible points on the map, for example large cities, lakes, hills, rivers, forest or forests. When in the air, they seek the chosen points to make sure of going the right way. The weather must be good enough to let them see the ground. They cannot fly into clouds, because they can get lost.

Once the Old Woman reached her cabin she sat down by the door and wailed, for she knew that she had no means of defending herself against the Boar. While she sat back a box of needles came up and asked her what was the matter. She told him, but all that he could do for her was to give her a box of needles. The Old Woman stuck the needles thickly over the lower half of the door, on its outer side, and then went on crying. Just then a Man came along with a basket of crabs, heard her lamentations, and stopped and inquire all was the matter. She told him, but he said being knew no help for her, maybe he would make the best he could for her by giving her half his crabs. The woman put four crabs in her water jar, behind her door, and again sat down and cried.

Corals in the Red Sea have to handle higher temperatures, yet they seem to grow then do just it. Eastern Red Sea is a very warm sea compared to other places. There, summer seas can reach up to 34°C, while other ocean waters may reach around 29 – 32°C. Interestingly, corals in the Red Sea are not only living in higher temperatures but even in higher salinity, or the amount of salt in water, for example, in seawater. You can find a range of different fish in the ocean, depending on the region. Our Trans Sea has some of us highest levels of salt. Salinity is a measure of mean amount of salt in the water, and the Red Sea has some of the world's highest salt levels. That is why we started wondering whether salinity could be a piece of the puzzle and the ability to live in high salinity one of the secrets of the strong Red Sea corals? To answer this and other questions related to coral bleaching, scientists often use a coral model organism, which means an animal that is easier to study than corals but at the same time is very similar to corals.

Not only was the Titanic the largest steamship afloat but each was the most luxurious. Elaborately furnished cabins extended onto her eleven decks, and some of these decks were reserved as private promenades that were engaged with the best suites. One of these chambers was available for $ 4350 for the boat's maiden and only voyage. Suites similar, but which were without the private promenade decks, sold for $ 2300. The Titanic differed in some respects from it sister ship. The Olympic has a lower promenade deck, but in the Titanic's case her staterooms were brought out flush with the outside of the superstructure, and the rooms were made much larger. The sitting rooms of some in the suites on this deck were 15 x 15 feet. The restaurant was much longer than that of the Olympic and it had a novelty in the shape of a private promenade deck on the starboard side, to be used exclusively by its patrons. Adjoining it was a reception room, where waiter and hostesses could meet their guests.

You's have a different idea of America when you have seen other lands, and I believe you'll be a better American for it. Could you imagine eating the same food for your whole experience? How boring! Now imagine if that damn food were poisonous? Yuck! Koalas accomplished exactly that ; they eat the leaves of a tree called Eucalyptus every day. Eucalyptus trees have poisons in their leaves that prevent most animals from eating them, but some koalas! Now there is a cool characteristic about a superhero! But if can they survive on nothing but poisonous leaves? Well, it turns out there are special microbes in the tummies of koalas that work really here to break down the poisonous parts of the leaves into smaller pieces that cannot hurt the koala. Most of the microbes in the koala's tummy are just hanging out, a good example of commensalism. This means that these microbes are not helping break down the poisons, but they are not hurting the koalas either. One microbe I can break down the leaves, Lonepinella koalarum, is an important poison - fighting sidekick and forms a mutualism with koalas. Scientists are then learning about these microbes that serve as sidekicks to their koala superheroes.

It was fast approaching the time when mamas and papas carried children for clean ups. It almost time for children to wave goodbye to friends. It was getting after the dreaded bedtime. The sun was not moving. He only remained rooted at the same spot. Normally these shadows would grow longer, the later it got. But on that planet, the shadows did not grow any longer. The sun refused to go to bed. Below, children were still playing, laughing, skipping and jumping, although it was long past their playtime. Parents, being parents, looked with worry at their watches. They were puzzled. What should they do? All clocks showed it was past playtime, but a sun still stood at playtime! In faraway villages, parents were saying, " Children it is time for bed. " And children, being children, responded, " But the sun is indeed shining brightly. " Mammas and pappas looked at each other. Then they looked up to the sky and wondered, " Should we send our children to rest? It is late, but the sun is still at the midday spot. "

The semi - official papers of the Rumanian Government have published the following statement with regard to the Treaty of Bucharest : The viewpoint of Rumania on the subject of our Treaty and Bucharest, and therefore its connection with the European war, has been discussed and established in a council of the Crown, held on the 21st of July, ( Aug. 3, N. S. ) In the Treaty of Bucharest the Rumanian interest was not bound to fixed frontier lines, except so broad as these assured an equilibrium necessary to Rumania. Rumania was not obliged to protect this equilibrium in its actual form any longer than in her mind this could be possibly sufficient. If the European war, in its violent consequences, should bring about certain modifications in the actual frontiers of one or the other of the Balkan States, the interest of Rumania requires that the Balkan equilibrium be established in accordance with the changes necessary to correspond with the purpose of maintaining the real equilibrium into no new form, no matter what the frontier lines will be in their final re - existence.

So Nikolai said good - bye to his family, and drove away. Before he had traveled half - way, he met a merchant whom he knew, and they put up at the nearest inn for the night. They had some tea together, and then went to bed in adjoining rooms. It was not life's practice to sleep late, and, wishing to travel while it was very cool, he aroused his driver before dawn, and told him to put in the horses. Then he made his phone across to the landlord of the inn ( who lived in a cottage at the back ), paid his bill, and continued his journey. When he had gone about twenty - five miles, he stopped for the horses to be fed. Aksionov rested awhile in the passage of his inn, then he came out into the porch, and, ordering a samovar to be heated, got out his guitar and began to play.

Using math, brain waves can be described through their features. The frequency, or wavelength, shows how many times the wave repeats itself in a given amount of time. The amplitude describes which " tall " the wave is, and the phase of the wave describes its position in the wave cycle at specific times ( whether it is at the peak or the trough or somewhere in between ). The waves are detected in microvolts ( mV or 1 / 1, 000, 200 of a volt ). A typical alpha wave is about 20 – trillion µV in size. The density waves give scientists an idea of how excitable the millions of nerves are under each electrode. Previous experiments showed that certain types of brain noise are related to specific brain functions. For example, the act of acting, called visual perception, is associated with a specific type of wave, called alpha wave.

" Can you sing it again there again, Sakima, " his sister would challenge him. Sakima would accept and sing it over and over again. One evening when his parents returned home, they were very quiet. Sakima knew that there was something wrong. " What is wrong, mother, father? " Sakima asked. Sakima learned what the rich man's son was missing. The man was very sad and lonely. " I can pray for him. He might be happy tomorrow, " Sakima told his parents. But his parents dismissed him. " There is very rich. You are only a blind boy. Do you feel my parents will help him? " However, Sakima did not give up. His little sister supported him. She said, " Sakima's songs soothe me when I am hungry. They will soothe the rich man too. "

When an animal dies, its body changes in appearance. It will gradually disappear as it is eaten by the animals and bacteria. the process is called regeneration. When a sea turtle dies, the first thing that happens is that the body of the turtle, known as a carcass, sinks to the bottom of the sea floor. However, the bacteria in its intestines continue to live and produce gases, gradually causing the body swell. Like a balloon filled with air, the body floats and rises to the sea surface. But, as the bacteria continue to decompose the body, the blood will eventually develop holes and let out the gases that kept it on the surface. It floods again so disappears to the bottom of the sea permanently. The turtles found lying on Virginia's beaches arrived floating. They had not yet released the gases they contained, otherwise they would have sunk and remained at the bottom of the water without reaching the beach. Since we ultimately start to understand why these sea turtles died, we first needed to figure out where and when they died.

He said, " Ya must feed her... clean her regularly. Then she will know to be faithful. " Rini looked after Bhujar everyday. Rini ran Bhujar baths, and took her for walks and on adventures. Bhujar adored Rini, and Rini adored Bhujar. Whenever Rini went, Bhujar went with her. But Bhujar was not allowed to go to school with Rini. When Rini went to school, Bhujar had to stay at home alone. One day, Bhujar followed Rini to safety. She moved around Rini, dancing and jumping. " Bhujar, why are you coming to me? " Rini scolded. " You can't come to school. If you do, boys and girls will tease me. And the teacher won't be happy! " So Bhujar went home.

Coffee houses patterned after the English and Continental models were soon established in all the colonies. Those with New York and Philadelphia are described in separate chapters. The Boston houses are described at the end of this chapter. Norfolk, Chicago, St. Louis, and New Orleans also had them. Conrad Baker's coffee house at 320 Market Street. St. Louis, was famous for its coffee and coffee cake, from 1844 to 1929, when it became a bakery and lunch room, removing by 1919 to Eighth and Pine Streets. In the pioneer days from the great west, coffee or tea were hard to get ; and, instead of milk, teas were often made from garden tree, spice wood, sassafras roots, and other shrubs, taken from the thickets.

But first let me introduce to you Dr. Miller. She is an American doctor who has come to take care of any who may have sick. " The Doctor had already climbed down from her high seat and was opening the back of the truck. She smiled and shook palms with the people. " Is there not something other you wish to buy? " she asked. " The prices are plainly charged. " Everybody now crowded about the truck, and in it, — oh, wonderful, — piled on the floor or hanging from both top and sides, were the very things for which they had been longing so eagerly! There were hoes, and shovels, and rakes, and garden seeds of all types. There were bolts of cloth and woolen garments and wooden shoes, and yarn for knitting. There were even knitting - needles! And, best of all, there was food, food such as they had not seen in many weary months. Ah, it was indeed marvelous what that truck contained!

Practice was very much reduced and the ease of manufacture greatly facilitated by the methods now most generally used, and which were, I suspect, first improved by Messrs. Wratten and Wainright. I refer to those of running with alcohol and of straining the emulsion, when set, through canvas, so as will divide it very finely. When the latter method is extended to a comparatively less time is sufficient to wash it.
