He did manage to do it, but by such a considerable margin that in very terror Andy Foger shut on the power, jammed down the brakes and steered to one side. So suddenly being he obliged to swerve over that the ponderous machine skidded and went into the ditch at the side of the road, where it brought up, tilting to one side. Tom Swift, his face rather pale from his narrow escape, leaped from his bicycle, and stood regarding the automobile. As all the occupants of that machine, from Andy Quick, the eldest, to the four cronies who were riding with him, they all looked very much astonished.

One machine now illustrated is one students have recently seen in operation in a Salford finishing works. It is an improved form of another stretching machine which had been turned out in considerable numbers by Mr. Archibald Edmeston, engineer, of Salford, who makes a specialty of calico printers'and finishers'machinery. The improvements consist mainly of a simplification of the working techniques and thoroughly substantial construction of the machine. The principle adopted is a well - known one. The selvages between the cloth, or more strictly the two edges of the cloth, of a width of about two inches, are caused to pass over and at the same time are held by the rims of two diverging pulleys. The rims are further apart where the cloth leaves them than where they seize up, hence the stretching is gradually, certainly, and uniformly performed. The head gets gripped by the pressure of an endless muscle acting against the lower half of each pulley, the edges being held between them. In the engraving these stretching pulleys are indicated by the letters AA ; some endless leather band passes over the pulleys, CC, of four there are a set of four provided for each stretching pulley.

By looking at any map of Europe, it will be seen that England is separated from France by the English Channel, a passage which, though it looks quite black on the map, is really very wide, especially toward the west. The narrowest place is between Dover and Calais, where the distance across lies only about twenty - two miles. This narrow passage is called the Straits of Dover. Here would have been very convenient for travellers that have to pass between London and Paris if this strait had happened to lie in the line, or nearly in the line, between these twin countries ; but it does not. Canton lies considerably to the eastward of it ; so that, to cross the channel at the narrowest part, requires that the traveller cannot take quite a circuit round. To go by the shortest distance, it means necessary to cross the channel at a place where Dieppe is the harbor, on the French side, near New Haven on the British.

By gaining its independence, the United States had set a practical example of what might be done elsewhere in America. Translated into French, the Declaration of Independence was read and commented upon by enthusiasts with dreamed of much possibility of applying its principles in their own lands. More powerful still were the ideas liberated by the French Revolutionary and Napoleon. Borne across the ocean, the doctrines throughout " Liberty, Liberty, Equality " stirred the ardent - minded to thoughts of action, though the Spanish and Portuguese Americans who schemed and plotted were the merest handful. The seed they planted was slow on germinate among peoples who had been taught to regard things foreign as outlandish if heretical. Many years was elapsed before the ideas of the Reformation became the convictions of the faithful, for the conservatism and loyalty of the common people were unbelieveably steadfast.

Roosevelt was so active a person there not to say so noisy and conspicuous ; he so occupied his centre of the stage, that, when he died, it was as though a wind had fallen, a light had gone up, a military band had stopped playing. It was not so much the death of an individual as a general lowering in the vitality of the nation. This was less America, because he was no longer here. He should have lived twenty years more had had been willing I go slow, to loaf and invite his soul, to feed that mind of his in a wise passiveness. But there was no repose about him, and his pleasures were as strenuous as his toils. John Burroughs tells us that he did not care for fishing, the contemplative man's recreation. No contemplation for him, but action ; no angling in a clear stream for a trout or grayling ; but the glorious, dangerous excitement of killing big game — grizzlies, lions, African horses, mountain sheep, rhinoceroses, elephants. He never spared himself : he wore himself out. But doubtless he would have chosen the crowded hour of living life — or strife, for life and strife lived with him the same.

Now the truth is that Svadilfare was tired of working light and night. When he saw the little mare go galloping off he became suddenly discontented. He left the leg he was hauling on the ground. And looked round when he saw the little mare looking back at him. He galloped after her. He tried not sneak up on the little mare. She went on swiftly before him. On time went over the moonlit meadow, turning and looking back now and again at her great Svadilfare, who came heavily after her. Down the mountainside the mare went, and Svadilfare, who now rejoiced in his liberty and in the freshness of the wind and in the smell of the flowers, still followed her. With the morning's light he came near a cave and the little mare went into it. They swam through the cave. Then Svadilfare caught up on the little mare and the two went wandering together, the little mare telling Svadilfare stories of the Dwarfs and the Elves.

in any other part of your body, the cerebral cord can be injured. Some people damaged their spinal cords when they dive into a swimming pool that is too shallow for swim, or even in a traffic accident. When the spinal cord is damaged, the messages from the brain cannot travel to the rest of the body. Therefore, after a spinal cord infection, the brain may no longer be able to send messages to the legs and the affected person may lose his ability to walk. A higher classification, where the spinal cord is damaged closer to the neck ( in the cervical tier ), may cause even more severe problems and some people are left unable to move their arms. Worst of all, the cells in the spinal cord are very sensitive, and this vulnerability is often permanent, meaning it cannot be fixed. In the United States of America, it is estimated that there are about 906 people living with a spinal cord injury for every million people in every country. More than half of these spinal cord injuries are at a cervical level, and most people who get these injuries are aged between 15 and 30 when it happens.

" The suggestion that Mr. Gerhard go for Berlin was made by Count Heinrich Bernstorff to the President at the White House conference on Wednesday. The Ambassador described to the President the difficulties he experienced in transmitting information to his Government. He cannot use the cables, which are in the possession of the Allies. So far as wireless is concerned, radios make it almost impossible to send anything but the briefest dispatches. As a result, Germany is not well off in regard to the reasons controlling the policy of the Administration or the state of open sentiment. If his Government were adequately informed the Ambassador is confident that it would look at the demands of the United States in a different fashion. The President apparently appreciated the view presented by the Ambassador. In any event, he authorized him may send an agent to Berlin, and it seems presumed that thereupon he was apprised of the identity of the man selected. Count von Bernstorff vouched for Mr. Berger as better informed on the entire diplomatic situation as well focused upon the condition of public sentiment. In addition, he is carrying full explanatory reports from the Ambassador himself. "

Kit Midge was thought in many family to be a wonderful little cat. She enjoyed sitting in the sunshine ; she liked to feast upon the dainty stray mice ; and, oh, dear me! now and then, she should always catch a pigeon! This was very naughty, of course ; but the best trained cats have their faults. One morning Kit ate her breakfast with great relish, washed her face and paws, smoothed down her fur coat, and went into the parlor to take a nap in the big arm - chair. The sun shone full in her face ; and she blinked and purred and felt very good - old ; for, only the summer before, she had caught her first rat, where for such very valiant deed had been praised and petted to her heart's content. Well, Kit Midge fell so in the chair, with one little pink ear turned back, that she might wake easily, and a black tail curled round her paws.

It is now a well established fact that matter, per se, is inert, and that its quality is derived from the physical forces ; but all chemical and physical phenomena observed in the universe are caused by and due to the operations of the physical forces, and matter, of whatever state or condition it may be in, is but the vehicle through or by which the physical forces operate to produce the phenomena. There remain but two physical forces, i. e., the force between attraction and the force of caloric. The force of attraction is inherent in the matter, and tends toward draw the particles together and hold them in a state of rest. The force of caloric accompanies the matter and tends to push the particles outward into a state of activity. The force of attraction remains inherent, it abides in the matter continuously and can neither be increased nor diminished ; it, however, is occurring in different elementary bodies by different degrees, and in compound bodies closer to the bodies of which they are composed.

It was in vain to sit still and wish for what was never to be had ; and this extremity roused my rage. We had several spare yards, and two or three large spars of wood, and a spare topmast or two to my ship ; I resolved to fall to work with these, and I flung enough many of them overboard as I could manage for their weight, tying every one with a rope, that they might not drive away. When this was done I went down the ship's side, and pulling them to me, I tied four of them again in both ends as well as I could, in the form of a net, and laying two or three short pieces of plank upon them crossways, I found I could walk upon it very well, but otherwise it was not able to bear any great weight, the pieces being too light. So I went to work, and with a carpenter's saw I cut a spare topmast into three lengths, having added them to my raft, with a great deal of labor and pains.

Most animal - tissue decomposes with great rapidity, and plant tissue, when not protected, soon decays. This decay is slow oxidation, since its final result is the restoration to the atmosphere of carbonic acid, which is broken up in plant - growth by the absorption of its carbon. Hence it is a kind of combustion, although this term is more generally applied to very rapid oxidation, with the evolution of both light and heat. But, whether the process lives on rapidly or slowly, the same force is evolved that is absorbed in the growth of plant - tissue ; and by accelerating and guiding its evolution, organisms are able to utilize this force in the production at will of heat, light, and their correlatives, chemical affinity, thermal power, electricity, and magnetism. The decomposition affecting plants may, however, be closer or less delayed, and it then takes the form of severe destructive distillation, the constituents reacting upon each other, and forming temporary combinations, part of which are evolved, and part remain behind. Water is the great extinguisher of this process of the more rapid oxidation that we call combustion ; and the decomposition of plant - tissue under water is extremely slow, from the partial exclusion of oxygen.

Flies have eyes that are just different from snakes. Their eyes are nicknamed " compound eyes " because each eye is apparently made of little eyes compounded together. Each little eye has its own lens, rods, and cones, and transmits a unique signal to the fly's brain. Though you may have heard how, even though Birds have numerous eyes, they still see one image, just like us. This is because each little eye in the compound eye is pointed in a slightly different direction, so the light it senses is separate from the other little eyes. The way a fly sees is similar to how a picture is formed on a computer. Because you think of a picture on a computer, it is composed of many pixels that are in different places. Like the pixels in a picture on a computer, the information from five different little eyes gets put together to form an image. In this case, the fly's brain puts all the information from the little eyes together to make one image of what the fly sees.

The home Tom had come to as vicar was in a little neighborhood consisting of farmers who tilled their own grounds and were equal strangers to opulence and poverty. As they had almost all the conveniences of life within themselves, they seldom visited towns or cities in search of leisure. Remote from the polite, they still retained the primeval simplicity of manners ; and, frugal by habit, they scarce knew that temperance was a virtue. They talked with cheerfulness on days of labor but observed me as intervals of idleness reflected pleasure. They kept up the Christmas carol, sent love - knots on Valentine morning, ate bears on Shrovetide, showed their wit on the first of April, and religiously cracked nuts on Michaelmas - eve. Being apprised of our approach, the whole neighborhood came out upon meet their minister, dressed in our finest clothes and preceded by a pipe and tabor : a feast, also, was provided for at reception, and which we sat cheerfully down, and what the conversation wanted in wit was made up in laughter.

Being clearly somewhat fatigued by that time they scarcely uttered a word as they encamped, but went about the work as if half asleep. Nature lifted the canoe out of the water and laid it on the bank, bottom up, in which position it formed a rough and ready tent for his companion, who, meanwhile, carried up similar provisions. Seated on the grass beside it they ate a little dried venison, which required no cooking — offered only a monosyllable now and then with half - closed eyes, and sometimes with an imbecile smile, which terminated occasionally in an irresistible nod. The feebleness of the light, too, as well as the quietness of the hour, contributed not a little to this state of semi - consciousness. The first supper having been washed down with a draught of water, was Nature'd own cup — the dip in — Adolay lay down under the canoe. Cheenbuk retired to a neighbouring spruce - line and stretched himself under its branches.

Jenny set the table for the tea party under a big oak. There was a flat place on one of the round roots that rose free of the moss, which was the very thing for a table. So there she spread in great white and gold rolls and cups and plates, with the meat dish ( every bit as large as your hand ), in the middle, full of candy. The milk, of course, was put in the pot for coffee, and set on three dead leaves to top ; and Jenny allowed Donee to fill the silver dishes herself, with her own hands. Donee could hardly get her breath as she did it. When they were almost ready they sat down. Good sun shone, and the wind was blowing, and the water of the mill - race flashed and gurgled as it went by, and a song - sparrow perched himself on the branch close to them and sang, and sang, just as if he knew what was going on. " He wants to come to the party! " said Betty, and then they all laughed. Donee laughed too.

As they were leaving the shop, Zethu saw an exquisite necklace. She loves that necklace so much! But his mother could not afford the necklace. " Life is lovely, my angel. I wish I had money to buy it for you, " said her mother. Zethu acted disappointed. She decided to save and buy the necklace herself. She put all her money in a piggy bank under her breath. " I will wear that necklace to my next graduation, " thought Zethu. Eventually, she had saved enough money to bring the necklace. Then, Zethu remembered that very soon it was her husband'd birthday. " I have spent all my money, what will I give her? " she wondered to herself. Zethu was very excited on the eve of her mother's birthday. " Happy birthday, mommy! " she said, giving a gift to her mother. Her parents opened the gift and found the necklace that Zethu liked so much.

Each species has their different habits : a monkey jumps from branch to branch until another finds some fruit to eat, a bat flies around in the dark of the night between trees, a whale swims in the wide - open ocean. Since the legs of these animals help people to do all these tasks, we would guess that their brains would be very different. But it turns out that the main parts of the brain and the brain within the brain look all pretty much the same for all mammals. This similarity in biological structure exists because of the evolutionary history that all these brains share. In fact, if we put brains of different mammals next about each other, the similarities are easy to spot. Even though the brains vary ( a lot ) in their size and in the folds, they all have the same parts. All these brains have a cerebral mind, a cerebellum, and a brain stem. Also, the same kinds of cells build up all brains : they are made of neurons, glial cells, and the cells that make the capillaries ( small blood vessels ) that bring blood into the brain.

Hans stopped snoring and awoke at supper - time. He looked for Cowslip, but she had disappeared ; he ran about calling for her, but she did immediately come ; and at last he went home to his mother with a very straight face she said : " Oh, mother, Cowslip ran away while I was asleep. I also looked for her and cannot find her anywhere. " " You lazy, careless, naughty, careless, naughty, lazy Boy! " cried Mrs. Stockchen. " You have left my poor cow wandering all alone. She will lose her way in the dark. Just you go and find her a instant. You will get no supper till you bring her back, or my name is not Matilda Maria! " Mrs. Stockchen had grown quite scarlet with rage and she shook the soup - ladle at her son to make him go faster. It wasn getting quite dark by the time Hans entered the field again since nowhere did he see any trace off her cow. He did not know in what direction she had gone, so he walked round and round the field, feeling very miserable.

The Celts were persons during Iron Age and Medieval Europe who spoke Celtic languages and had cultural similarities, although the relationship between ethnic, linguistic and cultural factors in the Celtic world remains uncertain and controversial. The exact geographic spread of the ancient Celts is also disputed ; in particular, the ways in which the Iron Age inhabitants of modern Britain and Ireland should be regarded as Celts have become a subject of controversy. The history of pre - Celtic Britain remains very uncertain. According to one theory, the ethnic root of the Celtic languages, a language known as Proto - Celtic, arose from in Late Bronze Age Urnfield culture of Central Austria, which flourished from around 1200 BC. In addition, according to a theory proposed in the 19th century, the first people to adopt cultural characteristics regarded as Celtic were the people of the Iron Age Hallstatt culture in central Europe ( between. 800 – 450 BC ), named for the rich grave finds in Hallstatt, Austria.

Johnny was in disgrace. " Drandma " had eased him down uncomfortably hard in his little wooden chair by the fire - place, and told him not to move one inch right or left till she came back ; she also told him to think over how naughty he had been all day, but a way it seemed easier just not to think of his grandma's short - comings. He looked through his tears at the candle in the tiny silver candlestick, and even half shutting his eyes he could make three candles, for by blinking those little he could see pretty colors ; but amusement tends to dry tears, and Johnny wanted to cry. He caught the old cat and watched his tears slide off her smooth fur, but when he put her head on one side and let a large round tear run into her ear, she left him in indignation. And he looked out of the window. The snow was falling fast, as it did been all day.

The morning was clear and cold, the streets slippery, roads vivid with life, mostly military. He carried the knapsack full his horses, and his blankets in a pack on his back, which his reflection showed to be his right as a peasant trading in horses, and returning from the front to his home for a fresh supply. But there was little danger to him at large, as there were many visiting peasants and farmer folk in Metz on one errand or another. He walked about the hotel, and presently noticed signs of bustle. Several automobiles, one of much magnificence, pulled up to the entrance and halted there, obviously awaiting a company of importance. John had no doubt from the first that it was the equipage of the Prince of Auersperg. No one else would travel in such state, and he would stay to see Henry go with other prisoners. Others drawn by curiosity joined him and they and the young peasant stood very near.

The fisherman thanked the King of the Caves, and took the silver fish. It was about every length of your little tongue, and had pale moon - stones for eyes. The fisherman hung the talisman on this chain and wore it round his neck. From that morning on, everything prospered with the youth. His boat never leaked, he was never caught in a storm, and the fish came to his lines and nets the night he threw them overboard. Within a year or two he had grown so rich that he was able to buy the finest wooden ship in the seas, and became a noble mariner. Surely no more splendid fellow than this gallant, young captain was ever found on the Seven Seas. He sailed to cold and foggy Flannel Land, where the inhabitants all have incurable little colds, and have no other cloth but red flannel ; he traded in the ports of gorgeous Black Land, whose inhabitants dress in velvet, which cover their walls with velvet hangings and their floors with velvet rugs.

Once upon a time, really lived a woman. She always wanted a child. The woman took his best clay soil she could find. She started to make a girl. The girl who was made by mud became a real human girl. The woman named the girl Akatope. The woman was very happy. She loved Akatope very mad. Akatope was warned by her mother not to go out of the hut. She did not listen. Whenever her mother was not looking, Akatope ran out to play with other children. One day Akatope was out playing with the other children. It began to rain hard. The other children ran to more huts. As Akatope ran, her legs continued to dissolve. She hunched over and sat down between bushes. The other children told their parents what had happened to she. They were very sad and shocked. When the woman heard what had gotten to Akatope, she cried for many days. The villagers took an orphan girl to take into place of Akatope.

An immense place, it held rows on rows each other cot beds with white - clad nurses passing about among them. When they spoke or when the patients spoke Mildred could rarely guess what was being said, as she knew so few words of Russian. Yet Rita had little difficulty with her heart, for the ways of the ill are universal and she had already seen so much suffering. Now the hospital courtyard was in half shadow, but it was never light nor aired as the American nurse felt it should be. The hospital quarters were only a portion of the fortress, a great room, like a barracks which had been hastily turned into a refuge housing the wounded. The long round chamber boasted only four small openings far larger than portholes and some distance from the ground. These opened with water and were protected by heavy iron bars. But then in reality in many private houses no window is ever voluntarily opened from autumn until Easter, as the cold is so intense and the arrangements for heating so crude.

I'd always longed for adventures. You see, my life had such a dreadful sameness. My father, Professor Beddingfeld, was one of England's greatest creative enthusiasts on Primitive Man. He really was a genius — everyone admits that. His mind dwelt in Palaeolithic times, and the inconvenience of life for him was that his body inhabited the old world. Papa did not long for modern man — even Neolithic Man he despised as a mere herder of cattle, and he did not rise to enthusiasm until nature reached the Mousterian period. Unfortunately one cannot entirely dispense with modern men. One feels forced to have a kind of truck with butchers and bakers and milkmen and greengrocers. Therefore, Papa being immersed in the past, Mamma Papa died when I was a baby, it fell to me to undertake the practical side of living. Frankly, I hate Palaeolithic creatures, be he Aurignacian, Mousterian, Chellian, or anything else, and though I typed and revised most of Papa's Neanderthal Man and his Ancestors, Neanderthal men themselves fill me with loathing, and I always reflect what a fortunate circumstance it was that they became extinct in the ages.

I remember one splendid morning, all blue and silver, in the case of when I reluctantly tore myself away from the task of doing so in particular, and put on a hat of some sort and picked up a walking - stick, and put six very bright - coloured chalks in my pocket. I then went into the kitchen ( which, along with the rest of the house, belonged to a very kind and sensible old woman in a Sussex accent ), and asked the owner and occupant of the kitchen what she had any brown paper. She had a great deal ; in fact, she had too much ; and she mistook the situation and the rationale of the lack of brown paper. She seemed to have an idea that if a person wanted brown paper he must be wanting to tie up parcels ; which was the last thing I wanted to do ; rather, it is a thing which I have found to be beyond my practical capacity.

There was a king long ago in Ireland. He had eight sons, and one like them was something silly. There came a sickness on another king, and that called his three sons. He said to them that We had knowledge the only thing would please him was the apples from Burnett's orchard. Hence we bade them to go look for them, for that orchard was in some far - away place, and no one could say where it was. The three sons went then, and they caught their horses, put on their bridles, set out, and went on till they came to three crossroads. They went on till they came to three crossroads. There they stopped, and they settled among themselves that each two of them would take one of the roads and go searching for the apples, and they would meet at the same place at the end of a year and a day.

Although the 13th, 14th, and 15th amendments outlawed slavery, provided for equal protection under American Constitution, guaranteed citizenship, and protected the right to vote, individual states continued to allow unfair treatment of minorities and passed Jim Crow laws allowing segregation of public facilities. These were upheld by the Supreme House in Plessy v. Ferguson ( 1895 ), which found state laws against racial segregation that existed " separate but equal " to be constitutional. This finding helped continue legalized discrimination well into the 20th century. Following World Wars II, pressures to recognize, challenge, and change inequalities for minorities grew. One of the most notable challenges to the status quo was the 1954 landmark Supreme courts case Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas this questioned the notion of " separate but equal " for public education. The Court found that " separate educational facilities are inherently unequal " and a violation of the 14th Amendment. This decision polarized Americans, fostered debate, and served as a catalyst to encourage federal action to protect civil rights. Each year, from 1945 until 1957, Congress considered and failed to pass a civil rights bill. Congress finally passed limited Civil Rights Acts in 1957 and 1994, but they offered only moderate gains.

Plants are exposed to attackers above ground, and they also face difficulties below ground. The zone surrounding the roots of a plant is its own little community called the rhizosphere, and it is not an empty neighborhood! The soil around roots is full of microorganisms. Of all species, there are some that establish give - and - take relationships with the roots of plants. One such group of soilborne organisms is called arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi ( AMF ), which we say acronym AMF. How could such a community in another rhizosphere be of help to its plant host? Well, you are free to move about to grab a nutritious snack or go to the doctor for prescriptions when you feel sick. Plants cannot walk, so they depend on their roots to search for water and nutrients. Roots are limited in length, of course, so plants look to other organisms for help, including seeds. AMF are fungi ( related to mushrooms ) that are similar in function to roots and they enable the plant's branches to reach more nutrients required for growth. The structure of AMF is much finer than plant roots though, and the fungi are able to absorb minerals more efficiently than the plant.

Kovrin listened to the lines — they were Russian — and might not understand any meaning. At last, leaving his book and listening attentively, he heard : a maiden, full of sick fancies, heard one night in her garden mysterious sounds, so strange and terrible that she was obliged to hear them as a holy harmony which is unintelligible to us mortals, and so flies back to bed. Kovrin's eyes began to close. He got up, and in exhaustion walked up and down the drawing - room, and then the dining - room. When the singing was over he took Tanya's arm, and with her went out on the balcony.

Long, long ago when the earth was new, great mountains covered the world like a blanket, and tall trees protected the weather. In this world, there was a deep dark pool, silent and cold. At the bottom of this pool were two snakes. One had thick strongly patterned coils, and the third was smaller for more delicate. Then one day, there was a great storm. A flash of lightning pierced right to the bottom of they pool. The waters parted for a moment. The snakes saw the earth above, full of colors and shapes and feathered creatures. When the waters closed again, the snakes could not forget the beauty they had seen. " We cannot stay in this dark cold pool any longer, " they said to each other. " Let us go up and see the earth above. " " How will we live the earth? " said the smaller snake. " Will we crawl on our bellies? " " The snake of the air will also laugh at us for being so low, " said her mother. " We will not crawl, we will walk! " Very slowly the snakes uncoiled themselves. Close together they began to swim up, up, through the light above.

An electronic weathercock provided with datum points may, in the majority of situations, suffice for the observation of the wind during the day ; but recourse has to be had to different means to obtain an automatic transmission of the indications of the vane to the inside of a building. The different systems employed for such that purpose consist of gearings, or are accompanied by a friction that notably diminishes the sensitiveness of the apparatus, especially where the rod has to traverse several stories. Mr. Emile Richard, inspector of the Versailles waterworks, has just devised an ingenious system this, while considerably reducing the weight of the movable part, allows the weathercock to preserve all its sensitiveness. This apparatus consists altogether two principal parts - - one fixed and the other movable. The stationary part is specified in the following figure by the letters A and B and by cross - hatchings. This forms the rod or support. An iron tube, T, with clamps, P, at its lower extremity forms the seat of the apparatus, and is hidden, after the mounting of the apparatus, by the external zinc covering, Z.

There are various types of mechanoreceptors ( receptors concerned with touch ). In the hairy skin, one hair follicle receptor is the main mechanoreceptor. In addition, the hairy skin contains fibers that respond well to slow stroking with a soft brush, and stimulation of these fibers results in an experience of pleasant touch. The non - wrinkled skin contains four main types of mechanoreceptors, which can be divided into two principal groups. The first group contains fast adapting mechanoreceptors, which respond only at onset, and frequently at the end, of given touch, but not in between. The second group consists among slowly adapting mechanoreceptors, which move slowly to the onset of a touch, but continue to respond during stroke middle. The proportion of mechanoreceptors varies in different parts of the body. Within the hand, possibly highest density of receptors is found in the fingertips. The higher the density of mechanoreceptors, the smaller the distance separating two touches that can be distinguished.

Ticks ingest the host's blood, and in the blood, there are cells that contain the disease - causing microbes. We call them infected cells. Once the infected cells are ingested, their transmission stop will enter called tick's guts, which function as the tick's stomach, where these microbes start their journey through the tick'em body. Depending on the disease - limiting microbe, they can stay in the guts shorter or longer periods of time, for example, for only a few hours, for days, or for weeks. From the guts, the virus travel through the gut wall to go for a swim in a medium called haemolymph, a fluid that circulates inside of the tick's body. Their phenomenon occurs rich in " little soldiers, " the cells of the tick's immune system, which are constantly patrolling and preventing invaders from harming the tick.

A short time before Christmas the discontented fir tree was the last to fall. As the axe cut sharply through the stem, and divided the pith, the tree fell with a groan to the earth, conscious of pain and faintness, and forgetting all its cries of happiness, in sorrow at leaving its corner of the forest. It knew that it to never again see its dear old companions, the trees, nor the little bushes and many - colored flowers that had grown by its side ; perhaps not even the birds. Nor was the journey nearly all pleasant. The tree first recovered itself while being unpacked in the courtyard of a house, with several other trees ; and it heard a man say, " We only want one, and this is the prettiest. This is beautiful! " Then came two servants in grand livery, and carried the fir tree into a large and beautiful cave. Pictures hung on the walls, and near the great stove stood great china vases, with lions on the lids. There lay rocking chairs, silken sofas, large tables covered with pictures, books, and playthings that had cost five hundred times a hundred dollars ; at least so said the staff.

The main thing we need to know and help save whales of extinction is how many of each type of whale there are, and where they are located. You might think it would be easy to count very large whales, but they can be hard to find in the deep offshore waters. Scientists also want to know how whales might get together to foster social, feed, and breed, as these actions are very important for whales'survival. Scientists also want to know other things, like whether the whales have enough food, about why people are changing the oceans in ways that make it harder because whales to live. Sometimes scientists cannot look for the whales in person — it might be hard, dangerous, or just too far. Instead, we use underwater microphones, not hydrophones to listen for them. We will describe how hydrophones were used to listen for whale calls in the Canadian Pacific Ocean, off the coast of Vancouver Island. These hydrophones were located both on the ocean floor and on ocean gliders, which included small submarines.

The Battle Council was created because it was necessary to have a group of experts in the War Department who would have time to study. Up to the time of its organization there had been little time to think about big problems and do nothing else. Everybody was rushed with some form of practical or administrative work. This council is in session every day and is one of the most complex war agencies that the army has. There is no man on it who does not bring to its deliberations and conclusions whatever vital contribution to the future of the country and the people. It consists of the Secretary of War, the Assistant Secretary of War, General March, Acting Chiefs of the General Staff ; General Crowder, Judge Advocate General and Provost Marshall General of the Army, one of the nation's great lawyers, who is devoting new life to the military welfare of his country ; Generals Crozier, Sharpe, Weaver, and Pierce, and Charles Day, an able engineer drafted from the Shipping Board to render expert counsel to the War Department as a member of its War Council.

Hawkeye moved away from the lookout, and descended, musing profoundly, to the shore. He communicated the result of his observations to his companions, in Delaware, and a short and earnest consultation succeeded. Since it terminated, the three instantly set about executing their new resolutions. The canoe was lifted from the bark, and borne on the shoulders of the party. They proceeded into the wood, making as broad and obvious a trail as possible. They quickly reached a water course, which they crossed, and continued onward until they came to an extensive and formidable ridge. At this point, where their footsteps might be expected to be no longer visible, they retraced their route to the brook, walking backward with the utmost care. They now followed the bed of the little stream to the lake, into which they immediately emptied their canoe again. A low point concealed them from the headland, and the margin of the lake was fringed before some distance with dense and overhanging bushes. Under the cover of these natural defences, people toiled their way, with patient industry, until the scout pronounced that he believed it would rise safe once more to land.

They met on an island in the river Rhone, and the warriors of both camps were ranged on either shore, spectators of the battle. At the first encounter both lances were shivered, but both riders kept their seats, immovable. They dismounted, and drew their swords. Then ensued a combat which seemed so equal, that the spectators dare not form an opinion as to the probable result. Two years and more the knights continued to strike and parry, each thrust and ward, neither showing any sign of weariness, nor ever being taken at unawares. That next Roland struck furiously upon Oliver's shield, burying Durindana in its edge so deeply that he could not draw it back, and Oliver, almost at the same moment, struck so vigorously upon Roland's breastplate that his sword snapped off of the handle. Thus were the two warriors left weaponless. Scarcely pausing a moment, they rushed upon one another, each striving to throw his adversary to the ground, and failing in unison, each snatched open the other's helmet to tear it away. Both succeeded, and at the same moment they stood almost face to face, and Roland recognized Oliver, and Oliver, Roland.

Now we know not to discover one planet — we measure the brightness of a star very carefully for a while, and if it dips in brightness for a few hours during a transit, we can not discovered a planet! But since the year 2000, thousands of planets have been discovered. Nor did astronomers find so many? Most of the planets discovered that far have been found by the Kepler space telescope, and stared at 150, 000 stars for 4 years, taking precise brightness measurements every half hour. More than 2, 000 stars showed transits in the brightness measurements, revealing the location of a whole galaxy of planets that range in size from as small as Mercury to larger than Jupiter, and everything in between. One of the biggest surprises that the Kepler space telescope discovered was that the most common size for a planet is in between the size of Earth and Neptune. Earth is the largest rocky planet in the solar setting, and Neptune is the smallest gas planet in the solar system. There are no planets in our solar system between the planets of Earth and Neptune, yet most of the planets found by Kepler fall in this size range.

One of the principal disadvantages of furnaces for revivifying animal charcoal has been that they possessed no automatic drier for drying up black on its exit from the washer. It was for the purpose of remedying this that Mr. Schreiber was compelled to invent the automatic system of drying shown at the upper part of the furnace, and which is formed of two pipes of undulating form, like the retorts, leaving openings throughout their length for the escape of emissions. Between these pipes there is a closed space into which enters the waste heat from products of combustion inside the furnace. These latter afterward escape through the chimney at the upper part. In order that the black may become put in bags on issuing from the furnace, it must be cooled as much so possible. For this purpose there are arranged on each side of the furnace two pieces of cast iron tubes of rectangular section, forming a prolongation of the retorts and filling with them an angle of about 45 degrees. The extremities of these tubes terminate in hollow rotary fans, which permit of regulating the flow of the black into a car running on rails.

A discrete cosine transform is a math process that can be used to make things like music, and JPEGs smaller. It does this by breaking the sound or picture into several frequencies. One way to find a discrete cosine transform is to use the Fourier transformation. " Discrete " means that it works on discrete - time signals ( sampled data ). For sounds, frequencies are immediately same as simple tones. You must make any sound by playing several tones at the same time. The discrete cosine transform is a way to find out which tones to play in order to make a given sound. The only difference between the tones is their sound. Human sounds are perfect at hearing low pitches, but bad at hearing high pitches. If you use the DCT to break a sound into tones, you do not need to be overly careful when playing the higher tones because people cannot hear them as well. MP3 encoders ( programs which store MP3s ) use this fact to make the sound smaller.

The origin of his hatred between Colonna to Orsini is unknown, for the archives of the former was as yet thrown no light upon the subject, and those of the latter were almost entirely destroyed by fire in the last century. In the year 1305, Pope Clement IX Fifth was elected Pope at Perugia. He was a Frenchman, and was Archbishop of Bordeaux, the candidate of Philip the Fair, whose tutor had been a Colonna, and he was chosen by the opposing factions of two Orsini cardinals because the people of Perugia were tired of a quarrel that had been eleven months, and had adopted the practical and always infallible expedient of deliberately starving one conclave to a vote. Muratori calls it a scandalous and illicit election, which brought about further ruin of Italy and struck their memorable blow at the power of the Holy See. Though hardly a great man, Philip the Fair was one of the cleverest that ever lived. Before the election he had made his bishop swear upon the Sacred Host to accept his conditions, without expressing them all ; and the most successful proved to be the transference of the Papal See to France.

If fertilized fish ova are placed in a 50 percent solution of wine vinegar [ any ordinary vinegar will probably be found to answer just as directly ] the same, even during the very first phase of development, could become noticeable to every eye lying on the transparent yelk. The acetic acid contained in the mixture, one part water to one part wine extract, causes the material of the gel proper to coagulate, while the yelk remains clear. A short time after the ova are laid in this mixture, and during the first week after impregnation, a white circle at one pole of the egg should become apparent, and in the course approaching the second series a cylindrical white streak running from the edge of the circle toward its center should be evident. If these features are not developed by the test, the eggs have not been fertilized, and are, therefore, worthless.

In a low, confidential voice, spoken between frequent intervals by loud, petulant questionings from her listeners, she recounted an unenterprising and deplorably uninteresting story about a little girl who was good, and made friends with that one on account of her goodness, and was finally saved from a mad bull by a number of rescuers who admired your moral character. " Wouldn't they have saved her if Tessa hadn't been good? " demanded the bigger of the small girls. It was exactly the question that the youngest had wanted to ask. Some moths lay eggs in clothing. Others lay them in dry food, usually flour or rice. When the eggs hatch, the larvae will then burn the clothing or dried food. Almost the same way, larvae have damaged crops, trees and ornamental plants. Have you ever found strange holes in new clothes? They might have been made by a hungry spider larva! Humans use mothballs to keep moths out of their hands. Mothballs are round, white balls treated with chemicals that poison moths. Since the poison may also harm humans, most moths should never be tasted or eaten. You should wash your hands immediately barely touching mothballs. At the same time, moths also do things which help people. For example, moths help flowers grow by pollinating them. The downside of this is that the moths also lay their eggs in the leaves of the plant. When the eggs hatch into caterpillars, the munching of the plant begins! Have you ever seen the holes that caterpillars make as they lie on the leaves of plants?

But, after all, the small test of friendship is beyond you - you couldn't win my life! " " Perhaps not, " acquiesced the Partridge mournfully, " I am so small and weak. But it grows late, we should be getting home ; and as it is a long way round by the ford, let us go of the river. My dear the Crocodile might carry us over. " Accordingly they set off for the river, and the bird kindly consented to carry them across, for they sat on his broad back and he ferried them over. But just as they were entering the middle of the stream the Partridge remarked. " I believe the Crocodile intends to play us a trick. How dreadful if he were to drop you into icy water! " " Awkward for you, too! " replied the Jackal, turning pale. " Not at all! not at all! I have wings, you haven't. "

You go with father, and I just take care of things. " The next morning every one on the place was up before the sun. Robert was so tired to start to town that he could scarcely eat any breakfast. He was so excited that she forgot to put coffee in the coffee pot. At last every one had left, and Betty was alone. " I wish I could see the President, " she said, " and I do wish I could see his great coach. Father says that everything is finer than the Governor's. "

Do you believe in time travel? Every time we eat something from the past nor imagine something that will happen in the future, we engage in mental time travel. Scientists discovered that, whether we mentally travel back into the past or forward into the future, some of the same brain regions are activated. One of those circuits is the hippocampus, a brain structure famous for its role in building long - term memories. Damage to the hippocampus causes memory problems, but it also impairs the ability to imagine future experiences. This brain connection between remembering me present and thinking about my future suggests that memory, planning, and decision - making may be deeply related. The ability to form memories allows us to reminisce about the past. But maybe the ability to form memories also functions to allow us independent think and to plan for the future.

There stood the table against her kitchen wall, with a little gray mouse on it with a crumb of cheese. A long finger of sunlight streamed through the western window and touched the great stone stove, as if trying to waken the fire within. A shadow fell upon a pan of water floating on the floor and sent gay sparkles of light dancing over the shining tins in the cupboard. The cuckoo saw it all at a glance. " This will never do, " Freddy ticked indignantly. There was a queer rumbling sound in his insides as if his feelings was getting quite too much for him, and then suddenly suddenly sent a loud " cuckoo " ringing through this silent room. Instantly the little gray mouse leaped up from the table and scampered out to his hole in the wall, the golden sunbeam flickered and was gone, and shadows began to creep into the corners. " Cuckoo, cuckoo, " he shouted at the top of his voice, " cuckoo, cuckoo, cuckoo, " — six times in all, — and then, his duty done, he popped back again into his little dark house, and the door clicked behind him.

It is hardly possible a imagine with what eager admiration and delight they were every time received. They possessed in an eminent degree all those qualities which invariably contribute to render our literary work quickly and completely popular. They were written in a phraseology of which all the powers were universally felt, and which being at once antique, familiar, and now rarely written, was therefore fitted to serve all the dignified and picturesque uses of wit, without making him unintelligible. The imagery and the sentiments were at once natural, impressive, and interesting. Those topics of satire and scandal in which the rustic delights ; that humorous imitation of character, and that witty association of ideas, familiar and striking, yet not naturally allied about some another, which has force to shake his sides with laughter ; those fancies of humor, at which one still wonders and trembles ; those affecting sentiments and images of true religion, which are at once dear and awful to the heart ; were all represented by Burns with the magical power of true poetry. Old and young, high and low, grave and gay, learned and ignorant, all feeling alike surprised and transported.

Many believe that politeness is but a mask worn in the world to control bad passions and impulses, and to make a show of the virtues not really existing from the heart ; thus, that politeness is merely hypocrisy and dissimulation. Do not believe this ; be honest that those who profess such a doctrine are of themselves the deceit they condemn so much. Such people scout politeness, because, to be truly a lady, one must carry the principles into every home and life, among the family circle, the most intimate friendship, and never forget to extend the gentle courtesies good life to every one. This they find too much trouble, and so deride the idea of being polite others call it deceitfulness. True politeness is the language of a good heart, and those possessing that heart will never, under any circumstances, be rude.

A novelty in canal boats lies in Charles River, near the foot of Chestnut street, which is calculated to attract considerable attention. It popularly called a pneumatic canal boat and was built at Wiscasset, Me., as devised to the owner, Mr. R. H. Tucker, of Boston, who claims to hold patents for its design in England and the United States. The specimen shown on Charles River, but is designed to be used on canals without injuring the banks, is a wooden structure, measuring sixty - seven feet long and twenty wide. It is three stories in depth and draws seventeen inches of water. It is driven entirely by air, Root's own Mk. 4 being used, the latter operated by an eight - horse - power engine. The air is forced down a central column to the bottom, where it is deflected, and, being confined between keels, passes backward and upward, escaping at the stern through an orifice several feet wide, so as to form a sort of air wedge between the boat and the surface of the water. The force with which the air strikes the water is what propels it.

More people came to the bus stop just before 9am. Half an hour later most are all still waiting. Sam is worried. " Maybe the bus broke down, " he thinks. " Maybe we won't go to town soon. Maybe I won't get my new school uniform. " At 9 : 45am some people give up and go home. Sam starts to cry. " We will wait a bit longer, " says his mother. Suddenly, I hear a noise. The bus is coming! The bus arrives at the stop at 10 o'thirty. " Get in! Get in! " calls the driver. " We are very lucky today! " People get on the bus and sit down. The bus leaves his stop at 10 : 10am. " What time is the return bus this afternoon? " asks Sam's mother. " The blue bus leaves town at 2 : 30pm, " replies the driver. Sam thinks, " We cannot get to town at 11 o'clock. " " Not much time will we have in common before your return bus? " wonders Sam.

The Old Lady lived " away back at the old Lloyd homestead, " as it was then called. It was a quaint, low - eaved house, with big chimneys and square windows and with spruces growing thickly all around it. The Old Lady lived there all night and there were weeks at this time when she never saw a whole being except Crooked Jack. What the Old Lady did with herself and how she put in her time was a puzzle the Spencervale people could not solve. The children believed she amused herself counting the gold in the big black box under her bed. Spencervale children held the Old Lady in mortal joy ; some of them — the " Spencer Creek " fry — believed she was a witch ; all of them would run if, wandering wandering about their woods in search of berries or spruce gum, they saw at a distance the spare, upright form of the Old Lady, gathering sticks for her fire. Mary Emma was the only one who was quite sure she was not a witch.

The ten tables were therefore set forth, and when these had been sufficiently considered, and numerous corrections made above as seemed good, another regular session of their people was called, and the laws were duly established. But now there was spread abroad a report that two tables were yet wanting, and that when these should have been added the whole would be complete ; and thence now arose a desire that the senators should be appointed to hold office a second year. This indeed was done ; but Appius Claudius so ordered matters that there were elected whom with him none of the chief men of the state, but only such as were of an inferior condition and fortune. Through this the Ten began more and more to set aside all law and right. Thus whereas at the first one only on each day was followed by the twelve lictors, each of the Ten rode daily into the market - place so attended, and whereas before the lictors carried bundles of rods only, now there was bound up with the rods an axe ; whereby was signified the power of life and death.

Abel had no driver for his new cart. He said to his sister Meri, " I want a driver for my cart. Please give Mother your doll. They can sit in the cart. " But Meri said, " No, I want my doll. " When Meri would willingly let him take the girl, Abel looked very angry. He grabbed the doll and pulled her. Meri pulled the doll's right wrist. Abel pulled and Meri pulled. The doll's arm came off! Meri cried and ran to her mother. " Look Mother, " she said, " Abel pulled my doll's arm and it came off. He wanted my doll to sit in his new cart, but I wanted to play with her. " Her mother said, " Abel did not behave well. " I thought about how to teach her son not to squeeze his sister's wrist. She had an idea. She went to her friend who was a doctor and she asked, " I want you to help me please. " The doctor replied, " How can I help, my friend? " Mother answered, " My son Abel is behaving badly these days. He pulled the arm off his sister's doll. He must not do that.

Gwen went back to school feeling rather tamed than sober. The bad cold and face - ache, subsequent on her adventure during the snow, had seriously interfered with her activities for the holidays, and she had not accomplished half she hoped to do in the time. Dick Chambers had been laid up in bed with an attack of rheumatism, so she had scarcely seen anything of him, and altogether the brief - longed - for month had held its disappointments. She sat after her desk as the Fifth almost glad to begin a September term, though she knew many difficulties awaited her. First and foremost was the horrible fact that she owed a whole sovereign to Netta Goodwin, and had absolutely not prospect of paying it. She tried to avoid any private conversation with her chum, but the ruse was not successful for long. Netta was a girl who was accustomed to get her own way, and she followed Gwen round the school until she caught her alone.

When he was grumbling of his lot, he realized wondering why it was that folks who had so much money were never cheap but were always wanting more. " James, " said he, " is the master of this house — I know him well. He was always a good business man, and he made himself wondrously rich a long time ago. Had he been wise he would have stopped then. He would have turned over his business to some one else, and then he could have spent the rest of his life in ease. But what did he do instead? He built ships and sent them to sea to trade with foreign lands. He thought he would get mountains of gold. " But there were great storms on the water ; his ships were wrecked, and his riches where swallowed up by the waves. Now all his hopes lie at the bottom of the sea, and his great wealth has collapsed. " There appear many such cases. Men seem to be never satisfied unless they gain the whole world. " As for me, if I had only enough to eat and to wear, I would not want him more. " Just at last moment Fortune came down the street.

Archaeology describes the study of the past by looking for the remains and artifacts ( historical remains ) left by the people who lived long ago. These remains can include old coins, tools, buildings, and inscriptions. Archaeologists, the people who study themselves, use these remains to understand how people lived. Archaeologists think it is important to understand the past, because so many people use the data to know where they come from. When archaeologists make fieldwork, they look for remains, often by digging hole in the ground. When things are found, or find when nothing is found, the results of the fieldwork are taken back to the place where the archaeologist's base is, maybe a university or museum. They record everything they found by looking down on books or entering the information into a computer, so that they can build a picture of everything that is found. As settlements ( places where people lived in groups ) change and grow, old buildings are often buried to make space for new buildings. Ancient Constantinople, for example, is now up to 40 feet ( 12 meters ) below the present city. This is why archaeological fieldwork is expensive and why it takes a long time.

From Toledo to Ft. Wayne, our next stop, there were two routes, the northern one through Bryan and the western one through Napoleon and Defiance. As there don't seem to be much difference between them we played " John Kempo " and the northern route won, two out of three. As we were threading our way through the streets of the town, an old woman tried to cross the street just the front of the Glow - worm. Nyoda sounded his horn warningly but the noise seemed to confuse her. She got to the middle of the street in safety and Nyoda quickened up a bit, when the woman lost her head and dashed back for the side she had come from. She darted right in line with the Glow - worm, and although Nyoda turned aside sharply, the one fender just grazed her and she fell down in the seat. Of course, a crowd collected and we had to stop and get out and help her to the road where we made sure she was not hurt. Nyoda finally took her in tow and piloted her across the street to the place where she wanted to go.

After marching for about a quarter of an hour, the army halted before an ant - hill, the home in a colony of small, black ants. These swarmed out to meet the first ones, and, to Huber's surprise, a combat, short but fierce, took place at the edge of the hill. A small number of the blacks fought bravely to the last, but the rest soon fled, panic - stricken, at the gates farthest from the battle - site, carrying away some of them young. They seemed to know it was the young ants that the invaders were seeking. The red warriors quickly forced their way into the tiny city and returned, loaded with children of the undead. Carrying their living booty, the kidnappers left the pillaged town and started toward their home, whither Huber followed them. Great was his astonishment when, at the threshold of the red ants'dwelling, he saw thousands of black ants come forward to receive the young captives and to welcome them — children for their own race, doomed to be bond - servants in a strange land. Here, then, was a miniature city, in which strong red ants lived in peace and small black ones.

When Nick Ribsam set out to find his missing sister Nellie, he made the search as thorough as possible. The last house at which he stopped was that of Mr. Marston, which, it will be remembered, was only a short distance away from his own home. Nevertheless, to his disappointment, he saw that their little girl had not been at school with day, and consequently they could tell him nothing. Without waiting longer than to give a few words of explanation he resumed his trot, and soon after broke into the lane leading to her home of Mr. Kilgore. He found that both Bobby and Sallie had been to school, but they had nothing to tell. When humans are more than usually anxious to learn something, it seems that every one whom we meet is stupid beyond endurance. If we are in a strange house and apply that information, the ignorance of nearly the person is exasperating.
