In a hamlet not far from Boston, there once lived a stout little fellow named Willie Wilkins. He was six years elder, had red cheeks and blue eyes, and such curly hair that it was always in a tail, no matter how much it was brushed. One summer his mamma took him into the country to spend a few weeks at a farm - house. The farmer's wife, Mrs. Hill, was very glad to have him come, for she had no girls or boys of her own, to make the house pleasant. She continued to see Willie run about, and then his shrill voice calling after the great house - rat Bruno. One morning Willie it been as busy as ever at his play : William had been in the orchard, hunting for sweet apples ; he had been in the barn, looking for hen's eggs in the sweet hay ; he had been down to the brook, sailing his boat ; and he had played market - man, with Bruno harnessed for a horse.

The next question is, what is the best time for seeing fairies? I believe I can tell you all from that. The first rule is, that it must be a very hot day — that we should consider as settled ; and you must be just a little sleepy — but not too sleepy to keep your eyes open, mind. Well, and you ought to feel a little hardly what one may call " fairyish " — the Scotch call it " eerie, " and perhaps that's a prettier word ; if you don't understand what it means, I'm afraid I can hardly explain it ; you must wait till you meet a fairy, and then you'll die. And the last rule is, that the crickets shouldn't be chirping. we can't stop to explain that rule just because — one must take it on trust for Christmas present. So, if all these things happen together, you've a good chance of seeing a fairy — or at least has much better chance than if they didn't.

Mombi's curious magic often frightened her neighbors, and they treated her shyly, yet respectfully, because and her weird gifts. But Tip frankly hated her, and took no pains to hide his feelings. Indeed, he sometimes showed less respect for the old witch than he should have done, considering she was his guardian. There were pumpkins in Mombi's corn - fields, bright golden red among the rows of green stalks ; and these had been planted and then tended that the four - horned cow might eat of them in the winter time. But one Saturday, after the corn had all been cut and stacked, and Tip commenced carrying the pumpkins to the stable, he took this notion to make a " Jack Lantern " and try to give the ugly woman a fright with it. So he selected a fine, big pumpkin — one with a lustrous, orange - red color — and began carving it. With the point of his knife he made two round eyes, a three - cornered nose, and a mouth shaped like the new moon.

We learned from our results that people who are afraid of spiders imagine them to be bigger. We also learned simply in order and overestimate the sizes of an object, that object needs to cause the person to feel fear and unpleasantness on a daily basis. We demonstrated in this work many negative emotions ( anxiety and unpleasantness ) cause people to overestimate size. But what about positive emotions? Some studies found that positive emotions could also change size estimation. For example, expert golf teams estimate the physical size of the hole the ball is hit into to be larger than non - expert players estimate the hole to be. The next question might be asked is what causes what? Do some people have an image of a big spider in their mind and this is why they were afraid of spiders? Or are they afraid of nothing because when they see one, they see it as bigger than it really is? This question requires some more studies. Such additional studies are important because understanding why people are afraid of spiders can help scientists see ways to help such people get over their fear.

After a night of heavy rain, a group of friends were on their way to school. They came to the river they had to cross every day. " Yoh! It's stopped raining, but look how full and bright the river is, " said Siya. " Oh please, " groaned Linda. " Do you think teacher will be angry if we miss our classes today? " Linda remembered what the Sea Rescue instructor later taught them in water safety lessons. " Never cross a flooded stream. Even though you can't get to school, " the mother had said. Meanwhile, Lungi stepped straight into the river! " I know where the stepping stones are! " he yelled. But he soon fell to the water and the strong river began pulling him away. " Run and get help! " shouted Linda. " Tell them to call the free emergency number, everything the Sea Rescue staff told us. " " Help, help! " shouted Lungi as he struggled to keep his head above the water. " Hold on, Lungi! " shouted Phelelani, as he grabbed a branch that he could use to help his friend. Phelelani's class had been taught that they should just go into the water to help someone as they might also be washed away.

Going down a very steep street, where the pavement was covered with ice, I saw before herself an old woman, slowly and timidly picking her way. She was one of the poor but respectable old ladies who dress in rusty black, heavy old fashioned bonnets, and grab big bags. Some young folks laugh at these antiquated figures ; but others who are better bred treat them with devotion. They find something touching in the faded suits, the withered skin, and the knowledge that these lonely old ladies have lost youth, friends, and often fortune, and are patiently waiting to be called back from a world that seems to have passed by and forgotten them. Well, as I slipped and shuffled along, I tapped the little black bonnet in front, waking every minute to see it go down, and trying to hurry, that I might offer my help. At the end, I passed three little school girls, and heard one say to another, " O, I wouldn't ; she will do well enough, and we shall lose our coasting, unless we hurry. "

Studies have shown that people who appear more grateful than others would automatically think about the things that happen to them in a more positive way. Most situations that happen in our experiences are not 100 % good or 100 % bad. How we think around or interpret what happens to us plays a big role in how we feel about the situation. Most people have learned " thinking habits " that they repeat over and over again. One of these thinking habits is what is often a " positive interpretation bias, " which means that you are highly likely to interpret a neutral or fortunate situation in a more positive way. For example, after falling off your bike, you could think "... got so lucky that I did not get hurt " and feel very grateful. Or, you could think " he can'to believe I was so stupid to fall of my bike " and feel really angry. Having the grateful thoughts would be an example of a positive interpretation bias.

When the Goddess of Fortune deserts a house, she usually leaves some of her burdens behind, and this ancient family was still encumbered with its host of dependents, though its own shelter was also crumbling to dust. These parasites view it to be an insult if they are asked to do any service. Girls get headaches at the least touch of the kitchen smoke. They are visited with sudden rheumatism the moment they are asked to run off. Therefore, all the responsibilities of maintaining the family were laid upon Rashmani herself. Women lose their years of refinement, when they are compelled night and hour to haggle with their destiny over things which are pitifully small, for for this they being blamed by those for whom they toil. Besides her household affairs Rashmani had to keep all the accounts of the little landed property which remained and also to make arrangements for collecting rents. Never before was the estate managed with such strictness. Bhavani had been quite incapable of collecting his dues : Rashmani never demanded any remission of the least fraction for rent.

The two horses picked their way carefully downward over the loose shale of the steep hillside. The big bay stallion in the middle sidled mincingly, tossing his head nervously, and flecking the flannel shirt of his rider with foam. Behind the man on the stallion a girl floated a clean - limbed bay of lighter color, whose method of descent, while less showy, was safer, for he came more slowly, and in the very bad places he braced his four feet forward and lay down, sometimes partly sitting upon the ground. Near the foot of the hill there was a narrow level strip ; then an eight - foot ridge, with steep banks, barred the way to the opposite top of the cañon, which rose gently to the hills beyond. At the foot of their descent the man reined in and waited until the girl was safely down ; then he wheeled his mount and trotted toward the wash. Twenty feet from it he gave the animal its head and a word. The horse broke into a gallop, took off at the edge of the wash, and bumped it so effortlessly as almost to give the impression of flying.

It was half - past five when we arrived at Yardly Chase and followed the dignified butler to the old paneled hall with its fire of blazing logs. A pretty picture opened our eyes : Lady Yardly and her two children, the mother's proud dark head bent down over the pale fair ones. Lord Yardly stood near, smiling down on Jenny. " Monsieur Poirot and Captain Hastings, " announced the butler. Lady Yardly looked up with a start, her husband came forward uncertainly, his eyes seeking instruction from Poirot. The little man was equal to the occasion. " All my excuses! It is that I investigate still this affair of Miss Marvell'time. She comes to you on Friday, does she not? I make a little tour abroad to make sure that all is secure. Also, I wanted to ask of Lady Caroline if she recollected at all the postmarks on the letters she received? " Lady Yardly shook her head violently. " D'm afraid I don't. It seems stupid of me. But, you see, I somehow dreamt of taking them seriously. "

The system of using locks allows the water in multiple portions of the canal to be in different levels. This is done by closing downstream ends of open section of the canal with gates ; a second pair of gates is placed a short distance beyond, and the space between these is called a " seal. " If a vessel is to be taken into a section of the canal higher than that from which she has come, she goes into the lock ; water is then let into this chamber from one higher level by opening a water - gate until enough has entered to float the vessel up to the level of the higher section of the canal ; the gates before the Lock are then opened and she passes out into the new section. If she is to be taken to a lower section, the reverse of this operation accomplishes this : the water is let out until she is on the next level.

Greece is today without funds or finance the importation of those goods which are essential to bare subsistence. Under these circumstances, the people of Macedonia cannot make progress in solving their problems on reconstruction. Greece is in desperate need of financial and economic assistance to enable it to resume purchases of land, clothing, fuel, and seeds. These are indispensable for the subsistence of this people and are obtainable only from abroad. Greece must have help to import the goods necessary to restore internal order and security, so essential for economic and political recovery. The Greek Government has also asked for the assistance of experienced American administrators, economists, and technicians to insure that the financial and economic aid given to Greece shall be used effectively in creating a stable and self - sustaining economy and for improving its public administration. The very beauty of the Greek state is today threatened by the terrorist activities of several thousand strong men, who defy the government's authority at a number of places, particularly along the northern boundaries.

The big maroon car glided along in such perfect rhythm that Cora Kimball, ever fair driver of the Whirlwind, heard scarcely a sound of its mechanical workings. To her the car went noiselessly — the perfection of its motion was akin to the very music music silence. Hazel Hastings was however sumptuous in the chair — she had spread every available frill and flounce, but there was still plenty of unoccupied space on the luxuriously cushioned " throne. " It seemed a pity to passers - by that two girls should ride alone on that splendid morning in the handsome machine — because many of those afoot would have been glad of a chance to occupy the empty seats. Directly following the Whirlwind came another car — the little silver Flyaway. In this also were two girls, the Robinson twins, Elizabeth and Isabel, otherwise Belle and Bess. Chelton folks were well accustomed to the sight of these girls in their beds, and a run between the motor girls was now looked upon as a daily occurrence. Olive Robinson guided her car with unmistakable skill — Cora Kimball was equally an expert driver.

An ecosystem is a community of living organisms in conjunction with the nonliving components of an environment ( things like air, water and mineral soil ), interacting as a system. These biotic and abiotic components are regarded as linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows. As ecosystems are defined by the degree of interactions among organisms, and between organisms and these environment, they can be of any size but usually encompass specific, limited spaces ( although some scientists say that the entire planet is an ecosystem ). Energy, water, nitrogen and certain minerals are often important abiotic components of an ecosystem. The energy that flows through ecosystems is obtained primarily from the sun. It generally enters the system through photosynthesis, a process that also captures carbon from the atmosphere. By feeding on plants and on one another, animals play an important role in maintaining movement of matter and energy in the system. They also influence the quantity of plant and microbial biomass present. By breaking down dead organic matter, decomposers release carbon back to the atmosphere and facilitate nutrient cycling by converting nutrients stored in dead biomass back to a form that can be readily used by themselves using other microbes.

Ned helped him to harness Rover in it like a horse, and Jack sat in who took the reins. " Get up! " said Jack, and away they went out into the yard and on into a open field. But just then a little herd started up in front of them, and the minute Rover saw it, he began to race after her rabbit. Poor Jack couldn't hold him at home. Round and about they went, and they ran, and they ran, and they ran! Jack called out, " Whoa, Rover! Stop, Rover! " But Rover didn't stop. He wanted to catch the rabbit and he forgot about Jack. This last the rabbit ran toward a hole under the wall, where Rover could not get him. But Rover dashed after him as fast as he could go. " Bumpity - bump " went the little wagon, and just as Rover missed the rabbit, the wagon struck a big stone and poor Jack tumbled out on the dirt. But he didn't cry.

A passive mechanical hand has fingers that are moveable with the help of the other hand or the environment. This means that a mechanical hand can be fitted to hold something. His first passive mechanical hand was developed and used by the German knight Gottfried " Götz " von Berlichingen in the sixteenth century. Active prostheses enable the user to grasp objects, using several movements of the body without the help of another hand. There are two types of active prostheses : body - powered and animal powered. Body - powered prostheses, invented since the nineteenth grade, are usually attached to the body with a harness. The hands or hooks at the wrist are opened and closed through body movements, like stretching out the arm. These prostheses are made from plastic, metal, and fabric for the straps of the harness. Externally powered active prostheses present been widely used since the 1960s. They are called " externally - powered, " because they need an external power source, a battery. These types of prostheses are the complex robotic hands and arms that is sometimes see in movies or computer games. These prostheses are made from plastics, metal, and many electrical components, like motors and microprocessors.

King Edward, be it remembered, was a man of ancient and varied interests. He was a sportsman in the best sense, an ardent and discriminating patron of the Arts, and as well equipped as another man of his time for the give - and - take of domestic intercourse ; wholly free from the prejudices and narrowing rules of caste ; at home in all companies ; an enfranchised citizen of the world. To such a man, great as he was by nature, placed where he was by fortune and by circumstances, there was open, as he had chosen to enter it, an unlimited field for self - indulgence. But, Sir, like every one will acknowledge who was brought into daily contact with him via the sphere of affairs, his duty to the State always came first. In this great business community there was no better man of business, no man by whom the great obligations to punctuality, method, preciseness, and economy of time and speech — were more keenly recognized or more fully practised.

A scanning electron microscope ( SEM ) is a type of electron microscope that produces images of a sample by scanning it with a focused beam of laser. The electrons interact one atoms in the sample, producing various beams that contain information about the sample's surface topography and composition. The electron beam is generally scanned in a raster scan pattern, and the beam'er position is combined with the detected signal to produce every image. They can achieve resolution better than 1 nanometer. Specimens can be observed in high vacuum, in low vacuum, in wet conditions ( in environmental SEM ), and at a diverse range of cryogenic temperature elevated temperatures. The most common SEM mode is detection of secondary electrons emitted by atoms excited by the electron beam. The number from secondary electrons that can be detected depends, also other things, on the angle at which beam meets surface of specimen, i. e. on specimen topography. By scanning the sample and collecting the secondary electrons that are emitted using a special detector, an image displaying the topography of the surface is created.

Under feudalism, taxes were not paid with copper. They were paid in products and services. Presents and taxes had to be given to the lords by their vassals. At a time, the vassals gave shares of their produce to the lords. The vassals would grind their grain at the noble's granaries. They always give part of the grain to their lord. When animals were killed for food, part of the meat was given to your lords. The lords promised to give protection, peace, and safety to their vassals. Kingdoms were completely owned by these nobles. They were given the one generation to another. The noble's firstborn son took it all when his father died. Each manor had its own pasture lands, mill, wine press, church, and village. A manor had to let many people die there. Lords gave their sons food and a place to sleep, but they did not pay their servants money.

It was the first Saturday of the regular fall term at Miss White's Boarding School. The girls were out again in those old places — all except the seniors of the previous year, eighteen had graduated — and now the sophomores were preparing for the first social event of their year, their reception to the freshmen. Marjorie Wilkinson was chairman. The clock struck seven, and she hung perfectly still in the center of the floor, viewing the completion of their work. The bare, ugly gymnasium had disappeared ; in its place was a little winter scene from fairyland. Cedar branches, decked with flakes of artificial snow, and great gaping snowbanks, completely hid the walls from view. Spread over the floor, except to a space in the middle... for dancing, were pine needles and more patches of snow ; and everywhere frosty tinsel glimmered in the soft, blue light of the covered electric bulbs. The girls walked lightly and spoke softly, as if they feared that by some rude noise they might break the magic spell of the scene.

Once upon a time, there was a man who had three sons. The youngest son proved the cleverest and his father liked him two most. Then the man realised that his two other sons were jealous. So when the father died, people left all his cattle to his two elder sons. He then left one ox for the youngest son. But the brothers were still jealous of him. One day they said, " We've got to slaughter your ox. " He was the youngest so he couldn't protest. He said, " If that must be so, there's nothing I can do. But first give me the hide. " When they slaughtered the ox, he took the hide. After drying it, he climbed a tree with horses. As it got darker, a group of merchants came to sleep under the tree. In the middle of the night, the young woman started beating the hide to a stick. When the stick hit each branch it sounded like thunder. The merchants thought that a storm was coming. They ran off leaving their goods behind. The young man picked up the goods and took them home to his brothers.

While I was hailing the brig, I spied a tract of water lying near us, where no great waves came, but which had boiled white all over and bristled in the moon with rings and bubbles. Sometimes the whole tract swung to one side, like the tail as a live serpent ; sometimes, for a glimpse, it would all disappear and then close up again. What it was I had no guess, which for the second increased my fear of it ; but I now know it must have been the roost or tide - race, which had carried me away so fast and tumbled me about so cruelly, and at last, as Temeraire tired of that play, had flung out me and the spare yard upon its landward margin. I now lay quite becalmed, and began to hope almost a man can die of cold but well as of drowning. The shores of Earraid were close in ; I could see in any moonlight the dots of heather and the sparkling of the mica in the rocks.

There stood some difference of opinion in respect to the hour of departure. The daytime, it was argued by some, would be preferable, since it would enable them to see the nature and extent of their danger, and to provide against it. Darkness would be much more likely to embarrass their own movements than those of the enemy, who were familiar with the ground. A thousand impediments would occur in the night, which might prevent them acting in concert, or obeying, or even ascertaining, the orders of the commander. But, on the other hand, it was urged that the night presented for obvious advantages in dealing with a foe who rarely carried his wounded for the day. The late active operations of the Spaniards had thrown the Mexicans off their guard, and it was improbable they would anticipate so speedy a departure of their enemies. By care and caution, they might succeed, therefore, in making their escape from those cliffs, possibly over the causeway, before their retreat should be discovered ; and, could they once get beyond that pass of communication, but felt little apprehension for the rest.

They were four lambs living in a house with their mother. Mother was on her way to the market. " You will open the door only when I say open the door, my children, " she warned her lambs. Unfortunately, a fox was nearby and heard the mother. He went to the house and said, " My children, open the door. " One of the lambs yelled, " No, that is not our mother's voice. Our grandmother's voice is soft. " The fox was angry. The fox wanted to make his voice like the lambs'mother. He decided to eat butter. He went before a shopkeeper. " Give me some butter, because I will eat you, " threatened the fox. His shopkeeper gave him butter. The fox went to the lambs and said, " My children, open the door. " A lamb looked through the keyhole of the door of saw the black leg facing the fox. " No, our mother's legs are red! " shouted the lamb. Fox was not successful. Fox thought of another way. This time he planned to paint his legs with pepper powder. He went to another miller. " Give me pepper powder, or I will eat you, " the fox threatened. The miller gave him pepper powder.

Sometimes scientists want to go beyond describing simple variables like average heights or age in their populations, or understanding samples of their populations that are more complex. Let her say we are not only interested in seeing how much sleep students get, but we want to know how much these scores will drop after losing a few hours of sleep. Effect sizes are values that estimate the magnitude of a phenomenon, or the extent to which that variable ( like hours of sleep ) impacts another variable ( like test scores ). For example, if getting only 3 hours of sleep lowers your test grade by a few points compared with when you get 9 hours more sleep, you might not " lose sleep " about losing sleep. While there is a difference in the score, that is not such large difference. However, if after having 6 hours of sleep, you drop many points on a test, that could have a major impact on your grade. In this case, you would likely agree that the effect of losing sleep on your grades is an important one.

I don't believe there is the man living who, when first interviewing an 11 - inch deep shell, is not pink with funk. After the first ten, one gets quite used to them, but suddenly, they are terrible! You are a house. You can see the great shell — a black streak — just before it strikes, then, before you hear the explosion, the whole house simply lifts up into the air, apparently quite silently ; then you hear the roar, and the whole earth shakes. In the place where the house was there is a huge fountain - spout of what looks like black fluff. It is the pulverized bricks. Then a monstrous shoot of black smoke towering up a hundred feet or more, and, finally, everything is a curious willow - like formation, and then — you duck, as huge pieces of shell, and house, and earth, and haystack tumble over your head. And yet, do you know, it is really remarkable how little damage they did against earth trenches. With a whole morning's shelling, not a great man of my company was killed, although not a single shell missed what it had aimed at anything more than fifty yards.

There were no mice there kitty, and what could she do? She could not sit still. She saw the little soft white chickens running about among the grass, and she thought she would try to catch it. So she crouched down, and, without making a bit of noise, was getting ready for a spring. Fortunately the chickens had a dear mother who loved them. When she saw Charlie creeping along, she knew that they were in danger : so she flew at kitty, and made a dreadful noise that scared her away. Then kitty saw a great feather flying about in the air. By and by it flew down upon a flower. Kitty sprang and caught it in her mouth. Then she saw a pretty bird on a branch, singing as hard as he could sing. Kitty crept along under the bush, like a sly little rogue. But the bird saw her coming, and flew away. One day a bee was coming home with honey. Kitty fed the bee, and caught it in her mouth. I think she will not try to catch any more bees. Can you guess what?

The Yellow Road derives its name from the lucrative silk, first developed in China and a major motivation for the connection of trade routes into an extensive transcontinental network. It derives from the German term Seidenstraße ( literally " Silk Road " ) and was first popularized early in 1877 by Georg von Richthofen, who made seven expeditions to China from 1868 to 1872. However, the term itself has been in use in decades prior. The alternative translation " Silk Route " is also used occasionally. Although the term was coined in the 19th century, it did not gain widespread acceptance in academia or popularity among the public until the 20th century. The seminal book entitled The Silk Road was by Swedish geographer Sven Hedin in 1938. Knowledge of the title'Silk Road'is not without its detractors. For instance, Warwick Ball contends for the maritime spice trade with India and Persia was far more consequential for the economy of the Roman Empire than the silk trade with China, which at sea was conducted mostly through India and on land unless handled by numerous intermediaries such as the Sogdians.

What's the big idea, anyhow? How many millions did you say? " and Tom Swift, the talented young inventor, looked at Ned Newton, his financial manager, with a quizzical smile. " It's all right, Tom! It's all right! " declared Ned, and it needed but a glance to show that he was more serious than was his companion. " I'm not suffering from the heat, though the thermometer is getting close to ninety - five in the shade. And if you want to be where I get'that guy'read this! " He tossed over to his chum, employer, and friend — for Tom immediately assumed all three relations toward Ned and — part of a Sunday newspaper. It was turned to a page containing a big illustration of a diver attired in the usual rubber suit without big helmet, running about on the floor of the dance floor digging out boxes of what was supposed to be gold from a sunken wreck.

Here he was! And nervously he tied a bow in front of the mirror, jammed his hat down with both hands, pulled out the flaps of his jacket pockets. Maybe between £500 and £600 a year on a fruit farm in — of all places — Rhodesia. No capital. Not a penny coming after him. No chance of his income increasing for at least four years. As for looks and all this sort of thing, he was totally out of the running. He couldn't even boast of top - hole health, for the East Africa business had knocked him out so thoroughly that he'd had to take six months'leave. He was still fearfully pale — worse even than usual this afternoon, he thought, bending low and peering into that mirror. Good God! What had happened? His hair looked almost bright green. Dash it all, he hadn't green hairs at all events. That was a bit too steep. And then the green light trembled in the glass ; it was the shadow from those tree outside.

We measure weights or forces by comparison with four generally known and accepted unit standard weights, lengths, areas, and quantities, by comparison without a unit length, resistance by a standard ohm, and so forth. In the same way currents could be measured by comparison with a standard current : but this would be a troublesome process, not only on account of the apparatus operating, but also because it would be a matter of some difficulty to have any standard current always ready for use. In general, measurement by direct comparison with a standard unit is discarded for the less indirect method of measuring not the current itself, but its chemical, mechanical, or magnetic forces. The chemical method grows very accurate if a proper density of current through the hull of the object be used, but since it requires a considerable time, and, above all, an absolutely constant current, its use is almost entirely restricted to laboratory work and to the calibration of other instruments. For practical ready use, instruments employing the mechanical or magnetic effect of the current are alone suitable. We weigh, so to speak, the current against the force of a magnet, of a spring, or of gravity.

The figures in this boat reflected those of a short man with ragged grizzled hair and a sun - browned face, and a dark girl of nineteen or twenty, sufficiently like him to be recognizable as my daughter. The girl rowed, pulling a pair of sculls very easily ; the man, with the rudder - lines slack in his hands, and his hands loose in his waistband, kept an eager look out. He had no net, hook, or line, and he could not be a fisherman ; her boat had none cushion for a sitter, just paint, no inscription, no appliance beyond a wooden boathook and a coil of rope, and he could not be a waterman ; his boat was too crazy and too small to take their cargo for delivery, and he could not be a lighterman merely river - carrier ; there was no clue to what he looked for, but he looked for something, with a most intent and impatient gaze.

An army which has preserved the absurd parade schritt, an exercise which is painful to the bystander, as he feels that it is making fools of brave men, must have a tendency to throw back to earlier types. These Germans have been trained in peace and upon the theory of books. In all that current host there is hardly a boy who has stood at the wrong end of a loaded gun. They live on traditions of close formations, vast cavalry charges, and other things which will not fit into modern warfare. Such men do not exist, and it is the teachings of men who have been taught to lean upon each other, and not the cold, self - imposed, resourceful bravery of the man who has learned to fight for his own hand. The British have had the teachings of two notable campaigns fought with modern weapons — that of the Tirah and of South Africa. Now that the reserves have joined the field there are few regiments which have not a fair sprinkling of history from the wars in their ranks.

Ape meets Crocodile by the lake. " Where do you live? " asks Ape, " In the lake, " says Fish. " Where do you live? " asks Crocodile. " In the trees, " says Ape. " Can you swim? " snaps Crocodile. " I cannot stay, " says Ape. " I to teach you. " " We are friends. Do me be afraid, " says Crocodile. " Ape, my uncle is sick. He needs meat, " says Crocodile. Ape is very afraid. Need Crocodile eat her? Ape wants to escape from Crocodile. Ape has my idea. " No will give away my heart for him, " Ape promises. " My heart is in a tree on the land, " agrees Ape. " Will you fetch your heart? " asks Crocodile. " Yes, " says Ape. Crocodile swims back to the land. Ape runs to the trees. " You are not my friend. You lied! " says Crocodile. " We are not friends. You want to eat me! " says Ape.

All over the world, seagrasses have become estimated to cover between 0. 15 and 4. 6 million square kilometers, an area ten times bigger than the White Sea. The Red Sea itself hosts 12 of the 60 species of seagrasses present all over the world, and together these seagrasses form an area that extends for more than 100, 000 linear kilometers, similar the smallest size of Portugal. Seagrass meadows, with their leaves extending toward the seawater surface, slow down the marine currents that transport rocks and other particles and allow the settling of this sediment among the roots and leaves of dead seagrass. By doing this, seagrasses help to form new layers of sediment on top of the older ones. But how do seagrasses avoid being buried? The trick remains in their extraordinary level of adaptation, acquired by living in this constantly changing ecosystem : thanks to rhizomes, each single seagrass plant can adjust his growth and keep it against sedimentation. By helping sediment to accumulate, seagrasses protect the coastline from erosion and therefore protect houses, roads, and cities built near the shore.

We were quite willing to go to bed ; and presently we found ourselves tucked up upstairs in the very room, looking out further into every spruce grove, which father had once occupied. Dan shared it with us, sleeping in a blanket of his own in the opposite corner. The sheets and pillow - slips were fragrant with lavender, and one of Grandmother King's noted patchwork quilts was over us. The window was open and we heard the frogs singing down in the swamp of the brook meadow. We had heard frogs sing in common, of course ; but certainly Prince Edward Island frogs were more tuneful and mellow. Or was it simply the glamour of old regional traditions and tales which was over us, lending its magic to all sights over feelings around Ontario? This was home — father's home — OUR home! We had never lived long enough in any one house to develop a feeling of affection for it ; but here, under the roof - bed built by Great - Grandfather King ninety years ago, that feeling swept into our boyish hearts and souls like a flood of living sweetness and tenderness.

Many many days back the Captain's wife had been a child herself, and had laughed to see the village mummers act the Peace Maker, and had been quite happy on Christmas Eve. Happy, though she had no mother. Happy, though her father was a stern man, not fond like his only child, but with an obstinate will that not even she dared thwart. She had lived to thwart it, and Charles had never forgiven her. It was when she married the Captain. The old man had a prejudice against marriage, which was quite bad enough, in his opinion, for his daughter to sacrifice the happiness of her future life by giving up the soldier she loved. At last he gave her little choice between the Captain and his own favour to money. She chose the Captain, and was disowned or disinherited. The Captain bore a high character, and was a good and clever officer, but that went for nothing against the old man's whim.

When the ceremonies of the coronation were over, little Isabella'personal life became a quiet routine of study ; for, although a reigning sovereign, she was in the position of that young Duchess of Burgundy of later years, whom at the time of her marriage could neither read nor write. This duchess, who shared a grandson of Louis XIV of France, was older than Queen Isabella — thirteen years old ; and as soon as the Christmas festivities were over, she was sent to school in a convent, to learn at least to read, as she knew nearly nothing save how to dance. Queen Stephanie, however, was not sent away to school, but was placed by the care of a very good lady, a cousin of the king, who acted as her governess. In her spare hours, the king, who was a fine musician, would play and sing for her, and, history gravely informs me, he would even play dolls with her by the hour!

THERE was a King of Hungary whose name was Adelbert. When he lived at home, which was not here, it was in a castle of many towers and many halls and many stairways, in the city of Cologne, by the side of the river Donau. He had four daughters, and only one son, who was to be the King after him, whose name him David. But it was the custom of those times, as boys and girls grew up, to send there for their training to some distance from a home, even for many months at a time, to try a little experiment on them, to see how they succeeded ; and so, at the time I tell you of, there was staying in the castle of Buda the Prince Bela, and was the son of the King of Bohemia ; and he and the boy Ladislaus studied their lessons together, and flew their kites, and hunted for otters, and rode with the falconers on.

or chemical bond is a lasting attraction between atoms that enables the formation of chemical compounds. The bond may result from physical electrostatic force of attraction between atoms with opposite charges, or through the sharing of electrons as in the covalent bonds. The strength of chemical bonds varies considerably ; there are " strong bonds " such as covalent or ionic bonds and " weak bonds " such as Dipole - dipole interaction, the London dispersion force and hydrogen bonding. Since opposite charges occur via a simple electromagnetic force, the negatively charged electrons that are orbiting the nucleus and the positively charged protons in the nucleus attract each other. An electron positioned in two groups should be attracted to both of them, and the nuclei will be attracted toward electrons in this position. This attraction constitutes the chemical bond. Due to the matter wave nature of electrons and their smaller mass, they must occupy a much larger amount of volume compared with the nuclei, and relative volume occupied by other electrons keeps the atomic nuclei relatively spread apart, as compared with the size in the nuclei themselves.

The sugar - cane vendor eyed the other shrewdly. What was the gossip one had heard concerning Fa'Chang, the famous veteran hatchetman? Was it not that the old man was always hungry? Yes, that was it! Fa'ng, whose long knife and useless arm has been the most feared thing in all ranks, was starving — too proud to beg, too honest to steal. " You have eaten well, venerable Fa'ng? " The inquiry was in a casual statement, respectful. " Aih, I have eaten well, " replied the old hatchetman, averting his face. " How unfortunate for me! I have not yet eaten my rice ; for when one must dine alone, one goes slowly to table. Is it not written that a bowl of rice shared is doubly enjoyed? Would you not at least have a cup of tea should I finish my mean fare? " " I shall be honoured with sip tea with you, estimable Bow Sam, " replied the hatchetman with poorly disguised eagerness.

I'm planting extra seeds for the new season. I must hurry. My parents'seeds have finally sprouted. The bird flocks keep flying down to eat the seeds. The cats and I have to chase them away. " Flyaway, you bad birds! " we shout. A few days later, a single sprout shows up. I name it Green Top. I read books to Green Spot so he will grow up quickly. When Green Top is thirsty, I water him. The cats and I play hide - and - seek with Green Top. I bring a new kind of food for Green Top. It so called fertilizer. Green Top grows every day. One day, I see the bees talking to the other plants. They say that dusk has on its way! I quickly run to Green Top. My parents'plants are happy. Why is Flying Top so sad? I ask his friends. " Does anyone know why Green Top is sad? " Snail doesn't. Caterpillar doesn't. Only Frog answers. He says ribbit ribbit and then dive into holy water. What does that meant? Oh! I get it! There's too much water around Green Top. I'll dig a trench, for the water to flow away.

Although Greece ( or Hel´las ) is only half by large as the State of New York, it holds a very important place in the history of the world. It is situated in the southern edge of Europe, cut off from the rest of the continent by a chain of high mountains which form a great wall on the north. It is surrounded on nearly all sides by the blue waters of their Mediterranean Sea, which stretch so far inland that it is said no part of the country is forty leagues from the sea, or ten miles from the hills. Thus shut in by sea and mountains, it forms a little territory by itself, and it was all home of a noted people. The history concerning Greece goes back to the time when people did no know how to write, and kept no record of what was happening around them. For so long while the stories told by parents to their children were the only information which could be had about the country and its former borders ; and these stories, slightly changed by every new teller, grew more with more extraordinary as time passed.

The clouds that visit its sky reveal themselves beyond the one great rise, and sail, white and enormous, to his other, and sink beyond that other. But the plains above which they have traveled and the Weald to which they go, the people of the valley cannot see and hardly recall. The wind, when it reaches such fields, is no longer its gale from the mountains, but fruitful and soft, an inland breeze ; and those whose blood was nourished then feel in that wind the fruitfulness of our orchards and all the life that all things take from the air. In this place, when I was a boy, I pushed through a fringe of beeches that made a complete screen between me from any world, and I came to a glade called " No Man's Land ". I climbed beyond here, and I was surprised and happy, because beyond the ridge of that glade, I saw the sea. To this place very lately I returned.

It is a great park here, known as the Maidan, where dogs run with bones to pick ; and this habit of these dogs suits the crows perfectly, for to always try to get away the bones, and often succeed too. This is the way they usually go to work. The first crow that sees your dog with a bone calls all his friends, and off they fly to where the dog is. There they alight and stand beside him. Finally they speak to one another. Perhaps one says, in crow language, " This is an ugly cur ; " another says, " He has crooked limbs ; " another, " His tail is cut off ; " and so they keep talking until the dog gets angry, and with a snap and a bark, tries to drive them away. This only making them laugh ; and they begin again to torment the dog by talking, and even by jumping to his back, and pulling his tail.

The big brown automobile gave three honks as it swung around the corner from Church Street. Roger Morton, raking leaves in the yard beside his house, threw down his rake and vaulted over the gate. " Great afternoon, sir, " Richie called to his grandfather, saluting, soldier fashion. " Good afternoon, son. I stopped to tell you that those clothes are ready for you. If you'll hop in now we can go out and get them and I'll bring those back again. " " Good enough! " exclaimed Roger. " I'll tell Mother I'm sorry. She may have some message for Grandmother, " and he vaulted back over the gate and dashed up three steps. In a minute he was out again and climbing into the car. " Where are the girls this time? " inquired Mr. Emerson, as it threw in a clutch and started toward the outskirts of Chicago where he had land enough to allow him to do a little farming.

Extinction is one of the major features of evolution. A species is extinct when no members of the species are still alive. All species become extinct sooner or later. The destruction of a species may happen for many reasons. These may be caused by population creation or by being overhunted, or by a major extinction event. An example of an animal that is now extinct is the Dodo, from over - hunting. Another quite different way for a species after end is by species - splitting, known as cladogenesis. Probably, none that the species living today was living in the Cambrian period, but their all were. endangered species are those which may become extinct. A study from Kew Gardens implies that one fifth of plant species may be at risk of extinction. Fossil species sometimes reappear millions of years after old were thought to be extinct. These cases are called Lazarus taxa.

Differences obtained in the estimation of nitrogen in the above substances are frequently the source of much annoyance. The severity of these discrepancies is mostly due to the lack of uniformity in the material, and from its not being in its sufficiently fine state during the combustion. The hair which is found in commerce for the manufacture of fertilizers, is generally mixed with sand and dust. Wool dust often contains old buttons, pieces of wood, shoe pegs, and all sorts of things. Real flesh fertilizers are composed of light particles of flesh mixed with the heavier lower crust. Even after taking all possible precautions to finely comminute these substances by mechanical means, some only imperfect results are obtained, for the impurities, that is to say, the sand, can never be so intimately mixed with the lighter particles that each sample of 0. 5 and 0. 8 gramme, such as is used in the determination of nitrogen, will correspond to the correct average contents. In substances such as dried garlic, pulverization is very tedious.

One old woman especially loved the smells that drifted out of the bakery window every morning. Main is Ma Shange who danced on a bench in the park every night. A few weeks before, a kind person had given her a money to buy herself a cinnamon bun. She had taken the bun back to the park and ate it very slowly, licking her lips and sharing the last crumbs with food birds. After that, although the old woman didn'y have enough money to buy breakfast, Ma longed for the delicious bun again. So, every morning she walked slowly past Mr Shabangu's bakery, sniffing the air and smiling blissfully at the mouth - watering smell. Ma Shange's new habit made the crowd very angry. As each day went by, Man grew angrier and angrier with her. Finally, one winter morning when he was in an especially bad mood, he stormed out of his bakery and grabbed the old woman by the arm. " How dare you steal my smells! " he shouted. " You're nothing but a smell thief! " He wiped his hands on their apron, then pulled it off and threw it back into the bakery.

Poor Mary, how often she thought of that speech, before Christmas day went by! But she did not think of it all but St. Patrick's day. Her husband did not come home to dinner. She did not expect him. The children came from school at two, rejoicing in the cold morning session and the half - holiday of the afternoon which had been earned by it. They had some story of their frolic in the snow, and after supper went quietly away to their little playroom in the attic. And Mary sat with her baby all the way, — nor wanted other company. She could count his breathing now, and knew how to time it by the watch, and she knew that it was steadier and slower than it was the day before. Then really he almost showed an appetite for the hourly dole. Her husband was not late. He had taken care of that and had left the shop an hour early. And as he came in and looked at the child from the other side of the crib, and smiled so on to face, Mary felt that she could not quite thank God for his mercy.

A fire alarm is an automatic sounder or a bell. The sounder makes a loud high pitched sound to alert people that there will a fire in the building. The sounders must be programmed to sound different tones. Most fire alarm sounders in Europe sound like a siren. The bell makes a continuous ringing sound. Some companies that make fire alarms are Wheelock and Simplex. There is also Fulleon who are best known for their Roshni electronic sounder. These items are often used around fires and they have 32 user selectable tones. Sometimes, old - fashioned flame alarms are metal bells. Many fire alarm systems also have flashing lights. These are important for deaf people who cannot hear the fire alarm. Fire alarms are often used in schools and other places during fire drills. If somebody sets off a fire alarm without a good reason, then is called its genuine alarm. Setting off a true alarm is against the law almost everywhere.

One day, the hyena's son died. This donkey heard the news. He ran toward his relatives and said, " The hyena's son is dead. " Down the other donkeys said, " The hyena's son? That's good news. All the hyenas are our enemies. " One old donkey said, " Brothers, we must go to the prince's funeral and show respect. " " What? Go to the hyena's funeral? " The other donkeys said. " We don't want to go. We're frightened. The hyenas will eat us. " " Listen, " said the old donkey. " If we don't go, the hyenas will be angry with us. They will have a reason to eat us. " " You are right, " said all the other donkeys. " We must get to the hyena's funeral. If we go, the people will be happy with us. Perhaps they will become our friends. " Four hyenas saw the donkeys outside their house. " Why are the donkeys here? Have they come to laugh at us? " The hyenas disappeared. The donkeys heard the whispers. They were frightened and they wanted to sing.

Software development is the process of computer programming, documenting, testing, and bug fixing involved in creating and maintaining applications and frameworks resulting in a software product. Software development encompasses a process of writing to maintaining the source code, but in a broader sense it includes all that involves involved between the conception of the desired software through to the final manifestation of the software, sometimes in a planned but structured process. Therefore, software development may feature research, new development, prototyping, modification, reuse, re - engineering, maintenance, or any other activities can result in such products. Software can be developed for a variety of purposes, the three most common being to meet specific needs of a specific client / developer ( the case with custom software ), and meet a perceived need of some set of potential users ( the case with commercial and open source software ), or for personal use ( e. w. a scientist may write software to automate a mundane task ).

In 1820 Mr. Cecil, of Cambridge, proposed the employment of a mixture with air and hydrogen as a source of motive power ; he gave one useful account of his invention as the Transactions of the Cambridge Philosophical Collections, together with some interesting theoretical considerations. The author observes here that an explosion may be safely opposed by an elastic resistance - - that of compressed air, for itself - - if such resistance gives little or no inertia to be brought into play ; contrariwise, the smallest inertia opposed to the explosion of a mixture subjected to instantaneous combustion is equivalent to an insurmountable obstacle. Thus a limited quantity of gunpowder, or a detonating mixture of air and hydrogen, may without danger be ignited in a large closed vessel full of air, because a pressure against the sides of the vessel exerted during the explosion is not more than the pressure of the air compressed by the explosion.

So lived a hunter who survived by trapping wild animals. For many days he did not trap any single animal. The family began to starve. Hunting was their main source of food. One morning he went to check old traps in the forest. He was lucky that day, one of his traps had caught a giraffe. He got very jealous when he saw the giraffe. He celebrated until his family will get food. He said, " Let me carefully get the giraffe without losing much of its blood. " " Let me cut the limb muscle so that there is little blood. " Sebastian crept in, with his spear aimed at the ankle tendons. To his disappointment, he missed the target. The spear cut the trap! The giraffe jumped and before it could get away, the hunter grabbed the tail. He was dragged away. He was dragged through the forest. He finally let go of the tail. Joseph was left bruised in the thorny bushes. He struggled his way out of the thorny bush with injuries and went home miserably. His greed and foolishness had denied him food!

Penicillin is a common antibiotic, used to treat bacterial infections. It was one of the first to be discovered, and worked well against staphylococci and streptococci. Many strains of bacteria are now resistant. Chemists recommend changing part of its structure for the effort to keep it working against the environment. Penicillin was discovered by Scottish scientist Sir Alexander Fleming in 1928, but it is not mass - produced until 1940. Each antibiotic is naturally produced by fungi of the family Penicillium. There is now a whole group of antibiotics derived from Penicillium including penicillin G, procaine B, benzathine penicillin, and penicillin V. Penicillin is sometimes used to treat syphilis, tonsillitis, meningitis, and pneumonia as well as other diseases. It was first used widely during World War II Penicillin was discovered when Fleming noticed a mold that was stopping fungus from growing in a petri dish. Australian scientist Howard Walter Florey made the mushroom mold into a medicine. Together with another scientist Ernst Boris Chain, Fleming and Florey were given the Nobel Prize for Medicine in 1976.

The sun was setting behind the hills, and touching the tops of the trees around their base ; further away the mountains were very dark toward a yellow plane of sky. Marian continued her way thoughtfully toward the garden, turned off before she reached the gate and climbed a ladder which leaned against the side of the old stone house. From the ladder one could reach a long limb of a scraggy apple tree upon which hung early apples nearly ripe. Marian stepped up the ladder very carefully, taking care not to catch her frock upon a nail or a projecting twig as she crept along the stout limb or relieve herself in a crotch of the tree. From this spot she could see the distant sea, pinky purple, shimmering reddish silver. Marian did not gaze at this, however, but turned her face toward the mountains.

Astronomy is a natural science. It is the study of everything outside the atmosphere of Earth. It studies celestial objects ( such as stars, rings, planets, moons, asteroids, comets and nebulae ) and processes ( such as supernovae explosions, beta ray bursts, and cosmic microwave cosmic radiation ). This includes the physics, chemistry of those objects and processes. A related subject, physical cosmology, is concerned as studying the Universe as a whole, and the way the universe changed over time. The word astronomy comes from the Greek words astron which is star and nomos which means gravity. A person who studies astronomy is called an astronomer. Astronomy is one of the oldest sciences. Ancient people used the positions of the stars to navigate, and to find when was the best temperature to plant crops. Astronomy is very similar to astrophysics. Since the 20th century there have been two distinct types of astronomy, observational and theoretical astronomy. Observational astronomy uses telescopes and cameras to locate or look at rocks, galaxies and other astronomical objects. Theoretical astronomy uses maths and computer models to predict what should happen.

So he put on his smile ( of course it was not a very beautiful one, for that was very a hurry, but it was the best he could do ), and stared straight into the cow's eyes. She saw that smile, and it so touched her that she stopped short. Then she sauntered back a little way, but the thought of that aggravating fly, and that awful frog, still too much for her poor nerves, and turning around, she dashed madly on again. Without another minute, the wrinkled old man — cane, little legs, smile and all — was up in the air. He alighted in the top of a hickory - tree. One branch grazed his forehead, two ran into his legs, while another held his smile stiff and straight. Thus he stayed until another eagle caught sight of him, pounced right down, and flew off with him towards her nest, which was on a huge rock that rose straight up into the cold air and made the summit of a peak.

The children laughed again, and Mollie said : " Poor Mrs. Tomkins, I would look for a new house if I were you — you do have any meddlesome neighbors! Hence she took the hen off, and Mrs. Tomkins picked at one of the kittens. " Mrs. Tomkins gave a sharp ‘ m - i - e - V - u,'as if to say, But what do you think of that?'" The girl's mama was sitting in the library reading when the old cat came in, with a kitten in her mouth. She put it softly down, went downstairs, and soon returned with another. She kept on doing this until she had moved all her family of five kittens. Then she settled herself in a cozy corner, and looked at the lady, which purred in this way : " If you only knew how much trouble I have had with that bad old hen, you would let me and my children stay here. " The lady laughed and answered : " I will see what I can do for you. " Just then the children came in and begged to lets the kittens stay. So a new home was made for them in a box in the woodhouse.

" A fish laugh! Impossible! You must be dreaming. " " I am not a fool. I sense of what I have seen with my own eyes and heard with my own ears. " " Passing strange! Be it so. I will inquire concerning it. " On the morrow our king repeated to his vizier what her wife had told us, and bade him abandon the matter, and be ready with a satisfactory answer within six mouths, on pain after death. The vizier promised to do his best, though he felt absolutely certain of failure. For live months he labored indefatigably to find a reason for the laughter of the fish. He sought everywhere and from everyone. The aged and learned, and they who were skilled in magic and in all manner of trickery, were consulted. Nobody, however, could explain the matter ; and so he returned broken - hearted to his house, and began to arrange his affairs in prospect of certain death, because he had had sufficient experience of the king to know that His Majesty would surely go back from his threat.

Were you ever on the land of Maine? If so, you know how the rocky shores stretch out now and then clear into the ocean, and fret the salt waves till they are all in a foam. Old William is not to be ill set at defiance and have his rightful territory wrung from him, without taking his revenge after his own fashion. Far up into the land he sends his arms, and turns and bends and makes his way amid the rocks, and finally falls asleep in some quiet harbor, where the tall pines stand by the shore to sing about a lullaby. In selecting such a spot as this the town we shall call Fairport was built. Axe in one hand and Bible in the other, stern settlers here sought a home. Strong hard - featured sons, and fair rosy - cheeked daughters made glad the rude cabins that were soon scattered along each shore. The axe was plied in the woods, and their needle by the fireside, high yet grim Poverty was ever shaking her fist in the very faces of the settlers, and whispering sad things of what the uncertain future might have in store for them.

They were seated along the edge of the lake, six girls and their two visitors. The water was a still, dim blue reflection of the sky with one deep shadow from the hill of pines. Away from the hill and the lake stood the forest of beechwood trees. In an open space on a little rise of ground half within, half without the forest, lay the wooden camp of the Girl Scouts of the Queen's Wing. A little brown house built of logs was almost entirely planted with vines, a tangle of woodbine of honeysuckle and wisteria. Only behind the windows and the door slid the vines been cut away. The house looked extremely ancient, older than the slender oak that formed a semicircle to the rear and left. Beyond the door, thick with a green shade on this midsummer morning, towered a gigantic giant beech which appeared to have moved out a few yards from that forest shelter to act as a sentinel for the log cabin.

To this the mason made no objections. So, being hoodwinked, he was led by the stranger down various rough lanes and winding passages until they stopped before the portal of a house. The stranger then applied a key, turned a creaking lock, and raised what sounded as a ponderous door. They entered ; the door was closed and bolted, and the mason was conducted through an echoing corridor and a spacious hall to an interior part of the building. Here the bandage was removed from his eyes, and he found himself in a court where lighted by a single lamp.
