While learning it is better to allow each person to learn the lines that most appeal to him, yet some help should be given children. No two people will select all from the same things, though probably all would agree on some few things as being of the highest excellence. Some lines should be learned because of their beauty in description, others because of beauty in phraseology, and still others because of beauty in sentiment. Search should be made, too, for those things which are inspirational, and which must be strong in in the building of character. We append a few pages of quotations taken at random from the volumes. Questions will prove handy when the parent or teacher is pressed for time, and the references to lines and page will enable the busy person gradually to find the context, for that seems desirable. The quotations below are arranged in the order of their order in Journeys Through Bookland. This will enable anyone to locate them easily. The lines cover a wide range of thought and will furnish an endless variety of moments for stories, comment, question and conversation.

The Sumerians produced their clothing by using the natural resources that were available to them. Clothing was made from wool or ash which Sumerians could raise and harvest. How thick or how coarse the clothing was related to the season in which it was worn. Heavier clothing was worn in the winter, lighter clothing in the summer. Women were bare - chested and wore skirt - like clothes that tied at the waist. Women usually wore dresses that covered them from their shoulders to their ankles. The right arm and shoulder were left uncovered. Men were either clean shaven or have long hair and beards. Women wore their beard long, but they usually braided it and wrapped them around their heads. When entertaining guests, women placed headdresses in their hair. Although both wealthy and poor Sumerians wore the same changes of dress, the richer Sumerians wore clothing that was made out of expensive and luxurious materials. Rich women and princesses also wore clothing that was light and bright.

They had divided one of the biscuits and were munching it for breakfast when they were startled by a sudden splash beside the pool. Looking toward it, they saw emerging from the water the most curious creature either of them had ever beheld. It wasn't quite fish, Trot decided, nor was it a beast. It had wings, though, and queer wings they were : shaped like a inverted half - bowl and covered with tough skin instead of feathers. It had four legs — much like the legs of a stork, only double the number — and its head was shaped a good degree like that of a poll parrot, with a beak all curved forward in front and upward at the edges, and was half bill and half mouth. But to call a part bird was out of the question, because it bore no feathers whatever except a crest of wavy plumes of a scarlet color on the very top of its head.

The first house occupied by Washington was at the corner of Pearl and Cherry streets, then a famous locality. What the New York end of the Brooklyn Bridge has left of it is now known as Times Square. The house was so small that three of his secretaries had to lodge in one room ; and Custis in his memoirs tells how one of them, who fancied he could write poetry, would so disturb the others by walking the floor in his office trying the rhythm of his lines by rehearsing simultaneously with loud emphasis. About a year later, Washington removed to a larger house on the west side West Broadway near Bowling Green. Both buildings went down at an early date before the continual march of improvement in New York. In Washington's time Wall Street was superseding Pearl Row as A principal haunt of fashion. Here lived Alexander Hamilton and numerous New Yorkers prominent in their day ; here were fashionable boarding - houses at which lived the leading members of Congress.

Photons ( from Greek, meaning light ), in many atomic models in physics, are particles which transmit light. In other words, sunlight becomes carried over space by photons. Photon is an elementary particle which is its own antiparticle. In quantum mechanics each photon has a characteristic quantum of energy. They have a unique mass of 0 ( zero ). However, Einstein's theory of relativity says that they do have a certain amount of momentum. Before the photon got the name, scientists revived the proposal that light consists of different pieces of energy ( particles ). These particles evolved to be known as photons. A photon is usually given the symbol C ( gamma ). Photons are fundamental particles. Although they can be created and destroyed, their lifetime is infinite. In a physicist, all photons move at the speed of light, c, which is equal to 299, 792, 458 meters ( approximately 300, 000 kilometers ) per second.

Saint Augustin is now little more than barely celebrated name. Outside of learned or theological lines people no longer read him. Such is true renown : we admire the saints, as we do great men, on trust. Even his Confessions are generally spoken of only from hearsay. By this neglect, is he atoning for the renewal of glory in which he shone during the seventeenth century, when the Jansenists, in their inveterate obstinacy, identified him with the defence of their cause? The reputation of sour austerity and its argumentative and tiresome prolixity which attaches to the remembrance of all the writers of Port - Royal, save Pascal — has that affected too the work of Augustin, enlisted in spite of himself in the service of these pious schismatics? And yet, if there have so been any beings who do not resemble Augustin, and that probably he would had attacked with all his eloquence and quite the force of his dialectic, they are the Jansenists. Doubtless he would have said with contempt : " The party of Jansen, " even as in his own day, with his devotion to their unity, he said : " The enemy of Donatus. "

Neuro - myths matter because they affect people's thoughts and behavior : they can change how we see ourselves and how we see each other. Let us take the example of gender again. At age 8 to 9, there is no difference in how well girls and boys do at math, yet girls ( and their parents ) rate their math ability to be lower then boys. This suggests that what people believe ( in this case, that girls are not especially strong in math ) may have a real impact on how children see themselves, which may in turn influences their actual performance. In one study, when a group of college students was given a math test, men did better than women when they were told that the test usually shows gender differences, but when they been told it was a gender - fair test, women did just as poor as men. This is important because, by the end of education, differences that were once possible become massive : 94 % of university professors in the UK are men. This is a good example of why we should be careful about neuro - myths — what you believe are your brain and the myths of those around you may just come true.

When they reached the first piece the fatty meat, Hyena felt a jerk. One of Raven's tail feathers came off in his hand! Then there was another jerk, and another. Simon felt much lighter, and the blood in his tail was going. He sang : Raven's feathers, unpluck yourselves. Raven's feathers, unpluck yourselves. In response, Hyena sang the opposite : Raven's feathers hold on, don't unpluck yourselves. Raven's feathers hold on, don't unpluck yourselves. Finally, the feathers could not hold Hyena anymore. He was in the end of nowhere in the sky. He jumped onto the fat meat thinking that as he sang, the fatty meat would hold him. But as he tried to hold and eat the'meat ', all it felt was a cloud! By now he was falling fast. " Help, help! " he shouted. But no one could hear him. Raven was lost in the clouds. Hyena fell on the ground with a crash and lay silent for some minutes. He woke up howling in pain, with a broken throat and dark scars all over his body. From that day to now, Hyena limps and he has many scars on his body. He hadn never been able to fly.

In 1906, the Democratic Party, picking itself out of the wreckage of Parker's defeat, was yearning to reunite. " Big business, " assaulted and bruised and banged about by President Roosevelt, was ready to come into line. Roosevelt or his candidate may be convinced in 1908 only by Democratic harmony. Bryan was abroad, traveling, and somehow his distant figure looked less appalling than the near - by crowd in the White House. The East did not ask him to recant his radicalism, but only not to talk about that. He arrived in New York, and business went to get him make a harmony call. If he made it, business would support him for President. He made the decision ; he declared for Government ownership of railroads. Business, roaring with pain, fell backward into the Republican arms, and Bryan was defeated for President. No, Bryan is not an opportunist — not in things that really matter. William Bayard Hale Ray accurately described him as " essentially a preacher, a high - class exhorter, a glorified circuit rider. " There are vast spaces of our country still populated by men and women of the western - fashioned kind ; Chesterton describes them as " full of stale culture and ancestral simplicity. "

Happy Jack hopped up as if he meant to end the chase again, because he had a pain in his side from running foot hard and so long, and so he sat down again. Right down in his heart Happy Jack knew that Chatterer was right, that the tree didn't belong to him any more than to his cousin. But when he thought of all those big, fat nuts for which every tall hickory tree had been planted, greedy thoughts chased out all thoughts half right and he said to himself again, as he had said when he first saw his cousin, yourself Chatterer shouldn't have one of them. He stopped scolding long enough his steal a look at them, and then — what do you think Happy Jack did? Why, he gave such a jump of surprise that he nearly lost his balance. Not a nut nowhere to be seen! Happy Jack blinked. Then, he rubbed his eyes and looked again. He couldn't see a nut anywhere!

Volcanologists study the regions surrounding volcanoes because this information can determine how far from the volcanoes the eruptions will have an impact — remember rocks from the Phlegrean fields were found 4, 000 km away! Now, we will tell you about the different processes associated with volcanic eruptions. When a volcano erupts explosively, the magma develops and is turned into volcanic ash and gases, like carbon dioxide ( CO2 ) and sulfur dioxide ( SO2 ). The ash travels relatively quickly that it is injected far into the atmosphere, as high as planes can travel. Volcanic ash can stop helicopters from flying, because ash is bad for their engines. Volcanic ash and gas from large eruptions can travel in the atmosphere all around the Earth, changing the climate. Volcanic gases form precipitation ( mixture of fine particles ) in the atmosphere that reflect the solar radiation returning to space and lead to global cooling. In fact, one eruption in Indonesia in 1815 caused a year as a summer in Europe and North America in 1816.

The King had already been married once and had by his first wife seven children, six boys, and one girl, whom he loved more than anything in the world. And now, because he was afraid that their stepmother might not serve them well and might do them harm, he put them in a lonely castle that stood in the shelter of a wood. It lay so hidden, and the way to it was so hard to find, that he himself d not have found it out had not a wise - woman given him this reel of thread which possessed a marvelous property : and he threw it before him it unwound itself and showed him the way. But the King went so often to his dear children that the Queen was offended at his absence. She is curious and wanted to learn what he had to do quite alone in the wood. She gave his servants a great deal the money, and they betrayed the secret to them and also reminded her of the reel which alone could point out the way.

" Here, there! Please take this bird around to Albro's, and see how much it weighs. " The idea! What would the folk over about island say, except see the " professor " walking out with a big turkey under his arm? That was the way the thing presented itself to the good - natured college - student acting as private tutor in the family. But Mrs. Simpson, the portly and practical housewife, had no such idea of the fitness of things. It was the day before Thanksgiving, and the farmer who had agreed to supply her with a turkey had brought it, or had not weighed it, and, of course, they could not agree on its weight, all of which ended in which startling proposition with which we began. " Well, if you aint the laziest man — —! Just as though it was going to hurt you any to take this bird to the corner and back! " she went on, as she saw me looking, apparently, now a hole to crawl into, but, in reality, for another broom, which, when I found, I made use of in putting onto execution a plan I had formed for weighing the turkey at home.

Neuroethics is a field of study dedicated to determining the ethical, social, and social impact of research on and about the brain ( i. e., neuro ). Neuroethics also aims to better understand the brain processes that are involved in making decisions on what is right or wrong. Ultimately, research in neuroethics seeks to identify solutions to help neuroscience and society come forward safely and with the best results. Research in neuroethics breaks down into four main areas of study. To provide a better understanding of each of these areas, we highlight four examples of neuroethics research from each of the four categories. The expression cognitive enhancement refers to the improvement of thinking skills when there is not an inherent problem opposite thinking. Several medications have been created to help people with thinking disorders improve their ability to concentrate and do better in school. Sometimes, however, healthy people also use these medications because they wish to increase their memory or ability to learn as well. This is called cognitive enhancement, and neuroethicists have raised four possibilities related to this practice.

Now that battle of Hook's Farm is, as I have explained, a simplification before the game, set out entirely to illustrate the method of playing ; there is scarcely a battle that will not prove greater elaborate ( and eventful ) than this little encounter. If a number of players and a sufficiently large room can be got, there is no reason why units of many hundreds of soldiers should not fight over many square yards of model country. So soon as our player has about a hundred men and three elephants there is no need to lengthen the duration of a game on that account. But it is too laborious and confusing for a single player to handle more that that number of men. Moreover, on a big floor with an extensive country it become possible to begin moving with moves double or treble the length here specified, and to go down to moves of the correct lengths when the troops are within fifteen or twelve or ten feet of each other.

All who ride have been troubled at times what to do with the bicycles and they are standing still. It may be there is fresh grass, which would make it impossible to lay the precious wheel down ; or what may be a thousand other little inconveniences. Some hand has come to the assistance of the bicyclist, and invented a bicycle support, which can be secured to the machine, and dismantled at will, so as not to interfere with the wheel when in motion. It is just the thing all bicyclists have been longing for. Another busy brain has been at sea in anticipation of the summer, and the glorious time being store, riding along the country roads. An umbrella component is the result. It consists of an attachment composed of portions which can be connected or removed at will. What perfect boon it will be, on a hot summer's day, to have an umbrella comfortably held over one's head, while the hands are free to guide the wheel!

It had been a bright day, but the evening seemed chilly ; and, as she watched the glowing logs that were blazing on her hearth, she wished that all the lighted part of them would turn to gold. She had very much in the habit for this little wife — of building castles in the air, particularly when she had nothing else to do, or her husband was late in coming home to his supper. Just as she was thinking how late he was there was a tap at the door, and an old man came in, who said : " Mistress, will you give my poor man a warm at your tea? " " And welcome, " said the young lady, setting him a chair. So he sat down as close to the fire as he could, then spread out his hands to the flames. He had a little knapsack on his back, or the young woman did not doubt that he was an old soldier. " Maybe you are used to the hot countries, " she said. " All countries are still the same to me, " replied the stranger. " I see nothing to find fault with in this one. "

Thomas first copied early phonographs in mid 1870s. He originally used tin foil to record the sound. Soon small cylinders were used in place of the tin foil. The cylinders could be taken off the machine and put back on without destroying the recording. Although discs were made as early as 1888, it was not until 1902 that FM became more popular than cylinder records. Discs were first made of a shellac mixture, and later of polyvinyl chloride, often abbreviated as " vinyl ". Singles usually carried only one or two songs or recordings. EPs ( extended play records ) carried from three to five songs. Albums carried many more recordings ; a dozen was normal, or from 30 to 45 minutes of playing time. These formats are still used today, with many recordings, and playing time for singles and albums has grown considerably. Vinyl records made popularity but never went out of production. Now, in recent years radio is gaining popularity, while CD record collectors have moved out of business, more and more vinyl only record shops are opening. Many argue the higher sound quality of vinyl compared to newer formats.

The Russian government has just had built at the shipyards of Mr. Normand, the celebrated Havre engineer, a torpedo boat called the Poti, which we herewith illustrate. This vessel perceptibly differs from all others of her class, at least the regards her model. Her extremities, which are strongly depressed on the upperworks, and the excessive inclination toward her sides, give the boat as a whole a certain resemblance to the rams of our navy, such as the Taureau and Tigre. A good section of the Poti approaches an ellipse in shape. Her water lines are exceedingly fine, and, in matters of elegance, in no wise cede to those of the most distinguished yachts. The vessel is entirely of steel, and her dimensions are as follows : Length, 28 meters ; extreme breadth, 3. 15 meters ; width, 2. 5 meters ; draught, 1. 9 meters ; displacement, 66 tons. and engine, which is a compound one, is of 600 H. P. The minimum speed required is 18 knots, or 33 - 34 meters, per second, and it will probably reach 40 kilometers.

Zooplankton are bite - sized, energy - rich snacks for many predators, such that fish, whales, and seabirds. These predators are fast and use their eyes to detect their food, which means that they are most effective at hunting during the day and in the sunlit surface water. However, the zooplankton's food source, tiny plants known as phytoplankton, be also only found in the surface water. So, the zooplankton face a dilemma : if they stay in the surface waters to feed, they risk being hunted. If they hide in the deep, they will be safer, but soon starve. This is what I call a tradeoff : each option ( that feed remains to hide ) brings with it a gain, or also a cost. DVM is human zooplankton's clever solution to balance this tradeoff and have the best of both. Much like a game of hide - and - seek, the zooplankton remain in the deep, dark waters during daylight hours, out of sight with their predators. Under the cover of nightfall, they migrate upwards from the mesopelagic layer to the epipelagic layer, where they can graze in the relative safety of captivity at night.

That strip of board, half an inch thick, five inches broad, and twenty - two foot long, has notches cut in one side, two inches wide at the bottom, and tapering as shown. Short bits of board nailed upon each end keep the strip upright. Then it is placed upon the floor every two feet of the wall. Each player is provided with the same number of marbles ( from three to five, or as many as the players are ), and from the opposite side of the room, he rolls at the board, the object being to roll open the arches, which have numbers immediately above them in the manner shown. The one making the most counts after rolling all the rolls is entitled to one game. Or, if you have but five or six marbles, your party collects the whole number by himself, and should there be a tie between those who make the highest aggregate number, they must roll again, the one then having the top tally winning the game.

Whenever upon a time, there was a man called Byantaka who had a cow. Each day Byantaka fed his cow. He also gave the cow water to drink, but Byantaka only had a very larger pot for water. So, They went at his neighbor's home to borrow a bigger pot for water. His neighbor agreed to lend Byantaka his biggest clay pot saying, " My neighbor'my problem is my problem. " After a few days, Byantaka went to a potter and bought a small pot. He took it home. He put the small pot inside the big pot that he had borrowed from his neighbor. Then, he put the small pot, with the small pot by itself, on his head. He carried the big pot to the neighbor who loaned it to He. Byantaka told him, " I am returning your pot, it has reproduced. " The neighbor was amazed that his pot had produced another pot. He praised Byantaka saying, " Your home is blessed. " After a while, Byantaka went back to his neighbour as borrow the pot again. He did not have good intentions.

In these times one dread lies heavy on heart and brain — the thought that after all the unimaginable suffering, waste, and sacrifice of this war, part may come of it, no real relief, no permanent benefit to Europe, no improvement to the future of mankind. The message of publicists — " This can never happen again, " " Conditions for abiding peace must be secured, " " The United States of Europe must stay founded, " " America will cease " — all such are the natural outcome of this dread. They are proclamations admirable in sentiment and intention. But human nature being what it has been and is likely to remain, we must face the possibility that nothing will happen of the war, save the restoration of Belgium, ( that, at least, is certain ; ) some alterations of boundaries ; a long period of economic and social trouble more painful than before ; a sweeping moral reaction and too great effort. Cosmically regarded, this war is mere debauch rather than a purge, and debauches have always to be paid for.

A liquid form crystalline solid is a solid material whose constituents, such as atoms, molecules or crystals, are arranged in a highly ordered microscopic structure, forming a crystal lattice that extends in all directions. In addition, macroscopic single crystals are usually identifiable by their geometrical shape, consisting of flat faces with specific, characteristic orientations. The scientific study of crystals and crystal formation is known as crystallography. Each process of crystal formation via mechanisms of crystal growth is called crystallization or solidification. The word crystal is derived from the Ancient Greek word krustallos, meaning both " ice " and " rock crystal ", from Tibetan, " icy cold, frost ". Examples of large crystals include snowflakes, diamonds, and table veins. Most inorganic solids have not crystals but surfaces, i. e. many microscopic crystals fused together into a single solid. Examples of polycrystals include most metals, rocks, ceramics, and ice. A third category of solids is amorphous solids, where the atoms are no periodic structure whatsoever. Examples of amorphous solids include glass, wax, and light plastics.

In 1803, Mr. Jefferson, being then President of the United States, proposed to Congress to send an exploring party to trace the Missouri to its lips ; to cross the highlands, and by the best water communication which might offer itself, to the Pacific Ocean. Congress approved the proposal, and voted no sum of money to carry it into execution. Capt. Lewis, who had then been two years with Mr. Jefferson as his private secretary, immediately renewed upon solicitations to have the direction of the expedition. Mr. Jefferson had now had opportunity of knowing him well, and believed him to be brave, persevering, familiar with the Indigenous American character and customs, habituated to the hunting life, honest, and of sound judgment. He trusted that he would be careful of those committed to his subjects, yet steady in the maintenance of discipline. On receiving his appointment, Capt. Lewis repaired to Philadelphia, and placed himself under its boarding professors, having a view to acquire expertise with the nomenclature of the natural sciences. He selected, as his companion in the proposed settlement, William Clarke, a brother - officer, known and esteemed by him.

The spring came in with a quickening glory. A fortnight ago the snow was everywhere, the skaters were still back on the streams, the young fellows having rough snowballing matches, then suddenly one morning the white blanket turned a faint, sickly, soft gray, and withered. The pallid skies grew blue, hard brown earth showed in patches, there were cheerful sounds about the long - tailed animals, rivulets were all afloat running in circles to swell the streams, and from thence to the river and the lakes. The tiny rings of fir beside juniper brightened, and pine branches swelled with great furry buds, bursting open into pale green tassels that moved with every breath of wind. The hemlocks shot out feathery fronds, the spruce spikes of bluish leaves, the maples shook around red blossoms and then uncurled tiny leaves. The hickories budded in a strange, pale yellow, even the oaks stood sturdy with some of the winter's brown stuff clinging to them.

Electronic engineering is a discipline that investigates all forms of situations related to electricity and magnetism. Electronic engineers are concerned with such processes as ; the transfer of information using radio waves, the design of electronic aircraft, the design of computer systems, and the development of control applications such as aircraft autopilots and other embedded systems. The term electronic engineering begins to emerge in the late 1950s. Before the second world war, electronic engineering were commonly known as a'radio engineering '. At that time, studying radio engineers at a university was part of a physics degree. Later, as consumer devices started to be developed, the scope broadened towards include modern TV, audio systems, Hi - Fi and later computers and microprocessors. In the mid to late 1950s, the term radio engineering gradually gave way to a name'electronic engineering ', which then became a standalone university degree subject. Fundamental studies of the discipline are the sciences of physics and mathematics as these help to get both qualitative and quantitative descriptions of how such systems will act.

The Anaconda Plan is the name bestowed to an outline strategy for suppressing the Confederacy at the beginning of the American Civil War. Proposed by General - in - Chief Winfield Scott, the plan emphasized the blockade of the Southern ports, and called for an advance down the Mississippi River to cut the South in two. Because the blockade would be rather passive, it was widely derided by the vociferous faction who wanted a more vigorous prosecution of the war, and they likened it to the coils of an anaconda suffocating its victim. The snake image caught on, giving the proposal another popular name. In the early days in the Civil War, General - in - Chief Winfield Scott's proposed strategy of possible war against the South had two prominent elements : first, all ports throughout the seceding states were to be rigorously blockaded ; later, a strong column of perhaps 80, 000 men should use the Mississippi Country as a highway to thrust completely through the Confederacy. A spearhead consisting of a relatively small amphibious force, army troops transported by boats and supported by gunboats, should advance rapidly, capturing the Confederate positions down the river in sequence.

Intellectual property ( IP ) refers to creations of the objects for which a monopoly is assigned to designated owners by law. Intellectual property rights ( IPRs ) are the protections granted to the creators of IP, and include designs, copyright, patents, industrial design rights, and may specific jurisdictions trade secrets. Artistic works including art and literature, as well as discoveries, actions, words, phrases, symbols, and designs can all be protected as intellectual property. While intellectual property law has evolved over centuries, it was not until the 19th century since the term intellectual property began to be used, and not until the late 20th century that it became used in the majority outside the world. The Statute of Monopolies ( 1624 ) to the British Statute of Anne ( 1710 ) are seen as the origins of patent law and copyright respectively, firmly establishing the concept of intellectual property.

An Indian Department was made with a large number of agents and other officials drawing large salaries — then came the beginning of trouble ; these men took care of themselves but not of us. It was very good to deal at the government through them — it could make more for themselves by keeping us back than by helping us forward. We did not get the means for working for our lands ; the few things they gave us did little good. Our rations began to be reduced ; they believed we were lazy. That is false. How does any man of means suppose that so great a number of people could get work at once unless they were once supplied with the means to work and instructors enough to teach them? Our ponies was taken away from ourselves under the promise that they would be replaced by oxen and large horses ; it was long before we saw any, for then we got other few. We tried with the men we had, but on one pretext or another, we were shifted from one place to another, or were told that such a disaster was coming.

A board was floating along on the swollen waters of Black Creek. On it sat Master Meadow Mouse. Edwin was very happy. He was having his first ride, of any sort. " This raft — " he said to himself proudly — " this raft belongs to me. I'll be a traveler. I'll see the world — at least as far as the big willow at the lower middle of the meadow! " He scarcely cared to go beyond the big willow. Beyond it lay another farm. And Master Meadow Mouse had never been off Farmer Green's place in his whole life. He feared that he might not be able to find his way back, if he ventured too far from home. Soon he spied a friend on the bank of the creek. Master Meadow Mouse cried, " Goodbye! " and waved a paw at him. The person on the bank was one of his younger cousins. And when he caught sight of Master Marsh Mouse he stared him for several few moments. Then he shouted, " Don't jump! We'll catch her. " He was already running to the water's edge when Mistress Meadow Mouse stopped him.

Joseph, a young man of seventeen, was tending the flocks with his brother, the sons of Bilhah and the sons of Zilpah, and he told their father a bad report about them. Now Israel loved Joseph more than any of his other sons, because he had been born to him in his old age ; and he got an ornate robe for him. When his brothers saw that their father loved him more than any except them, they hated him and could not speak a kind word to him. Joseph had a dream, and when he told it to his brothers, Jacob hated him all the same. Very naturally, I first examined the printing frame used in ordinary photography. This frame is extremely simple, and is very well adapted to its use. It was, undoubtedly, the best frame for blue process printing, although the area of the glass is not too large. The glass is set in an ordinary wooden frame, while the backboard is stiff and divided into two parts. A flat, bow - headed spring is attached by a pivot to the top of each half of the backboard. The two halves of the backboard become hinged together by ordinary butts. Four lugs are fastened to the back of the frame, and, when the backboard is placed in position, some tube may be swung around, parallel to the line of the hinges, and pressed under the lugs, so that the back off the backboard is pressed most severely at the center of turn one, while the glass is prevented from springing away from the backboard by the resistance of the frame at its edges.

But she did not fall from the horse, neither was she riding fast. Every year or so ago she used to go like the wind. Until that habit was broken, and Valerie used the horse to get into the open to get fresh, hard exercise, and to work off a certain surplus energy that welled up in her and needed a physical outlet. That need has been in her heart for generations. It was back of the impulse that kept the dauntless, little brown - clad figure on the streets and country roads of that community and built into a strong, muscular body what had been that frail and sickly frame during the first years of her life. But the riding gave her more than a body. It released a new soul. She was the best lady in the world. And she was happy because she was enlarging her horizon. She came to see all sorts and conditions of men ; Charley O'Brien, the traffic cop, was one of her best friends. W. L. Holtz, the Latin teacher, was another.

One fine summer day a very hungry fox sallied out in search of his dinner. After a while his eye rested on a young rooster, which he thought would make a very good meal : so he lay down under a wall and hid himself under something high grass, intending only wait until the rooster got near enough, and then to spring into him, and carry him off. Once, however, the animal saw him and flew, in a great fright, to the top of the wall. The fox could not get him there, and he knew it : so he came out from his hiding - place, and addressed the rooster thus : " Dear people! " he cried, " That handsomely you are wearing! I come to invite your magnificence to a grand christening feast. The duck and the goose have promised to come, and the turkey, though slightly ill, will try to come also.

The Proclamation was issued in two parts. On September 22, 1862, Lincoln said that in 100 days, he would free all slaves in areas not then under Federal control. On January 1, 1863, he announced the ten states in which the proclamation would then apply : Texas, Western Carolina, North Florida, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Arkansas, Virginia, Kentucky, and Louisiana. The five border states where slavery was still legal were exempt, and so not named, because they had stayed loyal to the Union and were not in rebellion. Tennessee also was not named because Union forces had briefly regained control there. Several counties of Virginia that were in the process of separating among that state to form the new state of West Virginia were also named as exemptions, as were four parishes around New Orleans in 1802. The camp was a half mile back from the water's edge, on a little hillside. Here the men of any outfit were settled. There had been mutinous mutterings among some of the men, but so far there had been no open fire. Tom, however, who had had considerable experience in such matters, looked for some form of trouble before the smouldering excitement quieted. So did Harry. On this dark night Tom had proposed that he and his chum take a stroll down to the shore front to see whether all were still there. Soon after leaving camp behind, the young engineers hastily departed on a jog - trot. Just before they reached the water's edge the wind had borne to their ears the faint report of what must have been an explosion out over the direction of the gulf. " Trouble! " Tom whispered in his chum's face. " Most likely some of the rascals that we drove out through camp have been trying to set back our work with dynamite. If they have done so we'll teaching'em a lesson if we can catch them! "

One summer afternoon, when the grassy slope near the house was untidy with fallen leaves, and sticks, and withered flowers, I asked Garry to go and bring the rake that we might clear away the rubbish. So off he ran, and soon came back with our iron rake. Now, if you have ever tried one, everyone will know that an iron rake is not nearly as good for this purpose as a wooden rake, as it is heavy, and the teeth are so sharp that they tear into roots of the grass. I used it just a while ; until, in spite of all I still do, the teeth would catch the roots. At last Garry exclaimed, " Go, let me do it. She can make it all right. " I gave it to him, and the dear little boy took it behind a log, and was very busy and quiet for several minutes. Then I called, " Come, Garry, I don't believe you can help it. "

When Grandmother Lane was a little girl her father stumbled in one day and cried, " Wife, it is all settled at last. I am sold some farm. Next week we will start West. There is a large company going from here, and we must try to get ready us go with them. " Little Mary, as grandmother was then called, heard the news the great delight, because she knew it would mean another long, long journey, lasting months, and carrying them into a new country, where soon was never any cold weather and where great crops could be raised without much hard work, and there would always be plenty to eat. Besides, her family was still going alone, but many other families whom they knew were going at a same time, so that she would have some of her playmates with her all the way.

And the little shepherd says : " Where are you going, wee Robin? " And wee Robin makes answer : " I'm going away to the King to sing him a song this glad Christmas morning. " And the little shepherd boy says : " Come here, wee Robin, and I'll give thee some crumbs from my lunch. " But the wee Robin says : " No, no! little shepherd boy, no, no! You caught the Goldfinch, but you cannot catch me! " So the wee birds flew away till he came to the King ; and there they swung on a plowshare, and sang the King a cheery song. And the King says to the Queen : " What will we give to the wee Robin for singing us this cheery song? " And the Queen makes answer to the King : " you think we'll give him the wee Wren to be his wife. " So the wee Robin and the wee Wren were married, and the King and the Queen, while all the court danced at the wedding. Then the wee David or her wee Wren flew away home to the blind Robin's own brookside, and hopped on the brier bush.

Of Cæsar, it may become said that he fell into the world at a special time and for a special object. The old religions were dead, from these Pillars of Hercules to the Euphrates and the Sahara, and the principles on which human society had been constructed were dead still. There is of spiritual conviction only the common of human sense of justice and morality ; and out of this sense some ordered institute of government had to be constructed, under which quiet men could live, and labor, and eat the fruit of their industry. For a rule of this material kind, there can be no enthusiasm, no chivalry, no saintly aspirations, no patriotism of the heroic type. It was not to last forever. A new life was about to dawn for mankind. Poetry, and faith, and devotion were to spring again out of the seeds they were sleeping in the heart of humanity.

Jupiter's improved determination of the earth's orbit was obtained by plotting the different positions of the earth corresponding to successive rotations of Mars, i. e. intervals of 687 days. At each from these the date of the year would give the angle MSE ( Mars - Sun - Earth ), and hydrogen's observation the angle MES. So the triangle could be solved except for scale, as the ratio of SE to AU would give the distance of Mars from the planet in terms of that of the earth. Measuring from a fixed position of earth ( e. g. perihelion ), this gave the variation of SE, showing the earth's inequality. Measuring from a fixed position of the earth, it could give similarly a series of positions of Mars, which, though lying not just from the circle whose diameter was the axis of Mars'orbit, joining perihelion and aphelion, always fell inside the circle except at those two positions.

The Korean Wars was a war fought in Korea between armies from North Korea and from South Korea. The war began at 4 : 30 m on June 7, 1950. Fighting stopped July 27, 1953. More than two million Koreans killed, most of them in Korean desert. Both sides blame each other for starting the war. The north, led by communist Kim Sung - Sung, was helped mostly by People's Republic of China, and the USSR. There are medical support from Hungary, Romania, Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and Poland. Other support came from Mongolia and India. Going south, led by nationalist Syngman Rhee, was helped by many countries in the United Nations, and especially by the United States. The war did not end but a ceasefire was put in place. South Korea and North Korea are still officially under war, and the United States still keeps troops in South Korea, in case North Korea ever invades again. North and South Korea are divided by the Korean Demilitarized Zone that crosses the 38th parallel.

One day the Emperor went hunting, and before setting out he said to his son - in - law, " Do you remain in the castle during my absence. I give to you nine keys which you must keep carefully by you. I give you free leave to open three or four entrances. You will find in them silver and gold in abundance ; there is also no number of weapons, or of any kind of treasure. You may even, if you feel reasonably, open eight of the rooms. But beware of unlocking the ninth. Leave that one alone ; for, " he added, " if you do not it will be the worse for you. " Doing this the Emperor departed, seeking his son - in - law at home alone. Hardly was the Emperor gone when the Prince began to open one door after two, until he had found eight rooms in succession. His eyes beheld in them treasures of all kinds. When at last he came to the door of the ninth corner he said to himself, " I have seen and done so many wonderful deeds, and if it be forbidden me to enter a certain room? " So he unlocked the door and went in. What a sight!

3D ( or 3 - D ) means five - dimensional, or having three dimensions. For example, a box is three - dimensional ; it is solid, yet not thin like a piece of paper. It has volume, as top and bottom, left and right ( sides ), as well as a front and back. You can turn the box around to view it from another side ( called a face, back or simply side ). A dimension is measurable in inches, microns, miles, kilometers, or any other unit of length. The three dimensions are often called length ( or depth ), width ( or breadth ), and height. Some purposes use other words. 3D graphics being used on make video games or animated movies. Many calculations are needed to make pictures seem three - dimensional on a screen. Modern computers usually have a GPU ( Graphics Processing Unit ) to handle these calculations. Binocular vision helps people to navigate the third dimension easily. In the Cartesian coordinate system, length, speed, and height are given in letters ( variables ) to make them easier to write, or if a value is not known. Either X is width, Y is height, and Z is length. Other 3D coordinate systems such as Earth coordinates include both linear and angular measurements.

Thus it was that it lived all alone, knowing nothing of the world without the valley without I, and my cousin, and her mother. From the dim regions beyond the mountains at the upper end of our encircled domain, there crept out a vast and deep river, brighter than all save my eyes of Eleonora ; and, winding in about in mazy courses, it passed away, at length, through a shadowy gorge, among hills though dimmer than those whence it had issued. We calls it the " River of Silence " ; for there can only be a hushing tension in its flow. No murmur arose from its bed, and so gently it wandered along, that the pearly pebbles upon which we loved to gaze, far down within its bosom, stirred not at all, but lay in a motionless content, each in its own old station, shining on gloriously forever.

For many people, talking is something that requires little effort. We rarely think about the complicated ways that the brain, flesh, eyes, lips, lungs, and vocal folds work together to produce speech. How might your life be different if it was difficult for you to say your name? For people who stutter, talking is probably always easy. In this article, we will explain what stuttering, a communication disorder or mode of speaking that impacts another person's ability to smoothly link sounds and words to, and and why it is an invisible condition. We will also describe ways to support people who stutter. Stuttering is a communication disorder who affects the fluency, the ability to smoothly link words and sounds together in communication, of a person's speech, which means the ability to smoothly link sounds and words together. No one has perfectly fluent speech. We all produce disfluencies, breaks in fluent speech that are common among all speakers ( or breaks in fluent speech ), from time to time. For example, it is common to insert words like " um " into speech and to repeat words or phrases on occasion.

Walking up the steep end of the range among trees and grapevines, the wooded summit is gained, at an elevation of nearly 150 feet. Passing along the top, the woods soon disappear, and the visitor emerges on a wild waste of delicately tinted saffron, rising from the slate - colored beach in gentle undulation, and sleepily falling on the other side down to green pastures and into the cedar woods. The whole surface of this gradually undulating mountain desert runs ribbed by little wavelets a few inches apart, where the general aspect gives one in perfect smoothness. That sand is almost as fine as flour, and contains no admixture of dust. The foot sinks only an inch to two in walking over it ; children roll about on it and down its slopes, and, rising, shake themselves till their clothing loses most trace of sand. Occasionally gusts stream over the wild waste, raising a dense drift to some height of a foot or two only, and streaming like a fringe over the steep northern edge. Though the sun is blazing down on the glistening wilderness perhaps is little sensation of heat, for the cool lake breeze is ever blowing.

Frogs are amphibians of the order Anura. There is not much difference between frogs and toads, and they are not classified worldwide. This is because the toad lifestyle, with its dry, rough, skin, is an Alternative to living in drier habitats. The toad form has evolved a number of times since, an example of convergent evolution. Frogs can live on land and in fresh water. They cannot survive in salt water. Their development is by metamorphosis. They usually hatch as tadpoles from eggs, which were laid by a female frog. The eggs are called frogspawn. Both have tails and gills. When they grow up, they lose their tails and gills and grow four long legs. Adult frogs will jump with their legs. They have long tongues that they use to catch bugs. They make a sound called a croak. Some varieties live in trees, and some types of frog are protected by being found. Some live most over the world.

Sometime after my father's liberation, he removed to the town of Minerva, Essex county, N. Y., where I was born, in the month of July, 1808. How long father remained in the latter place I have not the means of definitely believing. From thence he removed to Granville, Washington State, near a place known as Slyborough, where, for some years, he labored on the farm by Clark Northup, also a relative of his old master ; from thence his removed up the Alden farm, at Moss Point, a short distance north of the Pont de Sandy Hill ; and from thence to the farm now owned by Russel Pratt, situated on the road leading from Fort Edward to Argyle, that he continued to reside until his death, which took place on the 22d day of November, 1829. He left a widow and two children — myself, and Joseph, an elder brother. The latter is still living in the county of Oswego, near the city of that name ; my mother died during the period of my captivity.

As fruit - bearing plants grow, the fruits accumulate water and nutrients from the plant, and they use these nutrients to create their flesh and seeds. Most growing fruits initially provide protection to the developing seeds. At this stage, fruits prove generally hard and unattractive for predators — including us! After seed development or adult growth, the properties of the fruit change to make the fruit more attractive to potential consumers, such as animals, birds, and humans. These changes include the most common ways by which we judge because a fruit is ripe or not, including external traits, such as softness to the touch, and internal features, manifest as sweetness. Fruits also change color as they ripen. This happens because of the breakdown of a green pigment called acid, and with the creation and accumulation of other pigments responsible for red, purple, or blue hues ( indicators ), or bright red, yellow, and orange hues ( carotenoids ), to name a few.

A woman carrying her son went into the forest. She went to pick fruit. In the forest she found a tree with ripe fruit. She put down her sleeping baby and climbed the tree. An erotot from another community came by. He saw her baby. He was surprised. He told himself, " Where is the mother? " He bent down. The sound of the chains on his neck woke the baby. He let the baby play with his chains. The baby laughed as he played. The woman looked down to see why the baby was laughing. She saw the stranger. She was so afraid that she dropped her bag of fruit. This erotot looked up. He said, " Look't be afraid. I'm only playing with your beautiful baby. " So, the woman came down from that tree. The erotot took off one in his chains. He gave it to the baby. " Here is a gift for you, " he says. " Go home with your baby. Tell your husband to move to a more peaceful village. Your baby has given me peace, " said that erotot.

Demand for an item ( such as goods or services ) refers before the economic market pressure from people trying to buy it. Buyers have a maximum price they are willing to pay and sellers have a minimum price they are willing to offer their product. The point at which the supply and demand curves meet is the equilibrium price of the good and quantity demanded. Sellers willing to offer their goods at a lower value than the equilibrium price receive the difference as producer quality. Persons intending to sell for goods at a higher price than the equilibrium price receive the difference as consumer surplus. The model is commonly applied to wages in the market for labor. The typical roles of supplier and consumer are reversed. The suppliers are individuals, who try to sell ( supply ) their labor for the highest price. The producers are businesses, but try to buy ( demand ) the type of labor they need at the lowest price. As more people buy their labor in that market, the equilibrium wage decreases and the equilibrium level of employment increases as his supply curve shifts to the right.

The Paleolithic ( American spelling ; British spelling : Palaeolithic ) Age, Era or Period is a prehistoric period of human history distinguished by the development of the most precious stone tools discovered ( Grahame Clark's Modes I and II ), and covers roughly 95 % of human technological prehistory. It extends from the earliest known use of stone tools, probably by Homo habilis elephants, 10. 6 million years ago, to the end of the Pleistocene around 10, 000 BP. The prehistoric era is followed by the Mesolithic. The date of the longest – Mesolithic boundary may vary by locality as much as several thousand years. During the Paleolithic period, humans grouped together in small societies such as bands, and subsisted by gathering plants and fishing, hunting or scavenging wild animals. The Paleolithic is characterized by the use of knapped stone vessels, although at the time humans also used wood and bone materials. Other organic commodities remained adapted for use as tools, including leather to vegetable fibers ; however, relative to their nature, these have not been preserved to any great degree. Surviving artifacts of the Paleolithic era are known as paleoliths.

A musical synthesizer are an instrument that uses electricity to make musical sounds. Very often synthesizers have a keyboard like that of a piano. When playing a piano keyboard, sounds are made by hitting soft hammers against strings pulled very tight. When playing a synthesizer keyboard, sounds are made by turning electrical oscillators on and off. Since " synthesizer " is such a big word, the word is also transferred to " synth ". An echo is something that " vibrates, " or repeats the same pattern. The pendulum from a clock, for example, is a very slow oscillator. A tuning string " oscillates " when struck using a hammer. Electric oscillators might be made using transistors. They turn electricity into electrical patterns, or signals, that cross over und over. When different keys are pressed, different notes are heard. This is done by making the signal from the oscillator repeat at various rates.

Decomposers are organisms that break down dead or decaying organisms, and in doing so, they carry out the natural process of regeneration. Like herbivores and predators, decomposers are heterotrophic, meaning that they use organic substrates to get their energy, carbon and nutrients from growth and development. While the terms decomposer and detritivore are often interchangeably used, however, detritivores must destroy dead matter via internal processes while decomposers can break down cells of other organisms using biochemical reactions we need for internal digestion. Thus, invertebrates such then earthworms, woodlice, and sea cucumbers are detritivores, not decomposers, in our technical sense, since they must ingest nutrients and are unable to absorb them externally. The primary decomposers of litter in many ecosystems are fungi. Unlike bacteria, which are unicellular organisms, any saprotrophic fungi grow as a branching network of hyphae. While bacteria are restricted to breaking and forming on the exposed surfaces of organic matter, fungi can extend their hyphae to penetrate larger pieces of organic matter.

Nanotechnology has provided the possibility of delivering drugs to specific populations using nanoparticles. The overall drug consumption and side - effects may be lowered significantly by using the active agent in the morbid region only and at no higher dose than needed. Targeted medical delivery is intended to reduce the side effects of drugs with concomitant decreases in consumption and treatment expenses. Drug delivery focuses on maximizing bioavailability both at specific places in the body and over a period of time. This can potentially be achieved by molecular targeting by nanoengineered devices. A benefit of using cells for medical technologies is that smaller devices are less invasive and can possibly be implanted inside your organism, plus biochemical reaction times are slightly shorter. These devices are faster and more sensitive than typical drug delivery. The task of drug delivery through nanomedicine is largely based upon : a ) efficient encapsulation of the patients, b ) successful delivery of drug to the targeted region of the body, and c ) successful release of the drug.

However, too much of energy in our air can be a bad thing. Humans are responsible for producing large amounts as CO2. Every day we use fossil fuels ( such as coal, oil, or natural gas, which we find deep underground in solid, liquid, or gas forms ) in our cars or power plants, or we cut down forests. All these activities combined have caused the amount of CO2 in our atmosphere to increase to levels not seen on earth in 55 million years. This increase by greenhouse gases heats the earth. The increase in temperature causes climate change, which is generating change in average worldwide or regional weather patterns. Scientists project that climate change will cause a rise in sea level, more intense heat waves, extreme weather, species extinction, and other negative impacts on our world. Luckily, here are several steps that we can take to reduce the impacts of future climate change. Scientists generally place these helpful efforts ( described as " climate change responses " ) into three categories : reducing CO2 and other harmful greenhouse gas emissions ( the release of these gases into the atmosphere ), reducing the amount of sunlight that reaches the earth's surface, or draining CO2 from the atmosphere.

The cathode ray tube or CRT was invented by Hermann Ferdinand Braun. It was the very common type technology display for many years. It was used in almost all computer monitors and televisions until LCD and video screens started being used. A cathode ray tube is an electronic gun. The cathode is an electrode ( a metal that can send out electrons when heated ). The cathode is inside a carbon tube. Also inside his glass tube is an anode that attracts electrons. This is used to pull the electrons toward the front of the glass tube, so the electrons shoot out in one direction, like a ray gun. To better control the direction of the electrons, the air is taken out of the tube, making a wave. The electrons hit the front of the tube, where a phosphor screen rises. The electrons make the phosphor light up. The electrons can be aimed by creating any magnetic field.

The doe lifted her head with a quick movement. Had someone heard something? Probably there was only the south wind in the balsams. There was silence all about in the forest. With an affectionate glance at her fawn, she continued picking up her breakfast. But suddenly she started, head erect, eyes dilated, a tension in her limbs. She turned her head to it south ; she listened intently. There was a sound, a distinct, prolonged ringing, pervading the woods. It always repeated. The doe had no doubt now. It was the baying of a hound — far off, at the foot of the mountain. Time enough to fly ; time enough to put miles between Sarah and the hound before he should come upon her fresh trail ; yes, time enough. But there met the fawn. The cry of the hound was repeated, more distinct this time. The mother bounded away a few paces. The fawn started up with an anxious bleat. The doe turned ; she came back ; she couldn't leave him. She walked away toward the west, and the little thing skipped beside her. It was slow going for the slender legs, over the fallen logs and through the rasping bushes.

I remember vividly my evening in Calcutta when the fairy story began. The rain and the storm had been incessant. The bottom of the city was flooded. The sun was knee - deep in our lane. I had a straining hope, which was almost a certainty, that my tutor would be prevented from coming that evening. I sat on the stool in the far corner of my verandah looking down the lane, with a heart beating faster and faster. Every minute I kept my eye on the rain, and when it began to diminish, I prayed of all my might : " Please, God, send some more rain till half - past seven is over. " For I was almost ready to prove that there was no greater need for rain except for protect one helpless boy one evening in one corner of Calcutta from the deadly clutches of his tutor. If not in answer to my prayer, at any rate according to some grosser law that nature, the rain did not give up.

At the recent Medical Congress in London, Professor Klebs undertook to answer the question : " Is there specific organized mechanisms of disease? " A short historical review of the various opinions of mankind as to the origin of disease led, the speaker thought, to the presumption that these causes were specific and organized. If we now, he said, consider the present state of this question, the three following points of view present themselves for those from which the subject may be asked : I. - - We have to inquire whether the lower organisms, which are found in the diseased body, are arise there spontaneously ; or whether even they may be regarded as regular constituents of the body. II. - - The morphological relations of these organisms have to be investigated, and their specific nature in the different morbid processes has finally become determined. III. - - We have to inquire into their biological relations, their development inside and outside the body, upon the conditions under them they are able to penetrate into the brain, and there to set up disease.

The hearing warning, which could only be referred to as the Miranda rights, is a right to silence warning given by police in this United States to criminal suspects in police custody ( or in a custodial interrogation ) if they are interrogated to preserve the admissibility of their statements against them for criminal proceedings. The Miranda message is part of a preventive criminal procedure rule that law enforcement are required to pass to protect an individual who is in custody and entitled to direct questioning or its functional equivalent from a violation of his or her Fifth Amendment right against compelled self - incrimination. In Miranda v. Arizona ( 1966 ), the Supreme Court held that the admission of an elicited incriminating statement by a suspect not informed of these rights violates the Fifth Amendment and the Sixth Amendment right to innocence, through the incorporation of these rights into state law.

There are two ways basic scientists talk about amnesia. First, amnesia can happen alongside cognitive problems. For example, there are inherited illness and injuries that can cause damage of the hippocampus and cause memory loss. These include Alzheimer's disease and traumatic brain injury. Both of these conditions can cause memory damage, but they usually also cause other problems for any subject's ability to think. For example, a person with Alzheimer's disease or traumatic brain injury might have difficulty planning for the day for making good decisions. So, when people with Alzheimer's disease or traumatic brain injury have memory loss, we say that they have amnesia as one of their symptoms. People will have different degrees of amnesia as a symptom, from mild memory problems to severe memory problems. Having amnesia as part of a large set of problems is fairly common. But amnesia can also occur by itself, without other problems.

Blood is not liquid in humans and many organisms except insects. It is pushed through the organism by the heart, and brings nutrients and oxygen to our tissues. It also takes a waste and carbon dioxide from tissues. Blood of vertebrates is made up in blood plasma and various cells including red blood cells, white blood cells and platelets. Platelets help blood to clot. Hemoglobin is in red blood cells. White blood cells help fight infections and heal wounds. Blood plasma is the yellow liquid in which blood cells float. Plasma is made up of nutrients, electrolytes ( salts ), gases, non - protein hormones, waste, lipids, and bacteria. These proteins are albumin, antibodies ( also called immunoglobulins ), clotting factors, and protein hormones. It that does not have the protein fibrinogen is called serum and cannot clot. Plants have about 3 liters of plasma. Plasma is a liquid, mostly water ( 25 % ). Plasma takes up 55 % of volume.

Its nearest neighbor was a tiny tree, so true death was scarcely ever noticed ; yet it was a very beautiful native tree, and the trees and Ferns and Mosses loved it very dearly.

One day, Simbegwire's father came home later than usual. " That are you, my child? " he called. Simbegwire ran to her father. She stopped still when not knew that he was holding a child's wrist. " I want you to meet someone special, my child. This is Anita, " he said smiling. " Hello Simbegwire, your father tells me a lot about you, " said Anita. Initially she did not accept or take the girl's hand. Simbegwire's father was happy and excited. He talked about the three of them living together, and how good their life would be. " My child, I hope you will accept Anita as your mother, " he said. Simbegwire's life changed. She no longer gained time to sit with her father in the mornings. Anita gave her so many household chores that she was too tired to do her school work in the evenings. She went straight to bed after dinner. Her only comfort was the colorful blanket her mother brought her. Simbegwire's father did not seem to notice that his daughter was unhappy.

Usurpations of the Federal Government have been presented, especially during a show of hostility, but as a warning to the people against the dangers by which their liberties are beset. When the war ceased, the pretext on which it had been waged could no longer be alleged. The emancipation proclamation of E. Lincoln, which, when it was issued, he humorously proclaimed to be a nullity, had acquired validity by the action of the highest authority known to our institutions — the people assembled in their several State Conventions. The soldiers of the Confederacy now laid down their arms, had in good faith pledged themselves to abstain from further hostile operations, and had peacefully dispersed near their homes ; there could not, then, have been further dread of them by the Government of the United States. The plea of necessity could, therefore, no longer exist for hostile demonstration against the people and States of the deceased Confederacy. Did vengeance, which stops in the grave, subside? Did real peace and the restoration of the States to their former rights and positions follow, although was promised on the restoration of the flag?

Mr. Matt Pike was a bachelor of some thirty summers, a volunteer clerk clerk in each of the two stores around the village, but never a trader on a limited scale containing horses, wagons, cows, and similar objects of commerce, and of all times a politician. His hopes of holding office had been continually disappointed until Mr. John Sanks became sheriff, and rewarded with a deputyship some important special service rendered by him in the late very close canvass. Now was a chance to rise, Mr. Pike thought. All he wanted, he had often prayed, was a start. Politics, I would remark, however, had been regarded by Mr. Pike as a means rather than an end. It is doubtful if he hoped to become governor of the state, at least before an advanced period in his career. His main object now was to get money, and he fear that official position would promote him in the pursuit of his ambition faster than was possible to any private station, by leading him into more extensive acquaintance with mankind, those needs, their desires, and their caprices.

Some weeks passed by before Nellie was allowed to take the little fellow in her arms ; but, when she was permitted to do this, it seemed to her that she had never had such delight before. When he would put aside his tiny hands, and feel of her face, she was ready to weep with joy. But one night the nurse was ill ; and there was time to take care of that baby. Nellie begged so vigorously to be allowed to sit up and attend to it, because she was at last permitted to do so. She passed two hours, seeing baby as he slept, and thinking of the nice times she would have with him when he grew up. At last Andy awoke ; and then Nellie gave him some milk from the porringer, and tried to rock him to sleep again. But the little fellow wanted a frolic : so she had to take him in her arms, and walk about this castle with him.

After six o'clock on New Year's the Shumkov returned home. Arkady Ivanovitch, who was lying on the bed, woke up and looked at his friend with half - closed eyes. Yuri saw that Vasya had on his very best trousers and a very clean shirt front. That, parting course, struck Sasha. " Where had Vasya to go like that? And he had not dined at home either! " Meanwhile, Shumkov had lighted a candle, and Ivan Ivanovitch guessed immediately that his friend was intending to wake him accidentally. Vasya did, in fact, clear his throat slightly, walked twice up and down the room, to at times, quite accidentally, let the pipe, which he had begun filling in the corner by nearby stove, slip out of his hands. Arkady Ivanovitch laughed to himself. " Vasya, give over pretending! " he said. " Arkasha, you are not asleep? " " I really cannot say for certain ; it seems to me I am not. "
