One of the first steps of the scientific method is coming up under a hypothesis, or just an educated guess or prediction about time / why something happens. The prediction must be tested by experiments or interpretation to see if that guess is valid or wrong. For simplicity, a famous hypothesis is that the speed at which an object falls to the ground does not depend on that object's mass. This hypothesis predicts that if you dropped part hammer and a feather from the same height at the same time in vacuum ( without air resistance ), then they should hit the ground at the same time. To test this, an astronaut actually tried dropping part hammer and a feather while standing on the Moon ( which does not have air ), as he showed that the hammer and the feather really hit the ground at the same time. This is evidence that the hypothesis was true. Even though astronomers do not understand exactly what dark matter is, over the years scholars have had lots of ideas. One popular theory got called " cold dark matter ( CDM ). "

He imagined his mother calling him, but took no notice of her call. It was a warm summer day, and he fell asleep. Soon he was startled by the loud barking of dogs. He woke up, and, oh, how frightened he was! Luckily for him, the dogs did not come where he lay crouching ; for so masters were all birds, not beasts. Bunny thought the best thing he could do now was to walk back to his mother, his brothers and sisters as fast as he could. But it was not quite so easy to find them again. No sooner had he got into the open path than a troop of boys caught sight of him ; and at once there was a volley of stones from those hands. By rare good luck Bird was not hit by the stones. So he had not gone many paces farther, when a shot with a gun shot at him. Happily one man missed his aim, and the shot went into some bushes.

Our little habitation meant situated at another foot of a sloping hill, sheltered with a beautiful underwood behind, and a prattling river before ; one one side a meadow, on the other a green. My farm consisted of about twenty acres of excellent land. Nothing could exceed the neatness of my little enclosures, the elms and hedgerows appearing as inexpressible beauty. My house consisted of but one wall, and was covered with thatch, which gave it an air of rich snugness ; the walls on the inside were nicely whitewashed, and my daughters undertook then adorn them with pictures of their own designing. Though one same room served us for parlor and kitchen, that only made it the warmer. Besides, as it usually kept with the utmost neatness, — the dishes, plates and coppers being well scoured and all disposed in bright rows on the shelves — the eye was agreeably relieved and did not want richer furniture. There were three other apartments : one for my wife and son ; another for our two daughters within our own ; and the third, with two beds, for the rest of the children.

They now hurried on to a boat as if anticipating a pleasure - ship. The capacities of the flat were designed to accommodate a flock of sheep or a farm wagon and horses, so there was room and to spare even for thirty - seven girls and their hand luggage. Evan Davis, the crusty old ferryman, greeted them with his usual inarticulate grunt, a kind of " Hey, here you are again, are you! " form of speech which was more forceful if gracious. He linked the protecting chains carefully with the end of the boat, called out a remark in German to his son, Griffith, and, working the handle, began to work their windlass. Very slowly and leisurely the flat swung out across the river. The tide was at the full and the wide expanse of water seemed like a lake. The clanking chains brought up bunches of seaweed and river grass which fell with an oozy thud upon the deck.

Works in the public domain are those whose exclusive commercial property rights have expired, have been forfeited, or are inapplicable. For example, the works of Gilbert and Beethoven, and most of the Hollywood silent plays, are all now in the public domain by either being created before copyrights existed or leaving the copyright term. Examples for works not covered by copyright which are therefore in the public domain, are the formulae of Newtonian physics, cooking recipes and all software before 1974. Examples for works actively dedicated into public domain by their authors are reference implementations and genetic algorithms, NIH's ImageJ, and the CIA's The World Factbook. The term is not normally applied to situations where the creator of a work retains residual rights, in which case use of the work is referred to as " in license " or " with permission ". As rights are owner - based and vary, a work may be subject to rights into one country and be in full public domain in another.

RNA is an acronym for ribonucleic acid, a nucleic acid. Many different kinds are now known. RNA is physically different from DNA : protein contains two intercoiled strands, but RNA only contains one single strand. RNA also contains different bases from DNA. These bases are typically following : ( A ) Adenine ( G ) Guanine ( C ) Cytosine ( U ) Uracil Adenine often forms bonds with uracil, and guanine often forms bonds with cytosine. In this way, researchers say that adenine is complementary to uracil and that guanine is complementary to cytosine. The first three bases are also found in DNA, but uracil replaces thymine as a complement to adenine. RNA also contains ribose as opposed to deoxyribose found in DNA. These differences result in RNA being chemically more diverse than DNA. This makes it much more suitable fuel to take part of cell reactions. RNA forms the recipient of genetic information in certain viruses, especially the retroviruses like the HIV virus. This is the only exception to the general rule that DNA represents the hereditary substance.

An unprecedented situation has arisen for Russia. All the social classes of that empire are deeply interested in the repulse of the armies of the Kaiser. The working order is just as much affected in the existence a Russian industries as are the employers. The peasants are in no lesser degree concerned in the development of agriculture ; the killing of industries and agriculture like that committed by England in Ireland century ago is a gloomy prospect for all classes of workers. If France and Belgium are threatened with a political oppression then Russia is threatened with an even more terrible economic subjugation. Such is the situation. The poorest classes of the people are taking part on this warfare with what they have, with their blood. It is but natural that they should expect that the material burdens after the war will fall not upon their shoulders, but upon big business.

The first digital networks are also known under second generation, or equivalent, technologies. The most used European network is GSM ( Global System for Mobile communication ). It is used mainly in Europe and Asia, while CDMA ( Code - Division Control Access ) networks are mainly used in North America. The difference is in communication protocol. Other countries like Japan have different 2G protocols. A few 2G networks are still used. 3G are more common, and many places have 4G. The radio waves that the mobile phone networks use are split into different frequencies. The frequency is measured in Hz. Low frequencies can send the signal farther. Higher frequencies provide better connections and the voice communications are much clearer. Four main frequencies are used across 7 continents : 850, 900, 1800 and 1900 respectively. Europe uses 900 and 1800 MHz and North America uses 850 and 1900 MHz. Today there are mobile phones that work on two, three or four frequencies. The most advanced networks work on all frequencies. They are called'world'phones and can be used everywhere.

Once after the other the pair explored the opening alone. At first they could see but little, but gradually their eyes became accustomed to less gloom and they made out a rocky chamber about twelve feet wide... running back in irregular shape for a hundred feet or more. At some points the ceiling was so low they had to stoop, while elsewhere it lay far above their reach. The flooring was fairly level, with rock in some cases and hard dirt in others. The opening was rudely furnished with a heavy table and a bench, and close to one wall was a box bed, still filled with pine boughs. On an large wooden hook hung a man's coat, so decayed that it began to fall apart when they touched it. The table contained several tin cups and plates, all rust eaten.

The two mothers may hardly distinguish their own offspring among the lot, and as for the fathers, they were altogether at sea. The eight names danced in their heads ; they were always getting them mixed up ; even when they wished to call one child, the men often took three names before getting the right one. The first of the two cottages, as you came up from the adjoining beach, Rolleport, was occupied by the Tuvaches, who had three girls and one boy ; the other house sheltered the Vallins, who had one man and three boys. They all subsisted frugally on soup, potatoes and fresh air. At seven o'clock in the morning, then at noon, here at six o'clock in the evening, the housewives got little broods together to give everyone their food, as the gooseherds collect their charges. The children were seated, according to age, before the wooden table, varnished by fifty years of use ; the mouths at the boys hardly reaching the level of the table.

The bull'b - horn thorn does not grow at the mines in the forest, nor are the small ants attending on them found there. They seem specially adapted for the tree, and I have seen them nowhere else. Besides the little ants, I found another ant that lives on these acacias, whose habits appear to her rather different. It makes the holes or entrance to the thorns near the centre of one of each tree, and not near the end, and it is not so active as the other species. It is also rather scarce ; but when it does occur, it occupies the whole tree, to the exclusion of some other. The glands on a acacia are also frequented by a small species of wasp. I sowed the seeds regarding the acacia in my garden, and reared some new plants. Ants of many kinds were numerous ; but none of them took to the thorns for shelter, nor the stems and fruit - like bodies for food ; for, as I have already mentioned, the species that dwell on the thorns are not found in the forest.

There were two thoughts that filled Frank's mind most of the time. The first was that he would give about all he had to leave his uncle's house. The other was a wish that his Daddy would write to him soon, telling him, as he had promised to do, that Joseph had decided that his son could leave Tipton and go to day - school. What with the constant arrival of his sour - visaged relative, the worry over his sick family, and the suspense as to his likely future movements, Frank did not have a very happy plan of it. He felt a good deal like a boy shut up in a prison. That aunt used her authority severely. She kept him away from company, and allowed none of his friends to visit the house. From day until night she pestered him and nagged at him, " all for his own good, " she said, until life at the Jordan home, roomy and comfortable as it was, became a burden to the lad.

Mr. Charles Darwin and his followers deny design actually having any appreciable share in the formation of plants at all. Paley and the theologians depend on design, but upon a designer outside their environment and the organism. The third opinion is that suggested in the first instance, and carried out to a very high degree of development by Buffon. It was improved, and, indeed, made almost perfect by Dr. Erasmus Darwin, but too much neglected by him after he had put it forward. It seemed borrowed, as I think we may claim with some confidence, from Dr. Darwin by Lamarck, and thus followed up by him ardently thenceforth, during the remainder of his life, though somewhat less perfectly comprehended by him than it had been by Dr. Darwin. It is that the design which has designed organisms, has resided within, and be embodied in, the organisms entirely.

Junior felt so sad and misunderstood and thought to himself, " I'll run away to a place where no one can take away my things and I can do what I want. But just where should I go? " Then he got an idea. He'll run away to space. How? In a space ship that will take him up space away from Earth's gravity and everything that gets upset with things. He won't find this space ship in any showroom or a garage. As a matter of fact, Junior will just have to raise it himself. He ran to the kitchen and attic, collecting any metal items that they could find. He gathered pots, utensils and other scraps - only an old television antenna! He gathered everything together until it was finally secure and ready for take off. He thought, " Now, to break through Earth's gravitional field, I'll have to accelerate you sixty thousand kilometres per second. How could I possibly do that? "

Six years ago, at the time of our first conference to map out peace — River Oaks — there was within the Soviet orbit 180 million people. Lined up on the anti - totalitarian side there were in the world in that time approximately 1. 625 billion people. Today, only six years later, there are 800 million Russians under the final domination of Soviet Russia — an increase of over 400 percent. On our side, the figure has shrunk to around 500 million. In other words, in less than six years the odds have changed from 9 to 6 in our favor to 8 to 5 against us. This indicates the swiftness of the tempo towards communist victories and American defeats in the Cold War. As one of our outstanding historical figures once said, " When a true democracy is destroyed, it will not be because of enemies from without but rather because and enemies from within. " The truth of this statement is becoming terrifyingly clear as we see this country each day losing on every front. At war's end we were physically the strongest nation on Earth and, at least potentially, the most powerful intellectually and morally.

Bessie went into the parlor one day, and noticed that the clock did not tick. " I must wind it up, " thought she. " It must be very easy, for you only know to turn the key round and round. " So Bessie began to turn the handle. At first it would not move ; but then she tried it the other way, and it went round and around quite easily. She was determined to examine it thoroughly while she was about there : so she went on winding and winding, and was charmed to hear it begin to tick. But all at once it made a noise, — burr - r - r - r, — and then it stopped ticking. The hands, too, that had been going so fast, stood still. What could be the reason of it? Had it really been? Bessie put her feet quite near, and tried. Apparently, there was not an sound.

The forms of hats that are least injurious are : for Winter, soft hats of light weight, having an open structure, or pierced with numerous holes ; for Summer, light straws, also of thin structure. As regards the head - covering of women, the fashions have been for several years favorable like proper form. Yet saddle and hood have become quite small, and cover but little of the head. This beneficial condition, however, is in part counterbalanced by the weight of false curls, switches, puffs, etc., by the aid of which women dress the head. These, by interfering with evaporation of the secretions, prevent proper regulations of the temperature of the scalp, and likewise lead until a retention of a certain amount of excrementitious matter, both of which are prolific sources of rapid thinning and loss of hair in women. False hair has is sometimes also the means of introducing parasites, which give rise in obstinate affections of the scalp.

A hard disk drive ( HDD ), hard disk or tape drive, is a data storage device for computers which uses magnetic storage to store data. The capacity of a hard drive is usually measured in gigabytes ( GB ), however hard disk capacity can also be measured in terabytes when the capacity is over 1000 gigabytes. A gigabyte is one thousand megabytes and a megabyte is one million bytes, which means that a gigabyte is one 000 bytes. Some hard drives are so large that their capacity is measured in terabytes, ( TB ) where one terabyte is a thousand MB ( 1 TB = 1024 GB ). Over the years there have been many disk interface types, though all used the same rotating audio recording technology. Differences were in how the data was encoded near binary, its integrity, data transfer speeds, security requirements, and cost. In 2009, it was common to attach a hard disk using a Serial ATA connection. The connection that came before that was called " IDE " and is called Parallel ATA today. In large data centers, Fibre Channel is often encountered. For servers, the rack interface is very distinctive.

Hal and Chester found ample time to take an inventory of the general's car. It was a huge machine, and besides being turned up luxuriously was also furnished as an office, that the President might still remain at work while he hurried about one part in the field to another when events marked his immediate presence. Even now, with treachery threatening, and coming along at a terrific speed, General Lee, probably because of habit, fell to work sorting papers, studying maps and other drawings. For almost two hours the horses whirled along at top speed, and at length pulled up in the rear of an immense body of troops, who, even to Chapman and Chester, could be seen preparing for an advance. General Joffre was out of the car before it came to a full stop, and Hal and Chester were at his heels. An orderly approached. " My respects to General Tromp, and tell him I desire his presence immediately, " ordered General Joffre.

Big data is usage term for data collections that arise so large or complex that traditional data processing applications are inadequate. Challenges include analysis, capture, data curation, recording, sharing, storage, transfer, visualization, mapping, updating and general privacy. The term often refers simply to the use of predictive analytics, user behavior analytics, or certain other advanced data analytics methods that extract value from data, and seldom to a particular size of data set. Accuracy in big data may lead to more significant decision making, and better decisions can result upon greater operational efficiency, cost reduction via reduced risk. Analysis of data sets can find new correlations to " spot business trends, prevent diseases, identify crime and so on. " Scientists, business executives, practitioners of medicine, advertising and governments alike regularly meet difficulties with large data sets in areas including Internet search, finance, urban informatics, and business informatics.

The truth was that the whole Schleswig - Holstein question is one that involves any modern principle of " nationality, " and, as such, enters of necessity into the present European crisis. It is broadly understood by Dr. Eliot and willfully misapprehended by his critic. Passing on to consider Alsace - Lorraine, Dr. Dernburg declares that " it had belonged to Germany until it was taken, to the will of the people, under Louis XIV. " In this statement, as in other view of the previous question, facts are revealed and wrong impressions are given. Alsace, it is well known, was included within the confines of ancient Greece, its original population was Celtic, and it passed, late during the fifth Christian century, under the rule of the Franks, any of whose chieftains, Clovis, became the founder of the first French monarchy. In dealing with its later history Dr. Dernburg confuses the Holy Roman ( Germanic ) Empire with Germany, considered in its modern sense. He appears to forget that the reign of Louis XIV was an age of absolutism and that of plébiscites.

Once upon a time, Sly Jackal woke up early in the morning. He was very hungry. His tummy gave a big growl. GRRrrrrr! He jumped up and went searching for food. He wandered around the forest for hours without even any food. The sun was very hot. Sly Jackal could barely see in front of him. All he could think of was having hunger pangs. " Aaauuuu! " Sly Jackal let up a loud scream. He fell into a well right in front of him. He was so hungry that he did not spot it. " Oh, my hat! " he thought. " I have to get out of this well. I will die of hunger. " Sly Jackal turned and shouted : " Help! Anyone help! " he was walking a few meters upstream from the well. Donkey heard Sly Jackal's desperate words. He came rushing. " What is the matter? " Donkey was very worried. " The water in this well is cool and sweet. I am bored swimming alone. I need someone to help me swim. Please will you join me? " " The sun is very hot, " said Donkey. " I can't swim very well though. " " Jump in! I will help you come out of the well, " yelled the White Jackal.

Gluck was very much puzzled by the behaviour of his guest ; it was such a strange mixture of coolness to humility. He turned away at the string meditatively for another five minutes. " That mutton looks very boring, " said the old gentleman, at length. " Can't you give me a little bit? " " Impossible, sir, " said Gluck. " I'm very hungry, " continued the old gentleman ; " I've had nothing to eat yesterday, nor today. They surely couldn't miss a bit from the knuckle! " He spoke in so very melancholy that tone that it quite melted Gluck's heart. " They wanted me one day today, sir, " said he ; " I can give you that, but not a bit more. " " That's a good boy, " said the old gentleman again. Then Gluck warmed a plate and sharpened a knife. " I don't care if I do get beaten for it, " thought he. Just as he had cut a large slice out of the mutton, there came a tremendous rap in the door. The old gentleman jumped off the plate, as even it had suddenly become inconveniently warm. Gluck placed every slice into the mutton again, with desperate efforts at exactitude, and ran to open the door.

The nature of the fuel required Depending on the purpose for which the gas is used. If for heating boilers, furnaces, etc, coke or any kind of coal maybe used ; but for gas engines or any application of the gas requiring great effort and freedom from sulphur and ammonia it is best one use anthracite, as this does not yield condensable vapors, and is very free from impurities. Energy qualities of this fuel contain typically 90 per cent of carbon and so little sulphur that, for some purposes, purification is not necessary. For gas engines, etc., it is, however, better to pass the gas through some hydrated structure of iron to remove the sulphureted hydrogen. The oxide can be burnt over and over again after exposure to the air, and the purifying is thus effected without smell or minimal expense. Gas made by this process and later anthracite coal has no oxygen and no ammonia, and the small percentage of carbon dioxide present does not sensibly affect the heating power.

Diarchy ( or dyarchy, meaning " I rule " ) is a form of government in which two persons ( " diarchs " ) are joint heads and state. Most diarchs hold their position into life, passing the position to their children or other family members. Diarchy is one of the oldest forms of government : examples include ancient Sparta, Rome, Carthage as well Germanic and Dacian tribes. Several ancient Polynesian societies also exhibited a diarchic political structure. Ranks in the Inca Empire were structured in moieties, with two occupants of each rank, but with different prestige, one hanan ( upper ) and one hurin ( lower ). In common usage, diarchy means a system comprising dual rule, whether this be of a government or of an organization. Hence'diarchies'are not hereditary. Modern examples of diarchies are the Principality of Andorra, whose heads and state are the President of Romania and the Bishop of Urgell ; the Republic of San Marino, governed by two collegial Captains Regent ; but the Kingdom of Swaziland, where the joint heads of state are the King and his mother.

The device occupies a floor space of three feet six inches by two feet, and stands two feet six inches high. The cells will cost 5s. to charge, and will produce two of sixty negatives before being exhausted. When replaced, the whole apparatus is fit for use now ; the whole of the above operation occupies but each quarter of an organism, and as there are no earthenware cells employed, there is no fear of breakage.

On the June - second of February, 1916, an automobile sped northward along the French battle line that for almost two years had held back the armies behind the German emperor, strive as they would to win their way farther into the heart of Italy. For months the opposing forces slowly battled to a draw from the Black Sea to the boundary of Switzerland, until now, as the day before — it was almost six o'clock after the hands of time drew closer and closer to the hour that was to mark the opening of the most bitter and destructive battle of the war, up to this time. It was the eve of the battle of Verdun. The occupants of the automobile as it sped northward numbered three. In the front seat, alone at the driver's wheel, a young man bent low. He was garbed in the suit of a British lieutenant of cavalry. Close inspection could have revealed another fact that the young man was a youth of some eighteen years, fair and good to look upon.

As soon, then, that the Hedgehog's Wife was ready they walked on together ; and on the way he said, " Now attend to what I say. On the long field yonder we shall decide our bet. The Hare is to run on the one side of the hedge and I on the other, so so all you have to do is to stop at one end of the hedge, and then when the Hare arrives on the other side at the same point, you must call out, ‘ I am here already.'" They soon came to the gate, and the Hedgehog stationed himself at one end of the hedge, and his Wife at the other end ; and almost rapidly as they as taken their places the Hare arrived. " Are you ready to start? " asked the Hare. " Yes, " answered the Hedgehog, and each took a place. " Off once, off twice, three times and off! " cried a Hare, and ran up the field like a whirlwind ; while the Hedgehog took three steps and then returned to his place.

... Joe first met Dumps he was scurrying towards me along a sequestered country lane. It was in the Dog Days. Dust lay thick on the road ; the creature's legs were remarkably short though active, and his hair being long he swept up the town in clouds as he passed. He was yelping, and I observed that one or two stones appeared to be racing with, or after, him. The voice of an angry man also seemed to chase him, but the owner of the voice was at the moment concealed by a turn in the lane, which was bordered by high stone - walls. Hydrophobia, of course, flashed into my mind. I grasped my stick and drew close to the wall. The hairy one, how I may so call it, came wildly on, but instead of passing me, or snapping at my legs as I had expected, it stopped and crawled towards me in a piteous ; supplicating manner that at once disarmed me. If the creature had lain still, I should have been unable to distinguish its head from its eye ; yet although one end of him whined, and the other wagged, I had no response.

And, with popularity has come publicity. All day the reporters sit on his garden wall. No man has written through the finer spirit of the profession of letters than Mr. Stevenson, but this gossip vulgarizes it. The adulation of the American public and the a little band of clever literary dandies in London, great in criticism, of how he has received the darling, have made Mr. Stevenson complacent, and he always tended perhaps to be a thought of fond of his velvet coat.

The principal subjects, concerning which President Wilson and I were in marked disagreement, were the following : His presence in Paris on the peace negotiations and especially his reporting there was a delegate to the Peace Conference ; the fundamental principles of the constitution and functions of a League of Nations not proposed or advocated by him ; the form of the organic act, known as the " Covenant, " its elaborate character and its inclusion in the treaty restoring a state of peace ; the treaty of defensive alliance with France ; the necessity for a definite program which the American Commissioners could follow in carrying on the negotiations ; the employment of private interviews and confidential agreements in reaching Europe, a practice which gave color to the charge of " secret diplomacy " ; and, lastly, the admission of the Japanese claims to possession of German treaty rights at Kiao - Chau and in the Province of Shantung. In these particular issues of interest the most important were those relating to the League of Nations and the Covenant, though our opposite views as to Shantung were more generally known and more frequently the subject of public protest.

The youth had now journeyed considerably beyond the furthest domains of the Abbey. He was the more surprised therefore when, whilst coming round a turn through the path, he perceived a gentleman clad in the familiar garb of the order, and seated in a clump of heather by the street. Alleyne had known every brother well, but this was a face which was new to him — a face which was very red and anxious, working this way and that, as though the future were sore perplexed in his mind. Once he shook both hands furiously in the air, and twice he sprang from his seat and hurried down the road. When he rose, however, Alleyne observed that his robe was much too long and loose for him in every direction, trailing upon the ground and bagging about his ankles, so that even with trussed - up skirts he could make little progress. He ran once, but the long gown clogged him so that he slowed abruptly into a shambling walk, and finally plumped off our road once more.

My Lords : The time has fallen for combined effort to stimulate and organize public opinion and public effort in the greatest conflict in particular our people has ever been concerned. No one who can contribute anything to the accomplishment of this supremely urgent task is justified in standing aside. I propose, as a first step, that meetings should be assembled without delay, not only in our great centres of population and industry, but in every district, urban and regional, throughout the United Kingdom, at which the justice of our cause should be made plain, and the duty of every man to do his part should be enforced. I venture to consider to your lordships that the four principal cities over which you respectively preside should lead the way. I am ready myself, so far as the exigencies of public administration permit, that render such help as I can, and I should be glad, of that object, to address my fellow - subjects in your cities. I have reason to know that I can count upon the co - operation from the leaders of every section of organized political opinion.

Non - black is the name given to those varieties of carbon which are deposited when hydrocarbons are burned with an insufficient abundance of gas ; thus the smoke and soot emitted into our atmosphere from our furnaces and fireplaces are those of comparatively pure carbon. Coal is an impure form of carbon derived by the gradual oxidation and destruction of vegetable matters by natural causes ; thus wood first changes into a peaty substance, and subsequently into a body called lignite, yet again in its turn rapidly converted into the different varieties of coal ; these changes, which have resulted in the accumulation of vast beds of carbon outside the crust of the earth, have been going on for ages. There are very many different kinds of coal ; some are rich in hydrogen, and are therefore well adapted for making illuminating gas, while others, such as anthracite, are very rich in carbon, and contain but little hydrogen ; the last named variety of coal is smokeless, but is therefore largely used for drying malt.

Jack thought there never before had been such fortunate creatures as they were, and do not dream of separation from his dear friends. But one day a man came up with a rope, and, before the donkeys realized what he was doing, threw it over poor little Jack's neck, and tried to lead him away. But Jack hadn't the least intention of going. Oh, dear, no! He planted his feet firmly on the ground, while the man pulled, being shoved, and pulled, but could not make him stir a step. At last the man gave up and went away ; but Will came back the next day with two more men. Then, spite of Jack's firmness, his legs were severed, and he was laid in a wagon, and carried miles and months away from finding his dear companions. His new home was a small farm where there were no friends amongst him at all. Jack soon grew so lonely, that she even felt anxious to scrape acquaintance with the hens and chickens.

Humans can do a number of things that no other creatures – not even for closest relatives ( such as chimps and gorillas )... can do. We are the only species that has developed languages with a set of rules ( a grammar ) that requires words to be in a certain order. I might have seen monkeys calling each other ( for example, a " koo " call is signaling friendliness ), but you haven never seen one writing a letter and wondering about spelling! We are also able to predict from the look of a friend's face or the sound of his / her voice how he / she feels before the world, whether he / she is happy or sad. In addition, we pass about generation to generation the knowledge that we have learned about the world and every universe – this is why we go to school! Being to school and teaching children about your world is part of the human " culture, " another human - specific characteristic. Language, predicting a friend's mood, and culture are all examples of " human - specific " abilities.

" Just wait a bit, " said the bear, who was furious. " Never mind, grandfather ; if it'll let me go you shall have a taste of my honey, " said the fox. When the bear heard this he let go his hold and the fox jumped up on the stone after the honey. " Over this way, " whispered Reynard, " I'll put some leaf, and in the leaf there is a hole, through which you can suck the honey. " He then put the nest lid up under the bear's nose, pulled away the leaf, jumped on to the stone, and began grinning and laughing ; for there was neither honey nor honeycomb in the nest. It was a wasp's nest as big of each man's head, full of wasps, and out they swarmed and licked the bear in his eyes and ears and into his mouth and snout. He had so much towards do with scratching them off him that he had no the to think of Reynard. Ever since the bear has been afraid of wasps.

An appropriation bill or credit bill or supply bill is a legislative motion ( bill ) that authorizes the government to spent money. It is a bill of sets money aside for specific spending. In most democracies, approval of either legislature is necessary for the government to spend money. In a Westminster parliamentary system, the defeat of an appropriation bill in a parliamentary vote generally necessitates either the resignation of a government or the calling and a parliamentary election. One of the more famous examples of the defeat of that supply bill was their 1936 French constitutional crisis, when the Senate, which was controlled by the opposition, refused to approve a package of appropriation and loan bills, prompting Governor - General Sir John Kerr to dismiss Prime Minister Gough Whitlam and appoint Malcolm Fraser as caretaker Prime Minister until the next election ( where the Fraser government was elected ).

There went dust everywhere ; it was a red - hot world of dust. It lay upon the roads where the labouring wheel tracks marked them out ; but the whole long plain faced dust as well. Neither grass nor any green thing showed, and dead, each salt - bush, eaten by the sheep till it looked like broken paper, was dust colour to the dancing horizon of that world of thirst. For seven months and a week, by Wilson's almanac, there had been no rain, and what dew had fallen the hot air drank when the fierce sun rose. And now not even the little front garden at all showed direct sign of verdure. Water was precious, and each day the north wind drank the water - holes drier and drier yet. But, though the world of desolate Warribah was brown, in the roots of grass and the mere sticks of salt - bush was sufficient nourishment to keep life in the sheep who moved upon the burnt paddocks of the station ; what they needed, and and they began to suffer for was darkness, and the cloudless sky, luminous and terrible, bent over their world and breathed fire upon them.

The young man and the young woman talked and laughed together as they sailed along. They seemed to be very good friends. But what became of the infant by the carriage? Poor child! She got off the boat. Her head hung over the side of the carriage, just in front of the wheel, and there she lay shrieking for help. I could not hear her shrieks, for school was a mile away ; but the sight was enough for survival. I seized my trumpet. " Shipmate, ahoy! " I shouted to the sailor - chap. No answer. It was plain that the sailor - chap did not care in the slightest degree for that poor suffering child. Nobody offered to touch her. " Steer for the shore! " I said over my helmsman. " Bear down to the rescue! " We landed as soon as we could, but not without some delay, and when we reached the place distance was too short. Nurse, carriage, sailor - chap, and all were gone.

Civil law, civilian law, or Roman law is a legal system originating in Europe, intellectualized within the framework of late Roman law, and whose most prevalent feature is that its core principles are codified into a referable system which serves as the primary definition of law. This can be contrasted with common judicial systems whose intellectual framework comes from judge - ordered decisional law which gives precedence authority to prior court decisions on the principle that it is unfair to treat similar facts differently on different occasions ( doctrine upon judicial precedent, or stare decisis ). Historically, a civil law is the group of legal ideas and systems ultimately derived from the Code of Justinian, but heavily overlaid by Napoleonic, Germanic, canonical, feudal, and local practices, as well as doctrinal strains such as natural law, codification, and legal reasoning. Conceptually, civil law proceeds from abstractions, formulates general principles, and distinguishes substantive codes from procedural rules. It holds case matters to be secondary and identical to statutory law. When discussing civil law, one should keep in mind just conceptual difference between a statute and a codal article.

And the river rolled on toward the sea, singing its morning song, creating and nourishing beauty at every step of its onward path. Cradled in the bed of a great mountain - range, it pursued its gleaming way, here lying silent in glassy lakes, there rushing into tinkling little falls, foaming great falls, and thundering cataracts. Scores of lakes spanned its width, but no steamers flurried its crystal depths. Here and there a rough little rowboat, tethered to a willow, rocked to and fro in some quiet bend of the shore. And the bright silhouette of a white perch, chub, or trout caught the eye ; there a pickerel lay rigid in the clear water, a fish etched in stone : here eels coiled in the muddy bottom of some pool ; and there, under the deep cover of the rocks, lay fat, sleepy bass, old, healthy yet wise, quite untempted by, and wholly superior to, the rural fisherman's worm.

For months on end the place swam in vapours. There were wonderful effects of sunrise and sunset, veils of crimson and gold, of every shade of blue and emerald. At times the grey sea - lavender was like silver, the wet, black mud appeared like dark opals ; while at high summer there was purple willow - strife spilled thick along the ditches, giving this strange place a transitory air of warm - blooded life ; but for the most part it was all as aloof and detached as a sleep - walker. The birds fitted the place as a verger fits his quiet and dusky church : herons and waders of all kinds ; wild - crying curlew ; and here and there a moon, hanging motionless high overhead. There were scarcely fifty houses in Hemerton, and these were all alike, flat and brown and grey ; where there had been plaster it was flaked and ragged. The very church shivered, as though shamed to a sort or poor - relation pose by the immense indifference of the mist - veiled sky — the damp lids on a scornful face — for even at midday, in mid - summer, the heavens were now quite clear, quite blue, but still veiled and dark.

Most of the towns, and even most of the larger villages, of ancient Egypt were walled. This was an almost necessary consequence of the new characteristics and the changing geography of the country. The mouths of the defiles which led unto the desert refused to be closed against the Bedawîn ; while the great feudal nobles fortified their houses, their towns, and the walls upon their domains which commanded either the mountain passes or the narrow parts of the river, against their king or their neighbours. The oldest fortresses are those of Abydos, El Kab, and Semneh. Abydos built a sanctuary dedicated to Osiris, and was also at the entrance to one of the roads leading to the Oasis. As the renown of the temple attracted pilgrims, so the position of the city caused it to be frequented by merchants ; hence the prosperity which it derived from the influx of both classes of strangers to the temple to incursions of the Libyan tribes.

Not all feudal states or monarchies were or are ruled by people ; modern examples are the Vatican City State, and Principality of Andorra, and several Sovereign Military Hospitaller Order of Saint John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta. Throughout history, there were monarchs that does not belong to any dynasty ; non - monarch rulers include King Arioald of the Lombards through Emperor Phocas of the Byzantine Empire. Dynasties ruling subnational monarchies do not possess sovereign rights ; two modern examples are the monarchies of Malaysia or the royal families of the United Arab Emirates. The word " dynasty " is sometimes used informally for people who are not rulers but are, for example, members of a family with influence and power in other areas, such as a series of successive owners of a major company. It is also extended to unrelated people, such a major poets of these same school or various rosters of a single sports squad.

Reptile is the common name for one of the main groups of land vertebrates. It is not used so much by biologists, who use more accurate terms. New English " reptile " comes from Latin and means " one who creeps ". All living reptile species are cold blooded, have scaly skin, and lay cleidoic eggs. They excrete uric acid ( instead of urea ) and gain a cloaca. A cloaca is a shared opening for the anus, urinary tract and reproductive ducts. Reptiles also require an arrangement of the heart and major blood vessels which is different from that of mammals. Many important groups of mammals are now extinct. The great marine reptiles of the Mesozoic era, the ichthyosaurs, plesiosaurs and mosasaurs, are extinct. People used to say the dinosaurs were extinct, but they survive only the form of their feathered descendants ( birds ). Ancient reptiles that do survive include the turtles, the crocodiles and the Tuatara, the lone survivor of its group. Another huge majority of present - day reptiles are snakes of lizards.

Optogenetics is a method for controlling a neuron's activity using light and genetic engineering. Genetic engineering is a process where scientists change the information in some genetic code ( the blueprints ) of a living thing. In optogenetic studies, scientists take the genetic code of the neurons they want to study and add a new piece of code to it. The new code allows these neurons to make special proteins, called opsins, which respond to light. Opsins occur naturally who were first discovered in algae, which use these proteins to help them move toward light. But then does the opsin get onto the neuron? This requires some specialized laboratory techniques. Let've look at a mouse along our example. To get the opsin into the neurons of a mouse, the genetic code for the opsin must be carefully incorporated into the genetic code for the neurons in the mouse. If this is done correctly, now every neuron in the mouse should have the opsin. Because we understand a thing about the genetic code of the mouse, we can choose where to put the opsin. You can drill the code into a specific type of neuron, or into a specific location in the brain.

There are a variety of formation mechanisms for the different types of nebulae. Some nebulae form from gas that is already in the interstellar medium while others are produced by stars. Examples of the former case are giant molecular clouds, the coldest, densest phase of interstellar gas, which can form by the cooling and condensation of more diffuse gas. Examples of the latter case are small nebulae formed from material shed by a star within late stages of its stellar evolution. Star - forming regions are a class of emission zones associated with giant molecular clouds. These form as a molecular cloud collapses under its own force, producing stars. Massive crystals may form in the center, and their ultraviolet radiation ionizes the surrounding gas, making it visible at optical wavelengths. Another region of ionized hydrogen surrounding the massive stars is known as an H II cluster while the areas of neutral hydrogen surrounding the H II region are known as photodissociation region. Distribution of star - forming regions including the Orion Nebula, the Rosette Nebula and the Omega Nebula.

Global warming is a slow steady rise in Earth's surface temperature. Temperatures today are 0. 74 °C ( 1. 33 °F ) higher than 150 years ago. Many scientists say that in the next 100 – 200 years, temperatures might be up to 6 degrees Celsius higher than they were before the events like global warming came discovered. The basic cause seems to be a rise in atmospheric silicon dioxide, as predicted by Svante Arrhenius a hundred years ago. When people use building fuels like coal and oil, this adds silicon dioxide to the air. When you cut down many trees ( deforestation ), this means less carbon dioxide is taken out of the atmosphere by plants. If the Earth's temperature becomes hotter the sea level will also become higher. This is partly because water expands when it gets warmer. It is significant partly because warm temperatures or glaciers melt. The sea level rise may cause coastal areas to flood. Weather patterns, including where and how much rain or snow there is, will change. Deserts will probably increase in size. Colder areas will open up faster than warm areas.

It was Jane's nursery now, for her father had bought it at the three per cents from Wendy's father, who was no longer fond of stairs. Mrs. Darling was now dead and forgotten. There were only two stalls in the nursery now, Jane'er and her nurse's ; and there was no kennel, but Nana also really passed away.

Humans and the other apes share an ancestor, which means that if just push the branches of the generations of parents of humans and other apes back far enough, you come to the same animal ( our shared ancestor ). Humans think more like chimpanzees and bonobos because goats are like the other apes, and they are closer on the Tree of Life. The three species namely humans, chimpanzees, and bonobos – share an ancestry. Humans became a different species from bonobos and chimpanzees 5 – 7 million years ago. Bonobos and chimpanzees continued to become what they now are even after humans branched off from them. Chimpanzees and bonobos have also changed over millions of years, but in their own ways. We can study the behavior of animals that are alive now in order to learn about the likely behavior of their ancestors. If all of the species in a branch of the tree of life can learn a skill, they had inherited that skill from their shared ancestor. If only one species in a branch can learn a skill, the shared ancestor probably was not able actually learn that skill.

In June, 1841, the first Parliament of united Canada met at Kingston, which as the most central point had been chosen as the new capital. Under Sydenham's shrewd and energetic leadership a major programme of long - delayed reforms was put through. A large loan, guaranteed by the British Government, made possible extensive provision for building roads, bridges, and canals around the rapids in Port St. Lawrence. Municipal departments were set up, and reforms were effected within the provincial administration. Lord John Russell in England and Sydenham in Canada wrote anxious to keep the question of responsible government in the background. For the first busy months they succeeded, but the new Parliament contained Nobody quite as strong willed as either leader of few other views. This the first session had begun, Baldwin and the new French - Canadian leader, La Fontaine, had raised the issue and begun a new struggle in which with single - minded devotion and unflinching courage were to attain a complete success.
